en recorded, and the first time it has been with an 85-year-old guest. The first time was in March of 2020, and the second time is in June of 2023. The interview is recorded on June 27th, 2023.\n\nBill Henry was born and raised in the Ward of Elizabeth Street, near York Road. His parents immigrated from Ireland to Guelph when he was a child. He attended the Tyler School from kindergarten until grade six and then went to the Grand Central Vocational School. He says that he hated school, but it was a good one. Now, the Ward has two new schools: King George School and John-Galt School. Bill says that his family has passed away, and he is now an orphan.',NULL,NULL),(61049,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/03/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - July 3, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-03 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 12:51:38',NULL,'The narrator introduces himself as Nicholas Cooper, the guardian of the Sentinel. He explains that he is here to pay respects to the native peoples of Turtle Island and to acknowledge the influence that their music has had on the contemporary world.\n\nHe also acknowledges that many of the tracks in this new session were originally created under the oppressive conditions of racial oppression. The narrator also announces that he has taken a week off from performing to attend the Pride Parade. He says he was glad to be able to go. He notes that he likes the changes going on in the music being played on the new Toronto radio station, The Monsoon. He thanks the station for featuring his song, Ordinary Girl, in their May show, Ear glow. The first set of the new session is by Edzuyu and they have just released their new album.',NULL,NULL),(61051,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/03/Ripcord Radio - July 3, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-03 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 12:30:39',NULL,'This is the first hour of the program and it\'s all about the music. It\'s about 50,000 watts of music that gets loud, dirty