isten to it on their tablet or on their big screen. She ends the program by',NULL,NULL),(61057,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Let’s Get Lost - July 4, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 11:29:55',NULL,'On this program, CFRU\'s news and programming team discusses Scott\'s track \"Sumna\" and Colin Colin\'s upcoming performances. They also talk about the 13th anniversary of Riverfest, which will take place August 18-20 in Allora Park.\n\nA volunteer at the university, Handel, tells us that he\'s a fan of the university because he loves working with people there and he also loves the feeling of \"contribution something meaningful\" to the world . He volunteers at the music station, Humanoid Radio, and he and his friend, Jeff, are looking for new volunteer opportunities. The program begins with a short song from the Master Gardeners original motion picture, \"Sleeping Gunshot,\" and finishes with a song by Justin Hopper, a Tlingit. Justin is from New York and he describes potlatch as a \"very central teaching\" to balance the wolf and the raven.',NULL,NULL),(61059,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Let’s Get Lost - July 4, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 11:05:41',NULL,'Scott introduces the program and introduces Ayumi Ashto, a New York-based saxophonist. She is a member of the Spaceman project, which has just released its second volume, The Spaceman Volume 2.\n\nThe band has prepared a tune for the show, called Illuminated Futures from the project. Scott also mentions that Peter Brothman recently passed away, and the band has a number of new tracks for the listeners to hear.\n\nThe first track they play is Wintertime from an album by a drummer named Asher Gamadozi. Then they play a track from Gerdina\'s new project The Twain, called Goldwing, which he teamed up with some Japanese players for. They also play a tune from Henry Thread\'s Movement One Finale, which is out on Pi records. The program closes with Jerry Hemingway\'s album Riptide, which was released a decade or so ago.',NULL,NULL),(61060,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Humanoid Radio - July 4, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 10:43:57',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61062,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Wild Combination - July 6, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 10:24:13',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61063,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Wild Combination - July 6, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 10:05:57',NULL,'In this episode of Wild Combination, the musician plays two tracks from his latest release, a diary field recording of a storm frog chorus. He also plays music from his most recent release, Best Music of all Time, which includes music by two other artists, Zina Parkin\'s Lace project and William Wynaut\'s \"Lace 2.\n\n\" The first track is part of a sound diary recording of Ubid Indonesia, the second part is from his new recording series, \"Ubid Ubid.\" The third track is from the Lace project, which Zina has been working on since 2008. The first part of the Lace 1 consists of William and James Fay on percussion, Maggie Parkins on cello, and Tilt \"Brakkin\" on electric violin. The second part consists of Maggie, James, and William on piano.',NULL,NULL),(61064,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - July 4, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 09:50:33',NULL,'This is the first episode of the show. It\'s called \"The Cyber Lich Gothic Castle\" and it\'s hosted by the guy who calls himself \"the Cyber Litch\" . He\'s the host of a show called \"the cyberlicer\" and he\'s a guy who\'s in the middle of a terror attack and wants you to be his victim. The show is a little confusing sometimes, because the guy has a young kid and is trying to remember what time it is.\n\nHe also has another show called the \"Android\'s Dungeon\" which is a really good show. The music is really good, though, and the guy says he\'ll be back soon with more. The first track is Ulysios album, \"Arachnophony\" , followed by \"Casey of Web Mascara,\" \"Masakura,\" \"Achnophony,\" and \"Invasion.\" The next track is Carl\'s \"Whitebat 23,\" followed by the album \"Salt in the Wound.\" Then they finish off with \"Triptodon Boulevard of Corruption,\" followed with \"Cabled Corpses,\" \"Lasis Heels,\" \"Rock Flesh,\" and finally \"the core.\" The guy says the show is always good and he doesn\'',NULL,NULL),(61065,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - July 5, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 09:32:16',NULL,'The students discuss their research, and Caroline tells them about her past. She studied earth system science at McGill University and earth and planetary sciences at McGill. After completing her masters degree, she became disillusioned with the scientific method, realizing that it was too scientific.\n\nShe decided to take a year off to study skiing and snow science, and then returned to school to study mountain hydrology. She is currently completing her Ph.D. in this field. As she travels across Canada, she is frequently asked to go to meetings in Saskatchewan, but she has avoided that, instead living in Alberta, where she can conduct her research. Caroline tells the students that she studies glaciers and snow in the mountains of Canada.',NULL,NULL),(61066,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 5, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 09:08:14',NULL,'In this interview, Theo discusses his new release, \"Theo Alle: Release Points of Decay,\" and then moves on to his earlier work, \"Waiting for you to die, Coda.\n\n\" In this second part of the interview, he discusses a song called \"As the smoke begins to clear,\" a track he has been recording in response to the recent wildfire in British Columbia. In this third part, he describes a new album called \"Mirope,\" which he finds especially inspiring. He also dedicates the album to his old friend and co-worker, Jay Shay Carter, who is considered one of the most influential music thinkers of his generation. Mirope\'s track \"Alma\" is one of many beautifully produced tracks on the album, which also includes music from \"plinky plunky,\" \"dreams fallen from their release,\" and \"undisclosed promises\" by his friend, Jay Halepen.',NULL,NULL),(61067,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 5, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 08:54:45',NULL,'In this program, the voice of the artist discusses several new releases, including a new collaboration between Mikosa and Ciro. The two also work together on an album called \"El Final de las Insilaces\" which translates to \"The End of the Reign.\n\n\" The first track on the album is called \"Inverno Austral,\" which means \"Southern Winter,\" and the second track is \"Tu Muchachos.\" The third track is from \"Forest Knows Too,\" an album from \"Non Kana.\" The fourth track on \"Heaven Becomes a Periphobia,\" from \"Family,\" is \"the fear of eternity.\" The fifth track is a track called \"Is Winter My Country,\" a track from \"Codiab.\" The last track is one from \"Fires Were Shot,\" a Texas duo.',NULL,NULL),(61068,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/Seems Like Old Times - July 2, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 08:36:39',NULL,'The narrator says that he\'s afraid he doesn\'t know the enemy. He\'s a bit worried, because there\'s only one guy left in the office with him: a guy with white teeth.\n\nThe guy has some money, but he\'ll have to wait until he gets back. The narrator runs into a guy named Cairo, who\'s looking for a lost ornament. Cairo asks if he can borrow a gun and search the office for the missing ornament, which is a statue of a black bird. The man says he\'d pay five thousand bucks for the lost statue. It\'s not a good idea to shoot a guy like that, but the man says that\'s what he needs to do. He tells the narrator to stand up and let people in so he can search his office. He says he had a first guess that he had the bird, but now he wants to know if there\'sa second guess. He asks if they\'re hiring him to murder or to do burglary, but to get the statue back in some way.\n\nThe first guess is that he has the statue. But the second guess is where the statue is, or where he can find it. The fat guy pokes something into the back of the man\'s neck, and the fat guy wants to see what\'s going on. He wants to talk to the man. The conversation turns to the black bird, and we learn that the man wants to get money',NULL,NULL),(61069,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/End Credits - July 5, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 08:11:51',NULL,'On this episode of End Credits, host Adam A Donaldson and guest Peter Wesley Salmon talk about the upcoming festival at the hillside in Guelph. They discuss Canada Day, beer, and food. They also discuss the latest in movies and pop culture. They have a few more entries to discuss, including the new meta- scifi comedy Asteroid City and the latest entry in the Indiana Jones saga, the Kingdom of The Crystal Skull',NULL,NULL),(61070,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/Seems Like Old Times - July 2, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 14:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 07:56:30',NULL,'The program opens with a description of Len Gillard\'s orchestra. The program is an hour long program and is devoted to music and old-time radio memories. In this program, the program introduces a piece called \"Seniors for Peace\" that was originally performed by Maria in the TUC radio. The woman who performed the piece is alive and has revived the piece because she and her friends are still protesting outside of a California nursing home. After the program, they will have news of Rod Stewart, who is performing a song from \"As Time Goes By\" .',NULL,NULL),(61071,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/Trail Mix - July 5, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 07:28:16',NULL,'This week on the TUZONE, we catch up with the folks who have been listening to the trail mix show on CFRU .\n\nThey\'ve been waiting for the show to come on and they give us a little update on mental health. If you have a mental health problem, there are free toll-free mental health helplines in the province. You can call toll free 1-866-531-26. We also learn that a team of ethics researchers are looking for people who are 5 to 65 years old to participate in a pandemic research study. If they complete the survey, they can keep a journal, or they can listen to a podcast and learn more about the pandemic.\n\nIf the study is approved by the University of the Ottawa and the Vermont Institutional Review Board, then it\'s on to the next show. We\'ll start off with a song from the \'80s, called \"Firehose\" by the band of the Minutemen.',NULL,NULL),(61072,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/Wind-Down - July 2, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 07:12:29',NULL,'On this edition of the Wind Down, Sarah Willow, host of the popular music show, gives the listeners a rundown of the latest music on the air.\n\nThe show starts off with a song from the upcoming album Bless This Mess by US Girls, who will be opening for Patti Smith on August 20 at the National. The band also has a new single out called Want You, which was produced by Sarah. The next song on the show is from the band Clarell, who released a song called Story of Scar. The group Le Jadu Sister also released a new song called Come on Home. The song Life is Despair from the group Stella and Rodin came out in 2017, and the group Davy Boy released a brand new single in 2023 called Better And Better. The second song is from Duval Timothy, who just released a single called Fall Again.',NULL,NULL),(61073,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/Tone Zone - July 5, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 06:51:52',NULL,'The Tone Zone is back on the air with Matt. He\'s excited about the announcement that Slowdive is going on tour with a new album coming out called \"Everything Is Alive\" on September 1 st . The song they\'re going to play is called \"Kisses,\" and it\'s from their last album called \"Calling Out of Context\" back in 2004. We\'re joined by Arthur Russell and Matt to talk about the music that\'s been coming out of Guelph over the last few years.\n\nThe first song they play is \"Slowdive and Kisses\" from their new album \"Everything is Alive\" out on September 1. The next song is \"Memory Lane\" from \"Beat My Distance\" by Montreal band Anemonone. The last song is from \"The Monkey House\" by \"11,800 Dreams\" by Anemone. Peter Gabriel has been releasing a new song every day since the beginning of the year. We\'ve heard from a',NULL,NULL),(61074,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/B Siide Radio - July 5, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 06:27:35',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61075,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/Radia - July 5, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 06:12:22',NULL,'The second episode of the new season of Industry Tactics is a conversation between the host, Friendly Rich, and the musician, Georgia Weber, who uses the term \"graphic medicine\" in her book, \"Dumb.\" The show consists of a recording of the conversation, which can be found at FriendlyRich.Com. The conversation between Rich and Weber takes place in the second season of the show, and focuses on the influence of music teacher, musician, and author, Doug Friesen. The show\'s listeners can learn more about Rich\'s career by listening to the entire program at Friendly Rich.com.',NULL,NULL),(61076,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Tales from the Bridge - July 6, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 05:57:47',NULL,'The narrator and the other guests welcome Kate Elliott, a science fiction author, to the bridge. Kate has won many awards for her novels, including Locus Awards for her most recent, Furious Heaven.\n\nKate tells us that she is a big fan of James Corey and Arkady Martin. The narrator asks Kate to start off with her latest work without spoilers. Kate is going to tell us about her latest project, which is set in the future. She wants to tell her readers that she wants to write a story set in space, in which Alexander the Great is replaced by a female emperor. She also wants to show how the generals of the future fought in the war.',NULL,NULL),(61077,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Here Today - July 6, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 07:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 05:13:24',NULL,'Aaron Badgley, the host of the popular music show CFRU-FM, chats with his listeners about the band Cameron Noise. The band is composed of the voices of Tim Cameron and Rob Stewart. Aaron describes them as \"little bits and pieces\" that were not found on albums previously.\n\nHe is excited to hear about them, especially because they are in one place, making it easier for listeners to find them. Aaron also plays some new music from the Church of Trees\' new album, Courage and Oxygen. He says that he will be able to hear them perform live in the fall. He also talks about the new single by Len Mazzoni. The song is called \"Fly High My Butterfly\" and it is from his latest album, To Brook.\n\nAaron is so excited about the song that he says he is \"so young\" and that he loves the song. He goes on to say that he is so young that he can hardly hear the voice of the song, but that it is John Jenkins, an artist from Liverpool. He sings about how he spent his childhood in Liverpool. This song is from To Brook, the new album from John Jenkins. Aaron says that the whole album comes out this week and he will play tracks off it the next week.',NULL,NULL),(61078,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/FoodFarm Talk - July 6, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 04:52:23',NULL,'This episode of FoodFarm Talk is the first in a new series of podcasts hosted by Barb Swartzenhuber. The first in this new series is \"To In Conversation with our Food.\" It\'s about the creation of the \"circular food economy\" in Wellington, a city in southwestern Ontario, Canada.\n\nThe host of this new program is Dr. Tamara Sorenson, an assistant professor and research director for the Food Systems Laboratory at Simon Fraser. She\'s also an author and a changemaker. She was named one of 10 \"Inspiring Canadian Women Saving the Environment.\" Dr. Sorenson will have \"Snack Bites,\" a conversation about \"Circular Food System Planning in Canada.\" She\'ll be joined by Barb, who is the former executive director for \"Our Food Future Initiative.\n\n\" She and Dr. Soma are excited to be part of the conversation. The question they\'re trying to answer is, \"What do you see emerging in the circular food systems planning that you did not see five years earlier?\" The answer is \"like what is emerging today.\" They\'ll also discuss how little indigenous considerations are integrated in planning and policy, which is \"very shocking\" considering how little \"indigenous considerations\" were integrated into \"planning and policy.\" They also discuss Dr. McGregor\'s class, which was \"really lovely\" but \"shocking\" in its lack of \"inherent considerations.\" Back then, planning was \"all about land use\" and \"human settlements\" and',NULL,NULL),(61079,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/T.K.O. - July 6, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 04:39:15',NULL,'The second part of this interview focuses on music and the arts. It begins with a description of the music and ends with a plea to listeners to get involved with alzheimer\'s society. To do so, visit azheimer.ca and scroll down to the \"Slash Music\" section.',NULL,NULL),(61080,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Android’s Dungeon - July 6, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 13:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 04:16:22',NULL,'This is the first episode of the new show I, Joel. It\'s a solo episode, and it\'s about music, movies, and board games. The narrator doesn\'t say where he\'s been, but he\'ll be back soon. It sounds like the show is going to be a lot more music heavy than usual. Also, he\'d like you to check out the show on all of your favorite podcasting sites if you think the episode is good enough to get uploaded. In fact, he says, he doesn\'\'t like doing solo episodes unless he has an interview. Plus, he likes to do interviews with second people, so he\'ve got some good ones coming up.',NULL,NULL),(61081,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/RadiOPIRG - July 6, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 03:51:05',NULL,'In this episode, RadiopiRG goes back in time to hear Kate Nixon talk about her organization, Your Downtown Guelph Friend. Kate is a member of the organization, which is looking to address issues of inequity in the community. Kate started the organization when she was in high school because she wanted to address the issues of hunger and poverty in her community. She decided to start a food bank in her neighborhood and three years later, there were no hunger-related problems in Guelph. In this interview, Kate also talks about how she started hosting food drives to address hunger in her own neighborhood when she returned to school.',NULL,NULL),(61082,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Turtle Island Underground - July 6, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 18:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 03:38:13',NULL,'This is the first of several music conversations we\'ll hear as part of the University of Regina\'s \"Connect With Your Campus and Community\" series. The first two topics are \"Way of Street Pharmacy\" and \"Robbie Robertson\'s Self-titled Polaris Pharma Album.\" They\'re all about how to get students and faculty to listen to music on campus. The University also has a new program called \"Indigenous Alternative.\n\n\" It\'s an umbrella term for the university\'s record and music scene, and it includes everything from music to spoken word to poetry. The program starts off tonight with \"Exit Music For Exit Wounds\" by Ashnatani and \"Cheshire\" by Cheshire. Next up is \"Red River\" by Dan Monkman and \"Sunsetter,\" Andrew McLeod\'s solo project. The EPs are also great, too, and they all feature collaborations with some great artists.\n\nThe next two shows are \"Edzi U\" by Pop and \"Tinge\" by Wayfinding and \"Turtle Island Underground\" by \"Stinge.\" The first is \"Why Does the Indian Act Not Have Power Over?\" by Edzi U. The second is \"How do I Get rid of the powers that I do not give?\" by Panda-Up Squad. The song is about how important it is to be rid of power, and how important the power is to the people who don\'t have it. Panda-up Squad had been writing together for a while',NULL,NULL),(61083,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Open Sources Guelph - July 6, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 03:11:33',NULL,'The next day, the Open Sources team discusses how New Brunswick\'s conservative mayor, Blaine Higgs, lost. Higgs tried to use his political capital to win over young people in the city by attacking their pronouns and gender identities. Paris is again burning in the streets, and the cause is the same: police violence and \"systemic racism\" . The Open Source team asks whether the Paris protests have gone \"too far\" , and if they\'ve been successful.',NULL,NULL),(61084,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/The Crooked Beat - July 6, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 02:43:57',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61085,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/The Crooked Beat - July 6, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 02:27:20',NULL,'The first song on the program is a dub remix of a Wailing Souls song called \"Firehouse Rock,\" which was banned from Texas by the state government. The second song is a cover of Dream Girl\'s \"Fire,\" which is also banned from the state. The third song is an original from Redone, which was also banned out of Texas. The fourth song is \"Have Mercy The Gladiators,\" an album by Hal Anthony called \"Hal Anthony Sings The Greatest Hits.\" The fifth song is the cover of Gregory Isaacs\'s song \"Have You Seen the Light.\"',NULL,NULL),(61086,121,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Sundowner - July 6, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 02:11:45',NULL,'The show starts off with a heavy dose of music from the Sundowner crew, including some new tracks from Trauma Ray, a few from the local Trash Bonnie, and a few tracks from bands from around the world. The show ends with a song from Matt\'s personal favorite, Seal, from the Amen Dunes album, Rocket Flare. Matt thanks everyone for coming out to watch the show, and thanks them all for spending the night with him. He also thanks Ed Video, the city\'s arts hub, for hosting the show.',NULL,NULL),(61087,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/07/Forever Deaf - July 7, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-07 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-07 01:48:41',NULL,'Dean Yunt is the voice of H sphere, a band from England that\'s been out of the public eye for the better part of a decade. They\'ve just 