y Big Blood, which ends with Haunted. The fifth hour starts off the next show with Sarah Willow.',NULL,NULL),(61109,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/Zombie Jamboree - July 2, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 18:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 19:53:29',NULL,'The narrator explains that he\'s ready to start the Zombie Jamboree. He\'s the regional ambassador for the USSA Nation, a tribe that has been living in Canada for thousands of years. They\'ve been called a lot of names, but they\'re happy to call themselves the Halas Nation because they\'ve always lived in harmony with nature. He plays a song called \"We Are the Halus Nation\" to explain why they live in Canada. The narrator is also a citizen of the LaVoe nation, even though he doesn\'t really like music.',NULL,NULL),(61110,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/Through the Looking Glass - July 2, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 21:00:00',86638720,'2024-01-06 19:10:29',NULL,'The second part of the show opens with a description of the band Twin, who play a cover of Don Quixote\'s Don Quixote. The band also performs a number of other songs, including a Rob Stewart track, a Valance track, and a Hollow Body track with Spellbreaker. The next band is a Canadian band called Ghost Twin. They play a set of songs from their latest album, including the Rob Stewart remix of the Valance song, and the Rob-Stewart track, which is a reworking of the Ghost Twin song \"Babes in the Wood.\" The band closes the show by playing their cover of Catnap\'s \"Big Little Lion.\" The show closes with a reminder that',NULL,NULL),(61111,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/Backtracks - July 2, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 18:55:08',NULL,'The show begins with a rebroadcast of last year\'s edition of Back Tracks, a program that mixes music from the past with songs from the present. The program opens with a song from Canada, written by a trumpet player named Bobby Gimby who played at the fair in Montreal in 1967. The program then plays an iconic song from the Woodstock Music and Arts Festival. The show closes with a performance by Jimi Hendrix, who played the national anthem from his song \"American Dream\" at the Woodstock festival.',NULL,NULL),(61112,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/03/This Night Wounds Time - July 3, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-03 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 18:32:43',NULL,'This is the third hour of the program and it\'s dedicated to music by artists who live in the northern part of the country, which is called La Rioja.\n\nWe\'re going to hear music by a singer named Maria Selguero. She\'s from La Rioja, and she\'s known by the stage names The Witch and La Bruja. The name Selguero Wit is apparently a joke, but it sounds like a good name for a singer. She was born to a working class family, and her father was a bricklayer, so her family\'s story isn\'t very complete. The music we\'ll hear tonight is from two of her albums: Norte and Gritoio. The first is called Norte, which sounds a lot like a country song. The second one is called Gritoios, which means \"inner strength.\" The name of the third is also a joke. It sounds like it could refer to strength in the interior, but maybe not as much as in the city of Buenos Aires.\n\nThis is a little confusing. The show is also going to spotlight artists from the northern interior, not the southern part, but that\'s going to be the focus of the show tonight. The program is dedicated to the tango, and it sounds more like the country\'s version of R&B.',NULL,NULL),(61113,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/03/This Night Wounds Time - July 3, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-03 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 18:14:09',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part series on music. The first part is called \"The Geography of Music\" and the second part is \"The Music of the Night.\" The first section deals with music that is unusual and from all around the world, while the second section is devoted to music that sounds familiar to listeners. This first section consists of a series of musical numbers that begin with \"A,\" followed by \"B.\" and end with \"C.\" The music in this program is a mixture of familiar and new music, and the program ends with \"Go.\"',NULL,NULL),(61114,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/02/This Night Wounds Time - July 2, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-02 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 17:48:01',NULL,'This is the program known as \"this night wounds time\" and it is hosted by Christopher Curry. It is an hour-long show that is dedicated to music that is \"a little bit, or sometimes more than a little bit,\" off the beat.\n\nHe explains that this is a program devoted to \"music of a somewhat overly very off center nature.\" He adds that when the program is over, he will shift its focus to the \"geographic spotlight series\" of the show. This is where the show will feature music of artists from a particular region of the \"literal map of the universe.\" For example, the program will feature artists from the province of Argentina. The program will also feature music from the new release collection of the College of Brock University.',NULL,NULL),(61115,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Beautiful Druid - July 8, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 17:35:11',NULL,'In this program, Alden Hadwen, host of the university-affiliated program Beautiful Druid, introduces listeners to a variety of new music, including songs by Tom Waits, Sam Cooke, and Alex Kubba. The program also includes a song written by Tom himself, \"I Hope that I Dont Fall In Love with You,\" which he wrote in 1973, but which he thinks is still very appropriate for the summertime. Alden concludes the program with the song, \"Hope That I Don t Fall in love with You.\"',NULL,NULL),(61117,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/0