ent light when he was clearly on his compute.',NULL,NULL),(61120,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/06/Democracy Now - July 6, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-06 11:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 16:30:26',NULL,'In this program, David reports from Russia, where he discusses the latest developments in the war. He speaks with one of the country\'s most famous writers, Andrei Kirkov. In Syria, David looks at a new documentary, \"Captagon,\" which tells the story of how the powerful family in the government controls the drug trade.',NULL,NULL),(61122,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/Democracy Now - July 5, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 11:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 16:16:13',NULL,'Israel has withdrawn its forces from the West Bank town of Jenin, claiming it was necessary to do so to prevent further attacks on the civilian population. Meanwhile, Israel has intensified its military campaign against the Gaza Strip, which has led to the deaths of at least 160 Palestinians and the wounding of more than 1,100. Israel has also announced it is purchasing 75 new F-35 stealth fighter jets, financed through the United States.',NULL,NULL),(61123,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Rainbow Country - July 4, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 15:48:13',NULL,'This episode opens with Police Constable Botno, known as the \"LGBT Cop\" on the streets of London, talking with a listener named Mark Tara about the music he\'s been listening to recently. The show is called \"Rainbow Country,\" and it\'s all about music that\'s relevant to the LGBT community. We\'ve got music from the new wave era, the industrial era, and the old school. We also have music from artists like Holly Cinnamon, Frankie Goes To Hollywood, and Dana Lee. The police officer closes the show by saying that despite all of the craziness of the world, \"we are living in the days of making.\"',NULL,NULL),(61125,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Rainbow Country - July 4, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 15:31:32',NULL,'On this episode of Rainbow Country, we find out about the 1981 raid on the \"bathhouses\" in Toronto. Also, Tim McCaskill, author of \"Indigo: The Untold Story of the Sex Pistols,\" is our guest. Emily Saylor, a porn star and burlesque performer, joins us on this episode. She\'s also the host of \"Rainbow Country,\" which is a new kind of talk show that\'s all about the LGBT community in Canada.\n\nIt\'s a show about the stories of the past and the present. You can listen to the show by going to http://www.podcaster.com/rainbow-country. And remember, it\'s on a local radio station, CIUT FM, in Toronto, so it can be heard all over the country. And it has been recognized as one of the top 10 shows in',NULL,NULL),(61126,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Democracy Now - July 4, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 11:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 15:13:47',NULL,'On July 5, 1852, Frederick Douglass gives a famous speech, \"What to the Slave Is Your Fourth of June?\" Douglass was born into slavery around 1816. He became a key abolitionist movement leader. In 1852 Douglass was asked to give a speech in celebration of July 4th. Douglass begins his speech by asking why he is asked to speak to the nation. He asks, \"Fellow citizens, pardon / me and allow / me to ask why I am called upon to give this speech today.\n\nAre the great pillars of political freedom, and of natural Justice embodied in that declaration of independence extended to us?\" Douglass then proceeds to criticize the nation for celebrating the day in such a sham manner. Douglass calls the nation a \"sham\" and says, \"Your boasts of liberty, your boasting of vanity, your declarations of independence are empty and / heartless. Your denunciation ofs, your brass-fronted invective, your cries of freedom and equality are to him / mere bombastrophe, fraud, deceit, impiety, and hypocrisy.\n\n/ There is not even a nation of earth / guilty of practices / more shocking and / bloody than the people of this United States. Douglass closes the speech by saying, \"Had I the ability, and could reach this nation\'s ears, I would, today, pour forth a fiery stream, / biting ridicule, / blasting reproach, / withering sarcasm, and stern rebuke. / It is not light, that is needed, but',NULL,NULL),(61127,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Silver Screen Dream Machine - July 4, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 14:48:10',NULL,'This week\'s episode of Silver Dream Machine begins with music by the late Italian composer Enna Morricone, who died three years ago. Enna goes on to play music from the classic spaghetti Western dollars trilogy, starring Clint Eastwood. Ennio also composed music for the sequel to The Exorcist, The Heretic, Cold Eye of Fear, and The Thing, a 1982 horror film adaptation of a book by John W Campbell. The music ends with music from his scores for The Thing and Cold Eyes.',NULL,NULL),(61129,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/03/Democracy Now - July 3, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-03 11:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 14:31:11',NULL,'On June 16th, we remember the life and death of one of America\'s most renowned whistleblowers, the man who leaked the most important documents ever written about the war in the name of freedom.\n\nDaniel Ellberg died just months after suffering from pancreatic cancer. He was a patriot, a friend, and a great-grandfather. His family says he died peacefully. His son Robert says his father once told him that he would like his tombstone to say that he became a member of the antiwar and antinuclear movement. Ellsberg was sentenced to death in 1971 for leaking the most sensitive documents ever published on the subject of the war. The documents revealed the extent of the government\'s involvement in the war, including the names of thousands of officers and soldiers.\n\nThe release of the documents would help put down President Nixon and save the lives of countless',NULL,NULL),(61130,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Down the Rabbit Hole - July 4, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 18:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 14:09:09',NULL,'The show opens with the song \"Down the Rabbit Hole\" from Colin Stetson\'s new album, Down The Rabbit Hole. The song is the title track to Confessions Part 3, the third and final song on the band\'s latest release, BadBadNotGood. The band will also hear a song from Kendrick Scott, \"What Day Is it\" from his latest album \"Chorrels.\" The group will also listen to a song by a Filipino musician named Yik, \"ETA 2.\" The song features two California bands, Paris Texas and Yik. Yik is a great producer, and he\'s also a big fan of Paris Texas. The final song of the show will be by LaRajee',NULL,NULL),(61131,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/05/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - July 5, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-05 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 13:51:42',NULL,'The Griffin and the Special Olympics team is back on the air with the first of two new shows, this time with a special edition of \"Griffin Sports.\" The first show is called \"Griffin and Special Olympics\" and focuses on the past and the present. The show will feature \"Griffin interviews\" and \"special updates.\" The second show will be \"Griffin sports\" and will focus on \"special Olympics.\" The show opens with a recap of the previous week\'s Griffin and special Olympian show, including a description of Royce\'s time with the Griffins.\n\nThe interview is followed by a song from \"Arcade Fire,\" a band that has gotten into a lot of trouble for its lyrics. The Griffin team is aware of the band\'s problems and feels terrible about their harm. The reason Taylor wanted to play the song is that one of his best friends is Tim\'s brother, Matt Kingsbury, and he wants to play \"Toast\" because of that connection.',NULL,NULL),(61132,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/07/Industry Tactics - July 7, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-07 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 13:28:58',NULL,'The narrator explains that he\'s still doing shows at the university, but that he still enjoys making music and making people laugh. He\'s also got a new gig on the university\'s 250 watt FM station, which he calls \"Here Today\" . The narrator tells the listeners that he had a little talk about the bands that he listens to on the station. They\'re called \"New and Established Artists\" and they\'re on the air every Thursday at 7am. If you want to be a part of this, you can visit the station and get started.',NULL,NULL),(61134,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/07/Industry Tactics - July 7, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-07 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 12:50:51',NULL,'The narrator of this short and humorous animated program describes how CFRU, the university\'s public radio station, now offers a full-featured, web-based version of its station. The site includes a live broadcast stream, a weekly program guide, weekly music charts, a second live stream with exclusively local music, and many other features. It also has an easy-to-use donation section.',NULL,NULL),(61135,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/New or Never - July 4, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 12:29:07',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of New or Never, Adrian introduces the music of Bombshell, Body Wash, Feist, Fruit Bats, and the A.i. whisperer. Also new is the idea of a total eclipse of the sun on April 8, 2024. It will happen in Canada, Mexico, the U.S., and Canada. Also, astronomers have recorded the first image of the black hole. This week, the band Braids releases their latest work, which is called Labyrinthine.',NULL,NULL),(61136,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Jitterbuggin - July 8, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 12:13:27',NULL,'This is a very brief but very important interview with a very interesting local musician, Adrian. He is the host of the popular music show \"Jitterbuggin\" which airs on the community radio station, UOG.\n\nThis is Adrian\'s first live gig and he is very excited to do it. He explains that he has had to cancel his previous shows because of roadworks in the area. He says that he had to make the decision whether to come to the station early or stay home and wait in the traffic. He finds that his CD has crashed and he has to go to the local diner and play music for the audience. He tells them that it is the anniversary of his arrival in Guelph and that he hopes that they will enjoy the music. He also says that if they are at home and they want to invite their friends over and play some music, they can do so.',NULL,NULL),(61137,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/07/Hellfire Radio - July 7, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-07 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 11:53:15',NULL,'This week on the CFRU\'s Thursday Morning Show, Sam and Marty discuss Silence, a new music venue and art gallery in Guelph, Ontario, Canada. Silence offers flat rate rentals from 9am-5pm on weekdays for $100. The show also discusses DJ Double D, a local DJ who works at the grocery store.\n\nHe is a self-described \"love-revolution\" type of person, who hates the commercial radio that he has to listen to in order to survive. He also criticizes the music that is played on the station, which he calls \"awful\" and \"inappropriate.\" The show ends with a shout-out to the new light music on the air, which is a mix of underground and commercial music.',NULL,NULL),(61138,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/04/Under the Needle - July 4, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-04 13:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 11:30:02',NULL,'In this extended interview, Mr. Fearon discusses his life in music, his latest album, and his philosophy on the power of the music to inspire change. In his opinion, music has a positive effect on the masses. He suggests that young musicians do not compromise their hearts with their art. He explains that what they are looking for in life is truth and steadiness. He believes that music and other forms of art will do the same thing. He concludes the interview by offering his performance on this very night.',NULL,NULL),(61139,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/03/17/Under the Needle - March 17, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-03-17 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 11:10:57',NULL,'Hot Chip is a band formed by two guys named Joe and Taylor Goddard. They\'ve known each other for 22 years. They met when they were 11 years old, and they\'ve always been friends. The Guardian calls them \"the greatest British pop band of their generation\" .\n\nThey also collaborated with some of the biggest names in music like Timbaland and the Neptunes. They were also nominated for a Grammy for their latest album, \"A Bath Full of Emulation\" , which was released to critical acclaim. The guys are super stoked to have played live for them. And they\'re super psyched to have such a great band like Hot Chip play. They want to thank them all for listening. And then they\'ll see them next week.',NULL,NULL),(61140,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/03/10/Under the Needle - March 10, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-03-10 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 10:51:29',NULL,'This program is a special edition of Under the Needle, the music program hosted by Troy Nelson. In this special edition, the program focuses on Julia\'s mother, who loves to watch her daughter sing. Julia was born in Sydney, Australia, and when Julia was 6, her mother called in to Australia to see her daughter. Julia sings songs about her relationship with her mother, which is why so many people are listening to her music. Julia is known for her direct, intimate voice, and her songs have a lot of power. We thank her and her band, as well as the 3KND community, for stopping by the program.\n\nTroy also talks about how salamanders eat pitcher plants. He describes the bog where he and his colleagues have been studying salamanders. The bog is a wetlands that accumulates peat, so it\'s very unstable, and he\'s fallen in it many times. He says he got fitter during the summer because of all the holes in the bog, so he would not fall in.',NULL,NULL),(61141,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/03/03/Under the Needle - March 3, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-03-03 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 10:35:10',NULL,'In this episode, Troy and his crew talk about King Gizzard, a band that has released five albums in a single year. They also talk about how the band is planning to donate all of the proceeds from the three live albums they\'ve just released to charity.\n\nThe band also stops by the studio to play some songs. They\'re psyched about that. We also learn that there\'s a March Break Camp coming up at Ed Video in Guelph for kids to learn how to make music videos. They have a screening on March 20 at 4pm. If you\'re interested, check it out.',NULL,NULL),(61142,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/02/25/Under the Needle - February 25, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-02-25 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 10:12:39',NULL,'This week\'s show is called \"Ixweek\" and it\'s all about the psych rock band Alten Goons. They\'re hailing from Holland and they\'re a big fan of Turkish folk music.\n\nThey take traditional songs and rearrange them into their own style, but the sound is much closer to the Krung Bins or the King Gizzards of the world than it is to the bluegrass sounds of the day. They were signed by ATO Records and they played Gizfest Australia. It turns out that Amsterdam is a great music city and that\'s why people want to live there. Also, they\'ve just heard some songs from the band Dunya and Jay-Z. You can check out the KEXP recordings of their live shows here.\n\nThey also want to shout out Red Light Radio to Amsterdam. And we\'re talking about red worms. Isaac and his hosts are here to talk to Phil Loring, an anthropologist at the university of Guelph. He tells us about his work and how he\'s trying to find cases where people can meet their needs while also being able to do so in an environmentally sustainable way.',NULL,NULL),(61143,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/02/18/Under the Needle - February 18, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-02-18 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 09:51:42',NULL,'KEXP Sessions is the place to go to learn about new music. They\'ve already gotten a lot of exposure for a band called Sheer Mag. Here\'s how they did it: They took a working-class neighborhood in South Philadelphia and recorded some songs.\n\nThey wrote a song called \"What You Want\" for the band\'s first EP, which was released in October. Then they played Coachella and played late-night shows all over the world. They were also on Late Night With Seth Meyers\'s list of Artists You Need To Know. The band also had a singer named Tina Holiday, who was already a big star in the area thanks to her singing in the band \"The Shakes\" . Now they\'re covering the \"mighty buzzcocks\" with their sound. The brothers Seeley, Hart, and Kyle formed the band in the first place. They wanted to capture the vibe of a hardcore band, so they set up an 8-track machine and musicians like Matt Palmer, the guitar player, and Matt\'s brother, Hart\'s bass player, would add their own parts to the mix.\n\nIt was a \"pretty bare bones\" recording process. They named their first and second EPs \"Whatever\" and \"What\'s Up With That?\" . The third EP was called \"Need To Feel Your Love\" , which is even more accessible and accessible sonically. Now the band has released their latest album, \"A Distant Call',NULL,NULL),(61144,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/02/11/Under the Needle - February 11, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-02-11 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 09:29:28',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of Under the Needle , we hear from the California folk of the Wild Reeds. They\'re a band that\'s just released their fourth record, Blind and Brave, and they\'re playing in the studio with a band called KEXP Sessions, which means \"live\" in this case. The Wild Reed\'s fourth record is called Third Or, It\'s Just Lost Track Now, and it was recorded in Boston by WGBH Public. This is a really cool music video. Thanks to all of you. And thanks to our friends at KEXP, who\'ve been working hard to get this show on the air. This week, we\'ve got a special guest, Andrew Whiteman, from C-F.R.U. 93.3 FM. He\'s here to talk about organ donation.\n\nHe says that only 31% of Ontario residents have signed up to donate their organ and tissue in case of death, so there\'s still a lot of work to be done. If you\'re interested in becoming a donor, you can go to the organ donor registry site, BeAdonor.ca, and you can sign up right away. If this is your first time listening to a program like this, you might want to go back and check it out. And remember, if you don\'t want to, you\'ll have to share your wish with your family after you die.',NULL,NULL),(61145,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/02/04/Under the Needle - February 4, 2020 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-02-04 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 09:07:00',NULL,'The song opens the show with the famous line, \"Accidents can happen anywhere, anywhere\". The song is by Robbie Burns, and the narrator describes the song as \"a ghost legallion\".\n\nThe show starts with a song by Lorena McDee, followed by music by Mary Manson and Robbie Burns. The song ends with a poem by Alfred Noah, \"The Sever Highwayman\". The narrator introduces the program to listeners by stating that there are only two people who were born in February: Louis Saint Laurent and Sir Walter Scott. The narrator invites listeners to join the Toastmasters Club and learn how to improve their public speaking skills.',NULL,NULL),(61146,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/28/Under the Needle - January 28, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-28 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 08:51:45',NULL,'This week on Under the Needle we\'re joined by a band called Charlie Bliss, who is also known as Eva Hendrix, Sam Hendrix, Dan Simmons, and Spencer Fox. They\'re a punk band from Brooklyn, New York. They have a new album called Young Enough, which is all about personal issues like sexual abuse and domestic violence. The band is really happy to be able to share their songs with their audience, and it\'s always great to get a shout out from Brooklyn bandstand on free radio. We also catch up with another guest on the show, a journalist named Ramesh Bouchal from Kathmandu, Nepal.',NULL,NULL),(61147,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/21/Under the Needle - January 21, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-21 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 08:30:11',NULL,'This week on Under the Needle, we\'re introduced to the California folk band The Wild Rivers. They\'re known for their self-titled debut record, Blind and Brave . This is one of the first records that\'s popular on Bandcamp, and it\'s full of gorgeous harmonies.\n\nIn fact, according to the band\'s website, they\'ve been releasing their own stuff since they were a trio back in the day. Back then they were called the Morning Afternoon and Evening, and they used to be called a trio. They used to share lead vocal duties and write songs. Now they\'re called a duo. They use electric guitar and singing as their main instruments. The song title comes from a line on their first record, which says \"Blind and Brave\" . They also',NULL,NULL),(61148,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/14/Under the Needle - January 14, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-14 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 08:13:41',NULL,'This week\'s edition of Under the Needle is a live in studio performance by the band trust. The band has been making music together since 2009. Maya is a songwriter and drummer in the band Oustre, and she is also a producer in the experimental pop band Princess Century.\n\nShe has her own solo project called Princess Century, but she is not a member of the band. Robert and Maya formed trust in 2009 to write and release songs together. They had initially signed to a Brooklyn label, Sacred Bones, but they eventually signed to another label, Arts and Crafts. They released a few singles and a couple of EPs on the label, but eventually gave up and moved to Toronto.\n\nMaya now works as a producer and drummer for the dream pop group Oustre. She is also in a band called PrincessCentury, which is the perfect preparation for the last night of a trip to Berlin. Robert continues to work on his own as a songwriter, even if he doesn\'t usually perform live with trust. Maya would then return to working with Robert as an songwriter and producer. Robert switched to Royal Mountain Records for the Destroyer Parts 1 and Destroyer Parts 2 albums.\n\nThe songs trust played on the show are Control Me and Gone. They would like to thank the band and Robert for stopping by their studios. They\'d also like to shout out to the university for their work on this show. The show is hosted by Troy Nelson and produced by Jackson Long. It is an exclusive live session.',NULL,NULL),(61149,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/07/Under the Needle - January 7, 2020 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-07 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 08:00:23',NULL,'In this week\'s Under the Needle, we meet a young musician named Morby. He was raised in Kansas City and moved to Brooklyn to work as a delivery man for a cafe.\n\nHe met other musicians in a band called Woods and ended up playing bass for them. His next album was named best new music by Pitchfork. He would start another band called The Woodsist and start a label with his friends, the Woodsist. He also started another band named The Babies with a friend and roommate, Cassie. They made a record together and then moved to LA for his second album. He kept working and releasing a collection of tracks about New York. He put out a further three records and then a mob of friends supplied him with the studio appellate Dove.',NULL,NULL),(61150,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/12/31/Under the Needle - December 31, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-12-31 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 07:11:48',NULL,'In this week\'s Under the Needle, Troy Nelson and Jenny Lewis discuss Jenny\'s career as a musician. She\'s been making music since she was a child, but she\'s finally gotten to the point where she can make a living as an artist.\n\nShe has released three solo albums, each with a different artist. Her latest is called On the Line and it\'s her first album in over a decade. She says that she feels like a real artist when she goes into a studio to make a record, which is super cool. Jenny plays her latest songs live at KEXP as well as at the Cal State Northridge campus.',NULL,NULL),(61151,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/12/24/Under the Needle - December 24, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-12-24 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 06:53:22',NULL,'The host starts off this show by telling us that it\'s a good thing that people struggle to find their own way in the world. He says that if you\'re not alone, then you should try to talk about it. He tells us that the more people talk about what matters to them, the more they can build a community of people who care about what they care about.\n\nHe feels like the world has changed a lot over the last half-century or so, and that\'s because people are talking more about it and the people who are talking about it are willing to listen to it. The most recent album on Bella Union is called 12 Nudes. It has two great spiritual heroes, James Lindsay, also known as Jay, and the late Canadian poet, Anne Carson. First, James was a punk rocker, and second, Anne was a poet. She wrote a piece called The Glass Essay about how she meditated every day. She called her meditations nudes. She describes them as naked glimpses of her soul. The songs in this live performance are from 12 nudes and also Anne\'s Trans-Angelic Exodus, both on Bella Unearth.\n\nThe KEXP staff is excited to share the live performance with you. They also want to thank Ezra for stopping by. They want to shout out Clara on her show, Get Out of my Head at the university of San Francisco. And finally, they want to tell you that they\'ll be seeing you',NULL,NULL),(61152,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/12/17/Under the Needle - December 17, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-12-17 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 06:29:21',NULL,'In this episode of Under the Needle: The KEX, host Troy Nelson and co-producers Jackson Long, Julianloum, and Josh Moss are joined by Ezra Fuhrmann, who is playing a live set with his band.\n\nThey also have a shout-out to Clara, who was a guest on the KUSF-produced show \"Get Out of my Head,\" which is shot right next to Ezra\'s San Francisco home. The show is also available on KEXP.com. The festival is an annual event that brings together artists, musicians, thinkers, writers, and artists from all over the world. The main event is the \"Guelph 2020 Lecture on Being,\" which will take place on January 24th. The program will feature literary guest Tachell Partridge reading poetry, the Griffin Singers performing with the symphony orchestra, and Robert Enright, an artist, will speak to Eric Fischl, about his career that is \"focused on the undercurrent of suburban life.\n\n\" Clan Agale, a popular program on the campus, is also a part of the festival, and listeners can listen to it on Sundays at noon on the FM station. On this episode, Josh Moss is joined by Francis Habile, the founder of the Horticulture Club, which tries to educate people about horticulture. They brew beer and put in mints, spearmints, and nasturtium flowers, which is like a radish flower.',NULL,NULL),(61153,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/12/10/Under the Needle - December 10, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-12-10 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 06:11:13',NULL,'This week on Under the Needle, we hear from Morby, a musician whose latest record is called \"Oh My God.\" He was raised in Kansas City and moved to Brooklyn, where he met his band mates in the band \"Woods\" and eventually became their bassist. His name soon appeared on the list of best new artists by Pitchfork. The next Woods album was named \"best new music\" by Pitchfork and the people started listening. He also started another band called \"The Babies\" with his friends \"Kevin Ramone of Girls\" and then moved to Los Angeles to start his own band.\n\nHis solo debut album \"Harlem River\" was released and he also wrote and recorded the song \"Beautiful Strangers\" dedicated to the Orlando nightclub shooting victims. The song is a political piece of music, but Morby does not want it to be associated with a specific time or place in history. He wanted it to capture the insanity of \"a time I suppose.\"',NULL,NULL),(61154,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/12/03/Under the Needle - December 3, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-12-03 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 05:56:56',NULL,'This week, Troy brings us a story about a girl named Stella who moved to Australia when she was a child. She was born and raised in a suburb of Perth, and she started singing and playing the piano as a teenager. She studied jazz at Edith Cowan university. Edith was the first female elected to Australian parliament. She is from a middle-class family, but she is very independent and creative. She attributes this to being better in the states like Sydney and Melbourne.',NULL,NULL),(61155,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/11/26/Under the Needle - November 26, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-11-26 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 05:31:23',NULL,'The story of Meg and her band starts in a small town in New York, where Meg attended a highly regarded college music school. They are making a long trip east to Albany, where they are working in bands because they want to be able .\n\n. to play in different styles and play lots. Albany is a great place to be because it has a scene, ebbs and falls but it never ceases. One of Meg\'s bands, Better Pills opened for folk rockers and came up soon here at Under the Needle. Morby persuaded Meg to join his band, and he convinced Meg to move to Los Angles. Meg recorded their first two albums on band camp and split 12\" by 12\".\n\nThey also released their first full album on Woodysyst Records. They played with the Morby band as well as on the War On Drugs winning a Grammy for A Deeper Understanding and on the Front Row Seat To Earth winning a second Grammy. Meg also worked with many other artists on her new album, Placeholder. She went to Wisconsin to work with many collaborators, including Brad Cook, Sharon Van E\'s band, Andrew Sarlo and Tucker Martine, who mixed the album. We\'re excited to share the exclusives of their live sessions with Hand Habits and Are You Serious',NULL,NULL),(61156,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/11/19/Under the Needle - November 19, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-11-19 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 05:18:05',NULL,'Tim Showalter has been through a lot in his life. He was diagnosed with juvenile rheumatoid arthritis, had an affair, his house burned down, and his wife was involved in an affair.\n\nHe kept writing songs and putting out albums. His first album was a slow start, and then he put out the Pope Kill Dragon, which was a big hit. Then he released an EP, which got him signed by Phil Waldorf, who co-founded the band Dead Oceans. His next record was Heal, which would be a little more vulnerable and revealing, but it would also be a bit more personal. Then came the album Hard Love. It was a bit of an attempt to try to escape the self-reflections of Heal, but also to try and get away from the summer festival vibe. He came off the tour tired and asked what to do next. His friend Carl from the band My Morning Jacket asked him if he would ever play music, and he said yes.\n\nThen six hours later he received a call from his manager saying that he was making a record, and that there was studio time. Tim says that on his website, the songs are about \"existing and continuing on\" . He\'s glad that this record is available now for whoever wants to find it .',NULL,NULL),(61157,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/11/12/Under the Needle - November 12, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-11-12 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 04:53:21',NULL,'The show is called \"Compost Juice\" and it is hosted by Isaac, Josh, and Natalie. It is a program about the natural world and how people can benefit from it. The program is produced by Jackson Long, Julian Martlou and Sabell. The music is by American Football.\n\nThe show ends with a shout-out to the band. If you want to watch the music, you can go to kexp.com and find all of their featured music. Isaac and Josh also talk about Ed Video, a Guelph-based organization that offers courses in video production. The organization also has a web site where people can learn how to create their own work. Get started or advance your skills. Get involved in the Ed Video community by becoming a member. Isaac is a student at the University of Guelph. He is a friend of Josh\'s and he is a host of the program called \"Cutter Juice\" . The host is Isaac. Josh is a fun guy and he hosts the program. The earthworms are on the program as well. The students are listening to \"Compost juice\" and Isaac is the host.\n\nHe introduces the show\'s guest, a zoology student named Amanda Semenik. She is a part of Smith\'s Lab. She studies pitcher plants and how they interact with salamanders. She says that a few years ago, a field student found a salamander living in a plant. It was very exciting, she says, because generally, when people think',NULL,NULL),(61158,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/11/05/Under the Needle - November 5, 2019 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-11-05 11:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 04:28:01',NULL,'This week on Democracy Now! we learn that if you have a phone with a built-in FM chip, you can listen to the radio on it. We also learn that there\'s a Spoken Word festival coming up in Guelph, Ontario, Canada, where poets, writers, and spoken word artists will be performing and performing for free.\n\nIn the United States, the Trump administration is moving toward withdrawing from the Paris climate accord. Meanwhile, Yale\'s famous student, Amy Goodman, is in a private jail in Georgia for stage four of her bladder cancer. We\'re also going to look at a new voting system in New York City, called Ranked Choice Voting, which lets voters choose one candidate or the other.',NULL,NULL),(61159,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/10/29/Under the Needle - October 29, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-10-29 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 04:13:26',NULL,'Troy Nelson, host of KEXP\'s \"Under the Needle,\" is back with another exclusive edition of the program. This time, he discusses a band called the Power Poppers. They\'re a Canadian band that\'s been playing since the mid-\'90s. The band has won a bunch of Junos, and even beat out some of the big-name acts like Joni Mitchell and Neil Young for the best Canadian album of the year. They never really hit it big on the American scene, but they\'re always fresh and always sound like they\'ve just been playing.\n\nThey also know how to play the cowbell. And they have a new album coming out this year. So, yes, the band\'s still around. Troy and his crew are psyched to share this live performance with you. They invite you to check it out on KEXP.org. This is the second edition of \"Under The Needle,\" the program that Troy co-hosts with Julian Martlou. And if you haven\'t heard it, then you\'re missing out.',NULL,NULL),(61160,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/10/22/Under the Needle - October 22, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-10-22 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 03:52:37',NULL,'This week on Under the Needle we\'re talking about a band called XX. The band is made up of three women, Betsy Wright, Laura Harris, and Mary Timoney. The women are in a band in Washington, DC, and they\'re all looking for something different from their current bands. They\'ve formed a new band called Rips. They worked with a new producer, Jonah Takagi, and a college graduate, Mitch Easter. They toured with Rips for two years, then they released some of their material from their band, Helium, and then they went on tour with another band, Wild Flag. Then they released their new record, It\'S Real, which was recorded in a studio. They tried to record the drums in isolation, but it just didn\'t work.\n\nThey also tried using a headphone amp on the new album, built by Tom Scholes, a musician who graduated from Bard College and George Mason University. X- Hex\'s new album is out on Merge Records and it\'s available exclusively on KEXP. They want to thank everyone for listening to the show and for checking out the other shows at KEXP slash under the needle.',NULL,NULL),(61161,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/10/15/Under the Needle - October 15, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-10-15 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 03:32:47',NULL,'This is Mac deMond, who is here to talk about his latest album, \"The Country.\" He tells us that he\'s a country music fan, and that what makes his new album so great is its wit and humor and heartbreak.\n\nOrville, on the other hand, is a singer, and he explains that he studied mask making with a French teacher named Jacques Lacoce. Lacoce advocated using a mask that was \"neutral\" and \"ready for any expression.\" He believed this would allow students to express themselves more freely and that the body was the most expressive when the face wasn\'t available. He also believed that the mask allowed Orville to be \"the most sincere\" artist he\'d ever been. The mask, Orville explains, allows him to express himself \"more than it hides.\" Orville sings a song called \"Whoa, Whoa.Whoa.Snake hair, Just a mask,\" and it\'s on his latest record, \"Orville\'s Pony,\" that he sings in a super low voice.\n\nHe\'s got a diverse fan base, and one hopes that Orville is changing the way people think about masks. The show closes by talking about some of the other things they\'re doing on Under the Needle: Josh is talking about \"Not Your Typical Earthlings,\" and Troy is talking to a student from the Sustainability office on campus.',NULL,NULL),(61162,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/10/08/Under the Needle - October 8, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-10-08 12:00:00',86638720,'2024-01-06 03:11:38',NULL,'This week\'s guest is Sarah Tudson, the brains behind the project \"Illuminati Hotties.\" She\'s a punk rocker and songwriter who\'s worked with some of the biggest names in music, including Lady Gaga, Barbra Streisand, and Will Wells. Sarah\'s been writing and recording songs since she was a kid, but she\'s never written a song that\'s actually been performed live. She\'d always been a writer, but, now that she has a live band, she can finally express herself in a way she hasn\'t before. In fact, she\'ll be releasing her first single, \"Kiss Your Frenemies,\" in a few days.',NULL,NULL),(61170,211,'https://ciut.fm/wp-content/uploads/audio/slipmatandfriends.mp3','2023-06-27 20:27:00',0,'2024-01-06 02:50:26',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with Craig, also known as \"Slim Man,\" and his band. The first part of the interview is with Craig talking about the music he listens to. The second part consists of a discussion of the music that Craig listens to, and the reasons for listening to it',NULL,NULL),(61172,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Caribbean Anthology - July 8, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 01:08:23',NULL,'This is a very brief interview with Josh, the founder of Curb Anthology. Josh is very excited about the upcoming festival and tells us that he\'s happy that he finally got the \"House of Reggae\" back in the city. He says that he was on the fence about how he was going to handle it, but now that it\'s back in town, he\'ll be happy. He also tells us about the fact that they have found a venue in town that can handle the capacity for the festival.',NULL,NULL),(61173,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Caribbean Anthology - July 8, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 00:49:04',NULL,'This is the first of two conversations we\'re going to hear from the dude. First up, he tells us that he\'s been busy all summer.\n\nWe can hear it from the way he acts. He wants to thank all the people who\'ve been coming out to his shows. We also get a shout-out to some of the other people that have been at his shows lately. First off, he thanks everyone for coming out, especially the two dudes who are making the music for him: Anthony and Voss.\n\nAnthony is a singer/songwriter from Guelph, Ontario, and she\'s also a musician. She\'d been doing open mic events at the 360, which is a club in downtown Toronto. She also works as a seamstress, which means she creates fashion pieces. She works with Voss, who is in the th\'shirt game. The two of them put on a fashion show last weekend at Royal City Studios, which was a big hit. They also did a pool party too, and the show was a huge success.\n\nThey\'re psyched to be back, since they\'ve done some really cool things in the past.',NULL,NULL),(61174,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Alternativa Latinoamericana - July 8, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 19:00:00',86507648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61175,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Alternativa Latinoamericana - July 8, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 18:00:00',86507648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61176,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Tiempo de Mujeres - July 8, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 20:00:00',86507648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61177,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/08/Mach Vibe Radio - July 8, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-08 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-06 00:23:38',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61180,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3xdsi2/DrMouthCIUTaug12022_fullshow.mp3','2023-08-02 18:37:06',281402048,'2024-01-05 23:11:13',NULL,'The next day, the program begins with a tribute to the Canadian band Moxie. The band\'s lead singer and bassist, Terry Juric passed away on July 18th. The program then turns to another favorite of the band, The Who. The song is called \"Dogs Part 2,\" which is one of the few songs in their catalogue that makes a big impression on the listener. The show ends with a big set by the band. They play some of their best-loved songs, including \"Here Comes,\" a song from the new Spider-Man movie.',NULL,NULL),(61182,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/r6vvat/DrMouth_CIUT_july18_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-07-19 12:27:19',287683328,'2024-01-05 22:37:22',NULL,'Dr. Mouth brings us another edition of the Rock and Roll Party, this time focusing on a tribute show he made to Dallas Good who was a member of the band known as The Sadies.\n\nThis show aired on March 1, 2022, and it\'s full of songs from the band\'s discography. The first song is from their 2004 album Favorite Colors, which is their most famous song. Then they hear Song of the chief musician part 2, the Curdled journey, and Why be so curious when no one knows the truth. It\'s a really interesting song that Dallas wrote and the lyrics are really well-written. He wrote these songs to make people think.\n\nThe next song is a tune from another band called the Unintended, which basically is the Sadies and Rick White, Greg Keeler, and Blue Rodeo. The two of them wrote the songs and put them together. They also produced the album. The last song is on a new album called Internal Sounds, which was released last year. It was called Stop and Start, and it was supposed to be on their new album which was to be released in October.',NULL,NULL),(61183,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/buxby6/Career_B_Aug_28srls.mp3','2023-08-03 21:45:11',143961989,'2024-01-05 22:11:13',NULL,'On this edition of the show, Stephen Armstrong and his team discuss the future of agriculture and food. They discuss the challenges and opportunities facing the world of agriculture, and the role that economics, policy and technology play in addressing these challenges. The show concludes with a discussion of how to address the increasing demands of a rapidly changing world.',NULL,NULL),(61184,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/iw4xz8/Pot_Pourri_July_30713qo.mp3','2023-08-03 21:39:15',287962512,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61185,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/g4k66y/DrMouth_CIUT_july11_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-07-11 18:44:14',285228608,'2024-01-05 21:53:01',NULL,'It\'s time for another edition of Dr. Mouth\'s Rock & Roll Lunch Party. This time, it\'s James Brown. He\'s here with a band called Great and Mighty, and they play some early albums. One of them is called Beer Drinkers, Hell Razors, which is a cover of a classic ZZ Top song called Precious and Grace. The other one is called Halos, and it features early versions of some of the songs from Zappa\'s new collection of music. The band also plays an instrumental called Batgirl, which they call \"a bat girl\" .',NULL,NULL),(61186,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fz4rgv/Career_Buzz_July_26thamr1r.mp3','2023-08-03 21:43:50',143961989,'2024-01-05 21:34:10',NULL,'In this episode, we learn about Frank Camacho\'s career as a successful host and producer of his own radio show and as an organizer of large-scale community festivals and other social events. Before becoming a successful and well-loved host and organizer of events, Frank worked as an insurance agent for over thirty years.',NULL,NULL),(61187,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/xm2bk2/PP_July_237uwhp.mp3','2023-07-25 21:18:57',287962512,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61188,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/23z5cn/0508.mp3','2023-08-05 14:01:53',143961989,'2024-01-05 21:22:41',NULL,'Phil Taylor is the host of the new CIUT FM show, \"Critics Circle,\" and he welcomes a special guest to the show, David Nairn, Artistic Director of the Theatre Orangeville. David has been the Artistic Director at the theatre for 23 years, and he has directed more than 80 plays. David tells us that when he first took the job at the theater, he was acting for Jim Betts. David says that he remembers talking with Jim about directing projects.',NULL,NULL),(61189,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/c6us87/July_19_2023_-_CareerBuzz7nv13.mp3','2023-07-14 19:21:09',67238078,'2024-01-05 20:27:50',NULL,'This morning\'s program is a production of Hoda\' Career Info. It\'s a new edition of Career Buzz. It focuses on the difference between a job and a purpose. The show\'s host is a certified career coach, and she\'s also known as \"Right Career Fit.\" She\'s committed to increasing career literacy among the youth of Canada.\n\nShe looks forward to a whole season of career conversations with other international career professionals. Next up on the show is David Reynolds, who is a former teacher and administrator and the creator of the LeadLearnChange podcast. He\'s the host of the \"Point for the Impact\" project at the professional association of Georgia educators. He is also the author of the book, \"LeadLearnChange. David is a father, husband, and a woodworker. He does not identify as \"a career professional,\" but he\'s on the program because of his leadership in the field of education.\n\nDavid talks about how he thinks that people think of a career when they think of \"Purpose versus Job.\" He thinks that this is because of the fact that there are so many different kinds of jobs now. Gatekeepers have gone, and people can put their work out there on the job board.',NULL,NULL),(61190,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3y5xpd/Pot_Pourri_July_16th69ba4.mp3','2023-07-25 21:17:27',287962512,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61191,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/eg54k7/NF01_09-00.mp3','2023-07-29 14:07:17',143961989,'2024-01-05 20:09:33',NULL,'Phil Taylor, host of \"Classical Undergrounds,\" is joined by Lynn Slotkin and Phil Kahn, two of the most passionate and knowledgeable critics in the business. Phil tells the story of a young woman who has gone to see an opera. The opera is called \"Frog Song,\" and it is a story about identity, about kids singing, and about actors playing children.',NULL,NULL),(61192,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/htbjsv/CareerBuzz-July_12_20236i773.mp3','2023-07-11 16:58:55',9733024,'2024-01-05 19:49:48',NULL,'Welcome to Innovation nation on career buzz. Canada\'s \"unique radio conversation\" that \"empowers lives, enriching careers, and / energises organizations\". Stephen Armstrong is the host of the show. He introduces himself as \"Mr. Armstrong\" and the topic for today\'s program is \"if we want our project to succeed, / we need to do away with project management\".\n\nHe explains that project management is the \"use of specific knowledge skills, tools, and techniques\" to deliver something \"of value to society\". Since 1969, the Project management Institute has been established in the U.S. to advance the skill and professionalize project management. In the United States, \"tens of thousands\" of people have been certified as project managers each year. Stephen asks if project management truly is a profession or if it is a skill',NULL,NULL),(61193,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/2h99nr/Pot_Pourri_July_9th_96lpv.mp3','2023-07-13 21:34:32',287962512,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61194,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/923t5e/NF01_09-00_July_22nda4dci.mp3','2023-07-29 14:06:20',143961989,'2024-01-05 19:29:58',NULL,'Phil Taylor, host of the show, welcomes Bo Dixon, a musician, composer, a teacher, a playwright, and creator of concert. He has written, starred in, and created the music for a number of plays, including Beneath Spring Hill and the Morris Ruddick story. He is also the artistic director of the creative arts lodge, or PAL, for Stratford, which is to take place September 18.',NULL,NULL),(61195,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bdjy8s/JUly_15_2023_crits_c6l56r.mp3','2023-07-15 14:09:17',143961989,'2024-01-05 19:10:25',NULL,'This episode opens with Phil Taylor and Phil Conlon discussing the latest news from the baseball season. They discuss the home run that Vladimir Guerrero Jr hit during the All-Star break, and then they discuss a young player named Gabriel Moreno who hit another home run for the Blue Jays the night before.',NULL,NULL),(61196,169,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/7s7hgr/Indi_Waves_July_31st6y68s.mp3','2023-08-03 21:41:41',143961989,'2024-01-05 18:50:16',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of the show, co-host of Indigenous Waves, Jennifer Sylvester discusses the recent Indigenous Sounds festival at Trillium Park. She also discusses some of her favorite artists from the festival, including Buffy Saint-Marie, who was one of the featured artists on the show. She tells us that her family has a connection to the Poppy John and Purdy bands, and it was cool to be able to be out there supporting them. She concludes by saying that it was a beautiful night and that she\'ll be back next week.',NULL,NULL),(61197,158,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/g2wrsz/RadRev_Aug_n1aftpj.mp3','2023-08-03 21:47:38',143961989,'2024-01-05 18:19:51',NULL,'The Radical Reverend show welcomes Christine Smaller, a co-host for the summer, and Tristan Kuhlman, the president of the PFLAG York Region. The Radical Rev is happy to have Christine back and he introduces her