s are present. He adds that he would like to see the plants from other places, so they can compare the diversity from the U',NULL,NULL),(61326,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - July 10, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 12:12:27',NULL,'This first episode of the new show takes place inside the studio at the Canadian Broadcasting Company in Guelph, Ont. The program\'s guardian, Nicholas Cooper, explains that he is the station\'s manager and that he will be watching the music landscape.\n\nHe would like to pay respect to ancestral territories and local communities across the island from which the show is broadcast. He also wants to acknowledge the indigenous people of the land, and speak to the personal and social relation with it. He says that the majority musical styles featured were adapted from adapting black culture, which originated under circumstances of race oppression over centuries. He thanks the BiPOC community, for their \"too often dismissed\" contributions to the music spheres. He then invites the listeners to listen to the first of two sets, which will be played by the band Deer Hoof. The first set is called \"My lovely cat\" and it is presented by Ramshi.',NULL,NULL),(61327,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Big Sis Radio - July 24, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 11:50:42',NULL,'This week on Big Sis, the host of the show, Cece, welcomes his listeners to the show. He introduces himself as \"Your Big Sis with soon to be Hits\" and goes on to announce that he will be broadcasting live from the festival this weekend. He also announces a new track by Kim mortal, a new tune from Jenny Lewis, a brand new song from Geese, and a new song by The Beatles. All of these new music acts are featured in this episode, so check back often for more.',NULL,NULL),(61328,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/to know the