art of it. The board has over 250 original works that are available for streaming. It also has a new program called \"Inuit and Métis\" which will introduce communities to the stories of their own people. It will also give them the opportunity to screen their own stories in their own communities. The show will also be airing on CFRU 98.3 and on the CFRU website. The Riverfest is coming back to Allora for its 13 th year. The festival will feature music, art, food, and children\'s activities.\n\nTo find out more about Riverfest, visit allora.com/riverfest. On the program, we learn that the festival\'s founder, Alfredo Cachiac, came to Canada from Guatemala as a refugee in 1985. He is the founder of Sunfest, the largest free music festival in the world. Cachac tells us that it is 29 years since the festival was first conceived. He says that he has no idea how many stages he has.',NULL,NULL),(61331,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Ripcord Radio - July 31, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 10:30:37',NULL,'The show starts off with a brief history of the show. It\'s a punk rock show with a lot of music. We start off with some music from Minneapolis, then Minneapolis, Minnesota, then Cumberland, British Columbia, then Tokyo, then Yokohama, then Methuen, then Saskatoon, then DFA, then Los Angeles, then Montreal, and finally, Los Angeles. The show ends with a list of some of the bands that are coming up in the future. The band names are: DFA with that\'s gonna leave a mark, Cloned with suffering, Cave-in with terminal deity, Defi False Authority, DeFi Authority, and DeFi with Thats Gonna leave a Mark.',NULL,NULL),(61333,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 4, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 10:07:58',NULL,'In this episode, we find out that the Alzheimer\'s society of Waterloo Wellington has a music project to help people with dementia. It\'s called the \"Music Project\" and it\'s all about music. They\'re looking for people who can help them set up an iPod for someone living with dementia and then give them an iPod to play music on. If you\'re interested in helping out with the music project, you can find out more at alzamer.ca.',NULL,NULL),(61334,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Blues Around the Block - July 31, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 09:46:54',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61335,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Big Sis Radio - July 17, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 09:29:55',NULL,'The narrator introduces himself as a \"Big Sis\" with the Soon To Be Hits. He tells listeners that he\'s from the Treaty Land of the Mississauga First Nation. He says he\'d never let them down, and he invites listeners to listen to the music on the show. The first song they heard was \"Oceanic Waves\" by Lorde. The second song was \"Bleached by Zune\" and the third was \"Let\'s Go\" by a punk band called Lovers. The fourth song is \"Brewzeless\" by the Guelph artist, ELS. The fifth is \"Traveler\" by another artist named ELS, and the sixth is \"It\'s DNF Time\" by Arlo Park. The narrator goes on to say that the listeners are listening to the show because it\'s about good news, and they\'re hearing about climate change.\n\nThe scientists have invented a new technology called \"white paint\" that can cool buildings. This means buildings can stay cool even in the summer without using up all their cooling energy. This is good news for people who live in poverty, who have less access to cooling, and people who have been discriminated against because of their race.',NULL,NULL),(61336,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/to know the land - July 17, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 18:55:27',NULL,'In this episode of the Know the Land podcast, Byron speaks with the program director of the Greenbelt Foundation, Shelly Petrie. The two discuss the Greenbelt, a 2.1 million-acre protected area stretching from the east to the west across the greater Toronto area. The region includes iconic landscapes like the Niagara Scarpement, the Oak Ridges Moraine, and the Great Lakes. The Greenbelt protects farmland, natural resources, and water resources. The idea of a greenbelt, a vast, protected area, is often mentioned as being larger than the Province of Prince Edward Island. The story behind the Greenbelt begins with a song by Sarah Harmer, which asks, \"If we blow a Hole in the Escarpment, will the Creek still Flow to The Great Lakes?\" This question has been answered by many protection measures over the years. In the early 80s, a number of measures were put in place to protect the escarpment, the Niagara, and Oak Ridge. Then, in the early 2000s, the Green Belt came into existence. It protects farmland and natural resources as well as water resources and agriculture systems. The foundation is an independent charity, which means it receives funding from the province, but it does not have to deal with land-use policy. There are other examples of the importance of protecting the landscape around the world, including the Iron Curtain, a Green Belt created after the fall of the Berlin Wall. There is an ecological, or \"green,\" Green Belt in Australia. There was a Green',NULL,'The Great Lakes: How I Built a Green Belt in the 1980s?'),(61337,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/The Deep House Project - July 24, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 09:10:28',NULL,'This week on the Deep House Podcast, we talk to the host of the CFRU campus\'s old-school music show, Seems Like Old Time, about the upcoming Pirate Festival at Martin Park. There will also be music, art, and food. The show will air on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM every Sunday at 2pm. The program also discusses the upcoming hillside festival, which will take place at the lake in July. The Deep House Project is a local music show that airs every Sunday afternoon on 93.3FM. This week the show talks about the recent political and social events in the world.\n\nFor example, the Supreme Court overturned Roe vs Wade, providing women with the right to choose whether or not to have an abortion in the U.S. It also deals with the pandemic of racism in the United States. The music starts off with Dope by Nathan Barrotto, which is a song about the retro vibe of the \'80s. Then they play a song called Tortugion by Fred Everything, which means \"the Yellow Turtle\" in French',NULL,NULL),(61338,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 31, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 08:52:18',NULL,'This morning\'s topic is solid waste. It\'s all about the Blue Box program. We\'re talking about how cities can be more effective at managing their waste. What\'s more, the province is changing the way it manages waste. From July 2023, all municipalities in the province will transition to a new recycling model. This new model will require that the companies that make Blue Box materials fund and operate their own recycling system.',NULL,NULL),(61339,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Ripcord Radio - July 24, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 08:32:04',NULL,'This week on the Ripcord Radio show, we hear from a bunch of Canadian punk bands, a band from Toronto that\'s going to be playing at the New Friends Fest and some other stuff.\n\nThe first thing we hear is Young Canadians With Where Are You, a song from a single from the late-1970s. The lead vocalist is Jim Bescott, who\'s the lead vocalist for the band. Next, we get some punk from the early \'80s. It\'s called Diodes With Time Damage. And then we get a band called Piper Maru with My Friends Died In Space. The band will be playing as part of the Fest in two weeks. Before that we hear Dillinger 4 from Minneapolis, Minnesota, and last but not least we hear Off with Keep your Mouth Shut from Los Angeles.\n\nThis track was originally released on the 2022 Off LP Free LSD, but it\'s also featured in a movie called Free LSD. So we\'ll hear some music from this album next. Next up, we\'re going to hear the Ramones from Queens. The KKK took our baby away from a record called Pleasant Dreams, the New York mixes. And finally we get something from an album called This City Isnt Big Enough.',NULL,NULL),(61341,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 3, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 08:05:33',NULL,'On this edition of the program, we\'re joined by a music critic named Mac D. He\'s a local musician who\'s been playing all over the place. He plays a blues set that starts off with a tribute to a soul singer named Fats Domino and goes on to include a bunch of other great acts. If you\'re in the area, you can listen to the show on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM station.',NULL,NULL),(61342,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Blues Around the Block - July 31, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 07:48:25',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61343,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Big Sis Radio - July 10, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 07:36:38',NULL,'On this edition of Big Sis, Cece, the host of CFRU 93.4FM, the Guelph-based community radio station, gives a shout-out to another band, the Dirty Nil , who have just released a new single, \"Celebration.\n\n\" Cece also shares some uplifting news about the local economy with listeners, mentioning that this is the week of the July 10th air-conditioning appreciation day and the July 11th energy independence day. He also mentions that he\'s going to be attending the Rock the Park music festival in London with some of his favorite dudes and his dad, his bro, and his love. Cece says that if you haven\'t already made plans to go to the festival, this is a good sign. On the show Cece has brand new music from some of the local acts, including Blonshell and Tupperware Girls, as well as some new tracks from Chromio and US Teke.\n\nThe last track is a jam by the guys from Sun Junkies called \"I Wanna be Your Right Hand,\" and the song is about getting lost in the shuffle. Big Sis also talks about Hope House, a local organization that offers community services like food and health care. One of their services is a food skills class, which is offered twice a month to anyone in the community who wants to learn cooking.',NULL,NULL),(61344,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/to know the land - July 10, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 18:45:00',NULL,'The narrator introduces this week\'s episode of To Know The Land, a show about the connection between the land and the people who live there. The show is produced by the university\'s faculty of science, technology, engineering, and mathematics, as well as the faculty of geography. The narrator is Byron, a student at the university. He\'s interested in plants, and particularly in a group of them called the Amalanchier family, which includes the Juneberry, the Shadbush, and the Saskatoonberry. He listens to the program every week to learn more about these plants. The first thing he does is read a book called \"Shrubs of Ontario\" by James H Soper. The book is written in the early 1980s, and it was put out only in 1982. The narrator notes that the name \"Amlancier\" comes from the French word for \"honey.\" He also notes that some of the flowers are long and some are short. He notes that there are many different kinds of plants that live in the same place, and that it\'s hard to tell which ones are the same. He also says that he likes the fruit, which is a bright red, and then fades to a dark purple. He names his bike Juneberry in honor of the berries. He decides to read some of John Eastman\'s book \"Forest and Thicket\" because he\'s really interested in how it describes plants. It describes plants in very simple terms. The',NULL,'The narrator tells the story of plants that live in the land'),(61345,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/The Deep House Project - July 17, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 07:11:11',NULL,'Aaron plays some of his favorite tracks and tells us that he used to listen to the same station as a kid. He tells us about the use of mix tapes and how they were used to play music back in the days before the iPod.\n\nThe first track we hear is a classic from the early 90s club scene. It\'s called Push The Feeling On and was one of the first tracks we heard on the CFRU. The second track is called So Good To Me and is one of my all time favorite tracks. The third track is a remix from Chris Malinek and his crew called Put It Away. The fourth track is from Nightcrawler and it\'s a classic club track.',NULL,NULL),(61346,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 24, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 06:58:34',NULL,'The police chief discusses the challenges of dealing with auto-setting, drug dealing, and bike theft. He explains that News Benefit, the police department\'s broker, has done a great job, but that there are so many crimes that they can\'t do all they could. News Benefit focuses on certain individuals and groups of individuals who are causing harm to the community. When talking about bike theft, he explains that they have been here for two years and that his son lost his bike the first day he moved to Centennial. He tells the listeners that there is no cure, but there is a constant balancing of resources. He says that they need to be vigilant in making sure that their property is protected.\n\nHe adds that they must be very vigilant about this because petty theft is costing them thousands of dollars. The police department needs to be more efficient, he says, because the police budget is so tight. He also asks about the future of policing, and he asks if they will be able to help people in the future without moving people away from their homes',NULL,NULL),(61347,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Ripcord Radio - July 17, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 06:35:58',NULL,'This week on the Ripcord Radio show, host Jamie plays a bunch of new Canadian punk rock tracks. First up is a song called \"That Was Too Easy\" by Dead Bob. Next up is an EP called \"Coming Up Roses\" by \"The Nasties\" from Montreal. And then there\'s a track called \"Sky Is Falling\" by The Nasties from Guelph, Ontario. Next we hear from San Diego a band called \"Pitchfork with Placebo\" and then we hear a song from another band called Drive Like Jehuu. Finally, we hear an English band named \"Super Kill Me Now\" from Toronto.',NULL,NULL),(61349,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 2, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 06:10:58',NULL,'This week on Morning Soul Shake Up, the theme of the show is \"Give a Life, Would You Take It?\" This is an important message for the listeners because only 31% of the people in the province have signed up for organ and tissue donation. By becoming a donor, you can save up to eight lives and improve the quality and safety of life for as many as 75 people.',NULL,NULL),(61350,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Blues Around the Block - July 24, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 05:49:57',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music being played on the Alligator Records C23 compilation. The program then moves to the 2021 Alligator Records compilation, \"50 Years of Genuine House Rock\'n\'Roll\". The program ends with a performance of the song, \"Let it ride, Let it go, Let\'s ride, let\'s go\" by Mac Dee.',NULL,NULL),(61351,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/The Deep House Project - July 10, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 05:11:25',NULL,'The show starts out with a classic track called \"Good Life\" by Kenny Glasgow. The show ends with a mix of acid tracks. The program opens with a discussion on how many Canadians are enjoying the summer. The DJ says it\'s important to get outside and exercise, especially since the elections are coming up this week. He says he almost wanted to play some of his favorite tracks from the 80s, but he decided to stick to the \"acid theme.\" The DJ also mentions the recent Texas school shooting and how it has a huge influence on the program tonight.\n\nThe music is all about preventing such tragedies, whether it be with toys or guns. The first track is Cloud Nunn\' \"Come Home,\" the second is Brock Edwards\' \"The Madness,\" the third is Nightcrawler \"Push the Feeling,\" the fourth is Sam Adams\' \"distant memories,\" the fifth is Black Coffee \"who made who silences the secrets,\" and the sixth is Murney\'s \"Circles.\" The program closes with Frank Walker\'s and Sam Felds \"Maddux,\" which means \"close to me.\"',NULL,NULL),(61352,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 24, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 04:52:41',NULL,'This week\'s episode of the Breakfast at the Rise is called \"The Guelph Police Services.\" It\'s hosted by Phil Alt, and it\'s all about the Guelph Police. Our guests are Peter McShirley the chair of The Guelph Police Board, Gordon Colby the Chief of Police, and Steve Gill the Deputy Chief. They\'re talking about issues like safety, noise, and homelessness. Phil introduces each of the guests, and then introduces the Chief himself.',NULL,NULL),(61353,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Ripcord Radio - July 10, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 04:30:45',NULL,'In this program, the host of Ripcord Radio goes through a list of songs that he has collected for the show.\n\nHe starts off by telling us that he\'s going to play some music from the West coast. He\'s got songs from the San Francisco band Spitboy with Unknown, an album from Vancouver called Premonition , an EP from Handheld called The Mark , a CD from the band The Holdouts , and an album by Fugazi from Washington DC called In On The Killtaker . Then he\'ll play some songs from two other bands that are coming to town later in the week. First up, we\'re going to hear some songs by Soulside with the Tambourine from their new studio album, which is their first in twenty-five years. Next up is a song from an album called Carinning, which features a bunch of bands from the New York City scene.\n\nThen we\'ll hear a song by a band called The Spoils Of War from New York called From the Dumpster To the Grave from Fat Records.',NULL,NULL),(61355,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 1, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 04:06:45',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61356,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Blues Around the Block - July 24, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 03:50:43',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61357,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 17, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 03:32:12',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the Breezy Breakfast Podcast focuses on a topic of discussion for the next week: the safety of the downtown area. The guests for the week are Chief, Deputy Chief, and member of board Peter McSchnay, and Erin for her presentation and for answering all of her language questions. The next Breezy breakfast will be on Guelph Police Services and will focus on the safety downtown.\n\nThe listeners can also join the program from their own homes by signing up with the Zoom link and listening to the program live every Thursday at 8am. The program is produced by David. David also introduces us to the Ed Video hub for the creation of art, film, and documentaries. The goal of the hub is to provide a place where anyone can learn, create, and display their work. In addition, Ed Video offers a series of year-round workshops and educational opportunities. Get started or advance your skills, find challenges, and develop a community of collaborators through its year-long series of workshops. Get access to professional equipment, as well as access to a wide range of staff and professionals.\n\nApply for your skills with professional quality equipment at the hub. Become a Member by visiting our website or by visiting the partially accessible location, 404 York Road. Here\'s another program that David and his friend Amorowa run called Perk. Perk is a spoken word show that airs on the campus and community FM station CFRU. It\'s a show that focuses on',NULL,NULL),(61359,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 31, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 03:04:58',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61360,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Blues Around the Block - July 17, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 02:46:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61361,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 17, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 02:28:20',NULL,'This week on CFRU\'s program, we hear from the host, James Gordon, about gender. He introduces us to Erin, who is the first openly nonbinary counselor at the Breezy-Breakfast. She is also known as the \"Gender 101\" speaker, and she\'s here to talk about the language and etiquette of gender. She explains how people of different genders interpret gender and how the different cultures interpret gender differently.\n\nShe also talks about English grammar and how people can use it to their advantage. We\'re also introduced to our moderator Morgan, who will be moderating the program. It\'s International Non-binary Persons Day. The program is celebrating this day by giving a land acknowledgement to all the people of the province and giving a territorial acknowledgement to everyone. This is also the day that the province refuses to even search for murdered Indigenous women in the garbage dump. The province of Manitoba refuses to search the dump for these women, which is why the host says that if it weren\'t for two white women, the government wouldn\'t be doing such a thing.\n\nHe also notes that there are multiple Indigenous communities in the province, and that everyone has a responsibility to their territory and their place in the world. Finally, the host asks if Erin would like to talk more about herself. She\'s a councilor in Guelph, and two years ago she came out as a gender non-conforming person. She says that gender is a great way to learn more about oneself',NULL,NULL),(61363,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/28/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 28, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-28 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 02:07:28',NULL,'The narrator introduces us to a new character named Sheikh Hussein. He\'s the host of a weekly music show on the campus of the University of Guelph. The show airs every day from 8 am to 9 am on 93.3FM in Guelph and 101.5FM in Hamilton. The narrator tells us that he\'s got a funky blues doctor on his team, and the listeners should listen to his music.',NULL,NULL),(61364,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Blues Around the Block - July 17, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 01:47:14',NULL,'Mac Dee is a student at the University of Guelph who hosts a weekly music show called \"Blues Around the Block.\" He is a member of the \"Water Street Blues Band.\" He also performs on the local FM station, 93.3FM in the city of Guelph. He also has several other songs on the show, including \"Angel in My Bed\" and \"Hook and Got Money.\"',NULL,NULL),(61365,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 10, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 01:31:53',NULL,'The conversation turns to the issue of litter. The conversation\'s first topic is a famous advertising campaign of the 70s. The ad featured a guy who was crying because he was throwing litter out the window, but the man was actually an Italian guy from New Jersey who was wearing an Italian shirt.\n\nThe point is that we do all have a role to play. If you put a Tims in your driveway, people are going to throw the litter out to make room for the new drink. The problem is that it\'s not okay for people to clean up after their shift, which is why they do it. The idea that people have to do this is not something that\'s going to happen in a perfect society.\n\nThe next conversation is about the situation in Guelph. The city had been cleaning up its green in April and May, but unfortunately, it looks back the same way it did in May. The issue of plastics and micro-plastics is a big one for the group. The first thing that the group looks at is the bottle, which the group\'s representative says is disturbing because it doesn\'t contain any glass.\n\nThe second thing that they look at is what\'s in the water, which we\'ll talk about later. The group is going to talk about this in a bit, but before then, the conversation goes back to the bottle. The representative says that he\'s totally in agreement with everything the group is saying. He\'s also',NULL,NULL),(61367,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 27, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 01:06:59',NULL,'This is the second in a series of two-part stories. The first is about Morning Soul ShakeUp, a daily program on CFRU. The second is about the web site, where you can listen to all of the shows, listen to the program guide, and even find out how to become a volunteer.',NULL,NULL),(61368,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Blues Around the Block - July 10, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 00:46:11',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61369,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Breezy Breakfast Radio - July 10, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 00:28:29',NULL,'The program begins with a brief introduction to the listeners, who are listening to the program on Guelph\'s campus and community station CFRU- 93.3. The program\'s guests are: Nectar Tampetopolous, the general manager for water and wastewater services at the City of Guelph, and Wayne Fernandez who is a resident of Guelph and a concerned citizen about litter.\n\nThe general manager of water and Wastewater Services at the city, Nectar, is here to answer technical questions regarding water conservation and water protection. He also discusses the many concerns surrounding food and potato. He discusses the impact of water softeners on water quality, the size of the fat birds in London\'s sewer system, and how to deal with litter. Phil, the host of the program, introduces the two guests and discusses the city\'s territorial recognition. The city acknowledges the Mississaugas, the credit First Nation of the Inishbek peoples, who live on their traditional territory. The host then introduces the other guests and introduces them to their host. They are: Wayne Fernandez, a resident and concerned citizen, and Nectar, the General Manager of Water and Wastewater services for the city. They discuss the many practical concerns surrounding water conservation. They also discuss the impacts of food and potatoes.',NULL,NULL),(61371,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 26, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-03 00:06:08',NULL,'The Morning Soul Shake Up On CFRU FM is a public service announcement about organ and tissue donation. It\'s a great opportunity to save someone\'s life, but only 31% of the people in Ontario are willing to donate their own organs and tissue. If you\'d like to become an organ or tissue donor, you can go to beadonor.ca and sign up for a chance to save a loved one\'s lives.',NULL,NULL),(61372,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Blues Around the Block - July 10, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 23:46:50',NULL,'The show starts off with a recap of the previous shows. It\'s been a while since we heard a recap, so it\'s time for one. We start off with Strawley and howlin\' for darlin\', then we hear Crooked Eye Tommy\'s \"Hot Coffee and Pain,\" Donald Ray Johnson\'s last two dollars,\" Johnny Max Band\'s Time Well Waste\'d,\" Selwyn Birch\'s unusual \"Drive,\" Michael Jerome Brown\'s Please Help,\" and the Cashboxes Kings\' \"Hot Little Miss\" . And then we finish off the',NULL,NULL),(61374,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 25, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 23:27:11',NULL,'On this edition of Morning Soul Shake Up, we find out about a new summer concert series in Bellwood called Canadian Sound Waves. The series will take place every Saturday from July 1st through September 2nd at the old schoolhouse at 24 Broadway Street. The full lineup is as follows: Ian Andrews, the Vaudevillain , Nelson Sobrial , Astro Surf , and others.',NULL,NULL),(61376,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 24, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 21:06:04',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61378,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/21/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 21, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-21 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 20:47:37',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61380,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 20, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 20:28:18',NULL,'The new morning show is called the \"Morning Soul Shakeup\" and is a local all-you-can-eat breakfast. It\'s all about local music and local happenings. There\'s also a lot of local news and politics. You can listen to the show at any time of day or night. The program is hosted by a local guy named Phil. Phil is a super-duper musician. He\'s a little obsessed with music. Phil has a big ego and thinks he\'s the king of the world. Phil\'s like, \"Gee, I wish I had more music.\" Phil is super psyched to be a part of this new program.',NULL,NULL),(61382,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 19, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 19:08:06',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part interview with Karen Funk, a volunteer at the University of Guelph\'s Campus and Community Radio Station, CFRU-FM 93.3 FM, and the host of the Morning Soul-Shake-Up, a weekly program that airs on CFRU.org.',NULL,NULL),(61384,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 18, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 18:48:09',NULL,'This week on Morning Soul Shake Up, we\'re going to hear about a new program that\'s making a big impact on the community: the CHAMP CHAMP program, which works to help kids who have lost their limbs. If you\'ve lost your key tag, the WarAmps can return it to you via courier. And since you support a great cause, kids who lose their keys will be able to use the artificial limbs that they need to live a normal life.\n\nYou can order your key tags right now at 1-800-250-3030 or Waramps.ca . The program also discusses the upcoming Hillside Festival, which is going to take place at the lake from July 28 th to 30 th . Get your tickets to the festival now at the festival\'s official website.',NULL,NULL),(61385,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/23/Seems Like Old Times - July 23, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-23 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 18:29:22',NULL,'This chapter opens on a stagecoach in the middle of the American West. It\'s a beautiful day, and the passengers are looking forward to the day. They\'re all tired, but the young woman is wearing her new clothes, the young boy is wearing his old clothes, and a cowboy is riding across the stage with his son. The cowboy is wearing a shirt with a large \"B\" stitched on it. The woman is thrilled, and says she\'s used the cowboy\'s shirt for a pillow, and she\'ll give it to the cowboy if he wants it.\n\nShe\'ll take it back to Cinnabar, and then she can have it. Ben Farley and Jesse Meredith, two young men who have come to the American west, are on the stagecoach. Ben is a new guy, and he introduces himself as \"Jesse Meredith.\" He says he\'s going to the town of Cinnabar to buy a cattle ranch. He\'s also going there to stay with his friend, the cowboy, who\'s named \"Bill McGrath.\" They\'ve just come from Wyoming, and they\'re both excited to see what life is like in the new place.\n\nThey all agree that it\'s easier to just live in the present than it is to be in the past. Ben says he wants to start a dress shop, and Jesse says he plans to open a business of his own. They both agree that they\'ve got a lot to learn',NULL,NULL),(61386,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 2, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 18:08:00',NULL,'The show starts off with a song called \"Pine Song\" from Meadow Trail, followed by a track called \"Tynum House\" or \"Tinum House\" from another project called \"Crook Circle\" from Sun Rain, then a track from \"Walker Walker\" from Hush Hush Records. A track from White Lab by \"Soaring Johansson Recordings\" called \"The Wound\" and another from \"One Mile North\" from a 2002 release called \"Sketches from back then\" . Then a track \"Border Crossing\" from \"Brief Climps\" from his \"Innate\" , a track by \"J.Ryan Howpenny\" from the \"Again and Again\" release , and a song by \"Gia Margaret\" from her new release \"Romantic Piano\" ).',NULL,NULL),(61388,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 17, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 17:46:16',NULL,'In this edition of Morning Soul Shake Up, Michael Rolfe discusses how to promote a business, event, or initiative on CFRU\'s public service announcements program. If you\'re looking for a local business to advertise on the air, you can get help from CFRU.',NULL,NULL),(61389,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/23/Seems Like Old Times - July 23, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-23 14:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 17:29:32',NULL,'On this program, we get two hours of music from the 30s to the 50s and then some old-time radio memories. First up, we hear a tribute to the late Tony Bennett, who died on Friday, age 96. Then we hear some songs from the past, like a little bit of jazz from the \'50s. And finally, we learn that the CFRU 93.3 program will not be airing on Sunday, so if you\'re looking for a show to tune into, you can listen to it here.',NULL,NULL),(61390,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 2, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 17:07:54',NULL,'This episode of the music program The Stillness and The Dancing is a continuation of the previous week\'s program. It begins with a description of the host and introduces its listeners to the music. The host explains that he is in a funny situation this week, as he\'s house-sitting for friends.\n\nHe\'s also looking forward to a trip north to visit family. He says he\'ll be finishing up the last week of his studies and then he\'d like to go north for a vacation. He talks about the weather and how it\'s warmed up in his house. He hopes listeners are also feeling the same way. The music program begins with the soundtrack to a movie called Little Fish, which is a \"haunting sci-fi\" movie.\n\nThe track called \"The Beginnings\" is one of the tracks from the soundtrack. The rest of the program is about ambient, experimental and modern composition. The first track is called \"Little Fish,\" followed by \"Soy,\" \"Once It\'s all on the ground,\" \"You Shouldn\'t have to Worry Like this,\" \"Oro,\" and \"Midsummer.\" The second track is \"Midwinter.\" The third track is a folk song.',NULL,NULL),(61391,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/End Credits - August 2, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 16:52:19',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the new movie, The New York Times bestseller, which is set to hit theaters this week. The show\'s host, Adam Donaldson, introduces us to Tim Phillips, the co-host of the show. They talk about the new film and the latest in local culture. Tim tells us that he\'s not sure if the audience has seen the movie.',NULL,NULL),(61392,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Humanoid Radio - August 1, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 16:29:00',NULL,'The first segment of the Humanoid Room begins with a track by a Japanese artist named Raishi Sakato. He uses the name Vsior-Corskspr to describe his piece. Then he has a piece by Funky Porcini called Incredible Vinyl. Then David Brantor has a saxophone piece called Four Stories. Then there is a saxophone track by Piers Ulus called Solace Shard.\n\nThen a track called Castle Ith. And then there is another saxophone track called Indigo Dawn. So, we\'ve got some more music. We learn that some scientists believe that real extraterrestrials would use a form of communication known as \"universal communication\" . And we learn that terrestrial radio has been around for a long time. The key is the technology. The final piece of music on this program is a track from the Asta Hirok album. The name is Never Lose AnOpportunity.\n\nThen it\'s followed by DJs off the Album Music Beds for different Moods. Then they have a Climate of Clap. Then Groundation Damage off the Dreaming from an iron gate and a track named Between earth and Zion. Then Jace, Jace Swiss, Michael Leonhardt, and Keon Radio Harold all off the single release of the Chase. And finally, we have Dragon Child off the self-titled Album and a',NULL,NULL),(61393,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Wild Combination - August 3, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 16:07:19',NULL,'If you\'ve ever wanted to be a part of the community, you\'re in luck. The University\'s radio and media center offers a variety of volunteer opportunities, from music and production to public service announcements and live events. If you love music and want to help make the community a better place, you can join the Clan of Gale team. It\'s a two-hour program where you can listen to some of the best music in the world and learn to play your favorite instrument.\n\nYou can also start your own show if you want. If your goal is to promote a local business or event, the university can help you. You don\'t need to be an expert in any field, just know how to promote. We\'ve got a staff member who\'ll help you out with the whole process.',NULL,NULL),(61394,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - August 1, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 15:48:00',NULL,'This week on the program, the Lich and his victim are back on the show. They\'re broadcasting out of the \"pit of despair\" that is \"Gau of Ontario.\" They\'ve got three tracks from \"Isidors,\" including \"Dark Knight Genesis,\" \"Wave Rider,\" \"Synth Army,\" and \"Cyber Love.\n\n\" We\'ve also got two from \"Terminal Annihilation,\" \"Vengeance,\" \"My Man\'s Replicant\" and \"Longest Tolerated Kitchen.\" We apologize for not having a good time last week. The Lich apologizes for not being able to beat \"some pretender\" last week, and says that pretenders swooped in last week and tried to \"beat\" him. He apologizes again for not doing it this time. He\'s \"a little bit of the bitch.\" Okay, so it\'s time to get back to the program.\n\nThis week, the show is called \"Respectful Child.\" It\'s hosted by Ray Spoon. He tells us that the Art Gallery is having an exhibit called \"Alison Norrulins,\" \"Amateurs\" and Imaginaries\" and Jose Luis Torres has an exhibit titled \"Out of the Blue.\" The Art Gallery also has a community book sale coming up. You can find out more about the sale at the Friends of the Public Library\'s 15th annual Community Book Sale.',NULL,NULL),(61395,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - August 2, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 15:32:32',NULL,'In this episode, we meet up with a fellow graduate student named Louis Colarouotolo, who is studying the science of replacing gluten, a food that contains gluten. He\'s excited to share his research with us because he\'s a big fan of gluten. We learn that replacing gluten isn\'t as easy as it sounds, but he\'ll do his best to make it tasty. The two students discuss the various ways in which they\'re using pressure to make gluten-free bread.',NULL,NULL),(61397,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/14/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 14, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-14 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 15:07:52',NULL,'The morning soul shake-up is a new show on the CFRU 91.3 FM New York and CIOI 105.1 FM Hamilton. The show is all about giving back to the community. It\'s all about making a difference in people\'s lives.\n\nThe Alzheimers Society of Wellington is looking to raise money to buy music for people living with the disease. They need volunteers to set up the iPods and play the music. If you donate 75 dollars, you get an iPod, and if you donate 150 dollars you get a touch of an iPod. They\'re also looking for people who donate all of their iPods, gift cards, or money. If that\'s not enough, they\'re looking for other people to help them out.',NULL,NULL),(61398,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/16/Seems Like Old Times - July 16, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-16 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 14:52:41',NULL,'The novel opens with a flashback to the day when Nancy arrived in New York and was waiting for her husband at the airport.\n\nWhen she arrived, she told him she was tired of modeling and that she had to make some money. He said he was glad she was there and told her that he was returning to Bayville that night. Nancy told him that she was in love with him and that they were going to get married. He told her he was suspicious of her and she said she wanted to marry him. She told him about her love for him and he told her to be careful with his spending. She said she was going to marry and that he should not be too careful.\n\nHe asked her what she meant and she replied that she loved him and she was not going to waste her life waiting for him to marry her. She then told him he was often the mansion of bills. He scolded her and said that he didn\'t like to work at the house because he was so lazy.\n\nShe replied that he shouldn\'t be so lazy because he wouldn\'t have to paint next year. He then told her she was the most important person in the world and she should be careful about spending money with him. He explained they had to have money and he proposed that they get rid of the clothes they were wearing and leave the money in a safe. Nancy said she would do that but that she would like to leave the outfit when she had money and just how she would',NULL,NULL),(61399,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 26, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 14:32:01',NULL,'The host launches into a long list of tracks from some of his favorite independent artists, including a reissue of Talk West\'s album Black Coral, a new track by Saiawala atoh, and a new song by Arrow Wounds.\n\nThe group is working on an album series called \"The Theory Anthropocene,\" which consists of four parts. The first part is called \"In the Octopus Pond,\" and the second part is \"The Slow Boiling-Amphibian Dream State,\" which will be coming out later this year. The band also has a new release called Waters, which is a beautiful piece of music off a single track called \"Sun Rain.\" The band has also released a song called \"Le Onde, the Waves,\" which is based on a book called The Waves by Virginia Woolf. The song is a little bit of a departure from the typical underground noise, but it\'s still interesting. The other tracks on the program are some drone music from \"Good Night, and Good Morning,\" and some music from the book, \"The Waves.\"',NULL,NULL),(61400,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/End Credits - July 26, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 14:15:45',NULL,'This is the first of a two part interview with Peter Wesley Salmon, a student at the University of Guelph. The first part of the interview is about the craziness of the recent theatrical release of the new film \"Barbecue.\" The second part is about \"End Credits,\" a weekly movie show hosted by Adam A Donaldson. The show airs Wednesdays at 3pm on the campus of the university. The program discusses the latest movies and pop culture, including the meta-fantasy comedy \"Barbele,\" and the first film of the upcoming \"Barbenheimer.\"',NULL,NULL),(61401,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Humanoid Radio - July 25, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 13:49:56',NULL,'The second segment of the Humanoid Radio program begins with a track called Late Night Tales, followed by a track from the album Night Shift, a track titled Shallow, a song from the Ringo album, and a song titled Wawa. The third segment begins with another track called Shallow and follows it up with a song called Wawa, and the fourth segment ends with another song called Day 21.\n\nThe Humanoid Dio program ends with a mix of tracks from Iyum Ishitu, Kid Koala, Slow Pitch Sound, Fossil Radio, Edzil, Wolf Clan Exit, Devontae, Palm Skin Productions, and Soft Radio. The program ends on the program with a show about the upcoming hillside festival. The festival will take place at the Greenbelt, an area near the Guelph lake. Tickets are now on sale for the festival.',NULL,NULL),(61402,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Wild Combination - August 3, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 13:08:47',NULL,'This short, educational PSA is designed to educate the public about the need for organ and tissue donation and to encourage people to consider becoming a donor. The PSA is narrated by a young man named Mike Willis, who has been a heart recipient. He says that if someone had not signed up to donate, he would not have been alive today. The next time you\'re in the mood for music, check out the new website of the campus radio station, CFRU.org.',NULL,NULL),(61403,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - July 25, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 12:46:31',NULL,'The Lich returns to Walfontario to tell his listeners that he has just finished listening to four tracks from his latest album, \"Isidore\" . The first track is \"Commander in Arms,\" followed by \"Headhunter,\" \"Cyber Funk,\" and \"Isidore.\" The second is \"Maximum Turbo Overdrive,\" \"Gundak Saint,\" and the third is \"Karl Casey.\" He tells the listeners that they should listen to \"this kind of record\" while he makes a new one.',NULL,NULL),(61404,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - July 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 12:34:26',NULL,'The narrator says that farmers love to use cover crops because they provide them with more nutrients than they would otherwise need. The narrator is not a huge fan of the Canadian monarchy, but he is willing to hear more about what cover crops can do for farmers. The two of them are both graduate students at the university, so they\'re both listening to this program to learn something new. Before we get to the program, the narrator asks how he\'s doing. He\'s pretty good, he says. He tells us that he is from Woodstock, which is about 45 minutes away from the university.\n\nHe says he grew up on the farm. He got his undergraduate degree in crop sciences at the same university, which he says was kind of weird because he didn\'t know what he wanted to do. He was like, \"I\'ve been a farmer my whole life, so I\'m going to do this master\'s program.\" It sounds like an awesome origin story. He adds that he thinks people in the cities don\'t really understand that food comes from farms.',NULL,NULL),(61406,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 13, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 12:07:46',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61407,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/16/Seems Like Old Times - July 16, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-16 14:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 11:54:15',NULL,'On this program, we\'re back in the old days of music and radio. We\'re talking about a song called Kiss of Fire, which was recorded in April 1952 and went to the top of the pop chart in April of that year.\n\nWe also have a song by Rod Stewart called \"From As Time Goes by\" which went to number two in the American Songbook in 1952. And then we\'ve got some news about Rod, who just wrapped up his tour in Edinburgh with his sister Mary. The sisters sang a duet of his 1975 song \"Sailing. He introduced his sister as he walked onstage at the castle. He later told her that she is on a rock \'n\' roll stage and loves it adding it and continues to be taught about life. And finally, we get some news on the death of Lisa Marie Presley, who died of complications of a bowel obstruction rather than a heart attack. She was 54 years old at the time of her death. And this is the last song we\'ll hear on this program. There\'s going to be an Elvis tribute in Wellington on July 22nd.',NULL,NULL),(61408,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 26, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 11:27:20',NULL,'',NULL,'The \'minimal post-rock\' music begins with a new album'),(61409,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/End Credits - July 19, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 11:14:33',NULL,'On this program, we catch up with a guy named Adam Donaldson, who\'s a big fan of Hallmark\'s Christmas in July. He\'s also a huge fan of the 100 Days Of Horror movies, which are supposed to start in August and run through Christmas. He wants to know when they\'ll be airing their first Christmas movies. Adam tells us that he can\'t wait to hear about it.',NULL,NULL),(61410,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Humanoid Radio - July 18, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 10:46:30',NULL,'Alan is the host of a new music show called Humanoid that airs on a local station called CFRU FM in Manchester, England. Alan plays a selection of new music from artists like Porcini, Divat Jenny , Mary Ancheetta Quartet , E.B Soda , Archie Starch , Dread Horn , and more. Alan explains that since the first contact between humans and the extraterrestrials was by radio, the technology has advanced tremendously.',NULL,NULL),(61411,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Wild Combination - July 27, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 01:00:00',86638720,'2024-01-02 10:27:11',NULL,'This week, Sam, Marty, and Kevin host a new program on CFRU. They\'re called \"Tales from the Bridge\" and they interview science fiction authors, directors, and other creative types. If you\'re in the market for a rehearsal space or a jam space, you can find it at Silence, a new music venue and art gallery in downtown Guelph. Silence rents out the space to artists and creative types all the time for parties, concerts, and workshops. So if your idea is to run a party, host a dance party, or host a workshop, Silence can help.',NULL,NULL),(61412,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - July 18, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 10:05:12',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61413,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - July 19, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 09:56:31',NULL,'In this rebroadcast of the original episode, we hear from a student at University of Guelph named Louis Colarusolo. He is a student trying to get a Ph.D in food science at the university. He likes to see what other graduate students are learning and this week he\'s talking to Serena McDermid, a teacher who\'s trying to learn how to teach a better way of teaching. The type of student who Serena is teaching is refugees. And she\'s teaching them how to control their environment and how to interact with trauma.',NULL,NULL),(61415,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 12, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 09:29:47',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61416,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/Seems Like Old Times - July 9, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 09:16:02',NULL,'The next day, Jack Ellis is found dead from a lead poisoning. He was found dead in his hotel room 609, the same hotel where he was staying when Jane Carter was murdered. The next morning, Jack is in the middle of a conversation with Mary when he realizes that the conversation has gone awry. He wants to speak with her immediately, but he knows that she is busy with Alice\'s case. He decides to call her and tell her that he has found Jack Ellis dead from lead poisoning and that he wants her to wake up and find him.',NULL,NULL),(61417,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 19, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 08:51:37',NULL,'In this second hour of The Stillness and The Dancing, CFRU\'s Joel Cuthbert continues his program with a mix of ambient and folk music. He starts with a track called Golden Brown from Luminous, which he plans to butcher, but hopes that Sejawala Atu will pronounce correctly.\n\nNext, he plays a track from Talk West, which is a reissue of Black Coral Sprigg\'s Luminous, and then another from Arrow Wounds, called The Minimal Guitars Loops. Finally, they play a song from Lost Tribe Sound\'s Theory Anthropocene series, a four-album series that they\'re currently working on. The first one is called In the Pond, and it\'s part of a series called The Theory Antrope, which describes the idea of individuals being able to transform into animals or creatures by means of a shape-shifting phenomenon.\n\nThere\'s also a short story in the series that accompanies this, so you can read the whole thing on the Lost Tribe label\'s Bandcamp page. They also have a new release called Boiling the Amphibian Dream, which will be coming out soon. Another track from Waters, called Sun Rain, is a kind of aquatic drift. We\'re also introduced to Ludovico\'s and Aldi\'s releases, which are all based on Virginia Woolf\' book The Waves.',NULL,'The Stillness And The Dancing premieres Tuesday on CFRU-933FM'),(61418,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/End Credits - July 12, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 08:30:17',NULL,'On this episode of the End Credits podcast, the host and his co-host discuss the state of the movie business. They talk about the fact that they are nearing the end of their review windows for the year, and they decide to rank the movies they\'ve seen thus far in the year and the ones they\'re looking forward to seeing. The first movie they\'ll be looking at is Master Gardener, which they think is the best movie so far released in 2023. The second is The Secret Life of Walter Scott, which the host thinks is going to be a downer because of its self-serious tone.',NULL,NULL),(61419,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Humanoid Radio - July 11, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 22:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 08:10:05',NULL,'The second part of \"Humanoid Radio\" begins with a track called \"Whirlwind\" from Artemis, followed by tracks from Peter King, Kuna Maize and two versions of \"Me and Me Princess\" from Lightning Head Bigga Bush, and then a track from the Mary Ancheta Quartet. The station also includes tracks from Edzilu, Ayumi Ishtiu, and Ringo Drums. The program concludes with a message from James Gordon, the host of the CFRU FM 93.3 station in Guelph, regarding mental health services in the province. If you are in need of help, you can call toll-free 1-866-531-26.',NULL,NULL),(61420,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Wild Combination - July 27, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 07:49:38',NULL,'The next day, the festival is back. This time, it\'s going to be a full-blown festival. There\'ll be music, performances, workshops, and local artisans all over the place. Get your tickets to the festival now.',NULL,NULL),(61421,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - July 11, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 07:29:01',NULL,'The Dentist returns to the sound of things. He\'s back from a week\'s vacation and he\'s recording live from his torture office. He says he\'ll be back in a few minutes. He also says he has a new CD out called \"Dark Stronauts Galactic Genocide\", which is a collection of tracks by the band. The first track is \"Starbirth,\" the second is \"Venomous Dance,\" the third is \"Monolith,\" and the fourth is \"Bloody Paradise.\" We\'ll hear more of',NULL,NULL),(61422,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - July 12, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 07:17:46',NULL,'The students discuss their educational history. Caroline is from Quebec and received her undergraduate and masters degrees at McGill University.\n\nAfter graduating, she decided that she wanted to do science again, but that she didn\'t need to do it anymore. She took a year out to be a \"ski bum\" and learned snow science in the Rockies. After a year, she was convinced that science wasn\'t so bad after all, so she returned to school to earn a Ph.\n\nD. in mountain hydrology. She\'s based in Alberta, which is where she works. The two students discuss the distance between their universities. Caroline says that her previous university required her to travel to Saskatoon every time she needed to take a class or a meeting. Now, however, because of the pandemic, she doesn\'t travel so often. Caroline explains that she studies glacier ice catchment. She studies snow, ice, and glaciers in the mountains',NULL,NULL),(61424,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 11, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 06:52:31',NULL,'This is the first of two segments we\'re going to hear about the music industry. First, we learn that the Alzheimer\'s society of Waterloo Wellington has a music project to help people with dementia. They\'re looking for volunteers, and they\'re giving away iPods to people who donate their stuff. If you\'re a musician, you can help out. You can also help out by getting involved in the music making process. For more information about this program, visit the link above. Get started!',NULL,NULL),(61425,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/Seems Like Old Times - July 9, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 14:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 06:34:41',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music and memories of the old days. The first half hour is devoted to Billie Holiday, who is performing with the Artie Shaw Orchestra. In the second half of the program, Blackie and Andrews, Eddie Fisher, Debbie Reynolds, and Carrie Fisher are also introduced. There is also music from the 50s and 60s, including Duke Ellington, Ray Anthony, Don Cornell, and others. The program ends with a reference to the upcoming Mount Forest Fireworks festival, which will take place from Thursday to Sunday, July 30th to July 31.',NULL,NULL),(61426,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 19, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 06:10:28',NULL,'In this very first hour of the show, we catch up with the host of The Stillness and The Dancing, Joel Cuthbert, to talk about some of his favorite music. He\'s got a bunch of new music from his friend Mark Coatsy, and a bunch from his friends in the label Illitech, including a new track called \"Reflections Revisited\" by N5MD. He also talks about a remix of \"In Danger\" by the band Tangent, and some other music from a label called Good Night. Finally, he talks about the music from another friend, Brock Don Way, who\'s been doing a lot of work.',NULL,'Joel Cuthbert leads listeners on a tour of new music'),(61427,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Wild Combination - July 20, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 05:48:18',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61429,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - July 10, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 08:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 05:30:00',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61430,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 12, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 05:11:44',NULL,'On this edition of The Stillness and the Dancing, the show opens with a piano and a tape loop from Theo Alexander\'s release, Points of Decay, and then moves on to a Vancouver trip with his friend Ian Craig, who releases a song called As the smoke begins to clear. He also releases an expanded version of a track called Turn of Breath from another friend, Willem Craig, and a song from his friend Mirope, which is inspired by Lithuanian folk music. The final track in the show is from a friend, Jay Halepenny, who is running a label called Goodnight Nobody Records.',NULL,'TheStillnessAndTheDancingatCFU.ca'),(61431,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Wild Combination - July 20, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 04:49:55',NULL,'The university\'s campus, community radio, and media center, CFRU, is looking for volunteers for a variety of jobs. They\'re also hiring people to record public service announcements and play music on the station. If you\'re interested in working at an event, you can come back after work to join the festivities.\n\nWe also need volunteers to record ads and other sorts of information for our station. We\'ve also got a group of scholars studying the pandemic, and they\'re looking to hear from people who were affected by it. They want to know how these people shaped the world and what they think of the future. If this sounds like you, then you might want to check out the University of Guelph\'s slash Life in Covid Study.',NULL,NULL),(61433,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/The Stillness & The Dancing - July 12, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 04:33:36',NULL,'On this edition of the Stillness and The Dancing, host Joel Cuthbert is joined by another guest, the experimental musician Ciro Berre-Guer, to discuss the latest releases from Ciro and Mikosa. The first track on the new album, El final de las ilus, translates to \"Southern Winter,\" and the second track, Inverno, is a reference to \"the beginning of the reign.\" The third track, Tu mente, is described as \"Forest is not what it seems.\" The fourth track, Forest Knows too, is said to be \"a little hidden gem.\" The music concludes with the release of Pieces of the white sun, a project that Cuthbert has spent a great deal of time with.',NULL,'The second hour of the live show begins with a description of the latest episode of the show'),(61434,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Wild Combination - July 13, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 01:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 04:06:42',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61436,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Wild Combination - July 13, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 03:55:47',NULL,'This week on Roulette, Phoebe Leger introduces her guest, Alabama-based musician, Davey Williams. He is an avantgarde black comedy musician whose avant garde \"black comedy\" music into a \"free improvisational guitar\" is referred to as \"The Gambler.\" Some of the lyrics of the song are \"Uh-uh, uh-uh.\" In this episode, Phoebe asks listeners to send the song to her. The song is called \"Wild Wild.\" The lyrics include the phrase \"The gambler.\" Phoebe then asks listeners if they know the song. They do, and she asks them to send her the song with the words \"The gambler.\"',NULL,NULL),(61440,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/Tone Zone - August 2, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 03:33:27',NULL,'The band starts off with a song by a singer named Peach Kelly, who has just released an album called \"Pop and Doo-wah Diddy. That\'s Lady Grey from her new album \"I\'m not There Anymore,\" which came out in 2010. Before that, the band heard Lady Grey\'s \"Brand New Client\" from her 1990 self-titled debut. The band then plays a song from a band called \"The Ramblers and Trains,\" from their 1986 album \"Shut Down Volume 2,\" and a song called \"I am not there anymore\" from their new \"I don\'t there anymore\" album.\n\nNext up on the program is a band named \"Mully Grub,\" from Winnipeg, who just released a new album called Tragical, which is out on September 22. The group also has a song named \"Left of the Dial\" by the replacements, from their 1972 album \"If I am only my thoughts.\" The band is also releasing a new remixed version of \"Tim\" on September 22, and they\'re going to play it as part of this program.',NULL,NULL),(61441,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/Tone Zone - July 26, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 03:14:18',NULL,'On this edition of the Upscales 4 World, host Matt plays a bunch of great music. The first song is from Talking Heads\'s Stop Making Sense, which is coming out in a remastered 40th anniversary edition.\n\nThen he\'s going to play a song from the Japanese psychedelic rock band Sadistic Mika Bands, a song called \"Reward\" that was a single in the United States in 1981. The song is actually not from the original album, but from the upcoming edition of Stop making Sense.\n\nThen it\'s \"The Cities\" from the deluxe reissue of the original. And then it was \"Teardrop Explodes and Reward\" from 1981. And then \"Sweetest Teardrop\" from \"My Love Is a Terror\" from a band called \"Spouses.\" And then Will Oldham\'s new single, \"Keeping Secrets Will Destroy you\" from his new album. And \"Crazy Blue Bells\" from Bonnie Prince Billy\'s upcoming album \"Keeping secrets will destroy you\" .\n\nAnd finally, \"The System\" from New York synth pop band, The System. And after that, we\'re off to \"The Alms called Logic\" from British singer-songwriter, The Alchemist.',NULL,NULL),(61442,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/Tone Zone - July 19, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 02:54:21',NULL,'The narrator welcomes everyone to the fifth annual summer-themed soundtrack. The perfect summer soundtrack to your vacation or backyard picnic or pool party. The music selection for the evening will be carefully selected, and the show will start with two songs that are new to the show.\n\nThe first song is a song from the British band Hold Steady, Cool Ghouls. The second song is from the Polyvinyl compilation, Hot Summer. The third song is an old-school rock song from The Ramones, Oh, Oh I Love her So. The fourth song is one from the White Wires, Let\'s go to the beach.\n\nThe fifth song is the hottest summer tune of all, by the name of Matt. The band starts with a song called Summer Time from the band Tampa, recorded in Tampa in the year of the release of the Back From the Grave volume two compilation. The song is called Summer time blues and it is a wild, warped version of the classic song. The show ends with the Beach Boys, who recorded a follow-up to the original song called Forever she\'ll Be my surfer girl.',NULL,NULL),(61443,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/B Siide Radio - August 2, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 02:35:17',NULL,'The narrator recounts the day before the earthquake in which he was at the concert. He was already there in a \"frenzy\" when the opening band started to play, and many of the teenagers were crushed against the stage. He tells the story of how he and other teenagers were treated by ambulance before the concert was over.',NULL,NULL),(61444,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/Radia - August 2, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 02:18:46',NULL,'This week\'s show is hosted by Radia, a group of radio stations that bring new and forgotten ideas to listeners. They give artists a challenge each week to make a radio show that walks across Europe or beyond. They\'re at a festival in Los Angeles, where Rina is performing with Lord Huron, Shaky Graves, Toroli Moi, Shax Haze, and more.\n\nThe show starts off with a description of the festival, and then proceeds to talk about the artists in the program. They all have new albums out, and tonight they all play a part in the show. Rina\'s upcoming follow up album is due out next year. The Conscious Life Expo is coming to Los Angeles for its 17 th annual conference. The expo will feature 200 speakers, Spanish program, music, and a healthy and healthy expo hall.\n\nTickets are available at Conscious LifeExpo.org. Before the show begins, President Trump renews his resolve that America is not a socialist country, which is why he opened the American embassy in Jerusalem. He also says that America has been fighting wars around the world for almost nineteen years, and has spent more than seven trillion dollars fighting wars. He says that he has a new approach to war. Great nations don\'t fight endless wars, he says, and he\'s calling for an end to the war in Syria. He\'s also calling for a political settlement to be reached in Afghanistan, which the Zing side is happy to be',NULL,NULL),(61445,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/Trail Mix - August 2, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 01:46:56',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61446,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Let’s Get Lost - August 1, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 01:29:40',NULL,'This is the second part of the first part of Alan and Scott\'s weekly show on CFRU\'s 93.3FM. The first part is a mix of experimental music from around the world.\n\nThe second part is an introduction to EdVideo, a not-for-profit organization that offers training in the use of professional equipment in the production of video art and films. The program ends with a track by the band Acraa, which is on an album called A Trip To Bold Gotanga. This is one of many tracks on this show that are released on various labels. It is also one of the few tracks that sounds familiar to listeners of the program.',NULL,NULL),(61447,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/Tone Zone - July 12, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 01:15:21',NULL,'This is the first hour of the new show, which is called the \"Tone Zone\" and is all about listening to music in the summertime. The first song is from the early 70s, by the New Yorkers, and it\'s called \"The New York Dolls.\"\n\nThe second song is a song from the late 70s by the Goreys, and the third song is by the Flirtations. The fourth song is \"Personality Crisis.\" The fifth song is an early version of the song \"He\'s Doing it.\" The sixth song is the same song as the first, but this one is from \"Nothing but a heartache.\" The seventh song is another early version, this one from \"Outta Here.\" The eighth song is called \"Who\'s doing it?\n\n\" and the ninth is \"The Flirtations.\" The show ends with a song by the British punk duo, You Can. The song is about a guy who\'s got to get up and fight.',NULL,NULL),(61448,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/B Siide Radio - July 26, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 00:45:52',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61449,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/Radia - July 26, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 00:34:01',NULL,'The narrator wishes he had gone to Los Angeles when he was young, because he loved it so much. He wanted to be a famous writer, but he hated the South and the academic politics of UGA. He hated the whole \"academic political business\" of it all, so he applied to the AFI because it was his dream. He moved to LA with his grandmother, who had a homebirth practice and friends in the area. The grandparents loved her and they loved her. The narrator feels that moving to LA was hard, because everyone was younger than him, and he was old. He feels like he was \"on the outside too.\" He wants to be famous, but that\'s not what he is. He\'s a donut guy, and everyone was \"younger than me.\n\n\" He wishes he\'d started writing sooner, because it would have made his life easier. He knows that his dad told him he couldn\'t become a writer because he wouldn\'t have any money. But if he had started in college, he thinks maybe it would be different. He also knew that John\'s \"sales\" in college were really good, and his professors told him that they\'d never seen anything so good written. He loves words, and loves ideas. He liked to write because he liked the idea of creating worlds through them. He tells the story of how he told his dad that he could\'ve gone to art school even though he was dying,',NULL,NULL),(61450,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/Trail Mix - July 26, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-02 00:06:59',NULL,'The show begins with a discussion of the latest music news. The first song is a new song from Matt Baugh. The second song is an old song from Kongotron, and the third song is from Sessa\'s new album. The show ends with a song from Neil Young\'s \"Toast,\" which was released in 2022.',NULL,NULL),(61451,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Let’s Get Lost - August 1, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 23:47:57',NULL,'The program begins with a list of new music releases from various labels. First up is a new album from Jesse Zubat, a music production company. Tony Wilson, a friend of Tony\'s, has put together a band called Long Hand. The band is comprised of the Zubats, Josh and Jesse, and Tony himself.\n\nThe music on the album is called Plays Long, and it is a tribute to Peter Long. The Zubat brothers are playing on the song called Nautre Dam de la rivesse. The other musicians on the show are Anna Weber, Aurora Neeland, Chiquita Magic, John Hollenbecue, Mark Webber, Connection, and Ceramic Dog. The program closes with a program about a local musician named Zoamba, who played at the Hillside Festival.',NULL,NULL),(61452,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Here Today - August 3, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 07:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 23:33:13',NULL,'The show kicks off with a brand new song from B. A. who is also known as \"Deborah Fialkovich\" and \"John Koser\" . The song is from a compilation called \"Cyber Hacker 3,\" which includes a number of other artists.\n\nNext up is Ben Gunning, an indie musician from Toronto who has released a new EP, \"No Magic Hand,\" and an upcoming live album from the band \"Church of Trees\" , which will be coming to the city in September. Finally, Aaron Badgley and Rob Proust are joined by MeeLo, who has put out a ton of singles. Aaron has a plan to make his own album of his own music by releasing all of MeeLo\'s singles onto a CD. He\'s also joined by Rob Proust, who will also be releasing a new album during the same time. He also mentions that Honey and The Johnsons have released their new album, \"Cut Worms,\" and that they\'re on the road again. The show ends with a song from \"Sliver of Ice\" by Honey.',NULL,NULL),(61453,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/B Siide Radio - July 19, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 23:05:05',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61454,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/Radia - July 19, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 22:52:05',NULL,'This week, we hear from the Media Relations Manager at the University of Guelph, who tells us that they\'re always looking for people to be involved with their media projects. They have a lot of different kinds of projects to help out with. They can help with music production, engineering, and live events. They also have a number of different types of production to help with, like live streams and public service announcements.\n\nNo experience is necessary, just a little bit of experience is all that\'s needed. It\'s all very exciting. The next time you\'re at the lake, you\'ll want to come to the hillside festival, which is coming up on July 28th and 29th. You can get tickets to the festival at hillsidefestivals.ca. For more info, check out the festival\'s Facebook page. There\'s also a link to the Festival\'s Twitter page. We\'re also introduced to a new host, Mac D. He starts off the show with a little recap of the previous show. The program starts off with a bunch of music from Strawley\'s latest release. We also hear some new music from Donald Ray Johnson, Selwyn Jerome Birchwood, Michael Brown, and the CASHBOX KINGS.',NULL,NULL),(61455,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/Trail Mix - July 19, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 22:29:20',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61456,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Let’s Get Lost - July 25, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 22:09:58',NULL,'On this week\'s episode of the Talk Show, Bahamudah introduces the listeners to a number of artists who are featured on the program. They include Chris Corsano, Zoe Amba, Ayumi Ashitos, and Bill Otcutt. The program ends with a program about the National Film Board\'s collection of films made by Indigenous peoples. The show also announces the return of the Hillside Festival, a music and arts festival taking place on July 28th and 29th at the lake.',NULL,NULL),(61457,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Here Today - July 27, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 07:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 21:54:26',NULL,'Aaron Badgley is back on the show and he\'ll tell you all about some new music for the hour. He\'s going to play some brand new music from some established artists.\n\nFirst up, Aaron and his guests hear a new album from the Johnsons called \"My Back was a Bridge for you to Cross.\" Aaron says it\'s a great album. Next up is a new song from Dave Cousins from \"The Magic of it All.\" The song is called \"Paris Nights.\" Aaron also talks about Jonathan O\'Journi from \"Wolves Just Fine.\" He says he\'s an internet celebrity, a comedian, a musician, a director, a record producer, and a host on a TV show called \"The League\" . Aaron also says that \"Deborah Fajalkovich\" from \"Daughters of the Industrialist\" has a new single out called \"Don\'t feel a thing.\" Aaron is psyched to hear this new song.',NULL,NULL),(61458,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/B Siide Radio - July 12, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 19:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 21:38:12',NULL,'This is the second part of the show, where the narrator talks about music and the effects it can have on people with dementia. He also talks about the music project run by the Alzheimer\'s society in Wellington, where they provide a free iPod with a personal playlist to people living with the disease. Anyone interested in helping out can visit the society\'s web site for more information.',NULL,NULL),(61459,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/Radia - July 12, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 00:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 20:59:09',NULL,'The narrator explains that he went to Williams College to look for his sister. He spent four years looking for her, and then met Paul, who reminded him of her.\n\nHe married at 24, and they had two children. The narrator says that she did not fall in love because she wanted to, but because she needed someone to take care of her when she was sad. She says that her mother was something else, and she was drawn to the energy of her mother. She was a midwife, and the narrator went with her, feeling that he would be able to support her, even if he was a bore. She liked that he was mysterious and smart, something that her father had always been interested in. She did not know why she picked him, but she did like the fact that he seemed to be mysterious. He says that if he and his mother were older, they would not have gotten married, and he would not be the version of him that he is today.\n\nHe admits that he struggled with their decision to have too many children, and that he wanted them to be a family with a loud and chaotic nature. He thinks that a family should be like a circus. He doesn\'t want a family like that, but he does want something like that.',NULL,NULL),(61460,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/Trail Mix - July 12, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 20:27:58',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61461,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Let’s Get Lost - July 25, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 20:07:25',NULL,'This program is a mix of new music and old favorites, including the Pacific Jazz Group, a group of musicians in San Francisco. The group also includes Francois Bourassa , a Quebec-based pianist, and an outfit called George, an outfit of musicians from the city of Guelph, Canada. They also include a Canadian band called Eucalyptus, a band from the Toronto suburb of Titillators, and a new project from Ryan Driver, a street sweeper.',NULL,NULL),(61462,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Here Today - July 20, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 07:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 19:53:19',NULL,'The program opens with a look back at the past few weeks. The program\'s host, David, describes a number of artists who have recently released new music.\n\nFirst up is Cameron Noise, a musician who lives in Los Angeles. Cameron Noise has a new album coming out, called Cameron House, which is full of old-school 60s-influenced sounds. He also has a brand new single from another musician, Alex Southy. David also mentions that Deborah Fialkova is working with Anil on a new project called Daughters Are The Industrialists and Compilations-aLot. David is also a fan of David\'s former band, the Strobz, who he says are back with another new one called Our World.\n\nThe show also includes a listen to John Lennon\'s latest album, Double Fantasy, and a song from John Jenkins\'s new album, Passing Time. David even mentions that he has written a review of the album for a magazine. The rest of the program also discusses some of the artists from Liverpool who have released new albums, including The Remainder, who have just released their first album, Even Song.',NULL,NULL),(61463,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Let’s Get Lost - July 18, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 19:28:52',NULL,'In this episode of the Humanoid Radio Show, we hear from a CFRU outreach team member about how they can help a local business advertise on the station. The show is called Stillness and Dancing and it\'s hosted by Alan. It\'s a mix of ambient, classical, and experimental music. It airs every Wednesday morning at 9am on CFRU. We also learn that there are always new volunteers for the show. If you want to learn more about the show, check out the link at the end of this episode.',NULL,NULL),(61464,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Here Today - July 13, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 07:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 19:15:39',NULL,'Aaron Badgley welcomes listeners to his show. He introduces himself as the host of the show. This is his first appearance on the show, and he introduces his guests. He starts by playing a new song from the band Amaretto Sour\'s. It is called Jet Set, and the band is from Colorado.\n\nThey have released three EPs under the name \"Amrtato Sours.\" They also have a new single out called Dying. Aaron also introduces the artist Debra Fialko from her latest compilation, Kia Lowry Miniatures and the Sea and The Sand. She is an original and thought-provoking artist. The band is called Church of Trees and they have released a new album, Courage. The song that Aaron and Rob Stewart are playing is called \"Take It Away\" from their latest album, Singles 80. The album is part of Singles 80, a collection of 80 of Aaron\'s best singles. It has been remastered and put in a nice box. The singer/songwriter, Rob Stewart, is also a part of this show. The show is also streamed live on the web.\n\nIf you\'re interested in listening to this show, you can listen to it on CFRU.org. Aaron introduces the listeners to the artists he\'s playing. He plays the most recent songs from these artists. The most recent song from Cameron Noyes is \"Let Love In.\" The song is from Beautiful Human, which is also from the album \"Henry Shade of Winkler.\"',NULL,NULL),(61465,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Let’s Get Lost - July 18, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 18:47:19',NULL,'In this installment of the Acoustic Hour, Adrian tells listeners about some of the new releases he\'s been working on.\n\nFirst up, he tells us that he\'ll be returning next week with more new music. He also tells us about the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival, where he and his friend Brody West will be performing with their group, called \"Escalyptus.\" Adrian also talks about some other upcoming releases, including a new album from Artemis, and an album by Jim\'s Orchestra called \"Help With Your Heart.\" The program for this program is Scott\'s Name, \"Let\'s get lost.\"',NULL,NULL),(61466,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Let’s Get Lost - July 11, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 21:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 18:29:20',NULL,'In this week\'s program, Alan, the host of the CFRU-FM program \"Tuned to Humanoid\" , runs through some tracks from the new album by Henry Threadgill. He also tells us about two other recent works by Henry, one of which is the music for a large multimedia performance.\n\nThe other is \"Of Valance,\" a piece inspired by the human heartbeat and performed live in New York City in 2022. The New York Times describes the performance as possessing \"a galvanistic sense of swing\" and \"an oblique, danceable straightforwardly joyous threadgillian energy.\" Alan also discusses the organ donation campaign and how many people die each day due to lack of a donor organ. If you\'re interested in becoming an organ donor, you can go to the organ donor registry at beadoner . In the meantime, you should also share your consent with your family.',NULL,NULL),(61467,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Let’s Get Lost - July 11, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 18:07:59',NULL,'This week\'s program kicks off with a track called \"Split the Difference,\" which is a new song from a band called the \"Pilk Mutan-Honig,\" a group that reunited after 12 years.\n\nThe band played for three hours in the studio and produced enough material for several albums, but this one is called \"You Are the Song\" and \"You in capital letters\" and it produces a bunch of songs including \"The Polonius Monk Bemtia\" for the listeners to listen to. Next, the program plays a trio called \"London Brew,\" an album that celebrates Miles Davis\' pitch brew and features an all star cast of \"very young, well, not very young\" but younger London English players. The program then plays a new track from Ingrid \"The Last Quiet Place,\" a new album from her. It features a cast that the program is \"big time in favor\" of.\n\nNext up is \"The 2020 Blues,\" a song from Christine Jensen, who has just released an album. And then the program ends with the announcement that the \"Guelph Jazz Festival\" is coming up in September and the program will be picking the artists to see. The listeners should go to the festival\'s web site to get more info.',NULL,NULL),(61468,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Back in the USSR - July 31, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 17:27:16',NULL,'Back in the U. S. on 93.3FM CFRU, Seifried discusses media and the destructive power it has on the world. He brings up Michael Parenti\'s talk on destructive media narratives and his own talk, entitled \"Rambo and the Swarththy Hordes\" .\n\nThe talk is about how media narratives are used to fuel conflict, wars, and the military industrial complex. It\'s a long history of Hollywood and how it uses these narratives to get people to support militaristic outcomes. He says that even though there are no actual troops on the ground in the Ukraine conflict, there are still heroes and villains in the media.',NULL,NULL),(61469,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Bridging The Social Distance - August 3, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 16:30:41',NULL,'In this chapter, the narrator tells the reader that he lost track of time and that he enjoys each day because he likes to watch people interact with them and stay connected to the world around him.\n\nHe says that staying connected is extremely important to him and that there are lots of social activities in the neighborhood that he participates in. He also participates in the exercise routines, which he does because he is the type of person who likes to sit, read, and exercise. The exercises keep him healthy and he says that they keep him connected with the rest of the world. He tells the story of his former companion, who was 26 pounds and wanted to be exercised every day. He was a Lassa Absa, a breed of Absa that was developed from the Far East, and his companion was named Burt.\n\nThey walk together and he gets treats from his sister. The narrator says that now that he is with his sister, it is good to stay a part of the exercise routine to keep his body going. He adds that, given his age, he will probably get a companion. He explains that reading and exercise are two things he likes because they help keep him stimulated and focused',NULL,NULL),(61470,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Back in the USSR - July 24, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 16:15:33',NULL,'Back in the United States, you\'re listening back to back in the USSR',NULL,NULL),(61471,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Bridging The Social Distance - August 1, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 15:53:32',NULL,'In this episode, Jenny Mitchell, the host of the Bridging the Distance program, introduces her guest, Anne Kuzik who is a current resident at Riverside Glen. Anne is 80 years old and has been at the retirement home for four months. She says she enjoys each day because she brings something new to the table. Anne says she likes to watch people, and she says she would like to be a social butterfly.',NULL,NULL),(61472,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Tuesday at 5 - August 1, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 15:27:51',NULL,'The show starts off with a new edition of Tuesday\'s at 5 on CFRU 93.3. Mac Dee welcomes everyone to the show and tells us that he\'s the host. He also tells us about some of the latest news from the world. This week\'s news comes from Bruce\'s When You Arrive , from Jeb Loy Nichols\' Satisfied MIND , and from Jason Lang\'s Happiness Is .',NULL,NULL),(61473,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Tales from the Bridge - August 3, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 15:14:11',NULL,'The guys are back from their year-long hiatus and they\'re back on the podcast with a recap of the year. They\'re talking about their favorite moments, their favorite books, and their favorite authors. They say they wouldn\'t talk to as many people as they do if it weren\'t for Tristan, who is their primary chase producer. The guys say they\'ll be talking about some of their favorite interviews, or favorite books. And then they say they have a lot to talk about in the next few minutes.\n\nThey want to get to the bridge and see how many people are listening to the show from different places around the world, so they can see where they\'ve come from. They have listeners from all over the world listening to their show. They also want to thank them for tuning in to the city they live in. And they also say that the show is a radio show, so listeners may not be aware that it\'s a podcast.',NULL,NULL),(61474,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Back in the USSR - July 17, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 14:49:12',NULL,'The show opens with a new mix, this time of Canada and the \"native\" people, and then it\'s back to the \"classic\" invasion of the United States.\n\nThe show ends with another new track from \"Page\" , this one called \"Get You High.\" The guys hope everyone had a good time, and they\'re looking forward to seeing you next week. Finally, the guys want to thank everyone for tuning in. They also want to say a big thank you to the listeners on CFRU 96.3 FM. They wish everyone a great night and a good vibe. And, finally, they\'d like to thank you for listening to \"Back in the USSR.\" The narrator\'s just as excited as the audience is to hear this music. He says he hopes everyone enjoyed the music. The narrator goes on to say that he hopes that a \"king in England\" could just give a little bit of Canada to a few Englishmen, and that the Indians had nothing to say about it.\n\nThe Indians had no say whatsoever. Yeah, it sounds like the government is trying to figure out who to allow in to the country, and the narrator sympathizes with the government. He doesn\'t think that there\'s anything wrong with that, but he does think that \"tradition continuity\" and \"tradition hate\" are the root of all racism. He also says that \"the mind of man arrives on racism.\" Translation: the racism that we\'re',NULL,NULL),(61475,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Bridging The Social Distance - July 27, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 14:29:31',NULL,'Amy Goodman is the host of Democracy Now, a weekly program produced by CFRU 93.2 FM in Guelph, Ontario. Amy and her co-host, Jenny Mitchell, produce a weekly show called Bridging The Distance. Amy started the program in March of 2020, responding to the CoVID-19 pandemic.\n\nToday\'s guest on the program is Sandra Lubic, a recent resident at the village of Riverside Glen. She has multiple sclerosis and can no longer live on her own, so she moved to the retirement community in April. She tells Amy her story: she was separated from her husband five years ago, and now she is in a room at the retirement center. She\'s trying to organize her belongings and organize her life, as she\'s worried about her health, which is declining.\n\nAmy asks her to tell her story, and she says she\'ll tell it once her friend brings her some boxes of her stuff.',NULL,NULL),(61476,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Tuesday at 5 - July 25, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 17:00:00',86638720,'2024-01-01 14:09:33',NULL,'Mac Dee is back on the air with another program. He tells us that Tony Bennett has died at the age of 96. He has released 70 albums and has won 19 Grammys. Tony is also known for his duets with artists including Elvis Costello, Katie Lang, and Cheryl Crowe.\n\nTony\'s Girl I Love won two Grammys and his Duets won two. Mac Dee also tells us about his travels. He started off with a set from Bruce Coburn. He says that he was never cool and the Notting Hillbills. He reports that his grandfather\'s abscess is healing well and he and his wife are planning some camping and canoeing.',NULL,NULL),(61477,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Tales from the Bridge - July 27, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 13:54:03',NULL,'The narrator introduces himself as David, and they talk about Joseph, a childhood hero. He is a science fiction fan, and the narrator has a book by Robert Anton Wilson called \"The Illuminatus trilogy.\" The narrator says that the book was on Joseph\'s shelf, and that he has a copy. The narrator also mentions that David Menken voices Luke Skywalker in \"Lego Star Wars,\" and that David is in the new \"Final Fantasy XVI\" game.',NULL,NULL),(61478,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/FoodFarm Talk - August 3, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 13:29:21',NULL,'This episode of Food Talk, a podcast about food and agriculture, is a conversation between David Mackay, deputy managing editor of the National Observer, and Victor Doyle, an urban planner who has worked for 30 years in the Ontario Ministry of Municipal Affairs and was formerly demotioned because of his opposition to the development of the Greenbelt. The two discuss Ford\'s description of the decision to open the Greenbelt as \"a bunch of staffers with crayons, highlighters, and randomly going on a map, just a big scam.\" The two also discuss how the government is ignorant and ill informed about the decision.',NULL,NULL),(61479,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Back in the USSR - July 10, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 23:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 13:14:31',NULL,'In this brief but important speech, Willie Dunn, a Canadian artist and the subject of the 1971 film \"The Other Side of The Ledger,\" delivers a scathing indictment of the Hudson Bay Company\'s treatment of First Nations peoples in Canada. He argues that Canada is a settler-colonial society, and that the country must be told the truth.',NULL,NULL),(61480,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Bridging The Social Distance - July 25, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 12:53:36',NULL,'Jenny Mitchell, a host on a local community radio show, introduces us to her guest, Sandra Lubica who is a recent resident at the Riverside Glen Retirement Home. She is a woman with multiple sclerosis and she came to live at the home because she could no longer live on her own anymore. She says she is the youngest resident at this retirement home, which is interesting, because she\'s the youngest on the floor. She also says she was surprised to find that everyone seems to be a generation older than she is.',NULL,NULL),(61481,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Tuesday at 5 - July 18, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 12:29:07',NULL,'In this week\'s edition of Capricaylee, host Mac Dee introduces us to some of the new music on the air. The show is about the days of summer, and in this edition, we learn that the days are called \"dog days\" because they are associated with the rising of Sirius, one of the brightest stars in the constellation, Canis Major. According to Homer, the dog days were associated with war, disaster, and the rise of the sun. In other words, the show is all about the hotness of the summer.',NULL,NULL),(61482,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Tales from the Bridge - July 20, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 12:14:07',NULL,'Maheen is the host of the CFRU 92.3.3FM podcast, Tales from the Bridges. She is joined by Sam and Kevin, two of the show\'s producers. They are excited to discuss the year that was, and to share their thoughts about the year\'s events. Sam says that they had a great year, and that they talked to a ton of cool people, read a bunch of cool books, and talked to tons of authors.\n\nSam praises his producer, Tristan, for his work in producing the show. He also says that he loves doing it, and he loves talking to people. They\'ll talk about their favorite moments, or favorite interviews, or their favorite books, but they\'ll also talk about other things. They decide to take their listeners to South Lambeth, London, where they\'ve gotten a lot of listeners. They also mention that they have listeners in Dublin and Denver, Colorado. They say thanks for listening, and they also say that they\'re also a podcast show, so listeners in Canada can hear them as well.',NULL,NULL),(61483,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/FoodFarm Talk - July 27, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 11:49:10',NULL,'This episode focuses on the concept of \"cellular agriculture\" and discusses the use of this term to describe the production of meat and other animal products without raising or killing animals. The show\'s host, Mike Vamasse, describes the concept as \"a catch-all\" term that includes both \"lab-grown meat\" and \"cell culture.\" He describes these two applications as \"working in concert\" with \"plant-based products\" . He also describes the role of yeast and fungus in these applications as well as the \"mix of the two\" that he describes as \"blurred.\"',NULL,NULL),(61484,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Bridging The Social Distance - July 20, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 11:33:17',NULL,'Jenny Mitchell, host of the Bridging the Distance podcast, introduces her guest Bill Winship, a resident of the village of Riverside Glen. Bill is a survivor of the diphtheria epidemic that ravaged his childhood in Liverpool, England. He recounts his own life story. He was baptized William, but only the government, the police, and anyone else who wants to pin him on the board use his name. Bill\'s childhood is described in his autobiography, which is titled \"William: The Untold Story\" .',NULL,NULL),(61485,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Tuesday at 5 - July 11, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 11:08:29',NULL,'On Tuesday, Mac Dee hosts another edition of his show on CFRU 939. The show begins with a history of the Calgary Stampede, which takes place from July 8 to 16. The roots of the festival go back to 1886, when the Agricultural Society of Calgary first held its fair. Guy Wiedeck organized the first Stampede in honor of soldiers returning from the First World War, but it was not until 1920 that the festival merged with the Exhibition and Stampede to create the annual event. The Stampede attempts to balance the tradition of the rodeo against the concerns raised by animal welfare groups, who argue that the sport of chuck wagon racing is inhumane.',NULL,NULL),(61486,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Tales from the Bridge - July 13, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 09:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 10:55:50',NULL,'In this episode, the gang discusses the upcoming summer season and their book recommendations. As they walk along the bridge, they talk about the year Star Wars was released. They also discuss the month\'s book, Revelation by Space Reynolds. If you\'re new to the Tales From the Bridge Podcast, they encourage you to follow them and write a review of the show so that they can keep track of what\'s happening on the show. If there\'s anyone that they\'d like them to talk to, they invite you to come along and hang out until they finish.',NULL,NULL),(61487,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/FoodFarm Talk - July 20, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 10:32:43',NULL,'This episode of FoodFarm Talk is hosted by Derek Leahy, the host of the University of Guelph\'s Food and Farm Talk program.\n\nThe show is a local public radio show about food and agriculture in Ontario and beyond. The program is a part of a larger program called The Rule Roots to the Climate Solutions, which is a Canadian owned and operated podcast focused on land management and farm technology. In this episode, they\'re talking about women in agriculture, and they\'ve done this before. They\'re especially interested in this topic because women are growing up in agriculture and are becoming more and more involved in the production of food. This is the second episode in a series called Slice and Dice, where they take a webinar and slice it up into an episode.',NULL,NULL),(61488,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Bridging The Social Distance - July 18, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 10:13:05',NULL,'Bill Winship is the guest on this episode of Bridging the Distance. He is a resident of Riverside Glen, a retirement community in Guelph. He was born at an early age and has an average childhood. He contracted diphtheria in the epidemic that struck Liverpool at the age of ten. Only six of his ten children died, and he survived.',NULL,NULL),(61489,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/FoodFarm Talk - July 13, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 09:53:04',NULL,'This episode of FoodFarm Talk is the second in a series of podcasts exploring the science and impacts of beef production and beef and the environment.\n\nThe first was called \"Cows On the Planet.\" Kim Stanford is a professor at the University in Lethbridge and co-hosts the show with Tim McAllister, a principal scientist with Agri-Food Canada in Lethbridge. They discuss the science behind the improvements in the cattle industry in Canada and the United States. The guest for this episode is Frances Fluharthy, a professor from University of Georgia, and a deep thinker on the subject of livestock. Kim and Tim welcome Frances and tell her about her background. She was raised on a perford cattle operation in Ohio and went to the University of Ohio for her undergraduate degree and then to the State University for her graduate degree. Her family borrowed a ton of money to expand the operation.',NULL,NULL),(61490,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Bridging The Social Distance - July 13, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 09:29:20',NULL,'Sutahr is a designer and maker of upcycled fabric products. He has started a company called Niddlecraft and has plans to sell his products through a chain of workshops. He is a self-taught artist, and he learned his craft from his grandmother, who sewed and embroidered everything she had.\n\nSutahri\'s goal is to use the upcycled fabric to make products that benefit the community and children. He wants to make a charitable contribution to his cause. He calls his business Holistic, because he practices Holistic Living, where he gives away items to raise money. He sees a lot of potential in his business, and hopes to increase the community\'s awareness of his business. He plans to use his workshops to teach people how to make and sell their own products.',NULL,NULL),(61491,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Bridging The Social Distance - July 11, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 12:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 09:16:41',NULL,'This is a short rebroadcast of an earlier episode of the show. The show is called \"Bridging the social distance\" and it\'s hosted by Jenny Mitchell. Jenny Mitchell is a student at CFRU Guelph and she\'s been recording this show since March of 2020. She started recording this program in March of 2020, to help her stay connected through the pandemic.\n\nThis episode is a re-broadcast of one that she originally recorded. The first episode is about a woman named Abigail who\'s a singer songwriter and musician based in Toronto. She\'s released her fourth studio album called \"Stolen Time\" and she was born on a Sunday in North York, New York. She says she was originally from Toronto but she moved to Montreal when she was a teenager.',NULL,NULL),(61492,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/T.K.O. - August 3, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 08:53:13',NULL,'The second part of the UFC 291 card was a mixed bag of fights. The main event didn\'t go as planned, but there were some exciting fights, and the co-main event was a really good one. The co-headliners were a great one, though, and we\'ll get to that in a minute. The third fight was supposed to be a welterweight bout between a veteran named Wonderboy Thompson and a guy named TKO. There was a problem with the logistics of the fight, and Wonderboy had to cancel twice. We\'ll find out more about that later.',NULL,NULL),(61493,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Android’s Dungeon - August 3, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 13:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 08:34:12',NULL,'The guys talk about the release of the latest entry in the popular Baldur-s Gate series, which has been in development for eight years. The guys discuss how long it has taken to make the game, how much time has been invested in making it, and how people can buy early access for anything they want. They also talk about early access\'s drawbacks, which include the fact that it\'s a fad and that people who don\'t buy early are missing out on the full game.',NULL,NULL),(61494,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/RadiOPIRG - August 3, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 08:15:27',NULL,'This episode, we\'re joined by RadiopIrg, a co-founder of ZERO, a research organization that focuses on social justice issues. We learn that she\'s back from a trip abroad, and she\'d like to continue some of their work on identifying and highlighting LGBTQ activists in the community. This is a great opportunity to talk to Robin, one of two People\'s Histories Project researchers who\'ll be working on that summer in 2023. Robin is a 24-year-old white settler with an undergraduate degree in history and a contract position at arch.\n\nShe\'ll also be working as a visual narrative historian for the trans-peer team. We also learn that Robin is an autistic man with ADHD, and that he\'s struggling with chronic pain, but he doesn\'t seek medical treatment because he is trans and autistic and he doesn t want to be labeled as a \"disability\" by the medical community. He\'s not seeking medical treatment for it because he has a disability, he just wants to do something about it.',NULL,NULL),(61495,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/T.K.O. - July 27, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 07:54:42',NULL,'In this interview with Janan, the host of TKO, he tells her all about the happenings in the world of mixed martial arts and combat sports. He also tells her to enjoy the summer and to make the most of it, which he does by taking good care of himself and his family.',NULL,NULL),(61496,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Android’s Dungeon - July 27, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 13:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 07:16:35',NULL,'This week, the guys are back at the university, but this time, they\'re talking about a guy named Jack. He\'s alone, he\'s sad, and he has no one to talk to. Jack and the guys talk about their favorite board game, which is called Lawn Shot, and then they talk about the guy named Jason who\'s playing it, and the guy who is playing it is named Lucky Shot. They also talk about a weird horse racing game called Longshot.',NULL,NULL),(61497,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/RadiOPIRG - July 27, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 06:50:20',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part interview with the creator of the underground radio show, Radio Zeropirg. The first part of the interview focuses on the work of the work study students at the university, who are creating content for the underground station. The second part is about a forthcoming event called \"Monument America Resist Day\" that will take place on August 7th at the Royal City Brewery in downtown Toronto. The interview with Felix, the protagonist of the show, focuses on his name, pronouns, and age. He is 27 years old, Caucasian, British, and works as a farm manager',NULL,NULL),(61498,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/30/Wind-Down - July 30, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-30 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 06:33:12',NULL,'On this episode of the CNRU program, we catch up with the host of the Wind Down, a music festival that takes place every Saturday at the abandoned schoolhouse in Bellwood. This year\'s festival featured all the artists who played at the festival the previous year. The show starts off with a song by Lola Kirk, followed by songs by Begonia, Bebe Club, eBay, Ariel Pozen, Luna Lee, Trey Duality, and Tartarrelena. After the first song, the show moves on to a song from the artist Nico Paulo, and then to Billie Anne\'s song Full Circle',NULL,NULL),(61499,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/T.K.O. - July 20, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 06:16:44',NULL,'The second episode of TKO airs on CFRU 93.3 FM and is hosted by Janan. She introduces the show and tells listeners that they are listening to a live show about mixed martial arts. She also tells them that she is still recovering from her illness. She explains that she was hoping to fight at the tournament that had just been held, but she caught a cold and had to go on an antibiotic treatment.',NULL,NULL),(61500,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Android’s Dungeon - July 20, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 13:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 05:08:49',NULL,'This is the second part of the two-part interview with Josh. The first part was mostly about the game, and the second is more about Josh\'s publishing. He\'s excited for the launch of the game and he\'s also excited about the fact that he\'ll be able to publish the old print editions of the games.\n\nHe also wants to make sure that the other games he has waiting for him are also going to be published. The only thing that\'s not clear is whether or not they\'re going to have a publisher. Josh seems to think that Lucas has one, but he doesn\'t know if it\'ll come from him. Josh says that he has a partnership with Lucas, so that would make sense. Josh also thinks that Trax and 18 India are also on the horizon. He wants to see what happens with them. He knows that he wants to order the games, but it\'s too expensive to ship them yet.',NULL,NULL),(61501,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/RadiOPIRG - July 20, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 04:53:06',NULL,'In this episode, we hear from a new volunteer at the university, a musician named Jeff. He\'s on vacation and he\'s here to listen to a talk by a speaker named Mike Marcoff on the future of the green belt.\n\nThis talk is about how we are all selfish and we\'ve got to do something about it. This is one of the most important parts of the talk. It\'s all about how people are selfish. We love unconditionally, we love others selflessly, we donate without expecting anything in return, and we are very social. And if you think about it, we all miss out on all of this.',NULL,NULL),(61502,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/23/Wind-Down - July 23, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-23 20:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 04:31:02',NULL,'The wind-down begins with a classic from a band called Paradise, followed by a song from another band called Men I Trust, then another from another artist called Jit-Wam, and then a song by a singer named Feist. The show ends with a song called Absentee from Cas-Mccooms\'s latest album.',NULL,NULL),(61503,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Turtle Island Underground - August 3, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 18:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 04:15:42',NULL,'In this installment, Mac and the Underground\'s host, Kristy Sinclair, introduce listeners to some of the latest music from the library. They\'ll also play a couple of songs from the debut album of Robbie Robertson, who\'s been releasing new music since 1987. They start off with a trio of tracks from Beika Moyongan\'s new record, followed by three tracks from Dan Monkman\'s Bleached Waves. The third track is called Dodum Next, which is an ode to the Turtle Island underground. Next up is a listen to a new album from Inuarda, translated into English by an artist named Kan Robbie. This is one of the most exciting albums of the year.',NULL,NULL),(61504,124,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Planet Groove - August 4, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 10:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 03:10:11',NULL,'This is the second part of the show where the doctor discusses some of the music he is playing. The first part consists of some songs that he is going to play for the audience.\n\nHe starts out by playing a song called \"In Between\" about a band that played at the KW Blues Fest earlier this year. The song is about a bass player who is \"erotic unstuned\" and he\'s going to perform some of her songs. He also plays some of his own songs, including some that were cut out of him by Lee Fields. He then plays some songs by the artists he used to be friends with, like Carry Sweetman and Emily Land.\n\nAgain, the doctor is talking about music. The doctor is also talking about the show called \"Planet Groove\" with his \"Funky Funky Blues Doctor Baby\". The show is about to start when the doctor gets up early to \"burn weedabix\" . The show also features the band \"Purpertreators\" and \"Cedric and the Fogg Blues and Brass band\" who are playing a festival this Saturday. He\'s excited to play some of their tunes.',NULL,NULL),(61505,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Open Sources Guelph - August 3, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 17:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 01:12:16',NULL,'The Open Source guys are back with another one of our favorite program openers, this time dealing with union organizing in Waterloo. They\'ve got two organizers who are going to join them to talk about the union movement and how it\'s going. It\'ll be interesting to see how it goes. They also talk about some other trending topics in the last week. One of them is a tire rally in Oakville, which was attended by a bunch of white nationalists, including Paul Fowler from the \"alt-right\" .',NULL,NULL),(61506,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/T.K.O. - July 13, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 16:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 00:52:19',NULL,'We\'re back with the host of the show, who\'s calling us from his home in the middle of nowhere in Canada. He\'s called by the host\'s daughter, Janan, and she\'s here to tell us all about the world of mixed martial arts.\n\nShe\'s also here to talk about the sport of boxing, which is one of the sports that she studies so she can teach boxing to other girls. We learn that boxing is a mixed martial art that involves fighting with fists and grappling with sticks. It\'s a sport that involves a lot of kicking and striking. It involves a whole bunch of different types of fighting, from boxing to wrestling to MMA. The host says that he hopes everyone has had a great week so far, and that time is flying by. He hopes that',NULL,NULL),(61507,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Android’s Dungeon - July 13, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 13:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 00:32:39',NULL,'This chapter is all about the history of board games. It all started with Wizard and Melee, which was published by a guy named Steve Jackson, who\'s now the publisher of a game called Fantasy Trip.\n\nIt was all a bunch of weird stuff, but it didn\'t really catch on. It\'s not like it\'s a big hit, though, because it was so hackneyed. So, yeah, this is a big deal. It turns out that the guy who wrote the book, and who wrote it, was also a board game enthusiast. This is the first time we\'ve heard of his real name. He\'s from Colorado, and he used to play board games with friends back home. One day, a friend of his came to visit, and they played some board games together. But then he got a job at a place called Colorado. He was introduced to board games, and that\'s when he found out who he was.',NULL,NULL),(61508,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/RadiOPIRG - July 13, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 15:00:00',86507648,'2024-01-01 00:08:01',NULL,'In this episode, the host interviews two people who are experiencing homelessness in Guelph: Chris Kane, an unhoused person, and Dani, a member of Gruha and a housing advocate.\n\nThe first interview is with Chris, who explains that he\'s been trying to get housing subsidies from a charity called the Stepping Stone for the past two years, but no one will help him. When he was in the wheelchair for a while, they would put people in the Express at the Holiday Inn so that they wouldn\'t have to stay in a shelter. He says that he was the first to fill out all the paperwork for the program, but then the staff would cherry pick people who were doing the right thing and not complaining about how things were run.\n\nHe adds that his experience with the housing crisis has been \"horrible notrecious\" from the banks to friends and strangers to staying in shelters. He has been listed as a priority on every housing subsidy list, but nothing has come of it. He just hired a new manager for the organization, though he doesn\'t know his name.',NULL,NULL),(61509,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/16/Wind-Down - July 16, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-16 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-31 23:12:26',NULL,'In this edition of the Wind Down, Sarah Willow talks about self-love. She describes self-care as \"the most second day of the day\" with a \"silent pause, reflection\" and \"enlightening and inspired thoughts.\" Sarah also talks about the upcoming show by Ch