range of media-related volunteer opportunities, and anyone interested in music production, video production, or engineering can get involved.',NULL,NULL),(61648,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/Zombie Jamboree - July 9, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 20:49:58',NULL,'The second hour of this week\'s edition of the host\'s weekly music show is over, and this time it\'s about talking to strangers. The host describes some of the tracks that he and his friends heard at the first hour of the show. He says that they\'ll hear more of these tracks in the next hour, so tune in next Sunday at 6PM for another episode. He also says that he\'ll ask his listeners to keep in touch with each other to find new music.',NULL,NULL),(61649,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/La Buena Onda - July 9, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 16:00:00',86507648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61650,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/This Night Wounds Time - July 17, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 20:32:44',NULL,'The geographical spotlight section is the section where the artist plays music from a particular country or territory. For instance, in the past, the artist played music from Russia, Canada, China, and the United States. Now, in order to represent the whole of the world in one spot, he\'s going to do music from seven countries: Argentina, Australia, Brazil, India, the Vatican, the Marshall Islands, and San Marino. The next time the artist does a geographical spotlight, he wants to cover all of the provinces and territories in the country instead of just the big city.',NULL,NULL),(61651,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/Zombie Jamboree - July 9, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 20:09:46',NULL,'The first song on the program is a cover of \"Red Right Hand\" by \"Erica Grapes\" . The second song is from a band named \"King of Strangers\" and the third is from \"L\'Entour-L\'OOP\" , which is a band from France that has been playing music since 1964. The first two songs are from Andrew Bird and the first two are from L\'entour-l\'oop. They\'ve met each other, and he says he\'s going to follow them up with more music.',NULL,NULL),(61652,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/16/This Night Wounds Time - July 16, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-16 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 19:11:32',NULL,'The show opens with a soliloquy by Christopher Curry, who explains the philosophy behind his own show, This Night-Wounds Time. The show\'s title is a reference to a quote from Shakespeare\'s play The Merchant of Venice, which states, \"The greatest thoughts are my thoughts, they do not belong.\n\n\" This line, however, is also a direct quote from a song by K-Train, who plays the harmonica on the show. The song is about a man who wants to meet the next day and meet people he doesn\'t know. This is the second time the song has been played on this show, and the first time it has been performed live.\n\nThe second time, the song is a song about a woman who is trying to get over the fact that she\'s been raped. The first time, it\'s about a young woman who\'s trying to leave her abusive husband.',NULL,NULL),(61653,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Folk Roots Radio - August 4, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 18:48:22',NULL,'The show starts off with a trio of musicians: Brooklyn-based ZT, whose style is described as experimental, and whose music has been praised as the work of the Hamad Dukasamer; singer-songwriter-guitarist Dan Max on 10 Steps; and Montreal-based singer-fiddle player Alexei Campania on Won\'t be Scared. The trio also includes singer-guitarist Sollien Donner, who has won a prize at the prestigious Kirbil Folk Festival, and singer-flautist Dieter van der Weven. The show closes with Don Ross, a Canadian musician and singer songwriter who has been hailed as an innovator. The band also includes Anna Egg, a singer and songwriter from Saskatoon, and the photo duo O Robinson and Rode, who have released a song about America\'s reaction to newcomers. Other artists include Eliza Mary Doyle of the Dead South and the Hello-Darlings, whose songs deal with grief.',NULL,NULL),(61654,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/23/Clan Na Gael - July 23, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-23 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 17:08:54',NULL,'The narrator gives a tour of the CD room at 404 York Street. He introduces the songs on the CD and tells us that they are all from the Irish Clan.\n\nThe first song is called \"The Irish Rollover\" and the second song is \"Wolftones\" from their CD. The third song is a song called \"Big Strong Man\" from the same CD. It reminds him of a giant town called Englishtown in the Cape Breton Islands. The narrator then goes on to tell us that he knows some people from the CD, including Eric Bogle, Frank McGibbo, and Barley Juice. He says that Frank is a great singer and that he and the band started out with a band called \"Six Yanks\" and that this song is disrespectful to the Celtic people.\n\nHe adds that this is not the same song. He then shows us a second song that he has lined up. This song is about \"a pint of Guinness\" and he says that it is not offensive to the Gaelic people, but that he is in love with \"a priest\" who offends people',NULL,NULL),(61655,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/A Dog’s Breakfast - August 5, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 16:56:01',NULL,'In this special edition of the host, we find out about a new music venue in town, called Silence Guelf, where you can rent a place to hang out, rehearse, or play music. We also learn that Silence is now offering flat rate rentals for $100 per day. The host is psyched to be able to play music at such a great venue. He tells us that he\'s been to Koerner Hall and the Aga Khan Center for the Arts, so he\'ll be playing music there as well.\n\nHe\'s got a new gig lined up for this evening, and he wants to play a song called \"Whispers of Love\" from a Turkish song. The song is about a woman who\'s in love with another woman. The three women are all Canadian, so they\'re all going to be singing and playing Turkish music.',NULL,NULL),(61656,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/Sound Magic - August 5, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 16:26:22',NULL,'The program opens with Michael Doles-chell, the host of Sound Magic, discussing a recent work by the Russian composer Alla Pavlova. She was born in 1952, educated all her life in Russia, and now lives in the United States. The program then discusses the work of another Russian composer, Konstantin Fedosayev, who conducted the orchestra of the Tchaikovsky symphony in Moscow. The work is described as a large, rambling symphony, no longer fraught with technical landscapes, and it is a new age music. It was first released on Naxos in 2002. The program ends with Doloshell, the music critic for CFRU, signing off.',NULL,NULL),(61657,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/This Night Wounds Time - July 10, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 16:12:44',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music on the show. It\'s all from San Juan, Argentina, and it\'s being played by a band called \"Asterias.\" They\'re from San Jose, California, and they\'re releasing their first album this week. The band\'s name is Asteriascamp, and their music is described on their Bandcamp page. The first song on their album is called \"In The Air.\" The second song is \"In the Air 2.\"',NULL,NULL),(61658,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/21/Folk Roots Radio - July 21, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-21 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 15:10:07',NULL,'The program opens with a song by Noah Dirksen. He is a Canadian-American folk singer songwriter who has released his latest album Sanctity Of Silence. The song is about a broken heart and a walk through the woods. The rest of the show opens with some of the artists who have been featured on the program before. They are: Meredith Moon, Ron Fettbeck , Liv Kullzelra and Fellin , Braden Dawson , The  Fugitives , Brenda MacLeod , Charlie Acourt , Lloyd Spiegel , Bruce Coburn , Grant Davidson , and The Show of Hands .',NULL,NULL),(61659,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/23/Clan Na Gael - July 23, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-23 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 14:53:56',NULL,'Clan Na Gael is a music show hosted by John Fahy on CFRU 93.3. The show is a celebration of the music of the Gaelic and Irish peoples and it is a part of a larger program hosted by Fahy and his friends.\n\nThe show begins with a song called \"The Dunkey\" by a Scottish band called The Rogues. The song was first recorded in Irish by the Dubliners in the early 1800s. It has since been a worldwide hit. The next song is a tribute to Dubliners \"Seven Drunken Nights\" which has been banned in Ireland since it was recorded in English. The final song is Scottish by the Rogues',NULL,NULL),(61660,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/15/A Dog’s Breakfast - July 15, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-15 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 14:32:33',NULL,'This program is a re-run of the program \"A Dog\'s Breakfast\" from June 21, 2014, hosted by DJ Apostrophe. The program begins with a selection of music from the university\'s new library, including two songs by the Portuguese composer, Amor Pacifica and Thievery Corporation\'s \"Saldade.\" After listening to the songs, Apostrophe says goodbye to his listeners, who will be his last dog breakfast at the university. He announces that Kim Loew, who has replaced him as host of the show, will be taking over at 10 a.m.',NULL,NULL),(61661,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/Sound Magic - August 5, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 14:09:12',NULL,'The program opens with Harnold conducting his own orchestra, the Concentus Musicaus, in a program of unknown Russian symphonies. The music is made up of works by Aleksandrovich Kaurvakov, Aleksandrovich Yelvekov, and Sergei Slominski. The first three are works that were recorded in the late-Soviet era. The fourth is a work that is very brightly scored, and it was dedicated to Slominsky\'s father. The other works in the program are works by other composers who also recorded in this era.',NULL,NULL),(61662,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/Beautiful Druid - August 5, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 13:53:18',NULL,'On this week\'s program of the Beautiful Druid, Alden Hadwen, a student at the university in Guelph, Canada, reads poetry and plays music. He\'s been a part of the university\'s music program since it began in 2000, and he\'s the host of the program. The program is called \"Beautiful Druid\" and every week they play an hour of music. Today\'s theme is \"Irish sensibility and depth,\" which Alden describes as \"a sensibility, a Irish sensibility.\n\n\" He says that the song that made her famous was her song \"Nothing Compares To You,\" which was on her 1991 album \"I do not want what i havent got.\" She won a Grammys for her song. The first song she\'ll sing is from her album \"Sean No Snua,\" which is a collection of songs from her life. After reading the poetry, Alden says, \"We\'ll hear some songs from Sean No Snuva, which is my songs.\n\n\" Then he\'ll play a song called Nothing ComparesToYou, which was her first hit in 1991. She won the Grammy for best song of the year in 1991. We\'ll also hear Enya\'s song Shepherd Moons, and Van Morrison\'s \"She moves through the fair\" from his album \"Heartbeat.\" Then Alden\'s favorite song is by Enya, \"Marble Halls,\" which sounds like a traditional song about living in a \"castle as a woman.\" And then he',NULL,NULL),(61663,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/This Night Wounds Time - July 10, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 13:33:11',NULL,'In this episode of the Dimension of the show, Aaron Badgley and Connor Moran talk about some of the work they\'re doing on CFRU. They\'re working with a group called the Life in Covid Study. They want to study the experiences of people age 65 and older during the pandemic. They also want to hear from people about their favorite music. Aaron\'s a music host on the show called Here Today, and he\'s looking for listeners to come and listen to his show every Thursday morning.\n\nThe Alzheimers Society of Wellington is looking to get people to help them with their music program. The music program provides people living with a free iPod with a special playlist for them. They need people to set up the iPods, donate gift cards, or buy iPods. If you want to get involved, go to alzamer.ww.ca.',NULL,NULL),(61664,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/14/Folk Roots Radio - July 14, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-14 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 13:11:30',NULL,'In this episode, the host and producer of Folk Roots Radio talk about the music on the show. They explain that they\'re going to focus on the artists and not just the music they hear on the program.\n\nThey ask listeners to consider buying the artists\' music so that they can support them. They start with Canadian-American musician Noah Dirksen, who has a song called \"You Got a Hold On Me\" from his latest release, A Broken Heart Sanctity Of Silence. They also talk with singer-songwriter Janice Hall, who is here with the host. The first artist we hear from is the daughter of the great Gordon Lightfoot.\n\nThe second artist is Meredith Moon, who plays the banjo on her latest album Constellations. The third artist is Liv Kukultera, who also plays on her album, . The fourth artist is Steve Dawson, a Nashville-based singer songwriter. The fifth artist is Brenda MacLeod, a Vancouver-based musician. The sixth artist is The Fugitive\'s, a band from the city of Vancouver. The seventh artist is Statz, an artist from Mohawk, who sings folk songs. The eighth artist is Bruce Coburn who sings a song about climate change. The ninth artist is Grant Davidson, a Winnipeg-based artist. The tenth artist is Show of Hands, a legendary folk band from England. The eleventh artist is the legendary Irish American harmony group Trackdogs, who play the Cousin Emmys Ruby Bluegrass Standard. The twelfth artist is Summer',NULL,NULL),(61665,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/16/Clan Na Gael - July 16, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-16 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 12:52:55',NULL,'In Guelph, Jim and John Fahy discuss the history of Ardrossen, a small town in South Simcoe County, Canada. Ardrosseans are well known for their music, especially Stan Hamilton and Jim Bruce. Stan is now dead at Blind Scotsman, but his band continues to play.\n\nThe two men also talk about their host, Mr. Fahy, a man they met when they were young. He is a Scottish-American musician who has a special fondness for Scottish dancing. Jim tells a story about how he and his wife used to dance with Stan Hamilton, but when they asked John to join them, he refused to wear a kilt. Jim explains that he bought the kilt back after a friend gave it to him in Rochester, NY. Jim says that he had a sparring with John, but that he enjoyed the dancing. He describes Scottish dancing as one of the most enjoyable things he has ever done. Jim introduces his song, \"Bookle on Air,\" which he played with John in the first set of songs from the music CD of the same name.\n\nBefore Jim introduces the song, he tells Jim about his wife and his life. He says that they bought a boat and sailed around the world for ten years. They sold their businesses and moved to their new boat. They set off across the Atlantic Ocean in 1997.',NULL,NULL),(61666,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/Sound Magic - August 5, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 12:28:11',NULL,'On this week\'s program, Michael Dochowlas discusses the latest recording of symphonic dances by Russian composer, Sergei Rachmaninov. The program also discusses the recently released recording of his piano works by Russian-American composer, MarkAndré Hamelin. The two discuss the Russian composer\'s relationship with the salon culture of his homeland and the music of his contemporaries. The show closes with a discussion of the piano sonatas by the Russian piano composer, Alexander Feinberg. The piano music of these works, however, differs from the symphonies and concertos of his compatriots.',NULL,NULL),(61667,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/29/Beautiful Druid - July 29, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-29 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 12:09:01',NULL,'The show opens with a welcome from Alden Hadwen, the host of Beautiful Druid, a live music show that airs on CFRU, the Canadian Broadcasting Company. The show\'s theme for the evening is \"Nova Scotia,\" a province in Canada that is home to a great many people and places.\n\nThe song that Alden will play is called \"Rise Again,\" a song from the Rankin family, which is from their album \"Souvenir 1989.\" The song is about life\'s tragedies and rebirth. The other music on the program is from musicians from Nova Canada, including Ashley Mckayze, Stan Rogers, and the fiddle player, Ashley MacIsaac. The program ends with a song by Stan Rogers called \"Different from Rise Again,\" which is a song about a romantic re-floating of a boat.',NULL,NULL),(61668,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/This Night Wounds Time - July 9, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 11:51:40',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the show\'s purpose. The show is mandated by the government to feature music that is \"off-center,\" or \"too very off-centered.\" This means that they can play music from any part of the map, but they can\'t play music of a completely off-kilter nature. They\'ll be shifting their focus to the \"geographic spotlight entry series of The Night,\" where they\'ll simply play music that\'s from one place on the map.\n\nThis is the first time that The Night has been doing this, so it\'s important to note that they\'re not just playing music from the outside world. They can also play from the inside of the world, as they\'ve been doing with the \"Argentina spotlight series.\" This time, though, the spotlight will be on the city of \"Buenos Aires,\" which is by far the smallest city in the country. This means they can choose from any place in the city, even if it means choosing from something \"off the menu.\n\n\" The show will also begin with music from a new album by Louise Campbell, who is a Montreal-based artist. She\'s released an album called \"Sources,\" and she\'s got a long track called \"People of the Sea.\" This track was written in the midst of the Pandemic in 2019, just before it was officially declared a pandemic.',NULL,NULL),(61669,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/16/Clan Na Gael - July 16, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-16 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 11:30:46',NULL,'Clan Na Gael is a Scottish music festival. This year, it is hosted by John Fahy. The first act is a special guest, Jim Bruce. Jim is a singer songwriter and musician. He and John met in Beaton, Canada about forty years ago. Jim and John have been friends ever since. John tells Jim that he is not a great player on the guitar, but that he will try his best to keep Jim\'s listeners happy.\n\nJim tells John that he and his wife went to Hamilton to see the story of the two men who brought Simon and David Garfunkel\'s songs to life. They had a great time. They are going to play some songs. Jim says that he likes David\'s song about a paperboy. He also likes the song about the paperboy by Gwen Swick. He says that it is a haunting song. The other songs include those by James Gordon and the Silly Wizard. Jim also sings a song about being a Canadian. It is called \"The Blue Nose\" and he has sailed on it twice',NULL,NULL),(61670,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/15/Sound Magic - July 15, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-15 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 11:13:59',NULL,'In this program, Dolachow discusses Louis Andresen\'s \"Hybrid Work,\" which he describes as a kind of \"opera\" but which is more like a \"pre-dramatic issues\" kind of work. It is very well-done on the recording, but it is impossible to translate what is actually going on because it is constantly changing around.\n\n\"More than in dreamlike way, / It sometimes really seriously doesnt make any sense,\" he says. \"So it is basically a text-structure which / has changed into this kind of more than or less two-hour musical structure,\" he concludes. This is also one of the \"longest pieces\" he has ever played in \"in a single arc\" . The piece is conducted by Reinhardt de Leuven and it is recorded at the Walt Disney Concert Hall by Nunsuch.\n\n\"The incredible clarity of acoustics and sound\" , he says, \"is quite remarkable,\" and that\'s it for this program.',NULL,NULL),(61671,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/22/Beautiful Druid - July 22, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-22 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 10:50:14',NULL,'In this program, the host, Alden Hadwin, describes the program Beautiful Druid, an hour-long program of song and dance. He says that there is nothing like dancing, and he wishes that there were more opportunities to do so. The first song is George Strait\'s \"50 Number Ones,\" and the next four songs are all about dancing, including Van Morrison, Emmylou Harris, and Emmylou\'s husband, Rodney Crowell. The final song is Mary Chapin Carpenter\'s song \"Down at the Twist.\" The program ends with an interlude from Shall We Dance, a movie about dancing.',NULL,NULL),(61672,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/Clan Na Gael - July 9, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 10:36:15',NULL,'The next episode of Clannagale is a celebration of the American Revolution. This program will feature the work of Ed Video, a Guelph-based organization that supports the creation of new media and culture through education, workshops, and community outreach.\n\nThe organization encourages people to get involved in the process of making art. The association hosts a series of free, public workshops and professional development opportunities for local people to learn how to make their own work. It also hosts a yearly festival where local artists and others can showcase their work. The festival is free, open to the public, and is a great way for people to meet new people.',NULL,NULL),(61673,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/15/Sound Magic - July 15, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-15 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 10:14:30',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the work on the program. It is a work by a Dutch composer named Louis Andresen. The work is described as a \"theater of the world\" and is described in terms of its complexity and difficulty. The opera is performed in English and it deals with a medieval philosopher and a proto-science. The dialogue is in Dutch and the music is not too \"dodecaphonic\" or \"ultra-modern sounding\" . The music gradually takes the listener along the course of the opera.',NULL,NULL),(61674,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/15/Beautiful Druid - July 15, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-15 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 09:52:58',NULL,'This program is produced by KNEX Ontario and the Guelph Community Station. The program is called \"Trains, Summer Trains, and Travel by Train\" and is a half hour program. The theme for the program is trains. It is summertime, and people are traveling all over the country.\n\nThey are traveling up and down, and across their province too. The music program starts with a whistle recording of a train whistle. Then it is a little bird song. It reminds the listeners of the peaceful and tranquil nature of the summer. After that, the program ends with a brief piano piece to remind listeners that it is all peaceful.',NULL,NULL),(61675,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/09/Clan Na Gael - July 9, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-09 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 09:11:14',NULL,'In this program, we learn that the host of the show is a musician named John Fahy, who is from the town of Clannigale in northern Scotland.\n\nThe first track he plays is an American song by Joni Madden, but the reason he\'s playing it is because the band celebrated their independence day on Tuesday. The band includes an all-American band, Cherished Ladies, and a band from the area. The next song is from Laura Smith\'s \"Fire in the Kitchen\" compilation CD. The second track is from an American band called \"Solas\" which means light. The third track is a live double CD from the reunion concert of Solas. The fourth track is \"We Be Soldiers 3,\" a song by Theresa Doyle. The fifth track is an English song called \"Posing as Human,\" which means \"the river.\"',NULL,NULL),(61676,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/15/Sound Magic - July 15, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-15 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 08:46:12',NULL,'The first part of this program is about a few Dutch composers that didn\'t make it in the classical world. The first piece we hear is a symphony by Christian Bach, who was a big star in London during that period.\n\nThe symphony is a little bit of a history lesson. Back then, no one knew much about Sebastian Bach, the son of the famous composer. Sebastian\'s father wasn\'t very famous, and no one ever heard of him. Anyway, the whole thing was for his son. The Mozartists are playing the Christian Bach symphony, and they\'re called the \"Mozartists\" because it\'s a little too cute.',NULL,NULL),(61678,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Democracy Now - August 4, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 08:32:37',NULL,'On another historic day in the United States, President Trump pleads not guilty to charges that he attempted to overturn the election. Carol Anderson, a professor at Emory University in Atlanta, discusses the indictment and what it means for the rights of African Americans and other minority communities. She points out that the biggest lie of the Trump administration was the deliberate and systematic erasure of votes in many cities across the country. She adds, \"Because bedrock to the lie was the disenfranchisement of votes, African Americans, Black people, Hispanics, and indigenous people, it was treating American citizenship as if they weren\'t legitimate.\"',NULL,NULL),(61680,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Worst Responders - July 31, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 08:13:45',NULL,'This is the third and final episode of \"First and Worst on the Scene to Respond to the Internet\'s Low-Stakes Problems.\" The three female voices are Charissa, Renee, and Manuela. Their goal on the show is to respond to problems that people have posted on the internet.\n\nThey do this by talking about problems and giving advice and taking advice. They are \"improvised and it is in good fun, and it doesnt reflect the opinion of CFRU\" . They have a guest in the studio named Manuela, who is a comedian. She is a friend of theirs, and she tells them all about herself. She has been doing stand up for two and half years. She started doing it in Brazil just after she got vaccinated, she says. She tells them that she met her friend through doing standup. She says that she and her friend met in Brazil. She explains that they met because she was doing stand-',NULL,NULL),(61681,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Down the Rabbit Hole - August 1, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 07:07:29',NULL,'This week, Sam and Marty are back on the air to talk about the upcoming Ontario Pirate Festival. The festival will be held in Marden Park, in Guelph, from August 5th to 7th. There will be sword fighting, aerial work, storytelling, and a marketplace of artisans. There\'ll also be live music, dancing, storytelling and more.',NULL,NULL),(61682,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Industry Tactics - August 4, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 06:53:05',NULL,'The host begins this conversation by asking his father what he learned from him as a musician. He says that his father instilled in him a \"bringing to life\" ethic in his music. He also teaches him how to play the bass because his father was a great teacher. He adds that he does not recommend listening to any of the \"Bass Concertos\" because they are horrible. The only thing he recommends is listening to the \"Bottom of the Batacini Bass Concerto\" because it is the worst.',NULL,NULL),(61683,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Rainbow Country - August 1, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 06:31:38',NULL,'Part One: Jane and the Emmys Part Two: Schveld\'s invention of the modern homosexual Part Three: David Bowie\'s \"Moon Age Daydream\" Part Four: The lessons of life in general, and of David Jones in particular Part Five: The moral of the movie, \"Life is short; make every moment a adventure\" Part Six: The life affirming experience of going to a cinema Part Seven: The \"incredible life you have had an experience\" Part Eight: The world is a mystery to us, and we\'re not really sure what to make of it',NULL,NULL),(61685,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Silver Screen Dream Machine - August 1, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 05:13:26',NULL,'This is the first episode of Silver Dream Machine, the program about movies and the moving media. It starts off with the composer Howard Shore, who has composed the music for almost all David Cronenbergs movies and Cronenberg films. He\'s also composed music for the 1997 drama, The Ice Storm. The score is composed by MichaelDanna, who also wrote the score for the film. We also hear music from the 1997 film, based on the Watergate scandal, as two Connecticut families attempt to experiment with sex, and substance abuse, and spiral out into control.\n\nWe hear a piece of music from this film written by Alina Shoplis, Joan Allens character. The third part of the program is a tribute to the late Nichelle Nichols. She was famous for her role in the original series of Star Trek and her performance as Ahura in one of the movies. She also released her debut album, Down to Earth. She released two more albums after that. She\'s a singer, too, releasing her debut in the same year that the original Star series was running, and she also released a musical album.\n\nShe sang Lansbury in a musical. Her second album, Ahura, was an obscure effort in the mid 2000s. Her third album was a concert album. The guy who played the role of Scotty in the first season of the show had trouble singing. So something\'s wrong, he says. He kisses William Shatner in the third episode of the series',NULL,NULL),(61686,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - August 2, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 04:53:52',NULL,'The second segment of the program consists of a brief introduction to the listeners, a few songs, and a discussion of the upcoming women\'s world cup soccer tournament.\n\nThe song is a song about Martha in a muffin. The segment is interrupted by an interview with Leonard Skruls, who introduces himself as the host of the show. He explains that the show is a partnership between the Gryphon sports organization and the Kabiri sports organization. The show will include news of all of the Gryphon\'s sports, and will be available on Wednesday afternoons between 4pm and 5pm. Leonard also announces that open trials for all of Gryphon sports will take place in August and September. The fee for open trials is $30 and students must pay as a client service desk at a like center, or done individuals must create an account on the system.\n\nA copy of the receipt is required for payment. Interested students must contact Sky Angus, the varsity coach at the school at ca. growth dot com for more information. The trials for the womens and mens basketball team will be held in September. Leonard is looking forward to joining the team as a manager in late August.',NULL,NULL),(61687,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/Democracy Now - August 3, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 04:33:05',NULL,'Meanwhile, in Washington, DC, federal authorities have erected barricades around the courthouse ahead of the former president\'s arraignment on charges that he plotted to undo his 2020 election loss. Meanwhile, special counsel Jack Smith has requested a court hearing to determine whether an attorney representing Trump\' co-defendant, the body man of the president, has a conflict. In Pennsylvania a federal jury unanimously sentences the man who killed 11 worshippers at the Tree of Life synagogue to death. Rabbi Jonathan Perlman of the Tree-of-Life synagogue writes in the Jewish newspaper The Forward that he does not think that the death sentence will bring justice or justice.',NULL,NULL),(61688,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Worst Responders - July 24, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 03:26:32',NULL,'In this episode of Worst Responders , two stand up comedians, Charissa and Renee, discuss how to deal with everyday problems on the web. They\'re not professionals, but they\'re good at what they do. They give advice and hot takes on problems that people write about on the internet, and they never have boring moments. This is not a serious show, says Charissa, but rather a fun show that\'s full of improvised jokes and good food. In other words, it\'s a good day to be a comedian.',NULL,NULL),(61689,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Down the Rabbit Hole - July 25, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 02:45:48',NULL,'The show opens with a shout-out to the community radio station, CFRU, which airs live every Saturday afternoon. The station also has a huge web presence, with live streaming audio, program guides, weekly music charts, and more. You can also get involved with the station by following the link on the right side of this page.',NULL,NULL),(61690,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Industry Tactics - August 4, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 02:33:25',NULL,'The Host of the podcast, Friendly Rich, welcomes listeners back to the show. He invites them to listen to the latest episode of the show, in which he talks with the musician, singer-songwriter, and bass player, Vivian Wilder. The two discuss the use of recording in music, the power of the microphone, and the difference between industry and non-industry.',NULL,NULL),(61691,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Rainbow Country - August 1, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 01:12:13',NULL,'This chapter opens with a discussion of political action taken by the anti-war movement. This is a time when there was a lot of hope for peace between the U.S. and the communists. A lot of people were involved in political action against the war effort.',NULL,NULL),(61693,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Silver Screen Dream Machine - July 25, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 00:34:42',NULL,'The program is called \"Silver Screen Dream Machine\" and it\'s hosted by Silver Screen Dream Machines co-host, Leonard Squozin. This program is all about movies and all about moving images. We start off by talking about three people who have died in the last three days.\n\nThe first is Regis Philbin, who was 88 years old. He was a host of the Joey Bishop Show, a sidekick to Joey and Kelly, and a singer. He is also known as the host of Who Wants To Be a Millionaire, which was the original American version of the game show. Philbin\'s second album is called When You Smiling, which is 36 years old now. The third person who has died is Olivia De Havilland who was 104 years old three years ago.\n\nShe was an actress and singer who appeared in movies from 1938 to 1988. She is remembered for her roles in The Adventures of the Robin Hood, Gone With the Wind, Virginia, and The Snake Pit. She is also remembered for playing the role of Hamilton in Gone With The Wind. She and her co-star Ida Lupino performed a song called Thank You Lucky Stars in the movie. It was released last month.',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO `episodes` VALUES (61694,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - July 26, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-29 00:16:21',NULL,'The show starts off with a song by Kat Labon. The guys start off by talking about how they\'re doing, which is good. They talk about the golf report and then they\'ll have music. They\'ve got a special guest lined up for the show, who will talk about his work at the magazine and the Blue Jays. Then they talk about some of the other sports that they\'ve been watching, like women\'s and men\'s soccer. The show is on the air now. They have a power outage, so they have to take a break to get their studio back up to speed.\n\nThey start off the show by playing some music from the Doobie Brothers. They play some of their own music. The music is heavy and they play a few tracks off of the albums they listen to. They say that they listened to a lot of the music on Keith\'s list of the top Canadian artists, but it wasn\'t really a good list. So they decided to make their own list. They also play a little bit about the song DOA, which was one of their favorite bands.\n\nThe songs have a \"S\" word in them, so the guys run through it. They mention that Joe Lee is the singer of the band, and that he has another name with a \"s\" word. They don\'t say anything about the other singer\'s name, but they do say that the band is from Vancouver, British Columbia',NULL,NULL),(61696,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/17/Worst Responders - July 17, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-17 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 23:17:08',NULL,'This is a sketch comedy show called Worst Responders and it is hosted by two stand up comedians, Charissa and Renee. The two of them are experts at responding to problems posted on the web. The show is a little different than other comedy shows, because it\'s a bit more serious and serious than other shows. But the show is still very funny and the two comedians are the first and worst to respond to any problem.\n\nThey give advice and hot takes about the problems they discuss and sometimes it really is funny. This is what we like about the show, though: everything you hear is improvised, and it doesn\'t reflect the opinion of CFRU . Charissa tells us she just finished a show and was just about to give an interview when she started to cry. She was very close to giving the interview away, but she had to do it over and over again.',NULL,NULL),(61697,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Down the Rabbit Hole - July 18, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 22:48:16',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61698,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/28/Industry Tactics - July 28, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-28 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 22:26:04',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61699,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Rainbow Country - July 25, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 22:14:06',NULL,'Agnes, a singer and songwriter, is on stage at the University of British Columbia. She sings a song called \"Magic Still Exists\" on her new record, which was released in April. She tells the audience that no matter what shape her man is in, he is hers and she can do what she wants with him. She says that if she thinks someone else doesn\'t want her man, she can kick him out of the streets. Agnes tells her listeners that she told her woman one night that if they stop switching around, playing the field and listening to her, she will bring her chicken home.\n\nAgnes explains that she\'s a fan of CFRU\'s 93.3 FM, the campus community and media center, and that they are looking for people like her to help with the outreach team. They need people to table at local festivals and to record short public service announcements. If you\'re interested, you can get started on the virtual general orientation at the university\'s website. Sam and Marty host the weekly podcast Tales From the Bridge. They interview science fiction authors, including authors and directors of movies, and they also provide back episodes to check out. The National Book Board of Canada is excited to share its library of over 250 works by Indigenous people with you. The stories will inspire conversations and initiate conversations about identity, family and community. To learn about hosting a screening or to find out more about the National Film Board\'s work, email Wideawake at',NULL,NULL),(61701,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Silver Screen Dream Machine - July 18, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 21:14:00',NULL,'In this episode of Silver Dream Machine, host Leonard \"Electrified Voltage\" Squosin plays music from a number of popular films. They include the follow-up to the 1997 film Cube, the 2000 film Cube 2, the 2001 film Cube 3, the 1998 film Prince of Egypt from DreamWorks Animation, and the 2019 film yesterday from the music of The Ska Rangers. The music also includes music from the film Weird, the Al Yankovic story, which was released last year. In the song that he played, Harry Potter performed a new version of the song I Love Rock And Roll. The song also includes a famous parody by the singer Joan \"Depp\", who performed the song on Al\'s first album.',NULL,NULL),(61702,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - July 19, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 20:55:32',NULL,'Another episode of the Gryphon Sports Report. The show is hosted by Taylor Boss. The program is called \"Gryphrine and Special Olympics Sports Show\" and it is produced by Taylor and Leonard. The Griffin Sports website announces that the mens hockey team will be hiring Josh Dixon as their new coach. Josh brings 23 years of coaching experience to the Griffin team. Josh joins the Griffins with a vision, insight, and skill to help the team return to the national prominence that Griffins have created',NULL,NULL),(61703,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/02/Democracy Now - August 2, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-02 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 20:34:24',NULL,'The story of the four men who were arrested in Newburgh 14 years ago is finally being told. The family of one of the men has accused the Bureau of Justice of entrapment. A federal judge agrees and orders the release of the three remaining men. The former OBGYN, Robert Haddon has been convicted of sexually assaulting a woman when she was pregnant with her twins. This is a milestone in the long-running quest to free the Newburgh Four.',NULL,NULL),(61704,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/10/Worst Responders - July 10, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-10 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 20:16:30',NULL,'The show is called Worst Responders and the two stand-ups are comedians. They are talking about the problems they discuss on the internet and giving advice and hot takes.\n\nThis is not a serious comedy show, but rather an improvised comedy show. It is hot, and it is torture to be too lazy to clean your clothes. This lesson is sure to be relevant to children. The first time a child did laundry was when she was in high school. Her boyfriend left her a cashmere sweater and she had to do his laundry on the worst setting with the liquid detergent. The boyfriend was mad at her and she was a bad person.',NULL,NULL),(61705,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Down the Rabbit Hole - July 11, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 19:07:32',NULL,'This is a condensed version of the interview with MacDee, who talks about his time at the university and how he has been able to expand his knowledge of music and culture. He also talks about the university\'s new line of clothing, which is available at the station anytime between 10am- 4pm.',NULL,NULL),(61706,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/28/Industry Tactics - July 28, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-28 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 18:53:06',NULL,'In this short introductory video, Rich introduces his new album, \"Man Out of Time,\" and then describes some of the tracks on it. The first track is a song called \"Kill Dozer,\" which he describes as a \"family affair,\" a \"dark tune,\" and a \"humored ballad.\" He hopes that his listeners enjoy the album and send him an e-mail with an update at \"friendly rich calm\" by March 31, 2023. If you haven\'t already, check out the full-length version of the album.',NULL,NULL),(61707,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Rainbow Country - July 25, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 18:34:40',NULL,'In this chapter, we\'re introduced to a new character, a political scientist named David Wolsey, who\'s working on a book about political action. Wolsey\'s a big advocate of using political action to get people to change their minds about controversial issues. For example, when the film Rambo came out, a bunch of veterans of the Vietnam War organized a huge protest, demanding that the film be made into a movie. The film was pulled from theaters, and the political action was even more important.',NULL,NULL),(61709,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Silver Screen Dream Machine - July 11, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 16:53:08',NULL,'This week\'s program is called \"Voltage\" and is a celebration of music. It starts with a musical selection of Norman Orenstein scores for various films and television shows. The first song is from the 1985 adaptation of the classic children\'s story \"Anne of Green Gables\", followed by a score from the 1987 sequel, a third installment from the 2002 television film series, and a song from the 2000 animated film \"The Continuing Story,\" which stirred some controversy due to its not being based on a book. The second song is a Blondie song for James Bond\'s first film, and the third song is one from Kelly Preston, who died of breast cancer three years ago.\n\nThe final song for the day is a tribute to the late Jim Henson, who was a pioneer in the field of dinosaur recording. The program also includes a release of the animated series \"Classic Tales,\" which was released in the same year that \"Big Songs\" was released.',NULL,NULL),(61710,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/12/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - July 12, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-12 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 16:35:44',NULL,'The first segment of the show is devoted to a song by Beck\'s band, the Red Claw. The song is called \"Double Shot\" and it\'s a nod to the fact that Taylor is a fan of the band. The first part of the segment ends with the introduction of the co-host, Leonard \"boss Taylor\" Skrozen, and the show\'s name.\n\nThe show is a partnership between the Gryphon and Cariocao sports and music organizations. The co-hosts, Leonard and Taylor, talk about their recent trip to a cottage on Lake Huron. The cottage is at the beach at Bruce Beach, near King-Carden. The vacation was a great time for Taylor and his family. They went to the cottage and enjoyed the beach, the water, the food, and sports. The only thing that wasn\'t great about the vacation was that it was a bit rainy. The weather was nice, but not great. Taylor\'s favorite part was when his coach Nick came to visit, they played games, swam, and ate some yummy food.\n\nThey also took his mom to Guy-Rye to see the movie, Indiana Jones. Overall, he had a good time at the cottage, but he was glad to come back to the show and tell all you viewers his three segments so he couldn\'t wait for the show to be back. Back on the show. The boss thanks him for the tip about the cottage. He also tells',NULL,NULL),(61712,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/21/Industry Tactics - July 21, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-21 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 15:13:43',NULL,'In this chapter, the host talks about his early days as an artist. He says that he experimented with writing in the \"pre-internet\" era, before the advent of the web. He describes his life as traveling musician and writes about his experiences in his journal. He also writes about the \"social paranoia\" that he experienced while writing his journal entries.\n\nThe host says that, as a musician, he had to confront himself with the question of why he was writing and performing and what he was doing. He admits that he was uncomfortable putting up walls around himself, but he still wanted to be free. Now, he writes music and plays live. He realizes that his writing has changed, and he feels comfortable writing and playing the piano.',NULL,NULL),(61713,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Rainbow Country - July 18, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 14:47:03',NULL,'This is the final episode of the Rainbow Country podcast. The show is packed with music, and we hear tracks from all over the world, from queer artists, to punk bands. We\'re going to finish with a thank you from Mark. He tells us that despite the craziness of the world today, we\'re living in days where dreams come true, and that people will believe in us.',NULL,NULL),(61714,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Democracy Now - August 1, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 14:33:28',NULL,'This chapter will tell the story of how the FBI created a crime by sending informants into a poor community to do their dirty work. The Justice Department, the White House, and Columbia University have all been involved in this crime. The first victim of this crime is a former Columbia University OBGYN named Robert Haddon, who has been convicted and sentenced to twenty years in prison for sexually assaulting patients.',NULL,NULL),(61715,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/21/Industry Tactics - July 21, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-21 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 14:14:06',NULL,'This is the 21st episode of the Industry Tactics podcast series, and we\'re just here to tell you that we\'ve got a great show coming up next Friday night at the Lakestage. So if you\'re a fan of Canadian weird, this is a great time to check it out. This is a guy named Friendly Rich, and he\'s here to talk to us about his visit to the house of one of our favorite songwriters, Wax Mannequin, just outside of Hamilton, on the outskirts of town. It turns out that Friendly Rich had a pretty good time, and it\'s clear that he enjoys talking to us.',NULL,NULL),(61716,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Rainbow Country - July 18, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 13:53:43',NULL,'This is a special edition of the podcast where we talk with two of the stars of the show, Jared Conley and Lorraine Segato, as well as Gord Depp of the Spoons. We\'re starting off by introducing you to Rainbow Country, a new gay radio show hosted by Mark Tara. It\'s a show that\'s been getting a lot of airplay recently. And it\'s all part of a larger effort to expand the reach of this show, which is also a podcast. So this week we\'re going to meet a Canadian singer named Jackie Shane, who rose to fame in the early days of the music scene.',NULL,NULL),(61718,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/14/Industry Tactics - July 14, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-14 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 13:30:07',NULL,'The narrator talks about the many influences that have led him to his current position as a member of the Club Foot Orchestra. He describes his early days as a clarinet player, a Klezmer player, and a jazz history teacher. He also reflects on his time in New York and his travels. He says that his first experience teaching was in Berkeley, where he taught for three terms. The narrator says that he was lucky to have been adopted by Matt Brubeck, a Canadian cellist. He explains that the narrator\'s description of him as an American cellist makes no sense to him.',NULL,NULL),(61719,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Rainbow Country - July 11, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 13:09:10',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61720,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/Democracy Now - July 31, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 13:04:02',NULL,'The episode opens with the story of the four men who have been imprisoned in Newburgh, NY for alleged acts of terrorism. On Thursday a federal judge ordered their release, and the following day a judge sentences a former doctor at Columbia University named Robert Haddon to prison for sexual assault.',NULL,NULL),(61721,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/14/Industry Tactics - July 14, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-14 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 12:15:26',NULL,'This is the second in a series of Industry Tactics, where we catch up with some of our listeners. This time it\'s Matt Brubeck, who works as a manager for a software company in Guelph, a small city in southwestern Ontario. He\'s been in town for about four years, and he\'s a big fan of the city. He tells us that he\'d never heard of Guelph before, but that he found it to be a great place to be. He also tells us about his time in Berkeley, a big city in California, where he was a creative guy.',NULL,NULL),(61722,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Rainbow Country - July 11, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 11:55:39',NULL,'This is the second part of a three-part interview with Gino Vanelli, Mark Tara, Chris Harder and Emily Saliers. Gino is here to announce that this is the first part of the three part interview with Mark Tara and that the show is now airing on 12 different radio stations across Canada.\n\nThe first part is a general introduction to the show. The second part is an in-depth examination of the show and its purpose. The third part is about the people who are featured on the show, their views and opinions expressed. The guests on this episode are Gino, Mark, Emily, Chris, and Start Out, a non-profit that works to empower queer entrepreneurs.',NULL,NULL),(61724,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/28/Democracy Now - July 28, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-28 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 11:33:58',NULL,'Amy Goodman reports that federal prosecutors have filed a new indictment against former President Trump and one of his personal aides, accusing them of attempting to alter, destroy or conceal evidence. The charges also include a new count of illegally showing classified information to visitors at his Bedminster golf club. The indictment also accuses one of Trump\'s property managers, Carlos de Oliveira, of pressuring the director of information technology at Mar-A-Lago to delete security-camera footage so that it cannot be seen by federal grand juries. De Oliveira also lies to federal agents when he denies knowing of boxes of Trump documents stashed at the club. This new indictment is not a separate indictment related to his effort to overturn the results of the 2020 election.',NULL,NULL),(61726,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Democracy Now - July 27, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 11:16:11',NULL,'On this edition of Democracy Now!, we look at the legal problems facing former Vice President Joe Biden, who\'s facing federal charges for lying to Congress about his role in the Whitewater affair. A judge has rejected his plea deal and given him 30 days to explain why he should be allowed to keep his guilty plea. This is just the latest in a long line of problems for the former vice president. The program opens with a description of Hunter Biden, and we\'re told that he\'s in jail for lying about his involvement in the illegal gambling business.\n\nHe\'s supposed to be sentenced to three years in prison, but a judge has thrown out that sentence. Now, we hear from a journalist who was attacked by an attack dog at a Virginia prison, and from a police officer who',NULL,NULL),(61728,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/26/Democracy Now - July 26, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-26 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 10:53:50',NULL,'Democracy Now! is back in New York with a special program on the 70th Anniversary of the armistice that ended the Korean War 70 years ago. Peace activists are in Washington D. C. to call for President Biden to end the war and an eyewitness to the murder of Malcolm X reveals that he overheard a police officer asking about the killer.',NULL,NULL),(61730,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Democracy Now - July 25, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 10:33:24',NULL,'On this program, we\'ll hear about the fight for democracy in Israel and the United States. In Israel, the government has passed a law that will severely limit the powers of elected officials, and there\'s a mass protest movement against the bill. In the U. S., 19 state attorneys general are demanding action against a new law that gives the government authority to require doctors to check patients\' records for abortion history. This is an overreach of power designed only to intimidate and terrorize patients seeking health care. In Kentucky, the program will speak with a leading American Kurdish activist, who just walked out of Washington to the United Nation to rally for stateless Kurdish rights.',NULL,NULL),(61731,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/Hellfire Radio - August 4, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 10:15:50',NULL,'The guys are psyched to have Mike Moochie on the show, and they\'re psyched to hear his song, \"The Culperates,\" which they\'ve heard before. Saxon, the guitar player, asks Mike if he\'s ever played a guitar that wasn\'t made by someone else. Mike says it\'s not a normal guitar lesson, but that he\'ll tell his teacher about it later. Saxon asks if he played the show with Ben Grossman and his band, and he says it was fun.',NULL,NULL),(61732,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/15/Jitterbuggin - July 15, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-15 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 09:17:23',NULL,'This program is a mix of live music and conversation. It starts with Adrian Jaye, the host of the local community radio station Jitterggin\', and then it moves to a conversation between Jim, the DJ, and the listeners. Jim is excited to be in Guelph, and he tells listeners that he has managed to get into the university by convincing one of the bus drivers to let him in. He also tells listeners he plays rock and roll, gospel blues, and Canadian music. He says he plays a lot of music, but sometimes he\'s sleepy. He tells listeners to call him at 519-837-2379 if they want to talk to him.',NULL,NULL),(61733,1615,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/Off the Beaten Track - July 27, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 08:53:19',NULL,'This week\'s edition of Off The Beaten Track is a mix of soothing and experimental music. The first track is a Felix Laband song called \"Falling Off a Horse.\" The narrator imagines himself galloping along the back of the horse on a sunny, warm day in Italy.\n\nHe invites listeners to listen to the song and tell him what they think. Next, we hear a Japanese musician\'s song, \"Micro Blank.\" As the show continues, the narrator tells us that he\'s been experimenting with meditation recently and that he feels like he has found a secret cure for happiness. He wants to spread the word about the benefits of meditation to everyone around him. The narrator says that she noticed how people around her were changing after she started meditating, and that her son became a \"ball of sunshine\" because she was all about being \"present and playful\" with him.\n\nShe says that meditation is free and that she brings the \"Oasis\" with her whenever she can. She starts her day with a \"15 or 30 minute\" yoga practice and then concludes it with a ten or fifteen minute meditation. The song she\'s going to play is called \"Eleuthera\" by Tor, an award winning musician from Vancouver, Canada. When composing this song, Tor intended to evoke a \"sense of rootedness\" and \"peacefulness\" through his music',NULL,NULL),(61734,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/Under the Needle - August 1, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 08:34:59',NULL,'The band, now called the Rose City Band, is a psychedelic country rock band that avoids being lost in the \"morass\" of bar band music by simultaneously being \"true to its references\" . They play a variety of songs, ranging from familiar country rock to \"indie original vibe\" that sounds \"so fresh.\" They have a flexible line-up and they \"breeze through each number\" with a \"masterful\" vibe. The band\'s newest song is called \"Garden Party\" and it was recorded by the band on the road for their new release. We learn that the song was named \"porch music\" and that the porch music is a favorite of the band.\n\nThe song is \"weeding their time trying something to achieve something / Let\'s face / It is unrealistic.\" The band also plays two songs from their third album \"Earth Trip and Podcast\" and one song from their second album \"Summer Long.\" We thank the band for coming to visit KEXP and we invite you to check out their Sound and Vision program.',NULL,NULL),(61735,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/New or Never - August 1, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 08:15:17',NULL,'On this episode of the Hellfire Radio Show, we hear the guys talk about the upcoming hillside festival. The festival will take place at the lake conservation area from July 28 to 30, and if you\'re looking for some live music, you can check it out on the festival\'s website.\n\nThe next show is going to feature two different bands. It\'s going to be a Canadian loud band called Lemon Sleay Chunder, and it\'s also going to have an all girl band called Girl in This band. The guys also tell us that there will be a lot of CFRU programming going on at the festival, which means listeners can tune in for some of the news from the hillside. The show also features a song called \"Dead or Calling\" by a band called Crusher Special Ops. Leonard also tells us that he\'s used to seeing Terminator films, so he knows a thing or two about the Terminator movies.',NULL,NULL),(61737,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/28/Hellfire Radio - July 28, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-28 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 07:53:35',NULL,'The group discusses a number of new releases that they have heard from various bands. The first is a song called \"Low Body Chemical Burn\" by a band called LBCB. The second is \"Pure Sport\" by another band called Touching God, and the third is \"Courtship\" by an artist called Vortex. The fourth track is \"The Future Remains in Oblivion\" by the self-titled band. The fifth is \"Elder Scrolls: Skyrim\" by \"Touching God.\"',NULL,NULL),(61738,1615,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/13/Off the Beaten Track - July 13, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-13 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 07:17:29',NULL,'In this week\'s episode, the host talks about celebrating diversity in humans and encouraging everyone to live their lives on their terms. He compares today\'s music to a dance floor, where there are so many different types of music to choose from.\n\nNext, he falls in love with a song by Charli, who describes herself as \"everything I want\" and not a \"bad guy.\" The host goes on to talk about another song by a Canadian musician named Foxtrot who grew up with a classical upbringing, but she was never satisfied with her studies and wanted to express herself. She wrote her own music using \"a balance of great melodies and outstanding beats.\" In this episode of Off The Beaten Track , Jean talks about a song called Prickly Puffers by Galen Tipton, which he describes as \"a hyper-stimulating track blending ASMR , IDM and ambient sounds .\n\n. \" In this segment, the host talks about his first experience with ASMR. He was browsing through a music streaming services when he came across a track called \"ASMR\" . He listened to the music and felt like the music was whispering to him about \"who knows what.\" He turned off the music because he couldn\'t follow his curiosity.',NULL,NULL),(61739,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/Under the Needle - July 25, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 06:54:41',NULL,'Welcome to Live! On the show today, it is the debut of Caroline\'s new album, Desire I Want To Turn Into You. The song Welcome to My Island opens with a vocal acrobatics and the music flows effortlessly through genres. The first song on the album is called Welcome to the Island and it is one of the most talked about songs on the record, and the song is a direct response to the pandemic anthem.\n\nCaroline says she wrote Ocean of tears and So hot You\'re hurting my feelings in LA 2018, and it was just dumber, brat here and codeswitchy and deadpan and it wasnt really like crystalline and like narrative as the other songs. She says she was thinking about this album as something that was dealing with abstraction and like linear lyricism. She was trying to be freer and more wilder than she has ever tried before. Caroline plays three songs from the album Oh the Mode the Mode is lethal and she says she wants to show her place the place was that was blood butter and that was Dio and that song was our live show with Caroline.',NULL,NULL),(61740,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/New or Never - July 25, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 06:31:41',NULL,'On this program, we hear new music from a variety of different artists, including Katie Tupper, Spagonia, Julia Sound, and Sigur Rass. We also learn that the CFRU Media Center is looking for music and media volunteers to assist with all of their projects. If you are interested in music production, we offer you the chance to help edit music shows, live events, or assist with the production of ads and promos. We invite you to join us on Sunday nights at 8 to 9pm to hear the latest music',NULL,NULL),(61741,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/Democracy Now - July 24, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 06:16:18',NULL,'The program opens with a look at the cruelty that has been happening at Texas\'s border. The cruelty continues, and Texas Governor Greg Abbott has not stopped using large coils of wire to block the flow of illegal immigrants. The Department of Justice threatens to sue, and we\'ll hear from Texas Senator Roland Gutierrez and from a journalist who saw 50 illegal immigrants being held in chains with little shade. Then, the program launches into a big story about New York City agreeing to pay a $13 million settlement to the victims of police violence during the Black Lives Matter marches of 2020.',NULL,NULL),(61742,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/21/Hellfire Radio - July 21, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-21 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 05:52:01',NULL,'On this episode of Hellfire, the gang starts off with a CD they recently bought for a good price. It turns out that the CD is in very good condition, so they\'re able to use it as a starting point for a new episode. The gang then talks about some of their favorite bands, including Necking from west of the Rockies.\n\nThey also talk about the American punk scene, and how they are both equally as good as the British punk scene. They then switch gears to a Canadian artist who is releasing a new style of music called \"experimental.\" The band is called Flatbed, and the song \"Open Up and Bleed\" is the title track. After listening to some of the other bands, they switch gears again and start listening to the \"Tales of the Tomb\" album. They kill two of the band members and enter the \"nightmare hall\" to listen to the album.',NULL,NULL),(61743,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/Under the Needle - July 18, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 05:12:22',NULL,'In this week\'s show, Troy Nelson and Julian Martlew discuss the importance of the psychedelic band Los Mirlos and how they\'ve influenced music all over the world. They\'ve been playing music since 1973, and they\'re still going strong. They have more than 30 records to check out, and they have a lot of great music in this live session. KEXP thanks the band for coming on board, and it\'s also great to see that they recorded the music for our partner station, KWVA, in Eugene. Check out the music and all of the videos of this show at YouTube.',NULL,NULL),(61744,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/18/New or Never - July 18, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-18 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 04:53:32',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of New or Never, Adrian Hoad Reddick and a host of other guest artists bring you the freshest new music. The first track is a gorgeous song by Sigur Ross. The second track is from Ben Howard, a singer-songwriter who suffered a stroke last year.\n\nThe third track is by Lekke Awyinka, an African musician who grew up in London but has lived in Lagos for the last 30 years. The fourth track is passed clouds by Carla Luna White, a one woman show singer songwriter producer and engineer. The fifth track is Blue and Orange by Mary Bain, an English pop musician from her Buckinghamshire second studio. The sixth track is Rome by Alexei Franklin Electric, a Canadian folk collective who received a Juno Award nomination for breakthrough band of the year.',NULL,NULL),(61746,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/14/Hellfire Radio - July 14, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-14 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 04:32:47',NULL,'In this episode of Hellfire, Leonard and Saxon continue their conversation about punk music. They discuss Metallica\'s latest album, You Must Burn, which was released in 2023. They also discuss several other recent releases from the underground, including a metal band from the West Vancouver area, a punk band from Winnipeg, and a song from the Amazon tribes. The show ends with a song by the band Akshamel, which they call \"Akshamel a mouthful kingdom of sand\" .',NULL,NULL),(61747,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/Under the Needle - July 11, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 04:11:37',NULL,'In this episode, Troy Nelson introduces the band known as Austin TV. They\'re Mexican musicians who have been playing music since 2001. Their first record was an EP, followed by the B side and live cuts, Azrael , Fontana Bella , and their latest is out on Bandcamp. You can hear more of their live shows here. Also check out their new El Cintivo TV podcast. If you\'re interested in improving your job skills, KEXP offers a free program called UpSkill for Work. It teaches you how to become more confident in your skills. This program also offers free access to the Freehub Community Center, where you can get help with your bike repairs.',NULL,NULL),(61748,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/11/New or Never - July 11, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-11 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 03:12:23',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the ten new tracks on the new or never playlist. The first song introduces the story of a Japanese legend called \"Teke Teke\", which describes a ghost who chases and slices humans in half.\n\nThe second song introduces Doppelgangers, an underground band from Bristol, England. The third track introduces the band Elevator, who have been discovered by Elbow. The fourth track introduces Somerset\'s, an Ottawa-based band comprised of renowned singer-songwriters Callie Mattson, Andrew Sauca, and Louise Campbell. The fifth track introduces Badia Buriz, an Algerian singer and composer. The sixth track introduces Trans Rymel',NULL,NULL),(61749,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/21/Democracy Now - July 21, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-21 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 03:22:15',NULL,'Meanwhile, the United States continues to use cluster bombs on the battlefield in the Middle East. In Nebraska, a teenager who used an illegal abortion is now suing her family for helping her get the pills. Meanwhile, Nebraska has signed new legislation to ban abortion, and the U. S. Senate has signed a new law to ban it as well. We\'ll get more on this in a second.',NULL,NULL),(61751,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/Democracy Now - July 20, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-28 02:16:22',NULL,'A record heat wave continues across the southern U.S, with dozens of records set. More than 44 million Americans are affected by the smoke from wildfire, and in northern Mexico, more than 50,000 people are stranded waiting for asylum. In India, the swollen Yamuna River is causing widespread flooding.',NULL,NULL),(61765,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/prvqfa/karibuni_aug_6-23atsjj.mp3','2023-08-07 05:11:15',287962512,'2023-12-27 19:15:24',NULL,'On this edition of the show, we\'re joined by Jim Turner, who\'s coming to the show to introduce some guests, and by Nadine McNulty, the co-host of the program. Jim and Nadine talk about the upcoming Habari Africa festival, which is coming up next weekend. The festival will be free and there will be lots of music, children\'s activities, and workshops. Jim tells us that there will also be a big musical show called Cimaroni Revival, which will feature a bunch of musicians from Zimbabwe, as well as some tribute acts. The show will also feature some of the great singers from Africa, including Ms. Blandin, who is based in Toronto.',NULL,NULL),(61766,189,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3wfdhb/VFTC_Aug2ndJnBb2fxj.mp3','2023-08-06 08:09:55',281900929,'2023-12-27 18:53:54',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the music that will be played at the show. The DJ is named Joel, and he is the guy who manages the music at the Crypt.\n\nHe\'s also known as the Crypt FMmaster. He says it\'s a pleasure to do shows live in the studio. He welcomes back two guests who have been there before. They\'re back for an encore. The guys are called Mr. B. and the Jelly Roll Man. They are here for a show. They play a bunch of songs, and they\'re all inspired by the music they hear. They talk about how they\'d like to become a singer and sing to a \"Spanish bum\" who sings for ladies of great virtue, and how they would like to be surrounded by \"some Chinaman\" who would be like a \"Jules and the Devil\" to them. They would all be called \"Shackey\" and they would all grow up together. They all would be \"in an awful mess\" .\n\nThe sound of the sound comes from the Crypt, and the DJ says he likes it. He adds that the music is \"dope\" , and that the DJ brought ten songs, including Neil Young\'s \"How Can you Go Wrong\" and \"Edda James\", which is one of his favorites. He also talks about how he was ready to \"smoke\" when he heard \"Icontina Turner\" sing. He thinks that',NULL,NULL),(61767,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/vmzeb2/August_6_2023_repeat_of_July_2_2023_Across_the_Universeajt2v.mp3','2023-08-07 00:32:40',431961989,'2023-12-27 18:33:54',NULL,'Ken Stowar is the host and producer of the weekly music program, \"Across the Universe\", which airs every Sunday at 5pm on CIUTFM. He welcomes listeners from all over the province and the United States and thanks them for their support. He also acknowledges that there are many listeners from Minnesota who have been listening to the show every week.\n\nKen begins by playing a song from the Soul Macosa album, which was one of the most popular albums of the early 70s. The song is called \"New Bell\" and Ken sings it. Ken closes the show by playing another track from the Liquid Bloom project, \"Just Wanted to Dance.\" The track was written by Jane and produced by her longtime collaborator Nuchi. The track references Miriam, also known as \"Mama Africa.\"',NULL,NULL),(61768,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/b7rcs4/ABROAD_76_TFA_Vermont283klm.mp3','2023-08-06 23:32:56',113470824,'2023-12-27 18:10:00',NULL,'This is a very short program that takes place in',NULL,NULL),(61769,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Seems Like Old Times - August 6, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 23:09:10',NULL,'The play\'s director, David Copperfield, is ecstatic to have his latest hit made. He is especially happy because his star, the young actress, Sandra Owen, has been cast in the lead role. But, as soon as the play is finished, the role is cut short, and the actress, Bernice Rolf, is cast as the other lead. The director believes that he has created a poisonous situation for himself and his star when he cast an unknown as the lead. He also realizes that his friend, Murray Solano, is also involved with the actress.',NULL,NULL),(61770,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Seems Like Old Times - August 6, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 22:52:16',NULL,'The program begins with a description of the program and then proceeds to talk about the upcoming week\'s events. First, the program discusses the upcoming anniversary of the second atomic bomb of Hiroshima. Next, it talks about the recent release of Christopher Nolan\'s movie, \"Ophlet.\n\n\" Two weeks before the anniversary, two prominent scholars discuss the movie, and they discuss the importance of it at a time of heightened war risk. They believe that the two atomic bombings saved countless lives, but they also question whether it\'s possible to say that they ended World War Two. The two scholars discuss how the risk of war is at its highest since the 1962 Cuban Missile Crisis.',NULL,NULL),(61771,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Wind-Down - August 6, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 22:29:31',NULL,'The program starts with a new song by Ben Pierce, who\'s one of the most popular artists on the air today. He\'s also one of Canada\'s most popular underground artists. Ben Pierce and his band have been playing in the wind down all year long, so it\'s a nice segue into the program.\n\nThe wind down music starts off with some new music from Japan, then moves to Begonia\'s song Heaven, then Diana\'s \"What You Get\" from her album Familiar Touch, then Zoom\'s music, and then River Tiber\'s new song Waves from his album When the time is right. The program ends with some more music from Dayland. She\'s just released her first single, \"Baby,\" and we\'re about to finish the program when the program ends.',NULL,NULL),(61772,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/Mach Vibe Radio - August 5, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 22:07:08',NULL,'In this program, the hosts of CFRU\'s 93.3 FM, Kortra Skotra, and Big Sis, Cece, introduce listeners to their newest program, \"The Second Half of Mach-Vibe Radio,\" a free live music festival that will take place every Saturday from July 1st through September 2nd at the Bellwood Skoll House. The program is produced by Kortra, who is also the host of the program, and is accompanied by a band of listeners, including Miles, Solomon, Kim Davis, Desmond, Ole, Frisco, J2P, Nestor, Nestor Jr., Rich Lindo, and Win Bay.',NULL,NULL),(61773,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/The Underground - August 6, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 21:08:02',NULL,'This chapter begins with a description of how one can do one\'s everyday tasks in a \"E\" or easy-to-do way.\n\nThis is a very basic concept, but it\'s the only way to do a lot of things in the world. For example, if you\'re tidying up your house, you should be able to place a dustpan in the right place, place a cup in the correct place, and use your fingers to move the cup as if it were a plane landing. You should never let a bad technique pass. If you hit a chair or a window jam, you can just go back and do the same thing again. You might be surprised at how far off your course you are when you hit the chair, the window jam or the door.\n\nThe lesson is simple: if you want to be successful in life, you have to be easy. This applies to all tasks, whether they\'re free or work-related. For instance, if a student of DE wants to pick a route through the streets, he has to do it efficiently. If he wants to do his daily chores, he can do it easily.',NULL,NULL),(61774,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/05/The Underground - August 5, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-05 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 20:44:53',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61775,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - August 6, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 20:32:41',NULL,'The narrator and his friend, Oliver, go on a tour of Guelph\'s Science Museum. They\'re eager to find out more about the time machine, which is being sold by a company called \"Time Machine\" .\n\nThe narrator manages to get two of the museum\'s doors open so he can check out the machine. He also discovers that they need 600 batteries to open the machine\'s door, so they need to find a spare one in the closet. Oliver is psyched to see the machine, but he\'s worried that it\'s going to crash. He tries to hide his excitement at the prospect of the machine by saying that he\'d rather not touch the machine or use it.',NULL,'The dinosaur narrator asks if they\'re allowed to go inside the time machine'),(61776,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Visions fugitives - August 6, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 20:05:46',NULL,'The next work we hear about is George Ligetis Sonata for Viola Solo. It was written in the late 1800s. Bartok wrote a similar work for Viola in the early 1900s. This is his first work incorporating Hungarian folk music. The second work is a small orchestra work. The first work was written around 1905 and the second around 1907. This recording is a little bit more conservative than we\'ve heard before.',NULL,NULL),(61777,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Visions fugitives - August 6, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 19:11:29',NULL,'The program begins with the co-hosts, Christopher Curry and Fangwei, discussing the future of the music business. They\'ve been recording a music program called \"Visions of Fugitives\" since the beginning of the pandemic.\n\nFangwei hasn\'t been a part of the program, but he still plays a key role in selecting the music and in scripting the program. This program is set to air on August 6, 2023, and it\'s the first time this program has ever been aired on a regular basis. The program will focus on the theme of animals of summer. For the past few years, the program was focused on birds, but now they\'re going to focus on animals of the summer.\n\nThey include a work by Haydn, called \"The Bear,\" and a piece by Lechars, \"Porpor.\" The program also includes a piece called \"Winged Creatures\" by Léon, which Fangwei wrote as an introduction for the last program.',NULL,NULL),(61778,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/La Buena Onda - August 6, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 17:00:00',86507648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61779,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/La Buena Onda - August 6, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 16:00:00',86507648,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61780,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Clan Na Gael - August 6, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 18:49:54',NULL,'John Fahy is on his way to perform at the Clan-Na-Gael concert at 2pm. He tells the audience he\'s on the CFRU 93.3 program and he\'ll be there until 2pm to perform. He\'s been listening to the program, which is hosted by Pertook Blackwood. John tells the listeners that he is on the program to perform some songs from his collection of CD\'s.\n\nThey start off with a song from the Rankin family\'s collection called \"Take Me Home,\" followed by a song by Sharon Shannon called \"The Blackbird,\" and then they start with Celtic Thunder, a song that\'s very popular among the students at the university. Next up is Will Miller from the Irish Rovers. McGinty is a band from the east from a Scottish Gaelic song called \"Imlak,\" and before that they have a song called the Carlton Weaver.\n\nThe songs are all connected to the Irish having to leave because they had nothing to eat. He is reading a book called Gryphon Town Montreal, which in the nineteenth century was a haven for Irish people. Unfortunately, 7 000 Irish people died in the town after it was cleared by the Grosiels. There are more Irish people in Montreal than there were in Montreal. The next song is from a band called Wee Tree. They played at the Dublin-Ohio Irish festival. They were there this past weekend and missed the concert because of other things. But they did pay a',NULL,NULL),(61781,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Clan Na Gael - August 6, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 18:30:50',NULL,'On this day, John Fahy brings his Celtic music to the stage. First, he\'s going to play a few of his favorite songs. First up, though, is a song that he has been waiting to play all year: It\'s a song called \"I\'ve Been Strong Mom and Dad and Friends and School\" . The song is from a CD by a man named Cyril McPhee. The guy gave it to him 10 years ago. Next, he plays a song by Phil Cunningham from \"Brave Hearts\" , and then he plays the song \"Nelson Mandela\'s welcome to the city of Glasgow\" from \"Coming Home CD\" by Nody Thompson.\n\nAugust has finally arrived in Canada. The festival that John was at this past weekend was called the River-Hillside Festival. He\'s been to the festival before, but it\'s his first time ever. He says that it is one of North America\'s best festivals. He gives a shout-out to Rikki, the volunteer who helped him set up the station, and to Christopher Curry, who manages the programming for the festival. He also mentions that last week he read about the unexpected death of an Irish singer named Sinead O Connor. Sinead was from the area where John grew up.',NULL,NULL),(61782,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Zombie Jamboree - August 6, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 18:08:23',NULL,'In this week\'s program, we hear from Wendy McNeil singing a Sicilian accordion. Then we hear a track about John Gault, who may have been a fugitive from justice in Canada. Then, the second hour starts with a band called Sarus, and the first hour ends with the band, Sarus.\n\nWe also hear a Retro rocker from the band Kingdom Come Before the Osmonds. Then the third hour ends up with a track called Olalla. And finally, the fourth hour starts off with a song called Don\'T Lie. We\'re back with the program, which is all about the \"John Gault Day\" dance. It starts with the song \"Better Off with Nothing,\" which is a song about debt. Sounds like debts are bad. Then there\'s another song called Go Back Home by the Gnostic Mountains Choir. This is a warning to John to make sure he\'s not too rich to get a warm reception back home. John\'s son ended up becoming the first minister of Canada\'s economy. So, it all works out. The program ends with a reminder that it\'s tomorrow, the day before the Gault day dance.',NULL,NULL),(61783,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Zombie Jamboree - August 6, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 17:09:22',NULL,'In this program, the coordinator of the festival, Bruce, explains that the festival is a celebration of the life and work of the late John Galt.\n\nHe also describes some of the music that will be played. The first song is a song by the Constantines, which is a band that was associated with adventure and wildness. The second song is by the Young Lions, a group that had recorded a song called Young Lions in 1827. The third song is from a band called Red River Rambler, which also recorded Young Lions around 1827. This song is about a guy named Tiger Dunlop who became a drinking buddy and colleague of John\'s. The fourth song is called \"Aquarian Blood,\" a song about a \"country state\" that\'s basically a country where people hate each other. Bruce also mentions that the music being played is from the north. The music is from Jerry Cans , Tida , and Moby.',NULL,NULL),(61784,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Through the Looking Glass - August 6, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 16:48:12',NULL,'The show is about to begin. The first artist is the band from Hanover, Germany, called \"Fury in the Slaughter-house\" . The band tried to conquer North America with a video for their cover of \"When I\'m dead and gone\" , but the German version was too morbid for North American ears.\n\nThey also had a cameo in a Canadian animated series called \"Catwalk\" and a guest appearance on a Canadian comic called \"Mistress\'s Lover.\" The first track on the program is \"Mother Tongues,\" a band from the city of Barbie, Germany. The second track is \"Sauvage,\" a song from the album \"La Musique,\" by the band S. O.S. .',NULL,NULL),(61785,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/This Night Wounds Time - August 7, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 16:29:10',NULL,'This week on the Humanoid Radio program, we begin with a track by Pauline Laverros, who has released a new track titled \"Remedy Gathering\" off her latest release. It\'s about the desperation of the Solanus family. Next, we hear about Ali Aisa\'s latest track \"Barrel Stance\" off his latest release, \"Gouda Bar.\n\n\" We\'re also introduced to the host of the program, a guy named \"Hussein.\" He\'s a co-host of \"Humanoid Radio,\" which is a local public radio station. The program is hosted by a guy called \"Valerie Hussein.\" He tells us that if you\'re in trouble with your mental health, you can call toll-free 1-866-531-26. There\'s also a local station called \"Planet Groove,\" which airs every Friday from 10am- 11am. If you want to check out the music on the program\'s YouTube channel, check it out at \"CFRU 93.3FM.\" The program also has a \"green-screen dream machine,\" a recording studio set up in the university\'s library.\n\nThere are bands playing live in front of a green screen, and the program is constantly rebroadcasting their performances on the green-screen. We\'ll also learn that the military junta in Niger has closed its airspace in order to prevent any potential military intervention by ECOWAS, the West African region that has threatened to intervene. This is',NULL,NULL),(61786,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/This Night Wounds Time - August 7, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 16:09:14',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part program on the CFRU-FM station. It\'s called \"This Night Wounds\" and it\'s a program about the arts. It starts off with an introduction from Karen, who works for Die Out, a community-based organization that offers free public service announcements and workshops.\n\nIf you\'re looking for a local business to promote, they can help you advertise on CFRU. They also offer ad packages that can be tailored to fit your budget. Good evening and welcome to the program. This program is hosted by Alan and Scott, two of the most talented jazz artists in the world. They\'re both on the air every Tuesday evening at 6:00pm. We start off this program by playing a track called \"Remedy Gathering\" by Valerie and Pauline Oliveros, who are desperate. Then they play a song called \"Barrel Stance\" by Ali Aisa.',NULL,NULL),(61787,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/This Night Wounds Time - August 6, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-06 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 15:51:38',NULL,'The host of the experimental radio show This Night Wound\'s Time explains that he\'s never seen a prerecorded show before. He\'s decided to do it tonight because a colleague at the station told him not to tell listeners that a show has been pre-recorded because it ruins the magic of the radio. The show will indeed be prerecorded, and the technical issues with the recording have been resolved, so the show will go on.\n\nThe host explains that the show is not limited to one genre, but that they can play music from all over the world. They\'ll do a \"geographic spotlight series\" section after midnight, where they\'ll be playing music from a certain region of the world, even if it\'s not the most popular thing on the radio station. He says he still has bad memories of having to do a show on one particular region of Brazil, where he had to do something that was not his style of music, but he says that\'s just part of the nature of experimental radio. They have just received a new album from Emilia Cecilia Lebell, called Field Studies, on the label Redshift.',NULL,NULL),(61788,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/06/Backtracks - August