r to be Gone,\" from Gullah Geeche\'s album \"Too Much to Be Forgot.\" The fifth track is from Delbert Mac-Lintan\'s newest album \"Coming of Age,\" a collection of original songs.\n\nThe title track is one of his best songs. He\'s had a long career backing some of rock\'s most famous artists, including Little Richard, Bo Didrey, and Jimmy Reed. He also played with a band that played for the Beatles when they were in their prime. He was a part of the country blues movement.',NULL,NULL),(61883,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/mp2mb4/NF01_12-003.mp3','2023-08-08 19:04:25',143961989,'2023-12-26 00:50:48',NULL,'This is the first edition of Calling All Blues, the weekly music program on CIUT 99.5. It\'s hosted by Dr. Blues Doctor, who is also known as the \"Blues Doctor.\" He hosts the show with his fellow producers, Brooke Blackburn and \"Sugar Brown.\n\n\" They talk about the upcoming summer festivals and how to enjoy them. This week\'s program is dedicated to singer-songwriter Tammy Nielsen, who\'s living in New Zealand. She\'s a country soul singer who is performing at festivals all over the country. We also get a shout-out to two other local artists who are also performing this summer: Alison Russell, who won a Juno in 2021, and Leila Gilday, who just won a Grammy in 2021. We also hear about a group of musicians who are performing at local festivals this summer, including Mavis Staples, Gilday with Natsaju, and Leila Russell with Fo.',NULL,NULL),(61884,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/h556wj/NF01_12-002.mp3','2023-08-08 19:03:17',143961989,'2023-12-26 00:27:27',NULL,'This is the second part of the interview. It starts off with a description of Deborah Cox, a singer he used to listen to. She and her husband are good friends of his, and they used to play music together all the time. This is a bit of a change from the first part, which was about Michael Dunston and his family. This time, it\'s about another singer, Liberty Silver. It\'s a little different, though, because this time, she\'s coming to perform. She\'ll be performing all of her own material, and she\'ll also perform some of the material that she played with her father for many years.',NULL,NULL),(61885,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/7zxmdv/NF01_12-00.mp3','2023-08-08 18:57:54',143961989,'2023-12-26 00:09:26',NULL,'On this edition of Calling All Blues, host Julie Blackburn introduces the music on the show. He and his two co-producers, Brooke and Sugar Brown, host the show on a rotating basis. They play music from all over the country. This week, they play music by Brock Stonefish, Lenape Delaware, Po Boy Jeffries, and the duo Calamity Jane. They also play some music by Bessie Smith, Arlene Brown, and a song by the late Lucille Bogan. The show ends with a song about sex.',NULL,NULL),(61886,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bn4nje/NF01_12-001.mp3','2023-08-08 18:55:29',143961989,'2023-12-25 23:11:52',NULL,'This week on Calling All Blues, the show\'s theme song is \"Junior Wells on harp\" and the guitar slide is \"Earl Hooker\". The show is produced by a rotating producer named Julie Blackburn. She is one of three hosts along with two other rotating producers named Sugar Brown and \"Brooke Blackburn\". The theme song this week is \"Calling All Blues\" by Junior Wells. This is a song about the blues and the show is about the music festivals that are happening in Canada this summer.\n\nThis week the show will be celebrating Canada Day. The winner of the Toronto Blues society\'s new talent search is Brock Stonefish from Lenape Delaware who has an album Turtle Island produced by actor/musician Gary Farmer. The runner up is Po Boy Jeffries with his band Calamity Jean who are a duo who perform country blues and other acoustic style. They may not have won the competition, but they are the winners at the TBS. Now the program will tell the story of Po Boy and Calamity.\n\nPo Boy was a country blues band that started out as a busking band. Po was originally from New Orleans, so he came up with the name \"Po Boy\" because he is a sandwich from there. He and his bandmates decided to go by the stage name \"The Chitter Frog chain\" because of the heavy weight of the chain. They ended up calling their band \"The Morning Glories\" because they played all kinds of music. They met in New York City and',NULL,NULL),(61887,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ispf9c/August_11_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow7ddis.mp3','2023-08-14 17:02:13',287962512,'2023-12-25 22:44:48',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61888,289,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/yvuanw/The_Next_Stop_111a3tt0.mp3','2023-08-10 07:20:05',270185168,'2023-12-25 22:28:58',NULL,'The Next Stop is a Canadian independent music program that airs every Tuesday on CIIT 89.5 FM in Toronto. It is hosted by Sage Ranaldo, and it is produced by the same company that produces the CIIT.org website. The program opens with the music from the John Carpenter film Escape from the New York which was directed by Alan Haworth and was written by John Carpenter. The next two hours are devoted to listening to songs from the film.',NULL,NULL),(61889,1551,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/s5k4fj/AUG_3_FILE7vrq4.mp3','2023-08-14 00:38:35',431961989,'2023-12-25 22:08:34',NULL,'David James, a DJ and producer at CIUT 88.9FM in Toronto, introduces his show, \"Pam Moovin\' in the Right Direction.\" He and his crew play music from a wide variety of labels, including Antonioera, Heteris, and Sep Junior. The program starts off with a new track by Josh Wink, \"Uplifting House Music.\" After that, it shifts to a new music from Metric, a track called \"Fall to the Dust,\" and a track by Ray Keef, \"Birdman.\" Next, the program shifts to music from the upcoming Putz album, \"Protection.\" After the break, David James will host a special guest DJ set, which will include Pectin, Ian Cook, Scott Patterson, and others.',NULL,NULL),(61890,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zcac5i/ABROAD_77_TFA_Slovenia6eq5y.mp3','2023-08-12 19:36:59',113375529,'2023-12-25 21:12:49',NULL,'In this episode, Jesse introduces himself as Maximilianmo and welcomes listeners to the show, \"Tracks From Abroad.\" He explains that the show is a weekly program that focuses on the culture and education of international students at the university. The show is hosted by Jesse, who is a student and exchange student at the school. He and his student, Andre, have been friends since they were students at Robarts College.\n\nThey have developed a strong bond through their mutual interest in European culture. In this show, they will discuss music from Slovenia, a country in Central and Eastern Europe, as well as the country\'s place in Europe. Jesse also wants to thank all of the listeners for their support over the past few years. He asks them to send him an email to trackfromabroad@ciut.ca or if they have any suggestions for future episodes feel free to send a message to him on Twitter at @tfaradio.',NULL,NULL),(61891,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 15, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 20:47:40',NULL,'This program is all about organ donation. The idea is that if you have the chance to save someone\'s life, you should do it. If you don\'t have the money to donate an organ, you can still donate tissue. It\'s a great way to help save someone else\'s. And, as a bonus, it\'s free.',NULL,NULL),(61892,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 14, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 20:26:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61893,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 11, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 20:07:00',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61894,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/CFRU Playlist - August 15, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61895,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/10/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 10, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-10 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 19:07:09',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61896,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/CFRU Playlist - August 14, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61897,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Breezy Breakfast Radio - August 14, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 18:48:37',NULL,'This chapter opens with a discussion of the fixed cost of energy production and the benefits of self-sufficient power generation. The fixed cost is not the cost of the energy being produced. It is the cost to produce the energy. The self-sufficiency aspect of the project is advantageous because it allows people to control how much energy they consume and how they generate it. The other primary objection to energy is the price. The cost is also one of the most important issues that people come up with.\n\nEvan shows us a chart that compares the cost per unit of energy across several different sources. The chart includes the full life-cycle of each source. The levelized cost is the total cost of all sources. So it is not just the capital cost. It also includes the fuel cost and the fuel waste. He tells us that he is disappointed that people are not asking about the oil-sands and super-critical-oils.\n\nHe says that he knows people are trying to use these sources to reduce the carbon footprint of the tar sands. The extraction of tar sands is only about 30 percent of the total amount of greenhouse gas that goes into the atmosphere. The rest comes from burning it. He also says that the only way to reduce carbon footprint is to use more energy. He adds that he agrees with everyone else that we have a finite, growing population and need to talk more about how we use energy. This is because we are consuming more and more. He points out that we',NULL,NULL),(61898,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 9, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 18:22:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61899,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/CFRU Playlist - August 14, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:41',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61900,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Breezy Breakfast Radio - August 14, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 18:12:03',NULL,'This week\'S Breezy Breakfast has a panel discussion on the role of energy in getting us to \"net zero.\" The guests are John Stannard of Cando Energy, Evan Ferrari of Emerge, and Garetta Diaz from the School of Environment and Enterprise at the University of Western Ontario. John discusses the importance of reducing our reliance on fossil fuels, while Evan gives the pros and cons of different forms of renewable energy, while Garetta discusses the social and economic costs of mining rare earth metals for electric vehicles',NULL,NULL),(61901,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 8, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 17:06:54',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61902,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/CFRU Playlist - August 11, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:42',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61903,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Breezy Breakfast Radio - August 7, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 16:51:57',NULL,'In this episode, we hear an interview with two members of the super group Dabraha, who have been touring the world since the invasion of Ukraine by Russia in February of 2022. The group has performed over 200 shows since then, including six in Ukraine as the cities were being attacked. Since Russia invaded Ukraine, estimates have been that over 15,000 people have been killed and over 100,000 injured. In this program, we find out more about the mission of the group, as well as more about why they\'re doing this. They\'re trying to show the world that they still have the rich culture of their homeland and that they have the right to exist.\n\nThe group needs to rebuild the Russian Empire, which stole the culture from them. In the next part of the interview, we learn more about how Halanovich came to be a musician. He grew up in music and the arts, but he never thought he\'d have a career as a musician later in life, and now, as he says, he\'s really the \"face of Ukrainian culture\" . In other words, he was really the face and face of the country. He thinks about how important and important it is that he is the face of this country, and how it\'s so important that he\'ll be able to continue to play music despite all the war going on.',NULL,NULL),(61904,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 7, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 16:26:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61905,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/CFRU Playlist - August 8, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:43',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61906,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Breezy Breakfast Radio - August 7, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 15:08:55',NULL,'This is the second edition of \"Stampede Time,\" a program hosted by MacDee. It\'s about the upcoming Calgary Stampede, which takes place July 8-16. The program starts off with a recap of the history of the Calgary Stampede. It goes back to 1886, when the Calgary Agricultural Society organized a fair.\n\nIn 1908, American Guy Wiedloch organized the first Stampede, an event that was to become an annual event. In 1919, the first Canadian soldiers returned from the First World War. The first Wiedlich festival became an annual festival in 1923. The festival merged with the Canadian Industrial Exhibition in 2010 to create the Calgary Exhibition and the Stampede. In the program, MacDee and his crew talk about music and culture. First up, they talk about Bailin and hiding. Then they discuss music by the Farmer\'S Daughters.',NULL,NULL),(61907,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/CFRU Playlist - August 7, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61908,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/CFRU Playlist - August 7, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61909,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/The Deep House Project - August 14, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 14:48:59',NULL,'The guys are back from their summer vacation and they\'re ready to hit the road. They\'ve got a bunch of music to play, and they plan to start off with a song about a girl who\'s going to have a baby. That\'s it. The guys start off the show by listening to a Canadian remix of Eliza\'s truth, which sounds a lot like \"The Song of Siren\" . Then they switch it up and play a lot of music from the \'80s and \'90s. They start off by playing George Fitzgerald\'s \"Half Light\" , which reminds us a lot about \"The Siren Song.\n\n\" Then they play some classic disco tracks like None and T.Sho\'s songs \"Elixir\" and \"Water,\" and then they play \"I Go\" by DJ Cloud. Finally, they play a song called \"Me and my toothbrush Solst\" which reminds them of Will Smiths \"Atom Summertime.\" And then they finish the show with \"I Need a Lover For Myself\" by Glenn Turner.',NULL,NULL),(61910,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/04/CFRU Playlist - August 4, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-04 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:45',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61911,86,'https://archive.c