, but it wound up on his solo album. The song is called One Beer. The name of the song is Daniel Dumule',NULL,NULL),(61913,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/03/CFRU Playlist - August 3, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-03 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:46',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61914,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Ripcord Radio - August 7, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 13:52:42',NULL,'The show starts off with a list of bands that have come together in Texas and then moves to California where they have released albums. The first band is called \"marked men with imustbedead\" and they have just released their last full-length. The second band is \"MDC with tots with tofu spaghetti on ripcordradio\" and the third band is named \"Flag camp with hi hat\" and it has just released its latest album.\n\nThe fourth band is Dearhoo with \"And the moon laughs\" and their latest album is called Miracle Level. The fifth band is Jerk Ward with \"Inside my mind\" and this is from a collection called \"Too young to threesh\" which is from Supreme Echo, a record label which releases and re-issues old recordings. The sixth band is MX80 sound with \"Tidal wave\" from their debut. The seventh band is Econochrist with \"Tunnel vision on rripcord\" and \"New model army\" from Bradford England.',NULL,NULL),(61915,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/01/CFRU Playlist - August 1, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-01 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:47',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61916,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Back in the USSR - August 14, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 13:31:52',NULL,'In this interview, Haif talks about the recent developments in the Caucasus. He describes a recent military coup in Niger and the threat of war from France. He also talks about Victoria Nuland\'s visit to the country, where she was not allowed to speak with the deposed head of state or the new prime minister. She had only access to the defense minister. Haif asks where he would like to go in this story.',NULL,NULL),(61917,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Blues Around the Block - August 14, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 13:06:50',NULL,'Mac Dee is a musician who plays the blues from the South and Mississippi. He plays a lot of albums from the past few decades. He doesn\'t play the traditional blues from those parts of the country, but he does play some of the newer stuff. He starts with Roosevelt Sykes, who died in 1983. He then plays Dave Alexander, now known as Omar Shireth from an album he recorded in 1972. He also plays a few records from the early days of the Confessing The Blues movement. The earliest recording he could find was in 1957. That set had Robert Cray, I Wonder, and the Five Blues Band mid-Condition.',NULL,NULL),(61918,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/CFRU Playlist - July 31, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61919,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Back in the USSR - August 7, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 12:48:41',NULL,'CFRU\'s archives are listening to a conversation between a',NULL,NULL),(61920,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Blues Around the Block - August 14, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 12:28:11',NULL,'Mac Dee hosts a show called \"Blues Around the Block\" on the CFRU.org. The program opens with a performance by Jim Burns who covers Robbie Robertsons song \"The Shape Im In.\n\n\" This song has been covered many times by many artists including Bob Dylan, David Wilcox, and many others. Mac Dee then gives a brief history of Robbie Robertson. He joined Little Caesar and The Consoles in 1956, and then formed the rhythm section, Robbie and the Chords, in 1957. He joined the Swedes in 1959, then joined the Hawks in 1960, and the Swedes toured with Dylan in 1965. He has produced and played on many albums, film scores, and released six solo records. He passed away on September 9, 2023.\n\nHis first band was Little Caesar, and he formed the Rhythm Chords in 1957. In 1957 he joined the Chords again, and in 1959 he joined Ronnie Hawkins again. He was lead guitarist with the band until 1978. He has released many albums and has also written many film scores. In July of 1986, he released his first solo record, \"Hot Tuna.\" He then goes on to tell us about his girlfriend who',NULL,NULL),(61921,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - August 14, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 12:10:10',NULL,'In this chapter, the Guardian Overseer, Nicholas Cooper, explains that he is the guardian of the music scene. He wants to pay homage to the ancestral territories and to acknowledge the diverse musical styles that exist on the horizon.\n\nHe also wants to acknowledge that many of the musical forms featured in these recordings have adapted elements from Black culture that was created under circumstances of oppression. He wishes to thank the black community for their contributions to the popular alternative music spheres. The first segment of the program, entitled \"The Vigils,\" begins with the announcement that the program has been named the best program in the community at the recent NCRA Community Awards gala.\n\nThe Guardian Overseer then announces that he has just released his debut solo record, \"The Extended Play, the Visual Sequences,\" on August 20 on Bandcamp. He thanks a great deal to Brent OToole of the band Animatus and the label Gluegun Records for helping him to get the record on all the major streaming services. The main piece of the record will be released soon, but he wants to talk about some of the other music on the record.',NULL,NULL),(61922,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Big Sis Radio - August 14, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 11:47:56',NULL,'In this week\'s episode of \"Big Sis Radio,\" the narrator takes a deep dive into the latest news on the state of the world. He tells us that a new study by the Netherlands team has found that previous estimates of how much plastic is in the oceans have been wrong 30 times. This means there\'s still a lot of work to be done to clean up the oceans. The narrator also tells us about a band called the Darcys who will perform at the end of the festival.',NULL,NULL),(61923,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/to know the land - August 14, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 18:33:38',NULL,'The narrator begins by saying that the word \"eco\" is \"ecological functions first before our human relationship\" . He goes on to say that he doesn\'t know how to spell the word, but he thinks that it\'s important because it refers to the functions of plants before their human relationship. He says that plants need the surrounding environment to do their work. The narrator describes the weather for the next few days and says that he loves the changing seasons. He leads a walk with his partner in the Eroosa River Valley. They had a great time. The weather was beautiful and the landscape was beautiful. He wanted to learn more about the plants, so he decided to read some more. He chose to read a book about plants called \"nature\'s garden\" by Samuel Thayer, and a book called \"The book of field and roadside\" by John Eastman. The first book is from Samuel Thayer. The description of the plant is that it is a species of aster. It has a rosette of leaves that looks like dandelion. The leaves have hairs on the midrib, which is different from the leaves of the other plant. It is also very thin, unlike the other plants. The stalk looks like someone forgot to shrink the leaves. The plant has sessile leaves, which are smaller than the leaves in the rosette. The flowers have ray florets, which means that each flower petal on the flower has its own flower, not the other way around. They open',NULL,'The Garden of Aster: A Plant That Looks Like a dandelion'),(61924,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/31/CFRU Playlist - July 31, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-31 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:50',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61925,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Blues Around the Block - August 7, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 11:29:54',NULL,'Mac Dee continues his program, \"More Blues Music\" on CFRU.org. He\'s also got a new show, \"Blues Drops Falling,\" which he\'s going to finish off with Christian Rocha, who is also on the show.\n\nThe show is also free to listen to on the web. If you want to hear more of the music on the air, you can go to the archives at the university\'s web site. Also, if you\'re interested in volunteering at CFRU, there are plenty of opportunities. One of these is \"Handel and I,\" where Handel is a volunteer. The other is \"Perk,\" a spoken word show that Amorowa and Jeff run. Perk is a weekly show on the campus community radio station.\n\nIt\'s a mix of recorded interviews, pre-recorded pieces, and music. These shows are also free. The station also has a \"Ed Video,\" a hub for creating video art and film. Get started or advance your skills. Get creative and develop a community of collaborators through a series of year-round workshops and educational programming. Get involved by becoming a member of the all-star team at the Hoggtown All Stars.',NULL,NULL),(61926,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - August 7, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 11:11:35',NULL,'In this first episode of CFRU\'s new music series, \"Mixcloud,\" we meet Nicholas Cooper, the guardian overseer of the program.\n\nHe describes the mission of the show, which is to \"look inward and beyond.\" The program will be a \"live kaleidoscope\" that will \"look into the audible window out at the various, middle territories, and local indigenous peoples across Turtle Island.\" He also acknowledges that \"the majority of musical styles featured\" originated from \"adapting elements of black culture originally crafted over centuries past, and in the Prison Time\" . He also thanks the Black community for their \"too often dismissed, uncredited, contribution to 272 keys of the mansion.\n\n\" The show opens with a clarinetist named Geldin, who is an \"affected based\" clarinetist. The track on the program is called \"A Drink at the stream,\" from his album Island Friend, which was released in 2022. The other two tracks in the program are from his collaborations with the producers of the Avon Goth trio, named Output 111 and Janveer and Victor O. The first track is from his EP \"Corral from the Vigil sequences,\" which was recorded in only five minutes. The second track is a \"romantic and neoclassical\" composition, which Victor O played.',NULL,NULL),(61927,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Big Sis Radio - August 7, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 10:50:25',NULL,'This first part of the show is a bit of a ramble, with Cece introducing us to some new artists and their work. He also tells us about some of the upcoming events at the upcoming Guelph Fringe Fest. The first show is called Astro Video, and it\'s a play inspired by Oliver Pavia\'s time at a local video store.\n\nThe play will run three times during the festival: on August 10 th at 6.30PM, August 11 th  at 9.30PM and August 12 th 1PM at silence. If you want to find out more about the festival, head over to the festival\'s website',NULL,NULL),(61928,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/to know the land - August 7, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 18:22:58',NULL,'The show begins with a brief introduction of the listeners, followed by a description of the plant and a discussion of the different kinds of mulberry trees in the area. The show ends with a discussion on the differences between native mulberry and non-native mulberry trees.',NULL,'The native mulberry and non-native mulberries in the area'),(61929,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/28/CFRU Playlist - July 28, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-28 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:52',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61930,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Bridging The Social Distance - August 15, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 10:31:44',NULL,'In this episode, Jenny Mitchell interviews Bill Henry, an 85-year-old resident of the village of Riverside Glen. Bill Henry was born and raised in the East End of Guelph, and he tells Jenny about his life in the ward. He is now a senior citizen and lives at the retirement home. He tells Jenny that he used to live near York Road and Watson Road.',NULL,NULL),(61931,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Blues Around the Block - August 7, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 10:06:58',NULL,'Mac Dee welcomes his listeners to his program, \"Blues Around the Block.\" He asks them to listen to the show if they enjoyed it or any previous edition. He also asks them if they have any comments or questions about the show. Mac Dee says that he knows what he is talking about and wishes he knew then what he knows. He says that the woman he has been with has more \"itches woman\" than any man can take and wishes that he knew what he knew.\n\nHe tells his listeners that he has so many stories to tell, and that it takes time for him to \"know himself.\" He says he tried to clean her so he took her to the river and watched him drown. He said that he loved her all night, all his brain and night. He started with Hamiltons smoke wagon blues band and I Cant Change and then',NULL,NULL),(61932,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/27/CFRU Playlist - July 27, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-27 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61933,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Bridging The Social Distance - August 8, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 09:52:19',NULL,'Bill Winship is the guest on this week\'s episode of Bridging the Distance. He\'s a retired man who is a part of the community who has written his memoirs. He tells us his story. He was born very early and had a very average childhood. He contracted diphtheria in a diphtheria epidemic in Liverpool when he was very young, but he survived.',NULL,NULL),(61934,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Tuesday at 5 - August 15, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 09:08:14',NULL,'Mac Dee, host of Mountains to the sea, announces the passing of Robbie Robertson, a musician who played with both Bob Dylan and Ronnie Hawkins. He also wrote, produced, and acted in many films and albums. Robbie\'s first solo album was released in 1986. In addition to his work with Dylan and Hawkins, he also wrote and produced music for other artists. He has released six albums and 32 film credits, including Somewhere Down The Crazy River, Ghost Dance and CD Music for Native Americans.',NULL,NULL),(61935,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/25/CFRU Playlist - July 25, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-25 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:55',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61936,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Let’s Get Lost - August 15, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 08:48:46',NULL,'Scott\'s My Name, and Let\'s Get Lost, a weekly program on CFRU\'s 93.3FM, opens with a discussion of Scott Crocker\'s latest work, entitled \"My Name.\" Scott finishes by introducing the program with some music samples from the archives of the university\'s website. The program will conclude with a track called \"Simple Silver,\" a song about a woman who passed away. In the program, Scott and his co-host, Brad, discuss the importance of improving your skills in order to advance in your career.\n\nThey also discuss the free weekly program, \"UpSkills for Work,\" which is offered by the University\'s Department of Business. In this program, they discuss how to get started on a project you\'re working on, whether it\'s a new piece of art or a new skill you need to learn. They discuss Die Out, a community workshop that provides tools and equipment to help people learn how to make things.\n\nDie Out is having a grand opening on Saturday, August 19th from 12pm to 6pm at its new location, 700 York Road. On Tuesday evenings, Alan and Scott host a program called \"Humanoid Radio,\" a program that mixes experimental music with the latest jazz. This program begins with a song called \"Lull,\" from Asta-Hiroki\'s new album, Seeing anything. The rest of the program consists of tracks from other albums, including \"Groundation Meets Damage,\" \"Dream',NULL,NULL),(61937,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Tuesday at 5 - August 8, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 08:28:14',NULL,'Mac Dee, host of the Tuesday evening program on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM, opens the show with a description of the corn season. He says it\'s been domesticated by Native Americans in Mexico as early as 10,000 years ago, but it wasn\'t until Columbus brought it to Europe in 1493 that it became a staple food. He also talks about some of the new music that\'s being played on the program. First up is Willie Stratton, who\'s playing new music from his Turtle Music Records. Next up is Tracy Chapman, who is playing some new music on his smoke and ashes record.',NULL,NULL),(61938,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/CFRU Playlist - July 24, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:56',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61939,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Let’s Get Lost - August 15, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-25 08:08:28',NULL,'In this program, Scott introduces his new program, \"Let\'s get lost.\" It\'s all about the latest in jazz. He announces the release of a new album by the Mighty Quartet, called \"Pipe Dream.\" The group is playing at the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival and Scott encourages listeners to come see them.\n\nHe also mentions that one of his favorite bands, \"Eucalyptus,\" will also be performing at the festival. Scott also mentions a new track from George, the band that performed at the last festival. It is called \"Letter to George.\" The album is described as being a \"tribute to, or, at least, tributes to, four particular George.\n\n\" Scott also announces that the Jesse Zubat label has released an album called \"Plays Long,\" which was also part of the festival last year. Josh and Jesse will be performing with their band at the Royal City Missions on September 16.',NULL,NULL),(61940,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Humanoid Radio - August 8, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 07:09:09',NULL,'The second Humanoid Radio program begins with a track off the latest album by the African Head Charge. They then have Ash Walker off his latest album, A Trip to Bull-Katanga. Then there\'s a track called automation from Oscar and Joe, then groundation from an iron-gate, then an album called Dreaming from an Iron Gate, then a track titled brain beat and a track that\'s borrowed off a reconceived compilation. Then we have Rodney Sharman off his album, the Paramorph Collective off their album, a track borrowed off of a second reconceived album, an album with unknown mobile off of the reconceived disc, a piece titled brain beats off the brain beat disc, and then a piece that is borrowed off another reconceived release.\n\nWe\'re back with Beatrice Ferreira off her saxophilia quartet. We also learn that the Guelph Kidney Walk is coming up on October 1st, and that everyone is invited to join the walk.',NULL,NULL),(61941,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - August 8, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 06:46:44',NULL,'This is another episode of Gothic Castle and the music of the band from the \"pit of despair\" of Guelph, Ontario Canada. This time, we are introduced to the character I, the \"Cyber Lich\" and the listener, who is the victim of \"the darkest of sins\" . We are told that this is a 45 minute period of \"dark of dark sins\" for the listener. He is to listen to three tracks from the Isidor album Dark Knight, Genesis, and Lone Wanderer, followed by \"Remember Carpenter\" , which will never be known or remain mystery \"wrapped in an igua with a mystery riddle\". The music is \"slight at best\" and \"very few',NULL,NULL),(61942,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/10/Wild Combination - August 10, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-10 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 06:25:11',NULL,'The new line of CFRU merchandise is now available on the CFRU 93.2 FM station. CFRU students and faculty can now get a 30 percent discount on apparel during the fall/winter semesters and during the summer months. Stay tuned for the latest news. Every Friday from 10pm to midnight, Rich hosts his weekly show, \"Industry Tactics\" on the 93.2FM. This is a great opportunity for students to get involved with the arts on campus.',NULL,NULL),(61943,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/24/CFRU Playlist - July 24, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-24 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:58',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61944,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Let’s Get Lost - August 8, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 06:14:19',NULL,'On this week\'s program, Lee Fields and the hosts of CFRU\'s 93.3 FM discuss the latest music from the region. The program ends with a shout-out to the Friends of The Guelph Public Library, who have raised over a million dollars for the library. They also announce the return of the 15th annual book sale, which will be held a month earlier this year. This, combined with the library\'s 20 years of advocacy for the arts, earned the Friends the 2023 \"wealth today community builder award for the Arts\" . Lee Fields concludes his program by asking listeners to wake up early every morning to get their soul \"shaken up\" and to consider taking up medicine to save someone\'s life',NULL,NULL),(61945,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/10/Wild Combination - August 10, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-10 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 05:05:37',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61946,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/20/CFRU Playlist - July 20, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-20 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:00:59',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61947,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Let’s Get Lost - August 8, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 04:47:42',NULL,'This week on the program, the host of the Let\'s-Get-Lost radio show talks about the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival, which is set for February 14-17. The festival will feature an all-star line-up of musicians, including Francois Ulles\'s Genera Sextestet, which will perform music from his latest album, Imemorial. The program also discusses some new releases by artists such as Michael Formans Illusion Quartet, Melissa Pipe, the Art of Chicago, and the Frog Squad. The band also discusses the guitar-centric albums by Frog Squad, Zoamba, and Ceramic Dog.',NULL,NULL),(61948,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/07/19/CFRU Playlist - July 19, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-07-19 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:01:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61949,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 9, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 04:30:21',NULL,'This is the second hour of the program. It is called \"The Stillness and The Dancing\" and is hosted by Joel Cuthbert. He is a music host and he tells his listeners about some of his favorite artists. He also tells them about the upcoming Riverfest, which will take place in Alora on August 18th-20th.\n\nHe tells them that he will be giving away free passes, and that they can enter the word \"Riverfest\" to win them. He says that he has been watching the Women\'s Cup, and he wants to share it with his listeners. He starts off the program with a folk song from Michael Cattone, and then he introduces another song called \"Pine Song,\" which is from an EP called \"Meadow Trail.\" He tells listeners that he used to have the song on a prompt on the station, but that it is no longer true.',NULL,'The Stillness And The Dancing: Joel Cuthbert is listening to the program'),(61950,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 9, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 03:08:07',NULL,'In this episode, host Joel Cuthbert introduces his listeners to a new edition of his popular music show, The Stillness and The Dancing. He is currently living with his friends on the other side of town and is taking care of cats. He has been listening to music on his left ear, which is fine for him, but for his listeners the left ear is really enjoying what it is hearing. In this part of the show, Cuthbert introduces listeners to the music of the soundtrack of the film Little Fish.\n\nThe film is very haunting, and the score is composed by Keegan DeWitt, who is also responsible for the score to the film Labyrinth. The music on the track, The Beginning, is from Little Fish, and it is on the soundtrack to another of his favorite films, Once it\'s All On the Ground. The other tracks on the show are by Rob St. Johns band, Oro, and Andrew Aslaks, Pete Harvey, and others. Midsummer is a folk track and Midwinter is a gothic track.',NULL,'Joel Cuthbert introduces his guest to the world of \"ambient, experimental, and modern composition\"'),(61951,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - August 9, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 02:52:24',NULL,'The program begins with a conversation between Portia Woodruff, the founder of the Facial Recognition League, and Alexa Bliss, a professor at the College of William and Mary. Alexa and Portia discuss the racial disparity in facial recognition that plagues the league. Alexa says she\'s excited to see that the league will be able to use facial recognition again, and she\'ll be joining Alexa and the rest of the group at a postshow. Portia says she feels like facial recognition is biased against women of color, and that\'s the last thing she wants to discuss with Alexa.\n\nThe program then moves to a discussion between two graduate students, Lewis Coleratoolo, a student at the university of Guelph in Canada, and Alvaro de La Mora Pina, a research fellow at the University at Albany in New York. Lewis is a graduate student trying to get a Ph.D in food science, and he\'s interested in talking to other students about what\'s going on in the world.',NULL,NULL),(61952,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/B Siide Radio - August 9, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-25 02:26:16',NULL,'Freehub, the organization that runs the skatepark, has opened a new community center in the library to help members of the community get around. The center will provide a place where people can learn how to repair and maintain their bicycles. For more information, visit Freehub.org or contact the library at 9