d and they\'re back on the air. They\'ve got a new song, this time it\'s about a Native American woman. She\'s the narrator of the host and she\'s talking to the audience about the importance of storytelling and how it can help us understand our history and make sense of the world around us. The narrator says that the National Film Board is very excited to be a part of this program and that they\'ll be sharing all of their stories with you.',NULL,NULL),(61984,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/Folk Roots Radio - August 11, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 13:15:50',NULL,'This week on the program, we get another in-depth interview with Scott Cook, this time about his latest album. It\'s called Tangle of Souls and it\'s got a ton of great songs. It also comes with a book of stories written around the songs. Scott\'s back on tour now, and this is a great time to catch him.',NULL,NULL),(61985,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/A Dog’s Breakfast - August 12, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 12:51:12',NULL,'In this week\'s episode of the program, host Rich speaks with DJ Apostrophe about the upcoming performance by the Guelph Youth Choirs. The show is called \"Mythical Forest\" and it will take place on Saturday, April 30, at 7pm at the GYMC Recital Hall. The performance is free and open to the public, and everyone is welcome to attend. The program is also available on Soundcloud and on Facebook. In the meantime, the listeners can sign up for the program by visiting the program\'s Facebook page.',NULL,NULL),(61986,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Bel Araby with CAWA - August 12, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 12:31:16',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61987,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Sound Magic - August 12, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 12:06:16',NULL,'This week, Michael joins the CFRU Sound Magic team to talk about the upcoming Bike the Night. It\'s a night of guided rides, contests, and music by local station 93.3 FM. Michael introduces himself as MacDee, who\'s been hanging around the university for a long time.\n\nHe started off working on the equipment and producing shows, then moved into his own show. He\'s still hanging around and still doing shows. If what he does sounds like something that you\'d like to hear, visit us at the second floor, the University Centre, and find out more about what the university has to offer.',NULL,NULL),(61988,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Sound Magic - August 12, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 11:49:49',NULL,'In this edition of Sound Magic, Doleschell introduces a new recording of the works of Brian de Guise, a twentieth-century German composer whose works include some of the largest works of the Gothic Symphony. De Guise lived from 1876-1972 and was a \"rather late discovery\" for him. He discovered him about 1970, and realized that \"a major name\" had completely stayed away from the lists, concerts, and recording lists, \"because of the blowing\" .\n\nNow, he says, some of his larger works have been recorded or formed, or formed some five times roughly, \"a terrific musical effort\" , which has gotten \"a lot of interest\" in Brian\' music. \"Everything about Haber- Gul-brian is strange, and out of the-way,\" he notes, \"and we might expect the music to be that very much.\" He explains that the reissues of Brian\'s symphonies with the conductor, Meyer Friedman, have made the music even more challenging, as the music is \"the structures, the model that he uses is completely different.\" The program also includes a recording of a third symphony, the ninth symphony by Havergal.',NULL,NULL),(61989,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Sound Magic - August 12, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 11:27:38',NULL,'The program opens with a concert recording of a piano concerto by English composer, Cyril Scott. Scott was a prominent figure in the London music scene in the early 1900s, and his work is a rarity for a concert piece. The piano concerto was first published in 1900, but was never performed by the composer. However, the pianist Peter Donahoe and the conductor Martin Yates perform the piano concerto.\n\nThe program ends with a program of music by English composers William Sterndale and William Sternshiy English Music. Bennett was a composer who was influenced by the works of composers like Georg Solzhenitsyn, and he wrote an overture to a piece by Mendelssohn, which was first performed in Germany in 1837. Bennett also wrote an arrangement of a song by Brahms, which is one of the most popular pieces in the program.',NULL,NULL),(61990,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Caribbean Anthology - August 12, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 11:07:20',NULL,'This is the fourth installment of the Analog Sound System\'s Spotlight 4 concert series. The first half featured a number of new songs, and the second half featured some old favorites. The third half will also feature new music. The goal of the show is to support local artists, so the next show will be held next Saturday, August 19th at 7pm at the Guelph Ring. The second half of the concert will feature local artists and will include some of the artists featured in the first half.',NULL,NULL),(61991,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Caribbean Anthology - August 12, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 10:47:47',NULL,'The show starts off by giving listeners a little recap of the events of the last few months. They mention that they\'ve had a lot of interest in the shows and that they need to get more people to come out for the upcoming spotlight. They also mention that the spotlight is coming up on August 19th and they\'re trying to get as many people as possible to come down. The show is going to be hosted by an all-star line-up of artists including Rasiunchio, Naturalist, Gru, PlankidOne, Black Orchid and Alicia Ambrosia. It\'s all free and everyone is invited to check out the show at Well City Studios in North End of Guelph.',NULL,NULL),(61992,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Alternativa Latinoamericana - August 12, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:01:38',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61993,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Alternativa Latinoamericana - August 12, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-16 03:01:38',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61994,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Tiempo de Mujeres - August 12, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-16 03:01:39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(61995,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Mach Vibe Radio - August 12, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 10:29:00',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the Mach 5 radio show starts with a commercial break and continues with a music interlude. The music is a mix of spoken word and hip-hop. The program is hosted by Chris Sakocha and his crew.\n\nThey are all from the University of Guelph and they are on their way to the show. The show begins with a reminder that meta products like Facebook and Instagram are starting to block Canadian news content. The University is a community organization and thus they share news and upcoming events as well as learning opportunities. Unfortunately, this bill will make it impossible for people to access their social media accounts on Facebook and on Instagram. If you are upset with this, please contact the Member of Parliament for Guelph, Lloyd Longfield, for a response. The band also announces the 15th annual Friends of the Public Library book sale. The sale is a month early than usual and proceeds benefit the library. The Friends also won the 2023 Today Radio Guelph Community Builders award for the arts.',NULL,NULL),(61996,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Mach Vibe Radio - August 12, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 10:08:45',NULL,'This episode is from the Campus and Community Organization at the Canadian Free University. Bill C-18 has made meta products like Facebook and Instagram block news content from Canadians. Since the college is a community organization, it has to share its news and events on social media platforms. The organization asks its supporters to continue to support it by subscribing to its newsletter at the university\'s website.\n\nIn the meantime, if you are upset about this change, please contact the Member of Parliament for your area. The Member for Guelph, Lloyd Longfield, is also involved in this issue. The show is called TKO and it\'s all about combat sports. It\'s hosted by the guy that\'s the host of the show, and he\'s called \"Canadian Yardie\" . The guy introduces himself as Homeboy 728 and the guy who\'s hosting the show is named \"Nativity\" , who introduces himself by saying he\'ll be calling it \"Falling Up.\" Then he starts to run out of air, and apologizes to his listeners.',NULL,NULL),(61997,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/The Underground - August 13, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 09:05:08',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(61998,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/The Underground - August 12, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 08:48:43',NULL,'This is a special edition of the We Know Some Things podcast. It\'s called \"Mott-Vie Radio\" and it\'s all about keeping the listeners happy. They\'re sending them guys love tonight and they\'re giving away a week\'s worth of music. If you haven\'t already, check it out. You can listen to the show on Soundcloud and you can also listen to it on Facebook. We also tell you that the University of Guelph is hiring an outreach assistant to help with the club outreach. The job pays $20.',NULL,NULL),(61999,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Visions fugitives - August 13, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 08:27:33',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with Christopher Curry, the co-host of the show \"Vigilio Fugitive.\" The first part of the interview is with Fangwei, who is involved in choosing music for the program. The second part begins with a description of the music featured on the show. The first piece is a work by the Transylvanian composer, George \"Ligeti,\" who died in 1991.\n\nThe second piece is by the contemporary composer, Kim \"Kashkashian,\" who first heard of Ligeti before he heard of Kim. The third piece is an early work by another contemporary Hungarian composer, Baela \"Bartok,\" who was born in the west of the country. The two composers are ethnic Hungarians, and they were both born in Romania, but their work is different.\n\nThey are both composers who wrote works for Viola, a chamber music piece. The Opus 34 piece by Bartok is not a piece of Opus 34 but rather a piece designated by a musicologist. Bartok used three different numbering systems over his career, each of which stopped when he reached Opus 21, the highest Opus. The work in question is a suite number two. It was written in 1904 and was revised in 1907. The show is a bit more conservative than usual.',NULL,NULL),(62000,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Visions fugitives - August 13, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 08:12:13',NULL,'This is the program that the guys are going to play on August 6th, 2023. They\'re doing a music show that\'s basically a two-part series where each of them picks a piece of music to play in a specific week and then the other picks another piece to play the next week. The guy who plays the music will pick the music and the guy who doesn\'t picks the music picks the other piece. Basically, in this case, it\'ll be the guy playing the music who picks the piece for the first week and the other guy for the second week. This is sort of a reverse-chronological version of the CSI: Live episode, where you\'re listening to the CSI show and then it\'s the other person\'s show.\n\nThis time around, the show is all about animals. It\'s all about summer animals. For example, the first piece on the program is a Haydn symphony called \"The Bear,\" which was actually written after the composer\'s death. The other piece is a John Cage work called \"Torpor.\" And then the show ends with a quote from Feng Wei, who wrote for the show the last time the guys played. He says that bats are \"the only mammals that truly have mastered the art of living in the air\" . This quote has a lot to do with a harpsichord piece that they played last week, called \"Winged Creatures,\" by a French composer named Lé Léang. This',NULL,NULL),(62001,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - August 13, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 07:13:23',NULL,'The show ends with a message from Alice, who invites listeners to join her every Sunday night at 9pm to listen to the music wherever she may take them on the air.\n\nThe program returns to the theme of cleaning, and we learn that the song is called \"Cleaning by Secret\" and was a remix of a song called \"Uptown Funk\" by Kit Clayton, and the song\'s theme today is \"All About Cleaning\" .\n\nThe song is from the game \"Mega Man\" , and it has a cannon arm and a cannon that can shoot robots to defeat the bosses. Willy\'s castle level one is from \"Megaman 2,\" and levels two and three are from \"Mistress Mega Man\" and \"Garcia and both Crashman and MegaMan 2,\" respectively. The children untie their father and start playing their own songs. The songs include \"Jimmy Mack,\" \"Baby the boobies,\" \"Poppy T. Coney,\" \"Siegel Stop It Now,\" and \"I Hate Brenda.\" Alice says that her favorite song is \"I peed all on my pants,\" and that one day, he peed on his pants.',NULL,'The kids love a song called \"Cleaning,\" a remix of an old song'),(62002,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Zombie Jamboree - August 13, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 06:49:03',NULL,'The first hour of the World Youth Day Zombie Jamboree is over, and the stage is now set for the second hour. The first half of the set is David Bowie, followed by a slew of other artists. The second hour is full of music for the kids, including DJ Peanuts, the Soul Brothers, and Ry Cooter.\n\nThe third hour is all about advice for the youth, and it starts with a song called \"Honor Your Mother And Father.\" The final set is a sing-along with some serious advice on the song \"I Fucked Up I Was A Child.\" The next day, the \"Zombie Jamboree\" will be the finale of \"Alora Riverfest,\" and the wind is blowing.',NULL,NULL),(62003,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Zombie Jamboree - August 13, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 06:28:21',NULL,'The show starts with a group of insecure kids singing about M ward youth. After that, the show switches to a song called \"too young to die\" by Paul Simon. The show concludes with a performance by Selena Gomez and some of her girls. The sets start with a piece from \"The Future\" by Lonnie Holly.',NULL,NULL),(62004,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Clan Na Gael - August 13, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 06:09:15',NULL,'The next morning, the narrator tells Maggie that he heard about a battle which took place in Scotland. The battle was fought between the English and the Scots. The English won, but the Scots lost because they didn\'t know what to do with themselves. He tells Maggie about a Canadian song which has been adopted by the rest of the world. The song is called Maple Leaves and it was written by G.\n\nW. Robinson in 1864. It was a parody of the most popular Canadian songs. It turns up in the handwritten copy of a Helen Osborne which is attributed to the author. The narrator says that the song reminds him of a similar statement made by the Canadian public school system in the last century. It seems that the abilities of the students have been declining for some time',NULL,NULL),(62005,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Clan Na Gael - August 13, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 05:09:30',NULL,'The band is made up of all Irish Americans and all Irish musicians. They\'ve played before on the 4th of July, and they\'re planning to play more local music. The band also has a local band named Solas. The first song they play is \"Fire in the Kitchen\" by Laura Smith. The second song is \"The Nuri Highway Man\" by Eugene Ray. The third song is from \"We Be Soldiers 3\" by the Red Sky At Night band. The next song is a Scottish band.',NULL,NULL),(62006,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/La Buena Onda - August 13, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-16 03:01:46',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62007,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/La Buena Onda - August 13, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-16 03:01:46',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62008,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Through the Looking Glass - August 13, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 04:56:52',NULL,'This week we\'ll be listening to a German music correspondent\'s interview with a New Orleans musician named Melanie and his cousin, Troy Andrews. The first track we hear is a song from a Canadian DJ named Sticky Buds. We learn that the song is called \"Family Man\" and that it\'s a duet between the two men.\n\nThe two men are friends and they\'ve been recording together for a while. They\'ve recorded three songs in the past two years and this is the third song. Sounds like they\'re really good friends. We also learn that he\'s taking his new album \"All in Spirit\" to Canada to promote it. We get a little more information about the Andrews family and about the New Orleans jazz scene.',NULL,NULL),(62009,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/Backtracks - August 13, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 04:35:52',NULL,'This week on Backtracks, host Jennifer takes us back in time to the late 60s and early 70s. She introduces us to some of her favorite artists from that era.\n\nShe starts off by playing a track from a British band called Family. The band is from England and it\'s one of the first albums that Dave Mason produced. The song is called Old Songs New Songs and it was released in 1968. The band\'s lead singer, Roger Chapman, is also featured on the song. Next up is a song from an Ohio band called J. D. Blackfoot. The track is called The Ultimate Prophesy and it sounds like a country rock album.\n\nThe other band featured was Lydia Purple from British Columbia. It was a song about the frozen wasteland of the Arctic Circle. And finally, a song called Mr. Oil Man from the soul album from 1971.',NULL,NULL),(62010,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/This Night Wounds Time - August 14, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 04:03:06',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62011,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/This Night Wounds Time - August 14, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 03:36:16',NULL,'The narrator announces that he\'s going to be taking a break from his program for a week to do a special tribute to a composer who died a few days ago. He\'ll read an obituary for the composer, a 70-year-old woman named Kaya Sarajo. The obituary describes Sarajajo as a pioneering, experimental composer who worked in Paris at the Institut de Comte Musique, or IRCOM, from 1982 to 1988.\n\nHer work was based on the study of spectralism, a technique for manipulating sound to create music. Her first work, Graal Theatre, was a violin and orchestra piece. Her second, Orion, was an orchestra piece based on a 12th-century romantic epic. Her third opera, Adriana Mater, was set in the aftermath of a civil war.',NULL,NULL),(62012,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/13/This Night Wounds Time - August 13, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-13 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 03:15:01',NULL,'This week on the Talk Show, The Christopher Curry explains that he\'s going to change things up a little bit. He\'s not going to be presenting music from all over the place, but instead, he\'ll be focusing on music that is \"off the beaten track\" . So, for the first hour, the show is going to focus on music from an off-the-beaten-track artist named \"Daivat Jhani.\" This is a guy who\'s been around for a long time, and the show needs to get him on the air ASAP.',NULL,NULL),(62013,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/12/Beautiful Druid - August 12, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-12 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 02:54:42',NULL,'Beautiful Druid is a weekly poetry reading program that encourages listeners to imagine their own dreams. The program starts with a song called \"Wooden Ships\" by Crosby Still and Nash, which encourages listeners who have daydreams about being on the sea. Next up is \"Great Big Sea\" by the Newfoundland group, followed by \"Gordon Lightfoot\" from his classic masters album, \"All Right,\" and \"The Last Trip Home\" by a Scottish group. After listening to these songs, the program moves on to the songs of Lyle Lovett and John Denver. After hearing \"If I Had A Boat\" by Lovett, \"Alison Krause\" from Union Station, and \"Mary Chapin Carpenter\" from her \"Come On Come On\" album, the audience is invited to imagine what they would do if they had a boat.',NULL,NULL),(62014,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Democracy Now - August 15, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 02:33:30',NULL,'A grand jury in Georgia has returned an indictment against 19 individuals for conspiracy to commit election fraud. This is the fourth time that a grand jury indicted Donald Trump in the state since he took office. The indictment is based on a sweeping investigation of Fulton County Prosecutor, Fannie Willis. The charges are based on Georgia\'s notorious RICO law. The program will also speak to veteran journalist Michael isikoff who is writing a book about the case, and to Latasha Brown co-founder the Black Voter\'s Matter Fund. Ralph Nader, a longtime consumer advocate, says the indictment should include insurrection',NULL,NULL),(62016,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Democracy Now - August 14, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 02:12:11',NULL,'We begin with Amy Goodman\'s report from New York, where she describes the devastating effects of the recent wildfires in Hawaii. She reports that the death toLL from the fire has risen to 96 and that officials fear the true number may be much higher. She also reports on the assassination of Ecuador\'s president, who was shot while running for re-election. She concludes that this assassination is part of a political conspiracy to undermine the upcoming elections.',NULL,NULL),(62018,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/14/Worst Responders - August 14, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-14 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 01:52:14',NULL,'This show is called Worst Responders and it is hosted by two stand-ups, Charissa and Renee. They are both comedians and they have taken their roles as actors and comedians and are trying to respond to problems that people have posted on the internet. The show is funny, but it is not serious. It is a comedy and everything is improvised.',NULL,NULL),(62019,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/Democracy Now - August 11, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 01:12:19',NULL,'The death toll has reached 55 people and destroyed the town of Lehaina, formerly the center of the kingdom of Hawaii. A number of other buildings have also been destroyed. Governor Josh Green describes the scale of the tragedy. We are also told that many hundreds of houses have been destroyed, and it will take a long time for the town to recover.\n\nHe talks to an old man who had never experienced anything like this in his life and is in tears. Some residents wondered why Hawaii\'S emergency warning system did not go off as the blazes raged closer and closer. The president has declared a disaster as the tragedy has shown the urgency of climate catastrophe and the ongoing exploitation of the islands. After the news, Amy Goodman reports that tension is running high in west Africa.',NULL,NULL),(62020,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Worst Responders - August 7, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-24 00:51:19',NULL,'Anne Kuzik and her friend Michael are friends and grow up together. Anne is in her early 20s, and Michael was in his early 30s.\n\nThey both have jobs, and Anne is now a nurse at a retirement home in Guelph. Anne tells the listeners of the show that she spends a lot of her time out in the lounge area of the retirement home. She says she likes to watch the people around her, and she\'s impressed with the people at the retirement residence. Anne says that she likes mysteries and adventures, but that love stories aren\'t her thing. She admits that she used to read under the covers with a flashlight.',NULL,NULL),(62021,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Rainbow Country - August 15, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 00:27:19',NULL,'The first song we hear is from Miguel Brown, one of the members of the British New Romantics. It\'s called \"Alone\" and it\'s about a disease that\'s classified as a mental disorder. We\'re here from Chicago, from Scott Free, from Tom Robinson, and from Red Path traffic. This is about the struggle of his adoptive dad.',NULL,NULL),(62023,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Rainbow Country - August 15, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-24 00:17:27',NULL,'The guests on this episode are: Carol Pope, author of \"Boy Erased,\" a memoir; Lorraine Segato, co-author of \"The Spoons,\" a book of poems; and Chris Burketts, musician and producer of \"Rainbow Country,\" a new Canadian show that airs on 12 Canadian radio stations. The show is produced and hosted by Mark Tara, who also serves as the show\'s producer and host.',NULL,NULL),(62024,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/10/Democracy Now - August 10, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-10 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 23:17:41',NULL,'On this program, CFR Senior Fellow and Foreign Policy Analyst Ellen Johnson Sirleaf discusses the situation in Niger, where French troops have been withdrawn.\n\nShe tells us that the military intervention has reduced the country\'s insecurity. She says that the West African Community, ECOWAS, is holding an emergency meeting to discuss its next steps after the deadline passed to restore the ousted president of Niger. The United States, France, and the African Union are all backing ECOWAS. She talks to a Ukrainian pacifist named Yuri Shaly Zhelyzenko, who has been accused by the government of justifying Russian aggression after the war in the Middle East. He says that this peace agenda for the world is nonsense and denounces Russia\'s aggression. Then ten peace activists, including Sha',NULL,NULL),(62025,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Rainbow Country - August 8, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 22:49:50',NULL,'In this program, Tim McCaskill describes the history of Glad Day, a queer bookstore in Toronto. It started in a backpack by a man named George Morelenhauer around 1972.\n\nHe started selling books from one event to another. He moved it to an old house in a commune in downtown Toronto and then to a hall where he lived. As the book collection got bigger and the store got bigger, the store started having its customers call first to see what books they could buy. In the late 70s and early 80s, the Canadian government started to censor books that were published in the U.S. and Canada. Glad Day had to go through customs to import books from other countries. This was a problem in the early days of the queer community. The government was not going to let \"dirty, smutty\" books cross the border and corrupt innocent Canadians like Glad Day. In April of that year, police raided the store and charged Orweth with selling \"obscene material.\n\n\" Glad Day was involved in legal battles for years. American publications started producing special editions with blank pages to get the books across the border, but the government wouldn\'t let it happen. In 1983 partners Bruce Scott and Jim Deva opened a gay bookstore called Little Sisters in Vancouver. It was also having its books blocked by Canada Customs. It wasn\'t just the queer bookstores that were having their books blocked, it was also the mainstream bookstores. They fought the customs seizure through the courts, but it took',NULL,NULL),(62027,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Silver Screen Dream Machine - August 15, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-23 22:34:37',NULL,'This week on the Dream Machine, we pay tribute to Robbie Robertson, who died last week at age 80. He was a musician for Bob Dylan, a songwriter for Dylan, and a co-songwriter with Martin Scorsese. He worked on a number of soundtracks, including The Irishman, for which he wrote the theme. We also hear some of his movie music, including the theme from the 2005 disaster film Ladder 49 and a song from the 1994 documentary The Native Americans, which was recorded by the voice of the character Dale Gribble. After listening to some of the music, we hear a few clips from the animated show King of the Hills.',NULL,NULL),(62028,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Down the Rabbit Hole - August 15, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 21:11:22',NULL,'In this program, we hear from Douglas Blackwood, host of the Morning Soul Shake-Up program on CFRU 92.3. He\'s been your host for 25 years, and he\'s also been your local news guy for the past 30 years. He also hosts a program called Scenes Like Old Time on the program, which is a mix of old news and old music. The program airs old music and tells stories from the past. This program is for listeners who want to hear about local history, music, and arts. It\'s a great way to get out of bed.',NULL,NULL),(62029,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Rainbow Country - August 8, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 20:51:30',NULL,'In mid December, secret negotiations appear to deliver the key demands of the prisoners. The strike is called off. Sands, the main spokesman for the prisoners, is called in to brief them on the progress. He tells them that the British negotiating team has reached a deal, but that the prisoners are not happy with it. The document falls far short of their demands. The British prisoner Bobby Sauns is among them back at the tole, and he tells the other prisoners that they are going to embark on a hunger strike on March 1.',NULL,NULL),(62030,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/Democracy Now - August 9, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 20:35:28',NULL,'In this program, we\'re going to look at how the Ohio Constitution is being weakened because of the anti-choice sentiments of the voters. We\'re also going to talk to Portia Woodruff, a woman who\'s been falsely accused of crimes because of faulty facial recognition technology. Then we\'ll talk to six former police officers who\'ve been accused of torturing and killing two black men in Mississippi because of their use of fake facial recognition.',NULL,NULL),(62031,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Silver Screen Dream Machine - August 8, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 20:10:52',NULL,'In this short program, the narrator tells the students about the music they\'ll hear in the coming weeks. He starts off by introducing them to Robin Hood, the Prince of Thieves, a British film that was made in 1991 about a young thief named Marian. The song we\'re about to hear comes from the film Robin Hood: Prince of thieves, which was directed by David Cronenberg and starring Patrick Bergen as Robin Hood. The first song we hear in this program is a song called K-na with Mecca from David Cronenburg\'s film Cosmopolis, which is set in the Muslim world. The second song we heard is a score composed by David Bergen for the British film Marian. It was released the same year as the Robin Hood film. The third song is called Marian. We\'re also told that it\'s the one year anniversary of Olivia\'s death from breast cancer.\n\nOlivia co-starred in the movie Grease with John Travolta. The program starts off with a tribute to Olivia, who died a year ago. She\'s been an inspiration to all of us since she first appeared on stage. We hear music from a number of movies, including Grease, Two Kind, Xanadu, Hopelessly Devote to You, Suspended in Time, and a movie called Farley Gordon. The music from these films is very similar to the music we hear from the music from the animated movies. The animated movies are mostly based on books, so they don\'t have',NULL,NULL),(62032,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Down the Rabbit Hole - August 8, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 19:48:41',NULL,'In this message, Alice, the founder of Die Out, a community workshop that offers tools and equipment to anyone who wants to learn how to make things, explains how they\'re opening a new location on August 19 from 12 to 6:00pm. They\'re also holding a mental health awareness fair at the new location. If you\'re in the middle of a crisis, you can get help through the mental health helplines in the province of Ontario. You can chat with a specialist via the mentalhealthhelp line.',NULL,NULL),(62034,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/Industry Tactics - August 11, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 19:16:21',NULL,'This chapter begins with the narrator declaring that he wants to be an artist. He says that he admires other peoples work, but that he doesn\'t want anyone else to do his work for him.\n\nThe narrator then goes on to tell us that his father taught him how to play the piano. He also says that when he was a manager, he had a teacher who taught him the same thing. The teacher was like, \"it\'s about the music\" . He taught the musician how to bring something to life in the music. The music, the narrator says, is more important than any technical proficiency. He would have to play \"a stupid concerto\" , but he would still be able to play it well because he was \"going through the classical\" world. This is a reference to the Botocini Bass Concerto, which is a poorly written piece of music that no one wants to hear.\n\nThe Bass Concerto is like a joke, he says, but it\'s funny because the music is so bad. The bass player would be forced to play a music that sounds like a violin, but really isn\'t. But then he would be free to bring his own voice into the music, and it would sound good. The last thing the narrator tells us is that the best thing to do is to always play music with other people.',NULL,NULL),(62035,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Democracy Now - August 8, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 18:55:40',NULL,'Democracy Now returns to New York City with a look at the latest developments in the Middle East. The United States has sent thousands of Marines and sailors to the region to deter the Islamic Republic of Iran from seizing American oil tankers. The Iranians have responded by equipping their navy with drones and missile systems. We will also hear from Trita Parsi of the Quincy Institute about the growing tensions between the United States and Iran.\n\nThe U. S. has responded to asylum seekers at the border in Texas, and New York is beginning to run out of emergency shelters for immigrants. We also learn that the Iraqi men who endured torture at the Abu Ghorib prison will finally be able to go to court.',NULL,NULL),(62036,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/Industry Tactics - August 11, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 18:32:24',NULL,'This is the first of two shows where we talk about branding, the art of creating an image that people will associate with you. In this case, it is the image of the woman in the photograph. She tells us that she is in Parkdale, a suburb of Chicago.\n\nShe lives on the top of a dilapidated mansion. She loves it, but it\'s also a daily struggle waking up with the hairstyle she has. She says that it is a \"daily challenge\" to be the woman she is. She talks about how it is an industry tactic to \"brand\" someone, like a doll that is looking backwards at her. She also says that she has found conversations with other women in her field about how they are trying to do the same thing. She explains that she wants to begin with the \"',NULL,NULL),(62038,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - August 9, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 17:13:46',NULL,'The show opens with a video interview between Leonard and boss Taylor. Leonard says that he was on a trip since they did their show last week.\n\nHe says that they didn\'t have a picture with boss Taylor to share on their social media, so they will get a picture of him with the team if they make the playoffs. Leonard also says that since he went to Boston he visited Fenway Park. He\'s been to the park before, but never before. Leonard goes on to say that he saw the Blue Jays beat the Red Sox two games to one. Leonard then says that the show is going to be listening to a song called \"Sleep All Day\" on the rural Alberta station, and he\'s heard it before.\n\nThe song was a big hit back in the day. Leonard likes the song. Now to boss Taylor, who introduces the show. He introduces himself as \"Griffin Sports\" and says that if you\'re a fan of the Griffin team, he\'ll give you all the details. Griffin is a mythical Greek creature with wings and an eagle. It\'s the mascot of the varsity sports team at the University.\n\nThe University is founded in 1964, hence the Griffins are called the University Griffins. The open trials for all the Griffin teams will be held in the last two weeks of August and in the first week September. Anyone interested in attending an open trial can complete the Poyo information and pay the $30.00 trial fee. If you have any questions about',NULL,NULL),(62040,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/New or Never - August 15, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 16:49:53',NULL,'On this edition of New or Never , Adrian Hoade-Reddick introduces listeners to a new band, Jonathan Lajoua, who is known for his work as a stand-up comedian and actor. He also serves as a songwriter and record producer. The band members include Sigur Ross, Cable Ties , Brian Chatton , and others. The songs are all new and exciting. The show airs on 93.3 FM in Guelph. It is hosted by Tanya Iyer, who reports on the happenings at the local art gallery.',NULL,NULL),(62041,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/07/Democracy Now - August 7, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-07 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 16:28:08',NULL,'The Henrietta Lacks lawsuit, which was settled in 2021, marks 70 years after Henrietta Lack\'s death. Her grandson, Alfred, and granddaughter, Kimberly, discuss the lawsuit and how the family was wronged by the medical system.\n\nThe lawsuit, they say, will finally bring \"justice\" to the family. In addition, the settlement will help other companies to better understand the ethics of using Henrietta\'s cells. The National Institutes of Medicine has agreed to create a new program to use the full sequence of cells from Henrietta. Dorothy Roberts, the director of the university\'s Race and Science Program, has also been following the case closely. She gives a talk about the importance of the Henrietta case, which she calls \"long overdue compensation.\"',NULL,NULL),(62042,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/New or Never - August 8, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 16:09:02',NULL,'This week on Peace I Need you are listening to new or never on CFRU 92.3. Winnipeg\'s warm smiles is the music of Rub Rob chinski. Side Love in the Vicious Way, the reflective debut from Toronto\'Mother Tongues, is the brainchild of Lucas and Cherise.\n\nThe pulse of mother tongues is the creative partnership between a bassist and vocalist, Cherise and Lucas. The lonely ones is the name of the singer-songwriter, Sleepy Gene. UEP Sasha Hands amassed over a hundred thousand streams. From time we\'ll wait for no one that was Paper lanterns. From Time we will Wait for No one, that was IdolPaper Lanterns. From Dances with me it is like it\'s Like Tractor beam is the post folk songwriting project of Vancouver-raised producer Balazsik, from Turtles all the way it is Like We\'re just Like the moon. From Guided by Voices by GBV.',NULL,NULL),(62043,1615,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/10/Off the Beaten Track - August 10, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-10 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 15:49:37',NULL,'The host of Off Beaten Track, Jean, welcomes his listeners to his show. He tells them that he\'s listening to one of his favorite songs, Falling Off a horse by Felix LeBand.\n\nIn the song, he imagines himself riding on a horse along an endless road in Italy on a beautiful sunny day. He wants to know what his listeners think of the song by sending him a message on his Facebook page. He then launches into a mix of soothing music and meditative beats. Next up, a Japanese musician named Macro Blank. Unfortunately, the song is in Japanese, but if you\'re looking for it, you can grab it from his website. The next song is by an award- winning electronic musician named Tor. The song is called \"Theluthura\" and it was inspired by the feeling of rootedness in his music.',NULL,NULL),(62044,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/11/Hellfire Radio - August 11, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-11 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 15:31:54',NULL,'The gang gets ready for another Hellfire with some new music. We start off with Sex Pistols, who are the \"proper punk band\" .\n\nWe then head over to DoA, a Canadian punk band with a message of \"talk minus action\" , and then onto Fried Egg, a song from Weezer, then onto ACDC, and finally onto The Devil Wear Prada\'s \"Dead Throne.\" They also talk about the new TMNT movie, which is awesome. Finally, they go into the \"hell\" and play two songs, one from Hard Charger and one from the other band, Saxon. Saxon is doing a little segue between the two tracks, and they decide to play the first one after the other one. They then head off to the Blues Festival in Kitchener, which starts the next day.',NULL,NULL),(62045,2205,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/09/Samaismela Music Show + CFRU Playlist - August 9, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-09 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 15:10:01',NULL,'This program is all about the great work being done at CFRU, including the live streaming of all of our shows and the ability to search through the archived shows in real-time. The program also includes a weekly music chart and a second stream that features exclusive local music all day every day. In addition, there\'s a lot of information about how to get involved as an active volunteer with the program. You can also check out the 250 watt campus and community station and the CFRU website. It\'s all in one place.',NULL,NULL),(62046,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Under the Needle - August 15, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 14:50:45',NULL,'The band from Venezuela, Zeta, plays a psychedelic, post-rock, reggae, experimental, jazz cumbia punk, heck, even emo, and mambo track. The band\'s latest release is Toto, released on the Skeletal lightning in 2022. The first time the band heard the song, it was like \"a bunch of people\" .\n\nThey attribute this to the power and healing power of music to communicate, connect, and heal. They thank the audience and shout out to their partner station, WAWL, and to our new El Sinto podcast Exploring the meaning of place for modern independent Latin music artists. If you enjoyed this show, you can check out the entire program at slash. KEXP is supported by the Corporation For Public Broadcasting. The show is made possible by the CFRU. You can find out more about the three day passes that they\'re giving away to this year, by visiting the website.\n\nYou also can check them at the following link: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/riverfest-tickets-216521777453?affref=ebt. The winner of the draw will be announced on August 20th.',NULL,NULL),(62047,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Under the Needle - August 8, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 14:33:02',NULL,'In this episode, Troy Nelson introduces us to the band Party Dozen, a Sydney-based band comprised of two musicians, Jonathan Boulay and Kirsty Tickle. They\'re known for their loud live shows, experimental sound, and willingness to experiment with their instruments.\n\nThey have released three albums, including their most recent, Pray For Party Dozen. Their first two albums were heavy and sci-fi, and their third was more experimental and grimeier. Their second album is even more ambitious. Their saxophone player, Kirsty Tickle, sings through the horns on the album. KEXPs DJ, Cheryl Waters, asks about the band\'s origins. The two musicians explain that they\'ve been friends for a long time, and that they decided to form a band together so they could play together. After playing in bands together for a while, the two decided to do a band. They played drums and then played the sax, which was a natural progression. Jonathan says that the two musicians have similar musical backgrounds. Both have played in bands before, but it was easier to play with two people. The band has a different sound than the first two records, which were more experimental. They also play through the sax on the second album, which is more experimental, more chaotic, and more \"grimeier\" than their first two.',NULL,NULL),(62051,157,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dudp3v/495-33-45-78-aug14-23.mp3','2023-08-21 00:46:23',286363797,'2023-12-23 14:11:46',NULL,'The show starts off with a song called \"The Loop\" by the Surf Riders. It\'s a song about being crazy, which is the theme of the show. The song starts with Paul James\' band \"Crazy Little Baby\" singing \"I\'ll go crazy, let\'s go crazy\" .\n\nThe show goes on to include songs by Paul James, Prince, Queen, and Willie Nelson. Paul James is a Canadian musician who has been working in the United States since the early sixties. The first song he sings is called \"Crazy\" by Patsy Cline. He wrote the song in 1961 when she was just getting her big break. She had a friend named Hank Cochran play the song for her, but she had trouble following the song because she had to sing behind the beat of the song.\n\nAfter that, we hear the song \"The Crazy Walk\" by Chris Barber. It was recorded in London England in 1955. We learn that the song was called \"Shine On You Crazy Diamond\" by Pink Floyd. The band never really recovered from losing Sid Barrett. He was a founding member and the band would always have references to him. But in 1975, when they were having their recording studio Mother recording \"Shine on You Crazy diamond\" , Sid Barrett showed up dressed as a woman and shaved all of his hair. He gained weight by drinking or by wearing a lab coat and was told that he was Sid.',NULL,NULL),(62052,161,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/aa5hp3/VientoSur-August19th-2023.mp3','2023-08-18 02:20:32',85548704,'2023-12-23 13:52:35',NULL,'The next hour, we\'re about to hear music from a band called Tupai, which is a band from the town of Cochabamba in Bolivia. The band has been recording for a long time and they\'ve recorded several albums. The first album they\'re listening to is called \"Buscando pas\" which means \"looking for peace.\" The second album is \"Interim\" which is another band called \"Los Caracas prns mundo nuevo.\" The third album is an album called \"Recuerdo De Callewaya.\" The fourth album is a song called \"Mama Crisita\" written by an amazing composer named Ernesto Hacha Flores. The last album is entitled \"Typeek Ala\" which translates to \"Alone.\"',NULL,NULL),(62054,167,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/94k9xe/August_18_2023_Funky_Fridays9u33c.mp3','2023-08-18 18:35:56',431961989,'2023-12-23 13:31:59',NULL,'In this edition of Funky Friday, Pete, a DJ at a local station, talks about his love of Robbie Robertson, a Canadian musician who played with Levon Helm\'s band.\n\nPete admits that he was a big fan of the group during its 