 - August 16, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 22:19:42',NULL,'The credits team, Adam A Donaldson, Tim Phillips, and Peter Salmon, are back on campus to celebrate the third hundredth episode of the credits. They\'re joined by listeners for the first time, and they\'re psyched to be a part of the community. They have a big birthday celebration planned for this week, so they\'ve been working on the credits for a while now.',NULL,NULL),(62093,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/B Siide Radio - August 16, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 21:48:09',NULL,'MacDee is a friend of Michael K. and a host on his B-Side Radio show. He\'s also a member of the Canadian Society of Film and Video Artists, which helps him to gain the skills he needs to become a professional film and video artist. MacDee\'s show starts off with some new Canadian content and then shifts to R&B music. Next up, there\'s some new music from Cube, Ram Riddles and some private music from the private label. Macdee says he\'ll have to run into a big rock in the middle of the show to get it.',NULL,NULL),(62094,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/Trail Mix - August 16, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 21:13:18',NULL,'In this week\'s show, Aaron and the rest of the CFRU staff talk about the local music scene and its importance to the community. The show starts with a quote from a famous poem by Bob Dylan, \"Beauty Day Man.\" The song is about a man who takes a boat out and loses his beauty by throwing a life-jack at it. The song ends with the words \"What about my shade?\" . Aaron introduces the show and explains that it\'s called \"Here Today\" and that it is a new music show that he does every Thursday morning.\n\nHe also explains that the show is the launch of a new community bike center. The center will provide free access for people to have a place to get help with their bike repairs. Aaron says that the festival he went to a couple weeks back was a great experience. He went camping and went to Quebec in a park that was open two weeks before they camped there. He\'s been having a lot of fun lately. He tells listeners that he\'s had a few weeks off since he started doing the show.\n\nHe hopes everyone has had a good August and has been able to get to the Electric Eclectics festival. He says he saw all kinds of different bands he\'d never seen before and had a chance to go camping in Quebec. He then tells listeners about some of the music he has been playing. He starts off by saying he\'ll be playing some music from some local artists and then he',NULL,NULL),(62095,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/Tone Zone - August 16, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 20:49:37',NULL,'The Tone Zone is a music program hosted by CFRU\'s Matt. The program starts off with a tribute to the late Robbie Robertson, a songwriter for the Dallas Cowboys. Then it\'s a group of songs from the late 70s and 80s. The first song is a song from The Swan Song, which was a song written by the Cowboys. The second song is The Last Waltz from the Swan Song. The third song is the title track from The Stage Fright, which also was written by Robbie. The fourth song is from The Replacements\'s latest album. The fifth is from Prince Billy\'s new album.\n\nSo the show is over. Matt welcomes everyone to the program. He\'s reading a list of all the albums that shaped the city of Vancouver. One that caught his eye was by Circle C, a band that released an album in 1991. It didn\'t have a lot of success, but has since become a cult favorite with its songs. The band\'s name is Circle C. The song is \"It\'s The shop assistance and / It\'s up to you 1985.\" The other songs include \"Motherhood\" , \"Wandering Tad\" and \"Grease Box\" . The show ends with',NULL,NULL),(62096,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/Radia - August 16, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 20:31:02',NULL,'This show is a continuation of a conversation between Rallia and the University of Guelph\'s volunteer-run campus and community radio station, CFRU-9.3FM. Radia is a group of radio stations bringing new ways of making to their listeners. They are also known as \"the stations bringing old and forgotten ways to make.\" Each week, they give artists a challenge to make a radio station that works across Europe. Are you ready to make the station?\n\nOkay, come along with me. I\'m going to introduce you to the station. It is Radia, a group that is bringing \"new and forgotten\" ways to making the stations. They\'re known as the \"stations bringing new and forgot ways to our listeners.\" They are known for their talk shows. They do this every week. They invite artists to create a show that works on the continent. They ask listeners to come with them. Is you ready for it? Uh oh.',NULL,NULL),(62097,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Wind-Down - August 20, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 20:09:35',NULL,'On this edition of the Wind-down program, we find out that all of the artists who played at the festival were from the hillside, and that they were all playing new songs. Some of the songs we heard on the program are from artists who are playing this year, like Begonia, Ariel Pozen, Begonia\'s sister Bebe, and Witch Prophet. We also hear a song from Relayna, who is playing the song El Sistidi y el Cant.',NULL,NULL),(62098,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Here Today - August 17, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 17:09:11',NULL,'The show opens with a new track from Mystery Romance, followed by a song from the forthcoming Harmony and Discord album from the band. Next, Aaron plays a remix of Progression from the Paragon Cause album, and then he plays Forever For You, one of several new tracks from Deborah\'s new classical album. Aaron also plays a new song from John Lennon\'s 1973 album, Out the Blue, and a new single from Art Bergen, the Baltimore-based band that was influenced by The Hawk and The Tragically Hip. Aaron closes the show by playing the song from their upcoming album, In The Tangled Web.',NULL,NULL),(62099,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Tales from the Bridge - August 17, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 16:51:16',NULL,'In this episode, Sam and his buddy, Kevin, open the show by inviting listeners to \"tell us what they\'re doing\" . They\'ve got lots to talk about for the show, and they\'d love for you guys to chime in with your thoughts. The guys also have a book for the month, and then they\'ll talk about what\'s on their mind. They also have some science fiction and science facts for the episode.\n\nSam asks if there are any news stories that aren\'t science-fiction-related these days. Well, according to Sam, there\'s one YouTuber who does. The guy is called Mark Rober, and he\'s a former engineer turned YouTuber. He has made glitter bombs and squirrel contraptions.',NULL,NULL),(62100,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Android’s Dungeon - August 17, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 16:31:06',NULL,'The first part of this interview is with John Harris, the designer of the 1868 Wyoming. The two of them discuss the upcoming game. The interview ends with a question and answer session. Jack and John start off by asking each other what they\'ve been up to. Jack notes that he\'s been playing board games lately, and John says that he hasn\'t been playing much.',NULL,NULL),(62101,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/FoodFarm Talk - August 17, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 16:07:52',NULL,'The Sew and Grow FM podcast is a show on CFRMU 93.3 about food, farming, and the food system in Ontario and beyond. It\'s hosted by Stuart Oak and co-hosted by Alia Fraser. The show covers hot topics such as food sovereignty, farm economics and markets, food safety, soil health and circulating food systems.\n\nIt also includes other excellent podcasts about food and agriculture from across the province and beyond, including from other producers. For the latest episode, we have Alia Fraser talking with Dave Skeen, a co-founder of the Winowoc collective. Dave and Alia talk about the climate crisis from Dave\'s perspective as a farmer, a community organizer, and a Métis person. They discuss how to respond to climate change in a just way. Alia asks why it is important for the show to have Dave on the show, and she says that the work of Wissauk is an example of land-based systems that need to be improved.\n\nShe also says that responding to the climate change is more than just a conversation. She says that it\'s a conversation that was important for them to have, and thanks them for being a part of it. She\'s excited to learn more about the issues of the season from Dave.',NULL,NULL),(62102,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/T.K.O. - August 17, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 15:51:40',NULL,'On this episode of TKO, host Janan talks to her listeners about the state of the world of mixed martial arts. She tells them that the next day is the official work day, meaning that everyone is back at work. She says that it\'s normal to have a work day after a long weekend, but that she was one of those people who had to work late today because of all the holidays. She advises listeners to be kind to themselves.',NULL,NULL),(62103,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/RadiOPIRG - August 17, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 15:07:20',NULL,'In this episode of Perk, the host talks with LaMarrowas about Die Out, a community workshop that teaches people how to use tools and equipment to make things. The workshop is having a grand opening on August 19 from 12 to 6:00 p.m at their new location, 700 York Road. They\'ll be selling food, music, and other things. Perk also talks with Harine Hassan, a member of the Decoit-and-Land-Defenders group. She\'s been working with the water campaign as their organizer. She also talks about her involvement in the Shut-Down Canada movement. She explains that she\'s part of the group.',NULL,NULL),(62104,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Turtle Island Underground - August 17, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 14:48:56',NULL,'On April 2023, check out the latest edition of the Turtle Island Underground podcast as we hear a new song from the band Adam Sturgeon and Daniel Monkman.\n\nThe song is from their new album, Deeper, which is available on their new label, Sub Pop. The band also has a new single from that album, which they call Purgatory, which also comes with a new music video. The music video shows the band stuck in a purgatory waiting for the next song to come along. They also have a song from their first album that was recorded in 2021 and is a reference to the song they recorded in the trash can in 2021 but didn\'t use.\n\nThey decided to revisit the song with a guitar part which also came from the first song on the deeper album. This is the new version of the song that they recorded back in 2021 in a much faster and more dynamic way. The final track on the mix is a shoegaze track from the new super group, led by singer/songwriter Mary Tyler, who has been collaborating with musicians Matthew Cardinal and Ryan Beady.',NULL,NULL),(62105,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Open Sources Guelph - August 17, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 20:39:43',NULL,'On this edition of Open Source, the CFRU political and current news show, host Scottie Hertz breaks the news that the Canadian National Exhibition food list has dropped for 2023, making it \"as hideous as ever does.\" The CNE is a huge, three-day event, and the food is hideously cheap. In addition, the CNE has a huge selection of junk food, which makes the food even worse. The program also discusses a report from the auditor general, Bonnie Lissick, who found that the process for selling green belt land was not very thorough. The report found that some developers, including Silvio De Gasperis, were given the details of the land that was to be sold. This information came from a staff in the ministry of municipal affairs and housing. According to the report, the process of selling the land wasn\'t very thorough, and some of the people involved in the process were paid to do so. The release of the report came as a surprise to everyone, since it had been a long time coming. Ford has promised to cancel all of the recommendations in the report. The biggest recommendation is to take away the plum pickings from the friends of the mayor. The other one is to make sure that the contractors who gave Ford\'s employees the union t-shirts are investigated as well. The second recommendation is that the people who gave the mayor the fake green belt sign should be investigated. The first one is that he take the plums from the',NULL,'The CNE is a huge, three-day event, and the food is hideous as ever does'),(62106,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Forever Deaf - August 18, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 14:27:05',NULL,'Dean has left the stage for the night, so the next hour is dedicated to a new set of music. This new set includes new music from the likes of Dying Fetus, Dying Mantis, Dying Moth, Cataclyst, and Cannibal Corpse. Next up is Patrida, a new album from Kelly Shafer. The band is called Outside The Spiral, and it\'s a new band with Kelly Shafer on drums.\n\nIt makes my ears drown in tears. This is Death, 93.3 CFRUFM in... EVERY TIME. We heard Nuclear Power Trio, Beneath the Rose, God Made Me An Animal, Better Lovers, Triskelion, Visionaries, Extinction AD, Morality Bait, Aftermath, and Angelus Forever Appetrita. The last new track is from Childbite, who is from Detroit,Michigan. They opened the show, and from what he heard they were good. They are all, sorry, they all look away, not they are all.',NULL,NULL),(62107,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Forever Deaf - August 18, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 14:06:37',NULL,'Dean Yount is back on the program and he\'s got some new music for you. First off, he plays some of his favorite songs from Australia and the U.\n\nS. Then he plays a few songs from his favorite band, Todie. He tells you that his brain tumor has become resistant to all of his treatments, and that\'s why he\'ll have to go to a different hospital in Toronto for his final treatments. Dean also tells us that his friend Lisa is going to have her breast surgery later today, so we\'ll send her our wishes. And then we hear some more music from our Dying World. They\'ve got a new song called \"The Egregious sin of humanity\" . They also have a new track called \"Zenith passage from thedadalusium\" , which is a reference to the Trojan War.',NULL,NULL),(62108,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Forever Deaf - August 17, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 13:48:36',NULL,'In this week\'s program, Lee Fields, host of CFRU\'s Morning Soul Shake Up, plays music from a variety of artists. He also discusses a local concert that\'s coming up on September 2. First off, he plays two songs from Itis, one from Seagrave and one from Two Shadows. That\'s it, folks. And if you missed it, you can listen to it all on Soundcloud. Lee Fields is a host at CFRU, so he\'s got a special place in his heart for his listeners.',NULL,NULL),(62109,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Forever Deaf - August 17, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 13:31:17',NULL,'This is the first of a series of monologues in which the narrator speaks about the need for people to become organ donors.\n\nHe reminds listeners that a person\'s life can be saved if they consent to donate their organs. He also warns listeners that they should not forget to share their wishes with their family after the donation. The first of these monologues is from the Forever Deaf program, a program dedicated to preserving the culture of the Deaf. The program is hosted by Mike Willis, who is known for his strong opinions on the subject of human rights. The show begins with a monologue by the narrator, who begins by saying that if you are a person who is deaf, you have the right to be a part of the conversation. He says that he has heard many people complain about their inability to communicate with others, but he says that they all have the same complaints.\n\nHe tells the listeners that he is a deaf man, and that he was raised by a deaf family. He explains that he learned to speak and write when he was a child. He has always had a strong interest in music, but it was only when he began to write that he realized that he could communicate with people who were deaf that he began hearing more music. He feels that music should be a form of communication between people, and he encourages listeners to express their feelings through music.',NULL,NULL),(62110,121,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Sundowner - August 17, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 13:10:05',NULL,'The show starts off with a new song from Whitney Kaye, who\'s releasing a new album called VB in a couple of weeks. Before that, we hear from Jesus of Mary Chain, from the title track of Dark Lands, and from Serving Purpose, a song from a Chana Flowers release. The show then hears from Glitters 2021 Life Is Not a Lesson, from Girls\' Album, from Sleeplates\' Perfect Ruin EP, from Young Gov\'s 2009 LP, from Silver Dapple\'s Magique, from Spirit\'s I\'m so affected EP, and a song by Philadelphia\'s Natural Devotion from the Beehive Imso Lucky EP. We hear more songs from Younggov\'s last year, from Philadelphia, from Montreal, from La Securité\'s Stay Safe, from a song called Anyway, from Children of Desire\'s Time, and more.',NULL,NULL),(62111,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/The Crooked Beat - August 17, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 12:48:35',NULL,'The show opens with music from Harry Toddler, Cezdec Babylon Fallen, Larak, and others. Next up is a mix of ska music from the latest album from LAB, Runnin\', and some ska from the ska revivalists, the Scandalites and Soul Brothers. The show closes with more ska, this time from Sarah Lugo, who has released a new album called Flowers, Street, which includes a song called Running. The other musicians on the show include Ben Harper, Ziggy Marley, Pam Hall, Rico Rodriguez, and Mungo. The program concludes with Dredd playing some of his own music.',NULL,NULL),(62112,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/The Crooked Beat - August 17, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 12:29:24',NULL,'This week\'s edition of The Crooked Beat features music from various artists, including the late Jojo Bennett, a former student at the Alpha Boys School who emigrated to Canada and founded the Satellites. The first track on the show is a tribute to Bennett, who is remembered for his pioneering work with the Fugates and for his work with his students at the Satellite School. The second track is an introduction to Bennett\'s life and career, which began with Byron Lee\'s Celestials and ended with him forming the Satellite Band. The band recorded seven albums, won two Juno awards, and Bennett is survived by his seven children, 11 grandchildren, and 3 great-grandchildren',NULL,NULL),(62113,124,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Planet Groove - August 18, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 12:07:27',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62114,123,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Thanks for Listening :) - August 18, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 11:49:24',NULL,'The second half of the program begins with the song \"Take the Weight\" by John Common. After that, he plays songs from his \"Bloine Sister\" album. He also sings a song from the \"Nice to Come Home\" album, and a song by Haim, who is returning to Newfoundland after spending the summer in Newfoundland. He plays a song called \"Dim Reprise\" by Salami, and then a song of Jenny Havall\'s. He then plays songs by Tierra Whack, Naomi Elizabeth, and Kim Mortal. He ends the program by playing one of his \"Mother Tongues\" songs.',NULL,NULL),(62115,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Viejoteca - August 18, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-21 03:49:52',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62116,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Viejoteca - August 18, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-21 03:49:53',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62117,127,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/LiYghTE FM - August 18, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 11:31:27',NULL,'DJ Double D begins his set by explaining that he will be DJing at the Fierce Tonight at Onix tonight. He tells the audience that he is disappointed with the DJ character, who he says is \"emotionally distant\" from his friends and family, and who is trying to \"change the entire universe\" through a \"love revolution\" . He also explains that the DJ is changing the entire world, \"from one based upon empty monetary greed\" to one where people care more about who they are and how they treat each other than money.\n\nHe explains that he\'s not a \"human\" or a \"person\" but a human being. He laments the damage caused by a recent storm in Mexico. Maria, a friend of his from Harlem, reminded him that the rich were getting richer, while the poor were getting poorer. He reminds us that the poor are suffering under US oppression. He says, \"Remember, remember the campo, suffering in silence. separated by ocean and language still free, still free in love of people, fearless, and every roar. Every roar of revisionism.\" He concludes by saying, \"We are worth fighting',NULL,NULL),(62118,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Walkuman Style - August 18, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 11:04:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62119,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Digital Statik - August 18, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 10:48:58',NULL,'This is a new track called \"D\'E-J\'A-Y\'J\'U-L\'Z\" that we\'ve added to the new thread.',NULL,NULL),(62120,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Global Rare Grooves - August 18, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 10:26:56',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62121,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/A Dog’s Breakfast - August 19, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 10:12:44',NULL,'This is the second in a three-part program on the CFRU-FM 93.3 program To Know The Land. The first part begins with a warm welcome from the host and ends with a reminder of what the program is all about. The second part of the program begins with the host offering his breakfast to the guests. The host opens by saying that he\'s excited to play some music for the breakfast.\n\nHe\'s been listening to a lot of different types of music and he has a few new favorites he\'d like to play. First up is a band called Otter Rickshaw. They play music from all over the world. They have a great program called \"A Meeting by the River.\" The first song they play is a song by Vishwan Mohan Bhat. It starts out quietly, but as it gets more exciting, the music starts to grow louder. The next song is from a band named Zalora Swit. They\'re from their CD \"Black Peak.\" The second song is called \"Dalava, the Book of Transfiguration.\n\n\" It\'s by Julia Ulela. She\'s the musician on this CD. The musicians on the CD are Julia, Aram, and Peggy Lee. The narrator says that she\'s going to send the music to her husband, Ajay, who\'s home cleaning up after the day\'s work. She also says that the first song in English is \"Seven pairs of eagles,\" but she also wants to go to',NULL,NULL),(62122,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Folk Roots Radio - August 18, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 09:51:23',NULL,'Paul Mills is a Canadian musician, arranger, and producer who has worked in the music industry for 45 years.\n\nHe has made 200 albums and is a member of the Order of the Canadian Order of Merit. He is known for his work with artists like Stan Rogers and Sharon Bramison, as well as his work as an engineer and arranger for over 200 albums. Paul has been appointed to the order in June of 2017. He is a special guest on the show. He tells us that when he looks back on his career, it is hard to believe how much he\'s been involved with the music business. He says',NULL,NULL),(62123,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Sound Magic - August 19, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 09:10:35',NULL,'In this program, Doleschell talks about a composer named Michislav Weinberg. He is a Polish-born musician who was raised in St. Petersburg, Russia. He studied under the great Russian composer, Shostakovich, who was a compatriot of his father\'s. After his parents were killed in the war, he fled to Russia to study with Shostakovich. In Russia, he became a renowned symphonist, writing symphonies that describe life in Russia. One of his symphonies is a work for string orchestra with the highly respected Kremerata Balticas, led by the highly accomplished conductor, Miha Graziniti-tila.',NULL,NULL),(62124,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Sound Magic - August 19, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 08:48:48',NULL,'This program is a little shorter than usual, but it is still a good one. The program starts off with some \"out of the way\" music, mostly composed by Paul Georgy Greiner.\n\nGreiner is a German composer who was living in England when he moved to Germany in the early 1900s. He survived until 1944. Greiner\'s music is very accessible to the Germans because the Germans were not into \"ultra-modernism\" , but he is a talented composer. The music is by the North German Philharmonic of Hanover conducted by Andreas Albert. Then it\'s Paul Greiner again. He\'d been living in Germany since 1872 and he was born there in England. He stayed there for the rest of his life. He is a good composer, but the Germans weren\'t into ultra-Modernism. They were too rigid and didn\'t have a lot of modern ideas. So Greiner has some very accessible music. The North Germans have a good conductor, Andreas Albert, who is very pleasant to listen too.\n\nThen we\'re back to the music. This is Edward Lassen, a Danish composer who lived in Brussels and Weimar, Germany. He wrote a few pieces for the symphony orchestras, but his most famous work is a violin concerto. It is in D major from 1894 and he wrote a bunch of popular songs.',NULL,NULL),(62125,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Bel Araby with CAWA - August 19, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 08:29:45',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62126,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Bel Araby with CAWA - August 19, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 07:10:27',NULL,'This program opens with a description of the upcoming Bike-the-Night event. It takes place on September 9, from 7pm to 10pm at Guelph\'s City Hall. It is free and open to all. The program then moves on to a discussion of the importance of having the right tools to create something.\n\nA workshop is a community of volunteers who provide tools and equipment to help people get started on their projects. The workshop recently moved to a new location and there will be a grand opening on August 19, 12pm to 6pm at the new location. You can stop by and listen to the music on the station on Monday nights. The station also has a new line of clothing and merchandise.',NULL,NULL),(62127,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Alternativa Latinoamericana - August 20, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-21 03:50:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62128,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Alternativa Latinoamericana - August 20, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-21 03:50:09',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62129,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Mach Vibe Radio - August 19, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 06:47:57',NULL,'The Underground Underground Master explains how he applies his De philosophy to everyday tasks. He knows everything about how to do his job, and he knows how to organize everything. He uses this knowledge to do whatever he needs to do. The Underground Master says that the easier you do your job, the less time you have to spend with De. He says that if you want to do nothing at all, do it easily. You are listening to the underground on CFRU 92. DE, Do easy.',NULL,NULL),(62130,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Mach Vibe Radio - August 19, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 06:26:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62131,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Tiempo de Mujeres - August 19, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-21 03:50:10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62132,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/The Underground - August 20, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 06:11:07',NULL,'In other news, a state of emergency has been declared in California before a tropical storm slams into Mexico, and a tropical weather warning is also in effect for parts of the West.\n\nThe US also announces sanctions against Nicaragua, in response to the government\'s violent repression of opposition activists ahead of the women\'s world cup final. Around 30,000 have been ordered to evacuate their homes in British Columbia as massive wildfires continue to rage. The Okanagan Valley, a popular tourist destination in the province, is facing what authorities say is a \"highly dynamic situation\" as a powerful hurricane is headed towards the country. The mayor of San Diego tells people to stay home as the storm is getting stronger. In Niger, the leader of the last coup has warned that a three-year transition will take place.\n\nHe also warns of the \"regional implications\" of foreign intervention. The West African group, EcoWOS, says it has set a deadline for military operation if negotiations fail',NULL,NULL),(62133,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/The Underground - August 19, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 05:11:11',NULL,'This week\'s program is a look at some volunteer opportunities in the community and some news about the new law making it illegal to block social media feeds from Canadians. The program also discusses how meta-products are blocking news from Canadians and what can be done about it. If you haven\'t already, check out the news about Bill C-18 and how it\'s going to be a problem for you and your family.\n\nThe news is also about how many people die every day because of an inability to get an organ. Only 31% of Canadians have the right to donate their organ and tissue, according to the Canadian Association of Organ and Tissue Transplantation. If someone had not signed up, they wouldn\'t be alive today, says Mike Willis, who is a heart donor.',NULL,NULL),(62134,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Visions fugitives - August 20, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 04:50:00',NULL,'The piece that we\'re about to hear is a work by George Lucas, but it\'s actually a piece by another famous composer named Bala Bartok, who was born in Transylvania but grew up in the west of the country. Bartok wrote a number of works for Viola, including this one, which we\'ll hear about later. We\'ll also hear about the first work he wrote for a small orchestra, a suite called \"Suite Two,\" which was written in 1907 and revised in 1943',NULL,NULL),(62135,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Visions fugitives - August 20, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 04:35:23',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the show and its co-hosts. The show\'s co-presenter, Christopher Curry, introduces himself and explains that he is the voice of Visions Fugitives. He explains that the music for the show is selected by Fangwei, and that he has not been a part of selecting the music.\n\nThe program begins with a discussion of the theme of the last show, which was \"Torpor,\" a theme that Fangwei wrote about in his book, The Bat. He also writes that bats are \"the only animals that have mastered the air.\" The program ends with a reminder that the program will be airing on August 6, 2023.',NULL,NULL),(62136,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Clan Na Gael - August 20, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 04:08:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62137,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Clan Na Gael - August 20, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 03:14:15',NULL,'This is the second time John has been at the station. The first time was when he was in the audience at the Hillside, and he says he hopes people enjoyed it.\n\nHe says he\'s back in the city, but this time he\'ll play music from his collection. He brought in some songs he hasn\'t played on the show before. First up is a band from Winnipeg, Manitoba. They have a double CD collection. They\'ve also got a CD called Guinness God Will You Go, which is an Irish song, and another called Flugging Molly, a song from California. Some of these songs are from the station, but some of them are from his own collection. So he hopes he can play them all on his own. He wants to play one of the cassettes first, which he does. He doesn\'t know how to play the one he brought in, but he hopes it will work out.\n\n',NULL,NULL),(62138,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Zombie Jamboree - August 20, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 02:55:21',NULL,'This is an early version of the full-length version of Bruce\'s song \"The Zombie Jamboree,\" in which he describes the music that he and his band played at the Riverfest festival in Alora, Italy.\n\nThe first song is a song by Reverend Al Green called \"Take Me To The River.\" The second song is one by Selena Martin called \"If You Were A River,\" and the third song is by Gotobo called \"Fuerza Nacional.\" The band\'s signal is strongest at 93.3 mega-hertz, so they can hear everything they want. They\'re heading back to Guelph, where they\'ll find their studios at CFRU. The band heard a man on his way to the Alash river in Tuva or Mongolia singing a song called \"Arash River in Translation at least.\" The song is translated as \"The Arash River.\" They heard Pa\'uwa sing \"La Lugcuse,\" a song about the light, and they heard Blackie and his gang sing \"Grand River.\"',NULL,NULL),(62139,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Backtracks - August 20, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 02:32:59',NULL,'Backtracks with Host Jennifer takes listeners back in time to the 60s, 70s and 80s. They play a mix of old and new music and interpret it in American Sign Language. The program starts off with the classic song Moby Grape and ends with a new track by a Canadian band called The Headstones. Backtracks ends with another song by a British band called BlodwinPig. The show closes with a song by the Kingston band called Nothing Changes, which is about being stuck.',NULL,NULL),(62140,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/Through the Looking Glass - August 20, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 02:12:09',NULL,'Alice, the host of the show, begins by introducing herself as \"Alice,\" and she and her listeners will follow the music through the Looking-Glass. The first artist they will listen to is Water Baby, whose album is called \"Foam.\" The second artist they\'ll listen to will be Wolfie1s Just Fine, whose track is \"Saint Paul.\n\n\" The third artist will be The Monkees, who have just released a new album called \"The Monkees.\" The fourth artist they listen to, Greg Clark and his band, is \"The Madvarks,\" who have released a brand-new album on Bandcamp called \"Only the Best.\" The fifth artist they hear will be Octavian\'s \"The Line of Curve,\" who has not yet released an album. The final artist they have to listen to tonight is \"Anding,\" a song by Octavian. They\'ll hear more about her later in the show.',NULL,NULL),(62141,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/Beautiful Druid - August 19, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 01:11:07',NULL,'This is a short program from the university called Beautiful Druid. It is a stream-of-consciousness program, where we listen to music performed by singer songwriters and other artists who don\'t write the songs they perform.\n\nThe theme for the week is \"being positive.\" There are many challenges in the world and we must stay optimistic because that\'s how we will get through them. The first song we hear is a song by Jesse Winchester called Do It. He says that if we are skating on a thin ice, we should dance. Alden Hadwen, the host of the program, says that \"If we\'re on the floor, but you\'re not sick of it, you do it until you cant do it anymore\" . If you want to write to him, he says, just write at a beautiful place. The next song is from Matthew Barber\'s family album, \"I Must Be In A Good Place Now.\n\n\" It was written by Bobby Clark, but they like it and they are performing it. The final song is by Leonard Cohen from his album \"Popular Problems.\" Alden says that love doesn\'t have to be a love for partners. It can be love for family, love for your work, love even for your partner, but the more you have in life, the more resilient you are to handle the stresses. The song he\'s playing is \"If Not For You\" by Bob Dylan. The second song is Leonard Cohen\'s',NULL,NULL),(62143,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Democracy Now - August 18, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-22 00:52:16',NULL,'Amy Goodman reports on a number of recent disasters, including wildfire in British Columbia, mass evacuation in Alberta, a deadly wildfire in Hawaii, and a growing housing crisis in the wake of the tragedy. In Alberta, smoke from a massive wildfire has led to mass evacuations. In the United States, a wildfire has killed six people and destroyed thousands of structures.',NULL,NULL),(62145,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/Democracy Now - August 17, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-22 00:30:53',NULL,'The death to toll from this week\'s devastating Maui wildfires has reached 111, and the missing are still believed to be missing. Meanwhile, Hawaiian authorities have defended not using emergency sirens during this fire, even though they are used primarily for the tsunamis. The governor of Hawaii has proposed a ban on land deals in the state, saying he wants to make sure no one is cheated. In Canada, authorities have ordered all the residents of the small town of Yellowknife, which is located on the Canadian border, to flee as the city is in a \"state of panic.\"',NULL,NULL),(62147,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/Democracy Now - August 16, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 23:09:28',NULL,'This week, we take a look at the latest developments in the world of journalism. We begin with a conversation with Amy Goodman, a journalist and the author of the new book, \"The Price of Silence.\" Amy explains that the police raid on a family newspaper in Kansas and the publication of another bomb in another paper in Montana have all put a chill on the free flow of information.',NULL,NULL),(62149,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - August 16, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 22:49:46',NULL,'The next segment of the show is about womens\'s soccer and it\'s all about the womens world cup. The womens team is out of the tournament, and the country needs younger players to step up and be the backbone of the team. It\'s time for the country to get back in the World Cup, says the host. The top two teams from each division will advance to the final. The host predicts that the United States will not be in the final because of the depth of the Canadian team.',NULL,NULL),(62150,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Industry Tactics - August 18, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 22:31:52',NULL,'The next morning, the UM opens up to Nelly about his relationship with the people he\'s played with. He says he likes to make fun of himself, and he\'d like to make a lot of people happy. He\'s an \"irreverenttainer\" , and his whole career was to be a part of society. He doesn\'t see society changing, though, because he\'ll always be a \"contrarian\" .\n\nHe wants to have a \"common ground,\" and he wants to make people happy, too. He feels like America is a beautiful country, but it\'s also \"a country of extremes\" and \"on 11, right?\" . The UM says he can\'t figure out how to do what he does right now, but he thinks that art is great for dealing with reality, and that everyone has a story to tell.',NULL,NULL),(62151,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Industry Tactics - August 18, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 21:09:53',NULL,'In this episode of Industry Tactics, Gregory introduces us to Weasel. He tells us that he\'s a big inspiration to all of us who want to be musicians. He says that he didn\'t even know he was a musician until this point. We\'re not aware of him.',NULL,NULL),(62153,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/18/Hellfire Radio - August 18, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-18 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 20:31:45',NULL,'On this week\'s episode of \"Electric Hellfire Radio,\" we find out that the CFRU-FM station has a new feature-packed website. We also learn that the 13th Annual Riverfest is coming up in Allora on August 18-20. It\'s free to the public and there\'s lots of food and music to choose from.\n\nCheck out the website for more information. You can listen to the show on your iPod or on your iPhone. The guys also talk about a new show they\'re doing called \"State of Emergency,\" which is a live band from Winger, a progressive metal band. The band\'s first album was released in 1988. The guys decide not to play their first album by Jimi Hendrix, but instead play a live version of \"Emergency.\"',NULL,NULL),(62154,2205,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/16/Samaismela Music Show + CFRU Playlist - August 16, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-16 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 20:07:31',NULL,'The University of Chicago\'s Center for Student Involvement is hiring an \"outbound\" campus outreach assistant to help organize and lead club meetings and station tours. The assistant will be paid according to the number of club meetings that are held each week. The Assistant will be responsible for managing the campus\'s social media presence, as well as managing the clubs\' social media.',NULL,NULL),(62155,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Solipsistic Retreat - August 15, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 19:08:28',NULL,'This is the second half of the interview, and it begins with a lecture on \"The Only Smokes Guided by Voices.\" He describes the concept of \"guided by voices\" as a system in which voices always change and that people can always improve.\n\nHe says that he likes to believe that old people can also improve their art, just as people can improve their music. Next, the host plays a song called \"Pitchshifter.\" The song is the first song he has heard from the band, and he finds it very \"politically charged.\" The lyrics are very \"energetic and fun.\" The band is based in New York City, and the lead singer is from the Bowery. The host thinks that Pitchshifter is very punk influenced, and that the band uses an Atari ST as its recording equipment. He finds the music very \"fiery and noisier\" than the music he used to play in the arcades.',NULL,NULL),(62156,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/15/Solipsistic Retreat - August 15, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-15 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 18:49:39',NULL,'This is the fourth episode of the \"Solipsistic Retreat,\" a program on CFRU-FM 93.3 in Guelph, Ontario. The program is solipsistic that it is devoid of self-reflection, introspection, or self-care. The show opens by introducing listeners to a new genre of music.\n\nIt is called \"folk music,\" and it was a genre that existed in the 1990s. It was characterized by artists who were \"returning to music\" because of the concept of \"feminism.\" The artists who had returned to music were \"Bear Naked Ladies,\" \"Annie DeFranco,\" \"Karen Hanna,\" and \"Bibi Bikini Kill. Billy was the guitar player in Bikini Kill.\" The show describes how a Canadian man named Loudoun Rainwright made a protest against a Swedish band, Abba, on Saturday night Live in 1976. The show was very critical of the band because they had no American television, and they were not aware of the show\'s live nature.\n\nThe Canadian man, Michael Lornes, was mad at the Swedes. Rainwright, however, made the protest against the American Bicentennial and against the Swedish band\'s performance. The song \"Bicentennial\" is silly, and the song \"Loudoun SOS\" is incredible. The group that made the song, \"Scarlet O\'Hara,\" sounds great, and there is no flaw, no whinginess, no politics, and no song that the listeners will recognize. This is one of the',NULL,NULL),(62157,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Solipsistic Retreat - August 8, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 18:27:24',NULL,'The guys start off by playing two songs from the band F-U-N-L-O-D-E. They play a song from their first album and another from their second album. The first song is from the group K. M.F. D.M. and the second is from a band called Cool Modie. The guys talk about the cool modie and how he\'s a rap artist, but they also talk about some of the other artists on the show, like guided by voices and Sunforger. Finally, they play a harmonica.',NULL,NULL),(62158,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/08/Solipsistic Retreat - August 8, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-08 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 17:08:12',NULL,'The first event at the festival is called Battles, and it\'s their first EP, so it must have been released some time ago. The band has put out a bunch of EPs in the past few years, and they\'ve just released one single this year.\n\nThe guy also introduces us to a new website called Discogs.com, where people can find all kinds of information about music releases in different countries. He also gives us a PS3 guide, where we can find the best music on the PS3 from all over the world. The first thing he tells us is that he\'s got a bone with the company called Computer Entertainment, who releases music in other countries and says that they\'re releasing music on PS3s all the time, too.\n\nIf you own a PS3, you can buy a game called ViBRibbon. The game is very simple, and you can play it as a rabbit, which means you can only miss four buttons on the controller. But you still have to play the game as if you were a rabbit. The art style is very similar to the art style of the game. You see lines on the screen, and the shapes in the game correspond to the buttons on your PS3. So, the game is insane, because you can have anything you want with it, except for public enemies, which can only be played on a CD. But the fact that you can use a CD with the game makes it even more',NULL,NULL),(62159,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/17/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 17, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-17 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 16:47:45',NULL,'The Intercept Senior Writer, Julie, joins Amy and Nermeen to discuss a new community project, the Free-Huber Community Bike Center. The center will offer free access to bike repair space and will be open from April to May. The FreeHub Community Center is created to help people travel safely, stay fit and build skills to help them get around.\n\nAmy starts the show by introducing herself to a new listener, a woman named Patricia Boudreaux. She\'s just moved into a retirement community called Riverside Glen. She tells Amy that she used to live near her family in Weston, where she grew up. She says that she went to school well, graduated, and never got into the top schools. She doesn\'t like that she\'s old now, though, because she thinks it\'s unfair that she wasn\'t able to finish high school and get to be a part of the community.\n\nShe also says that one of her Irish grandmothers died long after that.',NULL,NULL),(62160,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-10 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 16:26:39',NULL,'On August 10th, the university will be holding a Prisoners\' Justice day, a day to remember the prisoners who have died while in prison. The university will also be presenting an album of songs recorded by prisoners, as part of its Pros and Cons recording project. The album will be Private Town, which was released in 2017, and Paint in Forest, which will be released in 2019.',NULL,NULL),(62161,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2018 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-10 17:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-21 16:07:50',NULL,'The group discusses the idea of having a cell door in the public garden. The cell doors were originally made like they were in a school, and they thought they would grow wild flowers.\n\nThe group also discusses a former prison in the United States that took out one of the doors and planted native plants in it. The idea of planting plants in a public garden is an enlightened one, but it is a very obvious one. The women in the prison are going to brainstorm about how the garden will look. They want the control of how it will appear to be, rather than the final decision, to be from the women who have been in prison. They are also going to have a meeting over the weekend to brainstorm ideas about what the garden should look like.',NULL,NULL),(62162,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2018 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-10 16:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-21 15:07:42',NULL,'The program ends with a brief description of the RJ Radio Project, which is a public interest organization dedicated to the improvement of the lives of incarcerated people. The program is hosted by Lee Fields, who describes the program as an hour-long program that explores the stories of the prisoners and their communities. The show also includes a brief introduction to the program\'s listeners and the people who are involved in the program. Lee Fields is joined by John Fahi and his wife, Kaylee, who are both students at the university. They are discussing how to start their own business, a Celtic kitchen. They also discuss the latest technology available to listeners of the program, including an FM radio chip that can be installed in a smartphone.\n\nThe chip allows listeners to listen to the latest news, music, and weather while using less data and using less battery power than streaming music services. The chips are also better for the battery than streaming services because some carriers and manufacturers block access to the chips because they want their data to be used. This week, on Making Contact, the program explores how the school system can be more reflective of Black Lives Matter in order to make it more inclusive.\n\nIt does not look like suspending girls for fighting in the hall, it does not seem like sending a student home because she wore short pants. It means we have to look differently at how we respond in conflict, and how we understand and understand what these behavior are. The school system will also discuss Dr. W. Morris\'',NULL,NULL),(62163,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2018 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-10 15:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-21 14:46:31',NULL,'This week on Talking Radical, Scott talks with poet and organizer, Elle Jones, about the history of her work on prisoner justice. She started out as a poet and eventually became involved in a number of different forms of prisoner-led organizing. She was the Poet Laureate of Nova Scotia and also involved in other forms of community organizing, including a local radio show. The Black Power Hour was a part of this community organizing. It was a prisoner led show that was part of a larger community organizing project called Black Lives Matter. The show was not meant to be about prisoners, but rather about people in prison, Black history, and other topics that were important to the prisoners.',NULL,NULL),(62164,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2018 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-10 14:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-21 14:27:54',NULL,'The next time you hear Tom Rydell, you\'re going to want to hear more of this program. He\'s going to tell you about some new ways you can support the university.\n\nFirst, he\'s got a tip for you: You can buy a card with a $10 donation and get discounts at 14 downtown businesses. One of those downtown businesses is Fantascapes. The card is good until January of 2019. If that doesn\'t sound like a good deal, remember that the card is valid for another year. Plus, you can use the card to support your campus and campus radio station, too. Tom also gives us a sneak peek at some new projects he\'ll be working on for the upcoming week. He wants to help out with Crime Stoppers, so he can help make a difference in the community.',NULL,NULL),(62165,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2018 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-10 13:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-21 14:06:41',NULL,'On Sunday, August 10, 1974, the day after the execution of the notorious prisoner, Eddie Nalen, the day is designated as Prisoners\'Justice Day, and CFRU is broadcasting material related to the day. On the program, guest host, Jim, brings on two guests: Chris Brown, an artist who works with prisoners, and John Copping , a musician who works in the Prison Farms program, which helps inmates create music. The program has been in place since the government shut down the Agricultural Program in the early 1900s, and Brown and Copping both began working in prisons. They\'ve released two albums: Postcards From the County, a collection of music by prisoners around the world, and Undisclosed, an album of original music written and recorded by inmates at the Grand Valley Women\'s Institution.',NULL,NULL),(62166,2678,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/10/CFRU Prisoners’ Justice Day programming - August 10, 2018 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-10 12:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-21 13:53:30',NULL,'This program opens with a poem from Al Jones, a poet and social justice activist from Nova Scotia. The poem is called \"Judges.\" It\'s a satire on the daily grind of life in the prison. This program ends with Scott\'s interview with Al Jones about the injustices of the criminal justice system.',NULL,NULL),(62176,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pzdv4m/ABROAD_78_TFA_Taiwan70qkp.mp3','2023-08-21 10:19:25',113425684,'2023-12-21 13:33:00',NULL,'On this episode of Tracks From Abroad, Jesse McDougall introduces us to two of his students, Simon and Ross, who are both studying at the university. They are both from Taiwan. Ross is married to a Taiwanese woman, and he wants to talk about her religion, Taoism. This is the first of two parts of the show in which Ross and Jesse talk about their religious beliefs. The first part is about Simon, who is studying psychology at U ofT. The second part focuses on Ross\'s family.\n\nHis parents, an American and a Canadian, are both teachers in Taiwan. They met in Egypt when they were young children, and they moved to the island when he was about four. They lived in the south of the island until he was old enough to go to school in Taipei, the capital of Taiwan.',NULL,NULL),(62177,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Breezy Breakfast Radio - August 21, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 13:12:43',NULL,'Linda and Phil discuss the value of \"affordable housing\" for developers, and Linda points out that it\'s not always the case that developers will pass on the cost savings to their tenants.\n\nLinda points to a new development in Dublin, where the project\'s developer is offering a 20 percent discount on market rent for the first year of the project. That means the project is going to cost about $3 million, but the city will get about half of the money back as a grant. Linda also points to the need for long-term care for seniors, who are not able to stay in their own homes anymore because of their advanced dementia.\n\nLinda suggests that the city should invest in building long term care for people who need it. This would solve a lot of the housing problems in the city.',NULL,NULL),(62178,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Breezy Breakfast Radio - August 21, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 12:52:00',NULL,'The program opens with a discussion on the groundbreaking ceremony of the new branch of the public library. There are strong views about the new Strong Mayors Bill. It is coming to all 26 Ontario cities including Guelph on July 1.\n\nTanya, the program\'s moderator, begins the program by reminding listeners that Guelph is part of the Great Lakes Treaty Land. The treaty is called the \"dish with one spoon treaty\" and is a system of communal living where all people contribute to the communal dish. The goal of the treaty is to live a peaceful and harmonious life. The program ends with a reminder that the citizens of Guelph are subject to the political machinations of the strong mayors bill.',NULL,NULL),(62179,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 21, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 12:28:45',NULL,'This is a very brief introduction to a new program called \"The Morning Soul Shake Up\" produced by the University of Guelph. It is a daily program on CFRU\'s 93.3FM in Guelph. The program is a part of the university\'s \"Life in Covidence\" study, which seeks to understand how young and old people are affected by the pandemic. If you are between the ages of 5 and 65, the university has a team of scholars who would like to hear your story.',NULL,NULL),(62180,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - August 21, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 12:12:21',NULL,'The Guardian Overseer of the Sentinels Marvelous Kaleidoscope, Nicholas Cooper, joins us in this first episode of his new series, \"Invisible and Beyond.\" He invites us to join him as he looks at the music of the future from a different perspective.\n\nHe\'s going to pay respect to First Nation, Inuit, and Métis peoples across Turtle Island, and he\'s also going to acknowledge the contributions of Black people in the music world. First, he thanks the listeners for tuning in to the show. Then he thanks Black people for all the work they\'ve done in the world of music. He thanks everyone for coming out to listen to his show. The show begins with Silver Pools, who are supporting a band called Devourers, who is coming to town to play a show. They\'re going to be playing a show called \"Mother of and Silver Pools\" at the Bar on Dundas Street West, in Toronto, on August 22nd at 8PM.\n\nThe tickets are already sold out, but if you want to buy them, you can go to the bar on the hour and get them for free. This is the first show in the series, and it\'s all about the music. The first artist in the show is a musician by the name of Alex Fournier, who\'s playing with his band.',NULL,NULL),(62181,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/CFRU Playlist - August 21, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-22 03:46:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62182,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/CFRU Playlist - August 21, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-22 03:46:54',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62183,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Ripcord Radio - August 21, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 11:52:06',NULL,'This week on the show, the band plays a number of different kinds of music. They play songs from various Canadian bands, including hysterics, DOA, Black Flag, SNFU, The Asexual\'s With World for the Taking, and Dogosucid with O team Deshae. Finally, the group plays a song from the band Sexiplasia. They played a show in Guelph a few weeks back, and they ripped down the house down there. The band can be heard on Soundcloud.',NULL,NULL),(62184,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/The Deep House Project - August 21, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 11:28:18',NULL,'Aaron and his crew are psyched to be playing their next gig at the Deep House Project. Here\'s what Aaron has to say about the night: \"We\'re starting off with Steph David with his track, PM\" . Then we get a track called \"PM\" from Jerry Folk and \"Better Days\" from Vangasel. Then there\'s another track by Jerry called \"Tega\'s Latest Hand in Hand\" , a track by Holograms called Holograms 32 , and a track from Dennis Quinn called \"Love Fire\" that sounds like it\'s from the Caribbean.\n\nWe\'ll hear more of this from Aaron later in the show, but right now he\'s talking about how \"Caravanah\" is coming up soon. He also talks about how cool it is to be able to play music in the summer. The show closes with \"Don\'t you want me\" from Lea-L',NULL,NULL),(62185,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Big Sis Radio - August 21, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 11:09:42',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of Big Sis, host Cece takes us back to the beginning of time and tells us how long the show has been on the air.\n\nHe also tells us that this is the 50th edition of the show. The show starts off with a dance track from Mother Tongues called \"Dance in the Dark\" off their latest release \"Love in a vehement way\" . Next up is a song from Noble Oak called \"When it Finds you\" , and then it\'s Kim Mortal\'s \"Always\" and \"Kim Mortal\" and then \"Always Kim Mortal\" from Kim Mortal. The other tracks on the show are from Non Crows, \"Tabby Tabby\" by Kim Mortal and \"Dying to Believe\" by the Baths. Cece then goes on to tell us that today marks the anniversary of the first 50 episodes of the Big Sis Radio show.\n\nThis is also the year since the show started, so this means that we\'re back on track. We also learn that a new study from Ohio State shows that acts of kindness are just as good for mental health as any other mood boosting techniques. So, if you\'re feeling down, maybe you could do some kind of kindness to someone else instead.',NULL,NULL),(62186,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Blues Around the Block - August 21, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 10:47:55',NULL,'Mac Dee is the host of a program called \"Blues Around the Block\" on CFRU 98.3 and he is a regular guest on the program.\n\nHe welcomes listeners and encourages them to share their stories and experiences on the show. He tells the story of the Chicago Rhythm and the Blues Kings, who are trying to juggle a girlfriend, woman, and wife. They are in trouble too, he tells us. Mac Dee then goes on to tell us that Michael Bloom, the blues prophet, is in love with a woman and that he remembers love and Toronto Cannon. As usual, Mac Dee ends the show with a song about people being talked about.',NULL,NULL),(62187,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Blues Around the Block - August 21, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 10:26:39',NULL,'Mac Dee is the host of a show called \"Blues Around the Block\" on CFRU.com. The show is a mix of music, comedy, and commentary. Mac Dee starts the show by saying that he\'s a member of the band \"No Dear John\" and that he started the show with a song called \"Derek Hooke, love don\'t live around here\" . Then he goes on to say that the music on the show was inspired by the murder of Robert Cray. The first song is called \"I Wonder\" and the second song is \"The Bluesland hornband, Midnight',NULL,NULL),(62188,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/to know the land - August 21, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 18:12:39',NULL,'The group discusses the creation of the garden, which they call the \"moth garden.\" They\'ve planted some flowers and are working on a larger garden. The group\'s co-creator is the author of the book, \"Pollinators and Butterflies,\" who has helped them choose the right plants for the garden. They also talk about the importance of sharing the garden with other gardeners and observing the plants.',NULL,'The \'moth garden\' is a big project, and they\'ve planted some flowers'),(62189,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/This Night Wounds Time - August 21, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 10:11:19',NULL,'In this short speech, the student explains that he is working at the CFRU Hillside Campus, the university\'s media center, where he and his fellow students produce and host the campus radio station, 93.3 FM. The station also has a community outreach team that volunteers to organize events and festivals. The students are also looking for volunteer journalists to record short public service announcements for the show. They also have a public relations team that writes press releases for the station. The program will be called \"This Night Wounds\" and will be hosted by Christopher Curry, a student at the university.',NULL,NULL),(62190,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/This Night Wounds Time - August 21, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 09:51:20',NULL,'The geographical spotlight section is the part of the show where we hear about the artists from a specific country or region. For example, in the first segment we heard about Russia, which is by far the largest country. The next segment was about Canada, and the third segment was China. The fourth segment was the United States, and now it\'s about Argentina. And finally, the seventh segment is about the smallest country on the face of the earth, which we now find out is the Vatican City.',NULL,NULL),(62191,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/This Night Wounds Time - August 20, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 09:09:27',NULL,'This week on This Night Wound\'s Time, the host opens by explaining that the show usually runs for three hours and that the first hour will be devoted to playing music that is \"off the beaten track.\" He goes on to describe how the show can play music from all over \"the map\" and that they can play things that are \"a mite\" off the beaten path.\n\nThe host also explains that they\'ve been working on a new state this week, San Juan, in Argentina, and they\'re doing so again this week. The first song on the show is a new release from the CFRU jazz collection. It\'s called Continuing, and it\'s by Tishon Sori, who is on drums and Aaron Deal on the piano. The album is a collection of covers. In other words, the album is full of jazz standards that were popular in the past. Now, however, the music is also jazz standards, which is something that\'s not very common these days. This is a case in point, because the group is composed of Tishon, Aaron, and Matt. They\'re covering a track by Wayne Shorter, who died a few months before this.',NULL,NULL),(62192,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Democracy Now - August 21, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 08:51:35',NULL,'The election results are in, and the Supreme Court has declared that the popular candidate, Bernardo Arevalo, has won. We\'re going to see if he\'s even allowed to be elected president. Then we\'ll head to South Africa, where the BRICS nations are holding a summit. This is going to be a show of solidarity and unity. And then we\'re off to British Columbia, where over 400 fires have forced more than 35,000 people to flee.',NULL,NULL),(62193,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Worst Responders - August 21, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 08:33:27',NULL,'This is a special edition of the show where a special case is made for introverted listeners. It\'s called \"Worst Responders\" and it\'ll be on 93.3 CFRU. The show is hosted by Charissa and Renee, two stand-ups who are best and worst at responding to the low stakes problems that people have on the internet.\n\nThey\'re also known as the \"worst responders\" because they try to be funny and serious at the same time. Their show is \"improvised,\" and they don\'t have to tell listeners what they\'re talking about. They tell listeners that everything they hear today is \"irreverent,\" and that it doesn\'t reflect the opinion of the university. They want to make people better. Charissa says that she\'s not a college student, so she didn\'t set out to be a stand-',NULL,NULL),(62194,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 20, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 08:13:50',NULL,'At the Riverfest festival in Elora, the host of CFRU\'s 93.3FM introduces himself as a \"stand with private bags\" , and he explains that he\'s there to listen to some of the \"riverfest artists\" that he likes.\n\nHe also announces that he has a guest with him, Sophie, who introduces herself as \"not from close by\" . She\'s been to the festival and says that she\'s had some great food. She also speaks another language, Welsh, and the host asks if she can introduce herself in English. Sophie says that it\'s a pleasure to be able to speak another language and that there\'s also a lot of singing at the festival.\n\nThe host then asks Sophie about her favorite part of the festival, which was seeing a band called \"Shebad,\" which she thinks is awesome. She says she still feels like a \"fangirl\" even though she\'d just seen \"Lee Vollbeck\" in the band \"Acorn.\" The host says that the band was \"excellent,\" and that he was wearing the same shirt as the band. The talk then turns to the other festival that Sophie has seen, which is the \"Riverfest Delora.\" She says it was \"beautiful\" and that she enjoyed the festival overall.',NULL,NULL),(62195,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 20, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 07:34:18',NULL,'The group is in Rosalia, Mexico, for a weekend festival. The band is here to promote their wares in foreign languages, and also to find a new tribe of cruisers for the Rafaels.\n\nThe musicians are talking about Britney Spears, who will be in their program. The group teases her by saying that she is the manager of a chica, or a restaurant, and that she will be playing in their show. The song is about a woman who is going to become the mother of her little sister. The first lady says that she\'ll be her mom\'s, and the second lady says she\'s going to be her sister\'s mom. The third lady says he\'s not going to have to eat any food, because he\'ll get to be the first lady\'s son. She says that little sister will be her mother\'s first lady, too. The fourth lady says the gang will be at the festival, and she says that they\'re going to play a song called \"melobarre,\" which means \"to barre,\" or \"to eat.\n\n\" The song says that the gang is going straight into the festival because it\'s the same song they\'ve been playing all day. The lyrics are a little weird. They say that they don\'t really know what the song is, but they\'d like to be able to play it if they were in it. They\'re not sure if they\'ll',NULL,NULL),(62196,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 20, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 07:26:00',NULL,'This is the reason why I\'m here. This is why I am here. I\'ve been told that I\'ll be a grandpa, and this is the story of all the stories. It is a big one, and I\'d like to be a grandfather, too. I want to go to the city of skiring. This city is called Nantillan. It seems like it\'s about to become a giant city, and Rudolph is psyched to be there. He doesn\'t really know what to say, but he\'s psyched to find out.',NULL,NULL),(62197,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 20, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 05:13:14',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the music that is playing at the festival. It\'s the music of Kelly Loader, Leif Volbeck, and the Birds of the Bellwoods. The music is from the new and never show that\'s on the air on Tuesday nights. The show ends with some information about volunteer opportunities that are available at the station. If you\'re interested in being a part of the community, come and listen to the show. The station will support your efforts.',NULL,NULL),(62198,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/20/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 20, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-20 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 04:55:43',NULL,'This program is part of a special edition of the Tuesday Night Show, hosted by Hoad Reddick. The program is a celebration of the Riverfest in Elora, a festival that takes place in and around Guelph every October. The show features music, food, and a variety of other entertainments. Reddick and his guests discuss the festival and the various activities taking place on it. They discuss the latest music from Shibaad, who is one of the festival favorites. They talk about the river festival and how beautiful it is, and then Reddick tosses a life-boat into the water.',NULL,NULL),(62199,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-21 04:37:25',NULL,'In this one-hour special, the \"music\" team at 93.3 FM tells the story of the festival they\'re putting on in Minneapolis. They\'ve been getting rave reviews from the crowds, and they\'ve even gotten word that Kelly Loader is coming to town to play tomorrow.\n\nThey play a little bit of music from the main stage, then they play a song from Bolson\'s \"My Ways,\" and then they head over to the Twist section to play some more from Metric. Then they head back over to \"the main stage\" to play more music from Adam Baldwin. They also play a few songs from Tock, who\'s been tearing up the stage. The crowd has really gotten into the festival, so they want to keep it going. Then, they head to \"Kelly Loader\" to tell her about her upcoming gig.',NULL,NULL),(62200,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 04:15:02',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with DJ Double D, the host of CFRU\'S Light FM. The first part of the interview takes place on the day of the Elora riverfest, and the second portion takes place during the week of August 7-8. In the first part, Double D describes his show, which is a community radio show that plays music from all over the world.\n\nThe second part takes place at the end of the second half of the same interview. The program starts with Feist\'s latest album, \"Of Woman Con.\" In the third part, the program describes how meta products like Facebook and Instagram have begun blocking Canadian news content. Because of the response to the anti-terrorism bill, Canadians no longer have access to the news content on these platforms.',NULL,NULL),(62201,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 03:09:22',NULL,'The crew returns to their live music and talks about the upcoming festival. They\'re starting getting lots of people coming to the festival, but there\'s still a lot of work to be done. So, they\'re going to give the festival-goers some of that Soka vibe tonight. If you guys want to link up with them, we\'d love to hear from you.',NULL,NULL),(62202,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 02:49:05',NULL,'This is the first time we have heard of the underground music scene in New York City. The underground scene has been described as a \"cool little vibe\" with a \"lot of different cool vibes.\n\n\" It\'s the very first time that we\'ve heard of underground music happening in NYC. Here\'s what the host has to say about it: \"We\'re right here with a lot of cool little vibes.\" The host is talking about the upcoming spotlight show at Royal City Studios, which will feature artists including Black Orchid, Phineak, and others. He\'s psyched to be a part of it.',NULL,NULL),(62203,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-19 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 02:31:08',NULL,'In this program, we catch up with the host of the local CFRU-FM program, Scenes Like Old Time, who\'s been on the air for over 25 years. He\'s a great listener and host, and he\'s got a lot to say. He tells us that the program offers features and community announcements on subjects that they feel would be of benefit to listeners, and each week they broadcast old radio programs, from the 1930\'s to the 50\'s, with music memories. If we\'ve heard anything about you, we\'ll hear about it. The program also has a job opening for a Campus Outreach Assistant.\n\nThe job is for someone who loves to ask questions, and the Campus Outreach Association has over 100 clubs and they need someone to talk to and record their events. This position starts September and pays $20 per hour. The deadline to apply is August 30th, 5pm. Sounds like a great opportunity. Check out the art galleries and check out what they\'re up to this summer on the CFRU 98.3FM. Art Gallery Of Guelph has three shows on display from now until the end of September, including a show called Worry Territories, Amateurs And Imaginearies, and Jose Luis Torres Temporary Territories. Head over to the Art Gallery\'s Facebook page for more info.',NULL,NULL),(62204,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/18/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 18, 2019 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-18 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 02:12:32',NULL,'The host discusses the show, which was about a trans woman who performed as an Indian woman. The show was a success, and the host is glad to hear about the trans woman\'s experiences.\n\nHe finds it refreshing to hear a person talk about politics instead of the news that he or she is used to hearing. He also finds it interesting that the show was about diversity, which is a token word used to denote a person\'s worth in society. He thinks that it makes a lot of sense, and he\'s happy to be educated on it. After they\'ve discussed the Trans Woman and the Indian Woman, they listen to Grateful by 2ataTCH from the Angry Angry duo.\n\nThey also listen to a band called Download with a song called \"The Flight Of Luminous Insects\". The Underground Men decide to play a few tracks from Animal Collective, a band that used to be called Avi Terre Panda Bear Geologist. They play a track called \"Dance Manatee\" from their second album, which they call \"probably the most loathe recorded in their discography\".',NULL,NULL),(62205,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/18/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 18, 2019 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-18 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 01:51:49',NULL,'The host is on stage at the Riverfest in Guelph, Canada. He tells Jack that he owes him, but he\'ll be back soon. He says they\'ll find Charlie, and that they can tell him that they\'ve learned a lot in their time together.\n\nThe two of them will tell Charlie that he doesn\'t have to die by exposure by the railway tracks, and they\'re going to tell him about how he filled their collective hallucination with his spirit. Jack says that when he first met Charlie, he thought he was crazy, but now he wonders if he\'s not that crazy one. He\'ll tell the story to Charlie even if he can\'t see it. He wishes the people who ran the school had never done what they did to him.\n\nHe feels that they stamped the world with their actions before he left it. Jack thanks the listeners for listening to him, and thanks everyone for taking his calls. He promises to see Charlie three minutes later. Andrea and Troy are on stage talking about the day\'s entertainment. They\'re talking about Hubert, who\'s playing at the festival. They say that everyone they know is psyched to see Hubert. Andrea says that he was the act that they most talked about in their conversation. They also talk about Begonia, Lady in my Mind, and Tribe Called Red, which are all playing at Riverfest that night. Troy says that the stage is loud and they can hear the music',NULL,NULL),(62206,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/18/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 18, 2019 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-18 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 01:30:55',NULL,'In this episode of the show, Chelsea plays some music from Riverfest, including some from bands that have played in the past at the festival. He also plays some songs from the CD of another Riverfest alumnus, Land of Talk, and a song from the album of a band called Highness. The band is based out of the town of Kitchener, and they play on the main stage. They also play some songs off their EP, River, which is a little different from the other songs they have played.',NULL,NULL),(62207,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/18/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 18, 2019 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-18 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 01:10:34',NULL,'The students of the University of Guelph are being threatened with a \"Student Choice Initiative\" that would force them to support a single set of services on campus instead of multiple ones. This would rob students of their right to choose what services they support and would threaten the autonomy of their campus organizations.\n\nStudents already voted in favor of these services through the democratic process, and the initiative will only increase the power of the student body. Instead of students choosing which services to support, they will have to gamble their money on these services, not knowing what they will get back in return. Students can contact their local MPP and ask him or her to stop the initiative before it is too late. The university also has a daily show called \"Stillness and Dancing\" on 93.3 FM that has a quiet, ambient air.\n\nIf you need to get your band out of there, they have a studio in town that can take your music. Unlimited student summer passes are now available for $99 or $199. The studio is near Riverfest. Chelsea, the host of the show, tells us that he\'s going to be broadcasting live from there until 6pm tonight. He says that he thought he\'d do something different from his usual show. He\'s broadcasting from there so that people who\'ve already played at the festival will be able to hear them. He also says that Hubert Lemois will be performing on the festival main stage at 4pm.',NULL,NULL),(62208,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/17/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 17, 2019 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-17 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 00:51:37',NULL,'The Kazoo Fest Programmer discusses the various stages and acts at the festival with the audience. He says that he\'s not always able to keep track of the time of the performances, but that he does know that they\'re playing on the main stage. The first band he talks about is Red, an Indigenous group who write important music. He also mentions the Sheepdogs, who were supposed to be the main attraction for the festival but ended up saving the day when they were unable to make it to the festival.\n\nThe festival is happening at 3pm, so the Kazoo guys will be playing music. The Darcys are playing at the main festival stage, and they\'ll be there for the first time. The next band he plays is a song called \"Tarot Cards\" from Lioness, a band that performs spiritual music. This song is very spiritual, and the lyrics are very poetic. The DJ says he hasn\'t heard the song before, but it sounds really cool. Before that, he played Dennis Ellsworth with \"Absent Mind Off of Things Change\" and B.A Johnson with \"I Don\'tUse Self Service Machines Off of the Skid\" .\n\nHe is one of his favorite live musicians, and he plays the funniest sets he can. So the DJ asks the audience to come see him. He\'ll also be performing at the after-party tonight at the cafe, so if you want to catch him that night, you should definitely go.',NULL,NULL),(62209,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/17/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 17, 2019 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-17 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 00:28:54',NULL,'This is a special edition of Andrea and her crew\'s show on the CFRU 93.1FM in Guelph. They\'re broadcasting live from the Riverfest festival in Elora, and they\'re talking about the music and what\'s going on. They have a special section where they\'ll be talking about all the different stages and artists that are playing. The first show of the show is called \"The Dual Plymotomy\" and it basically starts off by saying that it\'s cold and rainy, but it seems like Mother Nature is having some fun with it today.\n\nThen they go on to talk about some of the other great music acts at the festival, including Heinis, Ben Rogers, City and Color, and Done Alone. They also talk about the fact that Ben Rogers is set to play the main stage tonight. And then they play a little bit about how they\'ve been at Riverfest in the past and what they\'d like to know about it.',NULL,NULL),(62210,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/08/17/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 17, 2019 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-08-17 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 23:06:08',NULL,'The program opens with the news that it\'s been a beautiful sunny day. They\'ve been listening to all kinds of music, including the latest releases from Nicolette, The Nobodies, and Tribe Called Red, as well as some new songs from Terra Lightfoot and her band, the mighty Bostones. The program ends with a little announcement about the upcoming Riverfest, which will take place on the Grand River in Grand Rapids.',NULL,NULL),(62211,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2018 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-19 17:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 22:47:06',NULL,'The second half of the show starts off with a song by a Canadian artist called Army. The song is followed by a song called Want From Me by another Canadian artist named Javier Mighty. The third song is by Kuff The Duke, the artist who wrote Surging Revival, followed by the song Open Road by Roland Cross.\n\nThe fourth track is by Laid Broadcasting Deluxees, who is on the main stage. The fifth track is called Call it Ritual by a German artist named Wolf Parade. The sixth track is Dirty Windshields by Lee Roy Stagger. The seventh track is from the band Blue Rodeo, the eighth is from their album Trust Yourself. The ninth track is the song Homeboy by a band called Caveboy. The tenth is from Born Ruffians, who wrote Never Age by their album Birthmark.',NULL,NULL),(62212,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2018 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-19 16:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 22:33:07',NULL,'The host is back at Riverfest with Dylan, another musician. He\'s been having a good time. He says it\'s so nice to be surrounded by people who are having fun. He also says that he\'d never be able to enjoy a festival like this if it rained. But he\'s happy about it. He tells Dylan that he played at the festival the day before. That was cool, too. The Flaming Lips were right by the host\'s stage, so they watched him. Dylan says it was cool because everyone was there.\n\nHe plays all original music. The festival is chill and family-friendly, according to Dylan. Dylan also tells us that he used to be in a band with Feist and Broken Social Scene called Bi- Divine Right. Then he was in another band with another friend named Brian. Brian also tells the story of his band.',NULL,NULL),(62213,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2018 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-19 15:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 22:10:44',NULL,'In this program, Kim Loeg, the host of CFRU\'s Conversations Worth Having, and Chelsea, the co-host of the program, discuss music from the Riverfest festival in Elora, as well as the upcoming Ed Video festival in Guelph. The first program is devoted to discussing music from a band called Caveboy, who are playing a song called \"New Survival\" from their self titled album. The second program discusses music from Elevator, a band from Atlanta who are also playing. The third program is dedicated to discussing the music from Atlanta, which is playing on a stage called \"Wax on Wheels.\"',NULL,NULL),(62214,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2018 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-19 14:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 21:51:21',NULL,'The CFRU Live at the River Festival will take place at Market Square on Friday and Saturday, September 14 and 15. The two-day festival will include live performances from eight diverse acts, including DJ Shub Toronto, Surefire Sweat, and the Jason Robassotet.\n\nIf you\'re a friend of the university but haven\'t yet purchased a Friends of the University card, you can get discounts at 14 local businesses with your card. One of those businesses is Sweat, a retro candy shop that\'s just across the street from Market Square. The card is valid through January of next year. This year, the card will be valid until January of 2019. Augusta is Charlotte, and she\'s on the show to announce that the university is broadcasting live from the Riverfest in allura.\n\nShe\'s a big fan of the band Trash Wolf Parade. She tells the audience that she went to see them play, but she\'ll be happy to hear anything from Apologies To The Queen Mary. She also tells them that they\'re playing tonight at the main stage at the festival. She gives us a shout-out to the band, which is called Weaves, and says they\'ll play a song called Stress Hula Hoop off of their self titled LP.',NULL,NULL),(62215,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2018 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-19 13:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 21:10:13',NULL,'The host of the Clan-the-Gan-Lammer, Michael Murphy, chats with a young man named Chelsea who has come to Riverfest to see some of the local bands. The man and his wife have been living in the area for five years and have been to the festival every year since they moved to the city.\n\nThey\'ve seen a lot of bands at the festival and are looking forward to seeing more. The couple is looking for some food, so they get the food card for free. The young man is psyched to find out that he\'s a friend of the university and needs to buy a card to get discounts at local businesses. The card is good for a year and can be used to support both the university\'s campus and community station.',NULL,NULL),(62216,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/19/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 19, 2018 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-19 12:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 20:49:14',NULL,'This is the second of two Live broadcasts from Riverfest, hosted by McDee. He welcomes listeners to the festival and encourages them to come by and listen to the live broadcasts. He also tells listeners about the upcoming International Institute for Improvisation and Guelph Jazz Festival\'s Colloquium, which will take place from September 12 th to 15 th . McDee then goes on to announce that he will be broadcasting live from Laura\'s house on the way to the university. He then announces that there are people walking by who ignore him.',NULL,NULL),(62217,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/18/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 18, 2018 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-18 17:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 20:30:32',NULL,'The guys are listening to music at the festival. The first thing they listen to is a song called \"Born Ruffians,\" which is a folk song from New York City. They also listen to Dylan\'s first solo album, \"The Dill,\" which has 52 songs on it. They hear a group called \"Sorority,\" which sounds like it\'s playing an instrumental instrument, and then they hear \"Stalagmites,\" an album by a Brooklyn band called \"Brooklyn New York.\n\n\" They also hear \"Death at My Door,\" a song from the band Creep Show. The guys like the music so much that they\'re psyched to hear the band play. They heard \"Sticks and Stones,\" \"Blood Blood Blood,\" \"Tomorrow Never Comes,\" \"Another Way Out,\" and \"One Foot in a Grave.\" They hear \"Donovan Woods,\" which they\'ll listen to later on.',NULL,NULL),(62218,2778,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/08/18/CFRU Live from Riverfest Elora! - August 18, 2018 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-08-18 16:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-20 19:12:19',NULL,'The 30th Annual Eden Mills Writers Fest is taking place from September 7 to 9. This event will bring some of the finest and emerging Canadian writers to the village. The festival kicks off Friday with a celebration with a 30th year anniversary celebration and this Saturday will feature a conversation with Arden as she discusses her story and the inspiration behind the memoirs as she takes writing workshops with Craig and Sheila Hetty.\n\nOn Sunday, there will be an afternoon of authors readings along the Aramassa river featuring more than forty authors including Edouguien , Rahwee Heage ,Sheila Hetty , Thomas King ,Dennis Lee ,Madeline Theon and much more. For tickets and more info, visit eden-millswritersfest.ca. The show is hosted by Eclipse and the show\'s host, Devere, is followed by Planet Groove. The two discuss a few of the bands that will be playing at the festival, including Love Wagon, who are playing funk rock, and Bonnie Trash, who will play the second release of their sophomore album Azalinis dead. They also discuss two songs that they recently heard from their new album. The first song is \"Unbuffed Sheep and True Love Eat Me\" and the second is \"Eclipse\" from You Got it Baby. They say that they\'ll be checking them out again tomorrow.',NULL,NULL),(62220,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/vtiqgw/DrMouth_CIUTshow_aug22_2022_fullshow.mp3','2023-08-23 18:22:35',284970368,'2023-12-20 18:55:10',NULL,'The narrator thanks listeners for their support of the station during its fall campaign. He encourages listeners to visit the station\'s Web site and give generously to reach its goal of $100K.\n\nThe narrator then launches into his own program. He is joined by Dr. Mouth and his band, who play some of their favorite rock and roll songs. The program ends with the opening set by the singer-songwriter, James Brown. He plays some of his favorite songs from his collection of music. The first song he plays is from the new album by Dan Walsh, a musician from Southwestern Ontario who has been playing all over the country. The song is called \"The Booker\" and the narrator thinks that it might be the last track on the new record. He also mentions that the banker who heard this track loved the sound of this track too. The doctor is also a big fan of Dan\'s band, which he describes as one man band with loops in it. He says that if you are in the area tomorrow, you can check out the singer at bentbeards.com and his website. The man is also one of the hard working musicians he knows. He has a new album out called The Booker.\n\nHe loves that instrumental on the album. The next song the narrator plays is a song from Footstomp by Jet Harris, Tony Meehan, and the British Ventures, who were members of a band called Polaris. They were supposed to start a band together, but Jet Harris was',NULL,NULL),(62221,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hrez39/August_23_2023_Global_Rhythmsb8tkq.mp3','2023-08-23 14:02:40',431961989,'2023-12-20 18:27:10',NULL,'In this brief introduction, Ken Stower introduces the listeners to the program GlobalRhythms, which airs each morning on the U of T\'s community radio station. The program is produced by Ken Stowar and features live music from all over the world. The listeners can listen to the entire program and receive a copy after the program\'s end. To do so, simply go to the station\'s home page, scroll down, and then click on the program tab. There, you\'ll find the link to the show and the playlist. If you want to hear the program right away, just send Ken an email with the link and he\'ll send you a copy.',NULL,NULL),(62224,171,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/9cm6aa/second_to_the_right_aug_21_23_with_clips9gkop.mp3','2023-08-24 01:32:32',233184904,'2023-12-20 17:05:05',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62231,217,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/mgdzmq/CIUTAug22.mp3','2023-08-23 02:59:43',143961989,'2023-12-20 16:51:00',NULL,'The Spring Club is a series of community-centered arts events taking place in Toronto. These include a Pan African Film Festival, a reggae festival, a youth festival, and much more, all organized by the city\'s cultural hotspot. This year\'s festival will take place in Little Jamaica, which is part of the city of Toronto. It\'s a great opportunity to meet new people and learn more about the city and its arts community. The festival will include music, dance, and theater performances.',NULL,NULL),(62232,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/CFRU Playlist - August 22, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-24 02:48:56',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62233,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/21/Back in the USSR - August 21, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-21 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 16:31:41',NULL,'CFRU begins the program by introducing the listeners to Professor Michael Parente\'s talk on the U. S. war on Yugoslavia. The talk deals with the history of the war and how it is viewed by the West. It deals with how the United States destroyed Yugoslavia in the Cold War and how this destruction has implications for the current situation in Africa and the Middle East.',NULL,NULL),(62234,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Bridging The Social Distance - August 22, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 15:13:01',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with Dave Grennan of the band, Joyful Joyful, and Jenny Mitchell, the host of the show. The first part of the interview is about the band and their self-titled debut album. The second part is about Dave\'s and Cormac\'s history with the band.',NULL,NULL),(62235,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 23, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 14:50:17',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62236,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 22, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 14:25:35',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62237,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Tuesday at 5 - August 22, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 14:10:19',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the show starts off with Mac Dee hosting this hour of the program. He welcomes everyone to the show and asks them to join him in the house for some tea and dancing. He also asks if anyone would like to stream the show from CFRU\'s archives. Mac tells us that he\'s been working on the program as a group, so he hopes to entertain the listeners.\n\nHe starts off the program by talking about the Three Sisters, the three main crops of various Native American peoples. The three crops are corn, climbing beans, and squash. The corn is planted between the three crops, and the beans fix nitrogen and fix the root nodules. The squash is a shade plant, which keeps the soil moist. The individual plants and their cultivation origin in Mesoamerica, where squash was first domesticated. New music from William Prince and Bruce Coburn. Stephen Fearing, Colin went down to the water on true north records, and The Northern Pikes.',NULL,NULL),(62238,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Let’s Get Lost - August 22, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 13:46:55',NULL,'The program starts off with music from a new album called Banana Cannon by Lena Alimento. After that, they\'ll continue on to some more music.\n\nThey\'ve got a couple more albums to play and then they\'re getting ready to play Milton Graves\'s music. The program ends with news about the upcoming Eden Mills Writers\' Festival. It\'s going to take place on September 10th. Here\'s the link to the festival\'s website: http://www.emwf.ca/ The festival will feature 40 authors from across the country.\n\nFor more details about the festival, please visit the festival website. You can also tune in to the program on CFRU.com. This evening, the program begins with Panteo\'s new album. They have a new track called Pagdaloi, followed by Ash Walker, DJ Peanuts, E. B. Soda, Classic Orchestra, and Linda Kaitlin Smith. The Paramorph Collective\'s album is out, too.',NULL,NULL),(62239,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Let’s Get Lost - August 22, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 13:07:08',NULL,'Scott\'s name is Scott and he\'s the host of the new release program called \"Let\'s get lost\" on CFRU\'s public radio station. He and his crew listen to new releases and decide what they\'d like to play for the listeners. They start with a band called High Pulp, who have a new album called Days in the desert.\n\nThey\'ve invited some of their friends on the album to play on it, including Jeff Parker, Brandi Younger, and James Brandon Lewis. This is a band that\'s been around for a long time. The band has invited a bunch of famous friends on their new album. They also have a track called \"Dirt mouth\" on the new album, which they think is pretty good. Scott also mentions a couple of new releases by Beverly Glenn Copeland, who lives in Toronto.\n\nThis one is called \"The Ones ahead\" and has been out for 20 years. This album is also called \"Elephantine\" and is a little older than \"Mansion Moonshine\" . We\'ve also heard a track from Shabaka titled \"Ital is Vital\" and a new track from Tony Allen called \"Ebun\" , which has been waiting for a while. The program ends with a live performance by Lina Alimento, who\'s part of the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival.',NULL,NULL),(62240,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Humanoid Radio - August 22, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 12:46:19',NULL,'This week on Humanoid Radio we have a bunch of new music. The first track is African Head Charge\'s \"Asala Tua\" off their album \"A Trip to Bultanga\". This is followed by Ikiti Sounds off Drum Money, a piece called Mama Wata, \"Groundation Damage\" off the album \"Dreaming from an Iron gate\", \"Castle If\" off of the release \"Exotic Sounds\", and \"Asta Hiroki\" off \"Of Seeing Anything\" . The second track is \"A Golden Vision\" off Of Seeing Anything, and the third track is a \"Divertimento\" from the \"Metamorphosis\" album by Archer and the Saxophone Quartet. This is the last music we\'re going to hear on this program. We\'',NULL,NULL),(62241,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - August 22, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 12:28:48',NULL,'In this episode, we find out more about CFRU\'s community outreach program. They\'re looking to hire people to help out at local festivals, concerts, and other community events. We also learn that they\'re hiring people to produce short scripts for public service announcements and advertisements. So if you\'re interested in community outreach, CFRU has you covered. You can host your own program or podcast, help produce live events, or even help with engineering or production on our YouTube live streams.',NULL,NULL),(62242,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/Wild Combination - August 23, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 12:08:13',NULL,'The host continues his conversation with the host about love. He says that living in a \"culture of domination\" is a heroic thing to do. He compares loving to being in a war zone, a place where you don\'t have a choice but to do what you\'re told to do, whether it\'s to kill your enemies or to be a good soldier. He also notes that it is very possible that Earth will perish. If you are 5 to 65 years old, you can participate in a research team that wants to know how you and your peers experience disruptions and how they shape the world.',NULL,NULL),(62243,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 23, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 11:48:49',NULL,'The second hour of the show starts with a long form piece, a track called \"We Said We Trad a Year\" for one more afternoon. It\'s a track by a guy named Rick Johnson, who\'s been putting out new music on Bandcamp. He\'s always putting out great music. The first hour starts off with a new release from White Lab, called \"Waiting for Something To Break\" .\n\nThen there\'s some experimental music from our friends Carlo and Giustini, and finally new music from Mikos de La Recesistance, who just released his latest release called \"Last Night I Found my Shadow Crying\" , which is kind of a moody, eerie piano piece. Finally, we hear a track from another friend named John Cage, \"All Watched Over By Machines of LovingGrace,\" which sounds like it\'s going to be a nod to the guy. The show ends with a little cat talk, and then we get back to the music.',NULL,'The first track is from a guy who\'s putting out new music on Bandcamp'),(62244,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 23, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 11:28:18',NULL,'The host welcomes us back to the show and tells us that he\'s just returned from his first week of vacation, which was a little bit of a whirlwind.\n\nHe had a lot of things to do, like go on a tour of the nickel mine, but also went on a boat tour, took a tour, and went to the rail museum. He\'s a little boy, but he loves to go on tour. He finishes most of his schoolwork and then goes home to Montreal to see his family. The weather report, the personal report, and the music report. In music, we start off with a song called Ash by the singer/songwriter, Mia Gargarett.',NULL,'A new episode of the show, here in the stillness in the dancing'),(62245,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - August 23, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 11:12:08',NULL,'The two students are graduate students. They don\'t really know what they\'re doing, but they know that they want to listen to this program. The students are Serge, a graduate student at Laurentian and the creator of the Polychlorinated Biphenyls, and Owen, a student at the University of the Guelph. Serge tells Owen that he started his undergraduate studies in environmental science, but then decided that he wanted to study water.\n\nAs he was getting closer to his fourth year, he decided to go into the field of wastewater treatment. So he found his way to the university and was looking for someone to do water treatment. He ended up doing research on electrochemistry. He\'s studying electrochemistry for hydroponics, which involves using special metals such as rare earth elements to produce electricity.',NULL,NULL),(62246,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/End Credits - August 23, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 10:51:59',NULL,'This is the first episode of End Credits, a local talk show hosted by Adam Donaldson and Peter Wesley Salmon on the campus of the University of Guelph. The two men discuss the state of the Canadian economy and the importance of technology in the country. They also discuss the latest Canadian movies, such as the highly anticipated Blackberry.',NULL,NULL),(62247,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/B Siide Radio - August 23, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 10:24:55',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62248,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/Trail Mix - August 23, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 10:13:31',NULL,'The host returns to the host\'s weekly Wednesday night music program, which he calls \"Eternal Rhythm,\" to introduce listeners to new music. The program opens with a shout-out to the underground music scene in Canada and to the people who have been listening to the program. He also thanks the listeners for their continued support. The show begins with a discussion of the music that has been released in the past few weeks.\n\nThe Underground Men begin with the music of a Vancouver artist named Hazy, who has released two albums. The first is a song called \"Hear,\" which was released on a club called Agni Club Records in May. The second is an improvised song by a band called \"Ricardo Cometa,\" which has released a second album in June. The third is an acoustic song by New Fries. The song he\'s going to play is called \"More,\" which is from a 10-inch vinyl record. The fourth is an original song by \"90-year-old girl,\" which came out two years ago.',NULL,NULL),(62249,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/Tone Zone - August 23, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 09:48:54',NULL,'The show opens with a discussion of the recent news about the reunion of the Crack-Cloud Collective and the Vancouver band Stop Making Sense, which have both recently released new albums.\n\nThe first song from the new reissue is called Novel, which is an offshoot from a band called the Vancouver Band. The second song is called Untouchable, which sounds like it\'s a song from a new album called The Nonfiction. The third song is Dance and Slippery when wet from the 1980 Dance for your Dinner. The fourth song is Talking Heads \"Burning down the house\" from the Deluxe edition of the Stop-Making-Sense. The fifth song is \"The Dance\" from \"Dance for Your Dinner.\" The sixth song is The Dance and \"Slippery When wet\" from their 1981 Dance for Your dinner. The seventh song is Untouchables from their 2021 Nonfiction album. The eighth song is Talk to me Baby from the New York Dolls \"Dancing Backward in high heels.\" The ninth song is Divinals from \"Desperate.\" The tenth song is Boys in town from \"1983 debut album.\"',NULL,NULL),(62250,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/Radia - August 23, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 09:15:03',NULL,'The first part of the show is a production by the creative students of the university of Saragota, the country in the south of Venezuela, who have been invited to participate in a week-long music making competition. The challenge is to create a radio program that works across all of Europe. The students must also create a piece of music that relates to the theme of the week\'s competition, and they must also present it to the audience at the end of the program.\n\nThe program is presented in a series of short and very animated scenes, each with its own set of lyrics. First, the audience is introduced to the students, who are described as being from the country where the competition is taking place. They are described in terms that are familiar to listeners of the school, and the students express their enthusiasm for the challenge.',NULL,NULL),(62251,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - August 22, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 08:48:45',NULL,'The show opens with a song from Blind Love\'s \"Slice of Peace,\" followed by a song by The Spiders from their \"Split Album,\" a song called \"Tayo nosa\" from The \"Spiders Meets the Savage\" , Pat Coria from his \"Belt C-O R-I-a.,\" an EP from Digit 1 from his 2020 single \"Salama,\" and an EP by Lotus Child from his 2006 album \"Gossip Diet.\" The program then shifts to Kate Bush, who has just released her third live album, \"Before the Dawn.\" The album contains two live shows, one in London in 2014 and one in New York in 2015.',NULL,NULL),(62252,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Rainbow Country - August 22, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 08:27:37',NULL,'In this two-hour special, the host of the popular music show \"Rainbow Country\" introduces himself as \"LGBT Cop,\" also known as \"Danielle Botno.\" He explains that the show is all about music from the \"LGBT community,\" and that he\'s bringing listeners classic disco, 80s house, and 80s new romantic tracks. He ends the show with a shout-out to his listeners, saying that they\'re living in \"days of making dreams happen.\"',NULL,NULL),(62253,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Rainbow Country - August 22, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 07:22:53',NULL,'This is the first episode of a new show called \"Rainbow Country,\" hosted by Mark Tara and produced by Emily Saliers, who is also known as the \"B-Girls\" from the show \"Indigo Girls.\" The show airs every day on CIU-FM and is available in syndication on twelve outlets across Canada.',NULL,NULL),(62254,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/23/Democracy Now - August 23, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-23 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-20 06:56:02',NULL,'In this program, Fareed Zakaria continues his investigation into the role of religion in the United States. He looks at the recent history of the Crusades, focusing on the persecution of Christians in France and the Crusade of Jerusalem. He also examines the recent political developments in the Middle East, particularly Israel\'s role in the civil war in Syria and the recent violence in Egypt. He concludes by outlining the political, economic, and social factors that have driven the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood.',NULL,NULL),(62256,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/22/Democracy Now - August 22, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-22 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-20 06:14:26',NULL,'Donald Trump is set to go to court in Atlanta for his arrest and mugshot. The president will be released on bond, but many people in the city can\'t afford it. We\'re also going to hear from George Chitty, a reporter from Atlanta who was subpoenad to testify to a grand jury about how fake electors were thrown out of the country. And then we\'re going to talk about the coming BRICS summit in South Africa. The world is facing fundamental challenges that will determine 