responsible for the club meetings, reporting to the Director of Student Affairs. The position pays $20 an hourly hour and is available for undergraduate, graduate or international students from the university. Also on the show, Thebe is joined by Jerry Leger, who is looking for work. He has two lines open in the city of Columbia, Illinois.',NULL,NULL),(62292,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Wild Combination - August 24, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 16:06:47',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62293,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Here Today - August 24, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 15:52:03',NULL,'Aaron Badgley welcomes his listeners to the show and introduces himself as the host of Here Today. He\'s a regular on the CFRU 98.3FM show, where he\'s been playing music by rubbing from the band Warm Smiles\' most recent album. The band\'s name is \"Heavy Puka\" and they\'re from Winnipeg, Manitoba.\n\nThey\'ve got an album called \"A Kind of You\" that\'s the first single out. The track \"The Jimmy Jam\" is off the new album by the band and it\'s produced by the awesome Mo Berg. Aaron also introduces Rob Stewart, a member of the band \"Slave To The Square Wave\" who is also on the James Clark project. Rob is in the band called \"That\'s Church Of Trees\" and he\'ll be playing with the band in September in Toronto.\n\nAaron is psyched to hear all these new artists and he plays a bunch of old songs. He plays a song from \"The Forgotten Heart\" by the artist Debra Fajalkov, a song by \"Witching Time\" by Paul McCartney, and a song called \"Egypt Station And Do It Now\" by \"Paul McCartney\" .',NULL,NULL),(62294,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Tales from the Bridge - August 24, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 15:11:30',NULL,'In this episode, the host and his guests discuss Hugh Howey\'s latest guest, Kate Elliott. The show encourages listeners to rate the show, to tell a friend about it, and to check out the list of guests. They invite you to join them at the bridge, where they\'ll be talking to Hugh. He\'s a science fiction author who\'s published several successful works of fiction as serial narratives. He also has two television shows, one based on his novels, and one about his work as a self-published author.',NULL,NULL),(62295,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/FoodFarm Talk - August 24, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 14:47:04',NULL,'In this episode of FoodFarm Talk, Paul Smith and Stuart Wright discuss the work of the Sullen Crop improvement association and how they promote adoption of sustainability practices. The organization is a large network of farmers, scientists, and other professionals who work together to develop and promote innovative farming practices. They are all members of the \"innovation and diffusion\" system, which is a process of getting farmers to adopt new practices and then spreading them out to other farmers. Paul will also be talking to Stewart about how he manages his farm to improve soil and water quality.',NULL,NULL),(62296,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Android’s Dungeon - August 24, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 14:32:14',NULL,'In this show, we\'ll take a break from the usual monotony of the host\'s daily schedule to discuss some of the things he\'s been up to. This time, however, it\'s about the weather. The host admits that the fall is the best season of the year.\n\nHe explains that if you disagree with him, you\'re wrong. He\'s not saying that he wants to get frozen, but he doesn\'t like the deep freezes, the cold, and the Polar Vortexes. He hates the way the seasons change. So, he says, they\'ll split the show up into two parts: one for the game, the other for the music. As they\'re talking, we hear a track by Mount Shrine, who\'s a favorite of host. The track is called \"Beyond the Gates\" and sounds like a mix of Mount Shrine\'s \"Dream Chambers\" and \"Alfaxone\" . We\'ll hear more about it later.',NULL,NULL),(62297,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/RadiOPIRG - August 24, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 14:11:17',NULL,'It\'s been three years since the Wetsawiten First Nation evicted the T.P Energy from their land, but they\'re still fighting to protect their traditional territory from a proposed natural gas pipeline.\n\nThe First Nation points out that Canada doesn\'t have authority to approve any pipeline through their territory, and the Canadian courts and the RCMP have no authority to arrest land defenders. If the pipeline is built, it\'ll bring fracked gas from the West to the LNG export facility in Canada, which will make it one of the largest gas-export projects in the world in the first phase of its operation. The Coastal Gas Link pipeline, the other route through the Yintsiwaten territory, crosses 625 rivers and T. P. Energy already warned 51 times about potential violations of land rights.',NULL,NULL),(62298,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/T.K.O. - August 24, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 13:51:31',NULL,'The show is back and the narrator is happy to be home. She misses the show so much she had to go to California to visit family.\n\nShe\'s back stronger and more confident than ever. She says she used to have a set of quality assurance headphones that she would use to record the show, but now she can\'t use them because she\'s traveling. She hopes the show is coming across as good as it can. She goes on to say that it\'s very important to get some sleep and rest because it helps you not burn out.',NULL,NULL),(62299,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Open Sources Guelph - August 24, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 20:29:33',NULL,'The program opens with a long speech about the dangers of climate change. It then turns to a discussion of social media training. The program goes on to discuss the recent wildfires in the United States and Canada, and the Canadian government\'s plan to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 2045. Gollum says that the Alberta government is going to fight the federal government, but that it\'s important to note that the Canadian oil and gas industry is very dependent on Alberta for their power. The Canadian government has also announced a seven-month moratorium on all new energy projects. Gollum doesn\'t think that this is a good move, as it would be like shutting down a windmill. He also points out that some anti-carbon tax rallies have also had to be cancelled because of the recent Canadian wildfires.',NULL,'The Wildfires in the U.S. and Canada are the real threat of climate change'),(62300,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Turtle Island Underground - August 24, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 13:09:48',NULL,'This week\'s program starts off with some new music from the Turtle Island Underground program, which is hosted by Mac. The show is described as straightforward, with a mix of tracks from different artists. The first track is from Cheshire Cat, an indie bedroom pop by Ashnathani.\n\nThe second is from Rivers from Zune, an album by Dan Monkman. The third is from Red River, a post-rock record by Andrew McCloud and Michael Peter Olsen. The fourth track from Robbie Robertson is Sweet Fire Love, a throwback from his self-titled debut. The fifth track from Wayfinding is Edzi U, a concept release by Potlatch. The sixth track from Tinge is called The Wayfinding Song. The seventh track from Russell Wallace is called Owl Mountain. The eighth track from James and I is called Panda Village Up-Squad, a song written by James and myself. The song is about the fact that we have the power to take away the power of others.',NULL,NULL),(62301,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/The Crooked Beat - August 24, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 12:46:43',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62302,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/The Crooked Beat - August 24, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 12:27:31',NULL,'In this two-hour program, we hear from a variety of artists, including a jazz band from London, an all-star ska orchestra from Los Angeles, a new song from Marcia Griffiths and a new one from Taj Weeks, all from his latest album, \"Ska Style.\" We also hear from Zenith, a band from Australia, and some tracks from Bob Marley, including \"City Style.\"',NULL,NULL),(62303,123,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Thanks for Listening :) - August 25, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 12:07:51',NULL,'The guys check in on the new music scene with a shout-out to Jesse Lanza and her new album, \"Don\'t Cry On My Pillow,\" and to a few other artists. Then they hear \"Jungle\" and \"I\'ve Been in Love\" from the same artist\'s latest album. The guys are psyched to hear the music again, since it\'s been a while since they\'ve heard any new music from the likes of Jesse Lanza, Noah Cyrus, and Kim Mortal.\n\nAfter that, we hear \"One More Name\" from Shane Ghostkeeper\'s new album \"Songs for My People,\" which means he\'s got a solo album out. Then we hear a couple of songs from the new albums of Beverly Glen Harbor and Ray Spoon. The first song is \"Living More\" from \"Not Dead Yet,\" and the second is \"Song For Elizabeth\" from Glen Harbor\'s \"The Ones Ahead.\" We also hear \"Mother Tongues\" from Ray Spoon\'',NULL,NULL),(62304,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Forever Deaf - August 25, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 11:50:36',NULL,'This is Part 2 of the show and it\'s called \"Sounds Like Old Times\" and it features music and old-time radio shows from the 20th century. If you\'re interested in hearing a song or an episode of a show repeated, you can do so by sending an email to \"SoundsLikeOldTimes@gmail.com\" . Silence is a music venue and art gallery in downtown Guelph. They\'re offering flat rate rentals for $100 per day, so you can rent a space to play music, host a party, or even run a workshop.\n\nFor more info, visit \"Silence Sounds.ca\" or call 905-453-1900. This is the other part of the program and it starts off by saying that the show focuses on issues of history for older adults and that they\'re always looking for volunteers. They also have a vending machine in the hall and they have a lot of music.',NULL,NULL),(62305,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Forever Deaf - August 25, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 11:31:11',NULL,'The narrator and his son are talking on a community radio station in Guelph, Canada. The narrator tells his son that he is listening to the station and that he will soon see him. The son asks his father how he is feeling and the narrator tells him that he has been waiting for a compass. He says that he likes to be 18 years old without a compass because he is afraid of losing the identity that made him who he is.\n\nHe urges his father to help his son find the language and lyrics of the song so that he can understand it. The song is called \"Blow Up\" and it is one of many variations of a drum roll called a \"blast beat.\" The narrator explains that the blast beat was invented in the early 1900s to help drummers beat faster. The blast beat is a basic beat that is played in unison with a snare drum. In the 40s, 50s, and 60s, drummers like Louis Bellision, Sam Woodward and Sonny Murray used this beat to help them drum faster.\n\nMany credit Tony Williams with the first use of a blast beat. The drummer who first used this style was Karl Palmer. This is a classic example of a drummer using this beat. In this case, the drummer plays the right hand drum at a fast tempo and plays the left hand drum or kick drum at an even faster tempo.',NULL,NULL),(62306,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Forever Deaf - August 24, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 11:06:41',NULL,'This is a very respectful child, and he\'s listening to the program. It is called \"Dead Daisy\'s On Death\" and it\'s about a band called Prophets Of Demise.\n\nThe name of the band is \"Prophets of Demise\" and the band\'s members are brothers, Glenn and brother-in-law, Sean Derover, who used to be members of Megadeth, King Dammon, and X Megades. They also have a bassist, Dr. Vyazze, and vocalist, Vazze of metallium. The band is on a tour in the U.S. and Canada and they are playing in Kitchener on August 27th. They are also playing in Waterloo on August 28th. So they are on their way to play in Kitchener. Before someone calls him up, he tells him to stop playing the garbage on the floor. That was \"Machima.\"',NULL,NULL),(62307,124,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Planet Groove - August 25, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 10:47:20',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the recent events in the area. The Allora River Fest, the Kitchener Blues Festival, and the Guelph Jazz Fest are some of the highlights.\n\nThe program then segues into the conversation with the host of the show, Morning Dove. Morning Dove describes the show as \"Planet Groove Baby\" and then begins to discuss the acts on the bill. He describes the acts as \"Jack the Kaiser,\" \"Trash,\" \"Lads,\" and \"Sash Jordan.\" The first act on the list is \"Aretha Franklin.\" The second act is \"Drown in my own tears,\" \"Ray Charles,\" \"Lelone Vale,\" and the third act is the \"Jason Razzle-Funktet.\" The show closes with the song \"Give me some love,\" which is a song by \"The Evergreen Sash Jordan,\" a singer who sings of the \"Faces Stay With Me,\" a song she sang at the Waterloo Blues Fest.',NULL,NULL),(62308,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Forever Deaf - August 24, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 10:25:21',NULL,'This week on the Forever Forever Deaf show, Dean plays some new music from the cadaver, as well as some old favorites. He also plays a few new songs from the Brujujur band. The new singer on the band is Jessica Dementele, an actress who played the lead role in the smash hit \"Orange is the new black\" and is now a member of the band.',NULL,NULL),(62309,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Viejoteca - August 25, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-26 15:37:47',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62310,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Viejoteca - August 25, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-26 15:37:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62311,127,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/LiYghTE FM - August 25, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 10:10:59',NULL,'The DJ is disappointed in the character of Somerset, who he describes as \"emotionally distant\" and a \"love revolution\" . The show then turns to Somerset\'s music, which the DJ calls \"awesome live looping\" and \"classical huge pop sound\" and which Somerset calls \"Sonnet 18.\" The show also discusses the end of summer and the time off that children and school leave for vacation. The DJ says that he\'s never going to leave Canada and that he prefers the summer break to the winter break.',NULL,NULL),(62312,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Walkuman Style - August 25, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 09:49:45',NULL,'The festival is a family-friendly affair with exciting entertainment and a variety of food and drink. The author opens the festival by declaring that he wants to \"kiss myself\" and that \"everything I love\" is his own. He says that he loves himself so much that he \"enriches himself.\" He says he wants only one man to love him.',NULL,NULL),(62313,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Digital Statik - August 25, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 09:04:08',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62314,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Global Rare Grooves - August 25, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 08:44:13',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62315,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Folk Roots Radio - August 25, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 08:33:14',NULL,'The second half of this program is a conversation between Paul Mills, a musician, arranger, and producer, and his guest today is Ron Hines, who sings a song called \"Get Back Change\" from his latest album.\n\nMills worked with Ron on three albums, including this one, and says he met him back in the 70s when he was producing for the CBC. He says he was the first person that he worked with on one of his albums, and it took him a long time to decide that he would work with him again on this one. They worked on the album together and he says they had a lot of fun. One day when they were working on the vocal tracks, he says he\'s going home and tells Paul not to worry about the overdubs because he always works with artists.\n\nBut he ends up working with him on the track that he stuck in the ukulele on. The song is called \"Good Dog is Lost\" from Ken Tizard\'s tribute album to the late Ron Hines. The title song is from that same album. Paul says he loves the song and says that every time he listens to it, he gets goosebumps.',NULL,NULL),(62316,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/A Dog’s Breakfast - August 26, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 08:07:34',NULL,'In this program, Alice and Brian Cox discuss the National Film Board\'s partnership with the Canadian Film and Television Board and the importance of storytelling in Canadian history. Alice invites Brian to join her on Sundays at 9pm as she travels through the Looking-glass and follows her music wherever it takes her. She explains that due to the Bill C-18 that has been passed, Canadians no longer have access to news content on Facebook, Instagram, and Google. If you are upset about this, please contact the Member of Parliament for Guelph, Lloyd Longfield',NULL,NULL),(62317,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/The Underground - August 26, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 07:04:20',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62318,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/The Underground - August 26, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 06:44:31',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62320,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Democracy Now - August 25, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 05:31:13',NULL,'Amy Goodman reports that former President Donald Trump has been arrested and jailed on charges of attempting to overturn the results of the recent elections in Georgia. He is one of 18 co-conspirators who are awaiting trial. The only co-defendant who is not in jail ahead of trial is Harrison Floyd, the leader of the Black Lives Matter movement. The district attorney in Fulton County, Georgia, moved the trial date to October 23 after one of the co-conspiracy\'s lawyers, Kenneth Cheesebourg, requested his release.',NULL,NULL),(62322,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Democracy Now - August 24, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 04:34:45',NULL,'On this week\'s program, Amy Goodman reports that Donald Trump has refused to participate in the first Republican presidential debate, and he will be arrested later today for attempting to influence the election. Amy also reports that the head of a Russian mercenary group has died in a crash in Russia, two months after leading an unsuccessful mutiny against Vladimir Putin.',NULL,NULL),(62324,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Beautiful Druid - August 26, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 04:14:20',NULL,'Beautiful Druid is a music event at the University of British Columbia. In this program, Alden Hadwen, a student at the university, teaches a variety of music and poetry.\n\nHe performs songs by Sting, and plays two songs by the Russian pop artist. He also plays a short interlude from the romantic piano album by the Canadian artist Gia Margaret. The show opens with a set of blues, including a song by Taj Mahal, and then it moves to a set by a Canadian group called Blackburn. They play a song called \"Duck Diving Blues,\" which was recorded live at a Guitar festival in Hawaii in 2013, followed by a track by Earl Bloch.',NULL,NULL),(62325,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Industry Tactics - August 25, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 03:17:38',NULL,'This interview is one of many in which the artist reflects on his work and his own life. He explains that he finds it helpful in that it helps him to understand why he does what he does, and he is excited by the idea that he may be able to figure out another way to express himself.\n\nHe says that he has a friend, an artist named Paul Duchamp, who was once a big artist and then stopped making any paintings. The artist tells the story of his professor at UCLA who told him to drop his painting because there were so many other things to do besides painting. He admits that he does not see how he could drop the painting, but he does feel like he has painted a whole picture of himself in a coffin.\n\nHe thinks that when he dies, he will go to the end. He knows that he will still be a painter, though, and that he might be tempted to make sounds and perform other things as well. He also says that if he were to stop painting, he would not go \"squirly\" if he did not paint for a long time. However, he realizes that he cannot sell all his paintings. He wishes he could.',NULL,NULL),(62326,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Industry Tactics - August 25, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 02:56:26',NULL,'In this episode, Rich discusses his new band, the Jane Does, which he\'s co-founded with Tom Juhadz, Joan Smith, and other fine artists. He also announces that he\'ll be recording a new album in the coming months. Plus, he says, there\'s going to be more live dates, more tour dates, and more recording coming up in the future. So, check out the list of things Rich has to say in this latest episode of Industry Tactics.',NULL,NULL),(62327,1615,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/24/Off the Beaten Track - August 24, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-24 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 02:28:21',NULL,'The show opens with a monologue from Jean, the host and producer of Off the beaten Track, a live weekly music show on CFRU. The first song he listens to is Tape by a Montreal-based musician and producer named Joni Void. The song is a sampling and sound technique.\n\nWhat drew him to the song is the idea of sharing intimate childhood memories with his listeners. The next song is Lurk by a Canadian DJ named KCMQ. The third song is Wait by a German DJ named Foxtrot, and the fourth song is from a fellow DJ who had his own show. The fifth song is Walk Through Water, a song from Obermono\'s and Saint Panther\'s Good Lies album. The cover of the album is a cute dog. The sixth song is Hold On by Euro Not Waving, a love song about friendship.\n\nThe friendship will last forever. The seventh song is Illusion of Secession by Fote. The last song is All Night Live Sessions One, a dance song about a woman called Romare.',NULL,NULL),(62328,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/25/Hellfire Radio - August 25, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-25 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 02:07:26',NULL,'The gang is back at Electric Hellfire, where they play heavy metal and alternative music. They\'ve just heard some of Ozzy Osbourne\'s songs, including \"Over the Mountain\" with Rhodes on guitar, and they\'ve also heard some new songs from the likes of \"In This Moment\" and \"Blaps The Chronosphere\" from the new album by \"Cobalt Canyon\" .\n\nThey also heard \"7 Dust Truth Killer\" from \"Power Slave\" , which was released earlier this year. They were at the Riverfest this weekend, which is a big festival in Canada. The guys are planning to play a cover band of Leonard Skinner\'s \"Tragically Hip,\" the band everyone loves. Leonard says that he\'d like to hear the Leonard Skinner band because he\'s the same name as Leonard. He also says that \"More than Tragically\" is as good as \"Leonard Skinner.\" The guys decide to play another CD from Leonard\'s collection. He says he has too many of them, but he can\'t bring them all in. The band has to bring more \"alternative\" music, which he says is hard to find at the festival.',NULL,NULL),(62330,167,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dvd6hy/August_25_2023_Funky_Fridays7qru8.mp3','2023-08-26 18:04:46',431961989,'2023-12-19 01:11:21',NULL,'The show opens with Pete\'s description of the upcoming three hours of the show. He\'s going to play some music and then interview some people. In this case, it\'s a singer named Jeffrey Stoner who has a song called \"Fire and Rain\" on his debut album, Quadraphonic.\n\nHe uses this song as an example of how to make a good gospel song, even though it sounds like a standard country song. Pete talks about how he\'s always been a fan of music and how he and his bandmates have tried to make music that\'s really soulful and gospel sounding. He also talks about some of the other music he\'ll be playing in the next three hours.',NULL,NULL),(62332,175,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/qgxy99/August_24_2023_No_Man_s_Land7hnpr.mp3','2023-08-26 18:00:23',287962512,'2023-12-19 00:43:41',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62338,186,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hkcp5j/August_24_2023_Higher_Groundabpr3.mp3','2023-08-26 18:03:29',287962512,'2023-12-19 00:26:50',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62341,187,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/a2sfdh/DREAMING_-_EPISODE_AUGUST_25_2023ai5ba.mp3','2023-08-27 15:11:42',140986687,'2023-12-19 00:07:31',NULL,'On this edition of Dreaming In Stereo, Alexandra and her crew continue to present Canadian music in a style that is accessible to all listeners. They have just released two new tracks from the band Pilsid, one from Mediterrane and one from Dizzy. They also have a new track by the group Starlings and they are playing a show at the Danforth Hall on October 26, which is very exciting. Alexandra also discusses some of the other Canadian acts that have been announced to play in the coming weeks. They include Headlines, Islands, and Mono Wales.',NULL,NULL),(62342,197,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/waptb9/phil_s_inn_aug_26_23_MP3b3j9h.mp3','2023-08-27 05:12:56',156655884,'2023-12-18 23:11:31',NULL,'This is a short program from the fall campaign of CIUT FM. It is a thank you note to all the listeners who have supported the station during the fall. The listeners appreciate the rediscovery of the artist Beverly Glenn Copeland who has released a new album, \"The Ones Ahead.\n\n\" The listeners are also introduced to the artists featured on the album. They include the singer Nicholas Povik, the songwriter Kirovic, the singer Steph Yates, and the Latin artist Mariana. The listener also learns that the guest on the show is a South Asian businessman who brings his friends to the Caribbean island of Hispaniola. The guest tells the listeners that he is on an all inclusive vacation and that he wants to paint everything pink.\n\nHe plans to curate a music festival for the afternoon. The guests are invited to bring in their own music. He mentions that he has a paper umbrella and wishes he could have one of those. The music starts with a Vancouver artist named Luck Lucky, followed by a piece by Nicholas Povey, a singer songwriter and composer. The next artist is Kirovic. The artist is a singer, a songwriter, and a composer. He is known for his work in experimental and pop music. The last artist is Mariana. She is a sort of artist who has built her career on the Latin and salsa music that she has heard. The narrator is on vacation in an unspecified location courtesy of the businessman and flan artist, Mahatma KaneJeez. He will be returning to the',NULL,NULL),(62343,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bjfb5c/show_82623_mp3aemst.mp3','2023-08-28 22:30:22',84962812,'2023-12-18 22:49:33',NULL,'The host opens the show by explaining that as a kid, he used to think the U was dead. Now, he realizes it\'s actually a mouse. He\'s going to take a look at it and explain how it works. He invites anyone who would like to send him a message to the host at the Third-Face-All-Lower-Case-One-Word-at-Cit.fm. He also wants to hear from anyone who has a message for him.',NULL,NULL),(62344,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wcihtn/August_25_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_The_Pillow6veot.mp3','2023-08-26 18:06:13',287962512,'2023-12-18 22:25:12',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62345,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/28/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - August 28, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-28 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 22:10:48',NULL,'The first episode of this series is entitled \"A Kaleidoscope of Progressive, Fusion, and Alternative Sounds\" and is produced by Nicholas Cooper, the Guardian of the Sentinel. He says that he wants to pay respect to and acknowledge the ancestral and local territories and indigenous communities across the island from which the broadcasts are made.\n\nHe also wants to acknowledge that many of the styles featured are based on adapting elements of black