e to observe how those plants affected the way their species evolved. Rosalind was also interested in how these plants were able to change over time, so that the different types could mate and produce offspring that were of the same type. Rosalind is particularly interested in the question of \"perfect flowers,\" which she describes as \"wet that tail.\" She is also fascinated with the concept of gender, because \"the concepts of gender are extremely important.\" Rosalind describes a new project called \"Ontario Heritage and Feral Apples.\" The goal of the project is to better understand the distribution and abundance of domestic apples and to study the potential applications of these apples for cider production and wild environments. She also discusses the idea of \"heterozygous,\" which is the definition of a \"high heterozygousion.\"',NULL,'The UM\'s Rosalind explores how plants evolve from cross-breeding to exclusively self-breech'),(62359,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Wind-Down - August 27, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 16:06:53',NULL,'The program starts off with a discussion about the music that the listeners have listened to on the show. They hear new music from Jungle, Shozzeh, Shambhudekov, Tomod, Aphex Twin, Sun Little, Lands, Night Tapes, Raids and Daniel Romano. Then they hear music from Canada, from TEX, from Daniel Romano and from Dan San. Finally, they hear a song from the artist, Daniel Romano, who is currently on tour.',NULL,NULL),(62360,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Caribbean Anthology - August 26, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 15:08:21',NULL,'The host begins this new version of CFRU by saying that it\'s a brand new version, but he can play it because he has the instrumental.\n\nThe song is \"a wicked tune\" if anyone listens to it, he tells us. He tells us that he\'s been watching an interview on Teach Them with the legendary Dredd and the interview is very lengthy. The Underground Guy says that he likes the interview because Drededd is \"probably the selector that deserves all of the merit going to him,\" in the sense that he has contributed to the world of music and sound systems, cutting dubplates, and so on. He says that DredD is an older individual than most of the music selectors and that he respects him very much because he is an \"older individual in the music business.\" The Underground Dude adds that if not in the \"late 60s or even early 70s,\" he\'d be somewhere in that range. But he says that \"Dredd\" has an \"open mind\" with music, which is something that we hear all the time when people say that new music is \"garbage, trash, and no good\" and that they can\'t really listen to it anymore.\n\nThe underground guy says that if people listen to music, they\'ll be able to feel the music, and they\'re going to get to like the music. He adds that he was talking about artists like Brian Messia, Var',NULL,NULL),(62361,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Caribbean Anthology - August 26, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 14:51:59',NULL,'This is the second edition of the Caribbean Anthology. This time, the narrator thanks all the listeners for coming out to see the show. He also thanks everyone who came out to support Sharice and him. The next edition will take place in February. The narrator says that he\'s noticed how thankful artists have been for the show and how happy they are that they were able to be a part of it.',NULL,NULL),(62362,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Sound Magic - August 26, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 14:28:55',NULL,'The program opens with a discussion of the music on the program. The program is about to wrap up with a performance of a concerto by a contemporary composer named David Gumpner.\n\nIt then turns to a symphony by a composer named William Putz, who is considered to be a serious composer and who has several symphonies to his name. The first symphony is a response to the September 11th attacks. The second symphony is in response to this event. It is not a war-like symphony, but rather one that treats the event with a sense of distance and expectancy. The symphony is also available on American Classics on Naxos. The third symphony is by another contemporary composer, David. It features the Royal Philharmonia. It was written about ten years ago. The clarinet player in this symphony is named Michael Noseworthy, and it is conducted by the Royal Philharmonic\'s principal conductor, Emmanuel Sifat, and the clarinet player is named David. The final piece of music is a clarinet concerto by the American composer David.',NULL,NULL),(62363,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Sound Magic - August 26, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 14:09:05',NULL,'In this program, Doleschell discusses the recent release of a new issue of Sound Magic, a magazine dedicated to the history of American classical music. The magazine features a number of works by American composers, including Virgil Thompson, who died in 1989.\n\nHe is considered to be one of the most influential American composers of the twentieth century. His works were composed in the United States during the period from 1896 to 1989. He was a powerful critic and teacher in New York during this period. He also wrote for the New York Times. He stood against the ultra modern in his career and formulated a kind of conservatism against it. The composer\'s most famous work, Four Saints, was recorded by the Boston Modern Symphony Orchestra. The program also includes a new recording of three of Thompson\'s orchestral works by the orchestra, which have never been recorded before. The music on these new recordings has a \"tremendous hold up\" and is \"more and more solemn.\" This is one of many recordings of this work by the composer.',NULL,NULL),(62364,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Bel Araby with CAWA - August 26, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 13:51:00',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62365,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Sound Magic - August 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 13:28:41',NULL,'The program starts off with some American music, starting with a piece by an American composer named Henry Kimball Hadley, who was born in 1871 in Boston. He was the son of a prominent Boston musician. He went on to become one of the most important American composers of the twentieth century. The program also includes works by two other American composers named Arthur Foote and William Grant Still, both of whom lived from 1895 until 1978. The program ends with a number of larger pieces, including a piece from Visions, which Dolaschal says sounds \"very summery.\"',NULL,NULL),(62366,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Alternativa Latinoamericana - August 26, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-29 13:52:47',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62367,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Alternativa Latinoamericana - August 26, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-29 13:52:47',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62368,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Tiempo de Mujeres - August 26, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-29 13:52:48',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62369,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Mach Vibe Radio - August 26, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 13:06:20',NULL,'The first half of the show begins with a commercial break and the second half is \"invincible\" . The second half will be \"explosion\" , and everyone should stay inside. The program ends with a call to arms from the hosts of the program. They remind us that the festival is coming up on September 10th, and that it is \"physically accessible and includes ASL interpretation.\" The festival will feature authors from all over the world, and tickets can be purchased through Eventbrite.',NULL,NULL),(62370,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/Mach Vibe Radio - August 26, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 12:53:23',NULL,'The first part of the novel is set in the present, where the protagonist, who is called Priva Azulas, is writing a letter to her mother. The letter is addressed to \"Lorita,\" the protagonist\'s mother, and is written in the style of a school paper. The first line of the letter is \"I\'m very glad to be here\" . The next line is \"Thank you, thank you.\" The letter ends with \"This is the podcast\" , which is a kind of shorthand for \"I love you.\" This is the first of many letters that the protagonist will write in this novel.',NULL,NULL),(62371,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/The Underground - August 27, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 12:28:36',NULL,'A new law has made it illegal for Canadian news organizations to share their content on social media platforms such as Facebook and Instagram. A university in Guelph, Ontario, has decided to stop sharing its content on these platforms. The university says it\'s a community organization and that it shares news as well. It\'s unfortunate that this law has taken away their ability to share content on Facebook and on Google. If you want to continue to support the university, you can sign up for its newsletter at https://www.\n\neventbrite.ca/e/calgary-university-cancels-facebook-and-instagram-blockage. You can find out more about this by listening to this program. The MP who represents Guelph, Lloyd Longfield, joins us to discuss the bill. He says that he believes that it will make it easier for people to access reliable news, and he urges people to take action against this new law.',NULL,NULL),(62372,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/The Underground - August 27, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 12:03:56',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62373,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/26/The Underground - August 26, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-26 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 11:46:52',NULL,'The Underground Show starts off with a guy named DJ Vulgar telling the audience that they just got a guest for their set tonight. He\'s got a beard that won\'t grow back. Okay, now it\'s time for a little more costume talk. It turns out that this is the Underground Show, and they\'re going to be holding a Halloween party in Guelph the next day.',NULL,NULL),(62374,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Clan Na Gael - August 27, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 11:29:07',NULL,'The program begins with the story of Ray Anthony and his song Dragnet, which was released in 1953 and went to number two on the pop charts 70 years later. The song is from the time of the Great Depression, and the names were changed so that the innocent were not exposed. The program also discusses the Wellington County tax relief program and Jerry Brown\'s Canadian In the Morning. A couple of big lottery winners are announced. The show also includes a bit of highbrow music. It\'s Ernestine Anderson\'s tune and a song by Peter Appleyard called Sophisticated Ladies.',NULL,NULL),(62375,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Visions fugitives - August 27, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 11:07:42',NULL,'The show begins with the host, Christopher Curry, talking about some of the music on the program. He\'s talking about the music that he\'s been reading from the notes that he sent to him by Feng Wei.\n\nThe music on this show is from the same composer, and that\'s why it\'s called \"Opus 17.\" In other words, this is a piece that doesn\'t have an Opus code, but has a different composer\'s name on it. So this week\'s program is based on the music from Feng Wei, and it starts off with a piece called \"Rachimaninoff Suite No.2 for two pianos.\" The program ends with the show\'s final piece, a piece by a woman named Martha ArgeRICH.',NULL,NULL),(62376,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Clan Na Gael - August 27, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 10:51:25',NULL,'The host begins his program with a description of the song he\'s going to play for the listeners. First up is a song by a woman named \"Claire Negell\" who is a singer, songwriter, and musician. She\'s also a member of a band called \"Runs in the Blood\" and she sings a song about a prostitute called \"Alanna\" from a CD by Quincy Jones called \"Rations in the blood in bed with . . Quincy and Alanna are friends.',NULL,NULL),(62377,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Visions fugitives - August 27, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 10:30:53',NULL,'In this first episode of the new show, \"Visual Fugitive,\" the co-host of the show, Fangwei, and the composer, Christopher Curry, discuss the music selections for the upcoming week. The pieces chosen by Fangwei include the Concerto for Saxophone, Cyber Bird, by the composer Takashi Yoshimatsu and the Philharmonic\'s \"Bird in Colors.\" The \"Cyber Bird\" is a piece of music inspired by the wishes of the late Fangwei\'s sister, who wished that she could live to be a \"bird\" in her own next life.',NULL,NULL),(62378,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - August 27, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 10:12:37',NULL,'We\'re back with another episode of the Cuckoo Banana Variety Hour. This time it\'s about families. This episode\'s all about families, and the narrator talks about how many families there are in the world, and how different they are from one another. They\'re talking about the largest family ever, which is a family of 21, or 20 kids. We\'ll see what the biggest is after that, too, because we\'re going to hear some more family music.',NULL,'The narrator tells the audience to listen to a new song about moms and fathers'),(62379,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/La Buena Onda - August 27, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-08-29 13:52:55',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62380,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Zombie Jamboree - August 27, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 09:49:18',NULL,'The second hour of the show starts off with a song from Bihar by Hot Pastrami and another from Yale Strom and the piano sounds from Alan Tous Saint. Then they go out and play a few songs from the great Alan. They play a song called Bright Mississippi and a song about another river. They also play some songs about the Tijuana River. The band then plays some songs from Leonard Cohen, Uridicee, and Rock Sea Music. They finish off the show with The Burning hell. They hear some music from the next show.',NULL,NULL),(62381,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Clan Na Gael - August 27, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 09:11:20',NULL,'The program begins with John Fahy, the host of Clan Na Gael, the local Celtic music station, on his CFRU 93.3 program. He explains that he\'s going to play only Scottish and Canadian artists, instead of American, British, or Irish artists. He\'s sad to say that a dear friend of his passed away last week, and he hopes to have some volunteers to help out on the show.\n\nThe program then turns to some of the songs he\'ll play for the listeners. First up is a song by the Mcgillvery sisters, who are from Scotland. They have a song called \"Cotters from Loch Tey\" that\'s really pretty. Next up, he plays a song about Rob Crabtree, the world champion bagpiper, and a song for Isabel Monroe, who was from the Lowlands.',NULL,NULL),(62382,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/La Buena Onda - August 27, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-08-29 13:52:57',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62383,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Zombie Jamboree - August 27, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 08:52:15',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with the co-hosts of the \"Zombie Jamboree,\" which is a live music festival. The first part is an introduction to the music, where they explain that the music is a kind of recreation of the river itself. It\'s a way for the musicians to experience the \"great rivers\" of the world and express themselves.\n\nThe second part is a commentary on the music and how it\'s influenced by various influences. It starts off with a song by the super Yamba band, called \"Sleepwalking Through the M. Mekong.\" The band is from Brooklyn and they\'re known for their ability to travel. The band also has a song called \"Ded Dengue Fever,\" which sounds a lot like the disease. The show is called the \"Zombular Jamboree\" and it\'ll be floating through the Mekong River. The musicians are floating through shallow water with a band called \"The Legion Of Green Men.\n\n\" The first song they played was called \"Frequency Change.\" The second song they sang was \"Here Before.\" The show ends with the song \"Mismarized,\" which comes from the band \"D\'Donne.\" The song was one of two songs they played on their second album, \"Tumisian Tail,\" which was a remixed version of \"A Faraway Land.\" The cohosts, Danela, Solania, and Mikola, are on board the boat. They\'ve been listening to',NULL,NULL),(62384,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Through the Looking Glass - August 27, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 08:29:40',NULL,'Alice and her band plan to travel through the looking glass and listen to music wherever it takes them. They begin tonight with a journey through the Looking-Glass with Mary-Beth Carty from Crossing the Ascent album and the song Blueberry Mountain.\n\nThey then move on to the new album, The Spark in your Beams and take Back Ten. The next artist on the show is Ray Spoon from Not Dead Yet, the same album that Dizzy was listening to earlier. If you are interested in listening to the playlist, which has been posted on the Looking Glass, you can find it on the looking-glass.blogspot.ca. The show page will go up under the show pages at the beginning next week. If there is a band that needs to be featured, they would like to hear it. If someone has a suggestion for a band, they can reach out through the show page. There is an email address for the show or if you have an idea for a show, please let them know.\n\nThey are going to go into a rabbit hole, and they will be followed by Bambi from Infinity club and Hooked FM. The album and name of the song is Doomed, and you are listening to it on CFRU 93.2 in Guelph and in the other parts of Ontario.',NULL,NULL),(62385,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/Backtracks - August 27, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 08:11:13',NULL,'Backtracks is back with host Jennifer. She\'s got a bunch of new music for the listeners to listen to. The show starts off with a new track from Doug Hell\'s band called \"Problems\" which is an original composition.\n\nThe song is up on the web, and there\'s a video of it. We also hear from Sparkle Horse called \"I Pennies\" and from Brian Jonestown with \"What You Isnt\" and \"Live from 2014.\" The show closes with a song from Brian Rosenberg called \"Niagara Falls\" which means \"the blues\" . He is from Buffalo, New York. He has a lot of great stuff on his Bandcamp page. The other song on the show is from a punk band called Hanging Girls called \"Hanging Girl\" who is a melodramatic punk band.',NULL,NULL),(62386,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/28/This Night Wounds Time - August 28, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-28 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 07:10:19',NULL,'This is a special edition of the CFRU Radio show, hosted by Christopher Curry. It\'s called \"Music by Artists from the different Provinces of Argentina.\" The first hour of the show is devoted to music by established artists, but this hour, the show will focus on new bands.\n\nThey\'ll start with a band called Asterius, who\'s described as a \"Stoner band\" from the \"San Juan desert.\" They\'ve got a new album called \"Fuzz-terius.\" This is an \"Automatic Translation\" , which means that you can\'t translate the band\'s music into English. So here\'s what we\'ll hear: \"The Journey\" is from the first album, \"Horace.\" The band is described as \"from the San Juan Desert,\" which means they\'re not from San Juan, but rather from the desert. The group\'s first album is called \"Fucks-ter-iius.\" The group describes itself as \"a Stoner band.\" They say they\'ll find out more about their album later on. The first track they\'d hear in English is \"Athlus Journey,\" a song from their first album.\n\nThis is \"an Automatic Translation,\" meaning it\'s translated in an automatic way. But this is an example of a band that\'s been translated incorrectly in the past. The band describes themselves as a stoner band from \"the San Juan desert,\" which is',NULL,NULL),(62387,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/28/This Night Wounds Time - August 28, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-28 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 06:52:38',NULL,'In this chapter, the narrator breaks down the geography of the show. The geographical spotlight series is a series of segments where the narrator plays music from all of Canada\'s provinces and territories.\n\nThe purpose of the segments is to explore the country\'s diverse population, culture, and history. The first segment in the series was called Discovering Russia, and it was a chance for the narrator to explore Russia\'s largest province, the Sakha Republic, and its largest city, St. Petersburg. The narrator chose Russia because it was the largest country on the planet, and because he has never been a fan of Vladimir Putin. The next segment was called Canada, and the narrator chose Canada because it is the second-largest country on earth. The third segment was China, and he chose China because there is disagreement about whether China should be considered an independent country or part of a large entity called China.\n\nThe fourth segment was the United States, and that was because there was disagreement as to whether the country should be divided into 50 states plus the capital territory or the three contiguous states. The fifth segment was Brazil, which was divided into states plus national capital territory, and sixth was Australia. The seventh segment was India.',NULL,NULL),(62388,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/27/This Night Wounds Time - August 27, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-27 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 06:30:46',NULL,'The host starts off this show by explaining that it\'s not just any music that they can play on the stage. They\'re going to play music that\'s off-center, which means that it doesn\'t fit in with the center of the universe. They can\'t only play music from the \"center\" of the world, but they\'re also going to do music from \"the center,\" which means the actual geography of a place.\n\nSo, for this night\'s show, the host is going to focus on music from Buenos Aires. This is the smallest city in the country, so it won\'t be as big of a draw as other cities. We\'ll also hear some music from Louise Campbell, a Montreal artist, on her new album, called Sources. This track is called People of the sea, and it was written just before the start of the Pandemic in the year of 2019.',NULL,NULL),(62390,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/28/Democracy Now - August 28, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-28 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 06:12:13',NULL,'Sixty years ago, Martin Luther King delivered his famous \"I Have a Dream\" speech. The anniversary of the speech was marred by the shooting deaths of three black people in a Florida dollar store. The day was also marred by reports that a white man shot dead three African Americans at a shopping center in Jacksonville. The program also discusses a settlement between the city of New York and the family of Ken Chamberlain, a former Marine who was shot and killed by police after accidentally triggering his medical alert bracelet.',NULL,NULL),(62391,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/28/Worst Responders - August 28, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-28 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 05:12:48',NULL,'The Host of the Comedy Club, Charissa, returns to the show after a two-week absence. She is excited to be back and to be the \"coolest kid\" at school. She tells us that she has been on an \"excursion\" to the Middle East, including a month in Dubai and a month at London. She says that she is worried that people will misunderstand her and think she is talking about London, which she is not.',NULL,NULL),(62392,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Rainbow Country - August 29, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 04:46:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62393,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Rainbow Country - August 29, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 04:32:54',NULL,'Carol Pope is on stage and introduces the show. It\'s called \"Rainbow Country\" and it\'s hosted by Mark Tara. He\'s the producer and host of the show and he\'s also known as \"the B-Girls\" because of his gender. He introduces the two female guests, Conchita and Hard Cora, and they\'re also on stage. They\'re called \"B-Girls,\" and they are the queer voices on the show, too. They are the voices of a lot of the LGBT community in Canada and we\'re excited to hear their voices.',NULL,NULL),(62403,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Bridging The Social Distance - August 29, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 04:11:41',NULL,'David Edmond is the host of a show called \"The Pand-emic Show,\" which is dedicated to the stories of people living during the pandemic. David is also the co-host of \"Bridging the Social,\" a show that focuses on the social impact of the economic crisis.',NULL,NULL),(62404,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - August 29, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 03:08:39',NULL,'The music on this program is from around the world. The first song is from Madagascar, and it\'s called Desire. The second song is called Somoina from Denmark, and the third song is a song from Baby In Vain from Denmark. The fourth song is by Light Force from Australia, and that\'s a band that played for most of the \'80s.\n\nThe fifth song is another song from Adrian Raso from Canada, and this one is called \"We\'ve Got Ourselves a Dream\" from his latest album. The sixth song is again from Chile, and its called Efecto dea. The seventh is from China, and is called Cities. The eighth song is also from China. The ninth song is one from Chile.',NULL,NULL),(62405,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Democracy Now - August 29, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 02:53:09',NULL,'Democracy Now! opens with a discussion of the \"erosion of democracy\" in the United States. It says that the justice system must deal with the \"epidemic of election denialism\" and \"the attempt to overthrow elections\" .\n\nIt goes on to say that Donald Trump is in federal court in Washington, D. C., on charges that he plotted to undermine the election of President of the United states.\n\nThe group will go to Georgia and Florida to speak to the co-founders of Black Voters Matter and Mark Meadows, who testified in court about the need to move the Trump presidential trial to federal court. It will also go to New York to speak with two of the nation\'s most prominent legal scholars. It concludes with a look back at the recent violence in Florida. It reports on a white man who fatally shot three African Americans at a shopping center in Jacksonville.',NULL,NULL),(62406,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Under the Needle - August 29, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 02:29:07',NULL,'This is a live show on KEXP with Troy Nelson as host. It\'s the rock band All them Witches. They\'re all about exploring time and space and exploring music. They play music transmuted, which means they can play blues, rock, and more. All the musicians can play whatever they want and they put out one song a month for each month. We\'re going to thank them for stopping by and checking out our show. If you\'re a fan of the music, check out the KEXP Sound and Podcast for more music stories. Also check out our Soundcloud page for more info.',NULL,NULL),(62407,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Solipsistic Retreat - August 29, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 01:10:04',NULL,'The gang starts off by talking about some of the bands they listened to. They go to Britain, they visit a band called the Shapes, and they listen to a song called Looking Directly Into the Sun. They also go to Scotland and visit a group called the Fan Club. They claim to be from Ireland, not Scotland. Then they hear about two songs from a rock band called Grand Prix. And then they hear a song from an Alberta band called Psychee.\n\nThey used to be skinny puppies. And they made a song about a guy named Rick Rubin. They called him an \"arched nemesis of reality\" because he would destroy any band that got into his trap. Next up is a song by the band called The Paul Bears. They released a single called Fandom Pain. They had a woman playing the organ and a man playing the guitar. And now they\'re on their way to a \"solipsistic retreat\" .',NULL,NULL),(62408,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Solipsistic Retreat - August 29, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 00:50:03',NULL,'The first half of this program is devoted to the music of the late Glenn Meatmore. The second half of the program consists of the music from half Japanese, called Jump Into Love.\n\nThe first seven-inch of Jump into love was titled Calling All Girls, and the second half is called Jump into Love, which is a song about a girl. The song\'s title is a reference to Nirvana\'s song \"Smells Like Nirvana.\" The program concludes with the song \"Mikuchu and Good Sad Happy Sad,\" a song which the program describes as \"a great song.\" After that, the program moves on to \"Penn\'s Seven Inch Love Rules,\" a bit of \"the jolly old Britain.\"',NULL,NULL),(62418,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Silver Screen Dream Machine - August 29, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 00:33:17',NULL,'This episode of the Dream Machine begins with a brief introduction to the films of Orson Welles, Henry Mancini, Elliot Goldenthal, and Beck.\n\nThe first two films are Touch of Evil (1958) and Pettary (1989). The third film is the last in the Marvel Cinematic Universe, the fourth in the Spider-Man franchise, and the fifth in the Multiverse saga. Tom Holland is back as Peter Parker in the latest installment of the Marvel Universe. Before this, there was Tobey Maguire in the first live-action installment, and Andrew Garfield was in the second. In the new film, all three of the main characters are portrayed on screen. The score for this particular film is composed by Beck. We also hear music from The Hangover (