ates the suffering caused by animal research. The first thing that the narrator says is that she wants to talk about animal testing, which used to be a very important part of science back in the day.\n\nBut it isn\'t as important anymore. She says that animal testing has a lot of negative side effects. For example, it doesn\'t have enough information about human biology to make useful decisions about how to treat animals. It can also be dangerous because there are so many drugs out there that could be used to treat humans. And there\'s another problem with testing on animals. If a drug harms an animal, then it might not be used in humans. So testing on humans can be a waste of time.',NULL,NULL),(62456,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Breezy Breakfast Radio - September 4, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 12:52:22',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the U.O.G.W.\'s breezy breakfast will be the final one of the summer, and they\'ll meet again in September. They\'ll be discussing school issues, budgeting 101, and talking to a RMP. It looks like we\'re going to be back in school in a month, which means it\'s time to get back to work.\n\nLongfei Chen is a co-host of the podcast, and he and Jules Sabell are the co-hosts of the show. The show will return in September, after a month\'s break. The Alzheimer Society of Waterloo-Wellington is looking for music makers to help them with their music-related project. The music makers will play music for people with dementia, and the music will be personalized to each person. The society is also looking for people who want to donate all their iPods, gift cards, or money to help out. If you\'re interested in getting involved, check out the society\'s website for more information. And if you\'d like to hear more about the show, check it out on CFRU.\n\ncom. We also tell you about the upcoming Eden Mills Writers\' Festival, which will be held on Sunday, September 10. It\'ll feature more than 40 authors, including authors like James Gordon, Andrea Bennett and Paul Killigan. The festival is free to the public and will be accessible in both English and ASL.',NULL,NULL),(62457,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Breezy Breakfast Radio - September 4, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 12:31:40',NULL,'This morning, we\'re going to talk about solid waste. We\'re talking about how the city is honoring its treaty land, which is home to a lot of First Nations, including the Mississaugas. Before we get started, we need to read the city\'s acknowledgement of the land. It\'s important to note that the city has a responsibility to steward the land that it uses.\n\nSo, today, we acknowledge the land of the Mississauga First Nation. In a few paragraphs, we learn that all municipalities in the province will transition to a new Blue Box program. That\'s right, all the Blue Box companies will be responsible for running the recycling program. The new program will be called \"Circular Materials.\" It\'ll also require that all industrial, commercial, and other waste be collected in one',NULL,NULL),(62458,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - September 4, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 12:12:11',NULL,'In this chapter, the Guardian overseer of the music program, Nicholas Cooper, tells us that he\'s going to be looking \"inward and beyond\" into the world of progressive fusion. He wants to recognize that the music is made by people from all over the world, and he also wants to acknowledge that a lot of the black music and art in this program originates from the Black Lives Matter community.\n\nSo, we start off with a real-life story. This is a little bit of a cliffhanger, because it\'s the first time you\'ve heard the song \"Real Fiction\" on the program. It turns out that the song is actually a song called \"Ordinary Girl\" by Elkan, a Canadian band. Elkan also played a song from the show \"Ear Glow,\" which is on a Canadian station called \"Frozen Section.\" So, Elkan\'s back, and they\'re going to play a Piers Uli track from this show.',NULL,NULL),(62459,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - August 30, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 11:55:20',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the Sentinels\' Marvelous Kaleidoscope is a pre-recording of a live show that the artist has planned for the following week. The show will be at Silence, and the show will feature a number of songs from his new solo album, Solaces. The songs that he will be playing on stage are: Edge of Time, repose to repose of time itself, and Overcoming my doubts. The first song is a short piece titled \"Solving My Mysteries,\" and the second is \"Overcoming my Doubts,\" an instrumental soundscape.',NULL,NULL),(62460,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Bridging The Social Distance - August 31, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 11:28:29',NULL,'This is the first of a series of stories that will tell the story of a person\'s life at a retirement community. The first story is about an elderly woman named Anne Kuzick who is a current resident at the village of Riverside Glen.\n\nAnne is 80 years old and has been at the retirement community for four months. She says she lost track of time because she likes to watch people interact and stay connected to the world around her. She adds that staying connected is important to her because she is not just to herself, but to many people. Anne says she participates in all of the social activities at the community because she\'s a person who likes to sit, read, and strengthen her legs and arms.\n\nShe also participates in the exercise classes and they keep her connected. She explains that she used to have a companion that wanted to walk every day, but now he is staying with her sister. Anne\'s companion is a Lassa Absa, a breed of dog that came from the Far East and is very sociable. He is named Bert, and he is about 26 pounds. He likes to walk and enjoys his walks with his companion. He also enjoys the treats that his companion gives him. Anne does not know if she will take her companion back to her sister and take him back to his old life with her.',NULL,NULL),(62461,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/to know the land - September 4, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 17:52:58',NULL,'On this episode of the Talk Show, we speak with Byron, an artist, about his recent work, called \"Animal Forms.\" The artist is named Mickey Tamblin and he is a wildlife educator. He has created a series of masks that represent various animals that live in the forest and has invited people to interact with the masks and read journal entries. He also has asked people to take photographs of their experiences with the mask. The two talk about how seeing the world from another\'s point of view can affect one\'s actions, and about the work of the Council of Beings, an organization dedicated to bringing together all forms of being. The artist says he came to the project to participate in naming his own mask. He says he chose the raccoon mask as a challenge to himself and to the world. The project is playful and playful as well, and the artist says that adults often don\'t have time to play with their masks, which are a bit silly.',NULL,'Byron, a wildlife educator, has created a mask for the world'),(62462,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 4, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 11:08:49',NULL,'This is a special edition of the Morning Soul Mash-Up, where we\'re introduced to some of our favorite artists. This time, it\'s Sabell, who introduces himself as \"Sabell from Tragedy Anne\" and introduces us to his new band, \"Liv and Braden from Anne.\" They\'re coming to perform a concert at the Little Theater in Guelph on September 22nd at 7pm.',NULL,NULL),(62463,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 1, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 10:47:53',NULL,'The Eden Mills Writers\' Festival will take place on September 10th. The festival will feature 40 authors presenting their works in an idyllic setting. The event will also include music, food, and a variety of arts and crafts vendors. If you want to learn more about the festival, you can read more about it on the Eden Mills website.\n\nThe Morning Soul Shake Up is hosted by the Director of the CFRU Media Center. The aim of the show is to bring together the best talent in the arts to share their knowledge and talents. The students are given the opportunity to learn how the arts are conducted in the community. The program is hosted and produced by the same people who host the university\'s other programs and services.',NULL,NULL),(62464,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Blues Around the Block - September 4, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 10:27:50',NULL,'MacDee is back with another special edition of his program, Blues on the Block. This time, he\'s going to be playing songs from some of his favorite artists. He\'s got a new song from Mike Cozier, a song from his own latest release, and a new track from a local artist named Stellwyn \"Coco\" Burchwood.',NULL,NULL),(62465,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 31, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 10:07:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62466,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Blues Around the Block - September 4, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 09:47:09',NULL,'The program is called \"Blues Around the Block\" and the host is Mac Dee, and he thanks everyone for tuning in and for listening to the show. If you liked the show or previous editions of the show, then you can stream or download it from CFRU\'s web site. Mac Dee also says that if you have comments about the program, you can send him an email through his web site, MacD.\n\ncfru@gmail.com. The show is over, and Mac Dee thanks everyone. He tells everyone to go out and enjoy themselves, and then Charlie Musselwhite comes on stage. He has a new record out called Mississippi Sun, and here\'s another track from it. We\'re half way through the',NULL,NULL),(62467,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - August 30, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 09:11:47',NULL,'In this episode, we learn that the university\'s campus community radio station, 93.3 FM, is looking for a young man to host its morning soul show. The show is currently airing on Wednesdays from 8am to 9am. The program is a mix of soul, R&b, and funk. The host is called \"Respectful Child\" and the listeners are listening to the program from a variety of sources.\n\nYou can listen to the show on your tablet or on your phone. We\'ve also added a description of the station\'s work. It\'s a public service announcement station, which is a way for students to get involved with the community. The station also needs volunteers to help out at events like the Hillside Jazz Fest and the River Fest. If you\'re interested, you can contact the station at .',NULL,NULL),(62468,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Tuesday at 5 - August 29, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 08:47:04',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of the Upper Air, Mac hosts a program called Tuesday at Five. This program is a continuation of the program he started on Tuesday at 5:00, where he talks about music and news. This week, Mac talks about Summertime, a 1935 opera by George Gershwin. Summertime is a favorite jazz opera for decades, and most of the versions you\'ve heard are heavy on brass. Mac explains that he\'s started a new program called If These Summertime Could Talk, which is set in the present day.',NULL,NULL),(62469,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - August 29, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 08:26:44',NULL,'The second part of the episode opens with a brief description of the Gothic Castle and the show it is a part of. It is hosted by the Lich, a voice on the radio. The show is a community-based music show dedicated to educating the listeners about the latest and greatest music. It airs every Tuesday from 11pm to 12pm.',NULL,NULL),(62470,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Wild Combination - August 31, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 08:13:33',NULL,'The program is called \"Community Food,\" and it\'s all about transforming food waste into delicious gourmet meals for local communities. The Food and Agricultural Diversification Board, or FEWD, is a non-profit organization that offers community members free or reduced-cost food. It\'s a partnership between the Welsh government, local farmers, and the local food banks. The food banks are places where people can buy food from the farmers\' market and then share it with their neighbors.\n\nFood is a huge social issue in the Welsh community, and they\'re trying to figure out a way to make it work in their own community. The program also features an interview with Douglas Blackwood, who\'s been doing this program for 25 years. He\'s the host of \"Scenes Like Old Times,\" which is a kind of old-school radio program. This program has a lot of great old-timey music, too. You can listen to the program every Sunday at 2pm on the CFRU 98.3 FM station. This is a really cool program.\n\nIt offers a lot more than just old music, though. It also has a little bit of news. For example, this week\'s program is about a young man named Isai, who has written a song called \"I\'m a Singer, a Singer.\" Isai is a singer, but he\'s also a musician. He has a guitar, a voice, and a singing voice. So he can sing',NULL,NULL),(62471,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Humanoid Radio - August 29, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 07:06:29',NULL,'The show opens with a brief description of the science behind the music on Humanoid. It is believed that real aliens communicate through a universal language, and the key to making such communication is the technology of sending or receiving signals. The show ends with a description of some of the music that has been played this week. The last piece is a piece by Bill Laswell off his Navigation 4 album, followed by a piece from Pete Namla and another by Samira. The next piece is from the latest release by Piers Ulagai, titled Repose For SolievoMagnifico. The following two pieces are from his Thousand Knives album. The final song is from Lamento, the title track from his latest release.',NULL,NULL),(62472,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Let’s Get Lost - August 29, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 06:49:07',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part program on Humanoid Radio. The program begins with a song called Intongues and Eros by Ben Lamar Gay, who is appearing with the Natural Information society at the Guelph jazz festival.\n\nThen the show switches to a track called \"Hello, How, And Hey\" by Laura Scott, who will be appearing at the Royal city Mission on Thursday. The rest of the program consists of tracks from other artists, including Kia Ville, Mother Moore, and Nicole Mitchell. The first part of the show starts off with some music from the Mars Volta album, followed by tracks from the Music Beds For Moods album, the Astronaut album, Go Ask Alice, and the African Head Charge album. The second part begins with music from Ash Walker\'s latest album, A Trip to Etanga. The third part includes tracks from African Headcharge\'s newest album A Trip To Bulk Etanga',NULL,NULL),(62473,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Wild Combination - August 31, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 06:30:38',NULL,'In this chapter, the narrator reflects on his life, his family, and his goals. He describes his desire to have a child, and he uses the words \"egg,\" \"water,\" and \"fish\" to describe the emotions he feels. He says he wants to be a \"marine biologist,\" but he is afraid of fish. He uses the word \"pluck,\" which means \"fish,\" to describe a large pike. He and his father have soaked up the water at Peck Lake, where the pond is located.',NULL,NULL),(62474,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Let’s Get Lost - August 29, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 06:08:56',NULL,'This program is called \"Let\'s Get Lost\" and it is Scott\'s weekly program on the Free Public Radio station. Scott tells listeners that he is a jazz enthusiast and that he loves to play music from all over the world.\n\nHe says that this week he\'s playing music from the Chicago-based Natural Information Society, which has been a frequent guest at the Chicago Jazz Festival. Scott says that the festival is coming up in a few days and that people can find out all about it at the festival\'s dot com page. Scott plays a track called Dissensions from the album Dissension. If you want to find out more about the festival, he says, go to the festival website.\n\nNext up on the program is the Land of Kush band, which is a big band that has been playing a lot at the jazz festivals in the past. They\'re playing a big show on the 17th of September and will be playing the title track, Carnophobia. The track is called Sand Enigma. Anna Weber is a Canadian saxophonist who\'s been playing in New York for a long time. She\'s also a member of John Hollensbeck\'s band. She plays drums in his band. And Aurora Neland is a singer and instrumentalist. She also plays in the band. The band is called the Claudia Quintet and it was started by Bert and Ken, who were friends. They released their first album called \"Sand Enigma\" in 2001.',NULL,NULL),(62475,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 30, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 05:12:24',NULL,'The show opens with a discussion of the music that makes up the second hour of The Stillness and The Dancing.\n\nThe first hour is dedicated to a track called \"Coronation,\" the second to \"I Am Just a Pupil from the Crystal Pain,\" and the third to \"Sola Shards,\" the lead single from the latest release of the Montreal-based Silent Sounds. The show then turns to a friend of the program, a fellow artist on CFRU, who is doing a show in Guelph called \"Silent Sound.\" The show will be recorded, and the show will run from 8pm to midnight. The program is led by the host, who introduces the listeners to a number of the artists featured on the show and then launches into a list of the most popular tracks on the program. The list includes \"For Jonathan,\" a track from a band called Seal Beach, \"Sleep on the Wing,\" \"Otter Shadows,\" \"Into the Waves,\" and \"Turtle,\" the last track of the show dedicated to Brian McBride.',NULL,'A bunch of artists from sort of the experimental scene were invited to compose music for a videographer and photographer who passed away'),(62476,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/The Stillness & The Dancing - August 30, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 04:48:47',NULL,'The show starts off with some new music from the artist Jason Sharp, followed by some new tracks from a label called Meander. Then it\'s all about the music festivals, which is a good thing, says the host. He loves the idea of creating new music in old places.\n\nHe mentions that he\'s a part of a band that played at the first Jazz Fest in Guelph, and he was so happy to see them perform. Then there\'s some more music from a new label called IlluTech, which has released a bunch of new stuff. The first track is \"The Road,\" which is some kind of spectral music, and then some new stuff from another label called Music for Sleep. The second track is a little bit more dancey, and the third track is some sort of guitar music.',NULL,'The most recent as I speak edition of the stillness and the dancing Im your host here to meander your way through the world of ambient experimental'),(62477,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - August 30, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 04:33:40',NULL,'We\'re back with another graduate student, Hannah, who\'s studying water resources. We\'ll get to her education in a second, but for now, she\'s telling us her story.\n\nShe went to college in the east coast, and then went to school in the middle of the country to study water resources, which is basically the same thing as engineering. Hannah admits that engineering is more interesting, but she didn\'t want to do water engineering because it seemed more interesting. She says that the people who went to undergraduate school were like, \"Oh, I want the cool stuff, like swimming with the dolphins or doing sciencey stuff like stream gauging. But engineering was more interesting because it was science-y, like flood forecasting or stream gauging and so on. But Hannah says that water resources is more \"sexy\" because it\'s more like \"water math\" . So Hannah is now studying how nutrients move from the surface into the groundwater in agricultural watersheds.\n\nHannah doesn\'t know what she wants to do with this, but we\'ll call it \"nutrient transport\" and \"watershed\" , since it\'ll be a mouthful to describe. Hannah explains that a watershed is just an area where all of the precipitation is collected and then flows into a common outlet. When she was a kid, she used to memorize all the water cycle stuff.',NULL,NULL),(62478,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/B Siide Radio - August 30, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 04:11:05',NULL,'This is the first of two shows on the National Film Board\'s new program, called \"Wideawake,\" which will be hosted by the National Aboriginal Film Board. The first show will be a punk rock show hosted by Jamie, and the second will be an hour-long program on storytelling. The program will tell stories about the history of First Nations people, Inuit people, and Métis people. The stories will inspire conversations and initiate conversations about identity, family and community.',NULL,NULL),(62479,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/Trail Mix - August 30, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 03:50:02',NULL,'The show opens with a song by a man named Daniel Bachman, who is a few years younger than Dave. The song is from his latest release, The Morning Star, which is an 80 minute long double LP.\n\nThis is a song called New Moon, from this new album. Dave then picks up on some other music from the mechanical forest sound, a Toronto-based music collective. The Mechanical Forest Sound is a monthly series of live improvised rock concerts. In this program, Dave plays a song from the July 3rd performance of Jessica Stewart and Michael Davidson, two musicians from the Toronto music scene. Then he picks up the guitar playing of another musician named Lisa Reedy from Australia. She has released an album called Beholder, and she has a single called Imminerently.',NULL,NULL),(62480,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/End Credits - August 30, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 03:26:01',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62481,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/Tone Zone - August 30, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 03:09:08',NULL,'The guys at the Tone Zone are celebrating the fifth anniversary of their End of Summer music festival by playing a special album. This year, they\'re going with a title track from their 2003 album, \"Summer Sun and Beach Parties Tonight.\n\n\" They\'re also playing songs from the past five years, starting with the Cure\'s \"Never felt so cold,\" followed by the Buffalo Toms\' \"Summer,\" the Teenage Fan Club\'s Sometimes I don\'t need to believe in anything,\" and The New York Dolls\' \"Dancing backward in high heels.\" They also start their sets with \"Last Day of Summer,\" a song from \"The Drifters\'s\" 1964 album.',NULL,NULL),(62482,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/Radia - August 30, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 02:59:37',NULL,'In this episode, we learn about the radio station called Radia, which is bringing new and \"forgotten\" ways of making music to its listeners. They\'re trying to find a way to get people to listen to music that works across Europe and beyond, and they\'re giving the artists a challenge to come up with music that they think will appeal to their listeners. The show starts with a little bit of a pep talk, and the listeners are invited to join in on the fun. The listeners get to hear a lot of music, including some really awesome ones.',NULL,NULL),(62483,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Wind-Down - September 3, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 02:10:00',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of the Wind Down, the host of the local music show Praise The Ward, Michael Foyerstache, talks about the music that he\'s been listening to on the CFRU 98.3FM. He starts off the show with a bunch of new songs from Never Doll, the Scottish DJ Barry Cant Swim, and the DJ and producer Odessa and the Yellow House. He also mentions that Barry can\'t swim is playing a show in Toronto on October 5, and he\'ll be trying to get tickets to the show.\n\nYou can listen to all of the music on the show by going to the WindDownCfru.wordpress.com and clicking on the \"playlists\" tab. The final song on the program is from the animal collective Anima. It\'s called \"Stop Time\" from their latest EP. And it\'s also from the Prince Edward Island band Gweesa, who have a song called \"Floating\" on their new EP.',NULL,NULL),(62484,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Tales from the Bridge - August 31, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 01:53:15',NULL,'In this episode of Tales From the Bridge, the gang meets up with Kate Elliott, an award-winning science fiction author. Kate is known for her popular fantasy novels like Court of Five, which was named one of the best science fiction novels of all time by the Washington Post. Her latest release is \"Furious Heaven,\" the second installment in the \"Sun Chronicles\" series. The book has been praised by Anne Leckie, Anne Murray, and many others. Kate begins by saying that she\'s just going to start off with a little bit of information about her latest book, \"Unconquerable Sun,\" and then she\'ll talk about the books in the series.',NULL,NULL),(62485,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Here Today - August 31, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 01:10:06',NULL,'On this edition of the show, Aaron Badgley talks about some of the recent music on the air. First up is the new single from James Clark Institute\'s upcoming album Under The Lampshade. Then he brings up Jessica Ray and her band, the Ramshackles Parade. Next up is a new album from Jessica, called Sunshine Baby, which was just released.\n\nAnd then there\'s another new single out from a band called Ringo Starr, called Rewind Forward, which is produced by Ringo himself. Aaron also talks about Dolly and her new album, Let it Be, which has a cover of Let it be by Paul McCartney, Peter Frampton, and Dolly herself. And finally, Aaron brings up a song called Church of Trees, which sounds depressing, but is actually a good song.',NULL,NULL),(62486,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/FoodFarm Talk - August 31, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 00:49:23',NULL,'This is the first episode of FoodFarm Talk on CFRU 92.3. Host Mike Masseau says that the reality of modern farming is that people do not understand how food is grown. It is worth talking to farmers and getting a better understanding of what they do. He says that it is worth it to talk to people who have a good sense of what their farm looks like.\n\nHe talks to Jenny Tilton Flood and her family who produce milk on a farm in Maine. We talk a little about how they do their day to day farming and how they market and sell their milk. Because Jenny does not have a great rural internet connection, this is only an audio version. At the end of the show, Mike apologizes for the poor quality of Jenny\'s recordings.',NULL,NULL),(62487,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Android’s Dungeon - August 31, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 00:33:50',NULL,'The narrator begins by introducing himself as Jack, the host of a music-only show. He explains that he and his friend, Joel, are recording a short music and game show, but that they\'re not doing anything else. He says he\'s just going to do music for a good chunk of the show. The narrator doesn\'t want to get too bored with his listeners, so he says he won\'t say anything more than that.\n\nHe also says that August is the month of his birthday. He\'s happy for it, because August is traditionally hot weather. He loves the summer, but this August is a little damp and cool, which he has no problem with. He goes on to say that all the students are coming back from school, whether it\'s university or elementary school or whatever. The school year is back in session in September, which means that the town is getting a little crazy with all the kids back. The town shuts down downtown in the evenings and on Friday and Saturday, which is crazy. He likes the spirit of the school year, because he likes the way older people get the message that there\'s something wrong with the kids.',NULL,NULL),(62488,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/RadiOPIRG - August 31, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 00:08:26',NULL,'This week on the Perg, we learn about the upcoming book sale and the Kidney Walk. The Perg also plays a recording from last years Drug-Poison Awareness Day. This year\'s International Overdose Day was hosted by Arch Guelph, and the speakers included a couple of poets. It was a great success, and it\'s clear that the problem of overdose is getting worse. We\'ll hear more about this in a future episode of Perg. We also hear from the organizer of the International Overdosage Awareness Day, Karen Lomax.',NULL,NULL),(62489,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/T.K.O. - August 31, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 23:11:48',NULL,'This is the second episode of the latest episode of TKO Nation, and it\'s called \"What\'s Happening.\" It\'s all about the fighters and how they got started in this game and where they\'re at now. This is just a little bit of a catch-up, because we haven\'t been hearing much from the guys lately. But then again, we\'re always hearing about these guys and how awesome they are. So this is a great opportunity to catch up with the guys and get their thoughts on the latest happenings in the world of boxing. You know, like, what\'',NULL,NULL),(62490,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Turtle Island Underground - August 31, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 22:52:08',NULL,'In this episode, the Turtle Island Underground team discusses the program\'s recent rebroadcast of the previous week\'s Solidarity Day show, as well as a new program that will air on April 13 th , called \"Turtle Island Underground Presents: Native American Music.\n\n\" The show also includes an interview with Thompson Highway, an author and musician, and a review of his latest album Cree Country. In addition, the show includes a number of other rebroadcasts, including a show that airs every Thursday at 6pm, a show about modern alternative folk, and shows that explore the genre of \"Mocha-Gah,\" or \"conceited gaze.\" The program ends with a song by Zune.',NULL,NULL),(62491,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Open Sources Guelph - August 31, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 20:17:20',NULL,'The show begins with a discussion of the Whopper lawsuit, which has gone on for a long time. The show is not sponsored by Burger King, but it does take their money, and they will work for coupons, which they will do whenever they get them. The program also discusses a recent strike at the Ontario Ministry of Education, which is 11 days old. The Education Minister has come out and said that they have reached a tentative agreement with the teachers. The teachers will have to go to arbitration, which means that the other three largest teachers unions will not be able to have a say in the negotiations. The government has also come out against the process of collective bargaining, arguing that it is too time-consuming and that it will only delay the inevitable. The strike vote doesn\'t mean that the teachers are on strike, says the show\'s host. He has been voting for collective agreements every single time he\'s voted on them. He finds this to be a back-pocket bargaining tactic that the government uses to try and get things done. On the flip side, he finds the tone of the strike different than it was in the past, when there were so many distractions in the school. Parents are still trying to catch up with the times, but there is no hard talk this time around. The only reason the teachers got a contract in the first place was because of a pandemic, and the teachers wanted to sign a contract now, rather than come back and work out',NULL,'The teachers are on strike, says the show\'s host . The government has come out against the collective bargaining process'),(62492,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Forever Deaf - September 1, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 22:28:25',NULL,'This week on the program, Lee Fields plays a bunch of new songs from his upcoming releases. He starts off by telling us that he\'s on his way to work. He\'s got some new songs for you, too. First up is a song called Burn. It\'s from Godspeed\'s Thunder.\n\nAnd then it\'s about a naughty man named Gilles Ray. Before we get too worked up, let\'s check out the history of the song. The guy was born in 1415, and his parents died when he was only a baby. His father was killed hunting and his mother died of a mysterious cause. The first person to commit a hundred gruesome murders was Gilles Ray, the guy who killed his parents.',NULL,NULL),(62493,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Forever Deaf - September 1, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 22:07:29',NULL,'This short scene opens with a lengthy speech by the narrator, who goes on to announce that he will be leaving the stage shortly after Dean returns. He then announces that he has a number of songs coming up, including Killiva Dead Whitney, Code Orange, and a tribute to a wrestler named Bray Wyatt who has recently passed away from complications of CoVID. The song that he is going to play is a parody of Fix my Heart, which was the theme song for Fix My Heart in the early 2000s. The narrator then tells us that he\'s going to summon a demon and tell him his name. He\'s called Wicked One and he is a near Satan of the faith who comes from the very highest heaven and descends into',NULL,NULL),(62494,121,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Sundowner - August 31, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 21:11:39',NULL,'On this episode of Sundowner, Matt and GooseDoff play a set of songs from their latest releases. The first song is from Montreal, Marlena Moore, and the second is from Crime Family. The third song is a cover of a song from the Sour Widows\'s 2020 release. The fourth track is from the 1996 release of Lush\'s \"Sleep Talker.\" The fifth track is the cover of an old song called \"I Have the Moon\" from Tapalina.',NULL,NULL),(62495,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Forever Deaf - August 31, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 20:47:18',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62496,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/The Crooked Beat - August 31, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 20:32:58',NULL,'This week, the host of The Crooked Beat is back on the air with a special edition of the program. This time, he\'s talking about the music of Lee Perry, who\'s releasing a new album called \"Heavy Rain.\n\n\" He\'s also joined by two other artists from Austria, Double Stand Art and Dub Stand. The first track is called \"Crickets in Moonlight\" from the new album, which is also available on the Subatomic Sound system\'s new release, \"Zion\'s Blood,\" which is available on \"The Crooked Beat\" as well. The second track is \"Never Stop Never Flop\" from Lee\'s latest album, \"Thoristic Journeys,\" which he also produced.',NULL,NULL),(62497,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Forever Deaf - August 31, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 20:07:15',NULL,'We\'re back with the guys from the last show, and they\'re psyched to be back. We start off by talking about some new music from the show, which is mostly all new music.\n\nThe first song is called \"Till the Dirt\" and it\'ll be the first song from a new album called Outside the Spiral that\'s coming out soon. It\'ll feature Kelly Shafer, who\'s the guy from Atheist who basically plays everything. Scott Burns is the guy who produces this new album and he\'s from Florida. He actually asked Kelly to come back out of retirement and produce this new record. So check it out. Next up is some Cannibal Corpse, who have decided to remaster all their old stuff for the new record so it\'s totally new. They\'ll also have some new stuff from Death Clock, who released a new record called \"Death Album 4\" which is part of a new movie. So it sounds like this is going to be a pretty awesome show.',NULL,NULL),(62498,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/The Crooked Beat - August 31, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 19:47:44',NULL,'On the Crooked Beat, the program celebrates the life and career of Lee Perry. Perry passed away last week at age 85. He is remembered for his \"Roast, Fish, and Cornbread\" which was one of his most popular tunes. He also had a piece in the New York Times about Mr.\n\nBrown who bought Marley and his Wailers. It was also mentioned that Brown was seen carrying a crow on his coffin as it made its way to a cemetery. Perry also has a song in the program about Kung Fu / meets the Dragon 1975. He also has another song in that program about Funga. He has a piece called \"The H-K- Celebrating the Life\'s Works of LeeScratch Perry\" on the program',NULL,NULL),(62499,123,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Thanks for Listening :) - September 1, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 19:08:29',NULL,'This program is called \"Thanks for Listening\" and it is hosted by Megan. She is a community radio play-by-play host who likes to talk about music. She likes to play songs that she thinks are relevant to the community. She plays a song called \"Charlie\" by Barbie, who she considers to be a big hitmaker.\n\nShe also plays songs from the Crying Crystals, Anoni, and the Johnson\'s \"My Back Was a Bridge\" and \"Ancient Snowfall\" by Zac Zoya. She talks about her new hobby, \"worm grunting\" which involves picking worms out the ground. She says that she is not a good at it but she has found that she can use it to catch trout bait. She dedicates the song to Brent and Cindy, a couple she met in Newfoundland a week ago. She then dedicates \"The Clown\" by Megabog to them.',NULL,NULL),(62500,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Digital Statik - September 1, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 18:49:38',NULL,'The host and the host\'s lawyer discuss the latest developments in the court case. They discuss whether or not the case is finally going to be decided. The lawyer is certain that it will be decided in the affirmative, but he is also certain that the outcome will be determined in the negative. The two men discuss the extent of their success in winning the case.',NULL,NULL),(62501,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Walkuman Style - September 1, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 18:29:37',NULL,'This is the second of three short stories that the author will deliver at the upcoming Eden Mills Writers\' Festival. The first two stories introduce us to the protagonist and his lieutenant. In the first story, the protagonist is on a boat in the Mediterranean Sea and the second story introduces us to his lieutenant, Sadat X. Sadat is a member of a special team of Navy SEALs. He\'s on his way back from a mission in which he was involved in a major battle.',NULL,NULL),(62502,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Global Rare Grooves - September 1, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 18:06:47',NULL,'This week on the show, Sam Cee is joined by the music of Jay Wood, Jay Zone, Kenika Charles, Tony Allen, and others. The show starts off with a cover of the Jay Wood song \"Tyler the Creator\" and then moves to a song called \"Off the Rips\" which is a live version of Kenika\'s song Parkdale. Then the show moves to the Jay Zone album Intoxicated \"Skull\" and moves on to the tracks \"Mushburgers\" and \"Jazz is Dead\" which are part of Tony Allen\'s \"Afrobeat\" series.',NULL,NULL),(62503,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Folk Roots Radio - September 1, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 17:08:08',NULL,'The latest episode of Folk Roots features all the songs from Canadian artists, including a song by Bruce Coburn, a song from his latest album, Oh-Sun-Moon, an original song by Holland, a duet from Carla Muller and Yon Marand, a female vocal trio from the forthcoming album We-Will-Never-Be-Same, an instrumental from Don Ross, a blues song by Michael Jerome Brown and more. The band also includes Erin Costello, a singer-songwriter from Scotland, and the Scottish-Canadian Jason Wilson, who blends folk, roots, and reggae.',NULL,NULL),(62504,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Caribbean Anthology - September 2, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 16:47:29',NULL,'In this edition of the show, the DJ introduces the new merchandise line at the station. He also describes a new song that he is playing.\n\nHe gives a shout-out to the DJ and DJ\'s friend, the legendary DJ and music selector, Danny Dred. Dred is considered one of the pioneers of the sound system, and the DJ says that he respects Dred so much because of his older age. The DJ also comments on how many people dismiss new music as trash, garbage, or just plain old crap. However, Dred reminds listeners that they can actually appreciate music if they listen to it and take time to appreciate it.',NULL,NULL),(62505,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Alternativa Latinoamericana - September 2, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-05 01:16:03',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62506,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Alternativa Latinoamericana - September 2, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-05 01:16:03',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62507,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Tiempo de Mujeres - September 2, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-05 01:16:04',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62508,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/The Underground - September 3, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 16:28:03',NULL,'The team at U.V. wants to know how young and old people experience and shape the world. They\'re looking for people who are 5 to 65 years old. We\'d like to hear your story. If you\'ve ever been sick, we\'d love to hear about it. Or, if you\'re not sick, but you\'d still like to participate in the study, please send us an e-mail. We need to hear from people who\'ve been sick for a long time. The team is looking for participants for a new study called \"Life in Covid Study.\" We want to hear their stories, too. If they\'re 5 years old or older, they could participate in a survey, a journal, a podcast, or keep a journal. They need to know their stories. We don\'t want to know what\'s wrong with the world, but we want to learn about what they\'ve experienced and what they think.\n\nIf everyone agrees that climate change is a problem, then they should all agree that the world is getting worse. We can blame it on human beings. No one can deny the fact that the climate crisis is here to stay. The devastation caused by Storm Irma in Florida is an example of the impact of climate change, and no intelligent person can deny it anymore. No intelligent person could deny the impact anymore. We should all look around and see the damage caused by these disasters. There are more',NULL,NULL),(62509,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/The Underground - September 3, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 16:06:16',NULL,'This is the first episode of the Underground DJ, a weekly program hosted by Alice Ophyle. The Underground DJ and Oddie are two of the brightest lights in the community, and they\'re here to share the latest news about community food.\n\nFood Equity With Dignity: Takes high-quality fresh produce and food destined for landfill and transforms them into tasty take-home-gourd. Food offers a dignified, nourishing food source, no matter one\'s economic status. For more information, visit FEWD.org or follow community food on Facebook. Alice invites you to join her on Sunday nights when she travels through the Looking-Glass and follows the music wherever she may take it on CFRU',NULL,NULL),(62510,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/The Underground - September 2, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 15:44:13',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62511,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Visions fugitives - September 3, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 15:26:38',NULL,'The show is called \"Visual Fugeative\" and it is hosted by Christopher Kaylee Curry. He is the voice of the show and he and his co-host, Fangwei, play music centered around themes. The first hour is devoted to music by George Lentz, but the second hour is dedicated to music from another composer, Leo Ornstein, who is considered a \"recluse\" because he lived longer than any other living composer. He was born in 1895 in a town called Kremens in the Russian Empire now Ukraine. His family emigrated to America on February 24, 1906, and he died 96 years later in Green Bay Wisconsin',NULL,NULL),(62512,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Visions fugitives - September 3, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 15:09:33',NULL,'Fangwei and Christopher Curry co-host a weekly classical music show called \"Vigilio Fujitiv,\" which means \"The Golden Door.\" The show has a theme of \"Opus 17,\" which is the number 17 on the composer\'s or publisher\'s catalog.\n\nEach week, Fangwai and Christopher will choose a piece of music and each week, they will respond with their own pieces of the same music. The theme of the show is \"hidden artists,\" or artists who are not well-known but who are nonetheless \"largely hidden from history.\" For example, last week Fangwei chose to play music by French composer Amber Olmes, a woman of European descent who was a member of the Irish community in the nineteenth century. Fangwei also chose music by other women composers as well, including one named Maria de Gascon. The idea of playing music by \"unmasked artists\" struck Christopher, and he began to think about the composers he might play.\n\nHe realized that it was not easy to identify these artists in history, so he decided to find out if the composer of a particular piece was actually \"hiding from history\" by writing anonymously. He found out that the composer who wrote the famous 18th century piece \"Aida and G minor\" was actually a 20th century composer named Remo \"Giazzato,\" who claimed to have written the piece because he had arranged it for Albanoni. The problem, of course, is that no one is actually',NULL,NULL),(62513,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Mach Vibe Radio - September 2, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 14:49:37',NULL,'In this chapter, we learn more about welcoming week, a week-long celebration of the coming of immigrants to Canada. It is a week of activities to celebrate the diversity of people in Canada. We also learn about the Mock Vibe Radio show, which is a part of welcoming week.',NULL,NULL),(62514,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Mach Vibe Radio - September 2, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 14:24:16',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62515,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - September 3, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-08 16:30:45',NULL,'The Host of the Show introduces himself as \"Bum bum bum bum, bum bum. Bummer, Bummer. The Host and his crew are on their way to school, and they\'re bummed because there\'s not a school day today. The two guys decide to play some school songs. The first song is called \"Off to School To Start\" and the second song is \"Play School\" by Neil Richardson. The song is from a band called \"Bords of Canada\" and it\'s from a CD called \"So Can Week\" which means that whenever anyone plays a Canadian song, the person who played the song gets a check for his or her efforts.','Scenes Like Old Times airs Sundays from 2 to 4pm on CFRU 93.3 FM. The program offers features, community announcements and interviews on subjects that we feel would be a benefit to listeners. Each week we broadcast great old radio programs from the 1930s to 50s with music memories to match.','Scenes Like Old Times (Newsletter) (Website)'),(62516,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/La Buena Onda - September 3, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-05 01:16:08',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62517,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/La Buena Onda - September 3, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-05 01:16:08',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62518,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Clan Na Gael - September 3, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 14:16:03',NULL,'The narrator tells us that the shadow of the law and order in reality is the voice of a wealthy young man named Lamont Cranston. Years ago, he learned that the power of the shadow could be harnessed to cloud mens minds so that they could not see him. The narrator explains that he and his friend, Margo Lane, were the only person in the world who knew about the secret. They learned it from the Orient, where they had learned the power to cloud the minds of men so they couldnt see them.',NULL,NULL),(62519,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Clan Na Gael - September 3, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 13:49:19',NULL,'Frank Sinatra sings about love and marriage. The program then turns to a CD by Glenn Miller called \"25 All Time Favorites.\" The songs include \"Moonlight Serenade,\" \"Little Brown Jug,\" \"The Woodpecker Song,\" \"Pennsylvania 6-5000,\" \"Chatanou-Kachuchu,\" and \"Elphits.\n\nGerald Bundy sings about Duke Ellington. There will be a movie night at the Wellington Museum and Archives on Saturday night with popcorn, candy, and a Coke float. The Rick Clark collection is also showing at the museum. The show concludes with some music by Duke Ellington, including \"The Shadow\" and \"Blue Cellophane.\" The Aberfoyle fall fair is coming up this weekend. The Puss-Lynch Community Center will be holding a fair for all to view.',NULL,NULL),(62520,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Clan Na Gael - September 3, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 13:27:40',NULL,'The song is called \"Fires,\" and it\'s about a man named Johnny Jack who was a great fiddle player in his youth, but who lost his fingers playing the fiddle because of arthritis. Now Johnny Jack\'s son is a great fiddler, and the song is about the passing of that tradition from one generation to the next. It\'s also about the people who play the fiddle with \"an arm of gold,\" which means they\'re playing it with their soul.\n\nThis is the first time we hear Nemo on the bagpipe, which is more of a rebel song, but he\'s still a great musician. He also has a band from Cape Breton named High Kings, and he has a gig lined up in Colorado with a band called \"Cape Breton.\" So, yes, he\'ll be playing live. He says he wishes he were in Sherbrooke right now.',NULL,NULL),(62521,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Clan Na Gael - September 3, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 13:10:34',NULL,'On this program, John Fahy introduces himself as the host of the University of Guelph\'s live music program. He is also the proprietor of a local pub, where he performs several times a week. He explains that the program will be a mix of old and new music, all performed live.\n\nThe first song of the program is from a Newfoundland band. The next song is a love song about a man who joined the military and fell in love. The song ends with a story about a General George Custer who was stationed out West and lost his pay when he was caught traveling all the way to Kansas with his wife and had to sell some of her estate to help him. The band Fluggy Molly, Lazy Jacks, and Great Big C also perform. The show closes with a song from a movie called \"PS I Love You.\"',NULL,NULL),(62522,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Zombie Jamboree - September 3, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 12:48:37',NULL,'This is a short introductory scene about a group of people who are planning to return to their jobs after the apocalypse. The group is called the \"Zombie Jammers.\" They are all students at a school in the city. They have been preparing for a zombie apocalypse by reading books and listening to music.\n\nThey start off with a song by Lily, who sings about Desuaras, a famous Greek epic. Then they hear some more stories about how people are going back to school or work. One of the most common worries is that you\'ll never be able to return. This is something that the Plagues have been able to get over with. The band finishes off with some practical advice from Jeff Burner, who has written seven Plague Songs. Then Regina Rosenthal and Andrew Bird talk about how to pay people to stay home during a pandemic. They finish off with more practical advice. The next day is a holiday, so it\'s not like you have to go back at all. The jammers are going to play their last set for the night. So they start off by singing an anthem of',NULL,NULL),(62523,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Zombie Jamboree - September 3, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 12:27:38',NULL,'In this program, the hosts talk about the latest music available on the CFRU 93.3-FM radio station. They start with a song about intergenerational education, and then they talk about some of the new albums coming out.\n\nThe first is from Nathan McKay, who has a new album called Recess Everywhere, followed by another new one from him called Ritmo Machine. Then they play some music from the Zombie Jamboree, which was held in Guelph. The next two songs are from Warm Smiles, which is a band that does a lot of work in the service industry. They have two songs each named \"Mushburger\" and \"Boob City,\" and they play the Rolling Stones with \"Dirty Work\" . They also play a couple of songs from Lip Head, who have released a new record called Unisax, Romper. After that, the program ends with a show called Jambery.',NULL,NULL),(62524,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Through the Looking Glass - September 3, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 12:08:24',NULL,'The show begins with Alice\'s name and the title of the track. The first track is called \"Feel the Commotion\" and the second track is \"I\'m Feeling It.\n\n\" The third track was called \"The Feeling.\" The fourth track was \"Go Down a Rabbit Hole.\" The first artist on the show is named \"Dan Moxon.\" The second artist is \"Mary Beth Carty\" from \"Crossing the Causeway\" and \"Bon Garon\" and third is \"J.D.Pink\" with \"Tall Tall Trees and Sourdough Rag.\" The next artist is Glass Tiger, who is going to be honored with a Canada Walk of fame in December.\n\nThe track is titled \"Hear Me Out.\" The band is described as \"Fam in the City and the Archive\" and this is the band that has released five albums this year. The band has also had a number one single on the singles chart with \"World\'s A Bitch\" and has been playing festivals all over the country. The show is being put up on the website of the Canadian Film and Television Commission under the show pages. Alice says she hopes to see you again next Sunday.',NULL,NULL),(62525,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/This Night Wounds Time - September 4, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 11:52:27',NULL,'This week\'s spotlight is on music from the Argentine province of Corrientes, which is a hotbed of political activity. The program\'s narrator, Tanya Iyer, is a volunteer at the university and a fan of all things music. She tells the listeners that they can find her on the CFRU campus and on the 93.3 FM station in Guelph. She also tells them about the university\'s \"Ed Video\" hub, which offers free training in music production and allows students to create their own music. The narrator tells us that he\'s going to play a song by a singer named Mario Bofill who used to be a member of a political party called the Justicialist party.\n\nHe\'s still alive, and he was born in Rosario, a city in the province. The song is called \"Chamame de los etarios\" and it\'s about a man who\'s in an unfortunate situation. This is a character study, not a celebration, and the narrator is trying to figure out what happened to the man. He says he\'ll be doing another spotlight tonight on the program \"This Night Wounds time\" hosted by himself and the Christopher.',NULL,NULL),(62526,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/Backtracks - September 3, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 11:28:54',NULL,'Backtracks with Host Jennifer is a program devoted to reviving lost and forgotten tracks, rarities, and delights from the 60 to 70s. This program is especially notable on Labor Day, which is celebrated in Canada every September. In this program, Host Jennifer explains the history of Labor Day in Canada and its origins.\n\nThe first Labor Day was celebrated in 1872 by the Toronto Trade Association, the original trade union in Canada. The trade union was formed out of the need for a union to represent workers in the workplace and to organize workers in political disputes. The main reason for organizing the first workers\' demonstration was to release 24 liters of paper from the hands of a typographical union member who was imprisoned for striking to gain nine hours of work.',NULL,NULL),(62527,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/This Night Wounds Time - September 4, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 11:10:28',NULL,'In this chapter, we find out more about the geographical spotlight, which is a section of the stage that plays music from countries around the world. The first segment featured Russia, followed by Canada, China, and the United States. The second segment featured Brazil, Australia, and India. The third segment featured Argentina. The segment ended with a shout-out to the seven countries that are considered tiny by comparison to the size of the world\'s population. The seven countries include the Vatican City , Monaco , Nauru , Tuvalu , San Marino , Liechtenstein , and Marshall Islands.',NULL,NULL),(62528,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/03/This Night Wounds Time - September 3, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-03 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 10:47:26',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the show\'s structure: the first hour will be devoted to playing music that is \"off the beaten track,\" which means that it is not all that well-known. After that, however, the program will shift to a \"geographic spotlight series\" section, where it will focus on artists from a particular locale.\n\nThe first hour of this show will include music from the release of a new collection from the College of Charleston, called Continuing. The title of the album reflects a sense of \"taking up the mantle\" of those who have come before. The album also includes a tribute to Shorter, who died recently. The show closes with a new release by the same group.',NULL,NULL),(62529,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/Beautiful Druid - September 2, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 10:30:07',NULL,'The theme for the show is \"finding our way\". The first song on the new album Night Owls is called \"My Lighthouse\" and the second song is \"The Lighthouse Sounds\" which is a short piece by a new artist named Margaret Gia.\n\nThe third song is a \"Romantic Piano\" that is a piece of music that tells the listener what time it is. The fourth song is from the album \"Beauty of the North\" and it is a song about finding your way. The fifth song is by the Newfoundland group \"The Once\" and its song \"Stop and make you think\" is a very optimistic song. The sixth song is Paul Simon\'s \"Born at the right time\" which tells the story of a poor boy trying to find his way in the big city.',NULL,NULL),(62530,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Democracy Now - September 4, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 10:10:19',NULL,'The Labor Day special begins with Amy Goodman reporting that a man calling from India didn\'t come from Mississippi, Louisiana, or any other state. He came from India, calling to clean up the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina. Amy thinks that\'s unusual, considering that most of the immigrants who call on her are from these states.\n\nWe\'ll then hear from an immigrant labor organizer, Saket Sonit, about how immigrants like Sonit are being forced to work in the United States to rebuild communities devastated by disasters like Katrina. And then we\'ll hear from a young Salvadoran poet named Javier Zamora, who traveled alone from his home in El Salvador to reach the U.S.',NULL,NULL),(62533,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/31/Democracy Now - August 31, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-31 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 09:50:24',NULL,'The next day, Vice President Biden delivers a major speech on the serious impact of climate change on the country. He says that the climate crisis is real and will continue to get worse. In Gabon, the country\'s military junta announces General Brice, General Aligui and General Gama.',NULL,NULL),(62535,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/Democracy Now - August 30, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 09:30:25',NULL,'The soldiers in Gabon declare that they have seized power and have canceled the country\'s upcoming elections. The elections were marred by delays, and the opposition claimed that the vote was a fraud. Ali Ondimba, the current president, has been in office for 42 years. Critics accuse him of using the nation\'s resources to improve lives of a third of the population. The French Oil giant Total Energie is Gabon\' main distributor of oil products. As soldiers drive through the capital, residents of the country cheer them on',NULL,NULL),(62537,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Worst Responders - September 4, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 09:11:44',NULL,'In this episode, Charissa and Renee discuss the news of the day, such as the landing of the India capsule on the moon, which was published in the Canadian newspaper. They discuss the fact that news cannot be posted on Facebook, and that they will not be allowed to search for the news on Google.',NULL,NULL),(62538,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/30/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - August 30, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-30 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 08:51:32',NULL,'In this week\'s edition of the Boss Taylor Show, Taylor picks a song from the singer-songwriter\'s latest album, called \"That Was Lenny Says.\" The song is a new release by a dancer named Vera Ellen, who\'s also an actor. The song was originally called \"The First Five Times,\" but the artist who wrote it took the song\'s name from a famous song by the same artist, \"Russian Futurists.\" The first segment of the show consists of a conversation between Taylor and Leonard about the show\'s music and sports.\n\nThe show also includes a report on the Gryphons\' football team, which won its first game of the season, 33 to 10. The next segment is about a dance team called the \"Rachisil Little Ballas,\" which is one of the top junior dance teams on the circuit. In this segment, Taylor talks to Jacob, a dancer on the team, about how he got started in dance.',NULL,NULL),(62539,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/Down the Rabbit Hole - August 29, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 08:26:58',NULL,'This is Part 1 of a two-part interview with Ray Spinn, a volunteer at the university\'s campus, community and media center, CFRU. He tells us that the university is looking for people to help with outreach, like at festivals and events.\n\nThey\'re also hiring people to record public service announcements and short scripts for the show, Sounds Like Old Times. If you\'re interested in these roles, feel free to email the university at volunteer@cfr.u.ca. Another volunteer, Doug Blackwood, is the host of the show Seems like Old Times, which is a music and old-time radio show that focuses on issues that are of interest to older adults.\n\nHe\'s also looking for a part-time assistant to host the show. The assistant will interview and record clubs and events for the community outreach program. This is a full-time position that starts in September.',NULL,NULL),(62540,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Industry Tactics - September 1, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 08:07:21',NULL,'This is the final track from Mark\'s new self-titled album, Hope Animals, and he apologizes for stiffing his listeners last week. He tells them to keep in touch at friendlyrich.com. He also announces that he\'s doing some live shows, and that he needs people to be part of the outreach team.\n\nThey need people to go out and promote local events and festivals, as well as to record short public service announcements. You can join them after your shift, and they\'ll give you a high-quality microphone if you need one. If you\'re interested, you can get started by sending an email to volunteer@CFRU.ca. The show also has a special guest, Cece, who\'s going to be the new face of the show.\n\nCece\'s a local rock star, so he\'ll introduce you to some of his favorite songs. The program also has some news: meta-products like Facebook, Google, and Instagram have all started blocking Canadian news content as a result of Bill C-18. This means that you can\'t see Canadian content on these platforms.',NULL,NULL),(62541,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/Industry Tactics - September 1, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 07:11:34',NULL,'The guys are back on the Industry Tactics stage. Rich welcomes everybody back and thanks everyone for supporting the show. He thanks the guys at CFRU for having the show put on in Guelph, and he thanks them for supporting Macula Dog as well. They have a special place in the show for everyone, because they\'re playing there with Ben Mandelowitz, and Matt Cutler. Cue up, everyone. Rich is super excited to be back. He tells everyone to prepare to be dazzled, because he got to edit out some swears for his friends at the university out in Guelph.',NULL,NULL),(62543,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/New or Never - August 29, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 06:27:14',NULL,'The show introduces a number of new tracks this week. The first track is by Russian musician and singer-songwriter Keter-Levansky, whose stage name is Kedrina.\n\nThe second is by Australian DJ Golden Features, who is known for his dance music. The third is by New York-based composer Richard Orophio, who uses synthesizers to create his music in disguise. The fourth is by Montreal-based artist Liam Belle Larson, who describes his album If I was I Am as a story of selfhood and change. The fifth is by Canadian artist Matt Paxton, who released his song Southside of the west town in 2023. The sixth track is from Canadian singer songwriter Rachel Bobbit, who releases an album called Was Forgiven. The seventh is from Vancouver-based musician Jeff Berner, who has released seven new songs in the last week. This is the last song, and it\'s called Respectful child.',NULL,NULL),(62544,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/08/29/A Multilingual Affair - August 29, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-08-29 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-16 06:15:13',NULL,'The S.Tairs and the hosts begin the show with a mix of English, French, and music from around the world. The hosts discuss their trip and the diverse artists they\'ve seen. They\'re all in different parts of the world, so they\'re not sure where they\'ll be from. The show ends with the song, \"Love to Love You,\" by Chris Cox. The song ends with a shout-out to Emily. We\'ll tell you more about that later.',NULL,NULL),(62546,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dpyrwi/CAREER_-_CareerBuzzCUITfinalseptember0620239hm99.mp3','2023-09-05 19:56:56',88350115,'2023-12-16 05:11:14',NULL,'On this episode of \"Career Buzz,\" Mark Franklin, a professional career counselor, and his guest, Michel and Olivia Wagner, discuss the benefits of living as a \"digital nomad.\" They say that they\'ve been traveling to different parts of the world to do their work. They\'re also able to travel because they have their own company, which allows them to work wherever they want. They also talk about how much they like the freedom they have to move around and live wherever they like.',NULL,NULL),(62547,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/68xy2n/CAREER_-_CareerBuzzCIUTfinalaugust162023b7aps.mp3','2023-08-16 13:02:00',113554415,'2023-12-16 04:59:49',NULL,'This program is produced by Madison Communications, Inc., a New York-based public relations firm. Madison Communications is a division of Madison Broadcasting, a wholly owned subsidiary of Madison, Madison, and Co.\n\n, which is a publicly traded company. Madison is known for his pioneering work in the fields of career coaching and public relations, and he has been a member of the New York Society of Career Consultants since 1999. Madison is a certified career advisor and founder of Madison Coaching & Consulting, a firm that helps people find and keep jobs. He is also the host of the nationally syndicated radio program Career Buzz.',NULL,NULL),(62548,171,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3mkar4/podbean_versionbn1qa.mp3','2023-09-06 05:19:41',302284504,'2023-12-16 04:26:48',NULL,'The narrator tells us that the community radio station, CIUT 89, is in need of financial support. He asks listeners to contribute to the station\'s fund-raising efforts. He invites us to tune in to hear him sing a love song. He says that every day depends on how people respond to his music. He is the one who holds your hand and reminds you to not forget. He reminds you that he is here to be with you, reminding you to never forget',NULL,NULL),(62549,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/2bkwpf/September_6_2023_Global_Rhythms9dm5w.mp3','2023-09-06 15:17:07',431961989,'2023-12-16 04:08:32',NULL,'Ken Stowar is back on the air with his program, \"Global Rhythms.\" He\'s back to bring you more of his own music and storytelling. This time, he\'s joined by Amy Goodman, who\'s been a frequent guest on the program. Amy reports on the state of the world and what\'s going on in the Middle East. Then, it\'s time for \"Career Buzz,\" which is a music-based program that\'s all about people moving forward in their careers.',NULL,NULL),(62550,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8mkzyp/DrMouth_CIUTshow_sept5_2023_fullmix.mp3','2023-09-05 18:48:59',288463808,'2023-12-16 03:53:15',NULL,'The program begins with a thank you note from the listeners of the community radio station, Cient FM, for their financial support during the fall campaign. Cient urges listeners to continue to support the station by visiting the station\'s Web site at cit.\n\nfm and giving a donation. The program then turns to the opening set of the week at Dr. Mouths\' Rock and Roll Party. The song featured on the program is \"Whipping Post\" by The Allman Brothers. The music is also from the \'80s, and Cient praises Frank Zaffa for his version of the song. The band also includes a clip from \"Spider-Man\" and a couple of other music acts from the 60s and 70s.',NULL,NULL),(62559,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/vehtsy/September_3_2023_Across_the_Universe8l58k.mp3','2023-09-06 15:26:47',431961989,'2023-12-16 03:11:29',NULL,'The host of the program, Ken Stowar welcomes the listeners to the program across the universe. He tells them that it is an abbreviated program and that he will be going to Varsity Stadium until 10pm for a Varsity men\'s football game. Next week he will have a full new program. He also tells them about the life of the original host, Reiner Schwartz.\n\nHe says that he was attracted to the man because he could wax philosophical about broadcasting. He explains how he contacted him and then invited him to come and be a part of the show at CIUT. He took about four to five months to respond to his request. They had a long conversation and then they had a few more visits to the station. He said yes I loved it here I loved the people I have met I\'d like to come do a show. Then he said prophetically it will be my last chapter and so they left with that saying that they would soon get to the show rolling. In February of 2014, he began his tenure. He did nine full three hour shows.',NULL,NULL),(62560,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/epwb5v/Karibuni_Sept_3-20237nlix.mp3','2023-09-05 03:30:05',287962512,'2023-12-16 02:51:57',NULL,'New Africa opens the show with a shout-out to a festival in Hamilton, Ontario that they attended. They\'re going to hear a new track from Lorraine Klassan\'s latest album, Amampondo, a song from Emmanuel Jiao, a new song from an artist from Kongo, and a song by an artist who they just met. They also have new music from Prince Yannick, a Congolese artist, and from Kanika Traori, the cousin of Tapa. They thank everyone who came to the first edition of the Afro-jazz festival, and they hope the next one will be even better.',NULL,NULL),(62561,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5sybtg/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Sept_6_2023_podcastbsf2r.mp3','2023-09-05 05:57:35',282248880,'2023-12-16 02:26:40',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62562,212,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/4mzwmx/RobynFull.mp3','2023-09-06 02:05:45',284549980,'2023-12-16 01:08:57',NULL,'The narrator, Chris Durand, is in New York City with a message for the Mayor. He wants to know if it\'s okay for him to continue the story, even if it means that the action is cut off.\n\nHe\'s not sure what that means, but he\'s willing to listen. This is a long speech, and it basically amounts to, \"I\'m here to tell you that I\'m the most beautiful woman in the world.\" Translation: I am the queen of the world. I\'ve won a bunch of awards for being the best dressed woman. She\'s a world-renowned scientist, inventor, choreographer, fighter, and entrepreneur. She has the most decorated staff in the industry. And she\'s listed on section two or three of the',NULL,NULL),(62563,217,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/cfc2aw/CIUTSept5.mp3','2023-09-06 09:58:55',143961989,'2023-12-16 00:48:02',NULL,'On this edition of the host, David James chats with David on a Toronto dance floor. The host is a fan of the Pretenders, who are one of the most famous acts of the 80s. David and his crew are going to play a lot of Pretenders songs at the upcoming host music festival.\n\nDavid also reveals that the band was considered to be the replacement for Guns N Roses drummer Martin Chambers, who was fired by the band. David says that Martin Chambers is a laid-back guy who is probably not the problem at all. The next show will be a tribute to a band called True Confessions, a band whose name is an offshoot of a curse.',NULL,NULL),(62564,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/CFRU Playlist - September 5, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-06 17:24:19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62565,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/The Deep House Project - September 4, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-16 00:27:33',NULL,'Aaron Blair and his crew take over the basement of the CFRU building and play a mix of chill and funk music. They\'re also going to play a few more tracks from the upcoming show. Aaron tells us that he\'s a big fan of playing chill music. He says it\'s such a great way for people to get out of the house and stay out late. They start off with Nora and Pierre\'s \"Queen of Chill,\" then continue with Bob Moses\' \"Beautiful World,\" Daven\'s, Mernie and \"Mernie\'s,\" and then they end up with Dawah\'s latest \"Rolled the Dice,\" which is a favorite of Aaron\'s.\n\nThen they play a Zedd song called \"In My Head,\" followed by \"Dead,\" \"Count On,\" \"Rainbows and Dreams,\" \"Deadmouses,\" \"Zedda\'s Dead,\" and \"In my Head.\" Then they finish off the night with \"You Be Mine,\" a song by Hatcherus.',NULL,NULL),(62566,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Back in the USSR - September 4, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 23:10:24',NULL,'On July 26, a military coup was staged in the Niger nation. Since then, the new government has taken a number of unusual measures, including nationalizing the country\' mineral resources and ordering French and American troops out of the country. The American empire is not pleased with this move. Niger is rich country, full of gold and uranium reserves and the country is home to the largest U.S military base in the West Africa. According to recent polling, 78% of the people of Niger support the military coup',NULL,NULL),(62567,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Tuesday at 5 - September 5, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 22:47:13',NULL,'This week, the program covers the fall fair at Aberfoyle and other fall fairs in the area. It\'s orientation week for new students at the university, and the city is full of new people. And there\'s a lot of new traffic in the city with all the new students and new people moving in. And that\'s just the tip of the iceberg. You can read more about this program in the program notes',NULL,NULL),(62568,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/04/Ripcord Radio - September 4, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-04 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 22:30:10',NULL,'This week on the Ripcord Radio show, the program\'s host, Jim Brown, takes listeners on a tour of some of the best punk rock acts from the East Coast. He plays music from England, England, Virginia, and Canada. He also plays songs from some bands he saw perform live in the past month. The first band he plays is called Idols With Faith In The City from Bristol, England. The second band is called XTC from Swindon, England; the third is called Page 99 from Sterling, Virginia. The fourth is called the Tarleks from Vancouver, Canada; the fifth is called Dag Nasty with trying from Washington, DC. The sixth is called Seisha from New York, New York.',NULL,NULL),(62569,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/06/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 6, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-06 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 22:04:51',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62570,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 5, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 21:47:00',NULL,'The book opens with a discussion of the history of the American Psychological Association. The organization has been under attack since September 11th, when it was founded. In the aftermath of the attacks, the organization\'s leadership was ousted from power. Since then, the APA has been trying to reform its ethics standards, including prohibiting psychologists from participating in interrogations. In addition, the association has prohibited psychologists from working at unlawful sites, like Guantanamo. Over the years, the group has been subjected to harassment by members of the APA and by the military. The association\'s response has been to dismiss the group as \"opposal commentators,\" \"clowns,\" and \"collaterals.\" The group has lost many battles.',NULL,NULL),(62571,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 5, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 21:25:16',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62572,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Let’s Get Lost - September 5, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 21:08:00',NULL,'The show opens with a discussion of the latest music available on the market. It begins with the release of a new album from an Italian band called It\'s Magic. The band\'s name is Long Old Road, and they\'re known for their ability to swing. They\'re also playing a new track called Lightning Dreamers.\n\nThe group also heard from Robic, a Chicago trumpeter band, and London Brew, a London band that played Miles Davis\'s \"Bitches Brew\" album. They play a song called Future Shaman, and then they play a track from Lena\'s latest album, Pipe Dream. Next up, they hear from Pretty West, a musician from Guelph who\'s playing with his band. He\'ll be playing at the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival. Next week, the program switches to a discussion on community. The feeling of belonging is universal, and so is the gesture of greeting.\n\nWe\'ll learn more about welcoming week and how to participate in it. This is a great opportunity to save someone\'s life. On average, one person dies every three days due to a lack of an organ. If you\'d like to save a person, you can do so by signing up for the organ registry.',NULL,NULL),(62573,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Let’s Get Lost - September 5, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 20:46:41',NULL,'This program is from the \"Let\'s Get Lost\" radio program on CFRU 93.1 Scott discusses some of the music on the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival, which will take place on Saturday, September 16. The festival\'s headliner will be Francois Ull\'s Sextet, which includes the talented Aurora Neland on saxophone, and the other members of the festival will also perform. The show will also include Jonathan Blake\'s \"Passage,\" which was recently released on Blue Note Records; and Francois Borassac Quartet\'s 11th album, \"Swirl,\" which is being released on Fendi Records. The program closes with an invitation to attend the Guelph Jazz Fest.',NULL,NULL),(62574,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Humanoid Radio - September 5, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 20:26:10',NULL,'The first segment of this week\'s Humanoid Radio starts off with a song from Warm Smiles off their album Side Up. Then they have a track from Pete, followed by a track by Reuben Von Smith, then another track by Jay Zone, then one by Ford, then a track called Mad Mark.\n\nNext up is Black Dog, then they have another track called Raxmas, then Palm Skin Productions, then it\'s time for the last segment. The program begins with a description of the technology that enables real aliens to communicate with each other. It\'s been around for a long time, but it wasn\'t until the early 1900s that real aliens began using the technology to communicate.\n\nThe next segment of the program is about Nick McLean Quartet\'s latest release. It starts off on a good note with a track titled Convergence. Then we get a dub version of Strata, a remix of City Sounds, an instrumental version of Sound, a single by Demis, and a remix by Dawn Surf. Then there\'s the instrumental version by Shark. And then there\'ll be an instrumental track by Eve Egoian. And the last track is by Mauricio Poli and Eve.',NULL,NULL),(62575,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - September 5, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 20:06:00',NULL,'The second episode of the \"Cyber Gothic\" is here and this time it\'s called \"I Am the Night.\" It\'s a mix from the \"weirdest, the weirder, and the most punkiest\" of the cyberpunks. The first track is \"Night Drive EXE,\" followed by \"Fear Effect\" and \"Ocean Drive Override.\" The second track is a \"mix from previous album\" that he listened to at Nightwave, \"something like that.\" The third track is from \"I am the night. It is/I Am The Night\" and it is super hot outside.',NULL,NULL),(62576,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/06/The Stillness & The Dancing - September 6, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-06 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 19:07:28',NULL,'The two men discuss an experimental project called \"I Am Just a Pupil\" and its track \"Coronation.\" They also discuss a friend of theirs, a fellow artist at CFRU, who is doing a show in Guelph called \"Silent Sound.\" The two also discuss some of their favorite music from the past, including a track called \"For Jonathan\" by a band called \"Seal Beach.\" The song was released a few years ago as a way to raise money for a photographer who had recently died.',NULL,'An experimental sound drone, some modern composition, who knows what. The sound drone'),(62577,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/06/The Stillness & The Dancing - September 6, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-06 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 17:08:11',NULL,'The Stillness and the Dancing begins with a set of tracks from the Meander album. The first track is called \"A Tentative Understanding\" and the second track is from the collection \"Unwinding Surrender\" by artist Jason Sharp. The third track is \"The Still World\" by Constellation. The last track is a remix of reflections from the IlluteC remix collection.\n\nThe track \"The Road\" is a remixed track from \"Reflections Revisited\" by the N5MD label. The second track \"Ghostly Sounds from Grotto\" is an update of the first track. The progression of each track lured the listener into \"a kind of rhythmic reassurance\" feeling \"secure\" that the artists were guiding the listener \"into territory familiar even if \"unexpected within the tracks movement pulse in and \"out reverberating strongly\" before fading into \"haunting suggestions\" .',NULL,'A series of ambient experimental and modern composition that is always exciting and interesting to listen to'),(62578,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/06/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - September 6, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-06 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 16:55:27',NULL,'The students discuss plant genetics. The two graduate students discuss how they like to think of their work as science experiments. The students say that their work involves studying genes, which are the building blocks of life. They like the idea of genomics, which involves studying the human genome to understand how it all came to be.\n\nThe student says he likes to think about how people look, how they live, and what they are like. He says he\'s not a huge fan of genetics, but he likes the idea that people are able to look at the world through new eyes.',NULL,NULL),(62579,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/06/Radia - September 6, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-06 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 16:32:54',NULL,'This is a short introductory piece by a graduate student in the Department of English at the City University of New York. The student introduces herself as \"Katarina Smet\" and she tells us that she\'s making a short essay about the relationship between the \"I\" of the music and the \"U\" of an interview. She\'s talking about her thesis, which is about how the narrator of a story interacts with the listener. She says this essay is about the gap between the I and the U between the final product and the listener, and it\'s about her dissertation.\n\nShe asks us to listen to the essay. The essay opens with a description of the interview scene. The narrator is in the middle of a conversation with a writer named Ryder. He is a writer of fiction and non fiction about Detroit. He has lived in the city his whole life. He\'ll be able to give us some information about the city, and he\'s a thoughtful guy. He makes coffee for us with cake.\n\nHe seems like a thoughtful man, but he doesn\'t want us to ask him about his life in Detroit, because he\'d almost risked his life there. He says he\'ll put the interview off. He also says that he wants to know what inspires the writer to do something. He wants to ask what\'s up with the writer. He asks him if he wants him to go to a dinner party or a ball. The writer says he wants',NULL,NULL),(62580,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - September 5, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 16:08:06',NULL,'The first song of the day is from the latest album from Ghost Keeper, Songs for my People. The song is called \"One More Time\".\n\nThe second song is from Kelly, the third from Nakare, the fourth from Sezel Dias, the fifth from Cedar, the sixth from Nora Kay, the seventh from Garam ande, the eighth from The Constantines, and the ninth from Liam Gallagher. The show ends with a song by Master Stone. The band was formed in 2016 and released their first album Forest of Forsaken in 2018. The second album was released in 2018 and the third was released last month.',NULL,NULL),(62581,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/06/Democracy Now - September 6, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-06 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 15:49:18',NULL,'The program opens with a shout-out to the audience and the',NULL,NULL),(62583,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Democracy Now - September 5, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 15:08:07',NULL,'In this rebroadcast of the original show, Jenny Mitchell and her team talk with a long-time resident of Riverside Glen named Esmeralda Kennedy. She is now in her late 80s and lives in a nursing home called Riverside Glen. She has moved there just a few months after the pandemic.\n\nShe tells us that she has decorated her room to look like her home and her father\'s home. She also tells us about the way the nursing home screens all its residents for the pandemic and how she refused to get her daughter tested for the disease. Her daughter got two shots from the nurses and came to visit her.',NULL,NULL),(62585,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Rainbow Country - September 5, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 14:53:36',NULL,'This week\'s show is called \"Rainbow Country\" and it\'s all about local music. It\'s about a local filmmaker named Mark Tara, who\'s been working on a new documentary called \"Cured\" and is also a co-director. In this show, we\'re going to hear from a lot of different people: a local musician named D\'Bass, a local police constable named Danielle Botno and a local porn star named Karma.\n\nWe\'re also talking about the Terry Fox 5K run, which is going to be held on September 17 th . We also hear about the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival. The festival is looking for people to volunteer at the festival. If you\'d like to volunteer, head over to the festival\'s website.',NULL,NULL),(62586,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Rainbow Country - September 5, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 14:31:21',NULL,'On this episode of Rainbow Country, we get the scoop on the launch of Canada\'s film selection at the 48th annual Toronto International Film festival. Also, we catch up with the associate curator of TIFF\'s experimental film program, Wavelengths, and with Jesse Cumming, the senior director of community and audience at TIFF. Finally, we hear from Benny, the director of the festival\'s audience and community program.',NULL,NULL),(62587,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Down the Rabbit Hole - September 5, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 14:07:28',NULL,'In celebration of the upcoming Zombie Jamboree, the Canadian War Amputees\' Society invites you to join them for a Kidney Walk. The Kidney Walk is a provincial-wide movement that unites people affected by the disease to raise money to help them live healthier lives. The October 1st Kidney Walk will take place at the Guelph Country Club.',NULL,NULL),(62588,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Silver Screen Dream Machine - September 5, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 13:49:29',NULL,'On this edition of the Open and Informed Society, we pay tribute to two music icons who have died in the last week. First up is Jimmy Buffett, who died last week at age 76. Next is Steve Harwell who died just last Friday at age 56. Then we hear a tribute to Jimmy Buffett from the song Ain\'t no mystery by Smash Mouth. And finally, we hear the song The Pied-piper of Hamelin from the 1957 movie The Hermits. This is notable because it\'s the very first movie not shown live.',NULL,NULL),(62589,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/New or Never - September 5, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 13:06:55',NULL,'The Paramorph Collective is a Canadian band formed in 2007 that makes original music composed in the style of Canadian composers Rodneyn Sharman, Linda Hatlin Smith, and George Margot. The band\'s first release is called \"New or Never\" and it\'s a Canadian experimental music record. The songs on the record are all original compositions, arranged by the band and they all sound very different from one another. The first song is by Bebel Gildo, the daughter of the famous bossa nova singer Joao Gilberto, who is also a member of the band.\n\nThe second song is \"Ojala,\" by Bobby Bazzini, a French- Canadian singer-songwriter. The third song is from Bush Tetras, a New York City-based punk band. It sounds like they\'re playing a song called \"Too Many Creeps,\" a song they wrote in 1979. The fourth song is a cover of \"Appaloosa Bones,\" a work by Gregory Isaacov. The fifth track is \"Mon Mondo Tempo,\" an album by the duo Stephen and Thomas Lind, known as \"Freak Heat Waves.\"',NULL,NULL),(62590,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Under the Needle - September 5, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 12:50:19',NULL,'The band IlaBamba has been making music for over a decade. They\'re based in Portland, Oregon, and they\'ve been touring with artists like the Lumineers, Decemberists, Los Lobos and others. They have a new album out called Lucha, which means \"to persevere.\" The title track, Mujeres, is dedicated to her mother. The album also has themes of healing and living. The band also has a live session with singer/songwriter Ela Bamba, who played a song on the new album.',NULL,NULL),(62591,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Solipsistic Retreat - September 5, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 12:27:02',NULL,'Byron and his crew are back on the program, and Byron is blown away by the music of a guy named BP Hughes. Byron says he went to see the guy play and it blew him away, and he knew the guy liked \"industrial music\" . He did not expect to find an angle grinder in a small cafe, but he did find one. He says the guy invited him to make a bunch of stuff for Drone Day, and that\'s about it.\n\nThey\'re looking forward to the future. Byron mentions that he forgot to mention that Gashrat had a distorted jam session on the July 26, 2011 edition of their radio EP. So Byron is now going to start listening to \"Metal on Metal\" , which is a very long list of metal songs from different eras . Then he\'s going to play the first four songs from \"Anvil,\" which he thinks is a compilation of all of the songs from that band.\n\nHe\'s also going to do a little bit of reminiscing about how he skipped \"shoe days\" in order to listen to these songs. The guy is called Bahamudah, and his name is also Byron. Byron is the host of a show called \"To Know the Land,\" which is about how people can deepen their relationship with the land.',NULL,NULL),(62592,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/Solipsistic Retreat - September 5, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 12:08:36',NULL,'The show begins with a mix-and-match of songs from two different artists. The first song is an original by Jesse Hill, and the second is an instrumental by Taj Mahal. The song is called \"Upu Padu,\" and it was originally composed by the late Jesse Hill. The second song is \"Wake Up\" by Gob, from the 2007 album Muerto Vivos.\n\nIt was originally released in the same year as the first two songs. The third song is a \"weird\" song, which we learn is from the same album as \"Wake up.\" The song \"Gob with Dead And Love\" was released in 2007 as the third track on \"Muertoss Vivos.\" It was released as the \"weird one.\" We learn that Gob had photo shoots where it used to hold sledgehammers and then later on had paparazzi following them.\n\nThis is not what happened, but it is not that funny, because also it does not make sense. The show ends with a song by Blur, called \"The Heights,\" which is the end of the first song. The other songs on the show are from \"The Ballad of Ballad by Blur.\" They include \"The Everglades,\" \"The Great Escape,\" \"Entertain Me,\" and \"The Hills.\" The show closes with two songs by the band Big Black, \"Barbarian\" and \"Green Cover.\"',NULL,NULL),(62593,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/05/A Multilingual Affair - September 5, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-05 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 11:55:46',NULL,'This week\'s guest is MacCatee, host of Morning Soul Shake-Up on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM. He\'s joined by a few other guests, including a new artist named Samuel Grande, who\'s working on an abstract painting called Out of the Blues.\n\nThis week on Morning Soul-Shake-Up, Mac Catee talks about the 15th annual Community Book Sale, which runs from September 20 to 24. This year\'s sale is a month early, which means it\'s more convenient for people to come pick up their books. This is a great opportunity for the community to support the library, which has raised more than a million dollars so far. There\'s also a lot of helpful information on the sale\'s website, including how to donate, volunteering, and how to find out about the sale schedule. In addition, the Friends of the Public Library has earned the 2023 Guelph Community Builder Award for the arts.\n\nThis means they\'ve been able to advocate for the library for 20 years, and that\'s earned them a spot in the 2023 World\'s Greatest Libraries Hall of Fame. Mac Cate also talks about welcoming week, which is a week-long celebration of immigrants and immigrants\' rights in Canada. Also, there\'s a new block on Facebook and Google that\'ll be making it harder for Canadians to see news from the University of Guelph\'s social media accounts. So, to continue to support CFRU,',NULL,NULL),(62594,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/02/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 2, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-02 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 11:27:57',NULL,'Welcome to a special live broadcast from the University of Guelph, where students and their families are gathering to celebrate Move-in Day.\n\nHost Renee and co-host Carissa are at Brannion Plaza to watch the day unfold. They\'re excited to see the students and parents gather, but they\'re also excited to hear about the many services and food options available in the University Center, where they can pick up their student cards. They also discuss the many dining halls that are open, and what they should do after they\'ve moved in. The students should go to the dining halls and pick out the best one for them. They can then walk around the campus and check out the services and amenities.',NULL,NULL),(62595,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 11:10:16',NULL,'In this program, the CFRU students discuss the music they play on their station, CFRU FM. The students discuss different kinds of music and how they play it. The first song they play is a very light, dance-based song called \"Hyacinth\" by a local artist named Serpent. They play other great music such as \"Not There Yet\" by \"Dead Broke\" and \"Horns Arising\" by Black Mountain. They also play some local bands. The program ends with a shout-out to the two students who have been destroying their station every week.',NULL,NULL),(62596,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 10:50:32',NULL,'The students at the University of Guelph are listening to CFRU 93.3FM, a local community radio station, which they call \"Guelph\'s Local Campus Community Radio Station\" or \"GCU-GPRS.\" They are also listening to the 93.3 FM and 93FM, which are both local stations. The students are also being introduced to some of the local artists and bands that they will hear on the show, including \"Bonnie Trash,\" \"Richard Laviolette,\" \"Hollow Hooves,\" and \"Gulph Electric.\" The students welcome the students to the university, which is home to the \"local campus community radio stations\" .',NULL,NULL),(62597,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 10:31:15',NULL,'DJ Double D and the CFRU staff talk about the students and parents that they have talked to over the past few hours. The show will be winding down, but he promises to come back with some great programming. He is disappointed with the DJ because he has no views and has no friends or family. He has heard that the DJ is emotionally distant and that he has even tried to change the universe through a \"love revolution\" .\n\nThe host of the show says that he hopes everyone on campus is having a great weekend. He adds that there is going to be a great live music event happening tomorrow. The DJ says that it will be the \"move-in weekend\" and that the music will be all new and exciting. He mentions that he will be playing lots of new music from the three bands that will perform at the show.',NULL,NULL),(62598,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 10:12:11',NULL,'The students at the university are talking with the students at Brannion Plaza. The students are all new students, and they are all excited to be going to school. One of the students is named Katie, who is about to embark on a new adventure with her brother, Thomas. The dance brothers are about to leave home to go to college, but they will not be returning home. The brothers are excited about their new adventures, and one of the brothers is studying child studies. The boys name is Applesauce, and the dance brothers ask him a question about children. He answers that he is looking forward to not having his sister around, and Freedom!\n\nThe students then go on to talk with Shiva, an international student who is studying engineering. He is from India, and he is excited about coming to Canada. He says that he looks forward to his first snow, which is called a \"winter wonderland\" because it is so beautiful.',NULL,NULL),(62599,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 09:47:28',NULL,'This is the second part of a three-part program. The first part introduces the listeners to the station, and the second introduces the program\'s host. The host explains that the program will be broadcasting live from a public space called the Berenyun Square, where students, parents, and students\' families can gather to talk. The program will also be conducting short interviews with students and their families about their first day at the university. The students will be introduced to the host, who will then give the listeners a tour of the campus and its new residents.',NULL,NULL),(62600,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-15 09:12:02',NULL,'Welcome to the \"Move-In Weekend\" program at the University. It\'s a special time for students to move in to their new homes. This particular program is a shout-out to all of the students who are queer and/or trans and are planning to move to the university.\n\nThe program\'s host, a student named Lydia, is a queer woman who came out to her family when she was a student at the university, but she\'s also a good advocate for the university\'s resources for queer students. Lydia tells us about the resources on campus, which include the Sexual & Gender Diversity Advisor, a chat line, a newsletter, and a weekly discussion group. She also tells us that there\'s an awesome resource called \"Gulphage Queer Quality,\" or \"GQE\" . GQE is a little shop where students can get free coffee, tea, buttons, and other things they need to be themselves.\n\nIf you ever find yourself in the university center, there are also games and buttons to play. Lydia also says that she\'ll be back in a few minutes to talk more about her experience. She says she went to college from 2011 to 2016 and moved into the best student housing on campus , which is called Lampton Hall . She had a great time there, and then she came back to work at CFRU. Lydia says she loved the university so much that she decided to return.',NULL,NULL),(62601,3291,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/01/CFRU Move-In Day Broadcasts! - September 1, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-01 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-15 08:52:27',NULL,'Welcome to the station in Guadalupe, where Odisha is the new marketing and outreach manager for CFRU 93.\n\n2 FM. He is also the guy who\'s going to be blasting music to the students in Brangin plaza. He\'s also going to have a dance party there. Odisha tells us that he\'s here to greet the new students. He also tells us about the cannon that\'s painted on the side of the university building.\n\nIt\'s called Old Jeremiah, and it used to be used in the 1812 War. But it\'s been around since then. The cannon was painted all over the university. Odisha says he\'d like to invite the students to join them for some music. The students are in their first week of classes, and they have seven days to get to know each other before classes start.',NULL,NULL),(62603,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dk6xfh/pp_sep_3rdb3ctp.mp3','2023-09-08 18:21:03',287962512,'2023-09-10 02:44:06',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62604,156,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/6eiapn/pp_aug_279tvhp.mp3','202