'2023-09-10 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 14:03:58',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62721,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Mach Vibe Radio - September 9, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 13:53:35',NULL,'This episode consists of a series of mock-interviews with various members of the Two Rivers community. In the first half of the show, we hear the voices of Miles Costello, Solomon, Wynne Badu, Roche, and others. The second half is composed of these voices, along with others from the community. The mock interviews are meant to be a commentary on the community and its people.',NULL,NULL),(62722,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Visions fugitives - September 10, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 13:09:01',NULL,'The show opens with a description of K. Gompa, the title of a new song by the Albertans, which is a reference to the location of a hut where people gather to drink, smoke, and sing. The musicians sing a number of songs from the repertoire of Ella Fitzgerald, Chick Webb, and others. The opening song is \"When I Get Low / I Get High,\" a song about getting high when you\'re in poverty.\n\nThe show concludes with an announcement of the concert, which will take place on September 22nd at the Gwefs Little Theatre at 7pm. Tickets are $25 or $20 for those under 12 and are free. For more information, visit tragedyandmusics.com. The wind down begins with Junior Boys, Hot Chip, Joe Hirtler, and the Rainbow-Seekers. The band then goes on to Say She She, Night from their latest album, Perfect, Captain Planet, and Taj Bethel, and then Ben Bomer and Nils Hoffman, Malu, and Breathing.',NULL,NULL),(62723,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - September 10, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-08 16:16:56',NULL,'The students discuss their school years. They\'re in grades 7 and 3 respectively. Oliver is in grade 7, and Jake is in grades 6 and 7. Oliver says that he\'s now considered intermediate, meaning that he can go to the club and sports and stuff. Jake is now in grade 3, though, and that\'s the first time he\'ll ever hear the word intermediate. Oliver asks if he has a science teacher, and Jake says he doesn\'t. They talk about the ABC\'s, and a song that they\'ll hear today. The song is called \"Common Things That Have a Number,\" and it\'s a rhyming list of the most common things that have a number. For example, if you think of the number 1, there\'s one person and then one person thinks of the same thing. For instance, if the first person thinks that there are only two people, then the second person thinks there are three people. The third person thinks the same way. The fourth person thinks two people have four eyes. The fifth person thinks four people have three fingers. The sixth person thinks three people have five fingers. And the seventh person thinks five people have six fingers. Then the eighth person thinks eight','Oliver: I\'m now in grade seven. Jake: What\'s new about grade three? That I don\'t have a mean science teacher. Dave Rich singing about his school blues in the year 1952. The alphabet has 26 letters, but with only nine numbers and a zero, 10 figures.','Oliver is in grade seven. Jake is in third grade. Dave Rich sings about his school blues in the year 1952 '),(62724,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/La Buena Onda - September 10, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-11 15:49:47',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62725,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/The Underground - September 9, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 12:47:00',NULL,'This episode is called \"Sounded Out Together\" and is hosted by Ad Council. It is a conversation about community power. It\'s hosted by the Underground Show, a weekly program on CFRU 95.3FM in Guelph. The Underground Show is a great way to start your day. It has a great name: it\'s called the Sounded Out Show because it is all about community. You can find out more about it at soundedout.\n\norg. You\'ll hear more about Silence, a new music venue in 2023, on this episode. Silence is a community-based organization that provides creative space for artists, creatives, and the like. They\'ve just opened a second location in 2023 at 46 Essex St. In 2023, Silence will be open from 9am-5pm for $100 per day. So, if you\'d like to start a workshop, host a dance party, organize a conference, or just have fun, you can',NULL,NULL),(62726,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Visions fugitives - September 10, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 12:29:53',NULL,'It\'s grandparents day, and the show starts off with a shout-out to the listeners. The theme of the show is \"Building a Community Where Everyone Feels They Belong\" , and this is a great segue to talk about welcoming the immigrant community.\n\nWe learn more about welcomingweek.com and how to become involved. The program ends with a song about the year 1980, which is the year of your birth each week and a song by XT, Moscow Man. The song is called \"Myths Still Exist\" and it\'s a reference to the fact that the human race has evolved over time. This is a good segue into talking about how everything has changed in the last 40 years. The point is that humans have evolved over the years and this evolution informs everything that they do. The track ends with the words \"Please Allow Me To Show You Something\" .',NULL,NULL),(62727,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/La Buena Onda - September 10, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-11 15:50:03',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62728,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Clan Na Gael - September 10, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 12:07:56',NULL,'The band begins with a song by Enya, who has become one of the most popular female artists in the world. The song is called \"Paint the Sky,\" and the lyrics are, \"Out of the woods / Sweet is the tune.\"\n\nThe song was written by a friend of Enya\'s, and she gifted the musician the song as a gift. The band finishes off with Alison Debson\'s song \"Sweet,\" and then goes on to play a song called \"A Fine Line\" by Heather Rankin, a singer from Northern Ireland who has had some trouble in her family. The group also plays a song from Barto Nilsmack\'s \"Step Dance with Lucy,\" a song in which Andrea, the lead singer, has married a wealthy businessman.',NULL,NULL),(62729,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Clan Na Gael - September 10, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 11:51:05',NULL,'This is a two-song program. It begins with the voice of John Fahy and moves on to a Celtic music program. The program is a tribute to some of the great voices in the music world. It also includes some instrumental tracks. He begins by saying that he loves the voice. He is happy to be able to share some of his own music with the audience.\n\nHe then talks about a number of people who have recently died. One of them was Bruce Guthrow, a well-known singer-songwriter in Cape Breton who died young. He will play a song for him shortly, and then it will be on to his ladies. John also tells the audience that he has just celebrated his wedding anniversary with his wife. They went to the Royal Hall and had a nice wedding anniversary and their daughters met them in Toronto. They also went to Cabbage Town festival. The name Cabbage Town came from the English and Irish Protestants who lived there back in the 1800s and 1850s. They lived in the area because the Irish Protestants were poor. They had pigs and chickens and they grew Cabbages in the yard.\n\nHence, the name. The area is now a desirable area with lots of Victorian houses. The festival is held every September. The neighborhood is awash with garage sales and they have gone there for many years because they had family living there. But it is a lovely place and worth a visit if you come to it. The music ends with a song about a storm.',NULL,NULL),(62730,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/This Night Wounds Time - September 11, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 11:30:46',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the music featured on the program. The program is hosted by The Christopher Curry, a musicologist from the University of Guelph in Ontario, Canada. The show is dedicated to a particular artist from Catamarca, a province in Argentina. The music featured is by a singer named Margaritas, who was born in the year 1911 and died in 1983. She is known for her song \"Mepera de Valguna\" from her recent album, \"Palapalapero.\" The program ends with a closing announcement about the program\'s continuing.',NULL,NULL),(62731,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/This Night Wounds Time - September 11, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 11:11:28',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the geographical spotlight, which is a series of stories that the host does within a show about different places in the world and the people who live there. The first segment in the series is called Discovering Russia, which focuses on Russia because it is the largest nation by area. The next segment is called Canada, and the third segment is China. China is the third largest country by area, according to the host, and he includes Taiwan in the first segment because of the fact that it has never declared independence. The show then moves on to the United states of America, which consists of the 50 states and the District of C.',NULL,NULL),(62732,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/This Night Wounds Time - September 10, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 10:52:08',NULL,'The show is called \"This Night Wounds,\" and it\'s the debut of a new show on a new radio station. It\'s called \"The Christopher Curry\'s Late Night Experimental Radio Show.\n\n\" The show will be a mix of experimental and mainstream music, but it will be done in a way that\'s \"not limited to any genre of music\" . The show\'s first hour will be all experimental, and the show will focus on \"geographical spotlight series\" , which means that they\'ll be playing music from a certain place in the world . This is all very experimental, but there are times where you have to do it because there aren\'t a lot of options for experimental music. For example, he says, he used to do a show where he had to play music in a province of Brazil that was known for being \"a hotbed of a kind of local equivalent of the country music, which was kind of a \'local equivalent of\' country music.\n\n\" The first hour of this show will also feature some music from the Redshift Records label, a label that \"is really good label\" for experimental classical and experimental music . We also learn that the show is going to feature a new release from Emilia Lebel, a Canadian composer who\'s been at Central Florida State University for the last few years.',NULL,NULL),(62733,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Backtracks - September 10, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 10:31:47',NULL,'Backtracks is back with host Jennifer Pound. She\'s bringing back some of her favorite music from the 60s, 70s, and 80s. This time, she\'s got a bunch of tracks from the \'50s and \'60s. She starts off by playing a track from the 50s called \"I\'m Losing tonight\" by a band called The Great Scots.\n\nThe band is from Nova Scotia, and they\'re famous for wearing Mohawk hair back then. It\'s kind of weird, but they did it in the mid-\'50s. The track is called \"Lost in conversation,\" and it\'s a single from the early days of rock and roll. The flip side of the track is the B side. And yeah, it\'ll be a big hit. Next up is a track called \"Wrong, my friend\" by the Los Angeles folk band Thawing Shield. And that\'s from their self titled album from 1967. It has some weird syncopation going on.',NULL,NULL),(62734,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Zombie Jamboree - September 10, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 10:11:43',NULL,'The second hour of Jamboree Day is over. The music is great, but the theme of the day is grandparents. It\'s music for the whole family. The first track is from the year 19 and it\'s called \"Zombie Myths Still Exist\". This is a reference to a song called \"Moscow Man\" by Dexplicit. The second track is a 40 year anniversary track from CFRU. This is the year when the station started broadcasting. The other tracks include \"Making Plans for Nigel\" from XTC, \"The Snap, Crackle, and the Pop\" from Dexplicit, \"Mystical Rhapsody\" from Millennial Rhapsody, and \"Dexplicit with a Track called Zombie Myths still Exist\" from FM Junkie.\n\nThe last track is about how the world has changed over the past 40 years. This makes the listeners think about the importance of grandparents. They also hear about the teachings of Magic School Bus, Miss Frizzle, and Meta One. Finally, they hear a track called \"Please Allow me to Show you Something\". This track was about how Grandfathers are important. The Master who could hear grasshoppers compliments of \"Meta One\" in the track \"Conflict\". The masters of the Magic Bus and Miss frizzle brought to the station \"Data Banks\". Finally, the Jamboree Day has come to an end. They have one more song to play. This one is called \"The Rural Alberta Advantage and our Love\". The song has a big voice and lots of choruses.',NULL,NULL),(62735,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Through the Looking Glass - September 10, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 09:48:07',NULL,'The show goes up in the archives on the show\'s page, and a contest is still going on for the back catalogue of the church of trees on a usb stick. The next band on the docket is New Chance, and they play a new track called \"To The Edge.\" Chad Van Galen also plays a new song called \"Sleeps in Ice.\" Disorientation week is back, and Oprick Wealth and the University of G graduate coalition are excited to hold it on the university campus from 18th to 21st of September 2023. Disorientation is a time when people come together to make decisions about their lives.',NULL,NULL),(62736,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/10/Zombie Jamboree - September 10, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-10 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 09:09:37',NULL,'Bruce is back in Canada and this is the \"Zombie Jamboree,\" a dance party he organized with his friends. The first piece of music was an old piece of \"Old Music\" that your grandparents probably would have danced to.\n\nThe second piece was a \"jazzier driftier\" piece called Huw and Bennett now, and the third piece was an \"artist playing stretched to their thoughts\" piece by Richard X Bennett, a pianist from England. The fourth piece was by Kathleen Edwards and \"Dust to Dust,\" a song from her new album. The fifth piece was the \"Masked Mystery Cowboy,\" by orvillepeck. The sixth piece was \"Symbolism,\" a poem about life. The seventh piece was called \"The Feeling of Community,\" and the eighth was \"Welcome Every New Neighbor,\" a proclamation that Canada is becoming a more diverse community.',NULL,NULL),(62737,3445,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Bike the Night! - September 9, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 08:46:15',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62738,3445,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/09/Bike the Night! - September 9, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-09 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 08:34:07',NULL,'This week on the program, HeartRisk discusses the need for people to become organ donors. According to the Canadian Medical Association, only 31% of Canadians have signed up to donate their body parts. This means that, on average , one person in Canada will die every day because of an organ shortage. If you\'re interested in becoming a donor, you can go to BeAnorer.ca and take two minutes to sign up. Also, the program will be broadcasting live from Market Square during \"Bike the Night\" between 7 and 9pm. The program ends with a rousing \"Hey, fellas, come on in, we\'re off to the races!\"',NULL,NULL),(62743,171,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/55tuuc/podbean_version62lxb.mp3','2023-09-11 16:17:27',230404043,'2023-12-13 08:12:04',NULL,'The narrator and the other students discuss the anniversary of the September 11th attacks. They decide to listen to music that was inspired by the tragedy. The narrator suggests that they listen to a list of artists who have written about the day. The list includes a poet, a musician, and a composer. The students decide that they will listen to the music and reflect on the tragedy that occurred on that day. It is also a day that will be remembered by all of the students. The listeners agree.',NULL,NULL),(62749,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/am2jgk/karibuni_sept_10-23754en.mp3','2023-09-12 02:55:57',287962512,'2023-12-13 07:13:06',NULL,'The narrator thanks everyone who has supported the station during its fall campaign. The station still needs your help in reaching its goal of $100K. Stephen Cole joins the show to tell you all about the upcoming festival and the earthquake in Morocco. The show also includes music from a number of African countries, including Kenya, Equatorial Guinea, Angola, and Mozambique. The narrator also tells you about upcoming events in the African community in Toronto, including a Flamenco festival and a Cora Flamenco show. He also tells us that he will be sending out a song from one of his tracks, \"Baye Faloo\", to his listeners.',NULL,NULL),(62750,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/vp4c62/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Sept_13_2023_Podcast64yaz.mp3','2023-09-11 21:27:29',285878856,'2023-12-13 06:44:18',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62751,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/CFRU Playlist - September 11, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-12 03:35:45',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62752,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/CFRU Playlist - September 11, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-12 03:35:51',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62753,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/The Deep House Project - September 11, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 06:28:51',NULL,'The show starts off with a sped up track from Adam, who we\'ll call \"Where Are We Going.\" The first song is \"Hatress is Gone,\" which could be a reference to the news of Twitter. The song is followed by \"Sunrise,\" a song that\'s been around since the beginning of the year, which is a really good song to have on your playlist. The second song is called \"Pride,\" which is also a very good song. The third song is a song called \"Emmet\'s Memories,\" which means we\'re going to hear it a lot.\n\nThe fourth song is titled \"Center of Gravity,\" and the fifth song is about \"Sultan and Shepherd.\" The show closes with \"Othello and Taylor\'S Round,\" which sounds a lot like the song you heard earlier in the show. The show ends with a shout-out to all the people that showed up to watch the show, and we hope you enjoyed it. The next time you\'re in the area, check out the Tri-Cities Sync Society\'s \"Open Night\" at AOK Bar in Kitchener.\n\nWe\'ll have more info about the show in a few weeks. FYI: The show is free and open to the public, so you can check it out on Facebook or on Soundcloud. If you\'d like to see more of the program, you can find it on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM campus and community radio station, Guelph',NULL,NULL),(62754,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Blues Around the Block - September 11, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 06:06:02',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62755,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/to know the land - September 11, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 17:43:25',NULL,'The Underground Man begins his second song, \"The Top Soil . . snapping turtles in quietly brushes will grow\" . In this song, the Underground Man says, \"the top soil . will grow in places where they stolen the top soil.\" He goes on to say that, \"Toronto was born for 10 chillings old crooked feet like dominoes\" , which is a reference to the Ten Chillings of Jim Crow. He then turns to an album by a band called the Bolrushes, which he describes as \"an album of bull rushes.\" The album was released in response to the eviction of the Indigenous Peoples of Brantford by the Ontario Provincial Police and the destruction of native lands by a company called Target. The album is inspired by the resistance of the Iroquois people to this development and is dedicated to celebrating the \"colonization day\" of this country. The underground man says that he has been in Toronto to see shows and he hopes to be able to continue playing music in the future, but he\'s worried about the weather. He says that the wind is blowing from the west and it feels 38 degrees outside. He\'s been out exploring and looking for bugs all day, and he came up with the idea of recording a song in his journal about spittle bugs, a family of freshwater insects. The spittle bug is a member of the same family of insects as leafhoppers, which means it\'s basically the same group of insects, except',NULL,'The Underground Man is recording a song about spittle bugs, a family of freshwater insects'),(62756,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Big Sis Radio - September 11, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-13 05:11:25',NULL,'The next time you hear Cece, he\'s talking to you on a local radio station. He\'s the host of a local music show called Big Sis, which airs every Saturday on CFRU.\n\nIn this episode, Cece talks about some of the upcoming events in town. He mentions that he\'ll be broadcasting at the upcoming Hillside Festival, and that he has a new track for you from the art and music collective SheBad. He also mentions a women\'s music showcase coming up on August 4 at Onyx. All the proceeds from this show will go to Wellington Women in crisis, a local organization that helps women who are homeless.',NULL,NULL),(62757,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Ripcord Radio - September 11, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 04:53:19',NULL,'This is the second and final episode of the series. It starts off with a song by The Randy Bastard. It\'s a cover of Smells Like A Crustpunk Show by The Bastards. The song is on a split 7-inch that has a recording of the Bastards singing the song.\n\nNext up is a band from Canada called the Ravens. They played the third day of New Friends Fest in Toronto. They\'re on an album called Cube, which has a bunch of different bands in it. The first band they heard was called Jocasta. It comes from a split album with another band called Villain. The second band is called Jetsom. They are on a compilation called Do You Know where your friends are. The third band is from Montreal called Mostly Jetsom, who played on the second day of the festival. Their lead singer even threw down in the crowd during their set, which was a first for the two of them.\n\nThe next two bands we hear are from a friend of mine named Carl who traveled from California to see them. They come from albums called Sassafras asked and Approximation of Human. And finally, we hear from a band called Upper Decks. They have a song called The North End from their 2010 album. It is a cover song by Joie deVive with Upper Decks, which is from their album The North end. The last band we hear is called Life in Vacuum. They play on Do You know where your friend',NULL,NULL),(62758,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - September 11, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 04:30:50',NULL,'The first song on the show is a psychedelic post-punk track by Lighting Canyons called \"Mr. Curious\" from their latest album, Collapse the Chaos. The song is about a band of time travelers who explore the past through time. Allies were eliminated, the past was obliterated, and the future was to come.\n\nThe narrator says that the song is really good and recommends it to anyone interested in experimental music. In the next few tracks, the group listens to a mixture of hard rock and ambient pieces. The first track is by P. Dory, the second is by Nico Girois and the third is by Hunky-Dory. The group also listens to an album called Reverie, which is all about clouds.\n\nThe fourth track is a tranquil piano piece by Cleo-Loom and Yannick-Desrulo. The Montreal duo Chloe Loom and Yonnick-Dorulo recently released an album titled \"The Garden of a former House-Turned Mansion,\" which is described as \"very old time music\" with its lyrics. In this set, they listen to \"Letter Three,\" a collection of short words from the album. That\'s it. We\'re back with the narrator, who says he\'s been listening to music lately.',NULL,NULL),(62759,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Blues Around the Block - September 11, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 04:08:32',NULL,'The narrator begins his story by describing the first few acts of his set, which consisted of a mixture of live music and pop-up windows.\n\nHe tells us that he started off with Calgary singer-songwriter Donald Ray Johnson\'s \"The Last Two Dollars\" and went on to the \"Phantom Blues Band\" and the \"her aching back\" of the Phantom Blues. Then he tells us about the other acts in the set, including \"Coco Montoya\" from his \"August 2023 release\" and \"Big Dave\" and his \"Ultrasonics\" and Ben Racine\'s band from Montreal.\n\nHe says that he likes the music because it reminds him of the times before technology and cell phones. He also says that in that set he had \"Morgan Davis\" with \"What Do Dat Do Do\" and Brian Blaine with \"The High-Tech Blues.\" He says he thought he was making his wife happy, but that she had changed his life and made him \"something rough and',NULL,NULL),(62760,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Democracy Now - September 11, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 03:12:57',NULL,'Amy Goodman reports that a 6.8 magnitude earthquake has struck Morocco, killing 25,000 people. In addition, the African Union has announced that it has joined G20. The African Union joins the G20 as world leaders wrap up the summit in India. The declaration does not explicitly condemn Russia for its invasion of Ukraine',NULL,NULL),(62761,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Worst Responders - September 11, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-13 02:53:09',NULL,'The show opens with Charissa and Renee, two students at the College of Staten Island, talking about the fall, which is coming. They\'re both excited about the change in the weather, but they\'re also worried about how they\'ll manage to get around the new school year. Charissa says, \"You just got to roll with it\" , and that\'s what she did in the summer, when she could just go to the park and not worry about getting in trouble. Now, she says, she\'s worried about being able to do the same things in the fall. She\'s glad that she\'ll be able to go out, because she thinks it\'ll take a lot of work to be on the same level as everyone else.',NULL,NULL),(62766,180,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/6tddba/HOWL_SEP_12_20237zswi.mp3','2023-09-13 10:41:56',56666407,'2023-12-13 02:30:14',NULL,'The roots up. From the roots down. CIUT 8',NULL,NULL),(62767,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/j3juvt/DrMouth_CIUTshow_sept12_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-09-12 18:26:47',290030528,'2023-12-13 02:14:29',NULL,'The program begins with a thank you note from the listeners of CIUT FM for their financial support during their fall campaign. The station is still in need of more money, so listeners can help by visiting the station\'s Web site and giving a donation.\n\nDr. Mouth is the guest on the program. He is here to cure everyone\'s ills for a week. He promises to purge their soul. He tells them that he will kill himself together. He says that the demon is responsible for stone dealing. He also says that he has a statue in a girdle. Feeling free, feeling good. Feeling good, feeling free. The program then turns to some of the music that has been played on the station. It starts with the first album ever played on this program, called Berlin Express by the Great Octopus.\n\nIt\'s his new album, Experiment Perilous. He\'ll also be performing at a big release party for it on October 5th. Also, he\'ll be showing a movie called Night of The Demon. James says that Captain Beefheart has to lay some Beefheart on them to wake them up. He plays one of his favorites, called Trout Mask. It is from his Doc album in 1980.',NULL,NULL),(62768,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/y733hh/September_13_2023_Global_Rhythms9wci5.mp3','2023-09-13 14:03:08',431961989,'2023-12-13 01:11:33',NULL,'Ken Stowar is back on the air with his weekly program, \"Global Rhythms\" on the Canadian International Broadcasting Union. The program begins with some music from the Caribbean, and ends with some more from the West Indies. Ken invites listeners to send him an email with a description of the music they\'d like to hear. He\'ll send you a link to the show\'s iTunes page.',NULL,NULL),(62769,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3q5zqm/CAREER_-_CareerBuzzCUITfinalseptember1320239ayfm.mp3','2023-09-13 16:39:35',86308878,'2023-12-13 00:48:26',NULL,'CIUT FM is grateful to everyone who contributed to the fall campaign. If you didn\'t donate yet, we need your help. We still need your support to reach our $100,000 goal. Stephen Armstrong welcomes us to the show and introduces us to Bob Duff.\n\nBob is the Executive Director of the St.Simon\'s Shelter in Cabbagetime and he\'s been homeless for over 40 years. Bob tells the story of how he came to be homeless and how he became a frontline worker for the homeless population. He holds a bachelor\'s and a master\'s degrees in journalism, economics, and education. Bob says that the song Margaritaville reminds him of Jimmy Buffett. He also says that he has developed socially within Florida.',NULL,NULL),(62775,195,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fpzffb/Dementia13RadioShow_23_09_12.mp3','2023-09-14 00:48:04',175026553,'2023-12-13 00:30:34',NULL,'On this episode of Dementia 13 , the host talks about the death of his friend, the stream-weaver, Gary Wright, who died just days before the program aired. The program begins with a song by Spooky Tooth, followed by a song from Art, which was a group he joined after he left his group.\n\nThe song is called \"Numbers from 1968.\" It\'s one of his favorite Canadian bands, and he says he\'s playing it on the show because he has a song in one of the films at the upcoming Toronto International Film Festival. It\'ll be called \"Gone and Bleed.\" The music on the program starts off with some classic British music from the early part of the twentieth century. It includes the hits from the likes of Clattoo, California Jam, Jackal, and Max Millian.',NULL,NULL),(62776,217,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ierdkr/CIUTSept12.mp3','2023-09-14 01:44:53',143961989,'2023-12-13 00:10:36',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62777,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 13, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 23:07:18',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62778,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 12, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 22:48:48',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62779,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/11/Back in the USSR - September 11, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-11 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 22:34:08',NULL,'The program opens with the announcement that the BRICS countries-Brazil, Russia, China, India and South Africa-have just concluded their fifth summit meeting in Johannesburg. The BRICS is a grouping of fast-growing countries that have joined together to form an alternative to the Western-led International Monetary Fund and World Bank, two international economic institutions based on the Bretton Woods system of international economic relations. The five countries have come together in order to create a new economic system based on their own domestic economic interests. The US and the European Union have placed unprecedented economic sanctions on Russia as a result of the recent war in Ukraine. This means that one third of the world\'s population is being forced to live under Western sanctions.',NULL,NULL),(62780,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/CFRU Playlist - September 12, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-14 03:45:44',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62781,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Let’s Get Lost - September 12, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-12 21:10:08',NULL,'This week\'s program opens with a new track from Fred Stride, a saxophone player from the University of Guelph. The song is from a new album by Francois Uhl, which will be playing at the upcoming Guelph Jazz Festival. The show also includes performances by Brody West, Colin Stetson, Michael Formaneke, and Melissa Pipe. The program also discusses Die Out, a community makerspace that provides tools and equipment to help people make things. The club also invites listeners to join them on Wednesdays at 8pm for their weekly music program, \"Trail Mix.\"',NULL,NULL),(62782,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Let’s Get Lost - September 12, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 20:48:25',NULL,'Scott and his partner, Scott, are jazz lovers and they\'re always looking for new music. They\'re listening to a bunch of new music this week. First up is Kind Mine, a new album by Josh Cole. The other tracks on the album are by some other artists as well.\n\nThis week, they\'ll be playing some music from the Guelph Jazz Fest. One of the artists they\'ve been hanging out to see is Lena-Alomano, who\'s playing with her band at the Art Bar on Thursday at 10pm. The band\'s new album is called Pipe Dream, and it has some really good music, including a track called Burning Gray from a player named Jamie Branch. Next up is a trumpet player named Levi Lorenzo and his drummer, Peter Evans, from New York. The last track is from a band called Trio, who are based in Toronto. They have an album called Plateau. And the last track on their last album is Magnetic Dreaming, which was recorded during their last recording session.',NULL,NULL),(62783,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - September 12, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 20:24:06',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62784,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Bridging The Social Distance - September 12, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 19:13:07',NULL,'This show is for introverts. It\'s called \"Bridging The Social Distance\" . Jenny Mitchell is the creator of the show and she\'s recorded it for a university in Guelph, Canada. She\'s also the host of a show called \"Introductory Moments\" on Facebook. The show is all about introverts and their stories. The narrator says that she started recording the show for the university in March of 2020, and the show is about the social distance between people.\n\nJenny says that one of the first episodes she recorded was about a song she was singing, and she couldn\'t really remember the words to the song. She was up on stage and she heard the audience applaud and she got up and she knew the song was going to go down. She remembers the song and the words and how she',NULL,NULL),(62785,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/The Stillness & The Dancing - September 13, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 18:51:06',NULL,'In this episode of The Stillness and the Dancing, the show\'s host, Craig Brown, talks about some of the music he\'s been listening to recently. The first hour consists of music from experimental drone artists Kuma and William Bessinski, as well as a few cuts from new releases from artists like Glaceis.\n\nThe second hour begins with some cuts from a newly released release from White Lab Recordings, a label that Brown has been playing on the program for the last few years. The release is a reinterpretation of a piece of music by a well-known ambient artist, GlaceIs. The hosts of the show were invited to participate in a live stream of the artists\' performances. The host was thrilled to be invited to the live stream and chat.',NULL,'A new album from a Glaceis is a collection of interpretations'),(62786,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Tuesday at 5 - September 12, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-12 18:27:59',NULL,'On this edition of The Hour, the host of CFRU\'s 93.3 FM, Mac Dee, introduces listeners to a number of artists, including Bruce Coburn and PJ Western, who have recently passed away.\n\nHe also introduces a new release by Jimmy Buffett, who died on September 1st of this year. He has sold over twenty million albums worldwide and his final studio album is scheduled to be released in 2023. The show also discusses the upcoming Friends of the Public Library\'s 15th Annual Book Sale, which will take place at the library on September 20th and 24th. All proceeds will benefit the library, which has raised over a million dollars so far.',NULL,NULL),(62787,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Humanoid Radio - September 12, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 18:13:15',NULL,'On this show, we\'re going to talk to a musician named Piers. He\'s a guy named Ulvi, and he\'s got a big voice. He tells us how he got into music. He explains that his path into music started when he was a kid with piano lessons. When he got to playing the clarinet, he picked up the \"B flat clarinet\" . And then he picked the alto saxophone , which is the instrument from the SpongeBob Squarepants show. But he sold the sax so he could have his current bass clarinet . So, basically, he says, music has helped him to be a \"neurodivergent queer\" individual. He also says that music helped him communicate things he wouldn\'t normally say. And he loves experimenting with sounds.\n\nAnd that\'s how he came up with the name Ulvi. It comes from a game he played on his phone when the Game of Thrones version of the show was popular. He uses the word \"owl\" to describe himself, like an owl. And now he uses the name \"Owlboy\" to refer to himself, which he calls himself.',NULL,NULL),(62788,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/The Stillness & The Dancing - September 13, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 17:11:51',NULL,'The Stillness and the Dancing is back. This time, it\'s autumn, and the weather is starting to change. This is the time of year when the seasons change, so now is the perfect time to listen to music. In this edition of the show, host Joel Cuthbert introduces us to a new release from a band called the Balloonist.\n\nThe band\'s name is The Balloonist and the music on the record is described as \"a tape worn and / hazy / glide above the English countryside / an Arcadia / that has only existed ever within the mind\". The band is based out of Winland Recordings in London, England. The music on this release is described in great detail in the liner notes to the album, \"Tarifius Trace\", which was released in late May.\n\nThe album was conceived and composed in two months on a Norwegian island, called Skollmer, during which time the band experimented with a Norwegian made organ.',NULL,'It’s a series of curations of new music that are different from any of the others'),(62789,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/Tone Zone - September 13, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 16:49:30',NULL,'The Tone Zone is a music show hosted by Matt. He and his guests listen to a variety of different music acts from the 90s. The first act is a band called Velocity Girl, who have reunited for a show in Washington, D. C. since their last show in 2002. They have a new album coming out called Everything Is Alive and they are playing a show on September 30, in New York City. The other acts on the show are: Tim Hardly Wait, Tim Tallulah, Grade School, Easter Theatre, XTC, The Left Bank, and Peter One.',NULL,NULL),(62790,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/End Credits - September 13, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-12 16:28:02',NULL,'The Nun Part 2 is here, and the two discuss it with a little bit of comic relief. The Nun is one of many parts in the \"Conjuring\" universe, and it\'s a character created by James Wan. The two also discuss some of their favorite horror parts, which are usually called \"Whatever Two\" or \"The Nun Part Two.\" It\'s important to note that some of these parts are called \"Part Two,\" while other parts are just called \"whatever two.\" The two discuss the idea of a \"new director\" learning to make good horror, and how a good horror film can lead to many more good ones.',NULL,NULL),(62791,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/B Siide Radio - September 13, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 16:06:02',NULL,'CFRU is an amazing FM radio station that\'s been broadcasting all day long. But CFRU also has an online audio feature that you can use to listen to all of their programming.\n\nYou can also make a donation to the station and enjoy all of the great features. If you\'ve been looking for a creative space, then you should check out Silence Guelf. It\'s a community-owned music venue, an art gallery, and a place where you can start your own business or start a workshop. Silence is conveniently located in downtown Guelf, so you can rent out the space and make your dream come true.',NULL,NULL),(62792,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/Trail Mix - September 13, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-12 15:46:28',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62793,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/Radia - September 13, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-12 15:13:55',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with Max, a young man who works as a model. The first part of the interview is with Radia, a group of radio stations that are bringing new and \"forgotten\" ways of making to listeners. Radia gives artists a challenge each week to make a radio that works \"across the whole Europe and beyond.\" The second part is with Max. He tells Radia that his favorite mug is not his, but that it is \"inferior because it is thick.\n\n\" He also explains that he has hoarded his favorite mugs in his room. He says that he used to like a slightly blue and white-striped mug, which was perfect for tea. Unfortunately, the sports company replaced it with a \"sports giant thing,\" which was too much. He had a \"oversized holiday romance\" with it for three weeks, but it disappeared into the \"ether.\" When he goes out to get coffee, he drinks it with his left hand.',NULL,NULL),(62794,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - September 13, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 14:54:38',NULL,'In this episode, the two hosts of the popular science podcast, \"Learn Real Good,\" discuss their show and its aims. They are excited to be in the company of Louis. The two men are both scientists, and they\'ve decided to team up to create a show that\'s all about science. They\'ve come up with a name for their show: \"We Know Some Stuff.\" The show will be all about communicating science and making it accessible to everyone. The men are excited because they\'re both scientists. They both have degrees from universities, so they know what they want to share.\n\nThey want to give the people who listen to their show a platform to share their research. They also want to provide a resource for students to understand what it means to become a scientist. They think there\'s a lot of misinformation out there about what it is actually like to be an engineer. They wonder if there are sitcoms about it, but they haven\'t been able to find one.',NULL,NULL),(62795,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - September 12, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 14:29:19',NULL,'The show starts off with a song from Blast Dead, an Japanese metal band from 1990. They have a song called Another Dimension from their debut album. From Gambia, they hear the Soto Koto band with an African Sunrise song from their selftitled album.\n\nAnd from Peru they hear Tusk with a single from their 2020 album. A week ago today we lost Guelph musician Richard LaViolette who died of suicide. The show also hears songs from Tyler J Flice, who is from London, and from Richard La Violette, who has died of an assisted suicide. Then they hear songs from an Australian punk band called The Ninth Dimension and