n a mysterious young woman named Claire enters his life, he realizes that she will inspire him to complete the piece of music and reconnect with his community.\n\nBroken Social Scene, Desus, and Lament are also featured on the soundtrack to Half Nelson. 20 years have passed since Johnny Cash died from a sudden illness. He was only 71 years old at the time of his death. He died just months later of complications from diabetes. His wife June Carter Cash died in the same month. The theme song for Thunderball, the James Bond film, is also included in this tribute to Johnny Cash. The themes for A Gun Fight and Five Minutes to Life are also included. Cash\'s music for The Gospel of Jesus is also played. June Carter sings Follow Me from the same film.',NULL,NULL),(62800,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Down the Rabbit Hole - September 12, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 13:04:36',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62801,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/13/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - September 13, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-13 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 12:53:50',NULL,'In this edition of Griffin Sports, host Leonard Squall announces that he has a release for Griffin Sports and he\'s also got some other news. He tells the listeners that he is now working with the Women\'s Basketball team. He thanks the girls for allowing him to return for another season.\n\nAnd he thanks the women for giving him the chance to come back again. We\'re back with the music. The music is going to kick things off with Matt Anderson. The song we\'ll hear today is \"Gin and Special Olympics Show\". We get a shout-out to the girls and coach for allowing us to do this again. Now it\'s time for the first segment. It\'s called \"Griffin and Special Olympic Sports Show\" and it updates you on all of the sports happening at Griffin. It also has music that updates the listeners on Griffin. The first segment is about Griffin sports and it is all about the Griffin women\'s team. The team is ranked 4th in Canada. They\'ve just won their first game, a 48-8 win over McMaster. The men will play U of t and the women will play Trent.\n\nBennett Moore from baseball is named the athlete of the week. The Griffin women are also named as the team\'s sportswomens athlete. The show ends with the layout. The layout is a little different than usual. It has a bunch of different columns with the same name on each column. So this time,',NULL,NULL),(62802,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Rainbow Country - September 12, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 12:27:01',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62804,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Rainbow Country - September 12, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 12:11:44',NULL,'It\'s time for another edition of Rainbow Country, and this time it\'s with Chris Harder. We\'re talking about the 48th annual Toronto International Film festival, which will be followed by the Brazilian queer crime drama Hole.\n\nPlus, Naomi Snikas is on the show to talk about the TIFF launch and the Canadian slate at the festival. So stay tuned for more. Welcome back to the program, and we\'re happy to introduce you to the show\'s creator, producer, and host, Mark Tara. As always, he\'s a tour guide through the program. In case you\'re wondering, Rainbow Country is a Canadian-owned and -operated radio show that airs on 12 Canadian stations. It',NULL,NULL),(62805,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/New or Never - September 12, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 11:51:06',NULL,'The music on this week\'s edition of New or Never is some of the best new music you\'ll hear in a long time. The music starts off with Kitba, a New York-based singer-songwriter. He\'s known for his sweet melodies and his unpretentious lyrics. Then there\'s Mapachi, a California band led by vocalist Sam Lasucci. Islands, a Canadian indie band from Montreal. Fran Lobo, a London-based artist, has released a self-aware self-titled album. The Nova Scotia grant recipient is diving into the spotlight with her debut EP, \"Dive Deep.\n\n\" The song Be Back Soon is about the end of a movie and the song Be Home Soon is all about being home. Other artists on the show include Blue Broderick, Diners, Jen K Wilson, Infinity Plus One , Bebel-Gilberto, Active Dark Filament, Soft Illusions, Southy, Low Heaven Sound, Collapse, and Sullen Boy',NULL,NULL),(62807,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Under the Needle - September 12, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 11:12:45',NULL,'The band\'s latest album is called \"Miracle Level\" and it\'s their 19th studio album. They\'ve recorded all of their songs in Japanese, but this is the first time they\'ve done all of the songs in English.\n\nThey feel like the pressure of getting it on the radio is so great that they have to do something special to make it sound good. For example, they\'re going to give all listeners back their money if it doesn\'t make the cut. Sounds good on the air, sounds great in the store, and sounds great on Soundcloud. They also decided to do some Japanese language lessons for everyone. The band explains that they\'ll be doing this for the rest of their lives, and they feel like they always have something to say about what\'s going on in the world.\n\nThey don\'t have a goal for what they do. They just try to be good people and learn from what they have. They play songs from their latest album and the songs from the next one.',NULL,NULL),(62808,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Solipsistic Retreat - September 12, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-12 10:54:34',NULL,'The narrator goes on to talk about the band Gob, who he says is one of the best bands in the world. He thinks that their music is really good and their lyrics are really good.\n\nHe also thinks that they\'ve been selling out since they started out as a NoFX band and then moved to post-hardcore emo, then they moved to Blink-182, then even more so in 2003. The narrator also tells us that he\'s heard a lot of music about the Arctic- Monkeys and he doesn\'t really like them. The narrator says he\'d rather pay to see Gob or Billy Talon of the Arctic Monkeys or Queens of the stone age than go to see them. He says that people only listen to the band because they are in high school, they\'re from British families, and they sound British.\n\nThat makes them sound like they have the right to be British, when really they don\'t. The author also says that David Bowie has no substance and nobody listens to his music.',NULL,NULL),(62809,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/Solipsistic Retreat - September 12, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-12 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-12 10:32:31',NULL,'On this episode of the show, Connor Moran introduces himself and the listeners to his listeners. He tells them that he\'s from Guelph and that he works for a local radio station.\n\nHe\'s here to promote a new music festival called \"Solid Cystic Retreat\" that\'s taking place in the city. He explains that he doesn\'t want to play music from any one genre, so he chooses music from all over the world. He plays music from a lot of different kinds of music, and he plays music that he thinks is appropriate for the genre. He also plays music by a band called \"Tiergarden,\" which he calls a \"freak band.\" He also mentions that the band\'s label has been taking advantage of them for a long time, and they recently signed a new deal with a major label. He says that this is cool, because it means they\'ll be able to keep their music forever, and that they won\'t have to worry about how other people are going to get their music.',NULL,NULL),(62810,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/12/A M