r Deaf - September 14, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-14 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 14:03:34',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62864,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/14/Forever Deaf - September 14, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-14 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-11 13:45:26',NULL,'This is the second set, and it\'s full of heavy metal. We start off with a bunch of noise from Canada, and then we head over to the U.S., where we hear some thrash from the likes of Cataclyst with Combustion, Chaos Carnality, Triskelion, At War With Demons, Ghosts Invictata with Sinister Obsession, and more. We also hear some noise from British Columbia, where the band Hardball is playing. Finally, the next set is all noise from Switzerland, where North Shroud is playing as well.',NULL,NULL),(62865,124,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Planet Groove - September 15, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 13:28:39',NULL,'The funky blues doctor is back with his band for a show called \"Planet Groove.\" The show is described as \"an audacious and salutary and delicious\" mix of rock, blues, and jazz.\n\nThe band consists of the doctor, a drummer, a keyboardist, and two vocalists. The first act consists of a mix of original songs and covers of well-known artists. The second act is a tribute to the Stooges. The drummer says that he saw the Stooges perform in Massey Hall in 2008, and that the show is \"the best I have ever seen\" . The other acts are the doctor\'s friends from the University of Michigan, and he says that they are \"the fabulous Stooges from Detroit.\" The doctor also says he has arranged for Bonnie Trash to perform at the EBar next Thursday.',NULL,NULL),(62866,123,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Thanks for Listening :) - September 15, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 13:09:26',NULL,'The program opens with a monologue by the show\'s host, Billy Moffatt. He explains that he just ate some cream cheese so his mouth was feeling very sick. He then goes on to tell the listeners about some of the new music he\'s been listening to recently.\n\nHe tells them that this is his first day back on the air, which means it\'s a little different than usual. He also tells them about the band Islands, which he describes as a band with a bad album cover. They have a song called \"Lifes a Joke\" and another called \"Rock and Roll\". He also mentions the band\'s new release, \"Mondo Tempo\", which came out this summer. He says he hasn\'t been paying attention to the tour schedule, so he doesn\'t know what they\'re doing.\n\nThey play songs off of their new album, which is described as being like \"tempo\" and sounding like a \"tempo.\" They also play a song from their latest album, \"Bambi Tempo,\" which sounds like it could be \"tempo 5\" from their last album. They also hear a song off of the latest album from Reak HeatWave, \"Mongmo Tempo.\" They play another song called Brain Snack. It is a song about music synthesizers. They hear other songs too, such as \"Music Mouse One\" and \"Hooked/Aluna.\" Finally, the show ends with the song \"Richard Laviolette\"',NULL,NULL),(62867,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Viejoteca - September 15, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-16 04:40:41',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62868,121,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/14/Sundowner - September 14, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-14 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 12:50:10',NULL,'The next song on the program is a track from the Swedish band The 2020 Radio Department, who released a song called Weight off of Aggressive Passive in 2011.\n\nThe first song in the show is from Eddie Evey, who played the first song off of a record called Star from the Sad Good Happy Bad Shades. The second song is from the Toronto band I\'m glad you were born. The third song is off a new release called Alien. The fourth song is a new track from Vancouver Island called My Babys Dead. The fifth song is an old song from Elaine Malone, who recorded a new song called My baby\'s dead. The sixth song is on a brand new release from the band Vancouver Islands called Formless. The seventh song is called New York Pretty.\n\nThe eighth song is another from the duo Virgo Heros, who play the second song off their EP called Kicking Out by Seven, which is now available on World Music. The ninth song is also from the group, Cowboy Junkies. They play a cover of the Sweet Chain from the Velvet Underground\'s debut album. The tenth song is one from Newfoundland singer Weary. The eleventh song is Tori Moyes. The show closes with the new EP from Sandhills called Sidelines',NULL,NULL),(62869,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Viejoteca - September 15, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-16 04:40:42',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62870,127,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/LiYghTE FM - September 15, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 12:31:04',NULL,'This episode is called \"Hellfire\" and it\'s hosted by Double D of the CFRU 92.3. It\'s all about the love revolution, and how to change the world together. The show starts off by introducing the listeners to DJ Double D, who is the host of CFRU\'s local station, LiYghte FM. He\'s been known to bring listeners 222% more hits than any other station on the air, and he\'s also known to roast chestnuts.\n\nHe says he\'ll keep the listeners updated on what\'s going on with the show so they can listen to all of the songs in one place. The first song on the show is \"To Love to Live By Mother Tongues\" by a Canadian group. Then it turns out to be \"Love In a Vicious\" Way by a great Canadian group, \"Y and S\" by Speedy Ortiz, \"Rabbit Rabbit\" by Rabbit Rabbit, \"News of Her Death\" by Selena Martin, \"Disaster Fantasies\" by \"Selena Martin,\" \"Moon\" by Domi and \"Not Tight\" by JD Beck featuring \"Master of Genres unlike many\" by Herbie Hancock.\n\nAnd then it turns into a \"rushed episode\" of the show. The listeners don\'t need to know what this is about, but it is a great way to fall in love with a show like this. Double D says he \"plays chess not checkers\" . It\'',NULL,NULL),(62871,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Digital Statik - September 15, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 12:13:46',NULL,'The show opens with a brief introduction to the program, then introduces a guest. The guest is Poetic the Poet, who is a member of the underground hip-hop community and a frequent guest on the program. He is known for his rhymes that rhyme with the \"muddle\" and for his poetic imagery. The show then turns to a song by Left Lane, which Julz describes as a \"little brainchild\" that he has \"super proud\" of. The song is about a trip through his city, \"taking in the views.\"',NULL,NULL),(62872,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Walkuman Style - September 15, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 11:14:17',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part series on Two Rivers. The first part is about the upcoming Praise the Word festival, which will take place on September 23. The second part is a little more about a guy named Rockwell. He is a regular guy in the neighborhood, who\'s super into the music scene. He\'s also super into running the two-way streets of Two Rivers, and he doesn\'t want to get in the way',NULL,NULL),(62873,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Folk Roots Radio - September 15, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 10:54:40',NULL,'This week on the show, we\'re going to hear some new music from a bunch of different artists. The first artist we\'ll hear is a guy named Richard LaVialet, who was a great songwriter and one of the most popular guys in the area.\n\nHe died recently, and we\'ve got a great interview with him from when he first came out with his album, Taking The Long Way Home, which was one of our fave albums of the year. Then we get some more music from David Francie, who wrote a song after John Prine\'s death. And then we have some more from Rachel, Eliza, and John and Sheila. And finally, we get an interview with Richard from his latest album, taking the long way home.',NULL,NULL),(62874,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Global Rare Grooves - September 15, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-11 10:24:46',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62875,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Democracy Now - September 15, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 10:10:21',NULL,'The climate and labor movement is mobilizing for the first time, using a new tactic called \"stand-up strike.\" The strike will take place at all of the major automakers, Ford, and Stellantis, and thousands of climate scientists will join them in a major march in New York City to end the use of fossil fuels. In Washington, Hunter Biden has been indicted on charges of illegally carrying a gun and Republican lawmakers are considering impeaching the president.',NULL,NULL),(62877,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Industry Tactics - September 15, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-11 09:07:05',NULL,'This is part one of a two-part interview between O-Perk and his host, Friendly Rich, who is a student at U of G. The first part of the interview is with Rich and his friend Terry Fox, who are running a 5K for cancer research. The second part is with Amorowa, who runs a weekly talk show called SoPerg, which is a combination of recorded talks and live and prerecorded interviews.\n\nOn the program, Rich and Amorowa discuss a wide range of topics, including social and political issues, economic and social justice, and current events in the community. The program also includes music, such as the latest album from O\'Perk, Crash Worship. O-Perwealth, QB3913, and the U-G Graduate Coalition are organizing a week-long Disorientation Week, which will take place from September 18 to 21, 2023 on the U of Guelph campus.',NULL,NULL),(62878,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Industry Tactics - September 15, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 08:51:47',NULL,'Welcome back to the industry tactics podcast. This is the guy named Friendly Rich. He\'s a legend on the podcast. He was introduced to us by a librarian who kicked us out of a library when we were trying to talk to a guy named Jeff Mattson from San Diego. So this guy is a legend. Rich and Jeff had a great chat. They talk about animals, crash worship, New Orleans, and all the cool stuff.\n\nThis guy is super inspired by everything we\'re doing. So yeah, it was a great time. And we\'ve got a whole hour together. Rich wants to get into the head of this guy. He starts by asking where he\'s come from. And then he starts asking all the weird little questions about how he grew up. He says he was born in Los Angeles county. Then he says he moved to the West valley. And he says that horses were still in the area. So basically, he\'d been around a lot. Like, did you move a lot when he was a kid? No, just one time.\n\nIt was like, blood screaming. He then says he went to college to get a degree in exotic animal training. Now that\'s going to be a two-year program. So Rich and the gang start talking about how they\'re going to teach animals how to scoop up poop. And how to muck in the mud. Rich says he\'ll find out about this in the course of',NULL,NULL),(62879,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Hellfire Radio - September 15, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 08:28:45',NULL,'This is the first part of a two-part interview with the drummer of the thrash metal band, Krabothor. The first part consists of a description of the band, its members, and its music. The second part of the interview consists of an introduction to some of the new metal bands that have been playing in the festival. The band plays a song called \"Outsider\" and then a song by another band called \"Agurium.\" The first song on the band\'s new release is called \"Low Heaven,\" and the second song on their self-titled album is \"Skeletal Skeleton Lightning.\"',NULL,NULL),(62880,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Volunteer Playlist - September 15, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 08:05:00',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62881,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/15/Volunteer Playlist - September 15, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-15 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 07:07:03',NULL,'This is the first in a series of posts on how to get involved with CFRU.org. In this first post, we\'re going to look at how you can become a volunteer at the university\'s radio station and web site. If you are a fan of aggressive music, aggressive sounds, and loud-mouthing, we recommend you check out our live broadcast on 93.3 and our second live stream on our website. We also have a handy donation page, where you can give directly to the university.',NULL,NULL),(62882,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/14/Volunteer Playlist - September 14, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-14 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 06:48:22',NULL,'This is a special edition of We Know some Stuff. It\'s a show about science and technology. This week, it\'s about volunteer opportunities. The De Guelph Jazz Fest is looking for people to help out during the festival. For details, head over to the festival\'s website. We know you\'re a science fan. You\'re probably a fan of We know some stuff, too. If you haven\'t heard of it before, this is for you. We also want to tell you that Diode is a great resource for people who want to learn how to make things. They have a workshop and host maker\'s meetings every Monday night from 8pm to 9pm.',NULL,NULL),(62883,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/02/01/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - February 1, 2020 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-02-01 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 06:24:01',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(62884,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/31/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 31, 2020 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-31 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 06:05:20',NULL,'This week on the program, we\'re talking about a new partnership between the University of Waterloo and Crime Stoppers. The University of Guelph and the Crime Stoppers Society of Wellington are looking for community volunteers to keep the University safe. If you\'d like to help, you can apply for a position on the Board of Trustees or become a board member. You can also apply for help with a one-day event or to help establish a new Crime Stoppers program on campus.',NULL,NULL),(62885,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/30/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 30, 2020 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-30 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 05:07:29',NULL,'The Crooked Beat is on its way to a new venue. The show\'s host, Nicki Dred, announces that they\'re ready to rumble. She\'s got a line-up that includes the likes of Cross, Tony Nontali, and Koffee from New Zealand. It\'s a packed house, and Dred promises that she\'ll get the beats.',NULL,NULL),(62886,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/30/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 30, 2020 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-30 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-11 04:47:28',NULL,'The Crooked Beat is a weekly music show hosted by DJ Fireyard on CFRU 93.3. The program starts with a dub of Oliver\'s song \"Blue Night Dub\" and then it moves into a kind of vein with Ernest Ranglin greatest hits. It then moves into some other music from Jason Wilson, Tabarook, Canadian artist, Rising Tide, Second Hands, and Ernest\'s Memories of Barbara.\n\nThen it moves on to some of Tommy Tornado and the Jamaican Jazz Orchestra, Jackie Basil in French, Max Romeo, Richie Spice, Monty Alexander, and a few others. The program ends with some more music from the Valley of Jehoosa Fat. It\'s an extended version of the original track that was originally released by the Ebony Sisters back in 1970. It then goes on to commemorate the 153 elderly women that were killed in the Eventide fire.',NULL,NULL),(62887,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/24/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 24, 2020 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-24 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 03:09:08',NULL,'This week on the Server Screening Machine, the host and producer of the program return to discuss the upcoming production of \"When the Reaper Calls,\" a comedy drama co-written by Victor and Douglas Feggens, which will run January 23rd and February 2nd at the Guelph Little Theater. The program also discusses the new play \"Play Safe,\" a play co-produced by the Children\'s Hospital of Waterloo and directed by Christopher Feng, who was unable to attend the previous week\'s performance. The show is still not quite \"visioned, or vegetive\" , as the host explains, but he is determined to continue to produce it. He plans to use a set of classical recordings from the period of the show, including a performance by the concertgebouw orchestra of the country of the Netherlands, to further his goals.',NULL,NULL),(62888,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/24/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 24, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-24 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-11 02:50:41',NULL,'This week\'s show is called \"Eternal Rhythm,\" and it\'s hosted by Dave Handel, a volunteer at the university. He\'s also one of the hosts of \"Silver Screen Dream Machine,\" a program that\'s about to air on CFRU. The program starts out with a remembrance of the late Neil Peart , a legendary Rush drummer who died of a brain tumor two weeks ago. Next, the program pays tribute to Monty Python\'s Terry Jones, who died this week from a rare form of dementia called primary progressive aphasia. Then it pays homage to Graham Chapman and Neil Innes , both of whom died within three weeks of each other.',NULL,NULL),(62889,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/23/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 23, 2020 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-23 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 02:29:58',NULL,'The guy starts off by saying that this is a festival called the \"Zombi Jamboree\" . He and the other musicians have been listening to music from all over the world, and they\'re all about freedom. They play music from war zones, from the north of Africa, from Willie Thrasher, and even from an old song called \"I was a child\" that was written by a singer named Willie Thrasher. They\'re also playing music from Eloquent, from Fela-Kuti, and from a band called the Blind Boys. The guy says that he\'s going to be heading to the festival with Seen Mars.',NULL,NULL),(62890,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/23/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 23, 2020 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-23 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 02:08:42',NULL,'In this song, the host tells his listeners that he is a symbol of freedom. He reminds them that they have no power to change the world.\n\nHe tells them that he was born into a family of slaves and that his life has been a struggle against the power of the state. He is a man wrapped in no difference. The host says that he has a lasting honor. He says that everyone who has ever known him has been honored by his work. He explains that his work is a reminder of the sacrifices made by Martin Luther King, Jr., who was killed on January 12, 1968, at the age of thirteen. The song is a reference to the famous quote, \"The way you thought he life should be / Now the people dont have the power / To change things anymore.\" The Underground Master says that the people have no right to change anything and that Martin was a man who was \"wrapped with no difference.\" He says the Underground Master is a constant reminder to his listeners about the value of freedom and that they can use his song to express their own views.\n\nHe also says that there are other host songs that have similar messages. One of them is by Mavis Staples, who performed with Dr. Martin on Martin Luther Day in the United States. The underground master says that Mavis has been holding on for too long to give up and that this is why he wrote this song. He describes it as an instrumental and says that it\'s very difficult to',NULL,NULL),(62891,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/17/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 17, 2020 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-17 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 01:50:51',NULL,'In this chapter, the narrator talks about the reunion of Mac D. The first manager of the station, Mac D, has been at the station since 1970. He\'s back in the office, showing the staff his old newspaper clippings. He was the first person to serve on the board of directors, and he was also the first manager.\n\nThe narrator is excited to try to get people to come back to the station. He talks about how he\'s planning to use all sorts of different strategies to do that. He mentions that there are a lot of people who have left the university, including some of the professors. He wants to know why they\'re not there. He also mentions that sometimes, people take a job away because they\'ve had a bad experience with the university.',NULL,NULL),(62892,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2020/01/17/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 17, 2020 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2020-01-17 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 01:07:01',NULL,'The Host of CFRU\'s Morning Show talks about the club day that\'s coming up at the university. It\'s called \"Clubs Days\" and it involves a bunch of different student clubs. The Host tells listeners that he\'s going to be talking to some of the clubs that are participating in the day. If you\'re interested, he says, you can check it out by listening to the program. He also says that he always needs volunteers for the show. He\'s also going to give a spiel to the audience about how he has been getting involved with the club.',NULL,NULL),(62893,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/09/13/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 13, 2019 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-09-13 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 00:51:17',NULL,'The program opens with a discussion of the Urban Science Brass band. The band will perform outside on the street during the free event. The program goes on to describe the event as \"a party in the streets tonight\" and says that it will feature a number of bands and free performances.\n\nThe CFRU staff is also involved in the program. The station has a volunteer on the air and a staff on the ground, as well as on-air and off-air programmers. He also mentions that there will be free music tonight and tomorrow at the Guelph Jazz Fest. He says that if you are in the market for live music, the festival will give you a chance to see some of the best acts in the city.',NULL,NULL),(62894,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/09/13/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 13, 2019 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-09-13 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 00:28:08',NULL,'This program is a live broadcast of the Central Student Association\'s club day at the university. It is hosted by Tonya Iyer, who is a member of the club and a volunteer at the CFRU station. She is also the spokesperson for the club. The program begins with an introduction by Thomas King, the host of CFRU 93.\n\n1FM. He tells listeners that he is a friend of the university and that he has been a student since the late nineteenth century. He says that he and his family have suffered greatly under the influence of alcohol. He reminds listeners that alcohol is a disease that affects all human beings. If you feel that you are an alcoholic, you are also an alcoholic. He urges listeners to call the helpline for help at 1-866-200-0223. He then shows listeners how to find out if their loved one is an alcoholic and if they would be able to stop drinking if they loved them. He also tells listeners to listen to his show, \"Seems Like Old Times,\" on Sundays from 2:00 to 4:00 p.\n\nm on CFRU 92.3. He is a co-host of the show with Douglas Blackwood. The show airs on Sundays and focuses on issues that concern older adults. He asks listeners if they feel unloved or neglected if a loved one drinks. If they answer yes, they are not alone; they are suffering as well. He then invites listeners to join him at the club\'s outreach tables in the university building. He will be playing music',NULL,NULL),(62895,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/09/13/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 13, 2019 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-09-13 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 00:10:17',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the band, led by Tanya Iyer, who is a multi-instrumentalist and composer. She is known for her gorgeous voice and her ability to write and invent music. She and her band play songs that move gracefully and seamlessly. The music is underpinned by Iyers gorgeous voice. She also writes captivating melodies and invents the playing of her bandmates, and then they name their bandmates. The program ends with the announcement that they will be playing at Branion plaza on Friday, September 14, 2018.\n\nThe program was co-presented by the Central Students\' Association and the Guelph Chess festival. It aired live on CFRU. The audience is invited to tune in to hear the program. The voice introduces himself as a student at CFRU, and he explains that he is going to skip a part. He is going go to skip the part. I am going to go skip that part I\'m not going to do that part.',NULL,NULL),(62896,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/09/12/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 12, 2019 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-09-12 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 23:46:37',NULL,'The students talk about forming a Facebook group for their film club. They\'re planning on having a poll on the group and asking students to vote on what they\'d like to see in the movies. They plan to post the poll on their Facebook page and invite people to come to the club meetings.\n\nThey say they\'ll have a table at clubs days so people can come and meet the club members. The club members talk about the times they usually watch the movies and where they usually sit to watch them. They have a list of people they invite to come and join their club. The song they\'re playing is called \"Earl and the Duchesses,\" by Steve Earl. They also have a weekly program where they play public service announcements about upcoming events.',NULL,NULL),(62897,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/09/12/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 12, 2019 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-09-12 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 23:11:18',NULL,'The host starts off by telling us that he\'s going to play music with a band called Hush Hush Noise on his giant Golden Bus, a bus that he runs at the University of California, Berkeley.\n\nThey\'ll be playing on September 28th, his birthday. He also tells us that the band is playing a song called \"Dead Man\" off of their latest release, \"The Scrapes.\" The UM also mentions that he has only 20 tickets to the gig. If you\'re a UM student or know someone who is, you can get tickets by going to his Facebook page. This is a way for people to get tickets to his gig. The UM host explains that the Golden Bus is a sort of social hub where people can meet up with other UM students and start new clubs. There are people who want to start a club because they\'re missing a place to belong, or because they want to participate in a culture they\'ve never been part of before. But there are also people who start clubs just because they feel like they have a community that\'s missing at the university.',NULL,NULL),(62898,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/09/12/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 12, 2019 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-09-12 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 22:50:57',NULL,'This week on the Club Days program, host Tom Jarndyce introduces us to a new program: the University Club Days. He tells us that there are hundreds of different clubs in the university, and that he can easily find them all. He starts off by playing a track from a band playing the University Jazz Festival. The track is called \"Splits\" and it\'s from Thomas Fujiwara\'s album \"Stepwise\" . Before that, he plays some of Jelly Roll Morton\'s classic songs, including \"King Porter Stomp,\" \"Jelly Roll Morton Stomp Act II,\" and \"King Stomp Act I,\" all from Way North\'s \"Fearless and Kind\" album.',NULL,NULL),(62899,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/01/17/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 17, 2019 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-01-17 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 22:25:41',NULL,'This is Part 1 of a two-part interview with the chief officer of the Caribbean Culture club at the University of Waterloo, Nikolas. He introduces himself as Chief Officer of the club and explains that the club has a goal of making the world a better place by making it more equal. He goes on to say that the Caribbean community at the university is one of the few places in the world that has the ability to make world peace possible.',NULL,NULL),(62900,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/01/17/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 17, 2019 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-01-17 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 21:07:34',NULL,'The narrator is at Club Days with a special guest, Luke. Luke is a member of the improv club at the university. Luke explains that the club is an open improv group that runs a workshop every week on a specific topic. Luke says that the biggest skill that they focus on developing is acceptance of failure. He adds that not being afraid of failure is a barrier to creating cool things and collaborating with others.\n\nLuke gives an example of an improv game that he would like listeners to imagine. He says that imagine he walked into a room and he was about to do an improv-like game. The first letter of his sentence has to begin with the last one of his, and vice versa',NULL,NULL),(62901,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/01/17/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - January 17, 2019 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-01-17 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 20:47:13',NULL,'Amy Goodman, host of O\'Purg, a local radio station, and her co-host Mandy discuss the Club Days that are taking place at the University of Guelph. The Club Days are a series of events that are being held in celebration of the university\'s centennial. Amy asks Mandy to give an update on the O.P. Radio station\'s activities. She also asks Elizabeth from the Fossil Field Campaign to give a brief update on her campaign. On January 23rd, a big day, there will be a Fossil Free Guelph rally.',NULL,NULL),(62902,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/09/20/CFRU live from University of Guelph Clubs Days! - September 20, 2018 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-09-20 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 20:28:19',NULL,'This episode of CFRU\'s 93.3 is all about buying games. It starts off with a description of the game vendor at the university. The guy is selling SNES games and other games. He says that they\'re all sold in \"containers\" that are easily moved.\n\nHe tells us that he used to be a fan of one of these vendors in high school. The guys are like the new \"digital peddlers\" . They have a Starcraft for the N64, which makes him crazy. He also says that playing RTS with a controller is nuts. This is all part of the conversation about games. You never know what you\'re going to find. This time, we\'ll find out from the guy who plays the game. The man\'s name is Plastebir and he\'s from Turkey. We learn that he was in the U.S. back in 1995 and that he played the Settlers of K.I.',NULL,NULL),(62903,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/09/13/CFRU live from University of Guelph Clubs Days! - September 13, 2018 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-09-13 13:00:00',86376576,'2023-12-10 20:07:33',NULL,'CFRU\'s Club Days is live-streaming from the University\'s campus. The club is called the Juggler\'s of the U.G., and the host, Ray Spoon, and Jenny, the club\'s representative, are on stage. Jenny introduces herself as Jenny from the Chemistry Club, and she explains that she\'s here to speak with Mike Moore, a student from another club called the Jaruth Jugglers.\n\nMike is a student studying in the area of Chemistry and Education. He\'s been at the university for about eight years, and he\'s just gotten a Ph.D. from the School of Education. Mike explains that he was once a member of the Chemistry and Biochemistry Club, but no longer is. He says that he\'d like to get back into the science clubs. He is the representative of Jarutheth, which is a club that\'s started in 2009 and hopes to get more members today.\n\nMike tells the audience that the club has a Facebook group and meets twice a week, on Monday and Thursday evenings at 5pm and 7pm respectively. He adds that they provide props and even teach students how to juggle. Mike says that there\'s a scientific aspect to joining a club, so they will help students with their coordination.',NULL,NULL),(62916,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/rqecmv/September_16th_2023_Critic_s_Circle92g88.mp3','2023-09-16 14:03:19',143961989,'2023-12-10 19:56:08',NULL,'The show opens with Phil Taylor, the host of the Canadian independent music program, Critic\'s Circle, talking about the show\'s first guest, Daniel Garber, who\'s a regular on the program. The program is about movies and plays, and Phil introduces us to Lynn Sotkins, a passionate theatergoer. They\'re going to interview Chris Abraham, the director of the play The Master Plan, which was about the disastrous state of affairs in the city\'s waterfront and sidewalk-labs in 2017. Phil says that\'s going to be the last time he\'ll ever speak to Chris Abraham.',NULL,NULL),(62924,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/A Dog’s Breakfast - September 16, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 19:08:35',NULL,'The first part of the program is dedicated to encouraging people to become organ and tissue donors. In fact, it\'s only 31% of the population in Ontario has consented to donate their own organs and tissue. That means that an average person will die each day because an organ isn\'t available to save him or her. Sign up for BeADonOr.ca, and if you\'re ready to give, you can do it right away. If you don\'t want to, you should share your decision with your family. Mike Willis, who has been a recipient of organ donation, says, \"If someone had not registered their consent, I wouldn\'t be alive today\" .\n\nAnd for those of you who aren\'t ready to volunteer yet, here\'s a tip: listening to the program on Wednesdays, at noon, leads to an increase in episodes. Also, the feeling of community that\'s universal is universal. The feeling is universal and so are gestures that build community. So, \"welcome every new neighbor\" , and welcome our communities into the 21st century. Welcome to Welcome Week! Funded by... In this program, we\'ll hear about some of the new music that has been discovered in the last few months. The first thing we hear is the music of Jacques de Jeanette, an American drummer who\'s paired with a Japanese player named Fode Masuso. The two of them are playing together on a CD called \"',NULL,NULL),(62925,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Sound Magic - September 16, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 18:48:10',NULL,'The program opens with a discussion of the last hour of the twentieth century. The topic is music. The program discusses the importance of dissonance and complexity in music. It is important to note, however, that this discussion is not intended to be an exhaustive history of music.\n\nInstead, it is an attempt to give some context to the history of twentieth-century music. In this particular case, the focus is on the symphonies of a composer named Hans-Bana-Hense. The first symphony was composed in the early twentieth century, and the second was completed in the late twentieth century',NULL,NULL),(62926,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Sound Magic - September 16, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 18:25:18',NULL,'The program opens with a program about one of the most important 20th century composers, Franz Raissenstein. It\'s a bit of a history lesson, because Raisenstein was born in Germany in 1911, but lived in England until 1968, when he died.\n\nHe studied with a German master, Ray Fawn Williams. He was a serious composer, and he wrote some really funny pieces of music, like a \"Concerto for Orchestra and Vacuum Cleaners\" . Now that we have a chance to hear some of these pieces, we\'re really impressed. The program ends with a new recording from a company called Concerto Pche, which has a great new piano concerto by Oliver Trindl, as well as some other works by composers like John Cage and Philip Glass.',NULL,NULL),(62927,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Sound Magic - September 16, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 18:09:32',NULL,'This week on Sound Magic, the program opens with music by a German composer named Karl Goldmark who was a huge influence on Brahms during his time. He\'s also a big fan of opera, so he\'s one of the most popular composers of the twentieth century. The program also includes some other German composers, including a folk hero named Karl Zierini who fought against the Ottomans and helped to defeat them.\n\nAnd then there\'s another Viennese composer named Franz Josif Haydn who wrote symphonies and other works that are \"all just jewel examples\" of classical style. This is the program that\'s going to be presented at the end of the program. It\'ll be a symphony by Haydn that is supposed to come from the play \"Distracted Person\" about a distracted guy. It has six movements, but it seems like it\'s only going to go on and on.',NULL,NULL),(62928,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Bel Araby with CAWA - September 16, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 17:11:53',NULL,'CFRU has a new program called \"To Know the Land\" on the CFRU 98.3 FM. Byron and his crew take listeners on a tour of the land base which is a small city in the province. The government has funded the program with money from the Canadian Arab Refugees Festival. They are also helping the government to build a communal land base in Canada. The host of the program says that you can visit all the land bases in Canada and visit the different parts of the country. The land bases can also be visited during the Canadian Refugee Festival.',NULL,NULL),(62929,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Caribbean Anthology - September 16, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 16:50:33',NULL,'Dr. Def welcomes the listeners to another episode of the Caribbean Anthology. He thanks everyone for tuning in last week to listen to the live interview with Tasha T. She is a singer hailing from Toronto and has a promotion company called Ras Vibe. She has been in the music business for a long time. Dr.Def also thanks everyone who has tuned in to hear the interview with her.',NULL,NULL),(62930,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Beautiful Druid - September 16, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 16:30:06',NULL,'The first song on the program is by a Canadian artist named Alden Hadwen, who is a student at the University of Regina. He is the host of the weekly music and poetry show Beautiful Druid. He begins the show with a description of the beautiful September day he is recording.\n\nHe describes it as a \"clear blue sky\" with bright moonlight and starlight. He then tells the audience about the song by a singer named Bonnie Rait who is recording from her latest album Longing In Their Hearts. Her song is called \"Cool Water,\" a song that sounds exactly like it would feel if you were in the water on a September morning. The song was written in honor of September being the month of hurricanes and the upcoming fall season. Alden then tells us about some of the other songs he is going to play. He introduces them by saying that they all have their roots in the province of Saskatchewan. He says the first song is by the musicians from the album \"Too Many Roads,\" who are also from Saskatchewan. The second song is \"Plain,\" written by the artists from their album \"Moonlight Dancers.\" The third song is a song written by a man named Cat Stevens from his album \"Teater and the Firecat.\" The fourth song is written for his dog C4, who was a favorite of Alden\'s teenage boys.',NULL,NULL),(62949,197,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dnytj4/phil_s_inn_sept_16_23a00i1.mp3','2023-09-17 02:30:24',287962512,'2023-12-10 16:09:54',NULL,'This program opens with a conversation between the host and a listener. The listener tells the host that he is from an area outside of Ottawa called Overbrook. The host introduces the listeners to a local musician named Slim Moore and his band the Marques. The listeners are then treated to a selection of music from the album \"How Long\" by Slim Moore.\n\nThe program closes with a description of the program being aired at Phils Inn, a pub in the area. This program is being aired as part of a festival, and the host tells the listeners that he has not seen a single football game in his life. He says that he had a \"conversion\" one week when he saw three down and fourteen yards to go and realized that football was an analogy to life.\n\nThe man has come to a training camp to try his hand at one of the Senior Football Leagues and he says he is \"born-again\" and now he is a \"born again\" football player. He has been assigned to a classical music team called the Gustaaf Maulers, which is composed of people who are interested in classical music. The group plays music from all over the world.',NULL,NULL),(62950,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Alternativa Latinoamericana - September 16, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-17 02:40:39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62951,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Alternativa Latinoamericana - September 16, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-17 02:40:40',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62952,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Caribbean Anthology - September 16, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 15:50:26',NULL,'The show returns to the Caribbean Anthology, a music and record label that has been around for a long time. It is now in its second half. The show welcomes back to the \"second half\" with some \"brand new music\" and some \"regular\" music. It also welcomes some of the \"lovers rock\" and \"foundation vibes\" that have been added to the show. It\'s a big shout-out to everyone who\'s listening right now. The DJ also thanks Aaliyah and the other ladies who\'ve been supporting the project.',NULL,NULL),(62953,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Tiempo de Mujeres - September 16, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-17 02:40:41',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(62954,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Mach Vibe Radio - September 16, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 15:05:25',NULL,'Welcome to the 728 Show, where the host, CanadianYardy, introduces himself as your host. He welcomes everyone to the show and encourages them to join in the welcoming vibe.\n\nThe host and his guest, the DJ/Musicians, also introduce themselves. They explain that they have known for generations that there is a universal feeling of community, and that a few kind words or a smile are the first step to building a new community. They also explain how welcoming week is funded by Immigration and Citizenship Canada, and how people can get involved. The show ends with a short introduction by the two guests, Ben Zia Ash and Zila Ash.',NULL,NULL),(62964,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/Mach Vibe Radio - September 16, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 14:50:47',NULL,'This is the first half of the Mock 5 show, and it\'s called \"The Second Half of Mock 5.\" It\'s all about the music. The first half starts off with the song \"Yo, stand up.\" The second half is about \"Hot, we hot,\" and the song is about a girl named \"Canadian Yardy.\n\n\" She\'s the voice of the band, and she\'s in charge of keeping the music going. She tells the guys to stay locked in and not to let the music go to commercial break, so they can enjoy themselves. She also tells them that they\'re locked in the \"mock 5\" for the rest of the show. The music starts off the second half, and the guys are like, \"Hey, hey, everyone. Welcome to',NULL,NULL),(63001,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/16/The Underground - September 16, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-16 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 14:26:16',NULL,'This chapter is an introduction to the philosophy of De, which means \"doing things in the easiest and most relaxed way possible.\" This is a philosophy that is very similar to that of Oddie, who is taking over for Vulgar. The goal of De is to make things as easy as possible, which is a very good goal.\n\nYou can do whatever you want, as long as you don\'t move the thing you\'re doing. If you put a cup in the right place, you can move it as you like, but you can\'t do it as if it\'s alive or hostile. This is also a good goal for beginners, because it can help them overcome the block of thinking of things as work.',NULL,NULL),(63200,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/The Underground - September 17, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 14:05:23',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(63246,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Visions fugitives - September 17, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 13:46:03',NULL,'This is the second in a series of two-part segments on the CFRU-FM show hosted by Christopher Curry. The first part, entitled \"The Christopher Curry Show,\" is a brief introduction to the show and to the artist featured on it. The second part is a description of the music featured on the show. The show is all about Canadian artists, and this week they are going to focus on music by Sarah Devaki.\n\nThe name of her artist is \"Devachi\" and she has released a new album called \"Two Sisters.\" The first track on the new album is \"Icon Studies I.\" The second track is \"Harmonies in Bronze.\" The third track is called \"Aba to Voi.\" The last track is a \"Surean Giz.\" The program ends with a brief promotional pause.',NULL,NULL),(63256,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/9bi79x/Karibuni_Sept_17_20236hm8r.mp3','2023-09-18 03:16:00',287962512,'2023-12-10 13:31:08',NULL,'On Sundays at 3 to 5pm, a group of musicians known as the Karibuni, or the African Music Club, plays live music at various clubs in the city.\n\nOne of the members of the club is Nadine McNulty, who introduces herself as \"Mr. Tierno\" . He is a member of the group and is currently attending a concert at the Franco-phonie on Fort York Boulevard. He will be arriving at the concert at 6pm and will then rush off to another venue before the show is over. He introduces the first song he will play, written by La Bess from Algeria. The song is a response to the recent earthquake in Morocco. He then introduces a number of other artists and introduces them to the audience. They include Bombino, Ibo Pazum, Sahra Halagan, Asma Hamzaw, Binat Timbuku, Um, La Bess, Nina Ogart, and La Paz. They then move on to the next song. They will hear from Nina about the country they are visiting.',NULL,NULL),(63257,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Seems Like Old Times - September 17, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 13:13:11',NULL,'The next day, Tony is back at the police station looking for the killer of Sylvia. He\'s still trying to figure out the identity of Peter Churro, the man who killed her.\n\nTony says he told Sylvia that Peter was planning to kill her, and that he still has the information about Peter. He shows Sylvia a toy that he made out of a pocket knife and a wooden gun. He says he\'s been practicing carving things to make them look like real guns. He tells Sylvia that he loves her, but he also tells her that there\'s another man in love with Sylvia. This man is named Johnny Moore. He works on the docks along the river. Tony asks Johnny if he\'d like to talk to him about Sylvia. Johnny says he can\'t, because he doesn\'t have the words to express his feelings.',NULL,NULL),(63258,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Seems Like Old Times - September 17, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 12:49:22',NULL,'On this program, we hear from Diana, Glenn, and more in the old time. We start off by playing a bit of music from the 30s and 40s. We also hear some of the music from 50s. Django Reinhardt and the Hot Club from France recorded it in 1938.\n\nNow we hear more music from Diana. She\'s on a duet with Tony Bennett. She sings some songs written by George & Ira Gershwin. The program ends with some news about Legion Week. The Legion has a members appreciation day on Wednesday, a general meeting on Thursday, a veterans social on Friday, and a fun night on Friday. The students at the university are involved in the Legion too. They\'re involved in a lot of different kinds of music. Diana sings a duet on a CD with the late Bennett. The songs are mostly written by Gershwin and George. Diana also sings a song called \"U E\" written by Ray Downs. The first song in the CD is \"Falling in love with a love that\" .\n\nThe band that recorded this song is from Jack Lathrop. Now it\'s time to hear some more music. There\'s a little bit of a break. Then we\'re back to Diana. We hear more from her. We learn that Ellora Legion has some events coming up this week. Two more events are on Friday at 2pm and 8pm.',NULL,NULL),(63259,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Wind-Down - September 17, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 12:28:08',NULL,'The wind-down begins. The first artist we hear is Ginger Root, who has a song called \"Phone a Friend\" from her latest album. The second artist is Rob the Viking and Leilum, who have a song \"Post-Stalish Symmetry of the Hummingbird\" from their album \"Reiki\" .\n\nThe third artist is Moon King and \"Out of Control,\" who have their new single \"Born Ruffians, Us Girls\" coming up. And the fourth artist is Lou. He found this song while walking around the university campus. Lou is from a band called Strats S T R A A T S with their latest single \"Bush,\" which is one of the posters that are advertising their new music.',NULL,NULL),(63260,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Visions fugitives - September 17, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 12:11:44',NULL,'In this program, we learn about the Baha\'is, a religious community centered around the faith. The community was founded in the 19 century initially in the Islamic Republic of Iran, and the central figure was a man named Baha\'ullah, followed by an individual named the Bab.\n\nThe Bab was a kind of gate or door to a new thinking. The artist who works on the program is Harisas, an Iranian-Canadian artist. She has written a piece for her new album called Makhu. This is inspired by the letter she wrote to the former king of Iran in which she talks about how humans respond to physical suffering and spiritual pain. She also writes that when human beings reach their threshold or the point they think they cant take anymore, they tend to turn towards spirituality and find solace. This piece is to be heard as soon as it is released. In the meantime, we hear another work by the artist Parisas, called The Seville orange tree.\n\nIt is a work about a sacred mountain in Shiraz, a city in south-west Iran. The work begins with a series of images of a fortress in the heart of the mountain. The image of the fortress has been captured in a poem by the composer. The poem is called \"I am the countenance from which have I been created. I am from the primal point of which have all created things.\" The program ends with a disc by an accordionist named Joseph Petrich, who is a member',NULL,NULL),(63261,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - September 17, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-08 16:03:25',NULL,'The narrator announces that they\'ll be doing a lot of famous songs in this episode, but he\'s not going to include Joni Mitchell because she\'s too famous. Instead, he\'ll start with a song by Lee Dorsey called \"River Boats,\" which is a bit of love song. The narrator also announces that the song will be followed up by the Supremes doing a song called \"Four Tops.\" The narrator introduces his new cousin, Oliver. Oliver is a little chubby, and he used to be a bald baby. He\'s got a list of some of the things that kids used to say when they were younger. Oliver asks the narrator to bring it out with him so he can look up the funny things that were said when he was a kid. Oliver also says that he has to wait a while before River will start saying funny things like that. Then they get a couple of songs by a group called \"Friends from the 60s.\" The first song is called \"The River Song.\" The second song is \"By the River,\" which comes from a collection of songs called \"Bruton Music.\" Rowan comes in to say hello. He has a new cousin who was born on Boxing Day, so he wants to','We\'re gonna start today with Lee Dorsey from one of my favorite albums. And then we\'re gonna follow it up with the Supremes with the four tops. I\'d like to say hi to Ollie. Hi. Good morning. It wasn\'t too long ago that you were a baby.','Hello Ollie! How are you? (Sponsor)'),(63262,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Clan Na Gael - September 17, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 11:47:31',NULL,'In this program, Opere describes the events of the Disorientation Week at the University of G. He plays music from a variety of different albums and tells the story of a new girl he met in Stratford. The girl is called \"Ganymede\" and she is a member of a band called the Stelis Band. She sings a song called \"A New Georgie Girl,\" which he remembers the first time he heard it on the radio. He also tells how he met the girl from the album Simply the Best, and how many people will wonder who the girl is.',NULL,NULL),(63263,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Clan Na Gael - September 17, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 11:28:50',NULL,'The show begins with John Fahy, the host of a local Irish radio station, telling listeners that he\'s here until 2pm to bring them some Celtic music. The first song he plays is a song about seven old ladies who went into a public toilet in Dublin, and they were locked in the toilet. The song is called \"Ryan\'s Fancy from 15 Guinness Drink Along Songs\" and the second song is \"Voice of Ages\" by Carolina Rua. The third song is from the band \"Dusts from Winnipeg\" from their God CD, \"Dear Prudence\" . The show ends with a song by Patty Riley, who sings a Canadian song called \"Live for Ireland\" , which was originally written by U2.',NULL,NULL),(63264,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/La Buena Onda - September 17, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-18 12:07:26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(63265,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/La Buena Onda - September 17, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-18 12:07:26',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(63266,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Zombie Jamboree - September 17, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 11:05:38',NULL,'The last set of the day begins with a performance by Mitch Matthews. He tells the crowd that he\'ll see them next Sunday at 6pm. He also tells them that he wants to go out and play some music by Sveinnbord and called \"Overtage\"',NULL,NULL),(63267,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Zombie Jamboree - September 17, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 10:47:59',NULL,'On this episode of the Klezmer Jamboree, Bruce notes that it\'s now the New Year, and that the festivities are kicking off with the song \"Sada gora hot dub\" by the Amsterdam band. He also notes that Michael Winogard, a professor at the University of Guelph, is also in attendance, and he\'s here to give some advice on how to celebrate the new year. The music is international, uncategorized, and unidentifiable. The set starts off with a song by Dubmatics called \"Soul Scaw\" and then moves on to a song called \"These are the good old days\" by Abdul the Rabbi. This is the fourth song in the set, and this is the one that\'s going to continue for the rest of the show.',NULL,NULL),(63268,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Through the Looking Glass - September 17, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 10:26:29',NULL,'The group travels through the Looking-Glass to follow the music, and the first track is called \"Jaws from the Dizzy.\" The next track is \"Fear Pageant\" from the new CD \"The Spark in Your Take Back 10\" and the third is \"Better Somehow\" from an upcoming album.\n\nThe next artist is \"Fred Abong\" from his album Fear Pageant. The fourth track is a remix of \"Freak Heat Waves\" from \"Mongo Tempo\" and \"In a Moment Vine\" with \"Afix Twin\" and a \"Black Box Life Recorder.\" The final track is from \"Paramorph Collective\" from All We Are Made of. The group then decides to go in a different direction, this time by going with \"Fun Drive 2023\" from a community. The last track is by \"Wilfred Cozum\" on a CD called Beautiful and BeforeThought with \"Violet and Gravity.\" The group closes by going out on a song by \"W.',NULL,NULL),(63269,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/This Night Wounds Time - September 18, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 10:09:04',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(63270,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/Backtracks - September 17, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 09:50:43',NULL,'The University of Guelph hosts a free jazz festival on September 16 at Market Square. The program begins with a review of the show by Backtracks host, Eileen. He says that the music is mostly \"rare sides\" of the sound, but he does play some \"mainstream or newer stuff\" if the music calls for it, as long as it\'s representative of the era. The show opens with the Stranglers with their song, \"Golden Brown.\" The song is about a girl, but also about the colors of the autumn. The songs include \"Autumn Dance,\" \"Safe is Melt,\" \"Autumn\'s Child,\" \"Leaves Never Break,\" \"The Boat Brummells,\" and \"The Wimple Winch.\"',NULL,NULL),(63271,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/This Night Wounds Time - September 18, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 09:10:00',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the work of a composer named Kaya Sarajo, who has died of brain cancer at the age of 70. The Guardian describes her as a leading composer of her generation and a pioneer in the field of spectralism, which uses sound analysis to create music from the full range of sounds. Her works for orchestra and voice are some of her best known. Her opera, La Muere de Loix or Love From a Far, is one of her most popular works, and her opera, Orion, deals with an event in the present that the audience can relate to but is not specific about its location',NULL,NULL),(63272,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/17/This Night Wounds Time - September 17, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-17 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 08:49:09',NULL,'This is the program that Christopher Curry is bringing to you tonight. It\'s called \"This Night Wounds/Time\" and it\'s about music that is off the beaten path.\n\nHe\'s going to start off the show with music off the beat, but he\'s also going to play music from off-center. That\'s right, he\'ll play music off of the beat. But for this show, he wants to play some music from someone who\'s recently passed away.\n\nThis is someone named DaivatJani, who is a composer from Toronto. It sounds a lot like his name, though he doesn\'t actually play the instrument himself. The music on the show is from an album called \"Sum Parts\" that represents the life of the man from his birth in India all the way to his current home in Canada. The album is about the struggles, joy, tears, and the fight.',NULL,NULL),(63282,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 18, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 08:27:39',NULL,'On September 14, Guelph MPP, and leader of Green Party, Mike Schreiter, joins us for a Queens Park Update and Host a Q and A session. The issues facing the province are legion, and Schreiner has three new bills for the Greenbelt, a 400 series highway, and quarries to address them.\n\nThe program\'s moderator, Morgan, takes the opportunity to remind everyone of the importance of the two treaties, the Dish with one spoon treaty and the Two roll wampum treaty, which were signed in the 1600s. Schreiner says that reconciliation is a good way to bring the province back to the point of reconciliation. He says that he\'s glad to be here, and he thanks everyone for joining him in person. He also says that people in Guelph are calling on the premier to keep his commitment not to own Greenbelt for development in the last ten months. He adds that he looks out his front door on his street and sees all kinds of green signs telling him not to.',NULL,NULL),(63283,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 18, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 08:07:54',NULL,'The Morning Soul ShakeUp is a new program on CFRU 19. It\'s all about soul and funk and it\'s about to get a big show at the Little Theatre on September 22nd . Here\'s the announcement: tickets are $20 and $25 or free for kids 12 and under. For more information about the show, visit tragedyandmusic . You can also find out more about how to get to the show by going to the \"Live at the Theatre\" page on Facebook.',NULL,NULL),(63284,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Breezy Breakfast Radio - September 18, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 07:14:09',NULL,'This is the first of a series of interviews with political leaders in Guelph. In this interview, the mayor speaks of the importance of a caring community and his desire for people to step up when they disagree with his or her ideas. He also reflects on the fact that he is surrounded by people who care about him and his ideas. The mayor then asks the audience to listen to his speech and then listens to the other parts of the interview. He is pleased with the amount of energy he shows in his speeches.',NULL,NULL),(63285,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Here Today - September 18, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 06:50:41',NULL,'Aaron Badgley introduces himself to the listeners of the program. He is a member of the band with which he performs. He tells them that he is a friend of the musician, Aura Corrigan, who is from Ireland. She is known for her beautiful voice and her writing. He also tells them about some of her recent releases, including her latest album, Formless. The artist, who calls herself \"Aura Corrigan,\" is a musician who writes and performs music.\n\nShe has been described as having \"a beautiful voice, a beautiful guitar, and a beautiful writing.\" The show opens with a description of the artists on the show. The first artist is Deborah Fialkova, who has just released an album called \"Romantic England.\" The second artist is a new release by M.C Taylor, a North Carolina-based artist. The third artist is Sultan\'s string, a band that has won numerous awards for their live performances. The fourth artist is Aaron\'s bandmate, who plays guitar and sings. The show ends with an explanation of the album, Walking Through The Fire, a collection of collaborations between artists.',NULL,NULL),(63295,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Democracy Now - September 18, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 06:29:44',NULL,'Sabelle reports that thousands of people have gathered in New York to call for an end to the use of fossil fuels. They\'re also planning to attend the United Nations\' General Assembly in September. Meanwhile, the World Health Organization has called on the government of Libya to stop burying bodies in mass graves in the wake of devastating floods.',NULL,NULL),(63296,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Worst Responders - September 18, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 06:10:30',NULL,'On this episode of Worst Responders , Charissa and Renee talk about the fall semester at the university, and how it\'s not as easy as it used to be. They decide to take advantage of the situation by making fun of the wait times at the subway. They also discuss the fact that their favorite summer food is still not sold out at the Beyond Meat store, which makes them feel like they\'ve been successful.',NULL,NULL),(63306,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 18, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 05:09:22',NULL,'The UM art club is currently looking for a grant to create a larger project that will involve collaborating with professors to produce teaching materials for their classes. The UM student explains that he understands the role of the arts in bridging the gap between science and art. He explains that the UM has a wide variety of arts and sciences courses and that he finds one of the university\'s executives on his team to be a minor in biology and a major in fine arts . UM students interested in pursuing science and the arts can do so through the UM club, which is more like an interest-based club. UM\'s students are always looking for other ideas to expand into, and UM is always excited when they do.',NULL,NULL),(63307,3689,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/CFRU Live at Clubs Days! - September 18, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 04:47:30',NULL,'In this program, Jenny Mitchell, the volunteer coordinator for CFRU 96.3 FM, introduces listeners to the university\'s annual Clubs Day, an event that brings together hundreds of student clubs to present their activities to students.\n\nClubs Day is a great opportunity for students to see what they can do on campus. Today, we\'re going to hear from Alessia Drago, a student at the university who volunteers with a national organization called Let\'s-Talk Science. Alessia says that she\'s a third-year student studying biological science and plans to study speech language pathology. She says that volunteering with the organization is a good way to combine her knowledge of science with her presentation skills and career skills.',NULL,NULL),(63317,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/jeay5u/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Sept_20_2023_podcast893on.mp3','2023-09-18 21:49:19',284292701,'2023-12-10 04:28:22',NULL,'The Community Radio Station at CIUT FM wishes to thank all of its listeners for their financial support during its fall campaign. They ask that you continue to support the station by visiting their web site and giving money now. The summer is drawing to a close and the station is looking forward to the fall season. It is the end of summer in Canada and time seems to go by really quickly, so it seems like a long time to live. The station begins its fall season with some of the most popular music of the summer. It starts off with a song called \"Blessed Did Herb Dream\" and ends with an all new song by Donald Trump.',NULL,NULL),(63318,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - September 18, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 04:10:13',NULL,'This episode of Cfru.ca is a continuation of the interview series hosted by Nicholas Cooper on his Youtube channel. The interview begins with the introduction of the multi-instrumentalists, Jackson Darby, James Goddard, and Charlotte Joe Fraser . The trio performs music in the most unusual configuration. The multi-instrument, Pink Snail, is the band leader. Jackson describes his band as a band of synthesizers and effects pedals. He also describes his solo work as skin tone and his collective work as a trio. The group performs live at the Sentinel. In the interview, he asks the Deep question and gives advice for anyone who wants to find a new community.',NULL,NULL),(63328,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Big Sis Radio - September 18, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 03:49:01',NULL,'This is the 50th edition of Big Sis, and it\'s been a year since the show started. It\'s a little different than the other shows on the air, though, because they\'re just like adults.\n\nIt doesn\'t have a lid, it just can\'t understand the word \"no\" because it\'ll only be able to hold on to a chair and drink from it. Cece welcomes his listeners to the program and thanks them for listening. The program starts off with a song from Mother Tongues called \"Dance in the Dark,\" which is currently the top song on CFRU. The rest of the show is about summer, and the weather is finally getting nicer. So, now that the weather\'s finally nicer, we\'ll be in our sweaters and coats again. The last song we played was \"It is said in everything they are ready.\" The narrator says that, \"It\'s said with everything that they\'ve ready, no matter where they are or what they look like.\n\n\" This is a big shout out to all the staff and volunteers who make this program possible. And, speaking of animals, Cece is the host of the program, and today is the anniversary of the first 50 episodes of the Big Sis program. The show is hosted by Cece, and this is a reminder to listeners that \"it\'s going to be okay.\" Brain Snack: Brain Snack is a popular scientific term for something that\'s',NULL,NULL),(63329,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/to know the land - September 18, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 17:33:02',NULL,'The narrator explains that the walking stick is unlike an ant in that it is not a creature with the same body structure as ant, but is rather a large, giant insect with many appendages. He has seen these insects three times in the past year, and one time, when he was out with the other students, he saw a male walking stick on a tree. He then saw a female walking stick in the middle of a tree, but he could not get a good photo. The narrator also heard about two walking sticks being found in the forest and decided to go investigate them. He ran over to one of the tents and found the female and male walking sticks on opposite sides of the tent. The male was apparently holding onto the female\'s tail, and the narrator went on to explore the area, and discovered that about 45 other students were also interested in the insects. He decided to share some of his information with the students, and he decided to start with Stephen Marshall, a professor at University of Guelph in Canada, who wrote a textbook on the order of the phasmothedia. The phasmot is primarily tropical, but the species found in North America are mostly wingless. They are protected by a camouflage, a chemical spray, and by shedding appendages, which is unlike any other adult insect. They can also change colors and have outgrowth that resembles moss or lichen. They have a third line of defense: they can direct the chemical spray.',NULL,'The phasmothedia is a large, giant insect with many appendages'),(63339,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/qdfv7m/the_third_face_916ab77w.mp3','2023-09-19 00:37:37',143961989,'2023-12-10 03:31:29',NULL,'The Third Face is back with another special edition of his show. This time it\'s called \"The Third Face: Saturday Saviors, September Souls\" . The show starts off with a warning that this is the last show of the week, so don\'t waste any more time. Then they play a song by one of the most famous artists of all time, Drake, who is coming up on his 40th birthday this week. The song is called \"Time and Signs, Time and Signs\" , and it\'ll air on Monday at 6:00PM on CIUT 99.\n\n5FM. This is the same show that Victor first heard about on Facebook when he asked for a carpet cleaner. The carpet cleaner came to him and offered to clean his carpet for $10, and that\'s how they met. The man was named Kristina Caullai, and he was studying in India and teaching management when he slipped his back disc in his study and had to be treated for life. He bought a horoscope from an astrologer, and the astrologer told him that he would be completely healed on January 1 of the following year. This was the very first time that a psychic had told him anything. The guy also tells us that he bleached his hair blonde to help him feel his luck.',NULL,NULL),(63340,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/u5tkw6/show_sept_9th8nybt.mp3','2023-09-19 00:25:54',82549725,'2023-12-10 03:06:38',NULL,'This show is a follow-up to the last one. It\'s called \"The Third Face\" and it\'s about to go down in the history books as one of the most famous shows of all time.\n\nIt starts off with a great quote from a famous song by a famous American poet named William Faulkner: \"Faster than a roller-coaster going down like a Holly and Earhart\". This quote is followed by a series of notes from a poem by another famous poet named Henry David Thoreau. The note begins, \"If you want to know what it feels like to be alive, you need to know the history of time. Time is a living thing, and people are always looking for signs of the past\". This poem is about',NULL,NULL),(63341,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Blues Around the Block - September 18, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 02:46:04',NULL,'In this special edition of Blues Around The Block, Mac Dee takes us on a ride through the city with the train yard blues band at midnight. They play a number of songs from their own releases, as well as those of other artists. The songs that Mac Dee thinks are his favorites include: \"Hey Lucy,\" \"Fathom,\" and \"Selwyn Burchwood.\"',NULL,NULL),(63342,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Blues Around the Block - September 18, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 02:26:27',NULL,'In this edition of Blues Around The Block, we find out all the latest news and happenings from the local music scene. We\'re also introduced to Kenny Neal, who will be joining us on stage for the first time. Kenny has been coming to the Blues Around the block every week for the past ten years, so he\'s pretty familiar with the area. Kenny tells us that it\'s time for him to go back to his old stomping grounds.',NULL,NULL),(63352,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/The Deep House Project - September 18, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 02:06:49',NULL,'This week, the hosts of the Deep House Project are recording their CFRU music selector show. They\'ll pass this playlist to listeners so they can hear it again if they want. They invite listeners to come listen to the show and share their favorite music with them. They start off with a disco-sounding track, called Feel It, which was recorded by the legendary Flagg.\n\nThen they switch to a traditional house vibe with tracks like Overmono\' Is You, Jesse Lance\' Midnight Ontario, and Ford\'s everyday brackets far from. The show ends with a mix of Takeaway and the track they\'re playing now, which is called Down South from down South. The next week, they\'ll be hosting a public service announcement at the Tri City Synth Society\'s upcoming open night.',NULL,NULL),(63353,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Ripcord Radio - September 18, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 01:48:50',NULL,'The second half of the program starts with a description of the music on the program. The first half of this program consists of music from England, Canada, and California. The music comes from bands like Captain Everything, Wire with Sand in My Joints, Influx With Pit Alone, The Randy Bastard, Uranium 9 Volt with Splitderision, You Need Love, Hard Charger with Wereting Away, and Box Cutter. The only thing that doesn\'t make the program is a German song.',NULL,NULL),(63363,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/18/Back in the USSR - September 18, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-18 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 01:19:49',NULL,'