 musical montage of the artists\' tracks'),(63972,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Wind-Down - September 24, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 06:52:18',NULL,'The show starts off with a remix of a song by the Japanese artist, Tiger Bomb. Then we hear the latest from Jungle, which comes from their latest album, Volcano.\n\nWe also hear a song from Senka, which is from their new album, Holding On. The show winds down with the Montreal group, Pouler, with their song Nouveau. We hear from No No Boy, who has developed this project for his Ph.D. at Brown University. He draws on years of field work and research on American and Asian American history, writing folk songs with bands that turn on to American music by American soldiers. He also draws on his family\'s own family history, which he left behind during the war in Vietnam. He has a 2021 album called 1975, which is described as a \"powerful and moving album\" by NPR. The group US Girls is another one of the show\'s favorite albums.\n\nThey have a song called Bless This Mess. They also have a new song from Julia Cunningham, \"Dive Deep,\" which was from her latest album. The artist Hannah Georges also has a song on her latest release, \"I\'d be lying if I said I didn\'t care with the song',NULL,NULL),(63973,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Zombie Jamboree - September 24, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 06:31:52',NULL,'This is the first of a two-part interview with the host of the \"Zombie Jamboree,\" a weekly reanimmator of live music. The first part of the interview takes place on the 93.3 FM station, where the host and his guests dig through the latest releases to find the music they need for the evening.\n\nThe second part takes place at the \"green screen dream machine\" of the Olive Art studio at the College of the Free University of New York. The green-screen dream machine is a live-performance system that allows live performances to be recorded as well as re-watched. The program is available on the university\'s YouTube channel and on the CFRU.org web site.',NULL,NULL),(63974,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Through the Looking Glass - September 24, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 06:12:42',NULL,'The band travels through the looking-glass and listens to music. Tonight they listen to Patrick Creepe\'s album, Bewitched, and then to Toitanian Ghosts, a collection of songs from the new album Lusitania Ghosts.\n\nThey also listen to a band named Howland Circus, which will be releasing an album called Creature. The band\'s first single is called Innocence, and the album\'s name is Creature. If you are interested in the song\'s playlist, it can be found on the lookingglass. The next band is called Sparkle Horse, and their name is Chaos. The track is from the upcoming Hayes album, Catch The Sky With Prediction. They have also been listening to a new single from Robbie Coyne called Bitter Sweet candy. They are also listening to Indifferent Monkey, who has released a new track called Sagittarius A.',NULL,NULL),(63975,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/Backtracks - September 24, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 05:52:35',NULL,'On this edition of Backtracks, host Jennifer and guest host Eileen discuss Labor Day, a holiday celebrated in many countries around the world. The day originated in Canada in 1872, when the Toronto Trades Assembly, the original trade union body, organized the countrys first significant worker\'s demonstration. The purpose of the demonstration was the release of a Toronto typographical union member who was imprisoned for striking to gain an eight-hour working day. The assembly spoke out on the behalf of workers and encouraged union organization.',NULL,NULL),(63978,171,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/b4i5ay/podbean_version88d05.mp3','2023-09-25 04:34:35',220669553,'2023-12-07 05:12:03',NULL,'It\'s the beginning of autumn, and we\'re introduced to the narrator, a young man named Brad Reed. He\'s about to start his day with a poem, but before he starts, he takes a moment to reflect on the past week.\n\nThe seasons have changed on Saturday, and now it\'s time for the fall season. He loves the fall, he\'s not into heat, and he\'d rather have a brisk autumn day than a hot summer day.\n\nHe takes a few moments to read a few poems by Carl Sandberg, Mark Doody, and others. The narrator picks one that he likes best, the one about the fall. He picks a poem by Doody called \"theory of beauty Pompeii,\" which is about a girl reading a book in a cafe line. He thinks the poem is beautiful, but he wishes it were written in a Gothic novel.',NULL,NULL),(63986,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 25, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 04:47:36',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(63987,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Here Today - September 25, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 04:34:32',NULL,'Aaron Badgley welcomes listeners to his show on CFRU\'s 93.3FM and the CFRU.com. He explains that he is hosting the show because he is a fan of music and he is always looking for new music.\n\nHe plays a lot of music from different artists, including James Clark Institute who have a new album coming out soon. Aaron also plays a new song from MeeLo, who is releasing his first album. He also plays some music from the new album by the Church of Trees who are also releasing their first album in the next few years. Aaron is also psyched to play a song by Deborah Fialco from her romantic English album. Also on the show is a new track from David Francie who is on tour with his new album. Aaron says he is glad to hear new music from David because he has been looking for a song from him.',NULL,NULL),(63988,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/This Night Wounds Time - September 25, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 04:17:43',NULL,'This week\'s program opens with the narrator talking about the new merchandise line at CFRU, and about the fact that the university is also a great resource for information on how to become a volunteer at the university. He also talks about a new program called \"This Night Wounds\" that he\'s going to play tonight on the university\'s public radio station, 93.\n\n3 FM, in Guelph, Ont. The program is all about music from the province of Corrientes, which is located in the southern part of Argentina. The music featured tonight is from the band Amboué, who have a song called \"Me paje\" and another called \"Rfpegde.\" The narrator notes that this song has a lot of mature subject-matter, and that it\'s not necessarily a celebration of political history.',NULL,NULL),(63989,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/This Night Wounds Time - September 25, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 03:10:05',NULL,'The show is now at the geographical part of the stage, and it is time for the spotlight section. It is the time when the show spotlights artists from various countries. The show starts off with the geographical spotlight of Russia, followed by Canada, China, and the United States. Next, the show goes on to Brazil, Australia, India, China and finally Argentina. The last country to be spotlighted is the smallest country on the scale, the Vatican City. The next smallest country is the Marshall Islands, which are tiny little islands in the middle of the Pacific Ocean.',NULL,NULL),(63990,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/24/This Night Wounds Time - September 24, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-24 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 02:48:25',NULL,'In this week\'s program, Christopher Curry discusses the philosophy behind This Night, Wounds Time, which is a live music show that usually runs for three hours. The show usually begins with music that is \"off the beaten track,\" which means that the music is not really in the center of the music world. The music on the show will be from around the world, and the program will shift after the first half of the show to focus on music from a specific region of the world.\n\nThis week, the focus will shift to the state of Argentina, so we\'ll start off with music from the University of California, San Francisco\'s \"new release collection.\" This is an amazing collection of music, and it\'s called \"Continuing.\" It\'s a collection of covers of jazz standards, which used to be very common in the jazz world back in the day.\n\nBut these days, with the rise of the \"new wave\" of avant-garde artists, there\'s no longer a need for artists to release \"albums of standards.\" Instead, they release albums of original compositions. This is the case with the new release by the \"Taishon Sori\" Trio. The trio consists of drummer/pianist/bassist/guitarist/vocalist/composer/arranger/etc., and they\'ve recorded a song by the late great Wayne Shorter. This song was actually recorded in December of last year before he died, but it worked out remarkably',NULL,NULL),(63996,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8y483p/September_23rd_2023_Critic_s_Circle6l309.mp3','2023-09-25 14:41:32',143961989,'2023-12-07 02:30:39',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with Daniel Garber and Lynn Slotkin. The first part of the interview is about Daniel Garber going to the movies and the other part is about Lynn\'s play. The show is hosted by Phil Taylor, and it is a public radio show in Canada. The program features a variety of different guests, including Daniel at the movies, and Daniel reviews plays.\n\nThe other guests are Phil Conlon, a music critic and the founder of the Underground, and Lynn, a playgoer. They are all on the show now to discuss the latest news. The Underground has announced that the Waterloo Symphony Orchestra has gone out of business because of a lack of money.',NULL,NULL),(64001,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Breezy Breakfast Radio - September 25, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 02:12:17',NULL,'The chapter opens with a description of the city of Guelph, which is home to a number of First Nations communities. The city is hosting an open-mic with a crowd in the community. The purpose of the open mic is to hear people discuss issues that are important to them. They do not have Phil Ault to answer any questions, so they will be able to hear directly from the city. There is no direct answer to any questions that the crowd asks, so the group will try to answer them as quickly as possible.\n\nThe chapter ends with a conversation about the upcoming 200th anniversary of the first European settlement in the area. It is unclear whether any people from the community have approached the First Nations to organize a celebration, but no one has approached the Catholic Church or the government to invite King Charles to come to the area because of the last name of the First Nation.',NULL,NULL),(64002,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Volunteer Playlist - September 25, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-07 01:48:13',NULL,'This week on Democracy Now!, we learn that the Kidney Walk is a great opportunity to celebrate the strength of the kidney community.\n\nIt\'s also a great time to support the Comedy Festival, which is celebrating its 10th year. We also learn about the expanded Studio Tour and sale event that will take place on the weekend of October 14th and 15th. And finally, we hear that the Writers Guild has reached a new agreement with the Hollywood studios after 146 days of a strike. And then we hear about the Supreme Court Justice, Clarence Thomas, who is under new scrutiny after it was discovered that he participated in two right wing donor events organized by the Koch political network.',NULL,NULL),(64012,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Democracy Now - September 25, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 01:27:44',NULL,'This week, we continue our conversation with the author of the New York Times article \"The Rise of the Supreme Court as a Public Utility.\" The author discusses a number of recent Supreme Court cases, including a case called \"Chevron,\" which challenges the power of the federal government to regulate oil and gas development. The court\'s case in this case, however, is called \"Covenant.\" The court is considering adopting some kind of formal rules to govern political donations, but it\'s unclear whether they\'ll actually follow them.',NULL,NULL),(64013,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Worst Responders - September 25, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-07 01:10:40',NULL,'In this episode of Worst Responders, Host Jesse and Host Charissa discuss the importance of writing down a set before performing it. Jesse says that he has never written down his entire set before, so he has to break it down into smaller pieces to be more concise. He says he has a shorthand for the parts that he needs to remember, so that\'s how he writes down his notes. Host Jesse asks him if there\'s one skill that a comic needs to have to be good. He doesn\'t know, but he does know that a good comic should be able to be funny',NULL,NULL),(64023,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/CFRU Playlist - September 25, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-25 20:06:29',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64024,9234,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Art Not Shame Panel Discussion - September 25, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 00:55:39',NULL,'Art Not Shame hosts an event called \"Art In A Just Recovery: Unveiling\" on June 7th. This event includes a panel discussion and the introduction of the mural. The event is recorded by CFRU and is available on the organization\'s website.',NULL,NULL),(64034,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/qd6gxc/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Sept_27_2023_podcastb1fsp.mp3','2023-09-25 20:22:13',279886366,'2023-12-07 00:24:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64035,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - September 25, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-07 00:10:53',NULL,'In this chapter, the Guardian introduces his new role as guardian of the music scene. He will look at the diverse music scene from an \"inward and beyond\" perspective. He wants to pay respect to both the ancestral territories and local native communities. He also wants to acknowledge the contributions of the Black community, for their \"too often dismissed, uncredited, and/or ignored contributions to todays popular alternative.\" The first artist to be featured in this chapter is Daniel Field of Kilimeter Club, who will release his new album on September 29 th .',NULL,NULL),(64045,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/to know the land - September 25, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-30 17:22:02',NULL,'The University of Guelph\'s social media accounts have been blocked by the government\'s censorship bill, which makes it impossible for students to access their accounts on Facebook, Instagram, and Google. Students can still support the university by signing up for their newsletter, which will continue to include community updates. The University\'s public affairs manager, Byron, also addresses the censorship issue, telling listeners that the university will not be able to share its content on social media because of the bill. He encourages listeners to contact their Member of Parliament, Lloyd Longfield, to protest the censorship bill',NULL,'The University of Guelph’s social media accounts have been blocked by the government’s censorship bill'),(64046,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Big Sis Radio - September 25, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 23:08:58',NULL,'In this episode, Griffins introduces himself and his new show, Big Sis Radio. He explains that it\'s a community radio station that airs every Monday at 5pm on CFRU, 93.3 and at the University of G. He also explains that if you\'re a new student coming to the university this fall, he\'s happy to welcome you.\n\nGriffins also mentions that he wants to introduce you to the University\'s Native American community. The first song he\'ll play for you is a cover by Buffy St-Marie, who\'s known for her Anishinaabe art. Ombigazi recognized that she\'s an Anishaabe artist and wanted to wish Buffy well. The band also played a cover of Love God, Sarah Kinsley\'s song about God. The last song we\'ll hear is a song by the Beaches, called \"Edge of the Earth,\" which is about a breakup.\n\nLeandra Earl wrote the song. The narrator notes that this song might be good for letting your feelings flow after a breakup, especially if you feel like you\'ve been hanging out with someone too long. Finally, the narrator talks about the importance of beaver dams to the environment and how they make ecosystems more resilient during droughts. If you think that\'s not enough, remember that beaver dams are considered a \"Keystone Species\" because they\'re so important in the environment.',NULL,NULL),(64056,212,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wp2xba/BFFull.mp3','2023-09-26 01:28:56',207450112,'2023-12-06 22:48:00',NULL,'In this program, Chris Durand introduces the North Carolinian band Ben Folds. Formed in the mid-90s, the band consists of Ben Fold on piano, vocals, and Robert Sledge and Darren Jesse. They performed what they called \"punk rock\" for \"sissys.\" They released three LPs before their breakup and reunited in early 2010 with a new album called \"The Sound of Life of Mind.\"',NULL,NULL),(64057,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Blues Around the Block - September 25, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 22:26:01',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64058,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Blues Around the Block - September 25, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 22:06:51',NULL,'The show opens with a live band, and they play a number of songs. The first song is by Dutch Mason, and the second is by Jim Burns, still stuck on you. The third is by Eddie Cleanhead, the fourth is by Susie Vinik and the fifth is by Bill Wharton. The food is Chicken Livers.',NULL,NULL),(64068,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/CFRU Playlist - September 26, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 06:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-26 14:06:18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64069,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/The Deep House Project - September 25, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 21:48:00',NULL,'On this week\'s edition of the Sounds Like Old Times program, host Doug Blackwood discusses the fact that only 31% of Ontario residents have registered to donate their organ and tissue. If you\'re interested in becoming a donor, you can go to BeDonAor.ca and fill out an application.\n\nAnd if you\'d like to learn more about how to get involved with organ donation, check out the Canadian Association of Organ Sharing\'s website. The show is also a part of the 10-year-anniversary celebration of the Guelph comedy festival. There\'s also a show coming up called Clown Prov. It\'ll be hosted by Ken Hall, Isaac Kessler, and others. It will take place on October 21st at the Guelph Comedy Fest. You can register for the Clown-Prov at GuelphComedyFest.com. This week the Deep House project is broadcasting live from the university campus. They\'ve got a bunch of new and old tracks for you to listen to. They start off with Dabin and William Black\'s collaboration Black in the cold, which is perfect for the first weeks of autumn.\n\nThey also have some remixes from Kevin Glasgow and Martino\'s supernova. They are both GTA based DJs, and they\'re still in the game, but have recently been in the scene. They heard another remix from John Summit and another from The Rhythm, who is very well known as a DJ. Right now the Deep house project is listening to a Tronic track',NULL,NULL),(64070,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 26, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 21:26:21',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64071,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Back in the USSR - September 25, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 21:10:20',NULL,'Back in the Union on CFRU 92.3.3 FM. Seigfried gives an update on the recent BRICS meeting in South Africa. The BRICS is a grouping of fast-growing countries, including Russia, China, India and South Africa, that have banded together to create an alternative to the International Monetary Fund. The US and the European Union have recently placed unprecedented economic sanctions on Russia as a result of the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2022. This means that the economies of the BRICS member states are suffering from the effects of these Western sanctions.',NULL,NULL),(64072,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/25/Ripcord Radio - September 25, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-25 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 20:48:41',NULL,'The show starts with a great mix of music from the Great Lakes and a few from overseas. The first band we\'ll hear is Mexican Power Authority, who came out of British Columbia in the early 1990s. They\'ve released a bunch of records, including some of the best punk rock of all time. They have a jazz band, a blind man band, an American band, and a French band. Next, we hear a bunch more music from overseas, including a Canadian band, two American bands, and one from France. The show ends with some more great music from Hamilton.',NULL,NULL),(64074,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Rainbow Country - September 26, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 20:29:40',NULL,'In this program, we hear about how the College of Film, Film, and Media at CFRU is looking for people to help with outreach at festivals, jazz festivals, and other community events. We also learn about the university\'s YouTube channel, where they post all of their live performances and interviews.\n\nThe host of the show, Mark Tara, is also on the show. He is a Canadian Olympian who is a leader of the Hillside Athletic Club. The show is hosted by Mark\'s friend and fellow athlete, the wrestler, Mark Tewsbury. The campus is home to the Film and Film Office, the College\'s campus community radio station, and the University\'s media center. The Film Office is looking to hire people to cover local events and to celebrate community. They also need volunteers to record public service announcements. If you\'re interested in joining them, they\'ll train you on how to use a microphone. The hosts of the Tales from the Bridges podcast, Sam and Marty, are also on this program. They\'re looking to recruit new science fiction and science fiction authors and directors to create their own science fiction.\n\nThe listeners can check out their show on CFRU. You can also check out the Tails from the Bridge website to find out more about their work. They are also looking for listeners to join their weekly show on YouTube, where you can watch all of the live performances on the Green-Screen Dream Machine. The police constable, Danielle Bot',NULL,NULL),(64075,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Rainbow Country - September 26, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 17:09:56',NULL,'This is the second part of a two part interview with the co-hosts of a new Canadian show called \"Rainbow Country.\" The first part is from Emily Saliers, a programmer from the Indigo Girls radio station in Toronto, and the second is from Carol Pope, author of \"Boy Erased,\" a memoir. They are joined by Lorraine Segato, a poet and musician, and Mark Tara, producer and host of the show. The show airs on 12 different Canadian stations, and can be found in syndication on many more.',NULL,NULL),(64085,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5wz85s/utopia_review_filebhnhm.mp3','2023-09-26 15:58:35',85101366,'2023-12-06 16:47:53',NULL,'From the roots down CIUT 89.6 FM . From',NULL,NULL),(64086,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Solipsistic Retreat - September 26, 2023 at 10:19 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 10:19:00',1508,'2023-12-06 16:27:24',NULL,'This is the first half of the show, where the listeners are about to hear a song called \"Formless\" by Orgon. The narrator asks if this is a \"breathtaking exercise\" in female folk. Or is he a \"rascal for questioning\" the teacher? Or is it just a \"magic realism\" thing to do? The narrator then goes through a list of songs that he\'s listened to in the past five years.\n\nFirst, he goes through \"Olsen Twins Eternal Water,\" which was released in 2018. And then he goes over \"Sonic Use Sister\" which was first released in 1987. And finally, he talks about \"In A Moment Divine\" which is a song by a female vocalist named Cindy Lee. He feels like music is \"helping to corrupt youth of America\" .',NULL,NULL),(64087,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Solipsistic Retreat - September 26, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 16:07:19',NULL,'This is the second part of the \"formless\" section of the show. We find out that the voice of Oricogon is very interesting, and that everything in the world has a \"form aura\" . We\'ll get to that in a bit. But first, we have to listen to some of the music we\'ve heard on the program. First, we listen to the first two songs from the Quarry, which is where the Orcogon album was released. It\'s called \"Eternal Water Falling\" by the Olsen Twins and \"Sonic Use Sister\" by Kim Gordon. Next, we\'re listening to \"Freight Heak Waves\" and \"In A Moment Divine\" by Cindy Lee. And then we\'ll check in on our friend, the \"musicist\" who\'s been trying to corrupt American youth.',NULL,NULL),(64090,167,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/enjsff/September_22nd_2023_Funky_Fridaysarenp.mp3','2023-09-26 17:12:23',431961989,'2023-12-06 15:50:51',NULL,'The show starts off with a track from Norman Whitfield\'s 1975 album, Cosmic Truth, which was produced by the man himself. Next up is Milton Wright, who had been a successful musician in his own right. Next is Mel and Tim, who released a hit record in the early 60s with Backfield In Motion.\n\nThen they went to Stax and had a big hit with Making Love Is My Thing. Mr. Pete and the Funky Friday crew start off by playing some of their favorite tracks from the 70s and 80s. They include Arthur Lee Reeves who played blues and then switched to funk, Arthur Adams who played the blues but then switched over to jazz, and finally the band The Natural Yogurt Band who were married and played on the Gong Show.',NULL,NULL),(64093,175,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ytjn4r/September_21st_2023_No_Man_s_Land9j7qs.mp3','2023-09-26 17:09:32',287962512,'2023-12-06 15:06:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64094,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pxpi9v/September_24th_2023_EqualizingXDistortb84ht.mp3','2023-09-26 16:47:03',287962512,'2023-12-06 14:53:29',NULL,'This is the second in a two part interview with Neon Andre, the host of the music show, \"Caut Equalizing to Store.\" In this interview, he discusses the history of his band, Neon Taste, which was the first label to release punk music. He also discusses his bandmates, including Josh Nickel, who is the vocalist in the band, \"Chain Whip,\" and the guitar player in \"Bootlicker.\" The second part of the interview will focus on Josh\'s time at \"Neon Taste,\" and he explains how the label came to be.',NULL,NULL),(64095,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bdujru/September_17th_2023_EqualizingXDistortbad2k.mp3','2023-09-26 16:46:27',287962512,'2023-12-06 14:33:12',NULL,'This week on the program, the host of the community radio station, CIUT FM, is joined by his co-host, Chris Heffernan, who is also a member of the punk band, Equalizing XDistort. The program begins with a song called \"I\'m Angry,\" which is from the 1978 recording of Richard Helen, the Voidoids . The show will also include a live performance by the band, and a feature on the guitarist, Ivan Julien, who played in the band. He also introduces the guest, a musician, producer, and style innovator who will be playing a show in Toronto on September 22 and 23.',NULL,NULL),(64096,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/t64cjc/September_10th_2023_EqualizingXDistortaqkig.mp3','2023-09-26 16:45:32',287962512,'2023-12-06 14:12:54',NULL,'EqualizingXtort is a new music show from Counterpoint. They have a lot of music on the show, including a bunch of new releases and some classics like One Way System, Subhumans, and the polls. They also have an interview with the lead singer of the polls, Michael Jordana. The show also has some new releases like Psychwar and Fake Armored Tashme FM.\n\nThe band Front Eyes from Edmonton is also in the mix. They\'re also going to have a band called The Chats, which is a punk band from Toronto. Next up on the program is the interview with Michael. He\'s the guy who wrote the song, \"Primetime,\" which is also on the single. The interview is a bit of an odyssey. It\'s a bit about the idea of starting a band, and it\'s kind of like a letter to the creator of the band. It seems like the artist is well known for his art. He says he was involved in many different kinds of art, and that he started the band because of that.\n\nHe also says he came back from the Arctic with the idea that the polls would start up. The idea of the poll was very moving. We learn that the first time the polls played was at the New York City club A-Space in 1977. The interview ends with a discussion about the early days of the punk scene.',NULL,NULL),(64097,178,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/d397ja/September_3rd_2023_EqualizingXDistortb2buh.mp3','2023-09-26 16:44:01',287962512,'2023-12-06 13:51:28',NULL,'The show opens with a description of the music on the air. It\'s all about loud music that you can listen to when you are angry.\n\nThe music starts with a song called Gizm by a band called Endless Blockade For The PussyFooter. The song is about a guy named Sukevi who was a member of the band. The band is going to do some music reviews and a profile on a label called Efira Records from Connecticut. The first track in the set is a new release by Chain Whip called \"Call of the Knife. The second track is a teaser for their upcoming Neon Punk LP on Taste. The third track is by two balloys. The fourth track is called Jubilee. The fifth track is from another band called Katarsi.\n\nThe sixth track is another synth punk called \"Ezzod Lagoon. The seventh track is an amazing track from a band named Flash. The last track is \"Desarmonle\" by a French band called Camellia Sinensis, who released a demo in 2023. This is their first C-a-t equalized distro, which is basically a music store with all the music and lyrics from all the different music stores in one place',NULL,NULL),(64101,186,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pya5xi/September_21st_2023_Higher_Ground8u80h.mp3','2023-09-26 17:10:20',287962512,'2023-12-06 13:08:41',NULL,'The program opens with a tribute to Matthew Halsted, who has recently released a new album titled \"Afro Train Volume 2: Song of the Forefathers.\" It is the first release from the new Nat Virtual Afro Train, a series of Afro-Cuban instrumentals. The program ends with a shout-out to the University of South Florida\'s Afro-Latino Day, which is taking place in Detroit in the next few weeks. The show closes with a mix of new music from Lorenzo Horic and La Esso.',NULL,NULL),(64104,191,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/3nh36s/September_23rd_2023_Frisson_Radio8xg1j.mp3','2023-09-26 17:32:48',287962512,'2023-12-06 12:46:53',NULL,'This is a trip into sound! A journey which will bring you a new color, new dimension and new values. Welcome to Frison Radio! The show is hosted by Nabeel Pervadiz and it\'s all about music. He\'s got some great tracks to choose from, so check it out. The first track is by Diddy, who has teamed up with Justin Bieber. Sounds great.',NULL,NULL),(64105,191,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/88bp4u/September_9th_2023_Frisson_Radiobni71.mp3','2023-09-26 17:31:58',287962512,'2023-12-06 12:28:20',NULL,'This is the first time that we\'ve heard the name \"Nabeel\" on the program, which means \"Host\" in Arabic. The first hour is all about music. We\'ll hear some new music from some of the hottest artists in the city, including Charlotte Cardin , Govee , Safe , Jock Green , and more. And this isn\'t just any music. This is a music show, and we\'re talking the best of Canadian music. So, yeah, this is the best music you\'ve ever heard. And it\'s from the hottest music scene in the world: the world of Canadian artists.\n\nIt starts off with a new song by Amalou, who\'s just released her new album, \"I Came Home Late\" . Next, there\'s a new track from another Canadian singer, Tay Iwar , who just came out with her debut album. And finally, there is a new single from a new artist named Kiebra, who was playing in a festival in the park last weekend.',NULL,NULL),(64106,191,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zaj4c6/September_2nd_2023_Frisson_Radio9crfe.mp3','2023-09-26 17:27:00',287962512,'2023-12-06 12:10:26',NULL,'In this episode, the guys at CIUT FM thank everyone who gave during their fall campaign. If you didn\'t donate yet, they still need your support to reach their goal of $100K.\n\nCheck it out: CIUTFM.org/donate. The guys at Frisson Radio bring you a new music show this week called \"One-Word: Love.\" It\'s all about love and music. In the first hour, we hear some of the best new music from the city, including a new track from Taku and his partner in crime, Panama. The two of them are back with another new song from their new project, \"Songs to Come Home.\" The new song is also produced by Taku.',NULL,NULL),(64107,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wup8pv/Karibuni_Show_September_24_20235yj1r.mp3','2023-09-26 17:19:31',287962512,'2023-12-06 11:50:50',NULL,'The show starts off with a thank you note from CIUT FM for all the financial support they\'ve received. They still need to raise more money to reach their goal of $100,000, so they invite listeners to give them a little extra cash. The program continues with a song from Africa by one of the station\'s favorite artists, Papawimba, and then they head over to hear some more music from other artists from West and Central Africa. The first song is from a group called Benin International Music, and the second is from Eddie Kanfro. The third song is also from Benin International, and this is by the late Papawamba.',NULL,NULL),(64108,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wq5wgw/September_23rd_2023_The_Minx_Sessions7m7eg.mp3','2023-09-26 16:58:20',287962512,'2023-12-06 11:26:40',NULL,'The Minx Sessions is a weekly independent music show hosted by Binny. In this program, Binny takes listeners on an eclectic journey through the world of independent music. Throughout the program, he describes the music that he will be playing, including new releases from various artists, remixes, and mixes. He also gives a shout-out to the various artists that have appeared on the show, and he encourages listeners to follow his social media accounts.',NULL,NULL),(64109,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/u5r5i8/September_23rd_2023_Calling_All_Bluesbtuyj.mp3','2023-09-26 16:55:02',143961989,'2023-12-06 11:07:39',NULL,'The Calling All Blues Show begins with the announcement that the show will be playing blues music by Bob Dylan. The show will also include some of Dylan\'s classic songs, along with some of his greatest hits. The first song is \"Bringing it all back\" from his album \"Bring It All Back.\n\n\" The second song is Bullcalf Blues from Paul James\'s Lost in the blues album. The third song is from Dylans \"Highway 61 Revisited.\" The fourth song is Bo Diddley\'s \"Bring it to Jerome.\" The fifth song is the \"Subterranean homesick blues\" from the album \"Homesick Blues.\" The sixth song is Blind Willie Mctell\'s blues from his \"Buleseries Tombstone Volumes 1-3.\" The seventh song is Howlin\' wolf\'s version of \"I Ain\'t superstitious.\" The eighth song is Bob Dylans dirt road blues. The ninth song is a blues song by the legendary singer Lonnie Johnson. The song is called \"Tomorrow night by Lonnie Johnson/Muddy Waters I just want to make love to you.\" The show closes with a song by Dylan himself, \"My wife\'s hometown.\"',NULL,NULL),(64110,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Bridging The Social Distance - September 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 10:47:15',NULL,'The narrator\'s name is Fei Mei, which means \"I was born in the land of the rising sun\" . The narrator tells us that he and his family moved to Shanghai when he was a baby, and that his father was a journalist. He was born during the war, and his mother and father returned to America. The war ended, and the family moved back to North Dakota, where they lived with their grandparents and their grandfather was a Lutheran minister. The family lived there for a while, and then moved to Northwood, where the narrator and his father went to work.',NULL,NULL),(64111,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Democracy Now - September 26, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 10:29:55',NULL,'A deadly explosion at a fuel depot in the disputed South Caucasus territory has killed at least 20 people and wounded nearly 300 others. Thousands of Armenians have fled to neighboring Armenia. On Monday representatives of the region\'s ethnic Armenians held another round of talks with Azerbaijani officials, but no details were made public about the meeting. Azerbaijan\'s President, Elam al-Aleyev, has pledged his government will ensure the safety of everyone in the region.',NULL,NULL),(64121,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - September 26, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 10:08:24',NULL,'This is the third hour of Power Up!, and it\'s all about the death of Dubay. He was 43 years old when he died in a hijacking attempt.\n\nBefore that, the show heard songs from Spring, Lucky Dubay\'s son, and The Delays. The band formed in 2001, but they never made much of a name for themselves in Canada. Twelve years have passed since the band played their first show, and they\'ve had a singer named Greg Gilbert diagnosed with stage four bowel cancer. He passed away on September 30, 2011 at age 44. So, this is all about Greg Gilbert, who was the lead singer of the band.\n\nNow we\'re back to Canadian music, this time with Rock Voisin. He\'s a singer-songwriter who\'s been recorded in both French and English. He has a huge following in Quebec and has lots of success in Europe. In this set, we hear songs from Wild Strawberries, a band that formed in 1988, and from the Super Jesus. The Super Jesus were an Australian band that disbanded in 1994 and reformed in 2013. They\'re called Dream Spirit. The song they just heard is called Shut my Eyes.',NULL,NULL),(64122,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Under the Needle - September 26, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 09:51:13',NULL,'On this episode of Live on K.EXP, the CFRU co-host, Renee, chats with the comedians from the Do-It-Yourself Comedy Tour. The tour is coming to Marathon, Wawa and other places in the north for the next few nights. So, why don\'t you send a message to all of your friends in the area to catch this comedy train.\n\nThe comedians are in town, but Scott Porchess couldn\'t join them. The show ends with a Q&A with Frank Russo and Mike Payne. Frank and Mike talk about how the tour is doing, and how it\'s going. They talk about the beautiful nature of the area they\'re in.',NULL,NULL),(64127,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8mvf9n/DrMouth_CIUTshow_sept26_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-09-26 20:42:45',288726848,'2023-12-06 09:32:49',NULL,'Dr. Mouse returns to the program with a new song, this time called \"The End of Man.\" The song is a tribute to Porcupine tree, one of Brown\'s favorite bands. The song was originally released in the early 90s and is one of his favorites. The other songs include \"Up to Down Stair,\" \"The Sky Moves Sideway,\" \"Porcupine Tree,\" and \"The Delirium Years,\" a compilation of early Porcupines. He also shares a few of his favorite albums, including \"Stars Die,\" which was released in 1997.',NULL,NULL),(64133,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/Silver Screen Dream Machine - September 26, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 09:11:00',NULL,'This week on Silver Dream Machine, we hear music from three different films: Doctor Strange, the sequel to the Marvel Cinematic Universe; the 1994 video Need for Speed; and the 2018 Marvel Cinematic universe feature, Doctor Strange. We also hear from a Canadian animated short film, Caterpillar Plasti. The music is from a song by David Usher, a lead singer in the Canadian rock band, Moist. The song was inspired by a binge on Tarantino films. The songs from the films also inspire us to sing.',NULL,NULL),(64134,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/26/A Multilingual Affair - September 26, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-26 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 08:52:38',NULL,'The song opens with the