e heading to Greece to hear music. Next week they\'ll be talking to Fedra about Greek culture and how her experience has informed her studies. They\'ll also be talking about Andromeda, a song by a famous Italian musician. Seth is half-Greek, so he can\'t say the name of the song. The last thing that they want to mention is that last weekend Seth, Isabella, and another volunteer joined them on a trip to the Golden Gate to speak at a Global Jazz Conference. They spoke to a Toronto artist named Monika. He was very talented, and Seth says that he\'s been involved with lots of different people in the city.\n\nHe suggests that listeners follow the show on Soundcloud and listen to all of the interviews. Seth and Phaedra are also on the show, and they\'ve been talking to Phaedras from Greece. She\'s doing a performance class and a morning class. She says that one of her friends bought her and her sister a show to watch at the end the year.',NULL,NULL),(64371,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 28, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 08:07:47',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64372,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Here Today - September 28, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 07:10:54',NULL,'This is the first hour of the show, and it\'s all about new music. The first act is a Swedish band called Retro-Graaf, who are playing new music from their upcoming EP, Coercion, as well as a song called \"The Divine\" from the recently released Romantic England. The band is touring and releasing new music all the time. The second act is an American band called Dance Electronica, who have just released their new album called \"I Am Not Myself\" . The third act is another American band, called Hotel Myra, who\'ve just released an album. The show ends with some new music by a Canadian artist named David Francie, who is on a tour.',NULL,NULL),(64382,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/FoodFarm Talk - September 28, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 06:48:10',NULL,'The second episode of the six-a-gates to tipie or blackfoot agriculture project opens with a conversation between Lancefeathers of blood tribe or Kainai first nation and Mike Bruised head, a long-time rancher at Kainai.\n\nThe purpose of the treaty is to \"honour and revitalize the traditional relationship we have\" with Buffalo. The Blackfoot nations have signed the treaty since day one, and there are now 31 signatories. Another organization that Mike mentions is the Kainai Ecosystem Protection Association, or KIPA. KIPA was a cool organization that used to organize a summit for people off the reserve to attend, but it\'s become a really cool way to learn about the reserve and connect with other people. Just before he hands things over to Mike and Lance, Lahey gives us an update on the Sixakate-Satipii agriculture project. It\'s more than just a podcast. It is a project that\'s trying to connect Blackfoot nation members with each other and learn best practices from each other.',NULL,NULL),(64383,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Tales from the Bridge - September 28, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 06:33:01',NULL,'We start off this episode by saying that we\'re psyched to have a guest on our show today. It\'s none other than New York Times best-selling science fiction author, Andy Weir.\n\nHe joins us on the bridge and tells us all about his life. He started out as a Software Engineer and then became a full-blown science fiction writer. His first novel, \"The Martian,\" was made into a movie starring Matt Damon, and his latest book, \"Project Hail Mary,\" is being adapted into a feature film starring Ryan Gosling. The book is a Hugo Award-finalist and is one of his favorite science fiction novels.',NULL,NULL),(64393,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Democracy Now - September 28, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 01:07:39',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64394,12585,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/CFRU Mobile Community Radio Show - September 28, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 00:48:25',NULL,'Jenny Mitchell, a volunteer and studio coordinator for Community Radio Guelph, is here to tell us about the North-End Harvest Market, an initiative of the Guelph Neighbourhood Support Coalition. The market is a place where people can meet with other people in the community to get fresh produce. Jenny is surprised to find that she has a recorder with her at the market.',NULL,NULL),(64399,180,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/y736p4/HOWL_SEPT_29_20239pmib.mp3','2023-09-28 20:02:34',56693156,'2023-12-05 00:26:48',NULL,'This is the second part of a three part interview with the co-hosts of CIUT FM. The first part is a thank you note to the listeners for their financial support. The second part is about the upcoming October 31st Howl-o-ween Open Mic. The third part is the announcement of the Halloween Open Mic in 2023. The co-host tells the listeners that he will be starting off the show with a friend from his poetry community from Toronto. Before he reveals her name, he tells them about a poem he wrote for the show.',NULL,NULL),(64405,205,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/bepj4e/September_28th_2023_Music_At_High_Noonaxfsg.mp3','2023-09-28 18:14:44',287962512,'2023-12-05 00:05:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64406,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Android’s Dungeon - September 28, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 23:46:57',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64407,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Eclectic Selections - September 28, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 23:06:05',NULL,'The show\'s new name is \"Eclectic Selections\" and it\'s going to be all about exploring music beyond the boundaries of one genre. We\'re starting with free jazz. The music is from the past. It was recorded in the early 2000s.\n\nIt sounds like there\'s a lot of soul in this music, even though it sounds like it was recorded by free jazz artists like Grover Washington Jr and Bill Withers. It also sounds like this music was recorded on Bob Dylan\'s \"Pretty Woman\" album. We also find out that Michael Kewanuku wrote a song called \"Love and Hate\" that sounds a lot like this one. It has a spiritual vibe to it. The show ends with a song about freedom.',NULL,NULL),(64417,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/RadiOPIRG - September 28, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 22:50:36',NULL,'The 10 year anniversary is fast approaching. The Comedy Festival is bringing in some of the best comedians in the province. This is a great opportunity for us to get together and talk about the festival. On this particular day, the festival decided to celebrate by hosting a march.\n\nThe march was organized by five northern Ontario First Nations. They came together to call on the Ford government to stop mining activities on their lands. The festival worked with the Wellington water watchers and the Guelph students for environmental change to organize a bus to the march. On the way back, they ran into Chief Rudy Turtle, the leader of the Grassy-Narrows First Nation. He\'s just gotten back from the march, so he doesn\'t have a watch with him.\n\nHe thanks the festival for coming out and thanking him for coming to listen to them. He says that for 50 years, the First Nation has been suffering from mercury poisoning. The First Nation used to have a paper mill. The government dumped a lot of mercury into the river, but the government hasn\'t done anything about it. Now that the government has a plan, they\'re going to have to pay the First Nations for it. One of the former advisors to the government came up to him and said that he used to work for the government.\n\nHe told him that they were going to the mill. He also told the minister not to worry about it, it\'ll all be all right.',NULL,NULL),(64418,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/T.K.O. - September 28, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 22:31:08',NULL,'This is the first in a series of interviews with the Host of the Combat Sports Podcast, Tim Killam, or \"TKO.\" He tells his listeners about his show, which he calls \"Mixed Martial Arts\" or \"MMA.\" He explains that it\'s all about combat sports and \"issues that surround the universe with fighting.\n\n\" The show has been going strong for the past week, and he says that he couldn\'t be happier. He asks the listeners to tell him what\'s up with them. He says that this week has been a \"phenomenal week\" and that he hopes everyone had a good day. He tells the listeners that he\'s glad that the show is celebrating episode 340. He adds that he doesn\'t like to celebrate the milestone by baking a cake, but he does like to acknowledge how far the show has come since it started. He compares the amount of time that it would take him to record all of the episodes to the hours he\'d have to talk to the void on his personal phone.\n\nIt\'s hard for him to believe that he could have recorded every single episode of the show, but that\'s what he does. He thanks his listeners for their support and says that even if he could not have done it without them, he wouldn\'t have made it to this point. He also thanks the listeners for being such a huge part of his success. He admits that it makes him feel proud and humbled.',NULL,NULL),(64423,182,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dkphsi/Sept_27_2023bbghl.mp3','2023-09-28 22:19:17',142703803,'2023-12-04 22:09:12',NULL,'In this week\'s edition of No Beat, the host of the show, Suresh, thanks listeners for their financial support. He\'s been listening to new music from all over the city, and the first song he plays is from a band called \"Grave Desecrator,\" which is an abstract project by a Canadian artist named Bradley Davis.\n\nThe second song is from another Canadian band called Science Furric, which is celebrating its 25th anniversary. The third track is from the band \"Office Album,\" which sounds like it\'s going to be a hidden track. The fourth track is a song called \"Song Number 4,\" from an album called \"Crossing Field,\" by a band named Mono Negatives. The fifth track is an album from \"Lon Redhead,\" an early punk band from London. The sixth track is one of my favorites, from \"Repress and Curl,\" an album by \"Shabbo Palace, Black up.\" The seventh track is \"End of the World,\" from \"Dr. Systems,\" a psychedelic music collective from Toronto.',NULL,NULL),(64429,257,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/xpmm6w/September_28_2023_Psychedelic_Stoner_Rock72dhy.mp3','2023-09-28 22:23:33',287962512,'2023-12-04 21:45:04',NULL,'On this edition of Psychedelic And Stoner Rock, Ken Stauer delivers the first hour\'s program from a diverse group of artists, including Middle Mist Red, Kaiser Moon, El Caco, Egypt, Stoned Jesus, The Hazy tones, and the Black cat\'s eye. The program\'s title is Multicolored Drive and the first two hours of the program will begin with Middle Mist red.',NULL,NULL),(64430,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Open Sources Guelph - September 28, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 19:30:35',NULL,'On this week\'s episode of Open-Source\'s Guelph, the host of the political and current affairs show at the University of Guelph, Adam Donaldson, takes a look back at some of the recent events in the city. The show opens with a quick introduction to the program, and the host introduces himself as Adam Donaldson. Adam is a professor of political science at the university. He is also a co-host of the Open Source Discussion Show, a weekly program on the university\'s campus. The program is hosted by Adam, who is also the co-editor of the Political and Current affairs section of the university newspaper, the Guelph Politico. Adam describes the program as a public affairs show. It is produced by a group of students and faculty members who work together to discuss issues of public concern. It airs every Thursday evening at 5pm on CFRU. This program is a mix of current affairs, news, and entertainment from around the world. This week, the program will be covering elections in Manitoba, politics in Parliament, and a number of other topics. The first topic of the show is the Green Belt, which the province\'s premier, Doug Ford, broke his promise not to open it. He apologizes for breaking his promise. He says it was a mistake, and one that left too much space for people to benefit from it. It also left people to question the motives of the government. He also says that he will not make any changes in the',NULL,'Open-Source’s Adam Donaldson is the host of the political and current affairs show in Guelph'),(64431,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Turtle Island Underground - September 28, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 21:09:32',NULL,'The show opens with an interlude from a new record by the Tewa titled \"Gum Chum With an Indian Bum\". It can be found on the archives at the CFRU.com as well as a special interview with the band a few weeks before.\n\nDorothy and Natasha from LindyVision play some songs from their latest record \"The Third Kind\" and transform them into an \"entire listening experience\". They have become more of a \"new wave indie\" band than they were a few years ago. The show ends with a mix of lo-fi and local music. Next up is a new release by the Ennook singer, Katsu, who is a member of the multi-nominated group Silla & Rise. Beatrice Deer plays a song from 1997 on the show. The program will be sharing some new tracks with you in the coming weeks.',NULL,NULL),(64433,161,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/9sm46u/VientoSur-September-30th-2023.mp3','2023-09-29 01:18:47',72702539,'2023-12-04 20:47:06',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64442,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/The Crooked Beat - September 28, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 20:24:20',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64443,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/The Crooked Beat - September 28, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 20:07:34',NULL,'Welcome to the Crooked Beat. This is a two-hour set of new music. We\'ll start off with an Austrian band called In A Dub-Fashion, followed by a dub version of the music. Then we\'ll hear a new version of Bob-Marley\'s Talking-Blues. And then there\'s a song called Rocking- Blues, which is a new take on Bob Marley. And finally there\'ll be a rock version of Talking- Blues',NULL,NULL),(64453,121,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Sundowner - September 28, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 19:08:46',NULL,'On this edition of Sundowner, Matt tells us all about the upcoming music festival, Keep Hope Alive, which will take place in Guelph, Ontario, Canada. The festival will feature performances by The Body and The Big Brave, Swim Good Now , Raphael Wainright , Joni Narita , Brown Brown , and many more acts.\n\nTickets are still on sale for $25, or for a festival pass for $125. If you\'re looking for a great time, check out this list of the most popular songs from the past year on the show. The first song is called O\'sinner off leaving none but small birds from the Body\'s 2021 release. The second song is Dying on the vine from John Cales 1985 release Artificial Intelligence. The third song is Modern Fiction from the Ducks Limited label. The fourth song is Are you sure off of a record called Life is not a lesson from the Avlov label.\n\nAnd the fifth song is Stick from the 2018 release. This is the last song on the list. The program will be celebrating its one year anniversary with some songs from its archives. These songs include Margot Shake from California Gurion, Vivi Live from Whitney Kaye, White Horse from Montreal, and Blind from the swans 1991 release.',NULL,NULL),(64454,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Forever Deaf - September 28, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 18:47:43',NULL,'This week on the show, Dean and Byron talk about the upcoming Kidney Walk and the work of the Die Out Community Workshop. They also talk about how they can use their tools and equipment to help people start their projects. Dean plays a little bit of music from the escape from the fire release he played earlier. He\'s sad to say that Razor has pulled out of their remaining shows in 2023 because of a heart condition. He was hoping to find a band to play in his place while Bob was away, but he has a broken hand and will be out for six weeks.',NULL,NULL),(64464,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Forever Deaf - September 29, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 05:20:43',NULL,'Alice welcomes her listeners back to the show. She\'s played some of her favorite tracks from the past few years. She tells us that she first got sick a few years ago, and that she got a call from Robert Urbanati of Sacrifice. She had a great time talking to him.',NULL,NULL),(64465,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/28/Forever Deaf - September 28, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-28 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 15:08:06',NULL,'On this edition of the program, the young artists from the hip-hop collective known as the \"World Youth\" discuss a number of subjects, including impaired boating, the release of a new line of CFRU merchandise, and the latest news from his doctor. First, the group discusses Brain Scans, which are scans of the brain performed every two weeks. Brain Scan is a medical procedure that measures the extent of a tumor and its size.\n\nIt reveals that the tumor is spread throughout the brain, including the brain stem, and that it has tentacles that protrude outward. The tumor has three tiny lesions on its wall, which is why it is inoperable. The doctors hope that a new drug will help them. The next segment of the show is devoted to Hyperia, a type of extreme pain. The music is a combination of text, sword, and anvil from the cycle of the serpent.',NULL,NULL),(64475,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Forever Deaf - September 29, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 14:48:13',NULL,'The program starts with a song called \"Drowning in Silver\" by a band called \"Death Valley Driver\" from Charlottetown, PEI. The first song on the album is called \"Stone Cold\" and the second song is \"Death valley driver\" from \"Deeperable\". The third song is a mini-song called \"Reanimation\". The fourth song is called, \"Goliath\" from the song \"Armageddon\".\n\nThe program ends with a soliloquy by Mac-Catee. He says that he\'s feeling fine and asks listeners to listen to his show next Tuesday at 5:00PM. He also tells listeners that meta-products like Facebook and Google are blocking news from viewers because of Bill C-18. He explains that the university is a campus, community organization and so it shares news and upcoming events as well as learning opportunities. The university is proud to be a voice for its community and unfortunately due to the bill\'s response, Canadians can no longer access its social media posts.\n\nIf you want to continue to support the university, please sign up to receive the university\'s newsletter at slash newsletter. The Guelph MP for Guelph, Lloyd Longfield, is also in the program. Mac Catee says that this week is \"So Can Night\", Society of artists and composers and publishers of music of Canada. He plays some Canadian bands that are going to be paid for their work. He just finished playing with \"Withering Scorn\" from Prophets of',NULL,NULL),(64490,173,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/7irb89/Club_Ned_Oct_1_2023_Podcast86w3n.mp3','2023-09-29 11:19:31',431485386,'2023-12-05 05:22:35',NULL,'The station also announces that Anthony Rota has resigned as a speaker after honoring a Ukrainian veteran who served with the Germans in World War II.',NULL,NULL),(64500,175,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ewqux6/September_28th_2023_No_Man_s_Landat0su.mp3','2023-09-29 13:51:57',287962512,'2023-10-31 02:09:29',NULL,'The second annual Study & Go Abroad Fair will take place at the University of the West Indies on October 1st. The fair will give prospective students the opportunity to find out about all the different ways to get involved with colleges and universities abroad. There will also be a showcase of scholarships, volunteer opportunities, and work-abroad opportunities.',NULL,'Study & Go Abroad Fair takes place at the University of the West Indies'),(64506,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - September 29, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 14:12:11',NULL,'The International Olympic Committee has decided to allow Muslim women to wear headscarves at the Paris Summer Games next year. The French Ministry of Sport has said that the ban on women wearing veils is in line with France\'s strict secularism. The IOC says it will allow delegations from all over the world to participate in the Paris Games, as long as they adhere to the same rules as those in France.\n\nChina is expected to send tens of millions of people away for the week- long National Day holiday. The International Herald Tribune reports that Spanish archaeologists have discovered ancient sandals in a cave. A new report from the United Nations Children\'s Fund says that nearly one-third of unaccompanied children who have tried to cross the Mediterranean to Europe have died in the journey.',NULL,NULL),(64516,123,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Thanks for Listening :) - September 29, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 13:45:48',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64517,124,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Planet Groove - September 29, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 13:29:11',NULL,'The show opens with a little bit of a rundown of the music on the program, which is called \"Planet Groove\" with the \"Funky Blues Doctor\" .\n\nThe show starts off by playing some of the most popular music of all time, like \"Cocaine Blues\" , \"Too Cold to Cry\" and \"I Want to Be your Dog.\" The doctor then goes on to say that he\'s going to perform some more of the Stooges\' stuff, including \"Masters of Punk\" and the \"Shaker Down\" : \"That was Gia Wasted potential. And that was Jamie Standstill\'s Shaker Down.\" The Doctor then gets down to the business of the show, and says that he has a band called \"Great, awesome four-piece band\" that\'s playing some \"live taste, some \"black country communion\" and some \"UFO.\n\n\" The show ends with a discussion of Silence, a new music venue in town, which can be rented out for a fee. If you\'re in the market for a rehearsal space, or a jam space, then you\'ve come to the right place. Sounds is offering a special flat rate rent for $100 per day. Sounds also has a lot of great music on its roster, so you can always count on them to be there when you need them.',NULL,NULL),(64527,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Democracy Now - September 29, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 13:07:35',NULL,'Meanwhile, the United States is preparing for a government shutdown Saturday night. The Washington Post reports that a group of right-wing Republicans are planning to remove as Speaker of the House the conservative House speaker, John McCarthy. Meanwhile, Vice President Joe Biden warns that the Trump administration\'s embrace of the MAGA and white nationalist movements threatens the democratic process in America. A climate activist interrupts Vice President Biden\'s address in Arizona and asks why the President has not declared a climate emergency to address the growing threat of climate change.',NULL,NULL),(64528,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Volunteer Playlist - September 29, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 12:44:27',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(64538,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Viejoteca - September 29, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-09-29 20:07:17',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64539,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Viejoteca - September 29, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-09-29 20:07:18',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64549,127,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/LiYghTE FM - September 29, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 12:32:15',NULL,'This is the very first episode of what will be a series of interviews with the host of CFRU\'s 93.3 Liyghte FM, DJ DD. The show begins with a monologue in which the host admits that he is disappointed with the character of the man, who works in a grocery store and has no views on the music of any artist. The host explains that he has heard that the man is trying to \"change the entire universe\" through a \"love revolution.\n\n\" The host goes on to say that he himself is roasting chestnuts and that his station is the \"number one radio program\" in the world when it comes to the roasting of chestnuts. He also says that the number of people who are musicians is a great thing, as it enables people to contribute to the creation of music. He explains that the only reason he is angry or upset about people in music is because they are making money. The only real reason to be angry is because there are too many people making music. The lame commercial reason, he says, is a \"horrid reason\" to make music',NULL,NULL),(64550,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Hellfire Radio - September 29, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 12:13:02',NULL,'This is the second in a three-part series on the value of music. First, we hear about the cool stuff on this page, which includes a cool screen printing, a cool cassette liner notebook, and a CD that says \"Here burn a CD... at the famine\'s C a slash K R U / G E R.\" The CD is called \"Famines,\" and the liner notebook is \"Nardware The Human serviette / Monumental.\" This is a very different scene from the one on the first part of the show. The liner notebook was written by a guy named Nardware, who played punk music in the West Coast.\n\nThe CD and liner notebook are from a similar scene. The first song we hear is \"Elevator To Hell,\" a song about an elevator. This is kind of the first song that we hear that sounds like elevator to hell . The second song is \"The Who and Double Pleading,\" which is about the two guys who go to the bottom of the stairs. The third song is called Elevator To Hell, the Who and the Double pleading. The seventh song is a cool one called \"X Trip,\" which was the first project of Julie Doron, who used to work for Doron Music. The eighth song was \"Eric\'s Trip,\" a band called Rick White.',NULL,NULL),(64560,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Walkuman Style - September 29, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 11:10:34',NULL,'This program is called Clan of Gael and it\'s hosted by John Fahey. It\'s about two hours of music from all over the world and the surrounding area. You can tune in on Sundays at noon to hear all the best music from the world. John also tells us that if you\'re a local business or an organization that would like to advertise on the station, CFRU has the resources to help you. If you\'d like to learn more about how to promote your event or organization on CFRU, please contact us.',NULL,NULL),(64561,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Folk Roots Radio - September 29, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 10:49:08',NULL,'In this edition of Folk Roots, host Jan Hall introduces a new batch of Canadian artists, including singer-songwriters A. V., Anne Vrent, and The Inner City, an all-female vocal backing group from London. The Pairs from London, singer- songwriter Jill Barber from Vancouver, veteran folk trio Gendikorum from Quebec, and acclaimed songwriter and R&B singer-guitarist Avi Gervine from the Bahamas. We also hear from Winnipeg\'s Moonfruits, Boy Golden from his latest release, The 4Jimmy EP, and Cameron Nickerson from his sophomore release.',NULL,NULL),(64571,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Digital Statik - September 29, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 10:25:56',NULL,'On this episode, the guys discuss the weather and the latest music. The guys say they\'re getting ready to go, but before they get started, the guy says he\'s in the bank. He tells the listeners that he told his wife to get a hold of a gun. He\'s living fast, he says. He says he told her she\'s locked into a life of crime. The weather man says it\'s super cold outside, but he\'d rather be outside in the sun. He wants to go on a summer vacation. The guy says they just got a track from Primal Wind out of Edmonton, but the track is called \"Law Bent\" .',NULL,NULL),(64572,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/09/29/Volunteer Playlist - September 29, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-09-29 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 10:06:44',NULL,'The UM team wants to know what people are up to when it comes to the COVID pandemic. They\'re looking for people who are between the ages of 5 and 65. They want to know how they\'re disrupting the world in ways that make the world less safe. You can find out more about the UM team by visiting their website or by following them on Twitter.