 Dylan, the Grateful Dead, and many more. The program ends with a discussion of the most recent Wes Anderson movie, The Grand Budapest Hotel. Reed is a huge fan of Anderson\'s work, and he finds the movie self-indulgent and not very original.\n\nHe also falls in love with a song by Johnny Duncan, \"Last Train To San Fernando.\" The song sounds like a British band, but it turns out to be an old Calypso tune. Reed also hears Bill Monroe\'s band, the Bluegrass Boys. The group also plays an old song, \"An Old, Old Song,\" which Reed thinks was done by Elizabeth Cotton. The show ends with some other music from the Underground, including Bob Dylan\'s \"It Takes A Lot to Laugh\" and the \"Grateful Dead\'s\" version of \"Casey Jones\" from \"Workingman\'s Dead.\" Reed thinks that this song is the culmination of the Underground\'s early Jug Band roots.',NULL,NULL),(65395,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/07/Tiempo de Mujeres - October 7, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-07 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-08 02:07:15',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(65396,14544,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/07/National Day for Truth and Reconciliation - October 7, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-07 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-08 02:07:56',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(65406,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/07/Mach Vibe Radio - October 7, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-07 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-01 16:46:16',NULL,'This is the first half of the second edition of \"Mach Vibe,\" the music program hosted by the UM\'s friend and fellow DJ, Morty. The first half consists of a variety of different songs, each with a different theme. The second half of this program consists of \"a little tado,\" or pre-workout, music. This program is dedicated to the upcoming fight between Charlo and Canelo Alvarez, scheduled for tonight. The UM plays a song called \"Falling Up featuring Pharrell,\" which he apologizes to his listeners for not airing earlier.',NULL,NULL),(65407,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/07/Mach Vibe Radio - October 7, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-07 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 16:29:36',NULL,'Ritesh Das is a new member of the Toronto-based Tavla Ensemble and he is the voice of his new project, To Begin with, which is available on all the major streaming services. The group will perform live on November 4 at the Al-Green Theatre in Toronto and tickets are on sale now.\n\nThe song opens with a shout-out to all the members of the group, who are all in their mid-20s and up. They include Miles Costello, Solomon, Kim Davis, Ole, Frisco, Danny Fernandez, J.2 Meeks, Rohan, and the Mock Vibe Radios. The Mock Vibes are a collective of people who are constantly mocking and mocking one another. They are the only people in the world who are willing to do this kind of thing.',NULL,NULL),(65417,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/The Underground - October 8, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 15:43:47',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(65418,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/07/The Underground - October 7, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-07 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 15:09:51',NULL,'This program is produced by the Heffner studio, located in the library\'s Central branch. The National Board of Film and Television is pleased to be a part of this program. They have over 250 films produced by First Nations, Métis and Inuit peoples around the world. They invite you to visit their website to learn more about the films. The program also discusses Die Out, a volunteer-run makerspace. It is a community workshop that teaches people how to use tools and equipment. They also have a new line of clothing and accessories.',NULL,NULL),(65455,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Visions fugitives - October 8, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 14:53:02',NULL,'Fangwei and Christopher Curry co-host a music show called \"Visions  Fugitives\", which is meant to be a classical music program. Each week, one person chooses a set of music based on a theme, and the other person responds to the piece that he or she heard that week. The show is scheduled to run on October 8th of 2023, which happens to be Thanksgiving weekend in Canada. Fangwei sent the composer a list of music tracks and script for the music, and last week he sent him a list and script.\n\nThe music is based on animals that undergo what is known as \"acedivation,\" which is a form of hibernation. The two animals featured in the music are the salamander and the tortoise, both of whom undergo this process. The title of the music is \"Achilles and the Tortoise,\" which refers to the \"Paradox of Zeno,\" in which Achilles believes that the tortoise can never overtake him if the tortoise is given a head-start in a race because Achilles always has a lead.',NULL,NULL),(65465,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/32n4zv/October_8_2023_Across_the_Universe6vpuz.mp3','2023-10-09 00:03:51',431961989,'2023-10-31 03:42:26',NULL,'The program begins with a song by Baba Maul, titled \"Across the Universe\". The song is dedicated to Elizabeth Montgomery, the matriarch of the Montgomery family. She died on Friday evening at the age of 93. Elizabeth had lived alone for the last 50 years, but she managed to get by by on her own for 40 years. She had seven distinct bouts of breast cancer, but none of them was caught in time, and the eighth was caught this past Friday evening. Elizabeth was very stubborn, and her entire family is going to miss and miss her dearly',NULL,'Baba Maul\'s \"Across the Universe\" song is dedicated to Elizabeth Montgomery, the matriarch of the family'),(65466,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ztsxmm/Karibuni_Oct_8-239vsik.mp3','2023-10-09 00:24:42',287962512,'2023-12-01 14:30:05',NULL,'The first act of the show is called \"Ubuntu,\" and it\'s the first time we\'ve heard about it. It\'s an all-star line-up of artists, including Berita, an artist from the Eswatini kingdom of Swaziland, and a band from Zimbabwe.',NULL,NULL),(65467,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/mwc756/9_30_23_showap4iu.mp3','2023-10-08 21:11:52',80801820,'2023-12-01 14:07:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(65468,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Seems Like Old Times - October 8, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 13:57:03',NULL,'The whole gang is ready to take Cathy home. Just when we think it\'s safe to leave her in the back of the car, she suddenly notices the gas gauge on the dashboard. It\'s clearly not a gas gauge, but rather a liquid gas. This is the kind of thing that\'s called \"gas\" but is really \"stove gas\" . So you see, it doesn\'t really matter what the gas is called, it\'ll always be gas. Anyway, she\'s so glad to see her dad back in the car that she can\'t wait to get home.\n\nSo we find out what\'s wrong with the car. We find out that the car\'s ignition has gone off, and that the horn won t work. We also learn that the speedometer is broken, and the kid\'s not paying any attention to her dad. She\'s just laughing at him. He\'s going to get a speeding ticket. This whole time, he\'s been talking about how fast he was going when he was speeding. The kid has no idea what he is talking about. So she asks her dad if he was joking about her being pregnant.\n\nHe says that he was happy when her baby was born, but that he\'d been speeding so fast that he almost ran into someone else\'s car and knocked them down. He also says that when he blew his horn three times, the kid had no idea he was blowing',NULL,NULL),(65469,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Seems Like Old Times - October 8, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-01 13:32:10',NULL,'The program opens with a song from the musical The Ritz Rollin\' Rock, written by the great Cole Porter. The song is from a 1930 recording by Ted Lewis and the orchestra. The program also discusses the upcoming Lions Club Healthy Aging Show, which will take place on Tuesday.\n\nThe show is free and open to the public. The Legion branch 275 hosts a Mixed Cribbage Tournament on Saturday. The entry fee is $20 per person and the entry deadline is 1pm sharp. The tournament is open to everyone. The host introduces a new artist, Bria Skorbur, who sings on her CD Bria. She also performs the trumpet on her music. She is a relatively new artist on the music scene, and she is known as \"Bria Skonber.\" The program ends with a program celebrating Thanksgiving. It is a variety show called \"Lady Day herself\" and \"Billie Holiday\" and it is at 2pm on CFRU 95.3.',NULL,NULL),(65470,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Wind-Down - October 8, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 13:13:35',NULL,'Ritesh Das is the vocalist for the Toronto Thavlar Ensemble, which is nominated for a Juno award for its music. He has released his latest album, Volcano, which he will perform live on November 4 at the Al Green Theatre.\n\nThe show begins with the new music from Jungle, which has been going around the web, like YouTube, and people have been commenting on it. The music is very energetic and danceable, and Ritesh suggests anyone who has seen the music on the web to check it out. Next, the show is about to wind down, and the program offers music to drift into. The program starts with the latest music from Night Tapes, which comes from their Perfect Perfect album. The song is called Inigo, and it comes from the Toronto artists New Chance from Real Time, Bambi Earth Kindness House turning, and Luna Lee, who has released her 2022 album, Duality.\n\nNext up, the program features the music from Uma Jai, which came out a month ago. It is the music for the movie Where The Wild Things Are, which was co-produced by Karen Oh and her kids. If you havent heard the movie or havent listened to it, go and listen to the music. The band also plays a song called Bug Like An Angel from Mitski\'s latest album.',NULL,NULL),(65471,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Visions fugitives - October 8, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 12:50:31',NULL,'The heat wave has passed, and the air is cooler and more pleasant than it was during the summer. The narrator decides to shift the focus of the show to the seasons that fall. He\'s looking at the fall as a time when animals don\'t move and animals that look majestic or \" regal\" are often featured. One of the animals that he\'s going to look at is the wolf, which is one of those animals that doesn\'t really go into hibernation.\n\nSounds like a good idea. The composer of this work is Alice Ping Yi-ho, who\'s written a work called \"woman runs with wolves\" . The show will play this work, as well as a number of other works that have the same number of parts as an opus. This is because we\'re all supposed to be in the spring, and we\'ve been since the beginning of time. The work is called \"Opus 34\" and it\'s composed by two contemporary classical guitarists. The duo is named \"Denando Karuli\" and \"Fernando sore\" , which means \"friend\" or \"brother\" in Latin.',NULL,NULL),(65472,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Clan Na Gael - October 8, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 12:32:49',NULL,'This program is all about organ donation. The organ recipient is Mike Willis, who is a very grateful recipient. The program starts off with a look at some of the things that are on the program. First up is a song by a family from Cape Breton called the Cotters. Next up is an Irish song called \"Bottom Macneil\" by David Agnew. Then there\'s a whistle from David, an instrumental from Lanygan Wall. And then there\'sa song by Charlotte Church called \"The Welsh Angel\" and another one by Roger Whittaker called \"Mexican Whistler\" . The rest of the program is about music.',NULL,NULL),(65473,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Clan Na Gael - October 8, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 12:14:34',NULL,'The host of the program introduces himself and tells his listeners that he will be playing some Spanish music on Thanksgiving. He says that he has family over for the day and will be going to the States the next day to attend a family wedding. The host then tells them about some of the artists who played on the first set. The first song is from Linda Ronstad, who is Mexican.\n\nShe was born in the U.S. in Arizona and her father was from Mexico. She played violin and played the drums. She also loves the bagpipes. She says that there is a lot of Celtic music in northern Spain. She tells listeners that Christopher Columbus was in the area and that he probably came there because he wanted to see a church there.',NULL,NULL),(65474,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - October 8, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-08 15:20:18',NULL,'This episode of the Bananas\' Variety Hour is all about happiness. The theme for the day is \"happy.\" It\'s cold, wet and cloudy, but it\'s sunny. So they\'ll have lots of music from different decades and different times. They\'ll also have a segment with some of their friends. The narrator asks the kids what they think a song that sounds happy is like. They agree, but they\'re not sure if they agree with the song. Feeling happy is a different way to say you\'re in a good mood. The song they choose is called \"On the Sunny Side Of The Street.\" The narrator thinks that his grandpa would sing this song to him when he was walking with his grandparents. He also thinks that he learned it from his grandparents, which means he\'d known it since he was a kid. So the song is \"On The Sunny Side of The Street,\" and the narrator thinks it was also an old song. He thinks that Harry Richmond sang this song too, but he was only 13 at the time. So he\'s just like Stevie Wonder. The kids talk about what\'s on their minds right now. They talk about Christmas, and they say that every','Kookoo Bananas: Variety Hour is about happiness. Today we\'re going to have lots of music from lots of different decades, different times. We even have an interview segment coming up with some of your friends. Do you want to hear a song that\'s 89 years old? Whoa. That was Stevie Wonder.','Kookoo Bananas: Variety Hour (Sponsor)'),(65475,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Zombie Jamboree - October 8, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-01 11:48:48',NULL,'The first two songs are from the Zombie Jamboree. The second is a cover of Carl Deidor\'s song \"Please Don\'t cry if you are late to the party\" and the third is from Lack of Afro\'s \"Wide Open.\" The first song is from Fran Lobo and the second is from Mr. Afro. The third song is an introduction from the Ring.\n\nThe Ring is from his latest release, Square One. The set starts with Fran Lobo. The band is planning a Thanksgiving party and dance. The music is coming from all over the world. The song is \"All I want. This is a Zombie Jamboree Thanksgiving Dinner and Dance. You make it, we\'ll have the music. The sound of the band\'s voice is heard. The group consists of Solania, Maguela, and Danela. Solania is from Mexico and Maguela is from Spain. They are all from different parts of the world and they all have different names. They all have the same name, but they all sound the same. They\'re going to play a song called \"Zombie Jamboree\" for the Thanksgiving party.',NULL,NULL),(65476,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/La Buena Onda - October 8, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-08 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-09 12:07:52',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(65477,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/08/Zombie Jamboree - October 8, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2