2,'2023-11-29 11:48:52',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66010,1551,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/x8ff88/OCTOBER12.mp3','2023-10-14 05:12:04',431961989,'2023-11-29 11:27:38',NULL,'The right direction is back. It\'s time for a special guest DJ set from Ductail, who is always putting out some of the best new music in town. This week\'s guest set is a dance track from LPGOB, a major label that put out some major hits in the late 2000s and early \'00s. Next up is a track from Marcus Wilkinson, who put out a lot of great music in the early 2000s. Then it\'s Onglud music from a visionary named Marcus Wilkinson. The next track is from a scuba artist named Dactyl, who\'s been doing some really awesome stuff in the last couple of years.',NULL,NULL),(66011,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/13/Industry Tactics - October 13, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-13 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 11:13:05',NULL,'In this short speech, Lauren Stein, a long-time resident of Guelph, Israel, gives a rallying cry for her fellow citizens in Canada. She urges them to make today a day of love and unity. She tells them to reach out to people they haven\'t seen in a while, to talk to people who they don\'t usually agree with, and to visit their Jewish friends. She encourages them to show up at one of the local Jewish organizations and listen to what they have to say.',NULL,NULL),(66012,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Jitterbuggin - October 14, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 10:52:07',NULL,'Welcome to the Jitterbagin\' show, a music show hosted by Adrian Jay. The show starts at midnight, and the DJ says he\'s set his time as midnight.\n\nHe says he sets his time according to the time he gets up. He tells us he\'ll be playing some songs that he has been promoting, like \"Daddy Long Legs\" and \"Savage Kicks Vol 2.\" He\'s also going to be playing a bunch of music that he doesn\'t know what to play. He wants to play music more than talk. He gives us a triple header: \"Let It Rock,\" \"Barrett Strong,\" and \"Money and Blues Brother.\" He also tells us that it\'s a 106-mile trip to Chicago to play the music.\n\nSo, don\'t worry about moving your dial, because it\'ll just scold you. The DJ also tells listeners that he and Adrian have been back in town for a while, so they\'re back on the air. The first mistake he made was playing \"College Girl,\" which he thinks is a new CD he burned onto the DJ\'s old car. He also says that he didn\'t have a good time playing college girl, though.',NULL,NULL),(66059,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/A Dog’s Breakfast - October 14, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 10:31:13',NULL,'The host of the \"Cyber-licious Gothic Castle\" on CFRU, the station\'s music program, welcomes listeners to the show and asks them to \"sleep into the cyberlicious gothic castle\" every Tuesday at midnight. He also tells them that they can \"experience the darker side\" of synth, \"outrun\" and \"ambient, dungeon, and cyberpunk\" while listening to the program. The guests include DJ Apostrophe, the founder of the International Institute of Critical Studies and Improvisers, and Diamond Schmidt, the director of the new ImprovLab building at the university.',NULL,NULL),(66060,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Beautiful Druid - October 14, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 10:08:47',NULL,'The show opens with a welcome from Alden Hadwen, the host of Beautiful Druid. He tells us that the show is being aired live from the university in Guelph, Canada.\n\nHe says he\'s glad to be a part of it. He introduces himself as Alden and says he will be the host for the show. He\'ll be playing songs that relate to houses and how people feel about them. For example, the first song he\'ll play is called \"The House Song\" by Peter Paul and Mary. The song goes something like this: \"Peter, Paul, and Mary\" refers to houses, and the second song he plays is called The Spirit of The West.\n\nThe first song is \"One Less Set of Feet,\" by Jim Croce. The second song is Willie Nelson\'s \"Essential Willie Nelson Album\" . The third song is by Alison Croce and \"Union Station\" referring to a ghost in a house. The fourth song is from Eric Bibb\'s short piece \"Church\" , which is a little slice of country music. The show ends with a song by Joshua Redmond.',NULL,NULL),(66070,257,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fynfsc/October_12_2023_Psychedelic_Stoner_Rockaou6l.mp3','2023-10-14 16:56:08',287962512,'2023-11-29 09:45:08',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66071,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zcg5d9/October_13_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow8cauv.mp3','2023-10-14 16:57:16',287962512,'2023-11-29 09:27:07',NULL,'Ken Stauer joins Lydia to talk about the latest developments in sound recording. He explains that they are using a tape machine to record samples of music. There is no sound on the end of the machine, so there is no system noise, and there are no hiss, in case of a certain. They can make the music clear as possible, and that\'s why they only need two tracks to record the music. He says that the feeling that is everywhere, is actually the possible arrival of time. He then explains how they can use the technology to re-create the present tense and what it would mean to create a new beginning in the future',NULL,NULL),(66072,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Sound Magic - October 14, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 09:08:54',NULL,'The program opens with a description of Sound Magic, a three-hour program of classical music. The program is comprised of three main sections: 1) Classic Art Music, 2) Orchestral Music, and 3) Other Music.\n\nThe first section is devoted to classical music, and the second section consists of other music. Sound Magic kicks off with a piano concerto from Anton Rubinstein, one of the most important Russian composers of the nineteenth century. Rubinstein wrote symphonies and was the critic of Tchaikovskys piano concerto, which he completely trashes. He also wrote a few other piano concertos, including a work for the Scottish Symphony Orchestra. The second section has a recording of Marc-Andréi Hamelin playing the piano.\n\nThe third section introduces the entire Russian pianists, along with the other piano works. The fourth section introduces us to all the other musical developments that took place in the Russian territories during the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.',NULL,NULL),(66082,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Sound Magic - October 14, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 08:49:16',NULL,'The final piece of the program is a Russian composer named Nikolai Kapuskin. He was born in1937 and died as recently in 2020 . He had an eye-opener in his life because of his jazz sensibility. He did a lot of chamber music, mostly with a piano.\n\nThe piano is the instrument of the composer, so he had a very individual style. He is known for his chamber symphony Op 57 from 19. The conductor is Alek Skarnna, who is also the conductor of the chamber symphony from earlier in the program. The program ends with a volunteer at the university, a singer-songwriter named Lauren, who volunteers to play on the university\'s experimental music station.',NULL,NULL),(66083,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Sound Magic - October 14, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 08:27:05',NULL,'In this episode of Sound Magic, Michael Doleszell discusses the latest recording of the famous Russian Second Symphony by the Philadelphia Orchestra, conducted by Yannick Neshikenou. The symphony was composed in the early 1900s and has been played many times, but the recording is the most complete and complete recording to date. The Philadelphia Orchestra\'s music director, Janek Janek, has recorded the entire symphony, which is about an hour long and full of repetition. It is a masterpiece, and Doleschell raves about it all day.',NULL,NULL),(66093,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Bel Araby with CAWA - October 14, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 08:08:42',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66094,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Caribbean Anthology - October 14, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 07:06:13',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66104,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Caribbean Anthology - October 14, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 06:51:16',NULL,'In this interview with Darnay, Darnay speaks of the importance of unity in the music industry. He explains that he, like many other artists, has had personal issues with people in the past. He encourages listeners to let bygones be bygones and move on with their lives. Darnay admits that he too has personal issues, but that he tries to make sure he can still be a good influence on other artists and people in his community. He believes that the music business is a difficult industry to break away from, but it must be done.',NULL,NULL),(66105,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Alternativa Latinoamericana - October 14, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-15 00:07:13',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66115,142,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Tiempo de Mujeres - October 14, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-15 02:07:04',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66116,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Alternativa Latinoamericana - October 14, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-15 02:07:05',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66126,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Mach Vibe Radio - October 14, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 06:26:37',NULL,'The first half of the show is over and the guys are back on the second half. Solomon introduces himself as CanadianYardy, and the other listeners as Homeboy, Jordan, Rich, Frisco, and Winbae U. They\'re all psyched to have their voices heard. The guys are psyched to be back on 93.3 and they\'re psyched to get back to doing music again.\n\nThey all have their own stations on the air so they can all hang out and chill together. This is the first time they\'ve all listened to music together. The music starts off slow and then gets really loud. It\'s like a live music jam. Solomon apologizes to his listeners for getting too loud. He says he\'s going to get some bass music and he apologizes for not having a good mic. Next time he\'ll get a good one.',NULL,NULL),(66127,143,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/Mach Vibe Radio - October 14, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 06:09:48',NULL,'This short, rhyming song is a mock-interview with a group of students who have graduated from college. The students are eager to advance their education and careers. They are motivated by their desire to be independent and to make a difference in the world. The song is part of the mock-education curriculum offered by the mockvib radio company. The narrator describes the students as having no other options but to conform to the social conventions of their class. He explains that he is the girl of their dreams.',NULL,NULL),(66137,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/The Underground - October 15, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 05:04:14',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66138,144,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/14/The Underground - October 14, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-14 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 04:45:17',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66220,296,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/db3dwj/show_oct_7fl7xqa2.mp3','2023-10-15 22:30:48',85315779,'2023-11-29 04:28:07',NULL,'This is the third and final track in the series. It\'s a little different than the previous two, but it\'s still the same program. This time, we\'re talking about the snake, who is sharpening knives and sharpening tire irons. We\'re going to skip over to the next track, which is about the critic circle. This one\'s more of a focus, but we\'ll get back to that soon. Next up, we have two more pop-up tracks to hold you through until the Kingslayer\'s Day.',NULL,NULL),(66230,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/7pc42n/October_15_2923_Across_the_Universe88jfg.mp3','2023-10-16 00:05:36',431961989,'2023-11-29 04:08:01',NULL,'The show opens with a track called Across the Universe Heard by Steam Hammer, a band that was formed in 1968 and released their first single, Reflections, in 1968. They reformed and released a new song, Wailing Again, which is 53 years old or more. The music then moves to Marvin Gaye\'s \"Here, My Dear\" and \"Reincarnation\" by Nona Hendrix, Soulclap, Fontella, the \"Crooked Dub\" remix by Athletes of God, and the \"I\'m Free\" by the Rolling Stones. The band will be playing in Toronto on Tuesday.',NULL,'Ken Stauer and his guests discuss Solas, a local band, and their upcoming concert'),(66258,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/4zizgw/Karibuni_Oct15-238iz69.mp3','2023-10-16 02:25:43',287962512,'2023-11-29 03:11:28',NULL,'The host of the African Music show, Nadine McNulty, says that the community radio station, Ciut FM, is still in need of financial support to reach its goal of $100K. In this program, she and her co-host, Chirno Soumare, discuss the music that they will play for the listeners on Sunday.\n\nThe first set will be a showcase featuring an artist named Nia Nangango who is originally from Rwanda. The second set will feature a singer named Punle who is a folk singer from Brampton. The third set will include songs by Mary Annabelle, who is from Zimbabwe. The fourth set will also include songs from other artists. After the first set, the program will go to Gona, a town in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, to listen to some music.',NULL,NULL),(66296,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/kctux4/CC_Oct_146t8e0.mp3','2023-10-16 14:19:29',143961989,'2023-11-29 02:54:37',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66298,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fpam7n/CC_oct_7ao37i.mp3','2023-10-16 14:18:59',143961989,'2023-11-29 02:29:23',NULL,'Phil Taylor, host of the Classical Underground, talks with Lynn Slotkin and Daniel Garber about the latest movie news. They also discuss the Blue Jays. Phil starts the show by asking Philip Conlon what happened to the team. Philip explains that the team got picked off by the New York Yankees and traded to the Los Angeles Dodgers. The guys who ran the team decided to go back to the \"good old days\" of around 2000, when the team was the White Jays. They dismantled the \"heart and soul\" of the team and traded for the Dodgers.',NULL,NULL),(66300,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/74578d/CC_Sep_30th6aw2u.mp3','2023-10-16 14:18:34',143961989,'2023-11-29 02:08:50',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66307,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/jb96xi/October_14th_2023_The_Minx_Sessions6p2sh.mp3','2023-10-16 15:13:07',287962512,'2023-11-29 01:10:29',NULL,'The show opens with a mix of releases by independent artists. The first track is from IUT\'s Edin on Five straight into embers, followed by Frank\'s compilation. The second track is a mix from the show\'s third artist, Azu Tiweshan. The third track is an excerpt from the song \"Salmon Universe\" by Salmon Universe. The show ends with the release of \"Dangerk,\" a new song by Gezotek to Bankham, Wanham.com , Warhol Walker, and Anton Violet',NULL,NULL),(66308,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dwkvu4/October_14th_2023_Calling_All_Bluesae1pm.mp3','2023-10-16 15:15:43',143961989,'2023-11-29 00:49:02',NULL,'The show opens with a look at the diverse roster of performers who have been nominated for Juno Awards. The first artist is a blues musician named Derek Miller, who has won two Juno awards. Next up is a band called Indigenous, which is made up of Matto and Petey Nanji on guitar and brother Petey on drums.\n\nThe band\'s song is called \"Blues Doctor Julie.\" Next is a woman-led set, with Delanna as the lead singer, followed by Shani Kish as the featured artist. Then there\'s a song by a Juno-nominated artist named Crystal Schawanda. The song is about selling coffee, and it\'s about the fact that she\'s seen the world through the eyes of a loon.',NULL,NULL),(66345,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/kxa67x/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Oct_18_2023_podcastblshj.mp3','2023-10-16 18:29:44',280695117,'2023-11-28 23:06:49',NULL,'The narrator tells the listeners that the military has changed its business model in order to make more money. Instead of selling weapons as they originally planned, the munitions industry has come up with the idea of using other people to fight the wars and then selling the munitions to the countries that need them most. This is a solution to the problem of body bags, since American soldiers are returning home with body bags. But now, instead of killing American soldiers, they just sell the body bags to other countries who then use them to fight. The narrator warns listeners that if Donald Trump wins the election, the world will be even more concerned about the deaths of American soldiers.',NULL,NULL),(66373,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 16, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 05:31:02',NULL,'The next day, the group discusses the business case for the ten-kart. First, the company explains that it\'s still paying the same discount on its bonds as it did when they were first issued. The reason for that is that the current interest rates are higher than they were when the bonds were issued. On the investor side of things, they\'re asking people to manage the interest climate, and they hope that in the future they\'ll get to a more normal interest rate. Finally, they ask Julia to deliver her announcements for the party. Julia says that she\'ll pay to deliver them if she wants to. She says that if there\'s anything she\'d like to know about the accessible parking, she\'s willing to pay if she just wants to know what Paul has to say about it. She adds that she would like to follow up on that. She also says that the party will be a great way for people to connect with each other. The group thanks Julia for her report. They also thank Jess from Tennessee who was there to make sure everything was going well. They mention that they\'ve got two council meetings on the same day. The first is about housing and the second is about demolition',NULL,'The Ten-Kart Party: What\'s Next for Paul and Paul? (13 minute read)'),(66374,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 16, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 05:16:33',NULL,'The gang at the 10 C\'s discuss how they\'re celebrating 15 years in business. They\'re also talking about the city\'s new land acknowledgement, which means that the city is acknowledging that the land that they call home is part of the territory belonging to the Credit First Nations. Julia Grady, co-founder of Tensee, is joining them. She\'s also excited to be here, because she\'s a member of the group and she\'ll be able to tell them all about Tensee. Tensee is a membership-based organization that\'s working to make the world a better place.',NULL,'The 10 C’s are celebrating 15 years in business – and they’re excited to join them '),(66375,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 17, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 22:46:08',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66376,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 16, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 22:26:55',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66377,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/CFRU Playlist - October 17, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 06:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-17 16:06:11',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66378,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/CFRU Playlist - October 16, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-10-17 16:06:12',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66379,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/The Deep House Project - October 16, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-31 05:21:11',NULL,'On this week\'s Deep House Project, we hear about the release of Lauren\'s debut, The Lost Art Of Through. The album is full of pop, folk, and jazz elements. We also learn that the International Institute of Critical Studies and Improvisation will be holding its fourth annual Festival of Improvised Arts on October 20 and 21 at the university. The show starts off with the classic track So Glad by Legendary Fingers Incorporated. The song is about a young woman who has fallen in love with someone else. She tells the girl that she\'s too proud to love her because she doesn\'t know all that she knows about love. She says she\'ll never be the first person to break her heart, but she will never be first to say it. She\'s not just saying she loves her, she loves the girl she loves. She won\'t let it go like this. She wants her Pin Springs to stop loving her. The Underground Man plays some remixes of some of Tim Walsh\'s tracks. He closes the show with an \"AI sounding trackopia\" from him.',NULL,'Lauren\'s debut album, The Lost Art Of Through, is a big hit for the world'),(66380,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Back in the USSR - October 16, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 22:06:08',NULL,'The next time you see a concert, you might think that it\'s some sort of art event. Well, that\'s not the case. Instead, the next time someone asks you to sing, think of it as a silent donation to a local charity.\n\nThat\'s what Silence is all about, right? So, instead of just singing, pledge to support the organization by giving $10 a month. You don\'t even have to be a member of the organization to support it. You can use the pledge form on their website to support them. They\'ve also got a nifty app that\'ll let you keep up with the latest news.',NULL,NULL),(66381,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Blues Around the Block - October 16, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 21:06:54',NULL,'Mac Dee\'s the host of the show and he welcomes his listeners to his show called \"Blues Around the Block\" on CFRU\'s 93.3 FM. Mac Dee tells his listeners that he\'s a baby-boomer who got out of a bank before he could get a bigger one. He says his wife treats him like a child and she won\'t be able to get rid of him anytime soon. He also tells listeners that if they tune in to the show, they can hear him in the city.',NULL,NULL),(66382,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Blues Around the Block - October 16, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 20:46:55',NULL,'Mac Dee, a student at the College of the Free University of Guelph, hosts a weekly music program called \"Blues Around the Block\" on CFRU. He is joined by an alligator recording artist named Taranzo Cannon. Mac Dee thanks all the listeners who have tuned in to the program and encourages them to continue listening. He also gives the listeners the option to stream the program or to send him an email with any comments about it',NULL,NULL),(66383,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Ripcord Radio - October 16, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 20:29:56',NULL,'The Improvist RadioFests team breaks up the show with a brief announcement about the show and its purpose. The program is to bring you the latest in underground music from around the world. The band playing tonight is Nice from Los Angeles. They have a song called One Two on their new album, Must be Nice. They are also playing a concert in Guelph the next day. The show will also include music from a number of other bands, including Dave Shredder and the Jawbreakers from San Francisco, Youth Youth Youth from Toronto, Negative Rage from Halifax, and the Government Issue from Washington DC.',NULL,NULL),(66384,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Big Sis Radio - October 16, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 20:10:36',NULL,'The narrator welcomes everyone back to his show, Big Sis. He also mentions that he\'s happy to be back at the university and he and his crew can air any of their shows on CFRU or on any of the other local stations.\n\nAlso, if you\'re a new student, he invites you to come on over and check out the U of G campus. This is going to be a big day for you. The first segment of the show is from Ombigaze and it\'s about an Anishinaabe artist named Buffy St.Marie. OmBigaze wanted to wish St. Marie well as she leaves live performance and honor her positive legacy. Before we get to that, though, we have to check out some other tracks from the summer, like Loading Quicksilver with Changing by Babe Rainbow and Eagle Man Woman by Buffy.\n\nThe Beaches just released their latest release on September 15 th . Blame My Ex is a big hit and the narrator finds it a great breakup song. But he thinks the real heart-to-heart between Bella and Alice in Twilight was the one between Alice and Edward. He thinks Bella is a fire sign and everyone needs a break.',NULL,NULL),(66385,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/to know the land - October 16, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 16:03:27',NULL,'On this episode of Know the Land: The Land, Byron speaks with his friend, artist, Miki Tamblyns about her recent project, called Animal Forms. The project is a mask making project that invites people to come to the forest to interact with the masks and have a sit spot. The masks represent different mammals living in the forest, and people are invited to record their impressions in journals and take photographs. The idea of seeing the world from another\'s point of view excites Byron, who is fascinated by the idea that humans can see the world as it is and see that their actions affect other people. He is inspired by Joanna Macy\'s work with the Council of Beings and also by the work of the artist. He was also interested in the idea of making masks to represent animals and then having people come together and share what is going on. He says that the world is alive, and that he wants to get into this because a lot of times he feels like he is like animus, which is a term that he has come to use in his life. He wants to know more about how people participate in this project, naming their own masks, and how they feel about the mirrors. He likes the mirrors because they allow people to look at themselves in a mirror, and he likes that the project is about inspiring and encouraging people to be more empathetic. He also likes the book she has been reading, Becoming Animal, by David Abrams, which he finds very helpful.',NULL,'How To Make a Mask To Be a Friend of Miki Tamblyns'),(66386,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - October 16, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 19:13:14',NULL,'In this chapter, the host speaks to the audience about the music he\'s been listening to. He talks about how he wants to honor the Indigenous peoples who live on his land.\n\nHe also wants to acknowledge the contributions of the Black community to the alt-rock scene. The host says, \"This is your life, and there is no one to lose it. No one\'s to blame no matter what they get. No matter how they\'re treated, no one can blame them. He says that everything is going too fast right now, so he hopes everyone will enjoy his music. He begins with a song from the English band Beatrix Players, which he says he\'d like to say is an accomplice, not an accomplice. They\'ve just heard another song, This is Your Life from their latest album, Living and Alive, and they start off with some gentle music.\n\nThey play some more music, and then they play music from different parts of the world, like Prog Rock, Dream Pop and Indie Pop. The first band that they\'ll be listening to is Men I Trust from Montreal, who played before Thanksgiving. They have an album called How To Unravel, which is a little different than the other albums they\'ve played.',NULL,NULL),(66387,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Seems Like Old Times - October 15, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 18:48:50',NULL,'In this chapter, Obert tells the audience that she has just told her class that Patricia has died. The students in her class thought death must have been wrong, and when she told them that she had died, the students were shocked and wept.\n\nObert says that she wonders if the song of death that Miss Malay wrote is like the dream she had when she wrote it. She tells the students that she once lived in Maine, where she wrote of youth and symbols of mountains. She says that her favorite poem is one called \"The Harkweaver,\" which she says she translated for her mother. The song describes how Miss Malay\'s mother wove a cloak for her son. She wove it for a King\'s son, and then she died.\n\nShe was nineteen and not yet a day older, and she sat with a harp and sang. She sat there with a smile about her lips and a light and her hands frozen dead and piled up next to her, toppling down to the sky where the clothes were of a kings son just like my ties',NULL,NULL),(66388,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Seems Like Old Times - October 15, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 18:32:22',NULL,'This program is like old times, with music and memories from the 30s to the 50s. The program opens with an introduction from Doug Blackwood, who introduces himself as Ernestine Anderson. There are two hours of music, old radio memories, and a little bit later, Billie Holiday. The Fergus branch of the Legion 275 is having a beef dinner. Advance tickets are $20, non members $22, kids under 12 are $12. The Legion has a dance at the Evergreen on Saturday night.\n\nThe Wellington Seniors Association will be holding their next Dancing At The Evergreen on the date of this program. All adults are invited to dance. For more information, please call the Recreation staff at 519 837-5699. The program ends with a letter from the Community Relations Office at the University of Guelph. The university explains that due to the government\'s response to the anti-spam bill, it is no longer possible for Canadians to view their university news on Facebook or Instagram. If you are upset by this change, and want to support the university, you can sign up for the university\'s newsletter at the university slash.',NULL,NULL),(66389,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Wind-Down - October 15, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 18:09:22',NULL,'The festival celebrates its 10-year anniversary with a line-up of local performers. The festival will be held in downtown Guelph on October 19th and 21st. In honor of the festival\'s 10th anniversary, the festival has put on a music program. This program offers listeners a selection of music to drift into the evening.\n\nThe music featured at the festival tonight is from several different artists, including: Seshi-shi, Flight Facilities, Agar Bomb, Aiza, Allison Russell, Nihi-Awok, Harrison and Ka-jibone, and Rahil. After the music concludes, the program ends with two more songs. The first song is from Helena Dalen, who has released a new album, and the second is from Elisa P.',NULL,NULL),(66390,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/16/Here Today - October 16, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-16 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-07 06:51:10',NULL,'The band is comprised of musicians from different bands. The first song they play is an EP called Harvest. It\'s a great song because they\'re getting close to Halloween. Then the band plays a new album called Transients and the song they cover is a cover of a Bernard Crowley song called Pet Sematary. The band also plays a song called Lampshade. They also play a song they just heard called John Fox and The Maths Destination. They play two songs from Hotel Myra\'s new album I am not Myself. The name of the band is changed to Hotel Myra, which reflects the dirty direction of the music. So now they\'ll move to Winnipeg for the new band called Apollo Suns and they play a Paul McCartney song called \"The Kiss of Venus\" from his latest album.',NULL,'Hotel Myra is a Canadian band based in Winnipeg, Manitoba. They\'ve been playing a lot of songs since they were'),(66391,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Visions fugitives - October 15, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 17:10:00',NULL,'Fangwei continues to write the music for the show. The first piece, Man and Bat , is about bats and hibernation. The second piece, Cats and Bat\'s and Things With Wings , are about birds and poetry. The third piece, Jean Sibelius\' Violin Concerto, is a joke about Sibelius\'s creation of a string quartet instead of a full concerto. Fangwei notes, \"Now that we have reached Sibelius, today . . we have some stories behind his JS 34\" .',NULL,NULL),(66392,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Visions fugitives - October 15, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 16:52:07',NULL,'The narrator introduces himself as \"The Curry Christopher\" and explains that he is recording the show in person with his friend Fangwei. The two of them have been working on the show together for a while and have decided to do a music show based on the seasons.\n\nThe show has been on hiatus for a bit and now they are in a hot season. Fangwei comments on the theme of the show: \"A-E-s-t-i-v-a-tI-o-n. . .\" . The narrator then recommends two animals that are associated with this theme: Per Norguards Achilles and The Tortoise and John McCabes Salamander',NULL,NULL),(66393,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - October 15, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-08 15:04:55',NULL,'The guys decide to do an episode celebrating women, including women in music. We start with a song by a band called Bodega Run, which has a female vocalist. The song is called \"Crying\" and it\'s from their album \"Get Old.\" The guys like the song because it sounds like they\'re playing a game. They decide to have a song called \"When Brakes Get Ust,\" written by an amazing female singer named Mira Duaron. The guys think the song is a great one because it is about getting home from work in the rain and they all agree that it would be a bummer if they left their bike on the curb for a while. They also agree that if you left your bike on it for too long, it would rust and slip all over the place. They\'re also psyched that Jenny Omnicord will be singing her song \"An Amazing Woman We know\" in New York City. So that will be the first four songs in the show about women. But we\'ll also be hearing songs by other amazing women. The next song is by a super cool band called Uniq, who are made up of a bunch of female musicians. They play a song about two female musicians named Steff','It\'s International Women\'s Week this week if you\'re listening to us at the beginning of March. We thought we would do an episode that celebrates women, us three guys. We started with a song called Bodega Run by a group called Crying from their album Get Old.','This Is International Women’s Week (Sponsor)'),(66394,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Clan Na Gael - October 15, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 13:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 16:28:10',NULL,'The group starts off with a song called \"I will love you,\" which is a song from one of the albums. The song was written by a guy named Davey Landry.\n\nHe met him down in Cape Breton, where he lives. He says that he wants to go back there and visit and that he has a band lined up. He used to play in Georgetown and he says that the band will be playing some English folk music, some Celtic music, and some American folk music. He also says that a band called Folcha will also play some English, Celtic, and American music. The next song is called \"The Streets of NYC,\" which he says is one of his favorite songs.',NULL,NULL),(66395,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Clan Na Gael - October 15, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 16:09:00',NULL,'The show starts off with a song by a band called \"Rise and Go\" and then they play some more music. They play a song called \"The Irish Rovers\" from an album by Andrea Corr. Then they play \"Let Me See if I can Find Celtic R-editions past-the-point of-rescue\" from a CD by Mick Hanley and then \"Vichten from Quebec\" and \"MacPhersons Farewell\" from \"The Scottish Legend\" from Hamish Imlad. They also play a Spanish podcast for a half hour. John Fahy announces that he and Mike D will not be joining the show because they will be spending Thanksgiving with their families.',NULL,NULL),(66396,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/15/Zombie Jamboree - October 15, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-15 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 15:11:21',NULL,'The program begins with a message from the Responsible Gambling Council, which advises people to avoid gambling and to be safer when playing. The show then turns to the music. The first song is by the band led by the singer Alyssa P. She is followed by Aura, th