as been around for six years. They were on tour all over Europe when the pandemic struck.\n\nThey took a long time to come up with this album because they wanted to express their emotions. The album was a kind of salvation for them. Troy also discusses some of the other things they do on the show. For example, the show is produced and curated by Julian Mardil and he\'s also a co-founder of YouTube.com slash.',NULL,NULL),(66435,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/32hhfr/DrMouth_CIUTshow_oct17_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-10-17 20:57:57',287169728,'2023-11-28 09:13:29',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the program opens with a shout-out to the listeners who have supported the station during its fall campaign. The program then goes on to discuss Dr. Mouth\'s upcoming Rock and Roll lunch party, which will be held on October 17th at the Queen Elizabeth Theatre in Toronto.\n\nThe show will also feature the band the zombies, which has been touring on the strength of their latest album. The band also performs a song from their first album, which was released in 1965. The show ends with a review of some other local acts that the program has heard, including the fan favorites, the legendary surf band the hermits, and the band Faces of our Fathers.',NULL,NULL),(66444,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Silver Screen Dream Machine - October 17, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 08:53:32',NULL,'This is the second part of the two-part program. It opens with a look back at some of the movies that have come out in the last 20 years. The first part is about the making of the first James Bond film. The second part is a look at the music that has come out over the years.\n\nIt starts with a song from the animated children\'s show Josie and the pussycats, followed by a song by Fred from the Fred Penner sitcom. The song is called \"The Paveradian Friends.\" The song was written by Fred in the 80s and was performed at a Freddie Mercury tribute show. It was included in his debut album and was released by Queen three years later. This is Brian May performing the song. The music is from Brian May\'s latest album, \"Electrified Voltage,\" which includes a live performance of a guitar solo.\n\nIt has a couple of live music video clips of the Freddie Mercury concert. It is the closest that you could have gotten to seeing what Freddie Mercury would have looked like on stage. The other song is from the soundtrack of a 2005 film called \"Twin Cinema,\" which is also a music video. The title track is from that film.',NULL,NULL),(66445,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/A Multilingual Affair - October 17, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 08:32:05',NULL,'In this program, we hear a singer-songwriter talk about his life. He says that he\'s grateful for his job, for the people he works for, and for the chance to perform at the Mermac every year. He\'s also happy to be a part of a big production called Queen. He tells us that he and his partner are going to be in town for three days. He hopes that everyone is enjoying the music that he has prepared for them, and he hopes that they\'re happy with it.',NULL,NULL),(66455,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Tuesday at 5 - October 17, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 08:07:59',NULL,'This is the hour of the show where Mac Dee introduces himself and welcomes everyone to the show. He also introduces us to some of the other guests who are also on the show, including Jesse Cook, Melissa McClellan, and Bob Dylan.\n\nThe program starts with a history lesson on the War of 1812. In this chapter, we learn that Isaac Brock was killed by a cannonball at Queenston Heights during the battle on October 13th, 1812. John Macdonald, a lieutenant colonel in the York Militia, was also killed in the battle. We learn that John was a lawyer and that he had little military experience. We also learn that he was wounded in the back and died the next day',NULL,NULL),(66456,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Down the Rabbit Hole - October 17, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 07:09:02',NULL,'In this program, the host tells his audience about his upcoming show at the underground music venue, Down the Rabbit hole. He describes the show as \"a crazy show\" ahead of him. He tells listeners that it\'s getting colder, and that he\'s worried about the ghosts haunting the audience.\n\nThe host says that he hopes everyone is doing well. He says he saw an art exhibit at the museum in Toronto that explores contemporary black life. He doesn\'t know enough words to describe what is there, but he thinks it is cool. One of the pieces in the exhibit is a collection of art by a man named Kenneth Montague. He calls it \"the Wedge Collection.\" The Wedge Collection is one of Canada\'s largest collections of contemporary art.\n\nIt explores different works \"that talk\" about contemporary African American life. The pieces include works by artists like Alice Coltrane, Pharoah Sander, Grace Jones and Sun Ra. The host says he knows a lot about these artists, but that he has no idea how to describe them. He plays some songs from each of these artists\' albums. He also says that they\'re all good. He ends the show by playing some tennis. He wants to make sure that everyone gets home safely.',NULL,NULL),(66466,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Let’s Get Lost - October 17, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 06:46:47',NULL,'The program opens with a description of the Scandinavian band Grimsta, who are playing at the upcoming improv festival in New York City. The band has a new album out called Grimsta and they\'re playing a bunch of new music. They\'re also playing an old track by Molly O\'Brien from her last album. She\'ll be performing at the improv festival, which starts Friday night and runs through Saturday. The other performers include Vijay Iyer, Leo Smith, and Wada Leo.',NULL,NULL),(66467,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/New or Never - October 17, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-28 06:35:38',NULL,'This is the second track from the new album by Adrian Hoad Reddick. It is called \"New or Never\" and it is a meditation on the nature of time.\n\nIt begins with a scene in which a young man opens a mail box and finds a postcard addressed to his dead father. He reads the postcard and finds that the address is Julianne. He writes a letter to his father, saying that a strange man stopped him on the street recently and asked him if he had the wrong woman. He then walked away like \"a lonely ghost\". The next day he wakes up to find that his arms and legs are turned to \"old growth forest\" and that his blood is floating over the tea trunk.\n\nHe thinks that people like to go out to the movies and that they leave the movies in the lobby. He looks at the postcard from Lisbon and notices that it smells of mildew on the second floor window. He begins to walk. He asks a stranger if he hears him. The stranger does not hear him. He starts to walk, asking what is missing. He is wearing a yellow sweater, blue pants, and a white sea blue paint.',NULL,NULL),(66477,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/17/Humanoid Radio - October 17, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-17 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-28 06:08:57',NULL,'This evening, the Humanoid Radio crew continues their program with Dubmatics\' Lion of Judah and Audrey Ochoa\'s song Every Tragedy Needs A Line Punch. Then they hear Worms\' song Rock, Panda Bear\'s Go On Dub, Sonic Boom\'s Sonic Dub, and Adrian Sherwood\'s Reset in Dub track. The last track of the program is Bois-de-mirir\'s Portrait de l\'Artiste, which is an alien language that has been developed to communicate with other extraterrestrials. The program ends with Bellbird\'s