eek\'s episode of the animated program Tales From the Bridge, Sam, Marty, and Kevin discuss the need for people to become organ and tissue donors. According to the Canadian Medical Association, an average of one person dies every three days due to a lack of an available organ. The good news is that by becoming a donor, you can save up to eight lives and improve the lives of as many as 75 people.\n\nSam\'s new album is now available on all the major streaming sites. Ritesh Das\'s latest album is also available on streaming services. The show is called \"Android\'s Dungeon,\" and it\'s all about music, books, and games as Sam walks into the office. He\'s a student at the university and he\'s not too far away from going to school, but he still has to go to the music studio.',NULL,NULL),(66665,116,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/T.K.O. - October 19, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-27 02:30:06',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66666,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/FoodFarm Talk - October 19, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 02:09:15',NULL,'The program opens with a description of Food Farm Talk, a program on CFRU 91.3. It\'s a show about food and agriculture in Ontario and beyond. It also includes other shows about food, farming, and other topics. We play the shows ourselves, but we also play shows from other creators, like food scientists, farmers, foodies, and others.\n\nThe program starts with a history of the Green-Reverend, a movement that radically changed agriculture in the early 1900s. It was the first time synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and high yield crops were used to increase food production. The man known as the \"father of the green revolution\" received a Nobel Prize for this work in the mid-\'70s. Dr. Nichols believes that we need a new revolution of the soil, one that works with soil\'s natural ability to defend crops and to help combat climate change.\n\nThe name of the program is \"The Brown Revolution\" and it\'s about the 90th anniversary of the Bretton-Plots, a research site in Alberta. The day was rain-free, but the weather was good. The event featured two soil scientists, one of whom is Dr. Christine. She\'s working with the Food Water Wellness foundation. The other one is Kimberly Cornish, executive director of the foundation. They are both soil scientists. The soil scientist is known for her expertise in carbon sequestration. The workshop at the Plots was the last one she and Dr.',NULL,NULL),(66667,115,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/RadiOPIRG - October 19, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 01:10:58',NULL,'In this week\'s episode of Perk, we hear from a volunteer at the university who loves working with the students and is also passionate about making a difference in the world.\n\nHe\'s named Hendel and he\'s a student at CFRU, which is a public university in Canada. If you\'d like to volunteer there, you can find out more about it on their website. Hendel tells us that he and his friend are both passionate about music, since they\'re both into the blues. They play music every Monday night on campus on 93.3 FM, and they also have a vending machine right outside the main door. They\'ve got a lot of different kinds of music on the block, so if you\'re into blues, you\'ll want to check them out. The music is all over the place, from folk to rock and everything in between. So if you like the blues, check out the music on campus. This week, we also hear from Ritesh Das from the Toronto-based Thavla Radio Ensemble. He has his new album coming out soon, and it has a live show coming up on November 4.\n\nYou can find the album at Thavlat.com. On the program, we learn that a group of students in Guelph are holding an emergency rally on Saturday, October 21, to demand an end to the Israeli occupation of the Gaza Strip. They want an immediate ceasefire. They also want to hear from elected officials in',NULL,NULL),(66668,118,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/Open Sources Guelph - October 19, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-30 14:47:36',NULL,'On this week\'s Open 12 , Adam A. of Politico joins us to talk about the political situation in Israel and the war in Gaza. The war is now in its second week, and the death toll has reached 3,500 people. Israel has not invaded the territory, but it has allowed humanitarian supplies to enter from Egypt. The new supply convoy, like the one that we saw earlier, is similar to the old one, but with a new name: the \"new Coke.\" So what is the deal with the new convoy? Well, first, war is still going on in Israel. According to the authorities, about 1,400 people have already been killed in the first two weeks of the conflict. The number has gone up to about 199 people being held hostage, and there is no food, water, or electricity in the Gaza Strip. The WHO says that conditions are \"spiraling out of control.\" Benjamin Netanyahu has announced that he will allow aid into Gaza from Egypt after meeting with Vice President Joe Biden. He also said that he would allow humanitarian aid into the territory from the Egyptian border. There is still no ground invasion, but there has been no ground attack. The rockets have come after Joe Biden has been in the area, and it seems to Adam that he is doing a lot of behind-the-scenes work to keep the conflict going. In the aftermath of the crisis, \"has Israel been so connected with its own internal politics and with a corrupt Prime Minister who\'',NULL,'The Israeli War is now in its second week, and the death toll has reached 3,500'),(66669,121,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/Sundowner - October 19, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 16:46:44',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66670,119,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/Turtle Island Underground - October 19, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-26 16:35:51',NULL,'In this episode, Mac takes us back to the basics of the Turtle Island Underground program. He introduces us to some new music that he\'s been dying to hear.\n\nThe show kicks off with a few new tracks from some of Turtle Island\'s favorite artists. The first track is a shimmering shoe-gaze by a band called Sleepy Head. There\'s also a second track called All Sad by a shoegaze band called Window Rock. The third track is by Robert Mirabal, who\'s a member of the band Young World. Then there\'s another track by Death Scene. And finally, there\'ll be a rock track from Magitim. The song is called \"The Chief Who Sold his People\" and it\'s about a man who sold his own people. This is one of the songs that Lawrence and Sister Ray recently dropped. They\'re a band from the Midwest who\'ve released a new single called \"Up to my neck in you\" and they\'ve recently released a second song called The chief who sold your people. The narrator says that he had bad experience dealing with the chief, but he also wanted to share his experience with other people.\n\nHe wanted to make a song that people could listen to and talk about, but didn\'t want them to hear the whole story. He wants people to hear that the truth hurts, but also that it\'ll help people in the future.',NULL,NULL),(66671,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/The Crooked Beat - October 19, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 16:09:53',NULL,'This is the first of a series of short, one-man interviews that CFRU is going to do each week. This interview is with a former CFRU student named Emmanuel, who\'s now a professor and runs the university\'s West Indian music program. He\'s also known as \"Real\" because he\'s a real person, not a caricature. This is one of the first interviews we\'ve heard from him, and it\'s all about him and his philosophy.',NULL,NULL),(66672,120,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/The Crooked Beat - October 19, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 15:49:49',NULL,'The gang begins by introducing us to Dread, who introduces himself as \"The Crooked Beat.\" He says that he\'s here to promote some new music. There\'s a lot of new music on the menu, from all over the world, including some old favorites. They\'ve got some classic cuts and some new stuff too.\n\nThe first thing they play is \"Blockers Far East\" from Japan. Then they play \"Fly Away\" from Jamaica, \"Demolai featuring Hitax\" from Tokyo, \"Negril\" from American tourist Eric Gale, and so forth. They also play some of the classic cuts from \"Burn in 1973 when all of them were singing\" . Then \"Black Sounds of Freedom\" from Bob Marley, \"Wailers\" from Burnin, and \"Time to Unite\" from \"Black Sound of Freedom.\" Then Deville and \"Melody\" from VP Records will perform. Then we hear \"The Next Generation\" from the \"Groundation\" album.',NULL,NULL),(66673,122,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/Forever Deaf - October 19, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-26 15:06:39',NULL,'The show starts off with Dean playing a selection of songs from his latest album. The first song he plays is One Blood from the Artificial Insanity album.\n\nHe then plays a song from a band called Guava. Then he plays from a new album, The Forgotten Past, a song called \"Void, Lost Soul\". Then he performs from the Zweilich album, \"Mental Cruelty\". Then from the Damned and Decade album he plays \"Display of Decay\". And finally from Cryophilic, \"Into the Storm\". The next song Dean plays is \"Scorched Quadrants\". And the last song he performs is from the Singularity album.',NULL,NULL),(66674,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/19/Democracy Now - October 19, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-19 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 14:48:51',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66675,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/ar