ion.\" The guy is the same DJ that we heard on the first segment, but instead of being a bit more critical, he says that he just wants to listen to his music and not be influenced by other people\'s ideas. He says that\'s why he\'',NULL,NULL),(66773,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Hellfire Radio - October 20, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 11:11:01',NULL,'The gang continues to play music from the Weird West. They\'re starting with \"Melvins,\" which they think is the best album ever. Then they go into \"Tough Age,\" which is considered to be the best of all of the Weird World albums.\n\nThen Leonard and Saxon play a song for Pops, who\'s having lunch with them. Leonard says he was running a bit late, but he\'s glad to be back. He wants to play a metal track for Pops. He\'s also going to play an anti-heroin track from an all female metal band called \"The AntiHeroin,\" which he heard on the Electric Freak Radio. They go back to the half-fire, which is where the music is electrified more than ever. They hear the band Lethal Gospel talking about all the other bands on the show.\n\nSergeant Bacon mentioned Angus from the ACDC. ACDC was mentioned by saying \"Angus\" and then they talked about the crew of \"Molly Crew\" . Leonard asks if they dug up their slipknot with breadknot. He thinks that\'s a good idea. The gang decides to play some more death metal before going into \"Chromium reckoning from the Suffering Hour album\" , which relates to the story of the apocalypse.',NULL,NULL),(66777,170,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/94dcnq/Ruby_Slippers_Oct_20_mp3_-_2023-10-16_240_PM8xgtf.mp3','2023-10-20 22:56:13',111378520,'2023-11-21 23:52:04',NULL,'The show opens with a song called \"Toronto Slippers,\" which is from a new addition to the Ruby band\'s camp account, called \"Late 20th century Magnetic Tapes.\n\n\" The name of the song is \"never even new.\" The program opens with some music from Ruby\'s own band, \"Underdog,\" and then it\'s time for German Music Corps, a band from Germany that\'s on a tour in Canada. The show introduces its guests, and they are Emily, a singer/dancer from Vancouver, and Max, a member of the Cesar X band. Emily is also one of the \"Burly Girls\" in the song, and she\'s about to tell the story of how she met the band. She\'s a dancer, but she also has a talent for singing.',NULL,NULL),(66784,187,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/gm2hsc/DREAMING_-_EPISODE_OCTOBER_20_202392twr.mp3','2023-10-20 23:02:00',140882999,'2023-11-21 23:29:55',NULL,'Dreaming in Stereo Alexandra is on stage and she tells us that she\'s here until 7 p.m. and that she just heard a track from the Vaccines. They\'re opening for the K\'s in March next year. There\'s also a bunch of new music coming. This one is from a band called Lightning Dust. Alexandra is here at the K in March of the next year and he\'s about to go to the K.',NULL,NULL),(66785,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Folk Roots Radio - October 20, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 10:49:33',NULL,'The show opens with a conversation between Andrew Lambrecht and his friend, Jan Hall. They\'re both musicians, and Lambrecht is a member of a band called the Walked 45- 45s. They play a song called \"Thanks,\" which was written by Dave McEntire. They also play songs by March and April, who play a duet called \"Not to Fall,\" by Cody Walters and Faris Romero, and by Meredith Moon, who plays an instrumental called \"Needle Case Melody.\n\n\" This is the first time anyone has played a song that is the daughter of a famous folk singer. Next, we hear from Bruce Coburn, who reflects on his life on his latest album \"Osan Omen,\" which has already been critically acclaimed. Then we hear a song from Manitoba Prairie singer-songwriter, Del Barber, called \"On the Miladyhaha Taxi,\" which is a song about a female sailor who travels around the world. And then we hear the song \"On Lake Superior Sunset\" by Pete Eastmures from his latest release \"Devil\'s Sunset.\" And then there\'s \"Sea Glass\" by the Gallants, who are a band from the South.',NULL,NULL),(66786,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Walkuman Style - October 20, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 10:24:17',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66796,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Digital Statik - October 20, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 19:00:00',86507776,'2023-11-26 10:04:31',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66797,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Volunteer Playlist - October 20, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-26 09:46:38',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66807,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Global Rare Grooves - October 20, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 09:07:49',NULL,'The Rare Groove Show is a weekly music show on CFRU\'s 93.3FM. This week\'s show starts off with a track from Chu Yan, a song from the 1970 album of the same name. The next half hour is devoted to jazz music and a reissue of a great album by Pharoah Sanders, titled \"Pharahoah on India Navigation.\" The next guest is Jermaine, who just walked into the university for the very first time.',NULL,NULL),(66808,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Industry Tactics - October 20, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 08:50:18',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66818,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/20/Industry Tactics - October 20, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-20 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-26 08:28:44',NULL,'This is the second part of a three-part interview with CFRU\'s new music director, Kevin Vietnam. The first part of the interview is about the music on the new episode of \"Industry Tactics,\" which is a weekly program on CFRU.\n\nHe tells us that he\'s just heard the first part and that he doesn\'t have anything by the artist featured on the show. So he decides to do something a little different. He decides to feature some music from artists who are currently performing at a festival called \"Festival 2023.\" He\'s going to start off with Beverly Glenn, who\'s releasing his new album \"The Ones Ahead,\" and then he\'ll play music from the band Peripheral Vision, along with some music by Nick Frazier and Douglas Ewart. Then, there\'ll be music from Vijay Iyer, who has an album called \"Holding It Down,\" and some from Douglas\'s album \"Songs of Sun Life.\" And finally, there will be music by Douglas himself, who released his album \"Inheritance\" last year.',NULL,NULL),(66819,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Jitterbuggin - October 21, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-26 08:15:23',NULL,'The host begins by giving us a quick rundown of the show. He\'s going to start off by playing a song called \"Soulful Gospel,\" which is a kind of sappy, bubblegum pop song from the early \'50s. Then he\'ll play \"Savage Kicks\" , which is another kind of rock \'n roll song. And finally, he\'s also going to play \"Back to Back\" .\n\nThis is a reference to the host\'s studio where he works, which can get pretty noisy if you\'re not careful. So he tries to keep things light and to play less. He also says that if anyone wants to check out his past shows, they can go to his website, cfu.com, and find out all his past performances. And if they want to listen to his other shows, he doesn\'t mind if they\'re on the same day as his show.\n\nSo long as they\'ve got the time and the energy to listen, he says. He gives us ten minutes, and then he goes on to say that there\'s some really good music on the show and that if you come out and hear it, you can have a good time.',NULL,NULL),(66873,30061,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/IF 2023 - October 21, 2023 at 05:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 05:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 15:07:36',NULL,'In this short program, the organizers of the International Festival of Improvisation, also known as IF 2023, tell us about some of the other performances they\'re bringing to the festival. The first one is a performance by Matilda, and it\'s co-presented by the Sonic Arts Centre at Queen University in Belfast. The second one is by Gyoza, which was originally performed at the CHAPA Experimental Music Festival in Singapore. The third performance is by Nico, the guys from Silence, and they\'ve also been invited to perform at the festival as well.',NULL,NULL),(66892,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/A Dog’s Breakfast - October 21, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:51:00',NULL,'The next week, a festival is going to take place in Guelph. It\'ll be called the International Festival of Improvised Art. It will be held in the new ImprovLab building at the International Institute of Critical Studies. The festival is free, but it\'s limited in size.',NULL,NULL),(66893,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Beautiful Druid - October 21, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:31:43',NULL,'The first song on the program is called \"The House Song\" and it\'s from Peter, Paul, and Mary\'s 1700 album. The second song is \"The Spirit of The West\" and the third song is about when someone is missing from the house.\n\nThe first songs are Jim Croce\'s \"One Less Set Of Footsteps\" and Willie Nelson\'s essential recording \"Hello Walls.\" The next song is Alison Krause\'s and Union Station\'s live album \"Disc One,\" and the last song is by Eric Biddle. The show ends with Joshua Redman\'s new recording \"Where We Are\" and \"I Left My Heart In San Francisco.\"',NULL,NULL),(66903,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Sound Magic - October 21, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 14:09:27',NULL,'In this week\'s Sound Magic program, Michael Dolesch discusses two new recordings: a new recording of a concerto by violinist Max Bruch and a recording by the Philadelphia Orchestra of the same concerto by another violinist named Randall Goosbye. The first recording is for Florence Price, and the second for Florence. The second recording will be released later in the fall.',NULL,NULL),(66913,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Sound Magic - October 21, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 13:52:08',NULL,'The program opens with a lecture on the composer Walter Braunfels, who was a member of the Essen Symphony. He is a Jewish man who was forced to live in a walled town called Theresienstade, which the Nazis planned to use as a concentration camp for Jews.\n\nAfter the war, he moved to a quiet place in Cologne, Germany, and continued to compose music. He was awarded the Order of the Arrow by the Emperor of Germany for his services to the German cause. In the late 50s and early 60s, he became the first person to hold the rank of Chancellor of the Emperor\'s German Empire. He played the piano in the royal court and became a well-known composer in Germany. He has been awarded many prizes for his work.',NULL,NULL),(66914,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Sound Magic - October 21, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 13:28:58',NULL,'In this program, Michael discusses the history of German composers and how they influenced Beethoven, Mozart, and Schubert. He discusses the first symphony written by a German composer, Fritz Folbach who lived from 1861 to 1940. The first symphony is a large scale work, with beautiful contrasts. The second symphony, written in 1908, is a late work influenced by Beethoven. The third symphony is the first recording of a work by a composer not in the catalogs at all, a composer named Max Reger. The work is for two pianos and it is a masterpiece.',NULL,NULL),(66924,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Bel Araby with CAWA - October 21, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 13:12:32',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(66925,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Caribbean Anthology - October 21, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 12:47:39',NULL,'The show is a celebration of the 10th anniversary of the comedy festival. The Alzheimer\'s Society of Waterloo-Wellington is looking for music makers to help them create playlists for people with dementia. They\'re also looking for listeners to give them iPods. The listeners can donate money, gift cards, or iPods for the project. The program ends with a shout-out to everyone who has been supporting the festival.',NULL,NULL),(66935,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/21/Caribbean Anthology - October 21, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-21 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 12:33:01',NULL,'The first half of the second half of this interview is with the founder of the Guelph Comedy Festival. The festival, which is a non-profit organization, is looking for ways to promote cultural events in the community.\n\nThe idea, according to the founder, is to find a venue that will allow such events. The first place to look for a venue is Royal City Studios in Guelph. The studio is a place where musicians, artists, and comedians can record their work and then perform it live. The organization also has a stage where artists can perform their work. The only problem is that the studio needs to raise enough money to keep going.\n\nThe founder says there are many people in the Guelph community who would like to see a place like this exist. What the studio was for the festival was to give everyone access to the related types of music. They brought a wide variety of music to the studio, including reggae, hip hop, dancehall, Soka, and dancehall. They also planned to do a Halloween event there, but now they\'re moving to another venue.',NU