ns that he co-hosts the show with Fangwei, but the show is being recorded over different locations.\n\nThe narrator explains that this is because they haven\'t been able to record their show together. Each week they pick a number of music pieces to play for the audience, and the next week they choose a different piece of music based on the theme chosen the previous week . This is a music show, and it\'s called \"Axios and the Tortoise\" , which means \"Achilles and the tortoise\" in Greek. The show is set to run on October 8, 2023, and this is a brand new episode. Fangwei sent the narrator a list of music tracks and a specific script for the music tracks.\n\nThe music tracks are based on animals that go through a process called \"acedivation,\" which is basically a hibernation period. The animals featured in the music show are a salamander and a tortoise. The title of the music piece is \"Ants Achilles and The Tortoise,\" and it refers to the \"Paradox of Zeno,\" which says that Achilles can never overtake a tortoise in a race because',NULL,NULL),(67016,145,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Visions fugitives - October 22, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 10:29:13',NULL,'The show opens with Christopher Curry, who introduces himself as the host. He and Fangwei have been working on a script together, and he\'s decided to shift the focus of the show to the autumn season.\n\nHe notes that the heat wave has passed, and that the temperatures have returned to normal. In other words, the heat is gone, and the weather is cooler than it was in September. He\'s going to play some music from the fall, including a work by the Canadian composer, Alice Ping Yi-HO, who wrote a work called Woman Singular runs with Wolves, which was a big hit when it was first published in the mid-1990s. The music is performed by the percussionist Beverly Johnston, who also plays the part of the wolf.\n\nThe show has doubled in size in the past few years, and it\'s time to move up to 51, so that it\'ll be more like the seasons. There\'s also an album in the collection, called Together, by Julian Bream, and John Williams, who both play classical guitar.',NULL,NULL),(67017,146,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/The Kookoo Bananas Variety Hour - October 22, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-08 14:49:54',NULL,'The Cuckoo\'s Bananas hosts a lunchtime program called \"The Variety Hour\" in which they play music from various sources. The program starts with a party song about food, followed by a party classic, \"Ice Cream and Cake,\" which is a song about cake.','Cuckoo Bananas Variety Hour on CFRU FM in Guelph, Canada, is a weekly radio show. The program is hosted by DJ Tamil. This week\'s show includes a rap song about food and a party tune about food.','Cuckoo Bananas Variety Hour (Radio Show)'),(67027,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Clan Na Gael - October 22, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 10:12:08',NULL,'The next song on the bill is a bartom MacNail song from a Canadian band called Bartom McNails. Next up is a song called \"Great Big C\" from a Road Rage CD. The band then plays a mummer song from Ireland, a dance song from Scotland, and a song by an American singer named Esalen Deison. The song is called \"The Dance You Choose\" and is a piece of music from her CD. Next, the band plays a song from Patty Gordon from her \"20 Golden Irish Ballad\" CD. It is a bit of a mouthful, but it\'s true. Next is another song from the Canadian band \"Glass Tiger\" who are just getting inducted into the Hall of Fame.\n\nFinally, they play a song that they found in the trash bin from a station years ago. The tune is \"Biscuity Star\" and they play some bagpipes. They play another song by a Newfoundland musician named Rong Lidster. He finds a lot of songs that are sad and happy. He says that the Celts are a \"race where all wars are happy\" and all the sad songs are sad',NULL,NULL),(67037,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Seems Like Old Times - October 22, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 09:53:25',NULL,'This is the second hour of the program. It\'s the first half of the show and it\'s all about music from the 30s and 40s. It starts off with Gunsmoke and ends with a song called \"The Western Action\" from Gunsmoke. Then it goes on to the 40s and 50s with \"Sweet Home Alabama\" and \"The Miss.\" Then it gets back to the 60s and 70s with the Dean Martin Quartet and \"Dean Martin, Cab Calloway\" and more. The program ends with the second song from the program, \"The Tatum for You\" from March 21, 1938.',NULL,NULL),(67038,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Clan Na Gael - October 22, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 09:10:10',NULL,'This is the first song in the program, and it\'s called \"The Storm\" by the narrator. The song is about a storm that\'s about to hit the coast of Nova Scotia, and the narrator has decided to sing it. He says the storm is called Babette, which means \"beyond the shelter\" . The narrator tells us that this song was written by a guy named Robbie Smith, who used to live in Nova Scotia with his aunt and uncle.\n\nHe used to play music and make a lot of money writing songs. He\'s also a bit of a folk legend, because he played in a band named Killik and wrote songs like \"I Have the Condor\" and \"The Fury Brothers\" , which are about whales. He also plays a song called Maggie, which is actually a Canadian song. It was originally a poem written by an English teacher in the 19 century.\n\nThe teacher fell for Maggie and wrote a poem called Nora, which was later used by a musician named Nora Creed, who wrote a version of the song called \"Nora.\" The narrator also tells us about the \"Stormy Weather Boys,\" a collection of songs by Helen Creighton. Helen was a friend of the narrator\'s',NULL,NULL),(67048,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Seems Like Old Times - October 22, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 08:55:44',NULL,'Kitty asks Matt if there is anything he can do to help her. He says he understands, but that he hasn\'t been feeling well all week.\n\nHe tells her that life is never all good. He also says that he has a job more than a job and that sometimes you get to wonder what\'s going on. He asks her if she knows about the eviction of the Blakes. She says she does, and then she tells him to let her know if he finds out about it. She tells him that she always thought he was on his way to the jail, but he tells her he stopped by to check on the family. He told her that they were supposed to have vacated by sundown. He said that he would prefer to discuss business elsewhere than at the presence of the eviction.\n\nHe apologizes to Kitty, and says that Finnegan should have thrown some water on her. Kitty says that she doesn\'t think he should apologize, and that he had it coming, too. He will do everything he could to hurt her now. He may also take it on the other family, too, she says. He plans to see her later. Matt reminds her that he saved her life, and she reminds him that',NULL,NULL),(67049,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/La Buena Onda - October 22, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-22 22:07:16',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67058,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hdk5td/October_22_2023_Across_the_Universebo1a5.mp3','2023-10-23 00:03:04',431961989,'2023-11-21 23:04:53',NULL,'',NULL,'The 50th anniversary of hip hop in Canada is on CIUT 99.5 — and the 50th-anniversary event'),(67059,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/veez37/Karibuni_Oct_22-2023bu5xm.mp3','2023-10-23 04:08:46',287962512,'2023-11-21 22:52:16',NULL,'The band\'s new album, called Migration, will be released on November 1, and they\'re planning a party in celebration of it. The band has been hard at work on the album and has been writing new songs for the last year or so.\n\nThey\'re also going to perform some of the songs in the album, which is titled \"Migration.\" The band also has a new track coming out from another artist named Adam Solomon, who has released an album called Bocati, which they\'ll play during the show. They also have a new song coming out that they\'ve never played before. They don\'t know which song it is yet, but they plan to play it anyway because they want people to come out and see the new music. The show will be on December 2, and the band will be releasing the new album the following December.',NULL,NULL),(67061,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hst3ym/October_20_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow95bk3.mp3','2023-10-22 23:17:39',287962512,'2023-11-21 22:26:03',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67062,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Wind-Down - October 22, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 08:30:59',NULL,'The program starts off with Say She Humans with their song \"Astral Plain\" from their latest album \"Silver\". It\'s followed by Bibio with \"A Matter of Fact\", Teen Ravine with \"Friend of a Friend\", Little Dragon with \"Lily\'s Call\" from \"Slugs of Love\", Kaja Bone with her single \"For You\", Men i Trust with \"Serendipity of Water\", La Force with \"Exoskeleton\", Abby Sage with \"Milk\", and Elisa P with \"Time After Time\" from her \"Anuktituk\" set. After the program ends, the program goes to \"Playlux\" on the program and then to \"Mirror Mirror\" with \"Imaginary Friend\" and \"Elise P\" on \"Time after Time\" . And then it\'s time to go home.',NULL,NULL),(67063,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/La Buena Onda - October 22, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-23 10:07:20',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67064,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Zombie Jamboree - October 22, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 08:08:53',NULL,'On the second day of the festival, Bruce tells the audience that they can expect to hear music all day. As the festival draws to a close, the audience can still hear the music and enjoy the fall colors. Bruce explains that the festival is a celebration of fall and that it is a festival of color. He tells the crowd that they should stick around for the second hour because there is still time to dance.',NULL,NULL),(67065,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Zombie Jamboree - October 22, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 07:51:52',NULL,'Bruce, the tour guide for the Toronto Zombie Jamboree, tells the audience that they are in the middle of fall colors. He tells them that two groups have been performing together. They are called Uh-Huh and Lamping, and they seem to come from a place called Lamping. He plays a song called Reciprocat and follows it with After The Sun Sets. He also tells them they are on a local radio station, CFRU 99.3, and that they all go by the name of Tarafta-Haiduk. They perform Bride in a red dress. For the other two groups, he plays some authentic flamenco and plays it for them.\n\nIt is called Alegria and it is a song by Trini de La ila and Pete Townsend. They also play a tribute to fall colorama with Bell and his disappointment with red leaves. They were preceded by a subsonic by Bruce who performs performative. So they are nearing the end of the first hour of their festival of fall colour but you can still keep on dancing.',NULL,NULL),(67066,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Through the Looking Glass - October 22, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 07:14:35',NULL,'The first song on tonight\'s program is from a band called Squids from Canada. The second song is from the latest version of the swing band Stylin A Prophrine, which is performed by Emily Roald Deggers, a burlesque performer who came from Vancouver. Emily is the one who met the original members of the band, the \"Sazeracs,\" at a Berlin burlesque festival. She is also the person who hosts burlesque shows in her hometown of Vancouver.',NULL,NULL),(67067,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/This Night Wounds Time - October 23, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 06:49:07',NULL,'This is a short program from the CFRU radio program \"Cfru 93.3\" about the death of the late artist Carla Blay. The program begins with a tribute to Blay and a song from her album, \"Carla Blay Live.\" The program ends with a track from the same album, called \"Blunt Object.\n\n\" Blay grew up in a religious family, and this next track suggests that she is influenced by the \"Gospel music\" of her youth. The next track on the program is a cover of Sextet, a Blay album released in 1987. The program concludes with an album called \"The Carla blay big band goes to church.\" This album is \"not more Gospel infused material,\" but rather it is a reference to \"the fact\" that it was actually recorded.',NULL,NULL),(67068,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/This Night Wounds Time - October 23, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 06:38:11',NULL,'The narrator opens the show by introducing us to the jazz composer, the late Carla Blay. Blay died at the age of 87, and she was a role model of independent music.\n\nShe was a jazz composer who created a body of work that was emotional, intellectual, and musical. Her name is Lovella Borg, and though she used her stage name, she was actually born Lovella Anderson. Her mother died when she was eight years old, and her father was a musician. She played and sang in church as a child, but she was self taught on piano. She heard Lionel Hampton\'s Lionel Hampton and was blown away by it. She married the Canadian musician Paul Blay in 1957, and their marriage yielded the jazz label Escalator Over The Hill and a distribution service for experimental music',NULL,NULL),(67069,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/Backtracks - October 22, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 06:12:58',NULL,'The show opens with a track from the first album of singer songwriter Donovan, \"Colors.\" The theme for the show is \"linchpin\" . The songs are all \"intangible\" , so they\'re all about the theme. The first track is from Jesse Collin, the former lead singer of Youngbloods. The second track is a live version of the song, \"Blue on Blue.\" The third track is an early demo from Joni. The fourth track is one from a Canadian band called Mother Tucker\' Yellow Duck. The fifth track is \"True Blue\" from a singer songwriter named Elza. She\'s on her way there too.',NULL,NULL),(67070,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/22/This Night Wounds Time - October 22, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-22 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 05:53:11',NULL,'This is another new episode for the show. It\'s a \"rebroadcast\" of the previous episode. It doesn\'t have the latest edition of the \"Geographic Spotlight\" series, but it does have some music. The music for tonight is a little too \"off-center\" . The show starts with some music from Saint Abdullah and his band, \"Saint-Abdullah & Iomak.\" The music is from their new album, \"Chasing Stateless,\" which is on a label called \"Planet Mu MU Records.\" The name of the album is a good thing, but the band\'s name is not. Then they hear some more music from James Brandon Lewis\' \"World Turned Into Light,\" a collection of contemporary art songs.\n\nThe songs are from the 21st century, and the lyrics are from Leonard Cohen. The lyrics come from \"EJP,\" a song by the poet. The song is from \"Dancing With Love,\" a release by the singer/songwriter Afarin Mansuri. All of the albums featured on the show are new releases from the new batch of students at the university. This is a track called \"Epilogue Resilience.\" The show is now on CFRU 93.3 in Guelph, and',NULL,NULL),(67080,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 23, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 05:09:11',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67081,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Here Today - October 23, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-07 06:27:31',NULL,'The host of the Here Today show, Aaron, tells his listeners about some of the music he\'s been listening to recently. First up is the band Backstab, whose new album is called This Burning House. The band is from Toronto, and the members of the band said, \"Well, is it a full-length or an EP?\" Aaron says that he thinks anything from four songs to an entire album. Next up is James Clark, the founder of James Clark Institutes, who\'s going to be on the show in November, and he\'ll be releasing an EP called Rewind Forward. He\'ll have four tracks on it, including a song by Paul McCartney, who wrote it and produced it. And then there\'s a song called Pet Sematary by the band Church of Trees. It\'ll come out on an upcoming album, Transience, in 2024. Aaron says he\'d like to invite Bernard to play the show, so he could have him take over the role of host. Before that happens, Aaron mentions a singer named Debra Fyak, who is from England. She\'s from the Ottawa valley area in Ontario, and Aaron plays her every week. And if you want to support artists',NULL,'The host of Here Today tells us what he\'s been listening to recently '),(67091,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/pjx25z/October_21st_2023_The_Minx_Sessions68zub.mp3','2023-10-23 14:52:26',287962512,'2023-11-21 22:05:17',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67092,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/v88bxs/October_20_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillowbgmyw.mp3','2023-10-23 15:03:55',287962512,'2023-11-21 21:45:52',NULL,'The next morning, the narrator of this story goes to a party. He\'s dressed in black. He doesn\'t know that he\'s there to be a shadow. He just wants to hang out. It\'s the same party every year.',NULL,NULL),(67093,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 23, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 05:04:04',NULL,'The narrator of this story is a young man named Charlie. He\'s an orphan who grew up in a small town in Iowa. He went to college in Nebraska and now lives in the town of Prairie du Chien. He has a wife named Becky who is a real estate agent. He and his wife get married on the first day of every month. The narrator is a great guy. He goes to the movies, plays the piano, and generally has a good time.',NULL,'Charlie is an orphan in Iowa. He lives in Prairie du Chien. He gets married on the first day of every month '),(67094,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Breezy Breakfast Radio - October 23, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-09 04:50:56',NULL,'This week\'s edition of the \"Breezy Breakfast\" takes place in the House of Commons in Ottawa. The host welcomes Longfeld, a Member of Parliament from Guelph, who is visiting from the city. Longfeld gives an update on the political situation in Canada. He says that since the House rose in June, there has been a new crisis every week. This week, the crisis has been \"the rise of right wing authoritarianism\" and the \"treachery of the Hamas\" and \"the breakdown of governance\" . He also says that there are live discussions about how Parliament works in Canada',NULL,'The \"Breezy Breakfast\" in the House of Commons (11 minute read)'),(67104,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Democracy Now - October 23, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 04:50:58',NULL,'The United Nations calls for an immediate cease-fire in the Gaza Strip, where more than 5,000 people have been killed and more than 14,000 injured in the past 17 days. Two humanitarian aid convoys have started trickling into the Strip, but more aid is needed. The co-founder and editor of the Gaza-based company AIM Media, Roshti Suraj, has been killed by an Israeli strike. At least 23 other journalists have also been killed since Israel launched its offensive in mid-October. The United Nation\'s UNRWA agency reports 29 staff members of the organization have been murdered in the last two weeks.',NULL,NULL),(67105,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/Worst Responders - October 23, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 04:33:23',NULL,'The show starts off with a discussion between two students, Charissa and Renee. They\'re discussing the latest developments in the world of social media. The students are discussing the state of the world and what people are doing on the web. Charissa says that he and the other students are talking about problems people are having on social media and giving them advice and hot takes.\n\nThis is an improvised comedy show, which is why the students don\'t talk about the opinions of the professors at the university. We learn that the university is in mid-October, which means that people are in their mid-thirties. It is also the time of year when people start getting depressed. The two students explain that they\'re talking about the same topics. The student says that when he\'s talking to the other student, he and she are making hard eye contact and making little mistakes.\n\nThey talk about how the two of them are using the same technology, like chat, and how they can\'t really type into the search engines. They also discuss the upcoming reading week at their university. It\'ll be in October, which will mean that students won\'t have to go to class during the holidays.',NULL,NULL),(67115,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/23/CFRU Playlist - October 23, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-23 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-23 2