rrey, a New York Times bestselling author. This second episode features music from independent artists, LGBT artists, and voices that we come to know, and love, in classic disco. On this episode, Denny and Mary-John discuss the new film The Latent, a horror film about a lonely drifter who arrives at the door of a cabin.\n\nIn addition, they discuss Patrick Horrigan\'s novel, American Scholar, about a man driven by love, but afraid of knowing the truth about his past and present loves. In this chapter, they also discuss James Fitzgerald\'s collection of his records, papers, and other things, which he kept in his spare room. All of this material belonged to him.',NULL,NULL),(67172,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Rainbow Country - October 24, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 01:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 01:05:34',NULL,'In this first part of the show, the host, Mark Tara, describes the music that he is bringing to listeners. He says that he hopes that listeners stay with him and listen to the music, because he wants them to be able to experience the music in his house. He also tells listeners that the show is coming to an end and asks them to follow him on social media to keep up with the latest news.',NULL,NULL),(67182,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ztigut/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Oct_25_2023_podcast69weg.mp3','2023-10-24 09:43:29',286504750,'2023-11-21 21:07:31',NULL,'In this chapter, we find out that we\'re going to need to raise a ton of money in order to continue to be a credible news organization. So, we\'ve got to figure out how to get people to donate to our cause. One of the ways to do that is to find out what kinds of things people want to hear. And that\'s what we did. We found out that the most popular songs in the audience were all about fear, revenge, anger, and intolerance . So maybe we\'ll be able to get more listeners to donate if we focus on those things.',NULL,NULL),(67192,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/CFRU Playlist - October 24, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 06:00:00',86507648,'2023-10-24 12:06:31',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67202,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - October 24, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 00:47:24',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(67212,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Solipsistic Retreat - October 24, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-23 00:31:14',NULL,'The first song that pops into your head is from Temple Inay. The second song is from Doom 64. The third is from Roush by the Fall. The fourth is from Solops Aestic Retreat. The fifth is from Crab.',NULL,NULL),(67213,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Solipsistic Retreat - October 24, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-23 00:11:20',NULL,'This is the first of a series of two half-hour segments in which the Solipsistics, a band of underground musicians, present their live performances. The first half of the program is devoted to discussing the music that the band is playing, which includes songs by Mondo Mondo, Animal Collective, and three songs by Negative Approach.\n\nThe second half is dedicated to the music of Death Grips, including songs from their latest album, Total Recall, and their seven-inch ten-song EP. The audience is then introduced to the host of the show, Nicole Ferrero. She is a student at the University of Guelph and has not been able to participate in the recent season of the CFRU show because she was out of town for a long time and she is in her fourth year of college. She says that her favorite song from the show is \"Free Heatwave,\" which she has sent to many people. She also mentions that she saw Death Grip Live in Toronto two weeks ago. She describes the line for the show and how she was pushed into the front of the first row. The show was described as \"ten out of ten\" by the host. He adds that it was a \"great experience\" to see Death Grip',NULL,NULL),(67223,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Bridging The Social Distance - October 24, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-22 23:07:44',NULL,'This program is produced by Jenny Mitchell, a social worker at the University of Guelph. She has started the program in response to a pandemic, and she continues it as a means to connect with her community. Today\'s guest is Lillian, a long-term resident at Riverside Glen. Lillian has been there for two years, and her husband for three years. Lillian says that she misses her husband so much that she had to move out of her husband\'s room. She says that with her husband, she has no problem, but that she has had a few visitors, including Pearl, who has come to stay with her.\n\nThen, her husband had a stroke, and now has dementia. Lillian tells Jenny that her last guest had aphasia from the stroke. She explains that she never needs to apologize for her voice, because she has a variety of experiences and voices. Jenny says that this is very sweet that she and her family have had to deal with hardship, and that they have been very kind to each other.',NULL,NULL),(67224,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Democracy Now - October 24, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 22:47:15',NULL,'As the number of dead in the 18-day Israel-Hamas conflict in the Gaza Strip continues to rise, the situation in the war-ravaged territory is becoming even worse. An official from the United Nations says nearly 42 percent of the housing stock in Gaza has been destroyed or damaged, and the only source of fuel for many of the health centers is running out. Meanwhile, Israel has been unable to bring in enough humanitarian aid to alleviate the suffering of the people of the blockaded territory. In response, Hamas has agreed to release two elderly Israeli civilians, Yoavit and Nurit Cooper, who were held hostage by the Islamic militant group.',NULL,NULL),(67234,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - October 24, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 22:26:49',NULL,'This is a very brief introduction to the various acts that we\'re going to hear here. The first act is from the rock band Double Live, who released their first album in 1997.\n\nThe second act is by English experimental rockers Radiohead from their fourth album, Kid A, released in 2000. The third act is a Canadian band called Fur Trade, whose song is called \"Signature Moves\" from their latest release, Dark Celebration. The fourth act is also from a South Korean rock band called Walking After You. The fifth act is an English band called Radiohead, who\'s got a song called \"Morning Bell\" off of their 2000 album Kid A.',NULL,NULL),(67235,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Under the Needle - October 24, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 22:13:01',NULL,'In this program, Troy Nelson, host of KEXP-FM\'s Live On KEXP, tells us about the work of the campus community radio station, CFRU. The station needs people like him to help them promote the arts in the community. They need people to help at festivals and events. They also need people who can record short scripts so that they can promote the show after their shift ends.\n\nTo volunteer, visit www.curriculum.edu and sign up for a virtual general training. Sounds magic here on CFRU every Saturday afternoon. The mission of Silence is to \"ignite the flames of experimentalism, nurture risk taking, and celebrate diversity of musical practices, artistic expression.\" We need your support to continue this important work. You can pledge to donate a month for a year and support the arts with just $10, less than what you pay for a monthly subscription to Spotify.\n\nCommit to a month and support Silence with a photo of your finger on your lips. Act now to take the pledge or make a pledge of any amount. On this show, we hear about the story of the great grandmother who was deported from the Crimean peninsula to Central Asia in 1944. Her great-grandmother\'s daughter died during the trip to',NULL,NULL),(67245,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Silver Screen Dream Machine - October 24, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 21:50:48',NULL,'The show opens with a solo show by the late Leonard Squozin, who is away from the studio. It\'s a retrospective of the careers of some of the greatest actors who have ever played the role of James Bond. The first is Roger Moore, who was the first to portray the agent 007 in seven films. Then it\'s the late Sean Connery, who\'s 90 now. He\'s played the agent twice before, in a 1967 film called Casino Royale and in a 1983 spy film called Never Say Never again. Then there\'s also a tribute to John Williams, who wrote the score for both of these films.',NULL,NULL),(67246,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/A Multilingual Affair - October 24, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 12:54:05',NULL,'This is the first part of a two-part interview with Teta Chiese, a singer and a music producer who is a member of the Underground Railroad. She is also known as the Underground Man and she is a great advocate of women\'s rights. She speaks in both English and Spanish. She says that she wants people to believe that no matter what happens in their lives, they can always rise above their circumstances. She encourages people to be strong and courageous even in the face of adversity.',NULL,NULL),(67256,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Tuesday at 5 - October 24, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 12:38:25',NULL,'Mac Dee hosts the show and introduces the guests. The first guest is Joey Wright, who is known for his work on R&B and soul. The next guest is Orchestra Beobar, a band from Dakar, Senegal. The group is made up of a singer, two guitarists, a drummer, a congas player, and a bass player.\n\nThey have been together since 1970. The group has released 20 albums and won two awards at the 2003 3 World Music awards. The band has continued to tour and has released several studio albums. The last guest is Colin Colburn, who has released his latest work Fearing The Unconquered Past. Stephen Fearing has also released a work called The Ballad of Julian Taylor. Mac Dee then takes us on a tour of Canada.',NULL,NULL),(67257,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Down the Rabbit Hole - October 24, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 12:27:38',NULL,'The next song is called \"Down the Rabbit Hole\" and it\'ll be a song from the album \"Places and Spaces\" by Harvey Mason.\n\nThe narrator says that the song is \"one of my favorites\" and that it\'s very \"vibratory\" . He goes on to say that the album is a \"daytime album\" and has a drummer named Harvey Mason playing on it. He also mentions that the singer \"Kim Jong Mi\" is one of his favorite artists and that he\'s been reading about her in a book called \"Crying in the H Mart\" , which is about a woman named Kim Jong Mi\'s mother and her aunt who used to listen very much to her. The song \"Kim Mi\" reminds the narrator of Kim\'s mom and aunt and how they used to \"listen to\" her all the time and now they\'re all listening to her music together.\n\nThey also have a Brazilian artist named Valle and a guitar player named Jeff Parker. They\'re going to go listen to the last song, \"Go Away,\" which is a song about a guy named \"Jeff Parker\" who plays drums. He says that this song is very \"fun to play on',NULL,NULL),(67267,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Let’s Get Lost - October 24, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 12:14:02',NULL,'This week\'s program begins with a description of the program. The program is a mixture of jazz and contemporary music. It begins with an introduction by Scott, who explains that the program is all about listening to music that he loves. The music featured on the program varies from genre to genre. For example, we hear music from Morris Luca, who has been playing with Sam Shalab for many years.\n\nHis latest solo album is called Moonshine. Also featured on this program is the IPA band, which is based in Scandinavia. They are led by Magnus Brunh and his wife Atle Nemo, who are songwriters and musicians. They have a trumpet player named Ingrid Hulker Flauten on their latest album, Grimsta. The band also includes Matthias Stahl on soprano sax. They play a song called New Coming from the album The Sixth Decade From Paris to Paris, which describes the coming of new things in the contemporary world. We also hear a track called Burned Gray from the CD of the same name by Jamie Branch, who passed away earlier in the year. We hear from Peripheral Vision, a band based in Toronto, who have released their second live album, We\'ve got Nothing. They also play the track The Mask Has become the',NULL,NULL),(67268,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/New or Never - October 24, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 12:02:45',NULL,'The show starts off with a bunch of new music, including Corinne Bailey Ray\'s fourth studio album, Black Rainbows, which is full of unexpected sounds. The first song is a prayer. The second is a punk rock song called Need I am Adrian, Hoad Reddick, and I have twelve friends. The third is a folk song called The Spell, a Prayer. The fourth is a new song by Corinne, called Obar Desoir. The fifth is a song by Drew, a member of the Broken Social Scene, who is also on his new album.',NULL,NULL),(67278,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/wmahrc/Hungary.mp3','2023-10-25 02:01:00',22590372,'2023-11-18 11:51:51',NULL,'Seth Martosh is the host of the show \"From Abroad\" at the University Of Toronto. He and his co-host, Alex Stroxel, travel around the world to visit students, professors, and musicians.\n\nThis week\'s guest is Dorothy Kiss, a student at the university from Hungary. She is a world champion in the Kung Fu art form. They talk about her goal setting, her professional and academic life, and her interest in the field of outer space architecture, among other things. Seth tells us that he and his friend, Alex, went to Budapest, Hungary, to build a wooden UFO for a builder\'s summit. They met many people from all over the world, including people from the United Kingdom, Brazil, and Hong Kong. Seth says that his upbringing was international, and that prepared him to study abroad in Canada. He also tells us about his friend Amun, who is studying architecture,environmental studies, and visual studies at the U of T. He says that since he was 12, he has been fascinated with the coordinate system.',NULL,NULL),(67279,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Let’s Get Lost - October 24, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 11:35:14',NULL,'Josh Cole and his crew are back on the program again, this time to talk about Kind Mine, an album by the band. They\'ve been hearing a lot of music from this program, but they\'ve also heard that the band is going to be touring the country next month. So, they\'re back to talking about music again. The program also has some news about organ donation, which is a great opportunity for people to save a huge number of lives. It\'s also a great time to donate tissue for future generations. The show starts off by playing a song from Panda Bear\'s Reset In Dub album.\n\nIt turns out that the song is called Getting To The Point Dub. Then they hear a bunch of other tracks from that album, including Dubmatics, International Dub, Audrey Ochoa, The Con Artist, Apollo Suns, Amonnaut, Hole In The Ground, Mocha Only, Mocha Alone, All Bones, Honest Proposal, and Worm Worms.',NULL,NULL),(67280,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Humanoid Radio - October 24, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 11:24:38',NULL,'The Humanoid Radio crew plays a bunch of new music this evening. We\'re starting with a track called Source of Denial, which sounds like it\'s from a movie about a guy who\'s just trying to get to the bottom of a big, bad existential crisis.\n\nThen we hear a bunch more new stuff: Babe Terror, Igeoma, the Syndicate, and I, Weird Al, a remix of WYLTK\'s EP, and a song called Bata Bing. You can listen to all of these new tracks by going to HumanoidRadio.com. The show starts off with a short overview of the latest music available on the radio. It sounds like aliens are using the radio to communicate with each other. The key is to use the technology to make contact, says the show\'s host, MacKata.\n\nSo, for now, we\'re just going to listen to some of the music. He\'ll come back next Tuesday to tell us more. The University of British Columbia and the Media Center are looking for people interested in media-related work. They\'re looking for anyone interested in music production, or anything else that involves music and/or technology. If you want to help out',NULL,NULL),(67290,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/24/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - October 24, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-24 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 11:15:06',NULL,'This is a special edition of CFRU\'s Morning Soul Shake Up. It is produced by the sound engineer, Shannon Lee, who is also a member of the Women\'s Committee of the Kitchener Public Library. The program is for women, trans, gender-expansive people who are interested in music production and recording arts.',NULL,NULL),(67291,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/25/Radia - October 25, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-25 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 11:07:17',NULL,'This is a show for Radia. They\'re a