nks, and he realizes that he needs it. He thinks about how all his hopes of romance have been shattered, and now he realizes why it matters. He decides that he\'ll never be able to have a romantic relationship with another human being, and that\'s why he keeps drinking. He talks about an artist named Marcella Detroit who once was known as MarcyLevy. She put out an album called Gold Demos and she\'s been a successful musician since then. She co wrote a song with Eric Clapton called Lay Down Sally, and she also co-wrote a song called Pet cemetery for a movie called The King\'s Pet. Aaron also talks about a singer named Joe Jackson who has released an album of his own songs called What a Racket. And another artist named Jenna Nation who is based in Toronto. Aaron says that she has a new song out called \"Introspection\".',NULL,'How I Drink and I Want to Have a Romantic Relationship (27 minute read)'),(67480,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/FoodFarm Talk - October 26, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 06:45:54',NULL,'In this interview, Martin explains how he got his current job at the university. He got a Ph.D. in agronomy from the university and worked in industry for four years. He then got his undergraduate degree and then his master\'s degree. He\'s a pioneer in this field.\n\nHe tells Tim that he\'s been interested in how farming systems work and how farmers adapt to changes in the environment. He says that he learned from Wes Jackson at the Land Institute and that\'s how he came to the university in the first place. He also says that when he first started at university, he was interested in improving the efficiency of the production system. He adds that he has been training students in this area for over 30 years. After that, he says, he just wanted to do what he wanted.\n\nHe thanks Tim for his kind words and thanks him again for his job title. Tim asks Martin if there are any definitions for what he calls \"regenerative agriculture\" and Martin says that there are many different definitions. He explains that what they\'re really talking about is principles that have been around for a long, long time. They\'ve been used for many years. If you look at a cover crop,',NULL,NULL),(67481,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Tales from the Bridge - October 26, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 06:32:51',NULL,'Tales from the bridge. Tommo and Jim are psyched to have a Canadian on the show, and this time they\'re psyched to talk to someone who\'s Canadian. They\'re talking about science fiction author, Andy Weir. He has a new book out called Project Hail Mary that\'s being adapted into a movie.\n\nHe\'ll be starring in the movie with Mr. Abs. Jim is psyched to see him, since he thinks he\'s totally Canadian. He starts off by saying that his accent is stereotypical, since people always call him by his first name. Jim says that he wants him to tell everyone in Canada that he\'d like them to call him an American.',NULL,NULL),(67483,173,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/j5rr3i/Club_Ned_Oct_29_2023_Podcastanfdh.mp3','2023-10-26 17:22:49',565712978,'2023-11-18 06:21:22',NULL,'This section consists of a series of photographs, which illustrate the various effects of drugs on the soldiers. The first photograph depicts the burning butt of an uncured butt, which contains a small amount of fine uncured marijuana. The second photograph depicts a large, uncured bomb crater. The third photograph depicts smoke from a small pot, which is used to smoke hashish. The fourth photograph shows a wooden foil with a hole in it, which has been punctured to let in smoke.\n\nThe fifth photograph shows tinfoil foil, which can be used as a smoking block. The sixth photograph depicts what appears to be a group of men trying to find Kook headquarters. The section commander is unable to locate the location of his men, and the other men are unable to communicate with him. The troop commander gives up and laughs.',NULL,NULL),(67492,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Bridging The Social Distance - October 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-18 06:07:07',NULL,'This episode of Bridging the Social Distance is produced by Jenny Mitchell, who started the show in response to a pandemic. She continues it because it is very valuable to her to share stories and experiences with her listeners.\n\nThis interview is recorded on October 17, 2023. Lillian Parker is a long-term resident in the Village of the Riverside Glen. She has been there for two years and her husband has been with her for three years. Lillian\'s first husband was very sick and she missed him terribly, so she was forced to move into a room with her husband. Her second husband had a stroke and she has been living with him ever since. He has dementia and is very bad. She says that she had Pearl before, but now she has Pearl and then her husband and she had no problem with him. He had a bleed and then he had dementia. She had no problems walking and then she had a bleeding.\n\nThen she had another stroke and he had a dementia. He is now really bad and he has aphasia. She only speaks because she is coming to talk to people with different histories and experiences, and she never needs to apologize for her voice or any difference there. She explains that one of her reasons for coming to the village',NULL,NULL),(67493,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/26/Democracy Now - October 26, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-26 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-18 05:57:02',NULL,'The war in the Gaza Strip has reached a new crisis point as fuel and water run out at the Laxamanders Hospital. An Israeli airstrike has killed the family of one of the most prominent journalists in the area, Wael Dadduh.\n\nHe reports that the situation in the besieged area is dire. He adds that there is no place safe in the whole of the territory