ifferent country from the countries he has already covered. The first part of the spotlight is on Argentina, where there are 23 provinces and the city of the city, Buenos Aires. The second part of this is on the 19th province, which is called Taiwan, which means \"Taiwan island.\" It\'s a small island in the South Pacific.',NULL,NULL),(69281,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/12/This Night Wounds Time - November 12, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-12 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 10:57:39',NULL,'This Night Wounded Time The show begins with a description of the music on the show and then shifts to a discussion of the show\'s geographical focus. The show will be dedicated to music from a \"geographic jurisdiction\" somewhere on the globe. This is the first time the show has been able to do this, and the program will focus on music from the province of Buenos Aires. The program will also feature music from Northern Argentina, which is not a \"cultural capital\" of the province. The first act of the program begins with music from Drum Machine Mike\'s new album, \"The Space Between.\" The show is available on CFRU 93.3FM in Guelph, and it is also available on iTunes.',NULL,NULL),(69282,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/This Night Wounds Time - November 13, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 10:45:09',NULL,'This promotional night wounds time. The Christopher Curry is your host. This is a geographical spotlight section. We\'re doing a spotlight this evening on music by an artist from Formosa Province in Argentina. If we weren\'t doing this tonight, there\'s absolutely no way we would have played this last track. This isn\'t good, but it\'s only from one artist, so it\'ll be fine. We take a break. The host of the show, Rich, is here and he\'s here to announce that every Friday, 10pm till midnight, he\'d like you to join him as he interviews some of the best music from today. He\'s a member of the CFRU Media Center and he hosts his own show, Industry Tactics. He also runs a music project for the Alzheimer\'s society of Waterloo Wellington. They have a free iPod with a playlist for people living with the disease. They\'re also looking for people who want to donate all of their iPods or iTunes gift cards. All of these people are welcome to join them. For more info about the music project, visit alzawamer.ca slash. Iyer is here to introduce you to the Host of the',NULL,NULL),(69283,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 13, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 08:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-13 20:31:20',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69284,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Here Today - November 13, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-17 09:18:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69285,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Breezy Breakfast Radio - November 13, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-13 20:21:59',NULL,'The next day, the mayor responds to Morgan\'s question about whether the special act is the best way to raise money. He says that he doesn\'t think it\'s necessarily better, but that it is a better way for the province to administer the act. He also thanks Scott for being so blunt on this issue. Scott is a big advocate for raising money, but he says that until the provincial and federal governments are equal partners, they will constantly ask for money. The mayor says that property taxes are one of the worst forms of taxation. He blames the province and federal government for the mess they\'re in, and says that it will cost probably a ton of money to get them out of it. He wants to give Scott the chance to respond to his question. He adds that he thinks council has been strong on this, and that they need to do more advocacy in order to get the new deal. They need to be able to send a strong letter to the provincial government saying, \"we don\'t like this.\" They need a unified voice, he says, and this is where the mayor\'s involvement comes in. The mayors represent about 70 percent of the population of the province, so that\'',NULL,NULL),(69286,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Breezy Breakfast Radio - November 13, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 20:09:59',NULL,'The next morning, the group meets to discuss the new budget. They\'re planning to make some decisions about the budget, but they\'re also planning to take a moment to reflect on their privilege to live in a city built on rich indigenous history. The first thing the group is going to do is to think about how they\'ll care for the land, people, and generations to come in the future. First things first: Scott Stewart, the city\'s chief administrative officer, is here to help them understand the budget. The budget is the first of two Mayor\'s budgets, covering 2024 through 2027. Scott Stewart is an expert on the process, and he\'ll explain everything to the group. They can ask questions, but Scott will be the one to answer them. Scott explains that it\'s important to remember that the first budget is for a mayor, and the second budget is a multi-year plan that covers 2024 to 2027',NULL,NULL),(69287,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/2ghssi/November_11th_2023_The_Minx_Sessions7zup1.mp3','2023-11-13 18:09:34',287962512,'2023-11-13 19:56:37',NULL,'This is a short program from the music show on community radio station CIUT 99.5. It\'s called the \"Mink Sessions\" and it\'s hosted by David. He\'s a regular on the show and he\'s always been a big fan of independent artists. David introduces the new artist Cousin, who\'s from Australia and is coming out with a new album called \"Home Soon,\" which will be released later this year. The show starts out with an old favorite, Etienne De Cressy.',NULL,NULL),(69288,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/usq8fv/November_11th_2023_Calling_All_Bluesaipas.mp3','2023-11-13 18:11:33',143961989,'2023-11-13 19:46:25',NULL,'The program opens with a look back at the past month\'s releases. It seems that this is a very good time to release some new music. First up is Kingfish Ingram, who won a Grammy for his work on the recently released Chris Stone album. Next up is Big Krit who is releasing a remix album of a song that he wrote called \"Blues Meets Rap.\" The remix album is called \"KRIT\" meaning \"King Remembered In Time.\" And that\'s it. Next, it\'s Bisson with You who has released a new album called \"The Ballad Of Lucy Stone.\" And then Anika and Paul are getting ready to release their first album, called \"Trouble Good,\" in October. They\'re married for two years and now they\'re doing music together. So the show starts with a live recording from their upcoming debut album. It\'ll be coming out in October on a label called Viztone. The band then goes on to perform a song from Hill\'s upcoming album, \"Dear Illusion.\" It\'s called \"Everything You Got.\" And it\'ll come out in November on the same label as Hill, Anika, and Paul\'s new album. Then it\'',NULL,NULL),(69289,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Democracy Now - November 13, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 19:30:58',NULL,'The program opens with a reminder that the University of California, Berkeley, is holding its annual general meeting on December 14th. In addition, the university is holding a grant competition for 150 young people to work on projects that will make a real impact on the environment. The Ocean Action Grant will provide up to $3,000 to 150 applicants. In the program, Democracy Now!\'s Amy Goodman reports that the situation in the besieged Gaza Strip is very critical. The two largest hospitals in the area are running out of fuel, and the Israeli blockade has made it impossible for them to operate. Doctors at the Al-Shifah Hospital are trying to keep life-saving babies alive. A doctor with Doctors Without Borders, named Hamam Al Lav, was killed last Saturday by an Israeli shell.',NULL,NULL),(69290,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Worst Responders - November 13, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 19:19:59',NULL,'The show begins with two comedians, Renee and Carissa, discussing the problems they encounter on the web. They are both stand-up comic comedians and they perform on a show called Worst Responders. The show is a comedy where two comedians are \"first and worst\" on the scene when it comes to responding to the problems of the internet. The first comedian is Renee, who is a student at the university, and the second comedian is Carissa. Their show consists of \"improvised and it is in good fun\" and does not reflect their opinions. The second comedian, Georgette, is a Canadian, and she performs in the university. She is a female stand up comic who performs in a small, intimate theatre. She performs on a small stage. She and her fellow performers are asked to act as if they are on stage, and they are given the opportunity to act in front of a live audience. She tells them that they are only acting because they feel that they have to act. She says that she and Georgette have become very close in the past few years. They have become friends, and that they communicate with each other through the use of a \"chat\" system. When they are talking, they are',NULL,NULL),(69291,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/CFRU Playlist - November 13, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-13 21:06:01',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(69292,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - November 13, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 06:10:30',NULL,'In this chapter, Nicholas Cooper, the founder and host of the North American version of the live music show, the Sentinel, describes the scope of the show and its relationship to Turtle Island. He also acknowledges the contributions of the Black community to the music scene, and he thanks the listeners for their continued support of him. The show begins with a performance by Chris Squire, the legendary bassist from the Yes band. The rest of the session consists of new music from progressive artists including Jennifer Reiser of North Carolina, Pentayo of California, Suffer Fools of British Columbia and Callie Horse of Texas.',NULL,NULL),(69293,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Big Sis Radio - November 13, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 05:54:58',NULL,'This week on Big Sis, we hear tracks from two new albums. First, we listen to a track from the new album All Around You by Singaporean band SubSonic Eye. The band is inspired by the natural world and encourages the listener to sit with their complex emotions. The next track is a song by Arlo Parks called Brewzeless. It\'s an anti-war song. We also hear a song called What\'s The Holy Nobel Today from the voice of Bache-Prat. The last song we heard was Incidental Boogie from US Girls. This week\'s music picks are inspired by anger and sadness, and music is the medium for people to express their voices. It empowers people to gather and share ideas. It provides a space for people in the world to speak out against oppression. This is the weekly reminder that the world is going to be okay. In the second track, we learn about a school in Italy called Rondin. It teaches students the power to resolve conflict through reconciliation and is a unique institution. The school pairs students from different ethnic groups and encourages them to look at each other as different people. This approach encourages students to break the trance of seeing people as one another. This shows that when we',NULL,NULL),(69294,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/to know the land - November 13, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 05:38:58',NULL,'The conversation opens with a discussion about how to teach people in the U.S. how to live in harmony with the land, and what can be done to support that. David is particularly interested in the idea of teaching people how to be in good relationships with land and with each other, and how to not destroy the land. He talks about his long-time friend, Lisa, who works in the field of nature connection and teaches people about the land as well as how to develop good relationship with land. The conversation ends with a question and answer session, in which David asks Lisa how the ideas of nature education came into her life, and she answers that she grew up in cities, and that her innate desire to roam and be part of nature made her want to be outdoors.',NULL,NULL),(69295,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Blues Around the Block - November 13, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 05:23:13',NULL,'On this episode of Blues Around The Block, we catch up with some of our favorite musicians, including Big Boy, Big Smoke, and the SlideWinder Blues Band, as well as Kristone Ingram, Gary Allen, Robin Ford, and Water Street Blues. We also catch up on the latest releases from Susan Tedeschio and Little Magic Sam.',NULL,NULL),(69296,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Blues Around the Block - November 13, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 05:11:03',NULL,'The show starts off with Strawley trying to live her life without you, and then Matt Anderson rolling down the road, followed by Iskwa, Tom Wilson, Brandon Isaac, Chris Whiteley and Robert Finley. The rest of the show is set off by musicians who have released albums in the last ten years. Here are some of the songs: Brandon Isaac Do what you did last night. Brandon Isaac Life is Music. Robert Finley Better than I treat myself from his Sharecroppings Son album. And Coco Peter Montoya I\'d rather feel bad about doing it. You can hear all of these artists on the CFRU.FM 93.3 station in the city of Guelph',NULL,NULL),(69297,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/The Deep House Project - November 13, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 06:50:58','2023-11-14 05:06:04','On this week\'s edition of the Deep House Project, the guys play a bunch of new music from all over the world, including some songs that have been written by Diana Ross, Barbara Tucker, Prophetic Soul, Chris Malanchuk, and more. They also play some songs from Canada, including a song by a Canadian called E-track. They close the show by playing a song from George Fitzgerald, who\'s releasing a new track called Little Wing.',NULL,NULL),(69298,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Ripcord Radio - November 13, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 06:36:05','2023-11-14 05:06:10','This week\'s show will feature music from a number of different bands, including bands from Canada, the United States, Pennsylvania, and California.  The first track on the show is from Fashion Faux Paw, a band that\'s best known for their standoff with fashion faux-paw from their debut 2007 album Be Excited .\n\nThe band also includes some members of bands like New Day, Spread the disease, and Amenostra.  The second track is from Johnny Hanson, a singer who\'s also a member of Dead Bob and other underground acts.  The third track is a song from Native Nod, which is best known as one of the bands that cancelled a cross-country tour in the early 90s.  It\'s called Back to Mimmsy.  The fourth and final track is called Red Cross with iHateMySchool, which was part of the group\'s first self-titled EP.  The fifth track is The Hated With Somewhere, a collection of songs that was released in 1985.  The sixth track is Dave Buschmeyer\'s band, which includes members of New Day.',NULL,NULL),(69299,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/13/Back in the USSR - November 13, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-13 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 14:46:31','2023-11-14 07:06:41','On this edition of the CFRU program, we continue our program on the situation in the Middle East. More than 10,400 Palestinians have been killed in the recent conflict in the Gaza Strip.\n\nMany countries have severed diplomatic ties with Israel and many ambassadors have been withdrawn from the Jewish state. The one member of the US House of Representatives, a Palestinian woman named Rashida, has been censored by Congress for speaking out against the war in the occupied territories. The interview with Prashad takes place on the second day of the largest mass demonstration in the United States for the support of the people of the Occupied Territories. It was attended by over three million people. The demonstration reminded Prashard of the struggle to end apartheid in South Africa in the late 1980s. It reminded him of the way public opinion changed when the South African government turned against the apartheid government and a crusade and global crusade led to the end of the apartheid system. At the very same time, there is a member of Congress who cheated to leave and is being censored because she dares to speak out against Israel.',NULL,NULL),(69300,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Rainbow Country - November 14, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 00:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-14 14:31:41','2023-11-14 07:07:52','In this special edition of the show, host and producer Mark Tara introduces his new show, \"Rainbow Country,\" and explains that it is a \"little gay radio show\" that works to \"give voice to the lesbian community and beyond.\n\n\" The show is produced and hosted by Mark Tara, who is also the producer and host of the program. The show begins with a brief introduction to the show and then segues into the life of the \'80s, where the \"gay community was actually getting noticed.\" The police had never liked the decriminalization of homosexuality that was passed by the Trudeau government in 1969, but they began arresting gay men in the early \'80s. The most famous raid was the one in Toronto on February 5, 1981, when the police arrested 300 men in connection with the prostitution of men in public baths.',NULL,NULL),(69301,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Rainbow Country - November 14, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 14:19:47','2023-11-14 09:07:20','',NULL,NULL),(69302,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/CFRU Playlist - November 14, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 06:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 13:06:26','2023-11-14 13:06:26',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69303,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 14, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 18:31:10','2023-11-14 15:06:22','',NULL,NULL),(69304,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Here Today - November 14, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-16 10:12:51','2023-11-14 15:06:49','In this special edition of the Here Today program, Aaron plays new music from a number of artists, including a new single from The Beatles, a new album from the band Men Of North Country, a re-release of the band\'s classic albums, and more. He also plays a song from Paul Manchin\'s latest album, Master. The show ends with a special appearance by Aaron\'s wife, Deborah, who has new music to share.',NULL,NULL),(69305,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/14/Solipsistic Retreat - November 14, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-14 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-14 18:21:44','2023-11-14 17:07:53','Solipsistic enters and announces that he\'s listening to the music on CFRU, which is a community radio station. The music is so good that he can\'t wait to hear it. He also announces that the station has a great website with all the latest news and information abou