edit Union. The show is a mix of music from the province of Alberta. He talks about the silent film, Sherlock Jr.\n\n, which was released in 1924. The silent film has some of the most famous stunts in the film, including one in which the window of a house is cut open by the side of it. The music for the show starts with Hay Major, an elegant rock band. It\'s one of Cece\'s favorite things to do. One of his favorite things about music is that it makes him feel infinite.',NULL,NULL),(69445,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/to know the land - November 20, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 01:46:35','2023-11-21 01:06:04','In this episode, Byron talks about his show, \"How we defend the land,\" which is a podcast about how people interact with and defend the natural world.Byron\'s name is Byron, and he has an affinity for storytelling about the land, whether it\'s through scientific journals, or through storytelling in first person, or storytelling in both first person and in the form of mythology.\n\nByron also talks about the importance of October, the time of year when people tend to spend a lot of time reading books and collecting things. He finds that the stories and folklore that he reads often trace back to pre-Christian traditions of direct relationship between humans and the land. He thinks that the origins of all life, all nourishment, and all things are often traced back to those traditions.\n\nByron thinks that in these stories, there are often interspecies communication, that the plants and animals can communicate with the humans, and sometimes there are wood-spirits or sea spirits, and that there is a different kind of way of looking about the world that he thinks especially in the western identities and Western notions, which become rationalistic and rationalistic, and also Christian. And often, we start looking toward often like indigenous practices or practices of connection with the',NULL,NULL),(69446