23-11-21 23:07:25','The band starts out with a guy named Dargil from the Classic Irish Folk collection. Dargil used to live in a seaside town called Bray, about 12-15 miles from Dublin. He used to go there on Sundays, but the poor people couldn\'t go there because the town was too far away.\n\nThey went to the waxy\'s dargil, which is called Dollybrook. The word Dollybrook is from the song \"Dollybrook\" by the Dollybrooks. The band then goes on to play some songs from their CD collection. They start with Billy Cowe from \"Best of Scottish Folk\" and then they go on to a song called \"I\'m Not a Good Guy\" by Lorena McKinnon. Then they go back to Johnny McAvoy from \"Classic Irish Folk Machine\" .',NULL,NULL),(69465,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/19/Clan Na Gael - November 19, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-19 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 08:46:09','2023-11-21 23:07:26','The song is called \"Donna,\" and it\'s about a girl falling in love with a boy. It\'s one of the Irish songs, which is sad, according to the song\'s narrator. But the narrator thinks that the song will appeal to everyone, so he\'s going to sing it anyway. The song begins with a simple melody and moves to a more complex song about love.',NULL,NULL),(69466,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Democracy Now - November 21, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 08:28:58','2023-11-21 23:07:34','Israel\'s war on the Gaza Strip has taken a toll on journalists, with more than 50 of them detained and missing. In addition, Netanyahu has asked the Palestinians to leave the besieged territory. Meanwhile, the World Health Organization says all hospitals are out of service, and hundreds of patients are trapped in medical facilities that have effectively ceased to function.\n\nThe United Nations Secretary General calls for an immediate ceasefire, saying that thousands of children have been killed in the last few weeks. The U.N\'s chief spokesman says that the killing of civilians is \"unprecedented\" in any conflict, and that the death of the head of the Gaza Press House, Belal Jadah, is particularly significant.\n\nA woman named Ayat Khuddur has been killed with her family in an airstrike. She is one of the last of her kind to report.',NULL,NULL),(69467,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Silver Screen Dream Machine - November 21, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 15:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-22 08:13:18','2023-11-21 23:07:41','On this episode of Dream Machine, host Leonard Squozin plays music from a Canadian film, called Sleeping Giant. In this episode, Dream Machine remembers the death of actor and martial artist Jason David Frank who played the role of Tommy Oliver in Power Rangers. On November 19, last year, Frank committed suicide. On this particular day, the Dream Machine shows the theme songs for the four Power Ranger series. The first song is \"Go Go Power Rangers,\" the second is \"Chopin Levy,\" the third is \"Transformer Zero,\" the fourth is \"Franchise,\" and the fifth is \"Kinky Boots.\"',NULL,NULL),(69468,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Under the Needle - November 21, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 07:09:46','2023-11-21 23:07:50','On this show, we\'ll hear about Catherine Paul, better known as Catherine Paul or Catherine KP, a Seattle-based singer/songwriter. Her latest album is called The Land, the Water, and the Sky and it\'s her third full length. Her first two albums were full length records and featured some of her most popular songs.\n\nHer third record is full length and features songs about returning to her homeland in the Swinomish territory or ancestral homelands of the Chinook tribe. She\'ll also be playing songs about the ancestral homeland of the Clackamaws. She moved back to her home state after the pandemic to help her parents out. She says that she always wanted to go back out and tour, but when the pandemic hit, she wanted to stay home and help her family.\n\nHer husband and her step kids decided to move back in with her family and become a part of her community. This was a big deal for her, since it was the first time she\'d been away from home since she was a child. She felt like she had a much closer connection to homelands and her place in the world. For the show, Catherine Paul\'s band plays four songs from her latest record.',NULL,NULL),(69469,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Solipsistic Retreat - November 21, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-22 14:07:47','2023-11-21 23:07:53','The first album had a lot more fun songs and songs about poop and farting, and the second album had more of a mature vibe. Tom Thacker did some thinking on the first album and put more thought into the lyrics. He put on a song called \"How Far Shallow takes you by gob\" which is about letting go of a jerk.\n\nHe says most of the stuff on this show is personal, it matters to him a lot, and what else do I play?',NULL,NULL),(69470,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Solipsistic Retreat - November 21, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-22 06:31:09','2023-11-21 23:07:54','This is a soliloquy about Marnie Stern, a musician from Montreal who has released a new record this month. The program begins with the program host, a guy named Phil, talking about how he doesn\'t like listening to music every night because he wants to listen to music that isn\'t about music. Phil says he\'s listening to Marnie\'s new record because it\'s \"Grateful retreat\" type of music, not about music that\'s tame. He\'s not into the music that people like Aerosmith and Van Halen play. He wants to hear music that has something to do with the people who listen to it. Phil explains that Marnie has been working on her new record for ten years and that the guy who plays the guitar on her record is from Guelph, Ontario.\n\nThe guy plays the bass and plays the drums. He also plays the electric guitar. Phil and Phil talk about how they\'re not into music that only has one instrument in it. They talk about the fact that musicians need to learn to play the instruments they play before they can play the music they play. They also talk about some of the Montrealers who play on the Arcade Fire record. They\'re',NULL,NULL),(69471,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/A Multilingual Affair - November 21, 2023 at 16:50 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 16:50:00',1380,'2023-11-22 05:09:35','2023-11-21 23:07:55','In August 2023, the Canadian soul singer, Tanika Charles, releases her second studio album, Union Sessions. This time it\'s more of a celebration of love, as she sings about the power of love in her song \"Union Sessions.\n\n\" On this edition of MacDee\'s show, MacDee talks about the music of 2023, including three albums released that year: Colin Coburn\'s Oh Sun Oh Moon, David Francie\'s This Morning, and William Prince\'s When You Miss someone. He also talks about a walk he and Tanika took together in the autumn. They walked along the Royal trail, which is a favorite way to get away from it all.',NULL,NULL),(69472,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/k9ui25/DrMouth_CIUTshow_nov21_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-11-22 00:25:15',285723008,'2023-11-22 01:31:27','2023-11-22 01:05:20','Dr. Mouth opens the show by thanking everyone who donated to his show and to the CIUT. He then goes on to talk about some of his favorite movies, including the one he\'s going to be showing at the Trash Palace on December 8th . He also talks about a band called the Syndicate from Ottawa, a Canadian surf band. Then he plays a track from the 69 reissue of the band\'s first album. The track is called \"Moog Espana\" and it sounds like it\'s from Spain',NULL,NULL),(69473,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/21/Tuesday at 5 - November 21, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-21 17:00:00',8