ve made donations to the station. She also thanks Alvin for saying that the show is one of his favorites at the station, and she also thanks Praveen, Rohini, and other listeners for their support of the station and for supporting live concerts in the city. The host also announces that they will be giving away tickets to a show by the Okavango African Orchestra on December 2nd. The show will be a celebration of the band\'s new album, Migration, and they will also play some of their favorites from their previous works.\n\nThey will also be playing some songs from their latest album, which is out as well. They\'ll also be celebrating the upcoming Christmas season and the show will also pay tribute to Sarah Tavares, a Cap Verdean woman who has recently passed away. She was one of the guests on the program, and the host decided to remember her.',NULL,NULL),(69585,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/26/Through the Looking Glass - November 26, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-26 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 05:49:06','2023-11-27 05:06:57','The next hour, the band travels through the Looking-Glass and listens to music wherever it takes them. The first track is Departures, a collection of songs by Fonzie, which the narrator describes as a \"slight throat\" which he hopes will keep listeners from getting sick.\n\nThe next song is the Alter-Cacters\' \"Unsidable\" from the late-century magnetic tapes. It is time to turn the conversation over to the German music correspondent Melanie, who has been listening to a lot of music for the show. The song is from a new album, \"The Revenge Of Hieronymus-Bosch,\" which is about to come out. The proceeds from the sale of the album go to the Save-the-Children charity. The program will go up on the CFR-U website under \"the show page\" next week. The band continues on with a song from Raised-By-Haze, Touch the Sky, and then a new track by Night Parrots, The Storyline-Ends Here.\n\nThe music is described as \"completely beautiful\" and the narrator hopes that listeners will come back next week as they follow the music through the looking-glass. The final track is a song dedicated to Matt, from the Tone-Zone, who is a \"massive supporter\" of Juliana Hatfield, who sings \"ELO\" and \"Bluebird is Dead.\" The program ends with a track dedicated \"to Matt from the T-Zone\" who is \"',NULL,NULL),(69586,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/26/Backtracks - November 26, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-26 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 05:31:21','2023-11-27 05:06:59','The program opens with the first of many covers of songs by Frank Zappa, the West Coast pop art experimental band, and the British psychedelic band Kaleidoscope. The program moves on to a song by Moby Spence, Bob Mose, Don Stevenson and Peter Lewis called Indifference, and then to Egyptian Gardens from the psychedelic band Side Trips. The show closes with Mars Bonfire\'s Born to be Wild. Both Mars and his brother, Jerry, recorded the song in 1968 and released it with Steppenwolf.',NULL,NULL),(69587,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/27/This Night Wounds Time - November 27, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-27 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 14:04:07','2023-11-27 07:07:16','',NULL,NULL),(69588,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/26/This Night Wounds Time - November 26, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-26 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 07:29:45','2023-11-27 07:07:17','The program opens with a description of the music on the air. The program is all about music that is \"off the beaten track,\" which means that it\'s not in the center of the world.\n\nThe music in this program is from artists who live somewhere in the world, and they\'re from different provinces in different parts of the country, so they\'ll be playing music from different regions. The first song on the program is \"Stray Carrier hidgen\" by Pierre Bastine, an artist from Canada. He\'s from the Netherlands. The second song is from Gabriel Burnbaugh, who\'s also from the same country. The third song is \"Rapid fr\" by Josh Zubat.',NULL,NULL),(69589,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/27/This Night Wounds Time - November 27, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-27 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 09:33:07','2023-11-27 09:07:03','In this week\'s show, the host of a local radio show, Christopher Curry, talks about the geography of the world. He explains that the show has been doing a \"geographic spotlight series\" for the past ten years. Since then, they\'ve covered the internal parts of seven of the largest countries on the planet, Russia, China, Canada, the United States, Brazil, and Australia. They\'ve also done a \"mini-series\" on smaller countries, including the Vatican City, the Galapagos Islands, Monaco, and Nauru. They also covered the smallest country in the whole world, the Marshall Islands, which is just a tiny speck of land in the middle of the Pacific Ocean.',NULL,NULL),(69590,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/27/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 27, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-27 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 15:47:23','2023-11-27 15:06:45','The university\'s Media and Communications Center offers a variety of volunteer opportunities, including hosting your own show or podcasting, as well as helping with a wide range of creative projects throughout the year. We\'re always looking for people with an interest and passion in music production, video production, or public service announcements. If you are fascinated by music and/or production, we\'d like you to help out with one of our shows, live events, or live events and live performances. We also want you to be interested in engineering a live stream of our in-studio streams. No experience is necessary, just a willingness to learn. When you\'re ready, email us at cpu.ca and we\'ll get you started.',NULL,NULL),(69591,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/27/Here Today - November 27, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-27 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 15:29:55','2023-11-27 15:07:09','The program begins with a description of the band Dirty Hurricane, which is described as a \"rocking country on steroids\" band. They have released a new Christmas single, \"Christmas is Coming,\" and they are described as being in a festive mood. The band\'s members include singer-songwriter Joe Leskoff, former members of the bands While You Wait and Justice FM, and Mr. Bottomline. The song is described by the program as being a \"great song.\" The program goes on to describe a band called Hillsborough, which has just released an album called \"Hillsborough.\n\n\" The band also has a single called \"Coming Down.\" The show then turns to some other artists, including Juno Award-winning British artist Deborah Fejallowicz, the English duo Moons of Jupyters, and Len Mazzoni. The program also describes Bernard Frazier, a Canadian artist who has made a name for himself as a singer, songwriter, and performer.',NULL,NULL),(69592,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/27/Breezy Breakfast Radio - November 27, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-27 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 17:51:15','2023-11-27 17:06:11','Dr. Rivers discusses the importance of having a male role model in a family and how having a female role model can be beneficial for a family.\n\nHe also discusses his practice, which is diverse, and how he sees his clients. He says that his job as a psychologist is to hold space no matter where he is from or what his culture is. He explains that there are two kinds of men in his practice: men who want to return to their original cultures and men who need to stay in North America or Canada. He adds that he has lots of diverse clients, and he has a fair share of them. He tells us that the whole underpinning of everything he does is the pain he carries as a client. When he can help a client figure out that there is other options than suffering, that he is not his own pain, then he can realize that there may be other options for him.',NULL,NULL),(69593,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/27/Breezy Breakfast Radio - November 27, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-27 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-27 17:28:30','2023-11-27 17:06:11','This morning\'s guest, Dave Robinson, is a local psychotherapist who focuses on mental health. Dave\'s a big supporter of the annual men\'s movement \"Movember\" , which is dedicated to raising awareness and funds to support mental health in men. Before we get into the topic of mental health, we should mention that suicide is a common problem in Indigenous communities. Because of this, the discussion will be more about reconciliation than it is about suicide.',NULL,NULL),(69594,164,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ww6zkh/BTHNov27.mp3','2023-11-27 18:10:29',44384870,'2023-11-27 20:48:44','2023-11-27 19:05:26','This morning on Beyond the Headslines, Audrey, Mehdi, and Steffi discuss the housing crisis in Canada. The program aims to bring you into the conversation by discussing the issues beyond the headlines. The most pressing issue that we\'re going to discuss today is the crisis of housing supply. The government is making huge commitments to address the problem, but it\'s only part of the solution.',NULL,NULL),(69595,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/7jkyus/November_25th_2023_The_Minx_Sessions9d4ts.mp3','2023-11-27 17:44:21',287962512,'2023-11-27 20:27:26','2023-11-27 19:05:46','The host of the CIUT 99.5FM Minx Sessions program takes the listeners by the hand and tells them that he is a community radio station and that he cannot support all the independent artists if he did not have the same platform.\n\nHe encourages listeners to make donations to the station and to support the artists on the program. The music that he will play tonight will be all independent music. He will be playing music from Minas science out on the Balmat wonderful label, and he will also be playing some