 from that show, including \"The Secrets,\" \"The Ugly,\" \"Vile Tones,\" \"Teenage Head,\" and \"Cardboard Brains,\" as well as \"Senex\" . The show ends with the announcement that you can still listen to the show on your iPod or iPod Touch.',NULL,NULL),(69648,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/xqb5hg/Ep90_Kurdistan6ngni.mp3','2023-11-29 15:57:24',85277522,'2023-11-29 18:10:31','2023-11-29 17:05:40','In this program, we learn that Sinem is a musician from the region of Kurdistan in Turkey. She was born and raised in a musical household, and she explains that there is a huge difference in the language between the different dialects of her own language, Azaki, and the language of her parents, Turkmanji, who live in the city of Istanbul. In addition, she explains, there are also many Western instruments that are used in Kurdish music production, but that are still kept very much traditional. She says that in Turkey, the education system is very Western, because it was built on the ideals of the West. But in her opinion, most of the people in the region do not want to try to bring the culture of their own language to the forefront.',NULL,NULL),(69649,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/The Stillness & The Dancing - November 29, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 10:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 17:50:20','2023-11-29 17:06:17','The show begins with a brief introduction from the show\'s host, David Mill. He explains that he is returning to music after spending five weeks in the hospital. He tells listeners that he has spent the last few weeks in Toronto, undergoing some treatment for his bladder infection at Princess Margaret Hospital. He says that he feels like he has \"stumbled home\" and is grateful to have a routine of music. The first hour of the show consists of Illumina\'s most recent release, \"Number 4,\" and Kaiikadim\'s \"Three Piano Pieces For Peter Broderick.\" The second hour consists of Ocean Shores Decay, a project by the Dutch artist, \"Ocean Shores.\" The third hour consists primarily of the album, \"Paths,\" by the Canadian experimental musician, Olin Mill.\n\nMill explains that his music has shifted from a \"basic exposure to some kind of post-rock\" to a \"world of experimental drone\" in the past few years. He then lists some of his favorite albums, including \"The Square is Porcelain,\" \"Our Blessed Friend,\" \"O Lake,\" and \"Innocence,\" a piano piece by the French artist, O.',NULL,NULL),(69650,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/The Stillness & The Dancing - November 29, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 17:29:18','2023-11-29 17:06:18','This is the latest edition of the Stillness & the Dancing on CFRU 93.3. The host is feeling a bit tired today and he\'s just returned from a few weeks in Toronto where he was undergoing some medical treatments.\n\nHe\'s been living in the city for a while and coming back to work and sometimes recording for the show. He says that he feels like he has been on a \"roller coaster ride\" for several weeks, and he is ready to take a break from it all. He gives us a rundown of some of his favorite albums and also some new releases. He starts off by giving us a shout out to a band called \"Fully Submerged 1 .\n\n. The Beginning\" who released a bunch of albums in a one year period. The show starts off with a song called \"You\'re listening\" from that album. Then it\'s a track called \"Oh but a light\" from another album called \"Ants Altars\" and finally \"Air Shaper Homecoming\" from the same album as \"Existence Strategy\" . After that the show moves on to another project called \"Memory Hole\" from Dead Slow. Then we get some new music from another project named \"Ilan Vital\" who is releasing a new track called Off the beaten path. And finally we get a new song from another artist called \"The Wanderer Last Journey\" from his upcoming album.',NULL,NULL),(69651,185,'https://ciut.fm/wp-content/uploads/audio/atozblues.mp3','2023-11-29 18:33:12',0,'2023-11-29 19:05:26','2023-11-29 19:05:26',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69652,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - November 29, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 19:49:03','2023-11-29 19:06:17','This episode is all about a guy named Andre who is a graduate student at Cal Poly-Santa Barbara. He\'s from London, Ontario, and he\'s a bit of a crazy story. He says he went to the University of Guelph to study chemistry, but then he went back to London to get his master\'s degree, then he stayed in London to work as a laboratory manager, and then he moved to Santa Barbara to do a Ph.D.',NULL,NULL),(69653,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/Democracy Now - November 29, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 19:30:26','2023-11-29 19:07:17','Meanwhile, Secretary of State, Antony Blinken, speaks to the press in Brussels. He says that the United States wants to extend the temporary cease-fire in the Gaza Strip so that more prisoners can be released and humanitarian assistance can be brought in. On the same day, 30 women and children are released from Israeli prisons. This is Ruba Asis, a student and activist who was released yesterday. She says that this joy is filled \"with pain and sacrifice,\" but also with \"a short victory.\" She hopes that the truce will be renewed to a permanent one.',NULL,NULL),(69654,64927,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/Long Live the Hip! - November 29, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-29 21:31:45','2023-11-29 21:07:35','This program is all about the power of silence. You hold the magic to preserve silence with just ten bucks a month. Now\'s the time to do it. You can commit to donate $10 a month to silencesounds.org for a year. If you can\'t commit, you can support the cause by taking a photo of your finger and encouraging others to do the same. Act now, and visit Silencesounds.ca to pledge your support. Or you can make a one time donation of whatever amount you want. Together we will create a symphony that resonates with generations to come',NULL,NULL),(69655,195,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/w6sbh9/Dementia13RadioShow_23_11_28.mp3','2023-11-29 22:54:17',287962512,'2023-11-30 00:10:20','2023-11-29 23:05:37','In this show, the narrator plays a selection of songs from the ELO catalog. He also plays music from the Tommy James and The Shondells, a band that was associated with the early Moog synthesizer. The show ends with music from a Moog synthesizer that the narrator used to record the Crimson and Clover album by the shonds. The narrator calls the Moog \"the early synthesizer sound\" that Tommy James used to call \"plastic music hen\" because the sound was so different from the sound of the original Moog.',NULL,NULL),(69656,102,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/End Credits - November 29, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 23:49:14','2023-11-29 23:06:15','This is the first episode of the new show \"End Credits\" on the campus and community station of the University of Guelph. It is hosted by Adam A Donaldson. He is joined by Tim Phillips. Tim and Adam discuss the ending of the movie. Adam says that this is a cliffhanger and that he is part of it. Tim says that his solo movie has been shelved. He says that it is because of co-operation. The show is called \"Mid-Credits\" and it is a local film show.',NULL,NULL),(69657,1464,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/Gryphon And Special Olympics Sports Show - November 29, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-29 23:32:15','2023-11-29 23:07:08','The second segment of the show is called \"Griffin and Special Olympics\" and it\'s all about sports. The first segment is about Griffin Sports and it has some of the most important news about the local sports scene.\n\nIt has Maya Graham as one of the team\'s top players, and she\'s also named the \"Griffin Locker Athlete of the Week\" . The men\'s and women\'s basketball teams are also in the top five in the region. The girls\' hockey team is also doing well, and the women\'d team is in first place overall. The other team, the Buffalo Bills, is having a tough time making the playoffs, according to the host.',NULL,NULL),(69658,13298,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/CFRU Selector - November 29, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-30 01:07:44','2023-11-30 01:07:44',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69659,197,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/j2quv9/phil_s_inn_nov_25_23b9v6f.mp3','2023-11-30 01:07:46',287962512,'2023-11-30 04:15:23','2023-11-30 03:05:36','The program opens with a song about harmony and spirituality. It\'s called \"Red Road\" and it refers to a life of balance and harmony. The song is a reference to the Hopi word koyaniskatsu, which means \"living a life in harmony with traditional values\" .\n\nThe program ends with a bit of music from the song. Sounds like the song is about balance, harmony and spiritual things. Check it out. It starts off with a little bit of a history lesson. The word \"red\" comes from the Native American word \"go\" which means harmony. Red Road is a way of life and harmony is associated with a life lived in harmony. Basically, the song describes a life that is balanced and harmonious. It sounds like this is a place where you can live a balanced life.',NULL,NULL),(69660,106,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/Trail Mix - November 29, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 03:48:47','2023-11-30 03:06:24','',NULL,NULL),(69661,105,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/B Siide Radio - November 29, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 05:49:50','2023-11-30 03:06:25','',NULL,NULL),(69662,107,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/29/Tone Zone - November 29, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-29 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-30 05:32:48','2023-11-30 05:06:31','This is the first Noel of the season on the Crooked Beat, and it\'s the first dub of the day. It\'s all rooted in reggae, and we\'re going to start dropping a bunch more. Dub Spencer, Trance Hill, and the anniversary collection from Green. Also, some good new music. We start off with a bunch of new music and then we drop some old music. Then we drop new music too. We drop some new music by Culture. And this is when Val, VP Radix, and Linval Thompson all come out.',NULL,NULL),(69663,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Wild Combination - November 30, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 07:26:56','2023-11-30 07:06:16','',NULL,NULL),(69664,219,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/h9yv6i/ES231129.mp3','2023-11-30 07:25:57',139938047,'2023-11-30 09:46:40','2023-11-30 09:05:41','This program is called Toronto Electric because it\'s the only one in Canada that uses an electric stage. It\'s also the one that uses the signal oscillator. The program is going to be shut down at the end of the month and they\'re leaving the electric stage behind for another one that doesn\'t need to be there.',NULL,NULL),(69665,97,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Wild Combination - November 30, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 09:29:24','2023-11-30 09:06:08','On this week\'s Democracy Now! program, Amy talks about how the University of Guelph\'s free skills training program can help people improve their job skills. The program also shows how listening to the science program We Know Some Things on Wednesdays can increase the number of shows on the program by up to a factor of ten. Also, if you\'re interested in running a public service announcement or a commercial on the show, you can contact the program\'s outreach team at CFRU for more information',NULL,NULL),(69666,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 30, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 15:47:16','2023-11-30 15:05:53','The Funky Flues doctor is back on the air. He\'s back with another song about how silence is a good thing. He also reminds listeners that it\'s time for them to commit to silence for a year. He asks listeners to pledge $10 a month to Silence for one year, which is about half the cost of a Spotify subscription. If you can\'t commit a month, there\'s a way to support the arts without committing a month.',NULL,NULL),(69667,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Here Today - November 30, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 07:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-30 15:31:05','2023-11-30 15:06:34','Aaron Badgley welcomes listeners to his show on CFRU-FM 93.3 and says that he\'s going to play some new music for the hour.\n\nHe\'ll be talking about a local musician named Corey Weeds who is also a producer. He has an album out called Home Cooking, which has a title track called \"Home Cooking\" which is really eloquent. The other artists on the show are: Len Mazzoni, Jenna Nation, The Beatles, Bernard Frazier, Mimo, and Deborah Fajalkovo. Aaron says that the Christmas music he\'ll play this year is going to be pretty good. The first song is by Jenna, who\'s a singer/songwriter. The second is by Len, who is a jazz musician. The third is by the Beatles, who have a new song called \"Now.\n\n\" The fourth is by Bernard Frazier who has a new album coming out in February or March. The fifth is by Mimo who is from Windsor, Ontario. The last song is a new film music video called \"Farewell for Now,\" which is a really nice piece of music. And the final song is from Deborah, who has been working on producing new music all over the world.',NULL,NULL),(69668,173,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/iuic47/Club_Ned_Dec_3_2023_podcast8w10g.mp3','2023-11-30 16:29:11',284131786,'2023-11-30 18:08:37','2023-11-30 17:05:21','',NULL,NULL),(69669,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Tales from the Bridge - November 30, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-30 17:51:16','2023-11-30 17:06:26','The Transgender Author and Musician Talk about the violin and writing. The author tells us that he picked up the violin as a way to confront his biggest fears and desires within music. He says that the violin is like a voice that finally reaches when it\'s time for him to be a trans man.\n\nWhen he\'s a trans woman , his voice drops to the level of a man\'s voice, but he can still play the violin because his voice finally reaches. He explains that he can sing through his voice because it finally reaches the point where he can be a man. The narrator says that writing allows him to take control of his narrative. It allows his characters to say things that he couldn\'t say otherwise.',NULL,NULL),(69670,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/FoodFarm Talk - November 30, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 17:32:35','2023-11-30 17:06:27','In this episode of Food Farm Talk, host Clinton Machuck speaks with Timothy Caulfield, a professor and a well-respected expert on a wide range of topics, from food to health to climate change. We learn that he is a professor in the law and public health departments at the University Alberta.\n\nHe is also an author, a public speaker, and an expert on Netflix. He discusses his passion for science and his involvement with the public sphere. He speaks of the lack of trust in the scientific community in general and in the food and health community in particular. He believes that this is a result of the widespread availability of new technology and new methods of production. He explains that the science is being produced in a time when people lack trust in its usefulness.',NULL,NULL),(69671,189,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/2s2zkf/VFTC_Nov29784d4.mp3','2023-11-30 18:30:42',282287040,'2023-11-30 20:12:36','2023-11-30 19:05:35','The guys are back from Aurelia and they\'re psyched to be back. They\'ve been waiting for a year and a half for them to come back. Kent and Larry have been back for about a year now, and Larry says it\'s been a year since they last saw each other.\n\nThe show they\'ve put on has a history and music theme. The first song is the \"Big Bang Theory\" theme song, and the second song is \"The Bare Naked Ladies\" by Billy Joel. The third song is a \"Who\'s Death\" by Marilyn Monroe, who died on August 5, 1962. They\'re about to play a few more songs when they stop. Kent says they\'ll play some more of the \"Arcade Fire in Joan\" by Al Stewart',NULL,NULL),(69672,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Bridging The Social Distance - November 30, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 19:49:09','2023-11-30 19:06:01','',NULL,NULL),(69673,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Democracy Now - November 30, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 19:30:21','2023-11-30 19:07:21','',NULL,NULL),(69674,113,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Android’s Dungeon - November 30, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-30 21:52:24','2023-11-30 21:06:42','The host takes a few minutes to talk about his involvement with the board game community. He says that he\'s grateful when he can play something and that he often goes out to play board games with his wife. But the board games don\'t happen as often as they once did. He feels like the train games did not kick off until recently, when he played them a lot.\n\nThe tricky part of playing board games is that they\'re extremely player driven, which means that everyone has to make some decisions in the game based on what the players want. If everyone is playing at once, then everyone loses their collective knowledge. But if everyone is learning together, then you get the best of both worlds.',NULL,NULL),(69675,13307,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/30/Eclectic Selections - November 30, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-30 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-30 21:31:24','2023-11-30 21:08:01','This week on Eclectic Selections, the host, Karim Mosna, is joined by a student from the University of Guelph named Maddie Stewart. The two talk about Chet Baker, and the show is live-streamed on YouTube. When the show started, Karim immediately wanted to know what was the origin of Chet\'s music, and Stewart explains that his father was a big fan. When he was looking for a new music, Stewart says, he decided to go into jazz. Stewart says Chet is a good guy, and that he\'s always been interested in music',NULL,NULL),(69676,205,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/d6i7ij/November_30th_2023_Music_at_High_Noon8lvu6.mp3','2023-11-30 21:39:24',228269056,'2023-12-01 01:06:49','2023-11-30 23:05:45','This week\'s program opens with a track from Outta Sight, a song from the recently released album Music That Kinda Losers, by Autogram. The music starts off with Born Rockers, then it moves on to Love Is for Fools, followed by Everclear, then Santa Monica, then Low of the Low, then Lonely One, then Elephant Stone, then Behind Those Eyes, then Fairy Boat Of the Mind, then Macco Road, then Adam And The Volumes, and finally Mother Tongues.',NULL,NULL),(69677,289,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/aa8pwd/The_Next_Stop_127agsh4.mp3','2023-11-30 22:49:46',271541035,'2023-12-01 00:47:27','2023-11-30 23:05:52','This is the 127th episode of the program. It is hosted by Sage Ranaldo and it airs on CIUT 99.5 FM. The program is free and can be listened to anywhere in the world. Some of the tracks are from the 1973 Western directed by Sam Peckinph and directed by Billy the Kid.\n\nThey have the most famous score from Bob Dylan, which is also one of the songs in the film. If you want to listen to the previous episodes, go to the next stop on the program and listen to them 