rse74h11.mp3','2023-12-04 01:06:06',431961989,'2023-12-04 04:09:25','2023-12-04 03:05:38','On this edition of the show, Ken Stower takes the listener through a selection of the music that he has recorded for the program. The first hour begins with Misumeina\'s song Jungi, which is followed by remixes of other songs by Tom Jakeiti, Baba Sazokos, Tommy Guerrero, White Sands, and then by Cattle. Ken says that he will announce an update on the Cattle project in a few weeks, but that they look forward to having him back on the show',NULL,NULL),(69752,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/03/Wind-Down - December 3, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-03 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 03:50:56','2023-12-04 03:06:32','The program begins with a description of the music featured on the show. The first song is from Flight Facilities featuring channel t Trey. The second is from Le Couleur featuring the song DIsre. The third is from Drama. The fourth is from Moon River featuring Gavin Gardner. The fifth is from Seishi She. The sixth is from New Chance and the seventh is from Lee Paradise.\n\nThe seventh is called Lilys Call. The eighth is from Little Dragon featuring all of the reach trims. The ninth is from Onion Kings of Otsego at University Brown in Asian American History. The song is titled No No Boy and it is from a record label called Smithsonian Folkways. The label is part of a research institute at the Smithsonian. It was founded in 1987. The label was established in 1987 by a family of Moses ash under the conditions that the institution continues Ashs policy of eating some notable artists.\n\nLeadbelly, Toronto Harlow Guthrie and now of course No Boy. Serra Willow tells us that he has two more songs to play for us. First, he\'ll play from Kat Clyde with her song Down Rounder I Feel It and the second will play from Feist with her album Multi-tudes with Hideout in the Open',NULL,NULL),(69753,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/03/Zombie Jamboree - December 3, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-03 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 03:33:42','2023-12-04 03:07:10','The first hour of the show starts off with a song by Beirut called \"So Many Plans\" . The second hour starts with \"Lemon Jelly\" and \"Negroid Tension\" and the third hour is \"Migraine\" with Kimi-Jabate on it.\n\nNext up is \"Bitter Sweet Morning\" , followed by \"Personality Surgery\" with Georg Turner . We\'ll hear from the UnDecidable with \"Clones\" and then we hear from \"Violents\" with \"Gone Daddy Gone\". We\'re all about mental health, which is a big topic at this point. The last song we hear is from \"Dan Hicks and The Hot Licks\", with their \"I Scare Myself\" and another from \"Melissa Leveaux\" with the track \"Simalu\" ). We\'ve got a final song to play and it\'s \"Sarah Willow and the Wind\" coming up next.',NULL,NULL),(69754,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/03/Through the Looking Glass - December 3, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-03 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 05:50:30','2023-12-04 05:06:38','Alice opens the show by introducing herself and inviting listeners to travel through the looking glass and listen to music wherever it takes them. She introduces herself as Alice, and then they go through the music together. The first artist they\'ll listen to is the Blues Anova\'s, a band she\'s been following since the band formed back in 2015 and who\'s become one of the most popular bands in Germany. The band has gone through a few lineup changes, but they\'ve become very popular in Germany since then. They played with Eric Clapton last year, and they\'re even touring with him this month. Alice\'s voice has changed a bit, but it\'s still okay.\n\nThey begin with a change in the direction of the show, which is to play some of the same music that you\'ve been hearing. The next artist is the Trashcans, who\'ve just released a new album called Live Now. They also have an EP called K- Tell, which has been posted on the Looking Glass Cfru.com. Next up is the Canadian band Ox, who have just released an album called . They have a song called Wash, which will be played on the show. And finally, we get a cover of Dylan\'s \"Blowin\' in the Wind\" by the band The Cat Power. They play a song with Alice.',NULL,NULL),(69755,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/03/Backtracks - December 3, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-03 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 05:30:27','2023-12-04 05:06:39','This is a very brief introduction to Backtracks by the host, Walter Walter. Backtracks is a music program which deals primarily with lost and obscure music from the golden age of rock and roll.\n\nHe will often throw in some new material if the show calls for it, but usually the music is from a theme, such as weather. In this case, the theme will be weather. The first song on the program is a song by the garage rock gurus Blue Slow BlueSnow Night. The song was one of the earliest to incorporate Middle Eastern influences into their garage music. The next song is from the Cleveland garage band It\'s cold outside. The choir. The final song is a single from Kim Fowley\'s band The Bush. The Bush is considered a notorious figure of early rock and Roll and garage music, and the song To die alone is considered quite a sex offender.\n\nThe show closes with a tribute to the late Shane McGowan, a punk musician who was at the forefront of the Irish punk movement in the late 1920s and early 1930s. He was known for reinvigoration of interest in punk folk especially in Irish music in a time when bombs and bullets were used against punk folk. The program ends with a song from John Cale, a former Velvet Underground member.',NULL,NULL),(69756,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 07:51:50','2023-12-04 07:07:10','The program begins with a brief break and then moves into the geographical spotlight segment. The program then resumes with a description of the show, which is hosted by Christopher Curry. The show features music by artists from countries around the world. The music is performed in a spotlight on each of the seven largest countries on the map. This spotlighting of countries is done on a deeper level than just the country itself, and also on each province or territory in a country. The segments of the program can be found on the CFRU website.',NULL,NULL),(69757,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/03/This Night Wounds Time - December 3, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-03 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 07:31:04','2023-12-04 07:07:10','The show is called \"This Night-Wounds Time,\" and it\'s all about music that is \"somewhat off-center\" . The music will be from \"off the beaten track,\" as Curry puts it. The first hour of the show will be devoted to that, and the second hour will be dedicated to the \"Geographic Spotlight Series,\" which is a series of special music spotlights on certain geographical regions of the world. For example, this week, the spotlight will be on the capital city of a particular province in Argentina.\n\nThe second hour of \"Geographical Spotlight\" will also include a re-broadcast of the previous week\'s show, which was not recorded in the CFRU archives because of a technical problem. This week, he\'s going to play a second rebroadcast, this time from 2 to 4:30, and then he\'ll play the first one from 2 until midnight.',NULL,NULL),(69758,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 02:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 02:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 09:52:52','2023-12-04 09:07:02','The show is back on the air, and the Host explains that he\'s decided to re-run the show because the previous week\'s edition didn\'t make it into the archives.\n\nHe\'s also going to make sure that the music on the show is the same as the music that he originally planned to play. The Host then points out that this is a bit of a coincidence, since he originally wanted to play the music for the Michiones first, and then the music from Hohoe later. But then he realized that he was wrong, and decided that he should play the Hohoe first. This is the first time that the Host has played the music he originally thought he was going to play, and this is the second time that he has played it. He reminds listeners that he did play the last song of the show, which was originally intended for the provinces of Canada, but then realized that it was a mistake to play it first. He says he\'ll play it again tonight, and he also says that the show will be rebroadcast again tomorrow.\n\nSo the Host says that if you missed the previous show, you can go to Upscill\'s 4Work.ca and check out what the University of Guelph has to offer. The University offers a wide range of jobs, including music production, live events, public service announcements and ads, and even live streams of the shows on YouTube and Soundcloud. If you want to get involved, email the Host',NULL,NULL),(69759,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 09:31:40','2023-12-04 09:07:02','In this program, the host of a local radio station, Christopher Curry, gives an introduction to a local musician from his home province, Argentina. The artist is Ramn Ayella, who was born in nearby Garupa in 1927 and is still alive. He is known as one of South America\'s greatest artists. He was invited to perform in Cuba in 1962, and he met with a fellow Argentinian, Che Guevara, who advised Ayella that his song, El Menzel, had been performed in the region of Sierra Maestra during the revolution in Cuba. Ayella\'s song, Ama Nacer En Missiones, is an original composition, and he apologizes for any inappropriate lyrics.',NULL,NULL),(69760,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 04:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 04:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 11:50:37','2023-12-04 11:07:16','This week\'s show opens with a description of the program. It\'s called \"Music on the Bus\" and it\'s a live music radio show that airs every Saturday on CFRU, the Canadian Free Public Broadcasting station. The program starts off by describing what\'s happening on the program tonight. We\'re hearing music from the province of Buenos Aires, and we\'re also hearing tracks by an artist named Zamba Kiildor.\n\nNext, we\'ll hear music from an Andean musician named Uri Ramos. Uri Ramos is from Humahuaque, Argentina, and he plays the bamboo flute. So we\'ve got a little bit of an introduction to the guy. The guy is a noted musician and composer who lives in the province and is known for his music. So listen for the program\'s ending. If you\'re interested in a commercial or public service announcement for your local business or organization, there\'s an ad package at the station that can be used to run the ad on the air.\n\nThe station also has a great website that\'s easy to navigate. There are lots of features like live streaming of all of our shows, searchable audio archives, and a donation page.',NULL,NULL),(69761,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/This Night Wounds Time - December 4, 2023 at 03:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 03:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 11:31:14','2023-12-04 11:07:17','The show begins with a discussion of the show\'s geographical focus and the musicians that will be featured there. It turns out that the show will be a showcase of music from the region of Hohoe, Argentina. The music featured will be by an artist named Michaela Cienegui, a quilla flute player, dancer, composer, and teacher. She is from a quilera indigenous community in Salta province, Argentina, but she is also a musician, a teacher, and a luthier. She grew up in Tilcara, in Hohoe province, and she is one of the first indigenous women to play the flute.\n\nThe instrument is a male-only instrument. She has two albums, one of which is dedicated to the show. The other is dedicated specifically to a singer named Toms Lipan, a singer from the Aymara indigenous community. The song is called \"Coesta de Lipan,\" which means \"Covenant Slope. The name of the river is unknown, but it is thought to be a clearing between hills, \"more or less zigzagging.\" The name is also associated with National Route 52, a highway that runs through the area. The show concludes with a description of Lipan Slope.',NULL,NULL),(69766,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - December 4, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 15:47:08','2023-12-04 15:05:54','',NULL,NULL),(69767,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Here Today - December 4, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 15:29:17','2023-12-04 15:06:31','Aaron Badgley is back on the program to talk about some new music. He\'s going to start off with Fyokovich, who\'s putting out some great music. Then he\'s got Alan Doyle\'s band with St. Johns Waltz, from a tribute album to a Newfoundland artist named Ron Hines.\n\nThen there\'s a band called The Moons of Jupiter, who are from England. Aaron plays some songs from their EP and then he plays a song from their upcoming self-titled album. He also plays songs from the Beatles from Liverpool, Dirty Hurricane, and a song by a band from Toronto named The Gryphons. Aaron says he loves these bands because they\'re hard-driving, rock-and-roll. He says they\'ve got a new single out called Christmas Is Coming, which is a really great song. Then they have a new album out called Town, and he says it\'s good that Elliott Brood is back with it. Aaron also says he fell into the Gryphons\' music from the first song he heard on their debut album, Like Gary Newman.',NULL,NULL),(69768,164,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ijzf8d/BEYOND_UN_Dec_4th6qkqu.mp3','2023-12-04 16:07:41',37311353,'2023-12-04 18:10:06','2023-12-04 17:05:22','In this edition of Beyond The Headlines, host Kimberly Watata introduces you to a new program called Beyond the Headslines.\n\nIt\'s a weekly current affairs show that takes you \"beyond the headlines\" of your daily news. We\'re talking about the United Nations\' Sustainable Development Goals, or SDGs, which are ambitious goals to improve health and education and reduce inequality. The SDGs were agreed upon by 193 countries in 2015, and are supposed to be a blueprint for peace, prosperity, and economic growth. Now that they\'re 2023, the \"clock is ticking\" and the goal to 2030 is \"at its halfway point\" . The question is whether or not the goals are still within reach, or whether it\'s an impossible dream. This week, we\'ll hear from our young delegates at the High-Level Political Forum on SDGs, who answer the question. They\'re here to tell you that the SDGs still have time to achieve their goals. They also talk about the high-level political Forum, where they\'ve been invited to discuss the SDGs with other delegates from around the world.\n\nOur first speaker is Jo, who works for Deloitte as a consultant on human services for the public sector. He\'s here to chat about the SDGs and how Canada has been implementing them. Jo says that the Canadian delegation at the high level political forum presented their country\'s progress on many of these goals, and he was impressed by how honest they were about where they were',NULL,NULL),(69769,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Breezy Breakfast Radio - December 4, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 17:50:08','2023-12-04 17:06:05','The meeting ends with the announcement that there is a meeting of the Board of Trustees on Tuesday, December 25th. The meeting will be followed by a town hall style meeting. The next morning, the board will meet to discuss the report of the committee.\n\nThe report is critical of the government for failing to provide adequate food for the poor and vulnerable. The group will discuss how the government can improve access to food for all. The board will also discuss the creation of a food security committee, a committee that will consist of representatives from the government, the community, and non-profit organizations.',NULL,NULL),(69770,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Breezy Breakfast Radio - December 4, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 05:18:04','2023-12-04 17:06:06','Discussion on the need for food security. Guelph is blessed with a good number of food service providers. ',NULL,NULL),(69771,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Worst Responders - December 4, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-04 19:48:35','2023-12-04 19:07:29','',NULL,NULL),(69772,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Democracy Now - December 4, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 19:28:12','2023-12-04 19:07:30','',NULL,NULL),(69773,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fv8kn3/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Dec_6_2023_podcast8jlox.mp3','2023-12-04 19:10:28',275448684,'2023-12-04 21:29:00','2023-12-04 21:05:38','The narrator explains the concept of \"karma,\" or the \"effect\" of one\'s actions. He explains that if you treat someone well, they\'ll be more likely to do something nice than if they\'re treated poorly. So, if you give someone a bad vibe, they will be less likely to be nice to someone else. Even though there are lots of people, the social circle is much smaller when you\'re down to it.\n\nSo even though there may be thousands of people who get exposed to the \"chain reaction,\" they won\'t all be the same person for a long, long time. The narrator adds that this is why he tries to support farmers, because if you\'ve got a farm, you\'ll probably want to be a farmer.',NULL,NULL),(69774,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/CFRU Playlist - December 4, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 21:05:52','2023-12-04 21:05:52',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69775,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - December 4, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-04 23:31:15','2023-12-04 23:05:53','In this episode, we learn more about the music being played in the studio. The narrator says that he wants to acknowledge and respect the traditional territories and the local Indigenous communities from which the music is being played. He also acknowledges that many of the music elements featured originated from the Black community adapting elements of their own culture under circumstances of oppression over the centuries past and present time. He thanks the Black music community for their contribution to the popular alternative music sphere. He concludes by saying that he is feeling better after contracting a seasonal illness the last few days.\n\nHe says he wanted to finish a piece that he had to fade off in the previous live session. He finishes off the session by saying he is going to play a collaboration with a group called Dirty Projectors, followed by the group Shun Shun, the Gordy Gordon band, the Wu band, and the Laura Mish band. He is also joined by two other guests, Charity Cruz and Isaiah Farabahksh. They are both listeners to the Sentinels Marvelous Kaleidoscope, a program that airs on CFRU\'s 93.3FM in Guelph. The first track they play is from the album Bit Orca by the band. They begin their first grand set with the song.',NULL,NULL),(69776,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Big Sis Radio - December 4, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 04:32:16','2023-12-05 01:05:48','On this episode of Big Sis, Cece tells us that she wishes more people would actually keep their conversations with strangers real.\n\nShe tells us about a new article that suggests that when we\'re asked to predict the awkwardness of a conversation, we underestimate the happiness we\'ll feel when we actually have a genuine conversation with someone. And when we are asked to guess how much we care about a stranger, we tend to guess that they\'ll care less about us than they actually do. Brain Snack: This research article was published in 2022 and was titled \"Overly Shallow Miscalibrated expectations create a barrier to deeper conversation.\" In other words, when people predict how awkward it\'s going to be, they\'re guessing that they won\'t care about their own feelings, and that they will just think about how other people will react to their comments.\n\nSo when we engage in deeper conversation with people we know, the thinking goes, we feel more connected than we do when we talk about the \"usual, more shallow\" stuff. Cece then shows us the latest track from a band called Fontaine\'s Dc off their latest record, Skinty-Fya. The band\'s name means \"doomed deer\" in Irish. The album cover features a giant deer inside an ominous looking animal.',NULL,NULL),(69777,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/to know the land - December 4, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 04:40:45','2023-12-05 01:05:58','A decolonizing poet from the Chippewa First Nation in the Thames Valley and is an Ojibewa or Anishinabe man. He is an Irish man who honors both his native and his European ancestry. The first thing he says is that he\'s giving a workshop on \"decolonizing language\" at a Spoken Word Finals in Guelph.\n\nThe audience is listening, and the he has a few questions for them. First, he wants to know what it means to \"declassify\" our language. He says that it\'s an English question, and that\'s basically the way he and his audience use the word. The English language, he says, was stolen from the native people and the languages that were used by them.\n\nHe wants to talk about this for a second, because what happens if you steal someone else\'s language. Part of the way that language is developed is that it has to be established and developed in the context of the people who live and speak it. The people who have been in the colonial society can\'t believe that their language was stolen, but it can be \"dismantling or disorienting.\"',NULL,NULL),(69778,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Blues Around the Block - December 4, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 04:08:14','2023-12-05 03:06:07','The host of the show, named Dee Mac, welcomes listeners to the program and encourages them to share their thoughts on the show with him by sending him an e-mail at macdee@calf.\n\nca. The program begins with a description of the crime that has taken place in the city. The show\'s first listener, named Sylvia Dee, tells the story of how he pawned his clothes to pay his rent. Then he and another listener discuss the music that has been released in the wake of the crimes. They compare the various acts and hear from the band members that they have had a hard time keeping up with the latest news.',NULL,NULL),(69779,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Blues Around the Block - December 4, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 03:50:19','2023-12-05 03:06:08','Mac Dee, host of the popular program \"Blues Around the Block\" on CFRU.org, takes listeners on a tour of the best of the blues, beginning with a listen to the music of Mike Griffin and his band. He then switches gears to a selection of songs from the \"Durham County Poets,\" \"Girl of My Dreams,\" \"Hoot and Holler,\" \"The Hog Town All-Stars,\" \"Fats Domino,\" and \"Coal Mining Blues\" by Matt Anderson. Mac Dee concludes the show with two songs about coal mining, one by Esqua Wilson and Tom Wilson.',NULL,NULL),(69780,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Ripcord Radio - December 4, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 05:54:59','2023-12-05 05:05:47','This is the second hour of the program and it\'s called \"Punk Rock\" on the program. This time, the program is going to be all Canadian music.\n\nIt\'s going to start with a bunch of music outside of Canada, mostly from punk bands that formed in the United States and Europe during the same time period. The first band we\'re going to hear is called X with Revolution and the second band is called Aspirations. Aspirations is the name of the first band\'s first album and Aspirations was released in October of 1979, a few months before the first one was released. Next up is a band called Basque with Perks and the first single is from their new album, Pain without Hope of Healing. The band is named after the city of Kitchener in Ontario. They\'re also releasing an album called No Funeral Sound in the next few months.\n\nThe next band we hear is The Dominion and the latest single is called No Fate. The group is from Southern Ontario and their members are all spread out between Ajax, Guelph, Caledon, and Toronto. The last band we heard is called Reaper with Satanic Prophesies and they released their first full length album last year. Then we hear Blue Oil\'s song Celebration.',NULL,NULL),(69781,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/The Deep House Project - December 4, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 05:32:23','2023-12-05 05:05:53','In this week\'s show, the CFRU staff discusses the university\'s decision to close the VIS Gallery and the ways in which the university will respond to the public outcry. They also discuss some of the research they\'re doing on older adults and youth during the pandemic. The team is conducting a study of young and older adults\' experiences during the Co-Impacted Volcano Virus-19 pandemic.\n\nThey\'re looking for people who are 5 to 65 years old and want to participate in the study. If you want to learn more about this study, visit the University of Guelph\'s website slash Life in Co-Isolated Pandemic. The CFRU team also announces its Best of 2022 concert. They play a lot of songs from the year, including Bob Moses\'s \"Hanging On,\" Sunshine, \"Sons of Maria,\" \"Machiavellian Princess,\" \"Moxie,\" \"The Fool,\" \"Malabar Princess,\" and \"Sunshine,\" among others. The show closes with \"La Troz,\" a song by Murney, Sultan, and Shepherd.',NULL,NULL),(69782,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/04/Back in the USSR - December 4, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-04 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 07:51:42','2023-12-05 07:06:31','This program is an hour-long program that airs on CFRU, the communist station in Canada, on the anniversary of the October 20th, 1956, Great Socialist Revolution.\n\nIt\'s a program about heroic people and their armed forces. The program opens with a long speech by a member of the Communist Party, praising the achievements of the revolutionary movement. The speaker then goes on to talk about the tragedy in the Middle East. He\'s talking about the war in the Gaza Strip, which has been going on for the past seven days. The ceasefire ended on Friday, and Israel is once again bombing the Gaza strip. There are hundreds of dead civilians in the war. This is horrifying. The narrator says that it\'s hard to believe that war crimes are piling up so quickly. He',NULL,NULL),(69783,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Rainbow Country - December 5, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 07:31:24','2023-12-05 07:07:45','Kinga joins host Mark Tara to share his story on Canada\'s first dance radio show, called Rainbow Country. The show is produced and hosted by Mark Tara. He is also the producer and host of the show. He and his team have been growing the show into a national syndicated show and a number one podcast on Podomatic.com.',NULL,NULL),(69784,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Rainbow Country - December 5, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 09:27:49','2023-12-05 09:07:09','Welcome to another episode of Rainbow Country. This time, it\'s a police officer named Danielle Botno. He\'s also known as \"LGBT cop\" and he\'s the guy who\'s on your side when you go out with your friends. He and his friend are going to listen to music from artists from the LGBT community. They\'re going to hear tracks from acapella, acaplone, electronic, lesbian, rock, tribal, and so on. And this is going to be a long, long show.',NULL,NULL),(69785,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/CFRU Playlist - December 5, 2023 at 06:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 06:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 13:05:52','2023-12-05 13:05:52',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69786,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - December 5, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 15:26:51','2023-12-05 15:06:14','This is a very brief, very exclusive, very brief program that we\'ve just heard from a very special guest, the soul singer, \"Morning Soul Shake Up\" .\n\nHe\'s on his way to a gig as a DJ on a local community radio station in Guelph, Canada. He tells us that he\'s been thinking about this program and wants to tell you about it. He says that he wants to be a part of this program because it\'s very soul-centric. He wants to make sure that everyone is listening to this program. The program is hosted by the wonderful guy from CFRU, a 250 watt FM station. The guy talks about how awesome his station is and how you can listen to it anywhere in the world. He also says that you can donate to the program and learn more about how to get involved with the station.',NULL,NULL),(69787,167,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5d2jxx/December_1st_2023_Funky_Fridays64x75.mp3','2023-12-05 15:22:02',431961989,'2023-12-05 18:50:08','2023-12-05 17:05:16','The show starts off with a cover of a Jefferson Airplane song called White Rabbit, which George Benson did on his second album. Benson\'s arranger, Don Sibiske, arranged the song. Benson also covers a song called Walk Tall, which Esther Morrow and Joseph Zawinow wrote for him. The show ends with a Latin pop band called Black Sugar from Peru, who did a killer cover called Don\'t you worry a little bit. Pete and the Funky Fridays crew talk about their first show.',NULL,NULL),(69788,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/dpx4k4/December_2nd_2023_The_Minx_Sessionsavlj8.mp3','2023-12-05 15:23:58',287962512,'2023-12-05 18:25:34','2023-12-05 17:05:39','The Ming Sessions is pleased to announce that it has raised a significant sum of money in order to support its independent programming. The show begins with a thank you from the host, who goes on to say that the show will continue to be a source of great independent music. He will be playing some new music and introducing some of the old school stuff that he has been listening to recently. He also introduces some new releases and says that if you have not already listened to the show, you can do so now. The program concludes with the announcement that they are going to play some more music from the show.',NULL,NULL),(69789,247,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/hz34xc/December_2nd_2023_Calling_All_Bluesb2h5r.mp3','2023-12-05 15:25:19',143961989,'2023-12-05 18:08:38','2023-12-05 17:05:41','Calling All Blues This is the second part of a two-part interview with Blues Doctor, host and producer of the popular music show, which airs every Saturday on CIUT 99.\n\n5 in Toronto and on the web. In the first part of the interview, the Blues Doctor describes his childhood and his personal journey toward the blues. He says that he discovered the blues in popular music when he listened to local bands like the Lighthouse and the Crowbar. He also mentions that Elton John was a big fan of the music, especially of his song \"Honky Chateau\" which was named after Long John Baldy. The music also includes a song by another local band called Blood, Sweat, and Tears.',NULL,NULL),(69790,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Solipsistic Retreat - December 5, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 17:49:42','2023-12-05 17:07:51','In this special edition of the host, the underground punk opens by thanking Bri Webb for her years of service to CFRU. He thanks her for her latest album, which is at number one in the CFRU music charts. He also thanks the station for bringing the show to the community.\n\nHe says that he\'s not even in Guelph, but he was born there and raised. He explains that everything in the city of Guelph is changing, just like the rest of the country. He compares this to Carl Marx\'s theory of constant improvement, which says that all that is solid dissolves into air. He adds that it\'s the \"frivolousness\" of an economy that is based on \"constant improvement\" . He argues that people are buying stuff that isn\'t actually there.\n\nThe only way to know that you\'re buying the right stuff is to vote for it. Bri doesn\'t want to ask for money, though, and says that it is important to give it to friends. He plays a song called \"Breakdown\" by the AP Buzzcocks, which he says is their best song, but it is not included on any of their other compilations. He thinks that the song is \"first class junk\" , which means that it was made by an English man. The song is one of many that the band uses to change the track listing of other songs so that when a band does something, it will appear on the next',NULL,NULL),(69791,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Solipsistic Retreat - December 5, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 17:29:05','2023-12-05 17:07:52','The host starts off by thanking the Olsen twins for their hard work, and then turns to his friend, Aubrey Hodges. He tells us that he\'s been living in a cave in the woods for the last few years, and he wants to get out of it.\n\nHe wants his due, so he gives away all of his stuff for free on Bandcamp. He gives us a shout-out to the guy who\'s made ambient music for the past 30 years. He\'s also got a son who plays with his son, so they make music together. He does all sorts of weird stuff, too, and we\'re just going to listen to it for free. The Underground Guy doesn\'t own any of the stuff that\'s being played on Bandcamp, because he can\'t really afford it. So he says that if you go to a festival and pay him, you can have all the music he plays for free, even if it\'s just for a few hours. And then, if you\'re a fan of his son\'s music, he\'ll give you all of the music that he makes for free as well.\n\nSo we\'ll check it out for our listeners. It turns out that the Underground Guy isn\'t a big fan of the Nintendo Switch. He says that even if he did own a Nintendo Switch, he wouldn\'t be able to afford to buy it, because it would be too expensive. So, if someone',NULL,NULL),(69792,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Bridging The Social Distance - December 5, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 19:47:37','2023-12-05 19:06:02','This interview with the elderly resident of the River Cycline is an introduction to his life at the facility.\n\nHe tells us that he is 80 years old and that he has been there for four months. He says that he likes every day to be different, because it gives him the opportunity to stay connected to people and to experience new things. He likes to participate in the exercise and social activities that are offered there, and he is interested in reading and listening to music. He explains that he had a companion that wanted to walk him every day, but that now he is with his sister and she is enjoying his company, so he doesn\'t worry about him anymore. He also explains that the companion is a Lassa Absa, a breed of dog that was developed from the Far East, and that it is very sociable and likes to be walked.\n\nHe is the first he has seen of this breed, and his mother had one, too. Now that his sister is with him, it is good to stay a part of the exercise program to keep his body going. He does not know if he will take his companion back from his sister, but he does say that they have formed a special relationship, and so he will probably get a new companion when he gets older.',NULL,NULL),(69793,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Democracy Now - December 5, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 19:27:53','2023-12-05 19:07:44','Amy Goodman tells us that she',NULL,NULL),(69794,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - December 5, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-05 21:50:49','2023-12-05 21:06:34','This is a very brief program about the life and times of Shane McGowan, an Irish musician who fronted a Celtic punk band called The PopoAgs from 1982 until 1991. He went on to form The Popes, which reunited him in 1992 and he would front the band for six years.\n\nThen he formed the band The Snake in 1994 and they played a song in tribute to him. He died on Thursday of a broken hip and an inflammation of his brain. Back in March, the program returned after three years of a pandemic. This time the program starts with a song by a Canadian rock quartet from their latest release Steady. They play a song from their second album Stand in Fire. They also play songs from their third and fourth albums. The program ends with the song from Los Speakers, an active band from 1963 to 1969.',NULL,NULL),(69795,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Under the Needle - December 5, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 21:30:17','2023-12-05 21:07:21','On this edition of Live On KEXP, the show celebrates the lineage of Black Belt Eagle scout, Catherine Paul or Catherine Paul. Catherine Paul is an artist who records in her native Swinomish language. Her latest album is called The Land, the Water, and the Sky.\n\nIt\'s her third full length album and her first album in a long time. Her songs are all about her return home after having spent time in Portland or in the ancestral homeland of the Chinook tribe or the Clackams tribe. KEXP\'s DJ, Cheryl Waters, asks Catherine Paul why she wanted to move home after the pandemic. Catherine says she always wanted to go on tour and then move back home. When her parents needed help during the pandemic, she decided to move back to her hometown. Her husband, her stepchildren, and her band decided they were going to move as well. Catherine explains that she spent a lot time outside during the time of the pandemic because she had a much closer connection to her home and to her community.',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO `episodes` VALUES (69796,155,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/fqd3ds/DrMouth_CIUTshow_dec4_2023_fullshow.mp3','2023-12-05 22:33:37',284290688,'2023-12-06 00:32:30','2023-12-05 23:05:20','Dr. Mouth, James Brown, and a bunch of other local musicians perform at a charity rock concert. The band starts off with a cover of a punk song by Saint, and then they start to do their own songs. Then James Clark finally drops his new album, Under the Lamp-shade. He plays the whole thing in its entirety, then plays some other songs, and it\'s clear that he\'s playing like a real rock star. The b side of one of his earlier albums is on this one, which is also on his new one.',NULL,NULL),(69797,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/kuctwd/December_1_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow88liz.mp3','2023-12-05 22:01:15',287962512,'2023-12-06 00:07:40','2023-12-05 23:05:43','',NULL,NULL),(69798,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Silver Screen Dream Machine - December 5, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 23:48:47','2023-12-05 23:07:21','This week\'s program is called \"Silver Screen Dream Machine\" and it\'s produced by the folks at CFRU 98.3FM in Guelph, Ontario. The program is described as a show about movies, music, and other moving-media.\n\nThe show\'s host, Leonard Squosins, introduces us to the program and tells us about some of the music he\'s been listening to recently. He starts off by playing music from the buddy cop film \"Bon Cop Bad Cop\" and its sequel, \"Bon-Cop Bad Cop 2.\" He then goes on to play music from two other films: \"Falls Around Her,\" and \"Shades of History.\" He also tells us that he\'ll start a tribute to two long-time Sesame Street characters, Bob Johnson and Bob McGrath, who both died in December. Jim Henson\'s birthday falls on May 30th, 2020 and the program will be celebrating that day with a month-long tribute to him starting in May 2020.\n\nJim\'s death was postponed by a month to May 30, 2020, and the monthlong tribute was extended to two other Sesame Street cast-members who died in 2017: Luis Delgado, who played Fix-It Shop owner, and Bob Johnson, who was the music teacher on the show. Jim explains that he plans to start a separate tribute to both of them around the anniversaries of their deaths. Jim also talks about a song he played for the program: \"I Was Afraid of Nothing.\" It\'',NULL,NULL),(69799,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/A Multilingual Affair - December 5, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-05 23:34:12','2023-12-05 23:07:35','This is a brief program from the show, which takes place in Guelph, Canada. It is co-hosted by Istai Sogadawu and Takeyce. The program is titled \"A Good Day, A Multilingual Affair\" and it is part of the \"Le Monde Sperant\" series. This program is all about gratitude and expressing love for people. The theme for the program is \"let them\" and this is what the song is about. The song is called \"Mana\" and the lyrics are from Mexico. The music is also very good.',NULL,NULL),(69800,91,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Tuesday at 5 - December 5, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 17:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-06 01:46:46','2023-12-06 01:06:09','Dee Mac, the host of CFRU\'s live music program, introduces us to the show\'s guests. He tells us that if they make the program through December, they\'ll be okay.\n\nHe also tells us about the death of Pogues singer-songwriter, Shane McCowan. He\'s been ill for some time, but his hits include \"The Fairy Tale of NYC\" and \"A Rainy Night in London,\" which are both \"traditional stomping Irish music\" with the \"crashing chords\" of punk. The song is a classic. The band\'s greatest achievement was to bring together traditional Irish music with \"the crashing chords of north London punk\" . Like Brendan Behan, Dylan Thomas, and other Celtic musicians, Shane was an alcoholic who was also a great writer.\n\nBetween the years of 1984 and 1990, the band released a total of five albums with their hits, including \"A Fair of Brown eyes\" and the \"Aryday Night in Soho,\" which were both \"praised as classics.\" Christy McColl, the Pogue\'s lead singer and songwriter, worked with the band on the song \"Fairytale of New York,\" which made the song number two on the Billboard Hot 100 and became a Christmas tradition.',NULL,NULL),(69801,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Down the Rabbit Hole - December 5, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 01:28:38','2023-12-06 01:07:11','The narrator continues his story of the month. He begins with a song from the album of jazz drummer Charles Mingus, \"Minus Atum.\" The narrator says he\'s been trying to improve his technique of playing the drums. Next, the narrator listens to two songs from El Reyne\'s new album, \"I Killed Your Dog.\n\n\" Next, he listens to \"New Years Unresolution,\" an album about the coming year. Finally, he picks \"Uncertainty Principle,\" a new album by the Canadian musician, \"Eleanor Reyne.\" He\'s really into this one. The narrator doesn\'t know how much he\'ll listen to it yet, but he likes the lyrics and the music. Next up, he talks about the band Son-the-Kill-Moon. The band\'s song, \"Ben\'s my Friend,\" is about a guy named \"Son Kill Moon,\" whose name means \"boxer.\n\n\" The song is pretty good, and the narrator thinks it sounds like someone in his room or his garage. He also talks about a book he\'d been reading, \"Stream of Consciousness,\" by Clarice . The book deals with a girl named Nelly, who has grown up and is now in her adult years. She has thoughts that she\'s shared with the narrator, who\'s also been thinking about Virginia Woolf. Nelly is also reading about the idea that ideas are sometimes just products of time, and that people should interpret them',NULL,NULL),(69802,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Let’s Get Lost - December 5, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 03:46:21','2023-12-06 03:06:03','Scott introduces himself as a new student at the university and introduces himself to the other students and staff as Scott. He explains that he is from Toronto and that he works for a record label called \"Telephone Explosion.\" The label brings in a lot of new music from artists around the world. He tells the students about some of the artists who are on the label, and they can listen to each artist\'s work on the \"Let\'s get Lost\" program on the university\'s website.\n\nHe also introduces the students to Kate Gentile, who has a new triple album out on Pi records called \"Find Letter X.\" She also has a live band playing on the track \"In Casks.\" She is a drummer, a composer, a vibes player, and a producer. The band is made up of Kim Kast, Matt Mitchell, and Jeremy Vener.',NULL,NULL),(69803,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/New or Never - December 5, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 03:27:39','2023-12-06 03:07:01','The first song of the evening is by Kenny Anderson, a Scottish singer-songwriter. Anderson\'s band, the Bearskins, is a rock band from Elora, Spain.\n\nThe second song is by Andre 3000, an American rapper. The third song is from New Blue Sun, an Atlanta-based hip-hop band. The fourth song is taken from the second song, by Daneshav Sakha, a Russian Jewish singer songwriter. The fifth song is a folk song by Anna Beckerman, a Glenn artist. The sixth song is an alt-rock song by Stella, an Irish-Canadian musician.\n\nThe seventh is a post punk song by Ghost Vines. The eighth song is the psychedelic song Legba, the ninth is a dance track by Davey, the tenth is a full-length album by Datura 4, the eleventh is a song by Aura, the twelfth is a piece of music by Pauline .',NULL,NULL),(69804,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Let’s Get Lost - December 5, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 06:07:37','2023-12-06 05:05:58','The show starts off with Morpho, a track from Beyond Dragons, an album by an international saxophonist named Angelicasscher. Before that, Steve Lehman plays the track Speed Freeze Part II from Ex Machina, a project by an American musician named Maurice Luca. Then Kate Gentile plays In Casks from her new album, Find Letter X. Then, the show ends with Henry Threadgill\'s latest album, The Other One, which is called Movement 3.\n\nAs for the show\'s merchandise section, CFRU has a new line of t-shirt, sweaters, hats, and charging cables. Students get a 30% discount. CFRU also has a program called Industry Radio Tactics, which airs every Friday from midnight to midnight. This program is dedicated to interviews of the finest artists in music. The program begins with a track by an actress named LXXX-8, from her latest release. The piece is called Hit Thatd',NULL,NULL),(69805,95,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/05/Humanoid Radio - December 5, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-05 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 05:47:07','2023-12-06 05:05:59','On this edition of Humanoid, Mike plays a track from his latest album, \"The Space Between.\" The name of this track is self-aware, which means, \"I\'m aware.\" He tells us that he was born in the West and that his father always referred to the West as the \"last of the best.\n\n\" The second segment of the program begins with a Drum Machine Mike track called \"Self Aware.\" This is the second of many tracks that Mike will play this evening. They begin with Matmos off \"The Return to Archive\" of \"Michelle Banabila,\" followed by DJ Shadow\'s \"Action Adventure,\" and a piece called \"Craig Ingalls Wrightson.\" Then they hear \"The Best West,\" \"Enacted Off the Remembering Maronie OST,\" \"Barry Can\'t,\" and \"Goating of Think.\" The program concludes with \"Kimi Kwat,\" which translates to \"Wild Horses.\"',NULL,NULL),(69806,69374,'https://archiv