e also want to send out a shout-out to all the people who submitted poetry for the November Open Mic. That\'s it, folks. The December Open Mic is coming up and we need poets to submit their work by December 20th. If you\'re interested,',NULL,NULL),(69810,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/06/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - December 6, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-06 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 15:27:15','2023-12-06 15:06:04','',NULL,NULL),(69811,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/06/CFRU Playlist - December 6, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-06 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-06 15:06:05','2023-12-06 15:06:05',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69812,159,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5wjpiy/CAREER_-_CareerBuzzCIUTfinaldecember0620237qcjd.mp3','2023-12-06 16:14:00',86294314,'2023-12-06 19:11:48','2023-12-06 17:05:17','In this episode, Mark Franklin, a professional career counselor, and the executive director of the Canadian Association of Film and Television Presenters, host a special program called \"Career Buzz.\" In this program, Mark discusses the challenges facing professionals in the entertainment industry. In the year 2023, a strike by the American and Canadian actors resulted in a reduction in income for film and television professionals. To overcome these challenges, the Canadian Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences and the Canadian Film Board have teamed up to create a special series of career-boosting opportunities for entertainment professionals.\n\nThe first of these opportunities is to feature the stories of professionals who have found alternative income-generating activities. The second part of the program will feature the story of Tony, a painter who has found a way to make a living as an actor. The third of these career-building opportunities is with the interview of Birgitta, an actor who is also a coach, a facilitator, and a media expert. Birgitta\'s career is still going strong even though she has already been an actor for many years. Her husband and she own a production company that produces plays, and she also does audio books. She has had her agent for over twenty years and still gets great opportunities to shoot things. She says she\'s becoming a better actor and performer. She\'s also wearing multiple hats in her career.',NULL,NULL),(69813,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/nwud5k/December_6_2023_Global_Rhythmsb7nxo.mp3','2023-12-06 15:04:21',431961989,'2023-12-06 18:51:33','2023-12-06 17:05:19','In this episode of the program, Ken Stowar tells the listeners that they can get a free copy of the show after the program ends at 10am the next morning. He also thanks all of the listeners who have made donations to the campaign. He tells them that the campaign now sits at 87% of its goal of $100K.\n\nHe then goes to the music and tells listeners about some of the artists featured on the show. First up is the London Afro-beat Collective, an outfit made up of eight members hailing from the Congo, Italy New Zealand England France and the Argentina. They play a mix of funk jazz and Latin sounds. Next up is Zelle Sizko, a vocalist and choras player from Montreal, with vocalist and chorra player Jelly Tappa and vocalist Brenda Naffet. Then there\'s The Jolly Boys , a group that\'s been around for over 70 years. They\'re still together even though some members have already passed away. Ken also tells listeners that Angelique Kijo is playing a song called \"Once in a Lifetime\" from her latest release. She\'s originally from Benin and we first heard of her in 1991.',NULL,NULL),(69814,195,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8fke6e/Dementia13RadioShow_23_12_05.mp3','2023-12-06 15:24:44',287962512,'2023-12-06 18:31:17','2023-12-06 17:05:33','Co-founder of Guess Who Chad Allen and founding member of BTO Miles Goodwin have both recently passed away. The program tonight will be a bittersweet affair, as it will feature music from both of these bands. To thank the listeners for their generous support, th