rding of his first symphony, an Oboe Concerto. This symphony is conducted by the Royal Philharmonic\'s Meyer Friedman, and it is the shortest of the four symphonies that the composer wrote. The musicologist explains that the music of the late 20th century was one of \"the most extensive musical individualities\" in the twentieth century. However, there has been a \"constant conflict\" about how good the composer\'s music has ever been since.\n\nThe last ten years have brought the end to this conflict, and now there are recordings of all of his works on all sides.',NULL,NULL),(69884,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/09/Sound Magic - December 9, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-09 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-09 21:27:54','2023-12-09 21:06:44','In this program, Michael plays some of the English music of Charles Hubert Parry, a British composer of the Romantic era who wrote symphonies. Parry wrote only five symphonies, but he is considered one of the fathers of English Romanticism. The fourth symphony of Parry is the only recorded version of the symphony out of all the versions that have been made. The second part of the program is devoted to the music of Vaughan Williams, a mid-20th-century English composer who is considered to be one of music\'s greats.',NULL,NULL),(69885,139,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/09/Bel Araby with CAWA - December 9, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-09 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-09 23:50:33','2023-12-09 23:06:49','This is the first of many updates we\'re going to get from the Guelph branch of the Canadian Free Press. In this one, we\'ll tell you that meta products like Facebook and Instagram are blocking news from Canadians because of Bill C-18. We\'re also going to tell you why you can\'t access our social feeds on Facebook and on Instagram. We encourage you to sign up for the Free Press\'s newsletter to stay up to date with the latest news.\n\nThe Guelph branch\'s political advisor, Lloyd Longfield, is also on board with this plan. He\'s going to write a letter to all the members of Parliament to make sure that they\'re all on the same page.',NULL,NULL),(69886,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/09/Caribbean Anthology - December 9, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-09 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-09 23:27:20','2023-12-09 23:06:50','The next day, the group heads back to the office to discuss the business case for entrepreneurship. They\'ve heard that many people come to Toronto to find the best produce and seasonings. They want to buy fish from the Guyanese market, but they have to travel all the way to the market in order to buy the fish they want. The idea is that if the city can provide entrepreneurship programs to people who come from different ethnic backgrounds, they\'ll be able to start business that promotes their own culture.',NULL,NULL),(69887,141,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/09/Alternativa Latinoamericana - December 9, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-09 18:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-10 01:06:53','2023-12-10 01:06:53',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69888,140,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/09/Caribbean Anthology - December 9, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-09 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-10 01:31:36','2023-12-10 01:06:55','The host plays some of his latest tracks and tells his audience that he never lost his \"touch.\" He tells them that he and his brother Nitti are both in the hip-hop scene in Guelph. He also says that Noah 23, the artist whom he featured on his last track, is from the same area.\n\nHe tells the audience that they are all now in their mid-thirties and that there is a sense of rivalry in the music scene. He says that he wants to share an artist who is not yet in the game, but who is still making music because he is in a difficult situation. He explains that he does not want to divide the community because he doesn\'t like it, but he does want to let it be known that he is doing music for his own sake. He a