uth Pacific, the Marshall Islands .',NULL,NULL),(69914,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/10/This Night Wounds Time - December 10, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-10 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 07:29:24','2023-12-11 07:07:14','In this chapter, we hear the first hour of the show devoted to music that is off-center, but when the show reaches midnight, we\'ll start playing music that\'s a bit more in-depth.\n\nWe\'ll be playing music from a different part of the world, and this time, it\'s going to be music from Argentina. And then we\'re off to hear music from Alison Ow. That\'s the name of her new album, \"Migrations,\" which sounds like it\'ll sound like a song about people leaving their homes to move to a new land. It\'s also about her family history of migration to Canada, and her personal experience with that.\n\nThe music is very personal, and it speaks to her identity as an immigrant Canadian. We also hear some music from Philippe and Frossoi Bourassa\'s album Confluence, Josh Zubat\'s Strings with a song called Night Time, and Ancient Infinity Orchestra\'s \"Equanimity\" from their album, River of Light.',NULL,NULL),(69915,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/11/This Night Wounds Time - December 11, 2023 at 02:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-11 02:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-11 09:51:19','2023-12-11 09:07:10','The guys are going to do a spotlight on some music from an artist named Franco Fagioli, who studied piano at a university in the province of San Miguel de Tucuman, in South America. Fagioli is a baritone and has two albums, one of which is arias from works by Mozart and Handel. The guys say that they\'re not going to play each of the pieces individually, but rather, they\'ll play a piece from each opera and switch from opera to classical music at some point.',NULL,NULL),(69916,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/11/This Night Wounds Time - December 11, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-11 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-