teners that he is happy to be alive and should be left alone with his young lover. He tells the listeners that the young man has asked him to let him and the young woman have some fun. The man then turns to his wife and tells her that he has been married for 40 years and that she has been faithful to him for the last year. She tells him that she would be glad to keep her young fine thing if it meant that she could keep her husband. She then tells the listener that she saw the young lady driving home and told her to give him all her money.\n\nThe woman is acquitted of the charge and the widower says that he will not do it again. The listeners hear about a music project being run by the Alzheimers Society of Wellington. The project provides people with dementia a free iPod with a personal playlist. The Alzheimers society is looking for volunteer help to set up the iPod and create the playlists. If you\'re interested in running an ad or public service announcement on CFRU, please contact the station.',NULL,NULL),(69920,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/11/Here Today - December 11, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-11 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-11 15:30:33','2023-12-11 15:06:35','The show starts off with an introduction from Aaron Badgley, the host of CFRU\'s Here Today. He describes a new shipment headed for shipment from Tel Aviv, the capital of Israel.\n\nIt includes two new tracks from Israel, a band called Men Of North Country and the song Titanic from their latest LP3. The song is sung at Hanukkah, which begins on December 7th and ends on December 15th. Aaron also describes the Christmas song that is being released by Led Mazzoni, who has been around for a long time. In addition, he talks about the Christmas albums of the Beatles, who always released new music at Christmastime. He also talks about a classical vocalist named Gemma Nation, who is from Ottawa. She has a new single called My Christmas Wish and she sings her own material.',NULL,NULL),