fessor, who\'s also known as the \"Music Man.\n\n\" He\'s been teaching music since the age of 10. He says he\'ll be away for a couple of weeks and the University Center is closed for the holidays. He\'ll play some Christmas music from his collection of Christmas CDs. He starts off by playing a song from one of his favorites, Allard Jones, who was a big star in the United Kingdom when he was 11 years old. Then he plays a Christmas song from another of his favorite Christmas CDs, Bruce Coburn, who is a singer who didn\'t really have a voice until he was in his mid-20s.\n\nNext up on the program is Susan Boyle, a Scottish singer who came to America to sing in the church after her mother\'s death. Susan is such a great singer that she\'s one of the only people in the world who can sing a song like \"Hallelujah\" by Leonard Cohen.',NULL,NULL),(70058,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Seems Like Old Times - December 17, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-17 21:48:00','2023-12-17 21:06:29','On this program, we\'re going to hear some old-school Christmas music. It\'s going to be Mel Tourmay and Les Brown and their orchestra, along with a song by Bing Crosby. Plus, the government just announced a new program to help people afford dental care. The program will offer free care to seniors, children, and people with special needs over the next 5 years. Sounds like a great idea. And we\'ve got some more music from the \'80s, too. This is a song called \"From All the Holidays You Can\'t Be Known to Be Happy\".',NULL,NULL),(70059,148,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Clan Na Gael - December 17, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 21:27:45','2023-12-17 21:07:24','The show begins with John Fahy and his son-in-law, Doug, talking about the music they plan to play for the Christmas Eve show. The first song they play is Cherish the Ladies, a Christmas song about a woman who is a prostitute.\n\nThe second song is from the Christmas In the Mine, a song about the men who go to the mines during the holiday season. The third song is by O\'Connell, a Celtic singer from Boston. The show ends with David Francie, a singer who\'s been out of the music business for a while. The song he plays is Carols for Christmas Eve. The other songs include Snow Angel by Neutsin, The Irish Ascendance by The Gift, Night of Joy by the Rankin Sisters, and Do You Hear Me? by Elton John. The last song is a Christmas single from Ed Sheeran and Elton John, Merry Christmas. The music ends with Rand, a woman from Scotland, singing about the joy of Christmas.',NULL,NULL),(70060,197,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/an9n4h/phil_s_inn_dec_16_23_1_aunla.mp3','2023-12-17 21:19:30',287962512,'2023-12-17 23:57:14','2023-12-17 23:05:35','The show starts off with a little bit of a riff on the song \"From the roots up\" by David Copperfield. The song\'s title refers to the fact that Copperfield was born in Scotland and grew up in the United States.\n\nHe\'s a Scottish musician, so he\'s familiar with the country\'s music scene. Copperfield is a big fan of the Canadian folk music scene, but he also knows that there\'s something more to the song than that. He also knows it\'s important for the listeners to know that this is a music show, not a political one. He tells the listeners that they can vote for their favorite song of all time, and they can send it in as a gift to the listeners of the show. They can also send it to the Princess Margaret Hospital.',NULL,NULL),(70061,101,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Seems Like Old Times - December 17, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 23:39:09','2023-12-17 23:06:13','This chapter opens with a brief description of the day\'s activities for the three children. After breakfast, they go for a walk and then make plans to meet with Johnny and his aunt and uncle later.\n\nWhen they return, their parents will be home, so they\'ll all go and build a snowman together. They\'ll meet the man who\'s trying to speak to them in the newspaper, and then the man will come to pick up their things. When he does, the little girl is so excited about the snow that she can\'t believe how excited she was when she was a child. She\'s so excited that she\'s crying. The man who is trying to talk to her has a girl named Miss Fox, and she comes running in.\n\nThe girl\'s aunt, Miss Key, is also there, along with Miss Fox\'s cousin, Sandy, and her cousin\'s uncle, Uncle Johnny. Uncle Johnny is home, too, and he\'s very excited to see his niece and nephew again. The boy that found the trace of the missing socks has returned to his room.',NULL,NULL),(70062,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/La Buena Onda - December 17, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-17 23:06:56','2023-12-17 23:06:56',NULL,NULL,NULL),(70063,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/6fb9fp/December_17_2023_Across_the_Universe6zmep.mp3','2023-12-18 01:02:13',431961989,'2023-12-18 02:12:07','2023-12-18 01:05:40','On this edition of the Across the Universe, Ken Stowar plays a song from the Rolling Stones\'s \"Sertanix Majesty\" which was released in the year 2000 and was one of the first albums to be released in Canada. After the Stones\' release, Ken plays the Doors, the British band Free, Jones and the Indications, Natima, the Sugar Hill, the Pearly Queen, and Nina Simone. Ken then plays the songs from Nina\'s book \"Sea Lion Woman\" and \"Breaking the Rules,\" songs from Pudu, the song \"The Gambler,\" and the song from \"The Blinding Dark\" by Morsheba. There will be a special edition of \"Across the Universe\" on Christmas Eve.',NULL,NULL),(70064,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8mzu9a/December_15_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow7892e.mp3','2023-12-18 00:39:55',287962512,'2023-12-18 01:45:52','2023-12-18 01:05:51','',NULL,NULL),(70065,149,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/La Buena Onda - December 17, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 01:07:04','2023-12-18 01:07:04',NULL,NULL,NULL),(70066,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Zombie Jamboree - December 17, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 01:29:24','2023-12-18 01:07:05','Back to the Zombie Jamboree. We\'re back with another edition of the program. This time, it\'s all about music. This week\'s theme is \"House on Fire\" from the Plants and Animals album. Brain Snack: This is the first time we\'ve heard the title of a song on a music video.\n\nIt was released in the early 2000s and it was one of the first music videos to have its own social media account. So yeah, Brain Snack, this is a pretty big deal. We also learn that meta-products like Facebook and Google are blocking news from viewers because of Bill C-18. In other words, if you\'re on Facebook or Google and want to see some Canadian news, you\'ll have to go back to your old, boring Facebook or Twitter account. If you have a Facebook account, you can still follow the program, but you won\'t be able to follow the content on other social platforms.',NULL,NULL),(70067,108,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Wind-Down - December 17, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 03:49:20','2023-12-18 03:06:24','The Wind-Down is a music program hosted by Sarah Willow, a student at the University of Guelph. The show starts off with a cover of Barry Cant Swim\'s \"Easy Money\" and then moves on to some new music from Canadian artists, including a Canadian artist with \"Wicked Gal\" featuring \"Lady Leaks\" and a song from the band Bambi Pets called \"Heartbeat from the Knife.\n\n\" Next, the show shifts to a song called \"Tiger Bomb\" with the \"Bustin\' Loose remix\" of \"Tokyo Business.\" The show closes with a song by a Toronto artist called \"Moon King.\" The next song is from the Guelph-based band \"US Girls.\n\n\" The song is called \"Soul Promise.\" The last song is a cover by Ray Bull of \"The New Thing Dies\" from their EP \"Easy Way to Lose.\" The program closes with another song by Lewis Harrison featuring \"Kaja Bonet\" and \"Float from the Birds, Bees and the Clouds.\" Sarah Willow announces that the University has released a new line of clothing and merchandise for students and faculty alike. If you\'re looking for something to wear that\'s a little bit fancier, you might want to check out the new line.',NULL,NULL),(70068,150,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Zombie Jamboree - December 17, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 03:30:10','2023-12-18 03:06:58','The guys continue to play music for the deserters at the Zombie Jamboree. They\'ve got some new acts coming up, and they\'re all from different parts of the country. Some of them are from Mexico, and some are from the U.S. The first two acts are from Bosque, and the other two are from elsewhere in Mexico. The last two acts from Mexico are from Satellite and Singleaf. They don\'t sound like they belong anywhere in Mexico, but they belong to a different part of Mexico.',NULL,NULL),(70069,153,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Backtracks - December 17, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 05:51:23','2023-12-18 05:07:16','Backtracks is a new music program hosted by the UMG student, Eileen Jennifer, and it\'s dedicated to reviving old songs. The first song on the show is from 1969, by the British band, Lace. The UMG students have a double bill this year, so they\'re having a hard time finding the time to play songs. Backtracks reminds us that this is September, which means there\'s plenty of music on the campus. So, yeah, it\'ll probably be a little bit of a struggle this year.',NULL,NULL),(70070,152,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/Through the Looking Glass - December 17, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 05:29:41','2023-12-18 05:07:17','Alice and Gesta travel through the looking glass to follow the music. They start with a song by Geeze and then switch to a track by Ciara.\n\nThey\'re going for twists and turns, so this time they\'ll go with a twist and turn track. The first track is called \"When You Are Gone\" and it\'s from the album \"Intention\" with \"Fantasy featuring Ciara\" . The next track is \"Tarot Cards\" and its name is \"Psych O Billy\" and \"Impresto\" , and the last track is a \"Bloodshot Bill\" from \"Psych-O Billy and Impresta\" ). The show will be posted on the Looking Glass on the University of Regina\'s website under the name of \"Looking Glass\" at the end of next week . Next up is Postwar Books with \"Anticipation\" and the track \"Postwar Books\" is an album called \"Who Can See Forever\" and a soundtrack recorded \"live, pagan, angelic and a borrowed Car\".\n\nThe next band is \"The Bearskins\" and their name is Every King must Fall and the song is \"Give up on dreams and follow me down your error\" and that\'s it. The show is over and Alice wants to thank everyone for listening and to say that he hopes everyone will join him again next Sunday to follow their music wherever it takes them.',NULL,NULL),(70071,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/This Night Wounds Time - December 18, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 07:52:23','2023-12-18 07:07:12','The show opens with a set of numbers, which lead to a variety of other numbers. The show is called \"This Night Wounds Times.\" The first number is a \"badge,\" followed by a \"apoc,\" an \"ensemble,\" and a \"number.\" Next, the group French TVs with Drunkards Train goes to \"Bates.\" The second number is \"Migration Ensembles.\" The third is \"Choice.\" The fourth is \"Josh Zubat Strings.\" The show ends with a \"tradition\": \"We are going to end the first hour/hour-ish longblock of the show.\n\n\" The group turns to Henry Kaiser and plays some of his favorite Christmas tunes. The first song, Jingle Bells, is a parlor poem from the mid-Nineteenth century. The second song is a Christmas carol, but it\'s not a carol at all. It\'s a poem. \"It came upon a Midnight Clear,\" says the song\'s author, Edmund Hamilton Sears',NULL,NULL),(70072,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/17/This Night Wounds Time - December 17, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-17 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 07:32:38','2023-12-18 07:07:12','The show starts off with a description of what happened on the day of the concert. It was a \"funnest day\" , as Gesta describes it. The group heard Eels song \"In My Dreams\" from \"Ombre Lobo\" . They heard \"Underwhelmed\" from their album \"Smeared from 1992. They heard Gordon Lightfoot with \"the absolutely misogynistic\" singer Sob song \"Lovin Me\" from Lightfoot\'s \"Lullaby from 1966\". They heard Kate and Annas song \"Heart Like a Wheel\" from her debut self titled album from 1975. They heard Dont Turn Away From Me from Collectors for the \"What Is Love\" from the self titled \"Album from 1968.\n\nThey also heard a rare track called \"I am Destroyed\" from his \"I Am Destroy\" album. They close out the show with the song \"Love\" by \"Doug Hell\" from I Am Destroy. They\'re called \"Lonely Parade\" and they\'re on the air to promote a new line of apparel from CFRU. They also talk about the \"lonely parade\" and the \"creativity\" of the \"contemplative dance\" they play on Wednesdays from 9am to 11am. Sounds like a \"no brainer, right?\" .',NULL,NULL),(70073,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/This Night Wounds Time - December 18, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 09:32:17','2023-12-18 09:07:07','The program opens with a look back at the history of the song \" Vidalacoya\" by the singer and songwriter Leda Valladas, who was born in the province of Tocquemnn and lived from 1919 until 2012. She was known for her research on traditional songs, folklorists, and singer/songwriters. She was also a poet, and the first song she plays is a song about the military dictatorship which ruled the province from 1976 to 1983. The military dictatorship had many supporters in the arts, but Leda\'s song is ironic because the title of her song is a reference to the general who led the military junta that ruled the region from 1976 until 1983.\n\nThe program ends with a shout-out to the Terry-Fox Foundation, which supports families and patients in need. The Terry-Freud Foundation will match any gift made today with two times the amount of impact. The program then turns to a new program called \"Life in Covid Study.\" It\'s a longitudinal study of the experiences of young and old adults during the pandemic. They want to learn how these groups experienced disruptions and actively shaped the world in order to then recommend mitigation measures for future disasters.',NULL,NULL),(70074,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - December 18, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 15:46:03','2023-12-18 15:05:55','',NULL,NULL),(70075,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Here Today - December 18, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 15:30:05','2023-12-18 15:06:41','Terry Draper, a former member of the punk band Clattoo has released his first solo album in a few years. He is also joined by another chorister, Joy Chapman. The show also includes some Christmas music, including a song by Paul McCartney who changed one line of a song called \"Christmassy\" to \"Carolsy,\" a tribute to the memory of Mary Anne Faithful, an artist who died in this same year. The song is also included on an album called \"The Faithful,\" a collection of artists who pay tribute to her.',NULL,NULL),(70076,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Breezy Breakfast Radio - December 18, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 05:26:33','2023-12-18 17:06:05','',NULL,NULL),(70077,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Breezy Breakfast Radio - December 18, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 06:33:22','2023-12-18 17:06:06','The next morning, the Women\'s Club hosts a breakfast in celebration of the end of the literary season. This time, they\'re talking about novel novels and a movie. We learn that Guelph is on the territory of the Iroquois and the Attawawak, and that it\'s adjacent to the traditional hunting ground for the Haudeosaunee.\n\nThe guests for the day are Adam and Candice, who are doing a show on the CFRU. They\'re sitting right in front of the room, so everyone can see them. The women\'s club plans to give the guests a little tour of the show.',NULL,NULL),(70078,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Worst Responders - December 18, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 19:51:45','2023-12-18 19:08:08','In this episode of Worst Responders , Charissa and Renee discuss the importance of doing laundry early in the morning. In high school, they were instructed to do their laundry on the worst settings. They recall one incident when their boyfriend left them with a cashmere sweater, but instead of using the liquid detergent that is included in most laundry packages, he left with a powder detergent instead. Charissa attributes this incident to her boyfriend being a \"bad guy\"',NULL,NULL),(70079,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Democracy Now - December 18, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 19:31:24','2023-12-18 19:08:10','The international community is growing increasingly concerned about the human rights situation in the Gaza Strip. In the last few days, Israeli forces have killed three soldiers and injured scores of others, including a journalist from Al Jazeera. The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights has denounced the killing as a war crime and called for an immediate cease-fire. Meanwhile, the United Nations General Assembly has adopted a resolution calling for a halt to Israel\'s aggression against the West Bank and Gaza. The General Assembly also agreed to a new round of climate change talks in Paris.',NULL,NULL),(70080,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/CFRU Playlist - December 18, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 21:06:18','2023-12-18 21:06:18',NULL,NULL,NULL),(70081,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - December 18, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-18 23:47:50','2023-12-18 23:06:00','In this chapter, the Guardian overseer, Nicholas Cooper, pays tribute to the Native American peoples who live on Turtle Island, as well as to the Black people who inspired the music.\n\nHe also thanks the Bi-POC community for the work they do and for dismissing and uncrediting their contributions to the current state of experimental music. The first track we hear is from the Shennia Electronic Ambient project, Shanika LewisWaddle, and the second track is from I Am who I Am, which means stand in truth and connect to self. The second track that we listen to is from a new album by Andrew Osler, and Michael Baer Part, called Water like Embiara, and it is called A Million petaled Flower. The third track is a long piece by the duo Dark Room, which we heard earlier. The fourth track is another long piece from the duo, A Million flower, which is from Water like emra. The fifth track is two other long pieces by the same duo.',NULL,NULL),(70082,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Volunteer Playlist - December 18, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 16:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-18 23:26:41','2023-12-18 23:07:34','The guys from the Desert Drones are in town for a visit. It\'s the last gig for the Organic Music Society in 2023, but the guys are psyched to be together. They\'re psyched that they\'re able to spend time together. The show will be coming to a close next week, but don\'t worry, it\'s still a live show, with a lot of syndicating.',NULL,NULL),(70083,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Big Sis Radio - December 18, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 01:49:31','2023-12-19 01:05:57','Big Sis Radio is a music show hosted by Cece, a student at the university. Cece is a big fan of music and he and his Big Sis band play danceable music.\n\nHe wants to talk about how important it is to keep the conversation real. A recent article that he came across suggested that people underestimate how much people care about a conversation and that\'s why we can feel uncomfortable talking to strangers. He also wants to share some music that he\'s listening to. The music on this show is from the band Fontaines DC off of their album Skintyall. The band\'s name is Dublin City.',NULL,NULL),(70084,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/to know the land - December 18, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 01:30:53','2023-12-19 01:06:08','The narrator begins by telling us that at least six years later, he\'ll have the opportunity to air a classic radio show. This is a show that was first aired by the British Broadcasting Company in the early 80s celebrating the winter season.\n\nIt was written by an American novelist named Allison Mclay who died March 7 th . The show is called \"Interloper,\" which means \"connection between human world\" or \"the world of the woods and the spirit\" . It celebrates winter solstice in a very dark way. The narrator likes that the show is rooted in celebration of nature. He likes that it\'s \"not dark as in goth necessarily but almost horror\" , but he likes it even more because it celebrates the spirit of the season.\n\nThe winter solstice is also a dark time for him. He\'s not a physician or a specialist, but it feels \"doomy\" and \"a lot of people are sick right now\" and he doesn\'t know what\'s going on. He just feels like it is a dark season. He feels that it is like a time of year when things are born and everything is \"pressed up against mother\" and that the winter is the time when everything is born.',NULL,NULL),(70085,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Blues Around the Block - December 18, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 03:49:19','2023-12-19 03:05:54','',NULL,NULL),(70086,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Blues Around the Block - December 18, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 19:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 03:30:22','2023-12-19 03:05:55','The program is called \"Blues Around the Block\" and is hosted by Mac Dee. He thanks everyone for tuning in. If you enjoyed the show or previous editions of the show, you can watch it or stream it from the archives on the CFRU.org. He also gives a shout out to anyone who comments on the show. So, buckle up and take a ride. The program starts off with \"Trouble in Mind\" by Voodoo Walters. Then \"The Paul DeLay band from The Other one why can\'t you love me\" from the Ryan Studios. Then the \"Water Street Blues Band\" from \"Another life album for you\" from Ben Racine. And then \"The Sunny Boy Williamson\" tune \"Your',NULL,NULL),(70087,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/vixwue/Karibuni_Dec_17-238clqf.mp3','2023-12-19 03:35:22',287962512,'2023-12-19 06:17:12','2023-12-19 05:05:31','The show continues with a discussion between General Sumari-Afrikan and Kerry Boonie. They\'re both psyched about the upcoming performance of Youssou-Endure, but they\'re also worried about how they can play the song without him on it.\n\nThe two men talk about the latest news from South Africa, and one of the stories they\'ve heard is about a young girl named Zahara Bullelowa who\'s passed away recently. The young girl was born from a small village in the Eastern Cape, where she busked on the streets and sang in church fires. She went to Johannesburg to record her first album, Loliwe, and within a month, the album went platinum, which is unheard of for a young South African artist.\n\nThe show is hopeful that this young girl will live up to her name, because it\'s clear that she\'s a big star. The General says that they met her in 2019, when they were picking her up from her manager. She was a super-simple, sweet girl, and the General says she was just beyond everything.',NULL,NULL),(70088,85,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Ripcord Radio - December 18, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 21:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 05:53:34','2023-12-19 05:05:49','The following hour, the show will be all about punk rock and its effects on the listener. Most of the music will be inspired by horror stories, scary movies, and other spooky tales.\n\nPlus, there will be some cover songs. If you\'re thinking that this is going to be a Christmas music show, it\'s not. The first song that we\'ll hear is from a band called Pit Stop. The band\'s name is \"Radio Cleaner\" and they\'re from Toronto. The second song is from another band called \"Danger Sex With Coming Down on Broken Ripcord FM 93.3 CFRU\" and it features the lead singer from here in town. The third song we hear comes from a London band called Joy Division with \"Dead Souls\" and the fourth is from \"Boycott\" with \"Couch Slouch\" and \"DRI song.\n\n\" The fifth song is \"The Follow Ups With Love Letters From the Black Lagoon\" and this is a song about a guy who hates himself. The sixth song is a cover of \"Death Rock\" by a couple bands from the Southern California punk scene. Death Rock is a style of music that was popular in the early 80s in the United States and was very similar to the \"goth rock\" that was already popular in Europe. The style was rooted in classic \"punk rock\" with lots of \"grim\" lyrics and sometimes \"shocking\" lyrics. Though it didn\'t completely disappear,',NULL,NULL),(70089,86,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/The Deep House Project - December 18, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 22:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 05:34:42','2023-12-19 05:05:57','In this short program, the students discuss the release of a new line of apparel and merchandise by the university. They also discuss their upcoming program, \"The Deep House Project\" on 93.3FM. The program will be their last of the year, and they will play their favorite tracks from the past year. They will also play some of their favorites as well, and close the show with a song by James Jukes. The students hope that everyone enjoyed the program and that they will continue to listen to them in the future.',NULL,NULL),(70090,87,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/18/Back in the USSR - December 18, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-18 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 07:51:20','2023-12-19 07:06:08','The program opens with a poem by the poet, Rafat Al Arir. It is read by the actor Brian Cox. Since the beginning of the October 7th Israeli assault on the Gaza Strip, the poet has been killed, but his words have survived. If you want to learn more about the poet than he can describe, than he will.',NULL,NULL),(70091,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Rainbow Country - December 19, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 07:31:49','2023-12-19 07:07:12','This episode of the gay talk radio show, Rainbow Country, features the voices of Carol Pope, Lorraine Segato, and Gord Depp. The show is produced by Mark Tara, who is the producer and host of the show. Rainbow Country is a nationally syndicated show, airing on 12 outlets in Canada.',NULL,NULL),(70092,1447,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Rainbow Country - December 19, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 09:27:53','2023-12-19 09: