ngton, who was raised in Chicago and became a jazz singer and pianist by the time she was in her early 20s.',NULL,NULL),(70098,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Solipsistic Retreat - December 19, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 17:48:12','2023-12-19 17:08:26','The show opens with a Retrospect on Baby Labor, a band from Guelph that has recently disbanded. The show will pay respects to the band and their community by playing some of their songs on the CFRU show. The program ends with the announcement of Art Not Shame\'s annual matching campaign. The campaign will run from November 30 to December 31 of 2023. If you\'d like to support ArtNotShame, you can visit them at artnotshamoe.org and make a donation.',NULL,NULL),(70099,2653,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Solipsistic Retreat - December 19, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 09:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 17:26:31','2023-12-19 17:08:27','The second half of this program consists of a mix of music by Cardiac, a former figure skater who has turned his life into a career as a music producer. The music is a mixture of classic and experimental music. The first half of the program is a song called \"House Arrest\" by Ariel Pink. The second part is \"Rapture\" by Anidnak. The third half is \"Restorative\" by the French artist.',NULL,NULL),(70100,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Bridging The Social Distance - December 19, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 19:47:58','2023-12-19 19:06:04','In this short interview, the narrator introduces his guest, a Shanghai-born woman named Mei-fei Elric who is a resident at a retirement home in the village of Riverside Glen. She was born and raised in Shanghai and speaks Chinese, although her parents did not call her by her first name. Her parents decided to call her \"Mei-Fei\" because a friend of theirs was named \"Renee,\" but she was always called \"Meis-FeI.\n\n\" The story of her life is that she was born in China and that her parents called her \"Mie-Feis\" because she was \"plumb, blossom, and fragrance\" . Her father served in the Air Force during the war, and she was very helpful in the war because she spoke Chinese. Her mother and father returned to North America after the war. She says that she would have been born in North America before the war had it not been for her father\'s desire to go to China to work for a newspaper.\n\nThe narrator notes that the only thing she can think of about China is that when she went there 20 years ago she did not feel uncomfortable. She thinks that this is because people looked normal. This is cool, she says, to discover that she is \"hardwired\" in the way that people look.',NULL,NULL),(70101,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Democracy Now - December 19, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 11:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 19:30:23','2023-12-19 19:07:27','Amy Goodman reports that at least 13 Palestinians were killed and 75 were wounded in an attack on the northern Gazan refugee camp of Jabalia. In the southern town of Rafah at least 29 were killed, many more were under the rubble of three residential buildings hit by the latest round of airstrikes. The number of Palestinian killed since the start of the conflict has reached 20,000. On the other hand, Israel allowed a limited number of trucks carrying aid into the Gaza Strip for the first time in nearly a month. The drivers of the trucks say that the aid is not enough to meet the needs of the people in the camps.',NULL,NULL),(70102,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - December 19, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 14:00:00',86638720,'2023-12-19 21:47:57','2023-12-19 21:06:43','The program starts off with a song from Dess Embario called \"2 Claret Dad\" from his band\'s album HovinesPorciempre, followed by songs from Nigeria, Argentina, and New Zealand. Then there\'s a Greek metal band called \"Dark Nova\" and a children\'s entertainment act called \"Michael Bush aka Music With Michael\" from her \"2020 EP Christmas Cheer\".\n\nAnd then it\'s time for a Christmas song from Fred Penner. This time he sings a song called \"The Season\" from \"The season of family Christmas celebration\". There\'s also a performance of \"Christmas is tomorrow\" from the live album by West Vancouver\'s Fowley. And then Adima sings \"A-d-h-i-m-a\" from Uganda\'s \"Initial confrontation\". And finally Tribal Fish sings \"Tuesday on a tuesday\" from their 1994 album.',NULL,NULL),(70103,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Under the Needle - December 19, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 21:29:04','2023-12-19 21:07:39','John Darniel is the founder of the independent band The Mountain goats. He has released music under the name since 1991. His latest album, Jenny from the Bes, is his 22nd. He says that he was into music at a young age, when his bully would follow him back home. He liked going to the library or the record store to avoid the bully. Charles and Dorothy\'s World Famous Folk Music Center, where he attended with his friend Ben Harper. John was wary of the folk music scene, realizing that it was \"being exploited\" as a genre. He took piano lessons and learned how to play the guitar at age 22.\n\nHe likes to write lyrics. He returns to the town that first appeared on All Hail West, his 2002 album. He explains that he doesn\'t like writing sequels to things he already wrote because he doesn \"want to be crass.\" He says he usually does a part two after the characters have left, but he wrote the first song for the new album on the piano.',NULL,NULL),(70104,157,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5a9d7i/513-33-45-78-dec18-23.mp3','2023-12-19 22:30:27',286259307,'2023-12-20 00:30:08','2023-12-19 23:05:21','On this edition of the host, we get a two-hour listening session, which consists mostly of vinyl records. The first two hours are all about shaking things up. The second hour is all about the shakes. They start off by listening to a song by the Beatles called \"Twist and Show\" that was produced by George Martin.\n\nThe song is followed by a song called \"Shake It Baby\" by David Wilcox. Then they listen to \"The Blue Tones,\" \"Bob Marley,\" \"David Wilcox,\" \"Shak It Up\" by Ric O\'Kahsick, and \"Washboard Sam\" by Robert Fripp. They finish off with \"Shake it Up,\" by the \"Cars.\"',NULL,NULL),(70105,158,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/jckj3i/December_19_2023_Radical_Reverendb9izk.mp3','2023-12-19 22:20:51',143961989,'2023-12-20 00:10:09','2023-12-19 23:05:23','The Radical Reverends Show is a public service announcement designed to bring people together to address the most pressing issues facing the people of the city of Toronto. The program is hosted by the Reverend, a former schoolteacher, and is produced by the People\'s House. The show\'s main topic is the \"intractable\" problem of homelessness. The Reverend explains that without adequate housing, people will end up homeless and in emergency wards, meaning that they will spend their lives in poverty. The three people who will be speaking on the show are Curtis Jordan, a trustee for the Upper Canada School Board, who will speak on the need for housing, and the founder of the Church of the Good Shepherd, who is also on the program.',NULL,NULL),(70106,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/19/Silver Screen Dream Machine - December 19, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-19 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-19 23:46:47','2023-12-19 23:07:32','The Dream Machine returns with a new show. It has been four years since the last one. This time it\'s for Christmas. It starts off with a song by Howard Blake, called Walking In The Air, which is a song from the 1982 animated film The Snowman. Then it runs off to the 2017 animated film Tiny Christmas, which has a score by Howard Shore. Then they