0\'s. He formed a 17-Piece George G.Swing Orchestra in 1980. Now, they have been formally known.',NULL,NULL),(70143,173,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/tnv6br/Club_Ned_Dec_24_2023_podcast8jdes.mp3','2023-12-21 16:13:02',818308701,'2023-12-21 18:08:17','2023-12-21 17:05:21','The narrator and his wife are in their home for the holidays. The two men discuss the holiday season, which is a time for people to gather with family and friends. The narrator has two relatives in Alberta and Texas. He says that the holidays are a time when people begin to encroach on his and his family\'s lives. For example, he has a sister in Alberta who lives in Texas and a brother in Alberta. Both of them are foreigners, and they would like to convert him to their religion.\n\nHowever, he says that his family doesn\'t need to convert them because they live in places where they don\'t have to. For instance, he recently learned that a scientist from Alberta has proved that there is no link between carbon dioxide and climate change. This means that the man didn\'t say that climate change was caused by carbon dioxide. The men decide to go to their home and buy their brother, Bob, a Christmas present from him.',NULL,NULL),(70144,111,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/21/Tales from the Bridge - December 21, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-21 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 17:51:22','2023-12-21 17:06:45','This is the second of three episodes where the guys talk to Dennis Taylor about his books. The first one was called \"We Are Legion\" and it was a very popular book. The second one is called \"Earthside\" and is part of his \"Quantum Earth series\" which is a post-apocalyptic science fiction series. The fifth book in the Bobaverse series is coming out soon and will be narrated for Audible. The guys are all psyched to have Dennis Taylor on the show.\n\nHe\'s a science fiction author who\'s written nine novels, including \"The Bobaverse\" series. His latest book is called Earthside and it\'s part of the Earth series. He also writes for Audible and is currently working on his fifth book. He asks the guys about Christmas decorations, and they all agree that they\'re going crazy with Christmas decorations.',NULL,NULL),(70145,112,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/21/FoodFarm Talk - December 21, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-21 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 17:31:15','2023-12-21 17:06:46','The show opens with a description of FoodFarm Talk. It\'s a show about food in Ontario and beyond. We\'re talking about everything from food systems and farm economics to food security and soil health.\n\nThe show is hosted by a guy named Alayton Ogunote. He\'s the brains behind FoodFarmTalk. It starts off with a little history about how he traveled to Peru to work on a project that would alleviate poverty and promote economic development in the country. He also talks about his travels. After spending three months volunteering in Peru on a program called EquipubS, he spent some time exploring Peru and found a restaurant called Central. He wants to know if there\'s any energy left in him. The guy says he can eat everything he wants. He asks if he can get the menu for the drinks and the wine list. They\'re all ready to help him.\n\nHe thanks them all. And his name is Giancarlo.',NULL,NULL),(70146,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/21/Bridging The Social Distance - December 21, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-21 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-21 19:50:19','2023-12-21 19:06:11','Jenny Mitchell, the host of a local radio show, Bridging the Distance, introduces her guest, Joanne Loudon, who is a new resident at the Riverside Glen nursing home. She is from northern Ontario and her son lives in the city of Guelph. She says she came to the nursing home because she has family in Sudbury and she feels like southern Ontario people would say northern Ontario meaning southern Ontario, but she had a feeling that southern Ontario would mean northern