ollfroum was a German organist, choirmaster, and musicologist who lived from 1854 until 1919. He was not prolific, but he had a remarkable and decidedly \"fleshed out style\" . The title of the Oratorio is \"The Christmas Mystarium\" , and the piece is very popular in Germany at the time, but it did not really gain popularity in England until the turn of this century. The English version of \"Dream Of Gerontius\" was very successful, but the German version was even more successful, which explains why Elgar had to work with Wollfroem to get the English versions of Dream of Ganymede and The Christmas Carol. The first recording of this oratorio features some really \"stunning performances\" and it is the first time the work has been performed in English.',NULL,NULL),(70194,187,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/mr85nq/DREAMING_-_EPISODE_DECEMBER_22_2023a8hg1.mp3','2023-12-23 20:31:14',141190204,'2023-12-23 22:09:55','2023-12-23 21:05:28','Alexandra is back on stage and she\'s here to tell us all about her music. First up is a song called \"Umbrella,\" which she says is from a new Christmas album called \"Under Available.\" She\'s got a bunch of Christmas songs to choose from. Next up is \"Boy and Bear With Feel and Stars With Christmas Away.\" And then there\'s \"Cold War Kids.\" Alexandra has a lot more to say.',NULL,NULL),(70195,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/23/Sound Magic - December 23, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-23 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-23 21:55:41','2023-12-23 21:06:43','This program takes us back to the nineteenth century and focuses on some Christmas music composed in France. This program begins with a program from the 1890s. It\'s called \"Sound Magic.\" We\'re back in the twentieth century, and this program is about to go into the French music world.\n\nThe program starts with a Christmas music piece written in 1961 by Arthur Onager, a Swiss composer who lived from 1905 to 1892. The piece is called \"Cantata de Nolle,\" and it h