im that night. Thomas also thanks the Pimienta family for putting on such a great show. They\'re on stage with their two sons and one of the sons hasn\'t even been born yet. That',NULL,NULL),(70256,90,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Bridging The Social Distance - December 26, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 19:48:43','2023-12-26 19:06:11','Love Stone, a former communist, is a former director of the International Affairs Department of the AFLCIO. He was also a former CIA agent. He tells the story of the history of the American labor movement, including its ties to Israel.\n\nThe US has been the strongest supporter of Zionism since 1917, and its support goes back to the early days of the State. There are many public facilities named after American labor leaders, including sports stadiums, orphanages, and community centers. There is also the State of Israeli bonds, which are the top purchasers for many decades, and this is money that unions put their dues or pensions or healthcare funds into. One of the leaders of the Philadelphia union for the Israeli Labour Federation attended a fundraiser and said that the unions should invest millions in the Israeli bonds from their pension fund.\n\nThere has been a movement from rank and file workers to protest this. For example, in Detroit, Arab American workers in the United Autoworkers staged a wild strike against the UAW\'s purchase of $785,000 in state of Israel bonds. Over the past 20 years, there have been many protests against this practice, including the boycott, divestment, and sanctions movement led by the Palestinians.',NULL,NULL),(70257,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Democracy Now - December 26, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 19:31:24','2023-12-26 19:07:18','A growing number of United States labor unions including the American Workers Union and United Auto Workers are calling for an immediate cease-fire in the Gaza Strip. Israel has killed more than a hundred Palestinians in the past weekend, including a UN official and his family. On Sunday at least 106 people were killed in one single airstrike on a refugee camp. Meanwhile, a photographer has released a video showing hundreds of civilians, including some children, naked and forced into open ground. The United Nations has passed a resolution demanding more humanitarian aid into the Strip, but the United States has refused to sign on to the resolution.',NULL,NULL),(70258,125,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Power Up! with Electrified Voltage - December 26, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 21:49:59','2023-12-26 21:06:58','The program opens with a brief introduction to the music being played. The first song is a Romite called Secret Society that was released in 2020. The second song is from Australia, Loudwater with a single called Save Yourself. The third is from Zimbabwe, Aarida with her single Singing The Blues. The fourth is from Taki Vibe\'s with his song Shaneera. The fifth is from Canada, Judgmental. The sixth is from Peru, Synchronica with the song RayPraseon. The seventh is from Alberta, Rekt with a song Called It Aint Nobody population.',NULL,NULL),(70259,1783,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Under the Needle - December 26, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 21:32:46','2023-12-26 21:07:59','The band that Troy hosts, the Mountain Goats, has been releasing albums since 1991. They\'ve been making music since they were 12 years old, and they\'ve released 22 albums. Their latest is Jenny From Thebes. This is the 22nd full length album, so it\'s been a long time coming.\n\nThe band\'s name is inspired by a line from a song called Yellow Jacket by Jay Hawkins. This song was written by the guy who wrote that song. So the band is named for this song. The narrator says that John Darniel grew up with a bully at home, so he went downtown to avoid him. He also went to the Folk Music Center, where he learned how to play the guitar. He doesn\'t play the instrument, but he knows how to learn chords from piano lessons. By the age of 22, he had bought an acoustic guitar and learned to play. He was skeptical of folk music at the time, because it was being used as a genre and because there were many people making money off of it.\n\nBut he found an album by someone else, and it turned out to be a very different writer. So he went back to the town of Jenny and sees what the townspeople are up to, and decides to make a sequel to his first album, All Hail Texas.',NULL,NULL),(70260,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Silver Screen Dream Machine - December 26, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 23:57:26','2023-12-26 23:07:08','This week\'s program is narrated by Leonard Squoskin, who has been the host of the Dream Machine for three years. It\'s the first time he\'s narrated a story since the show went on hiatus. The story is about Finn McCool, an Irish champion who was born smaller than a dragon.\n\nHis father, King Cool, was a giant himself, so he took the kid under his wing and placed him in a lock below the castle walls. The kid\'s grandmother was on the shore at the time, and she watched as the kid plunged into the sea. She fed him a diet of peat and tree bark, but the kid grew too big for his grandparents comfort. They sent him off to the wild world, and he was named Finn.\n\nHe was as strong and swift as forty three hares. Before he was too old, he took off for his own. His new home was on top of a hill called Nockmany in Ulster, where he met a beautiful woman named Una. They lived happily together, and they were a match made in heaven',NULL,NULL),(70261,3033,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/A Multilingual Affair - December 26, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-26 23:40:08','2023-12-26 23:07:22','This episode is a long one, but it\'s about as good as it gets. It\'s all about gratitude, and it starts off with a little bit of talking about the weather.\n\nThen we jump into the interview and find out what the show is all about. O\'Perk is a guy who\'s been working in the community for a long time, and he\'s always trying to do better, so we\'re going to hear about his work on the show. He\'s also got a bunch of really cool ideas for how to help the community. He has a show on the community radio station called \"Perk\" and he and his buddy Amara Wah do a lot of live music and talking. O.Perk\'s a big advocate for the community and he wants to make sure that the people of the community are aware of his work. So this is his first show.',NULL,NULL),(70262,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/f8rg3c/December_27_2023_Global_Rhythms7y22t.mp3','2023-12-27 15:02:54',431961989,'2023-12-28 01:54:26','2023-12-27 19:05:25','Ken Stowar is back with the program, Rhythms on Cibi-Utt, and he starts off with a song called Synchro System, which was first released in the early \'80s by the King of Juju Music of Nigeria, King Sunny A Day.\n\nThe original version is 18 minutes long and was so well received that it\'s been widely distributed. There are three films that King A Day is known for including Juju Music, Live at Toronto, and Roots of Rhythm, which is a collection of three documentaries about his music.\n\nNext up is an outfit called Shakti, who disbanded in the mid-1970s and reformed recently. They\'ve released a double album, called This Moment, which features the original members of Shakti along with John McLaughlin and Zakir Hussain. The track is called Karuna and is from this album. On set, Ken plays an instrumental from the album Vision by Al Shankar, who is one of the members of the original group Shakti.',NULL,NULL),(70263,280,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/559w2a/Episode94_Best_of_Season_99d6i4.mp3','2023-12-27 06:19:41',115690187,'2023-12-28 01:35:45','2