show ends with an introduction to Han, who is a volunteer at the university. He is a co-host of the show.',NULL,NULL),(70269,94,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Let’s Get Lost - December 26, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 22:29:13','2023-12-27 19:06:20','Scott gives us a little background info on the Let\'s Get Lost program that he hosts every Tuesday night from 8 to 9pm on CFRU.org. He\'s a student at the university and the host of the program. The program is hosted by Scott, who is called \"Scott\" by his listeners. He tells us that the program is coming to listeners every Tuesday at 8pm. He says that he\'s been trying to find a few of his favorite songs to play on the program, and this week they\'ll be playing a song by a female artist named Lena Alemanos 4 band. They\'re playing a track called \"Dragon Fruit\" from her new album, \"Canon,\" which is coming out soon.\n\nWe also learn that another female artist, Kate Gentile, is also playing on the show. Kate has released a lot of music in the last few years through her partner Matt Mitchell. The other female artists on the list include Matna Roberts and her \"coin-coin narration\" of her life and heritage, Angelica Neiss, Tamika Reed, and \"Beyond Dragons,\" an album by her band.',NULL,NULL),(70270,96,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Cyber Lich’s Gothic Castle - December 26, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 23:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 22:06:36','2023-12-27 19:06:20','In this interview, MacDee, a student at the University of Regina, explains how he has been a part of the university\'s broadcasting and production team. He says he has learned a lot about local artists, and he is still hanging around the university. He hopes to find a job as a producer for one of the current shows. He also hopes to work as a live event or public service announcement production assistant. If you are interested in video production, he says, he would like to work on one of their live streams.',NULL,NULL),(70271,100,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/27/We Know Some Stuff + CFRU playlist - December 27, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-27 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 21:52:28','2023-12-27 19:06:21','The second half of the interview is a bit more in-depth. The guy tells us his story: he went to university in England, then to London, then back to England, and then to California, where he did his Ph.D. and then got a job as a postdoc at Stanford. Then he joined the company at the beginning of the Pandemic, which is when he met his future wife.',NULL,NULL),(70272,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/27/The Stillness & The Dancing - December 27, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-27 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 21:29:58','2023-12-27 19:06:21','The show begins with another two-hour program, this time dedicated to a holiday celebration called \"Advent, Hanukkah, or whatever you celebrate\" . The first hour is devoted to music, with the second hour dedicated to listening to new music. The program starts off with a short piano piece by Pierce Harbor, then moves to Mill Olin\'s \"In Waiting\" , and then to Tomozumi\'s latest release, \"The Long Night In Winter Light.\" Scott Tuma\'s guitar work is also included, as is another song from Closer Listen, \"Drum and Lace,\" from their \"Frost\" collection.',NULL,NULL),(70273,99,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/27/The Stillness & The Dancing - December 27, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-27 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 21:12:17','2023-12-27 19:06:22','On this episode of the Stillness and the Dancing, the host opens the show with a shout-out to the listeners of his show, who are listening to a holiday edition of the show.\n\nThe show begins with a release from Stephen Doman, a long-time favorite of the host. Doman\'s release is called \"St. Octave\" and is the first track in the program. The host then introduces listeners to other releases from Doman and his friends. The first release is from the Montreal project Exist, which has a track called \"Into the Montreal Project.\" The second is from Monono Aware, which released a track \"Warming Into Brett Nock.\" The third is from Rosewood Untitled, which is a new release from Eak Recordings. The fourth track is from Rest Recordings, called \"Hidden Place.\" The show ends with music from pianist Seamus Carmuru, who released a release called \" Forging for Wild and Light Snow.\"',NULL,NULL),(70274,109,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/27/Radia - December 27, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-27 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 21:07:56','2023-12-27 19:06:29','This episode begins with a message from the \"Responsible Gambling Council\" of San Marino. The message is from Ginevra and her friends in the Republic. They are all working on a project called \"Ginevra\'s Telegram\" in which they will send messages in random languages to each other in order to create a \"transfette chain.\n\n\" The Telegram chain is a simple way of knowing the meaning of a language. It is also a way of understanding a story. It allows one to see the \"beginning and the end\" of a story, the \"end of the story.\" The narrator tells us that the Telegram chain will be a way for the audience to experience the story.',NULL,NULL),(70275,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/27/Democracy Now - December 27, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-27 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 20:14:14','2023-12-27 19:07:19','On Friday, Israel bombed two houses in Gaza City, killing 90 people, including a United Nations official and his family. On Sunday at least 106 people were killed in one single airstrike. Issam and his wife and four children remain trapped under the rubble of the house. The family has been in hiding since the attack. The world is watching as they die, says Issam. Meanwhile, an Israeli artillery strike leaves several people injured in the town of Khan Yunis. The Red Crescent Society has reported an attack on their headquarters in the same town.',NULL,NULL),(70276,1455,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/Down the Rabbit Hole - December 26, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 19:50:41','2023-12-27 19:07:21','The narrator begins this chapter by describing a song by a band called \"Akade Abali.\" The song is a trumpet-like tune, and the narrator describes the band as \"like an intimate setting.\n\n\" The narrator also mentions that he has been reading a novel by Clarice-Liss-Spectress, \"The Stream of Consciousness.\" The book is about a girl who grows up and transitions to her adulthood. The narrator says that the book \"kind of speaks to the idea that sometimes ideas are just byproducts of their time, and it sort of just goes up to individuals and puts it out in its own way.\" He wonders what ideas the \"generation of today\" is latching onto, and interpreting, on their own, and putting it out on its own.\n\nThis is the first book the narrator has read, and he can\'t figure out what it is called, but he thinks it might be his favorite book. The group pauses for a bit, and then the narrator asks if they have any more books to discuss. He says that they have a few, but that he cannot pronounce them. They end the chapter by talking about the novel Akade Abilisi by Arawak',NULL,NULL),(70277,1591,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/12/26/New or Never - December 26, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-12-26 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-12-27 19:31:16','2023-12-27 19:07:24','On this edition of New or Never, host Adrian Hoad Reddick introduces a dozen new music acts for you to listen to. The first acts are Joseph Lee Paulette, Nichol, Sandro Perry, Krung Bin, Aaron Dyer, and Stargaze. The second acts are Ginger Beef, the first husband-and-wife duo of award winning flautists, and MSG. The third acts are Alex Daikin, an artist, and Focus Daikin. The fourth acts are Silver Lining, an experimental j